<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRISTOL-WALLACE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSTY WALLACE GEARS UP FOR TEXAS WITH 50TH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ With his 50th NASCAR Winston Cup victory in the
books and his mouth running almost as fast as his race car, Rusty
Wallace has drawn a circle around this weekend at Texas Motor
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace moved into a three-way tie for eighth-place on NASCAR's
all-time winner's list via his victory over Johnny Benson in the
Food City 500 at Bristol Motor Speedway yesterday. It was Wallace's
first Victory Lane visit since he won on the high-banked,
0.533-mile oval here last April, a span of 32 races. An
acknowledged short-track specialist, Wallace said he had been
pointing to this bullring, site of his first Cup victory in April
1986, as the perfect place to pump some gusto into his 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a big bull's-eye on this racetrack and told my guys this
is ridiculous now,'' said Wallace, driver of the No. 2 Miller Lite
Ford Taurus. ``I won seven freaking times at Bristol. It's the site
of my very first win. There were 147,000 people in the grandstands.
It's the most exciting track on the circuit. That's one of the
reasons I came here and had a real in-depth test for two days here.
We learned a lot, and I think it helped in the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The racetrack at BMS requires a completely different setup than
the one Wallace will employ on the 1.5-mile quadoval in Fort Worth,
where first-round qualifying for the Sunday's DirecTV 500 is
scheduled for Friday afternoon. But after an appropriate
celebration last night, Wallace said he is excited about heading to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great car there last year,'' said Wallace, who
finished fourth and on the lead lap in a race won by native Texan
Terry Labonte. ``At the very end of the race, my car was flying. I
finally got a second groove worked in. I think I was the only one
up there running a second groove, and while I'm up there I'm
thinking, `What am I doing here?' But the car was running pretty
good. We really thought that if we could have got another caution
flag maybe we could have won the thing with a little track
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love going there. I stay in Fort Worth at a great hotel.
Got some great restaurants there, and the speedway is big and
beautiful. And since they rebuilt it \Rthe racing surface in
1998\S, it's great now. So I am excited to get to go to Texas next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had only the third-best car on paper yesterday, as
three-time Cup champion Jeff Gordon dominated the day by leading
five times for 225 of the scheduled 500 laps. Wallace's
Penske/Kranefuss Racing teammate, Jeremy Mayfield, led four times
for 124 laps. But Wallace said he fine-tuned a setup he had hit
upon during Saturday's final Happy Hour practice, during which he
solved a front-end push that had made it difficult to turn through
the 36-degree banked corners.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the 1989 Cup champion, took the lead for the third and
final time on Lap 425, when he passed reigning series champion Dale
Jarrett and began pulling away from a pack that also included Ward
Burton, the winner at Darlington (S.C.) Raceway last Sunday, series
points leader and native Texan Bobby Labonte, big brother Terry and
polesitter Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the lead, Wallace withstood restart challenges posed by
the afternoon's ninth, 10th and 1lth caution flags to beat Benson
and his upstart Tyler Jet Motorsports team by 2.622 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, whose winning average speed was 88.018 mph, said he was
honored to join NASCAR legends Ned Jarrett and Junior Johnson at
the 50-victory level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit 47 and 48 wins and 49, I started thinking, `Man,
I'd really like to have that 50th. That would be a special deal,'
'' said Wallace, who now has won at least one Cup race for 15
consecutive seasons. ``And I really wanted to get it accomplished
during NASCAR's 50th anniversary season \Rin 1998\S. And when I got
my 49th win last year here, I thought that was my 50th win. I
miscounted, but it still was a special deal. It was my own personal
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this stuff forever and been lucky to do pretty
good at it. It's a big relief, and now it's a green flag to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, meanwhile, continued to impress in his first season as
driver of the No. 10 Lycos.com Pontiac Grand Prix owned by Tyler
businessman Tim Beverley. Benson's second-place result here, after
starting 33rd, was the best in his 133-race Cup career. Completing
the top five in a race that produced 18 lead changes among nine
drivers were Burton, Mayfield and Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, who began the day with a nine-point championship
lead over Mark Martin, finished sixth here and will carry a
41-point advantage over Burton into Fort Worth.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
