<HEADLINE>
BU FROZEN OUT IN FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If it had ended in the first overtime Sunday, St.
Lawrence coach Joe Marsh's words would have aptly and artfully
described the NCAA East Regional game when he called it ``one of
the greatest ever played in college hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   If it had ended in the second overtime, paeans could have been
sung praising Boston University's Rick DiPietro and St. Lawrence's
Derek Gustafson, a pair of freshmen goaltenders who dueled and
dueled, save after save, stopping everything coming their way.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, ``trying to end it as fast as possible,'' also was
looping passes from behind his net to the red line, ``hoping,'' he
said, ``to start a breakaway.'' Which he did once, sending Carl
Corazzini in alone on Gustafson in the first OT. But Gustafson, of
course, made the save.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite a show, wasn't it?'' marveled BU coach Jack
Parker. ``Just who was going to blink. It was simply a great game
to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it had ended in the third OT, it might have sufficed to
simply call this the longest NCAA hockey tournament game ever,
surpassing the Maine-Michigan semifinal in 1995, which ended 28
seconds into the third overtime. A laurel wreath or two could have
been borrowed from the Boston Athletic Association and placed on
the brows of this marathon's survivors, because that's what this
was about _ as Marsh put it, ``a matter of who survived.''
</P>
<P>
   But the game superseded all that, going on and on and on and on
and on, finally ending 3:53 into the fourth overtime with St.
Lawrence a 3-2 victor when Robin Carruthers banged home a rebound
of his own shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers and Skating Saints had played and skated and
endured and survived 123 minutes 53 seconds of hockey, two full
games and then some, leaving both teams ``legless'' in the final
OT, as Parker put it.
</P>
<P>
   It took until the fourth OT _ when cramps had reduced BU to only
``eight half-forwards,'' as Parker described his dehydrated but not
dispirited squad _ for Carruthers to turn on the red light after 72
minutes 3 seconds of darkness. He was assisted by Jim Lorentz, son
and namesake of the former Buffalo Sabre, who somehow found the
energy to scrum the puck loose from two BU players and feed his
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   When the second-chance shot went in, DiPietro collapsed in his
crease, not from the cramps that had bedeviled him, he said, ``but
from despair and disappointment. It was just heartbreaking to lose
a game like that.'' Especially after an NCAA-record _ and
mind-boggling _ 77 saves.
</P>
<P>
   But tales of the human body's endurance were as much a part of
the postgame words from players and coaches as comments on the
scintillating hockey. Parker recounted how Dan Cavanaugh collapsed
with cramps in the second OT, how Jack Baker's cramps laid him low
a little later, how it seemed his players barely ``had energy to
get over the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   BU trainer Larry Venis described the remedies employed to aid
the pain and misery of the players. ``We just loaded up on Gatorade
and water and were keeping cool with wet towels between periods,''
he said. ``We gave them water and Gatorade and vitamins and we gave
them pills to help with dehydration. Two guys missed time on the
ice, but everybody else had little epsidoes where they were
cramping up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers were perhaps more susceptible to physical
breakdowns as the game wore down, having played a first-round game
just 24 hours earlier while St. Lawrence enjoyed a bye. But the
Saints were feeling it, too. In the third overtime, referee Duke
Shegos skated over to the St. Lawrence bench to say that Gustafson
was cramping up in net. But when someone on the bench held up a
water bottle, the goalie signaled ``no.'' (``I don't like water
bottles on top of the net.'') A little later the cramps got worse,
however, and the goalie was given some pills and water. He took a
sip, and slid the water bottle back to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The game wore out Shegos as well. Later in the third OT, he
skated over to Venis ``and asked for some Gatorade and some
dehydration pills for him,'' said the trainer. ``And we gave him
some vitamins for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was the longest in NCAA tournament history, but not the
longest college game. Colorado College and Wisconsin played 9:30
into a fourth OT in a conference tournament game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But records did fall. The 77 saves by DiPietro broke the record
of Providence College's Chris Terreri, who had 62 in a 1985 NCAA
tournament game against Boston College. Terreri's total now is
third best, as Gustafson had 72 saves. The goalies' combined 149
saves set a record, obviously, as did the 154 shots on goal
(breaking the mark of 106 set by Maine and Michigan in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   The win makes St. Lawrence the first Eastern College Atlhetic
Conference team to make the Frozen Four since Vermont in 1996. No
ECAC team has won the national championship since Harvard in 1989.
St. Lawrence will meet Hockey East's Boston College in one
semifinal April 6 in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   The first 60 minutes Sunday can be described shortly and
concisely: St. Lawrence jumped out to a 2-0 lead but BU fought back
to tie the score on Brian Collins's tip-in of a Chris Dyment shot
from the right circle with 8:10 left in regulation. ``I think it
was great we came back from being down, 2-love,'' said Parker,
adding that these Terriers are ``one of the most resilient teams
I've ever coached.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the overtimes began.
</P>
<P>
   The second 60 minutes were scoreless simply because of the
goalies. Fatigue set in, legs began to fail, but neither team
played cautious hockey, as both had supreme chances. As an
indication, Gustafson had 31 saves during the 60 minutes of
regulation but made 41 in the next 63:53, while DiPietro had 43
saves in the first 60 minutes and 44 in the next 63:53.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best chances was when BU's Dyment let loose a
one-timer that hit the left post at 17:12 of the opening OT. ``I
gave the pipe a tap with my stick,'' said Gustafson in thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Twice BU had man advantages, and in the second OT St. Lawrence
had a power play for 3:37, but DiPietro and Gustafson stopped all.
</P>
<P>
   There were breakaways.
</P>
<P>
   There were 2-on-1s.
</P>
<P>
   There were 3-on-1s.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no goals in the first three overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to my team after the first overtime, `Hey, we'll do
this as long as it takes,' '' said Marsh, who is from Lynn, Mass.
``But I just didn't think it would take this long.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the paths of longtime friends Marsh and Parker crossed
at game's end, marathon's end, the coaches hugged and Marsh joked,
``Hey, you're not tired, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   No, ``exhausted'' is the word. The players, coaches, and
officials, but also the fans _ all exhausted by a marathon of
hockey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
