<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAATOURNEY-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBING WAY TO BE LEFT OUT IN COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nearly six hours later, Rick DiPietro's motor
skills were all but turned to stone. He wasn't so much playing net
as surviving it, remaining upright on his skates but sinking ever
so slowly into the quicksand of exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' said Boston University's prized freshman goalie.
``My whole body was cramping. Catching glove. Stick hand. You can
drink water and stuff, but after a while you lose so much fluid,
and there's only so much you can drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Both hands and forearms were cramping. DiPietro's legs were
tired, heavy, still responsive but a split second behind optimum
performance. Ultimately, DiPietro couldn't snap his legs together
in time to stop a Robin Carruthers shot in the fourth overtime, and
that split-second delay spelled the end of BU's hockey season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made that first save,'' said DiPietro, replaying that final
second of the longest hockey game in NCAA tournament history,
Sunday's 3-2 St. Lawrence victory in the East Regional. ``I knew
the rebound was out there, but I thought it was past the shooter. I
didn't see it go by me, but I heard the yelling and everything, so
right there I was sure it was in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   BU and St. Lawrence played 123 minutes 53 seconds at Pepsi
Arena, and for the Terriers it proved to be a long exit ramp to the
dead end of a season. Gone was their hope of reaching the NCAA
championship game for the fourth time in 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Only 24 hours after dismissing St. Cloud in the opening round,
the Terriers were forced to play a virtual doubleheader against a
fast, aggressive St. Lawrence club that had a bye in the first
round. The Saints, champions of the ECAC, were rested and ready.
The Terriers were tired, hoping to rely on momentum and the elusive
second wind of tournament time to carry them to Providence for the
Frozen Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be a war,'' said BU coach Jack Parker. ``For us, it
got to be a war of attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   With 5:32 gone in the second overtime, BU sophomore center Dan
Cavanaugh went down in a heap behind the goal line in the Terrier
end. He needed help leaving the ice. Done for the day. Or so Parker
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we go in the room for the intermission,'' said Parker,
``and he's getting dressed for the next period. A lot of guys were
hurting. Jack Baker had to leave the bench five or six times, his
legs were cramping so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey and overtime are a strange concoction, especially in the
playoffs. As the game drags on, skill and finesse give way to
lethargy and the loss of electrolytes. Plays don't end in a
flourish, they just end, a string of unfinished symphonies. The
best players eventually turn into Silly Putty, and it's usually
left to third- and fourth-liners to write the end chapter of
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Petr Klima, Edmonton's little-used Czech forward
who shot down the Bruins in the third OT during the 1990 Stanley
Cup finals. Here it was Carruthers, a third-line right wing from
Virden, Manitoba, who picked up a puck deep in BU's end, eluded
three Terriers, and needed two tries to push the winner between
DiPietro's wickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably after the second overtime, we were starting to get
doubts in our head,'' said Carruthers, ``and wondering when it was
going to end.''
</P>
<P>
   The clubs combined for 238 attempts at net, 154 of which landed.
They may have been tired, but they somehow kept regenerating enough
drive and stamina to keep the action from dissolving into a mid-ice
quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, both sides were spent by early in the third OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting monotonous,'' said DiPietro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be cautious,'' said Parker, whose club battled back
from a 2-0 deficit, forcing OT with a pair of power-play strikes.
``I thought we were legless and they were legless, and not a lot of
opportunities were created.''
</P>
<P>
   The bands played on without skipping a beat. The BU trumpeters
and the St. Lawrence drummers, perched high in the stands, tooted
and banged their way from high noon to early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The players for the day's other game, from Michigan and Maine,
impatiently poked their heads out portals to see if their 3:30
start was meant to be a.m. or p.m. The rink turned into a ballroom
and the skaters marathon dancers. By the third OT, a few of the
Maine Black Bears were limbering up with a game of indoor street
hockey, passing the puck back and forth outside the press room at
the arena's floor level.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when the shot by Carruthers swept between DiPietro's
legs, the abrupt ending segued to BU's long faces and St.
Lawrence's jubilant grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great ride by my club,'' said Parker, the Terriers finishing
at 26-10-7. ``We had a lot of fun. I don't feel bad or sad. I feel
gratitude for having the chance to coach these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it meant coaching for a little longer than he wanted to
one day, and not enough for a next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
