<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME CANADA?
</HEADLINE>
 THE SCENE-LADN  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER WOOD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar wouldn't be Oscar without a little controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park's'' Trey Parker and Matt Stone provided the
controversy and the laughs in their mock frocks. With just the
right wig, Parker revived the famous Versace dress with the
plunging neckline that Jennifer Lopez wore to the Grammys. Only
this time, the sequined hot pants and midriff-bearing dress left a
little to be desired. Stone sported a look-alike to Gwyneth
Paltrow's Ralph Lauren pink gown of last year's awards. While Stone
is a thin man, he doesn't quite perfect the waifish glamour of a
Hollywood star. You gotta love the two for trying.
</P>
<P>
   They were accompanied by Marc Shaiman as their pimp. The
co-writer of the Oscar-nominated song ``Blame Canada'' wore a very
non-Oscar-like white leisure suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this your first year at the Oscars?'' fashion maven Joan
Rivers asked Stone and Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, and probably last,'' the duo answered.
</P>
<P>
   In a cruel twist for the fans, there was no Jennifer Lopez. But
the 72nd Academy Awards preshow was hectic, nevertheless. If you
don't believe it, just try sitting among hundreds of screaming,
pushy, overwhelmed fans who seemed they would die happy if they
could just get that one photograph of Tom Cruise, Gwyneth Paltrow
or Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for the fans, they did snap many of those coveted shots.
But there was so much screaming going on, nobody knew which way to
look.
</P>
<P>
   One young girl wearing a T-shirt with messages scrawled to her
favorite actors nearly burst a vein screaming for `N Sync's Justin
Timberlake. Timberlake finally turned to face the girl, who nearly
fainted at the gesture.
</P>
<P>
   In the company of stars like Meryl Streep, Michael Caine and
Anjelica Huston, that pop-y boy band `N Sync provoked more screams
than any of the stars combined. They dominated the Grammy Awards;
couldn't they sit out just this once? Not this year _ the
five-member teen heartthrobs were singing a duet with Gloria
Estefan for the Oscar-nominated song ``Music of My Heart.'' Next
year, expect the Backstreet Boys to be up for an Oscar in a short
film about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Michael Clarke Duncan and Haley Joel Osment who wowed
the crowds the most. The two Supporting Actor nominees may have
gone home empty-handed, but their presence on the red carpet proved
their effect on their fans. Duncan came out towering over the
crowd. He whooped, he hollered, and he even stopped to give
autographs to at least a dozen fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just remember that I love you guys,'' he shouted to his
adoring fans. ``I wouldn't be here without your support.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Haley Joel Osment, barely visible among the throngs of
people, proved to be a photographer's and a fan's dream. He was
ear-to-ear smiles as reporters, photographers, publicists and
academy crew members pushed and pulled him along the red carpet.
The sixth-grade wunderkind took it all in stride. Just another day
in the life of an 11-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   As the classic and not-so-classic beauties and stars rushed to
fill their seats inside the Shrine Auditorium, the chaos died down,
but the excitement remained.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone involved in this year's historic Academy Awards _
from the die-hard fans, who camped out for weeks only to sit in
nosebleed seats, to the winners themselves _ the 72nd Academy
Awards proved that, in this town, our stars are our royalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
