<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS WAITING TO BE SPRUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ On their way to work Sunday morning, the Red
Sox passed one small airport, a couple of steakhouses, a few strip
malls, about 75 fast-food restaurants, and, unfortunately, not a
single Mariner, Angel, or Devil Ray.
</P>
<P>
   On their way to work Friday morning, the Red Sox . . . did the
same thing as Sunday. On the Friday morning before that, the Red
Sox . . . did the same thing. And on the Friday morning before
that, the Red Sox . . . did the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard Jimy Williams say that his team ``plays the
schedule.'' What the manager doesn't add is this: By now, that
schedule can turn a baseball player into a metronome.
</P>
<P>
   It's the last week of the Grapefruit League and the Sox are sick
of Florida. Many of the players tried to break up their spring
routine by watching the NCAA tournament. But since this state has
trapped the Sox on a treadmill, guess what team the Sox saw as they
stared at the screen? The University of Florida Gators, of course.
</P>
<P>
   If you approached a Boston player this morning and told him he's
won a trip to Alabama, he would respond as if he were a winner on
Oscar Night. (``I'd like to thank God. My family. My friends. My
fans. I mean, Alabama! Wow, this is such an honor . . .'') It's
nothing against Florida. Spring training and spring break are cool
for a week, two weeks, or even three. But by Week 6 you find
yourself saying, ``82 and sunny again? Damn!''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gaetti is Boston's spring master. The 41-year-old infielder
has been through this 19 times. ``I've done them both,'' he said
Sunday, ``Florida and Arizona.'' This is how it works:
</P>
<P>
   There is family-reunion excitement in February. A slight lull
emerges 10 days later. The energy returns in early March when the
exhibition games begin. By late March, you find yourself longing to
be booed in Yankee Stadium, Safeco Field, and, let's be realistic,
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are the bus rides, back and forth, back and forth,''
Gaetti said. ``A lot of it all is the same. It's time (for the
season to start).''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, John Valentin leaned in a chair and talked
about the real games of the regular season. It didn't matter that
he was speaking of unpleasantries like being booed and being
trashed by the media. Just the idea of playing games that count _
and the accompanying criticism _ seemed to excite him.
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman, who had two doubles Sunday in a 5-4 loss to
the Pirates, said he is ready for the prep work to stop. He wants
to play serious American League games. He wants the challenge of
blocking out all the reports that praise or slam his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players can read the paper and not be bothered by it; it
fuels them,'' he said. ``I heard that Michael Jordan used to read
the paper all the time.'' Valentin tries not to because, he said,
extreme reactions either way might affect him. ``Even when things
are going well and everybody says, `You're the bomb,' you can't
believe that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin spoke for a while. He even took the time to wonder what
would happen if players produced the season previews that appear in
just about every sports publication this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be a lot different,'' he said with a smile. He
eventually excused himself. I didn't even have to ask where he was
going. Wherever it was, I knew he would have to pass at least one
steakhouse, a strip mall, and an obligatory Publix.
</P>
<P>
   The extended spring is, and always has been, for pitchers. As
Pedro Martinez announced Sunday, ``Spring training is all right.
They've been doing it this way in baseball for the last 120
years.'' The theory is that pitchers need the time to strengthen
their arms. Ramon Martinez did that Sunday, throwing 73 pitches in
five innings. One of those 73 pitches was a fat, Grapefruit League
grapefruit that Bruce Aven sent deep over the left-field wall at
City of Palms Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are now 8-16. That's another frustrating thing about the
last week of spring training: No one gets excited or disappointed
by records. Ramon Martinez simply said his arm feels good, he
doesn't worry about his surgically repaired shoulder, he's throwing
in the high 80s, and on some days during the regular season, ``I
know I'll get my ass kicked.'' He also said he is resilient, so an
occasional bad start won't destroy his psyche.
</P>
<P>
   I believe Martinez. I think he'll be a fine No. 2 starter. But
here in the Late Spring Training Asylum, Opening Day can't come
soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
