<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-THRASHERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BEAT THRASHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One team is going to the playoffs, the other is going
home. But for the Los Angeles Kings and Atlanta Thrashers, there
was more than the sight of old teammates that bonded them Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Both are learning the importance of hard work at a time in the
season when it might be easier to sit back and watch others skate
by.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings regrouped from Saturday's embarrassing tie in Boston
to defeat the expansion Thrashers 4-1 in front of 15,857 at Philips
Arena. It gave them five out of a possible six points on their
three-game East Coast trip and 86 for the season with six games to
play.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the victory also extended the Thrashers' home winless
streak to 16. They have just two victories in their last 32 games.
But this is a point in the year when players continue to sweat in
order to make the team next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is no fun for them,'' said Bob Corkum, who
assisted on Brad Chartrand's second-period goal that gave the Kings
the lead for good. ``I was on the Ducks in their first season
(1993-94) and it was tough. But Atlanta was the perfect team for us
because they are playing for their futures. After Saturday, we
needed to get shaken a little. Wedid that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The game already presented plenty of emotion when Kelly
Buchberger and injured Nelson Emerson, acquired from Atlanta at the
trade deadline, returned. Buchberger was the Thrashers' captain and
scored the first goal in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger, who addressed the Kings before the game, received a
thunderous ovation between the first and second periods when an
interview was shown on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   And Donald Audette, disgruntled almost all season before the
Kings sent him to the Thrashers, assisted on Atlanta's only goal.
</P>
<P>
   The best sign for the Kings was their return to form after
taking off the first two periods of Saturday's game in Boston.
After the seldom-used Chartrand gave them the lead, the Kings
finished off Atlanta with a goal by Glen Murray (four in four
games, No. 27 for the year) and an empty netter by Ian Laperriere.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important was the performance of goaltender Stephane
Fiset, who was pulled in Saturday's game. He will be the Kings
starter when the playoffs start in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray made a point Saturday that he wasn't
blaming Fiset for the team's meltdown in Boston. And Fiset said
Sunday he did not hold ill feelings toward teammates for laying
down on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never blamed them,'' said Fiset, who refused to speak after
Saturday's game. ``I was angry at myself. I was a little nervous at
first tonight. It's always a little strange when you come back
after getting pulled. I have confidence in my play and after a
couple of shots I was right in the game. I knew things were going
to go well after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille scored first for the Kings, just five minutes
into the second period. After going nine games without a goal, he
has three in his last three games and 36 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hnat Domenichelli tied it less than two minutes later after
Audette passed in front of Fiset. But the Kings were in no mood for
another letdown. For Chartrand, who broke his jaw in the minors in
January, it was his sixth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of jump from our third and fourth lines,'' Murray
said. ``I was very pleased with the way we played tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray couldn't say that after Saturday's game, when the Kings
came back after spotting Boston a three-goal lead. He yelled
between the second and third period of that game and even threw a
stick against the wall. Even though the Kings tied that game,
Murray refused to speak to them afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke one of my rules,'' he said. ``I always talk to the
team no matter what. But tonight I think we've learned you can't
take any games off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
