<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-NORTHCAROLINA-TUL     03-27 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHCAROLINA-TULSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RECORD, N.C., GUTHRIDGE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A team from the Atlantic Coast Conference will
be traveling to Indianapolis for the Final Four this week. It's a
team from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the people on Tobacco Road wrote the script when
the NCAA tournament began two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But most people, other than a few loyalists residing in Chapel
Hill, figured the team would be Duke, No. 1 in the country and
top-seeded in the East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the script was changed dramatically by a North Carolina
team that simply refused to accept its casting as bit player.
</P>
<P>
   In a back-to-the-future performance at the Erwin Center, the Tar
Heels acted like, well, North Carolina with a vintage performance
that resulted in a 59-55 win over Tulsa in the South Regional
final, earning the program its 15th trip to the Final Four and
third in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   That North Carolina got there as an eighth seed _ with a 22-13
record some considered more befitting the NIT than the NCAAs _
matters not an iota to the Tar Heels, who will face East Regional
champion Florida in the RCA Dome on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That North Carolina is two wins away from its third national
championship, while Duke is back in Durham following its loss to
Florida Friday night in an East semifinal, makes it even more
surreal and satisfying for the Heels and coach Bill Guthridge,
making his second Final Four appearance in his three years as head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long, strange trip,'' said sophomore forward
Kris Lang. ``We have been considered underdogs in every game, and
we have been proving people wrong during the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the latest case in point. Tulsa, despite its low
(seventh) seed, was as hot as any team in the country. The Golden
Hurricane entered the game with 32 wins in 36 games, the most
victories of any team in the tournament. And their four losses had
been by a combined 7 points, each coming in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Carolina took control from the start, setting the
pace largely because of the play of guard Joseph Forte, the first
freshman to lead Carolina in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   All the 6-foot-4-inch Forte did was score a game-high 28-points
in 39 minutes, displaying more poise than anyone else on the court.
He was named the Most Outstanding Player of the regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go home,'' said Forte, who made 10 of 17
shots and pulled down eight rebounds. ``I shoot the most, so I
should make most of my shots and take us to Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come easy. Very little does when playing Tulsa.
Earlier in the tournament, the Hurricane had taken apart bigger
teams such as Cincinnati and Miami with first-half scoring binges
that hit with the ferocity of the storm for which the team is
named.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels didn't let that happen to them, however, as a half
in which there were 17 ties or lead changes ended with Carolina
leading, 31-30.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Hurricane used up a lot of energy in containing a
Carolina front line that included 7-foot, 264-pound Brendan
Haywood, 6-8, 224-pound sophomore Jason Capel, and 6-11, 243-pound
Lang. Outside of 6-10 Brandon Kurtz, Tulsa didn't have a man in its
rotation taller than 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't bother me that much,'' said Kurtz, who had 11
points and nine rebounds and more than held his own against Haywood
(8 points, 8 rebounds). ``We've been playing against bigger teams
all season. By no means were we intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Carolina, which had faced a tougher brand of
competition all season. After 15 minutes of serious jousting to
start the second half, the Tar Heels had a 51-41 lead, the biggest
advantage anyone had built on Tulsa all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tulsa is a good team,'' said Capel, the only player on the
floor who played all 40 minutes, scoring 8 points and pulling down
six rebounds. ``I knew they weren't going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Stunningly, it was Carolina that almost went into a tournament
death spiral, starting with senior point guard Ed Cota.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Carolina fans among the crowd of 16,731 were
starting their ``Final Four'' chants, Cota had the ball stripped
twice in the final 30 seconds by Tulsa freshman Dante Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, with 20.7 seconds left, Carolina's lead was down to 2,
at 57-55. And when Cota made only one of two foul shots with 18.0
seconds left, Tulsa had a golden opportunity, trailing by 3 with
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired at the end,'' said Cota. ``One of the turnovers, I
lost on my own. The last one Swanson did a great job. I'm not going
to blame it on being tired. I could have let Joseph bring the ball
up, but I wanted to take control.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes took control out of his hands, but when Tulsa's
David Shelton was pressured into a poor shot with 5 seconds left,
the Tulsa ride had come to an end. Carolina's, meanwhile, was
continuing to a place not even the most diehard Tar Heels fan had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to death,'' said Guthridge, who flew to Kansas
immediately after the game for the funeral of his 96-year-old
mother. He paid tribute to his players, saying, ``They really hung
in there all year through some difficult times and helped keep me
going. To be going to the Final Four is a real thrill for all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   So Carolina, with more losses than any Tar Heels team since
1990, has reached its sixth Final Four in the last nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Heels win two more? ``They're two good shooting nights
from winning it all,'' said Tulsa coach Bill Self. ``So they can
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be foolish to rule them out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
