<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLORIDA-OKLAHOMASTATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTION KEEPS GATORS IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ All season long, he preached fearlessness to
his players, but when his precocious and talented basketball
players faced the biggest game of their lives against third seed
Oklahoma State in Sunday's NCAA East Regional final at the Carrier
Dome, Florida coach Billy Donovan was fearful his fifth-seeded
Gators would not be able to reprise the physical effort they
submitted in Friday night's momentous victory over top-seeded Duke
in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   So Donovan appealed to his team's sense of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Using a motivational tactic that he came up with Sunday morning
after talking by phone with Ray Pelletier, a friend of the program
who is a motivational speaker, Donovan huddled with his players and
asked each to single out a loved one, someone near and dear. He
asked each player to dedicate Sunday's game to them by having them
write the name of that person on a piece of tape and wrap it around
their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   When times got tough on the court, they were to refer to it for
a little inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Splendid sophomore forward Mike Miller scrawled ``My Family'' on
his piece of tape, as did freshman guard Justin Hamilton. Sophomore
guard Teddy Dupay wrote ``Mom and Dad.'' Major Parker dedicated his
game to ``Grandma'', while sophomore center Udonis Haslem honored
his deceased brother, Sam, who was the first person to put a
basketball in his hand and taught him not to be afraid of the older
and bigger guys on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you're playing or doing something for someone you
love, you have a tendency to try to dig down a little bit deeper,''
said Donovan, who knows of such things after doing the same in
Providence College's improbable run to the 1987 Final Four. ``And
with eight minutes left in the game _ a 3-point game _ they reached
down inside and found a way to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about the Big Dig. With 7:57 remaining and Florida clinging
to a 56-53 lead, the Gators dug deep and found the resolve to
withstand Oklahoma State's 20-6 run that whittled a 17-point lead
to 3. The Gators held on for a euphoric 77-65 victory that lifted
Florida to its second Final Four in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, who got a team-high 14 points from Miller, voted the
regional's most outstanding player, will face No. 8 seed North
Carolina, a 59-55 winner over Tulsa in the South Regional, in a
Final Four gathering of the lowest seeds in tournament history at
the RCA Dome in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, we were right there, but physically we had a tough
time getting it done,'' said Donovan, who will become the sixth
person in NCAA history to play and coach in a Final Four. ``We gave
up three or four 3-point shots right in a row, just because we
could not get there physically. Now against Duke, they spaced us
out, but we got there. It's a tough thing, and I knew it going
through it as a player and I knew it going through it as a coach at
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how deep you are. The emotional and physical part
of playing in a regional semifinal and regional final is an
emotionally and physically draining experience. It's a tough
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half Florida's talented players, coming off the
bench in wave upon wave, inundated Oklahoma State with a
suffocating press. The Cowboys, despite having seven seniors on
their roster, twice trailed by as many as 15 points (33-18 and
35-20) in the first half before pulling within 43-31 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on we looked like our team was in a daze,'' said
Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton, whose team (27-7) got 14 points
from Fredrik Jonzen, 13 from Glendon Alexander, and 12 from Joe
Adkins. ``We did a poor job on the boards (OSU was outrebounded,
35-28). I thought the press didn't bother us that much other than
it speeded us up. We told our team to attack the press.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what Oklahoma State did in the second half,
when the Gators stretched their halftime lead to 50-33. The Cowboys
went on that 20-6 run, hitting 7 of 11 field goals, and getting
timely treys from Desmond Mason (9 points), and Alexander, who hit
one with 7:57 remaining that pulled Oklahoma State within 56-53.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its first-round squeaker over Butler, that's as close as
Florida allowed the game to get. The Gators scored on their next
seven possessions to take control. Miller fueled a 14-4 run by
hitting a pair of free throws and a top-of-the-key trifecta, but it
was Donnell Harvey who punctatuated it with a pair of thunderous
slams, including a particularly vicious lefthanded tomahawk that
gave the Gators a 70-57 lead and sparked a Final Four celebration
from Syracuse to Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we understand what's going on,'' said Miller, when
asked about Florida's relatively subdued celebration. ``Coach does
a good job of motivating us before every game. Today was a classic
way of motivating us. He can prepare us for everything. We know
what's going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
