<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON DIDN'T WANT KINGS TO GET TOO COMFORTABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Of all the statistics to emerge from the Los
Angeles Lakers' dramatic victory over the Sacramento Kings on
Sunday, the one that might matter most is 1-1. Especially as an
alternative to 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had lost two of their last three games at Arco Arena,
including their prior trip here in December. With the Kings
hovering between the bottom two seeds in the West, and the Lakers
at the top, they might be headed for a first-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers might want to win a game or two in these
unfriendly confines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to send them a message,'' coach Phil Jackson said.
``They have a feeling like they can beat us, and they have our
number, and things have gone well for them in fact in the past. But
we need to let them know we're going to beat them regardless of
whether they finish eighth (seeded) or whatever they're going to be
in the playoffs. And this is a good signal (to send) them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are still searching for answers to two matchups in
particular - at power forward, where Chris Webber (28 points) had
his way for most of the day, and at guard, where quick and
unpredictable Jason Williams (21 points) again hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were also playing with a hobbled Vlade Divac and
without injured swingman Peja Stojakovic, who also has had good
games against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well, but we played well enough to get a win
down the stretch,'' said Shaquille O'Neal. ``If we meet this team
in the playoffs, we just have to bring our `A' game every time. And
we will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers again left impressed, however, with both their
opponent and the intensity of the fans at an arena that has become
one of the most intimidating atmospheres in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough arena,'' Glen Rice said. ``Their crowd gets into
the game. It's a tough team also. They've got a lot of talent, they
work very well together....
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big win for us. It's going to help us as far as
confidence-wise, knowing that we can come in here and beat them on
their floor.... I don't think we've played up to our potential each
time we've played them, so if we can execute a lot better on both
ends of the floor, I think the outcome will be even a little easier
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Rookie swingman Devean George and assistant coach
Tex Winter, both suffering from the flu, did not make the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
