<HEADLINE>
JEFF GORDON, NEW TEAM CLOSING IN ON SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Jeff Gordon and his revamped Rainbow Warriors
pit crew returned to familiar territory _ the top 10 of the NASCAR
Winston Cup points standings _ with their most impressive
performances of the season in the Food City 500 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's eighth-place finish at Bristol Motor Speedway matched
his season-best result recorded the previous Sunday at Darlington
(S.C.) Raceway. But Gordon, who began the day wallowing in 13th in
points, had the dominant car on the high-banked, 0.533-mile oval.
Gordon started third and led five times for a race-high 225 laps,
nearly half of the 500-lap distance, before a mishap in the pits
cost him what would have been his first victory of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon pitted as the leader under caution on Lap 386, when he
clipped a stray tire in the box of Steve Park while heading back to
the track. The shot bent the corner of the left front fender of
Gordon's car, prompting him to return three times during the
caution for repairs. That dropped Gordon to 17th on the restart and
doomed an otherwise strong performance for the struggling
three-time Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my fault,'' said Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont
Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I was just trying to
get out of there and beat the 12 \RJeremy Mayfield\S or the 2
\RRusty Wallace\S, and I drove right into it. It wasn't very
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon lost five members of his pit crew to reigning Cup
champion Dale Jarrett's No. 88 Ford Taurus team at the end of last
season. Yesterday, Gordon said crew chief Robbie Loomis and crew
gave him an ``awesome'' race car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were clicking off awesome pit stops and keeping us
out front,'' said Gordon, who had not been in the top 10 in points
during the season's first five races. ``I'm not ashamed of having
to change pit crews at all right now. These guys are consistent and
confident.'' Benson impressive Johnny Benson overcame a 33rd-place
start and a backstretch pit box at BMS to notch a career-best
second-place finish. Benson delivered a terrific morale boost to
the team owned by Texan Tim Beverley heading into the DirecTV 500
at Texas Motor Speedway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said his steady drive to the front _ he moved into second
on Lap 490 of the 500 _ was the result of solid strategy by crew
chief James Ince and a series of super stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took four tires every stop,'' said Benson, driver of the
No. 10 Lycos.com Pontiac Grand Prix. ``We weren't going to try to
gamble on two \Rto gain track position\S _ not where we were at.
And we were just able to stay out of trouble.'' Earnhardt
sideswiped Seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt spent 206 laps
working his way into the lead yesterday before his designs on a
second victory of 2000 came to a grinding halt after an incident
involving Kenny Irwin Jr. in Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin crashed between turns 3 and 4 on Lap 206 and slid down the
36-degree banking. Earnhardt, who had spent the previous eight laps
setting up Jeff Gordon for a pass into the lead, tried to dodge
Irwin's car by running down on the apron. But Irwin's disabled
machine clipped Earnhardt's car in the right rear wheel and
quarter-panel, throwing the rear end housing out of alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt returned after lengthy repairs on Lap 362, en route to
a season-worst 39th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he \RIrwin\s had just held the brakes on, I would have been
all right,'' said Earnhardt, driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench
Service Plus Chevy. ``I'd done committed myself to the low side,
and that's all I could do. I went down there and got whacked.''
Kenseth on a roll Matt Kenseth will race at Texas Motor Speedway
next weekend as a double-leader.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth sits atop the NASCAR Busch Grand National points chase
heading into the Albertson's 300 in Fort Worth on Saturday. And
Kenseth retained his lead in the Winston Cup Raybestos Rookie of
the Year competition with his 12th-place finish in the Food City
500.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal goal is to try to finish in the top 15 every
week,'' said Kenseth, who leads Dale Earnhardt Jr. by eight points
(64-56) going into the Winston Cup DirecTV 500 on Sunday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
