<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LOSE A CLOSE ONE TO AVALANCHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Put your thumb next to your index finger. A little
closer.
</P>
<P>
   As close as you can get without letting them touch.
</P>
<P>
   That tiny space, where light barely sneaks through, is the fine
line separating winning and losing for the Stars on most nights.
Now, squeeze them closer, and realize exactly just how fine that
line got yesterday against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand it's a fine line right now,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``Hell, we played a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas played a better-than-good game up until just that moment
when Avalanche winger Milan Hejduk scored with 1:43 remaining in
overtime. In that second, the Stars' good game turned into a 2-1
loss to the Avalanche at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a fine line for us,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher
said. ``When you are banged up and don't have a healthy team, that
fine line usually does get thinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Try Ally McBeal thin.
</P>
<P>
   So thin that a disallowed goal, a not-quite-yet-jelled second
line and an impotent power play derailed a performance that both
Stars players and coaches characterized as solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the game we wanted to play,'' Stars forward Mike
Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   They did. Right down to Modano's one-time blast of a Jamie
Langenbrunner pass at 6:02 of the first period for a 1-0 lead. It
was the margin of error until 10:28 of the second period, when
Stars winger Brett Hull looked to have scored his 609th career
goal. Only, the goal didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle already had blown. The referees nabbed Stars winger
Kirk Muller for goaltender interference. The Avalanche had a power
play coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have been the right call,'' Muller admitted. ``I went
for an opening. Patrick \RRoy\S turned to kind of make the play and
kind of bumped into me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Muller in the penalty box, the Avalanche once again tried
its] fourth-ranked power play against the best penalty kill in the
league. Thirty-four seconds later, No. 4 beat No. 1, Avs center Joe
Sakic corralling a rebound and lifting it over a sprawled-out Stars
goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had been spectacular until then, with him and Roy
engaging each other in a game of goaltender chicken. One would make
a big save. The other would answer with a bigger save. Belfour
finished with 22. Roy finished with 29. Not including, of course,
the one that didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was big,'' Roy said of the disallowed goal. ``I think
I would be in time for the play if Kirk didn't hit me. ... That's
the dangerous thing if you pass in the crease you can interfere
with goaltenders. The crew made the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 2-0 lead, the Stars would find themselves once
again tied with the Avalanche. Which is nothing new when these
teams play. In the past five meetings between the Stars and
Avalanche, the games have either been tied or one goal apart for
all but eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, that explains Hejduk's NFL-like celebration of his
game-winner. He skated to center ice, did a belly flop and then
took a couple of fake strokes. It was almost as good as the move he
put on Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of my mind happy,'' Hejduk said.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say Belfour wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He outwaited me a little bit and made a nice shot,'' Belfour
said. ``I would like to have it over.''
</P>
<P>
   He may just get his chance, too.
</P>
<P>
   They play again in a week. And the way things are looking, the
Stars and Avalanche will meet again in the second round of the
playoffs. If the Edmonton Oilers, who are only four points back for
the Northwest Division lead, were to overtake the Avalanche, the
meeting would get bumped up to the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly the matchup Colorado wants, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said.
``Especially the way the season has gone, you can't pick and
choose. Whoever is in front of you, you have to raise your arms and
fight. Every team is good and every team has its weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   And the difference between winning and losing is often as small
as the space between your fingers. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
