<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN     03-27 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S HEROICS SPARK LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Some day, perhaps, this kind of thing won't be a
surprise anymore. Eventually, every second of the footage will seem
familiar, expected, routine. Possibly, it's already moving into
that realm.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, game-tying shot. Shaq, game-winning free
throw. Shaq, game-saving blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   Bing. Bang. Boom.
</P>
<P>
   For the Los Angeles Lakers, a comeback victory is as now as easy
as spelling ``M-V-P.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers on the edge of a loss Sunday, in the most
hostile of arenas, against a potential playoff opponent, O'Neal
made a stand - and took one giant leap toward unquestioned
superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   His three-point play with 6.5 seconds left, followed by a swat
of Vlade Divac's potential game-winning shot with time expiring,
lifted the Lakers to an awe-inspiring 90-89 comeback victory in
front of 17,317 stunned faces at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Layups are nothing new to O'Neal, and blocked shots are a
standard. But for the career 53 percent foul-shooter, a
game-winning free throw meant everything for a
championship-aspiring team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big-time,'' teammate Glen Rice said. ``The big fella's
always said, in the crunch time, when it's time to step up and hit
the free throws, he's going to come through. And he's been doing
that. He's been improving on his free-throw shooting. We have all
the confidence in the world with him at the free-throw line.... And
he has a lot more confidence in himself going to the free-throw
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreso since the All-Star break, with O'Neal having settled into
a 60 percent-plus clip. But he was just 3 for 7 on Sunday, when the
Kings foolishly abandoned defending O'Neal in favor of chasing down
Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   With 17.4 seconds remaining, the Kings were clinging to an 89-87
edge after Darrick Martin hit 1 of 2 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Bryant dribbled around the top of the key,
drawing a wave of Kings defenders, including Divac. Bryant stopped,
popped up and zinged a two-hand overhead pass to O'Neal under the
basket, guarded only by 6-foot-1 Jason Williams, who wrapped O'Neal
too late.
</P>
<P>
   The layup dropped through, and O'Neal followed with a free-throw
swish to complete a 34-point night and send the Lakers (59-12) to
their sixth consecutive win and 25th in 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably their plan to hack-a-Shaq. Kobe made an
excellent pass and I got it,'' O'Neal said. ``Me being the type of
player I am, I quicked it to the basket. I knew I was going to make
the free throw all along.''
</P>
<P>
   He trotted back to a bench of proud teammates and a greeting
line of high fives and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's happy for him,'' Robert Horry said. ``When he
first came in the league, everybody was wondering if he was going
be a dominant player. He's showing now he's going to be a dominant
force.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings were stunned by O'Neal's clutch three-point play,
the Lakers were surprised only by the ease with which it unfolded,
with Divac leaving O'Neal alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, absolutely (surprised),'' Bryant said. ``I was like,
damn, there's Shaq all the way under the basket!''
</P>
<P>
   As for making big free throws, it's starting to become an
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our confidence in him has grown as his confidence in
himself has grown as well,'' said Bryant, who finished with 24
points and 14 rebounds. ``When he was on the free-throw line, I
didn't even go for the rebound. I felt pretty comfortable he was
going to make the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Lakers were even in position to win was amazing. They
shot just 38.2 percent and had trailed from the opening tip, abused
for most of the game by Chris Webber's 28 points, 15 rebounds,
eight assists and four blocks, and a 21-point game from Jason
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers held Webber to just six points in the second
half, and he fouled out on a questionable offensive foul with 1:51
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we didn't earn respect yet,'' said Divac, held to six
points.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson was unhappy with everything but the
final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either team played or shot as well as they'd
have liked to in the course of a game like that, but the end result
is dramatic,'' he said. ``(O'Neal's play) is a big
confidence-builder. It's big for us to have him in there at the end
and be a go-to guy that can complete the play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
