<HEADLINE>
RAIN HALTS SUTTON'S MOMENTUM AT TPC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton, not Tiger Woods, had his
right fist pumping and final-round momentum on his side yesterday
at The Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sutton, not Woods, who played 11 bogey-free holes at the
TPC at Sawgrass. It was Sutton, not Woods, who carved out a
three-stroke advantage before the rains came and suspended play
until 8 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sutton, who has preached a fear-no-Tiger gospel to PGA
Tour peers since arriving at the event, who appeared ready to land
a knockout blow to the game's top-ranked player when the horn
sounded with Woods facing a 40-foot birdie putt on the 12th green
and Sutton preparing to chip from the 12th fairway in the day's
final pairing.
</P>
<P>
   How well Sutton's momentum carries over after a fourth
consecutive night to sleep on the lead at the season's richest
event ($6 million) remains to be seen. Sutton left the course
disappointed but exuding confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I would have liked to have kept playing. Everything
was going well,'' said Sutton, who drained a 25-foot birdie putt at
the 11th hole to break a string of 10 consecutive pars. ``It was
going the way I wanted it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, in turn, sounded like a man who welcomed the opportunity
to regroup. After taking a birdie on the first hole to square
matters with Sutton, he logged consecutive bogeys after missed
greens at Nos. 3 and 4. When Sutton dropped his 25-foot birdie putt
at No. 11 to improve to 10 under par for the tournament, Woods
followed by pulling a five-footer off line to remain at 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things aren't going exactly the way I wanted, but I've still
got a good chance of winning,'' Woods said. ``It's much easier to
come from three behind on this golf course. There is a lot of water
and a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods knows a little something about final-round comebacks,
especially at tournaments that have been extended to Monday because
of weather concerns. He rallied from seven strokes back over the
final seven holes Feb. 7 to win the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National
Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Woods reeled in Matt Gogel, a tour rookie. This time,
he's chasing Sutton, a teammate on the 1999 U.S. Ryder Cup team.
Among the 20 players stranded one the course when play was
suspended, none were within six strokes of Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, at 4-under, finished as the leader in the clubhouse.
Essentially, said Sutton, he has seven more holes of one-on-one
combat with Woods. He looks forward to the ongoing challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here looking for an easy win,'' Sutton said. ``I
am not going to look for a way to say poor, pitiful me because of
all this. We still have work to do, and I feel good about the way
I'm swinging at it and the way I'm putting.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Woods, Sutton is well-versed on Monday finishes. Especially
at this course. His victory at the 1983 TPC came after a rain
delay, when competitors played the final round Monday. Until today,
it stood as the only Monday finish in tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in the locker room thinking about that, right
after \Rplay was called\S,'' Sutton said. ``We finished that year
on Monday, and I won. I don't know if that has anything to do with
anything. But it was nice to think about.'' Red in reserve Tiger
Woods, who wears a red shirt during the final round at tournaments
where he competes, said his wardrobe rotation will not be thrown
off by yesterday's suspension of play. He packed an extra one, just
in case. Now, said Woods, he's got a choice.
</P>
<P>
   He can wear his backup red shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or a lot of cologne,'' Woods said, glancing at the
sweat-stained crimson shirt he wore yesterday. Super save Hal
Sutton said his sand save at the eighth hole, when he was forced to
stand on a hill outside the bunker while hitting his approach to 12
feet, ranks ``at the top of the list'' in terms of bunker blasts he
has authored on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have dreamed it any closer than that,'' said
Sutton, who made the 12-footer for par. ``As I'm taking my stance,
I'm thinking, `This could be a real turnaround, one way or the
other.' And I just flushed it. That was real big.'' Briefly Fort
Worth resident Mark Brooks gave back nine strokes to par on the
back nine, including a watery quadruple-bogey at No. 18, to close
with a 79. Brooks' back-nine fade caused him to drop 32 places on
the leader board, into a tie for 57th, pending completion of play
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Tryba and Joe Ozaki recorded aces at No. 8, a 226-yard
par-3, during yesterday's final round. Tryba used a 4-iron, and
Ozaki used a 3-iron.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
