<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-MOMENTS0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oscar moments: Lots of laughs, emotion
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some of the Oscar moments we'll be talking about
today:
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal, predictably sly in scenes that inserted him into
``The Exorcist,'' ``The Godfather,'' ``Psycho,'' ``Casablanca'' and
other films. Jane Fonda, looking superb with her perky short hair.
Supporting actor winner Michael Caine, speaking generously of his
fellow nominees. And Antonio Banderas good-naturedly dragging
director Pedro Almodovar offstage at the end of his rambling
Spanglish acceptance speech. (``He makes (Roberto) Benigni look
like an English teacher,'' quipped Crystal.)
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest moment of the 72nd annual Academy Awards was
also the most fun: Robin Williams singing ``Blame Canada'' from the
``South Park'' movie, accompanied by a comic chorus line and
Mountie-Rockettes. It was a blast of garish fun and a breath of air
in a ceremony that has become tasteful to the point of
petrifaction.
</P>
<P>
   As if determined to maintain the show's punishing length, new
producers Lili and Richard Zanuck padded it with several
self-congratulatory montages of old movie clips, plus a medley of
Oscar-winning tunes. At times it felt like a long commercial, as if
the Zanucks felt it necessary to convince the worldwide viewers
that movies are Fun and Good and Good for You.
</P>
<P>
   Though they were a laughable low point in previous years, the
tacky, overblown interpretive dance numbers were sorely missed.
</P>
<P>
   So don't blame ``Canada.'' Thank heaven for it. It kept us
entertained, at least for a few minutes of the show. Long enough
for Jack Nicholson to come out and introduce his old colleague in
revolutionary filmmaking, Warren Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's acceptance of the Irving G. Thalberg Award was the
evening's other major moment. Part of his rep has been that of the
libido that conquered half of Hollywood. But his real legacy is a
career of pushing the envelope as a multihatted filmmaker. As a
pretty-faced actor in the '60s, he challenged the fossilized studio
way of how things worked. He not only starred in ``Bonnie and
Clyde,'' he developed the script, produced it, pushed Warner Bros.
to release it the right way and walked off with a big chunk of its
profit.
</P>
<P>
   That 1967 film was among a handful that signaled the passing of
the old guard into edgier work reflecting the unease of the Vietnam
War and the emergence of younger filmmakers whose work would flower
in the '70s (Martin Scorsese, Francis Ford Coppola, Steven
Spielberg). Now, he's considered establishment. But as his edgy,
underseen ``Bulworth'' proved: He may be in his 60s, but he's still
a maverick.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
