<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIE LEAVES BRUINS' STOMACHS IN KNOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins booted away a three-goal lead Saturday,
allowing the Los Angeles Kings to climb back into a game they
appeared long out of. In the end, it wound up a 4-4 tie _ the
league-high 18th time this season Boston has ended a contest in a
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   The third period, in which the Bruins surrendered three goals,
was a microcosm of this season. Blown leads, fragile confidence,
shaky execution, and inconsistent goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   Seven games remain in this
unforgettable-for-all-the-wrong-reasons year. If it were a horse,
someone would've shot it a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a three-goal lead, they should be dead in the water,''
said forward Steve Heinze, whose two-goal, one-assist performance
in his first game back from an injury was tarnished by the
collapse. ``We should go out there confident and have a flow and
play well. We didn't do that. They get that goal early and maybe, I
hope not, but it's `Woe is me, here we go again.' Instead of
playing the game, you just start thinking too much. A three-goal
lead in the third period. Shame on us. We shouldn't lose that lead
against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Too true. But this 1999-2000 edition of the Bruins can't get out
of their own way. Blown leads are commonplace. One only needs go
back to March 16, when the Bruins blew two-goal leads three times
on the way to a 5-4 overtime loss to the Blackhawks in Chicago.
Saturday's meltdown was another pretty sour finish to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for it,'' said center Brian Rolston.
``Through two periods, we played very, very strong. In the first
period, we outshot them, 17-4. The second period we came out and
played very strong. We were up by three goals and it's unacceptable
to let a team back in the game like that. We stopped forechecking
in the third period, we didn't have as many chances. We seemed as
if we were back on our heels. I think LA came out strong in the
third, but regardless of that, we needed to do a better job, to say
the least.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no game plan to change strategies at the end of two
periods. Why, with a three-goal lead, would you want to? And yet,
the Bruins began backing up and backing up some more, allowing the
Kings to swarm them in the attacking zone.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston said he could sense trouble when the Kings came out
firing in the third, pulling to within 4-2 at the 48-second mark on
a goal by former Bruin Glen Murray.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the Murray coach Pat Burns had in mind when he
addressed the media after the game, saying this was like the Bill
Murray movie ``Groundhog Day,'' in which Murray's character lives
the same day over and over again. In Burns's case, the Bruins were
blowing leads over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got the power-play goal at the beginning of the
period, everybody starts looking at each other,'' said Rolston. ``I
don't think there's a whole lot of confidence. The first two
periods we were playing with plenty of confidence. Then in the
third, it was like a hand grenade out there, including myself. It's
a matter of being confident in the team and going out there and
doing the job. In the third period, we just weren't really there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, who also played for the Devils and the Colorado
Avalanche this season before coming to Boston, said the Bruins
don't corner the market on going into a defensive shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on teams where it's happened before,'' he said.
``It's not anything (unique to Boston). When I was in New Jersey,
we used to do the same thing; you get up by a couple of goals and
then you go into the conservative mold and try to hang on. We
didn't hang on enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get out of that is to go out in the third and
have a strong effort. If you play 60 minutes strong, those things
aren't going to happen. I think that's one of the most important
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
