<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BUCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPIRITED CELTICS BUCKED OFF TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ This was not the time or place to deliver what Rick
Pitino charitably called ``a clunker.'' But that's what the Celtics
did Sunday in a performance more reminiscent of their
earlier-season road debacles.
</P>
<P>
   Boston dropped a 99-84 decision to the Bucks and now is on the
playoff ledge, three games behind Milwaukee and 4 1/2 behind
Orlando, a team it faces Tuesday night in Hooterville. The Celtics
have lost four in a row. They have 12 games to play.
</P>
<P>
   They all understood the importance of this one. They all knew
they had, basically, no margin for error. So instead of coming out
spirited, determined, and defiant, they instead went the full 48
under water.
</P>
<P>
   They never led. They never were even tied. They never were
closer than 8 points in the final 28 minutes. They allowed the
Bucks free access to the basket as Milwaukee shot 51 percent. They
didn't move the ball (16 assists) or shoot it well (41 percent).
</P>
<P>
   They were, dare we say it, never really in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were into it emotionally or physically,''
said Paul Pierce, who, like everyone else, struggled. He was 4 for
16 from the field. ``That's something I can't understand. The
playoffs are on the line. I was surprised by the way we came out.
It didn't seem like we wanted to be in the game or compete for a
playoff spot from the first jump ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sad, but true. This one looked a lot more like the games the
Celtics played on the road when they were free falling in November
and December. But this is March, the Celtics are playing better,
and they are talking about the playoffs, even though they're closer
to the 12th spot than they are to the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Some MIT professor might be able to create a scenario that has
Boston sneaking in on the last day. Pitino believes his team can
lose once more the rest of the way, which would mean an 11-1
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of that are not very good for us,'' the coach
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino thought Sunday's stinker was as much because of circuit
overload than anything else. The team had lost a devastating,
double-overtime game in Philadelphia Friday night. Two nights
earlier, there had been the crushing last-second home loss to
Minnesota. Two nights earlier than that, another loss, this one in
Phoenix to the Suns. It adds up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the result of four or five back-to-back
wars,'' Pitino said. ``Unfortunately, you can't let it happen
because every game is monumental. You can't use those five wars as
an excuse because there's too much at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to start in this one? The Bucks made a defensive switch,
putting Ervin Johnson on Antoine Walker. You may recall Walker
abused the undersized Darvin Ham the last time these teams met
(Johnson did not play because of back spasms). Walker was limited
to 22 inconsequential points, including a trey in the closing
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Milwaukee got its transition game going, feeding off
turnovers (19, leading to 22 points) and long rebounds from missed
shots (Boston was 4 for 23 from international waters. The Celtics
don't do transition defense and they paid for it, big time. The
Bucks had a 16-2 edge in fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them too many easy baskets,'' said Walker. ``You can't
do that against them because they are a great offensive team and
have a lot of weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   They do, indeed. Ray Allen led the way with 27. Sam Cassell
added 22, including three straight post-ups in the fourth quarter
over Kenny Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to play him aggressive, but I didn't do a good job,''
said Anderson, who had only two assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Cassell hoops were huge because the Celtics had pulled
within 78-70 with 9:01 to play. They had a chance to get closer,
but Cassell swiped an Adrian Griffin pass and fed the streaking
Allen (12 for 20) for an easy basket. That was the first of four
Boston turnovers in a stretch of 2:23. By the time the smoke
cleared, Cassell, who also had 11 assists, was hitting his third
straight jumper over Anderson, blowing the lead out to 14, and
ending whatever hopes the Celtics thought they might have had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
