<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-BESTFILM0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An original `Beauty,' hopeful sign for films
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel-Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everything came up roses Sunday night for ``American
Beauty,'' a satirical and sometimes surreal portrait of suburban
malaise that ends on a curious note of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   What sets this deserving best-picture winner apart is that
there's never been anything quite like it. True,
America-the-Not-So-Beautiful has been a recurring theme in
Hollywood for decades. It probably reached its peak in the
anti-establishment early '70s. However, even then, gifted
filmmakers ranging from Martin Scorsese to Robert Altman only knew
how to say what was wrong with the American Dream. There's nothing
in their work _ wonderful as it is _ that suggests the transcendent
hopefulness of ``Beauty's'' dominant image.
</P>
<P>
   Not the velvety rose petals Kevin Spacey's character summons up
from his long-dormant libido, but the video of that white plastic
bag dancing in the wind. It's an ineffable image of mystery and
joy.
</P>
<P>
   Director Sam Mendes isn't better than a Scorsese or an Altman.
He simply sees things in his own way, and he's able to make us see
them that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' is unique. It's an original. That it
should've been the favorite as well as the eventual winner Sunday
is good news for any of us looking for signs of intelligent,
creative life in the Hollywood universe.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is exactly what its title says: American and a beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
