<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-R.MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ HAS SOUND STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ There will be days, Ramon Martinez said, when
he will fall far short of what paying customers demand. And he
knows what that means in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get booed back in Boston,'' he said after giving
up four runs in five innings in a 5-4 loss to the Pittsburgh
Pirates before another sellout (6,348) at City of Palms Park.
``They booed my brother Pedro when he had some rough times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a little bit about how Boston fans are. If you don't
do too good, they'll boo you. I expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro the Younger, dressing in the next cubicle, muttered an
aside. ``That's why they call it Boos-Town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Pedro the Younger was struggling, he said
that as much as he'd like to be reunited with Ramon, he wouldn't
want that to happen if it meant hearing his brother booed like he
was.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon the Elder doesn't sound too worried. In 1995, he was stung
when he heard his first boos during his long reign as a Dodger, and
responded by throwing a no-hitter against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very important year,'' he said. ``You
guys don't know the way I pitch. Maybe you've seen me on TV, and
Joe Kerrigan saw me in Montreal, but I know myself. I know
sometimes I get my butt kicked. The next time I come back again.
I'm very competitive that way. I never give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be games when I walk four guys, five guys. Who
knows, it's happened before. You may see some great games, too. You
can expect anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who gave up seven runs on eight hits and a walk
against the Twins Monday, breezed through the first three innings
Sunday, allowing just an infield hit by Warren Morris in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Aven hit a slicing double to left-center to open the
fourth and scored on John Vander Wal's double to right-center.
Wilfredo Cordero scored Vander Wal with a line single that Martinez
just missed (``I closed my glove too soon.'').
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Mike Benjamin, the ex-Sox infielder with the Elvis
sideburns, beat out an infield hit and scored on a home run by
Aven, who jumped on a hanging changeup from Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Martinez threw 73 pitches. He averaged 86-88 miles an
hour on his fastball, touching 90 a couple of times. He
occasionally overthrew his rising fastball, but otherwise
pronounced himself satisfied with his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite there yet,'' he said, ``but it's a matter of
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
