<SLUG> BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN IS THE HUNTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND _ Sue Gunter, the Louisiana State University women's
basketball coach, doesn't have the intensity of Tennessee coach Pat
Summitt, the glamour of former Purdue coach Carolyn Peck (she's
with the WNBA now), or the name recognition of Connecticut coach
Geno Auriemma.
</P>
<P>
   But Gunter has one thing over all of them _ longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Gunter, 58, has been a college coach for 36 years, the past 18
at LSU. She's the fourth-winningest coach in the NCAA with 613, is
a two-time Southeastern Conference Coach of the Year, and guided
the Olympic teams in 1978 and 1980. She played guard at Nashville
Business College and was a member of the national team from
1960-62.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've had a love affair with this game for that many
years,'' Gunter said. ``My office is a gymnasium.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gunter is the first to acknowledge that all of her
experience on the court won't make a difference when her team faces
UConn in the NCAA East Regional final Monday night. Her team (25-6)
is young (only one senior) and short (its two tallest starters are
5 feet 11 inches), and never has made it beyond the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   So how does she plan on neutralizing the Huskies (33-1), who
have made it to Final Four three times, and were national champions
in 1995?
</P>
<P>
   You just try, she said, noting that only one team _ Tennessee _
has been successful this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to dictate the tempo of a game, but I don't
know how you do that with UConn,'' Gunter said. ``You want to be
aggressive enough to try to get them to be in a little bit of foul
trouble. But their depth is so good, that's almost of no
consequence to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the size, the speed . . . '' she said, as her voice
trailed off. ``The thing is, I don't have an answer to that
question. And you know what? I don't feel bad about it at all,
because there are a whole lot of other coaches who haven't had the
answer, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunter said her team knows what's in store. ``The players know
what they're faced with,'' she said. ``UConn is on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the way Auriemma sees it. ``It's like the Holy
Grail, what everybody wants, what everything leads up to,'' he
said. ``Just the stakes that are involved _ at the beginning of the
season everyone talks about the Final Four. It's kind of like
climbing Mt. Everest. You climb and climb, but the last couple
hundred yards are unbelievably hard, probably the hardest that you
have. And that's probably the way it should be. The closer you get
to something you really want, the harder you have to fight to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For Auriemma, the game has even more significance when he thinks
back to a year ago. After the team won the first two NCAA tourney
games on its home court, the Huskies got knocked out of the East
Regional by Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Auriemma said, the team that played without point guard
Sue Bird all last year is healthy and prepared. ``I feel pretty
good, because we're even better than we were in December. We've
made giant strides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If LSU presents any problem, Auriemma said, it's in that the
Huskies and Lady Tigers never have played. ``I know LSU's not going
to be an easy team in a lot of ways, because we don't know that
much about them, so they're hard to get a handle on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he should be worried. The Huskies, who had all 12
players enter Saturday's 102-80 win over Oklahoma, are averaging
100.3 points in their first three NCAA games.
</P>
<P>
   LSU, ranked 15th nationally, defeated Duke, 79-66, in the
semifinal game Saturday behind Marie Ferdinand's 22 points. The
Tigers led the SEC in field-goal percentage (49.2) and assists
(20.2), and had the fewest turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   But Gunter said she's pragmatic. ``Sure, we're going to try to
come up with something, but I'm not about to broadcast that we're
going to have an upset,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to UConn, Gunter said, there's no reason to mince
words. ``I'm too old for hype; they are damn good,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
