<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS FIND THAT SECOND LINE STILL A TOUGH ONE TO FILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The season has been like a Rubik's Cube in progress.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the Stars hope, the pieces will fall magically into
place, their planets will become mystifyingly realigned, and they
will be the team that they are supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, however, there are days like Sunday. ...
</P>
<P>
   Once Mike Modano staked the home team to a 1-0 lead over the
Colorado Avalanche, the Stars could not find another piece of the
puzzle to fall into place. The 2-1 defeat was punctuated further by
a golden two-on-one chance in overtime that Joe Nieuwendyk and
Brett Hull could not cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great pass,'' Nieuwendyk said afterward in a locker
room that seemed roundly annoyed to have let the day slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm sharp and focused, that's a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   On a steal at center ice, Hull had found himself leading the
two-on-one with Nieuwendyk slicing down the left side and only
defenseman Jon Klemm to beat. Hull made the right decision, but the
puck somehow found the air under Nieuwendyk's stick.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, there was Colorado's Milan Hejduk working his
stick, sending the Stars' Darryl Sydor sprawling, and scoring the
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Reunion Arena crowd let out an audible arrrgh.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it was a decent day, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
tried to say. He cited his team's ``effort'' and ``good strong
play,'' and chose not to dwell on any festering issues.
</P>
<P>
   Issues such as his second scoring line, for instance. For
various reasons, it continues to underachieve.
</P>
<P>
   But at playoff time, you can't leave home without it. (See
``Stars, 1998 playoffs, post-Bryan Marchment''.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You need depth,'' Modano said Sunday. ``You need scoring not
only from your second line, but your third line, too. Depth at this
point in the year is crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the night Hull became the 12th player in NHL history to
score 600 goals, he has scored seven times _ seven goals in three
months. Nieuwendyk, meanwhile, missed 34 games due to injury and
has exactly three goals since the week before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock won't stop working the Rubik's Cube. Sunday, he spun
the blocks again and sent out a second line of Hull, Kirk Muller
and Aaron Gavey. Nieuwendyk was relegated to the fourth line,
alongside Jon Sim and Grant Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   But by the second period, the cube had been shifted again.
Nieuwendyk was back skating alongside Hull on the second line.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Nieuwendyk was hampered by the flu Sunday. His
season, on the whole, has been a medicine cabinet of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's starting to slowly get it back,'' Modano observed. ``I
think everything is going to be coming together at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's the plan, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be good if we would get it established so we could have
more punch in that area,'' Hitchcock said, politely.
</P>
<P>
   To the coach, however, lines seem made to be tinkered with, to
be juggled, to be mixed and remixed like an ongoing chemistry
project. Most players hate that.
</P>
<P>
   But Nieuwendyk defused the line-juggling question Sunday almost
before it left the interviewer's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good, to be honest,'' he said. ``I just need
some more time. But I feel good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The deeper the scoring punch, the more match-up problems that
the Stars will cause in the playoffs. Hitchcock is getting more
than ample scoring chances from the line of Modano, Jamie
Langenbrunner and Brenden Morrow. The three have 68 goals between
them.
</P>
<P>
   But somebody else is going to have to step up in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if we see these guys again,'' Hitchcock mused, ``the
difference is going to be how much our second-wave attack improves
and gives us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, of course, could be host to the Avalanche again as
early as the first round of the playoffs. A more likely scenario
would have the teams meeting in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line,'' Hitchcock said. ``For 60 minutes, it
was a 1-1 hockey game. That's just how close the competition is
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As close as an inch, the Reunion crowd was reminded Sunday. The
Stars came that close Sunday to being the overtime winners and
being asked about the bold message they had just sent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Joe Nieuwendyk and Brett Hull are still trying to find
each other, not to mention the net.
</P>
<P>
   They have two weeks to solve the puzzle.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
