<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-MICHIGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD PERIOD IS CHARM FOR BLACK BEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Deja vu?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   When the University of Maine defeated Michigan, 5-2,
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in the NCAA tournament East Regional at Pepsi Arena,
it became the second Hockey East representative to qualify for the
Frozen Four in Providence, joining Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears will play North Dakota April 6 at 2 p.m.; BC
faces St. Lawrence at 7.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Maine, which won it all, was one of three Hockey East
color-bearers, along with New Hampshire and BC.
</P>
<P>
   Maine, the Hockey East tournament winner, was a tower of
strength as it eliminated CCHA entry Michigan with a five-goal
third period, out-slugging a team that was in the regionals for the
10th consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   The contest was schedued to start at 3:30, but because of the
four-overtime game between Boston University and St. Lawrence, it
didn't get under way until 7:02.
</P>
<P>
   Maine simply blitzed the Wolverines in the third. Ben Guite's
second goal made it 2-2, and then Chris Heisten took a feed from
brother Barrett and scored what proved to be the winner. Matthias
Trattning and Brendan Walsh added insurance tallies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the possibility of repeating, Maine coach Shawn Walsh said,
``We're closer to a legacy. I feel we're in a golf match _ we won
the first three holes and we have six to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was not upset when his team was down after two periods.
``We've been behind in five of our last eight games,'' he said.
``We just kept rolling, and it paid off. Our game plan was to keep
throwing four lines on the ice, and we knew something good would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was to stay focused. We knew Michigan was tired
after that Colgete game Saturday and we hadn't played because of
our bye. It all worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan was indeed a tad slow following the 4-3 overtime win
over Colgate and the loss of defenseman Dave Huntzicker. While the
Wolverines were toiling Saturday, the Maine delegation looked on,
the bye being the perk of the top seed.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, Michigan's Hobey Baker Award candidate, Mike
Comrie, was flying around the rink trying to make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Brad Fraser was sent off for holding at 17:09. His
team down a man, Comrie sped in alone on Matt Yeats and beat the
Maine goalie with a neat backhander from 15 feet out. For Comrie,
it was his 23d goal and 58th point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Jay Vancik was caught for interference at 4:21 of the
third, and the Maine power play finally worked. Guite rammed home
an 8-footer from the left of the crease at 5:14, his 21st goal.
Niko Dimitrakos assisted.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Heisten was caught cross-checking at 6:21, and it proved
costly. The elusive Comrie scored his second at 6:52 when he tipped
in a shot by Mike Cammalleri. Jed Ortmeyer also assisted.
</P>
<P>
   Maine bounced right back and Guite hit again at 8:01 with a
rapid 10-footer with help from Cory Larose and Cliff Loya. It was
2-2, the house was alive, and the Black Bears weren't done yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
