<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS     03-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES ARE ON FAMILIAR PERCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Boston College already had used its one timeout
and there was less than a minute to play against Michigan State
Friday night. Still, as they had most of the night, the Eagles
trailed.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a third straight trip to the NCAA Frozen Four looked
grim. A season that started with the Eagles the top-ranked team in
the nation was about to end well short of that.
</P>
<P>
   And then Michigan State, eager to close out the Eagles and maybe
with one hungry eye on the empty BC net, from where Scott
Clemmensen had departed for an extra attacker, got caught with too
many players on the ice and took a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen stayed on the bench so BC had a six-skaters-to-four
edge. As the call was made, the Eagles' big guns got a chance to
take a quick break. Defenseman Mike Mottau, who does not get many
of those, went to the bench for just a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of funny,'' Mottau said. ``I was sitting there and
I'm thinking, `Something has got to happen. This isn't my last
shift in college hockey.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Something did. It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   And the Eagles are headed for their third straight Frozen Four.
It's the first time BC has been there three times in a row since
the first three years of the tournament in 1948, '49, and '50. It
was in 1949 that the Eagles won their only national title, beating
Dartmouth, 4-3, in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' Mottau said. ``We've been there the last two
years and this year I think we're going to get over the hump with
that experience factor. We're just due.''
</P>
<P>
   It was near midnight Saturday now and Mottau and his mates were
all smiles as they packed to leave Minneapolis. Early word was
their charter flight didn't have room for their equipment and it
might be late getting home so they might not practice until
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Much had happened since that desperate last minute against
Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles scored to send the game into overtime. Scored again
to win it. Mottau, who earlier Friday passed David Emma as BC's
alltime assist leader and now has 130, helped set up both. Then BC
came out and beat up on the Badgers from Wisconsin for a 4-1 win
Saturday night that delivered a spot in the Frozen Four next week
in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   BC plays St. Lawrence in one semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were loose and flying against Wisconsin, and Mottau
hopes they will be again in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into this game, I really felt like there was no pressure
on us,'' Mottau said. ``They were the No. 1 team. We had all the
pressure on us at the beginning of the year with the No. 1. There
is a little bit of pressure. Everyone is saying you're No. 1 and if
you get behind in a game or whatnot, you hear the `overrated'
chant, stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans did yell ``overrated, overrated'' Saturday night late
in the BC-Wisconsin game _ likely aimed at Wisconsin and led by the
North Dakota fans who hung around after their team beat Niagara.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was for them,'' Mottau said with a laugh. ``I
hope it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Wisconsin coach Jeff Sauer had it figured, the BC-Badger
game was the next best thing to a title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it as for the national championship,'' Sauer said. ``I
felt that if we could win, we would have a good chance at winning
the national title.''
</P>
<P>
   Mottau may think his team is due, but he's not as bold as Sauer.
He just hopes his team uses the same approach it took against
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just excited to be here,'' he said. ``We're just
having fun. Instead of letting the pressure get to you, play loose
and play with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked last weekend. The Eagles will try to make it work for
two more games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blake Bellefeuille, BC's sometimes-overlooked big-play maker,
was named Most Valuable Player of the West Regional. Bellefeuille
had a shorthanded goal and won the draw that set up the last-minute
tying goal against Michigan State, and had the first goal against
Wisconsin. ``He's a strong, hard-nosed player. Very, very gifted,''
said BC coach Jerry York. ``You can only have so many Hobey Bakers.
He was certainly a candidate for that.'' . . . For only the second
time, one school put three players among the Hobey Baker finalists
when BC's Brian Gionta, Jeff Farkas, and Mottau made the cut . . .
Farkas and Mottau both were named to the all-tournament team in the
West and Gionta just as easily could have made it. North Dakota
forward Jeff Panzer and defenseman Mike Commodore both made the
all-tourney team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
