<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-OWNERSMEETINGS-BO     03-27 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERSMEETINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COATES DEAL ON TAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ben Coates may be a Tennessee Titan before
you finish your coffee this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Reese, general manager of the American Football Conference
champion Titans, said Sunday at the NFL owners' meetings that he
could finalize a deal for Coates within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with his agent and gave him two contract offers for
Ben,'' said Reese. ``If there are no problems, we expect to sign
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates was released by the Patriots after the season, and there
was little interest in him until the Titans' starting tight end,
Jackie Harris, opted to go to the Dallas Cowboys in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run a lot of our offensive stuff with three tight ends, so
when we lost Harris, we had to find another one,'' said Tennessee
coach Jeff Fisher. ``We had Ben in to talk last week and had a good
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had some interest in former Dolphin Troy Drayton, but
word is his knees are so bad, unless a team was desperate, he
wouldn't be able to pass the physical.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appears instant replay will be a slam dunk to return for the
2000 season when the owners vote on the issue this week. Replay
passed, 28-3, last year, and one of the no votes came from the
Jets. Word is they will vote yes this year. That means any
opposition would have to change six yes votes from last year to no
votes this year, and that isn't going to happen. The opposition
needs eight votes to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top of the draft appears to be shaping up. The first pick
will be defensive lineman Courtney Brown of Penn State, to
Cleveland. Washington has the second and third choices and will
take linebacker LaVar Arrington of Penn State and tackle Chris
Samuels of Alabama. Peter Warrick, the highly publicized wide
receiver from Flordia State, probably will go north to Cincinnati.
Ravens GM Ozzie Newsome has the fifth pick and says he will take
either the best running back or wide receiver still on the board.
Baltimore owner Art Modell says his team will not trade its pick.
It was speculated that pick would be part of a deal with the Jets
to bring wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some veteran owners will be pushing commissioner Paul Tagliabue
to bring all of the possible misuses of the salary cap to the floor
for discussion at Monday's owners-only session. The heat will be on
Tagliabue to punish the San Francisco 49ers for cap violations, or
penalize former team president Carmen Policy and former GM Dwight
Clark. Policy and Clark now are with Cleveland. Also, some owners
want to hear more about Denver possibly having circumvented the cap
by deferring some salaries of veteran players. John Elway's name
has been involved in this issue. Pittsburgh turned itself in for a
possible cap violation, and has agreed to a sanction, which has yet
to be decided, pending the outcome of a court action in Minnesota
over the entire cap issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite what ABC might say, former Jets coach Bill Parcells
turned down a job as an analyst on ``Monday Night Football.''
Parcells and his agent both talked with ABC officials, and Parcells
decided that he didn't need the travel or the scrutiny that goes
with being on the Monday night game each week. ABC reportedly
denied it offered the job to Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins have big plans to honor retired quarterback
Dan Marino. Sometime early in the 2000 season, hopefully during a
nationally televised night game, Marino will have his No. 13
retired. There also will be a statue of him placed in front of the
Dolphins' stadium, joining those of original Miami owner Joe Robbie
and Hall of Fame coach Don Shula. The Dolphins also are thinking of
having another day for Marino during which fans who are not season
ticket-holders can come to the stadium to honor the quarterback,
with the proceeds going to charity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
