<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WORLDFIGURESKATING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKATING WORLD IS WHIRL OF ACTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ The global toe-pick crowd was supposed to be Down
Under this week, introducing the compulsory dance to baffled
Australians.
</P>
<P>
   Then the International Skating Union decided the Aussies
couldn't be trusted to telecast triple axels to the rest of the
planet, so it yanked the World Figure Skating Championships out of
Brisbane and dropped them here just as the topless season is
starting on the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone is complaining. Once the endless qualifying
rounds are done (eight hours for the men Monday, seven for the
women Wednesday), there'll be ample time to take in the salt air
along the Promenade des Anglais, haggle over violets at the Marche
aux Fleurs, wolf down salade nicoise, and try to break the bank up
the road in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are better here at the Palais des Expositions, where
all four crowns are likely to change hands by Saturday night. That
never has happened in midquadrennium, but two switches are certain.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze, the two-time pairs
champions, were pulled out Sunday by the Russian federation after
Berezhnaya tested positive for a banned substance at last month's
European championships in Vienna. (She claimed she accidentally
took medication for bronchitis.) And dancers Anjelika Krylova and
Oleg Ovsyannikov, also two-time champs, are down for the season
because of her aching back.
</P>
<P>
   The other two defenders, Alexei Yagudin and Maria Butyrskaya,
both are coming in as underdogs to countrymen Evgeny Plushenko and
Irina Slutskaya. As for the Americans, they'll be happy to hang on
to what they got last year _ a silver from Michelle Kwan and a
bronze from Michael Weiss. The four-medal days are over.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at this week's events:
</P>
<P>
   MEN:
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin hasn't been the same since getting kicked off last
year's Champions on Ice tour for alcohol-related misbehavior.
Plushenko, the 17-year-old springbok, has gone from nowhere to
bronze to silver in three years. This time, he should be golden.
Canada's Elvis Stojko, the three-time champ, is back on form after
his Olympic miseries. If he skates clean, the Americans could be
crowded off the podium. Weiss will have to hit the quad to have a
chance at a medal. The better shot may belong to Tim Goebel, who
landed three quads at the US nationals but has since split with
longtime coach Carol Heiss.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN:
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya, who became the oldest women's champion in history
(at 26) when she lifted Kwan's crown last year in Helsinki, now
looks like a one-night wonder. Slutskaya, who didn't even make the
Russian team last year after getting fat and formless, has won
everything in sight this season. The X factor is Kwan, who is
trying to become the only woman in history to regain her crown
twice. If she skates two clean programs, she can win. But Kwan,
who's been juggling skating with her UCLA studies, hasn't managed
that in a major event since the Olympics. Sarah Hughes, who was
seventh last year at age 13, could crack the top five now.
</P>
<P>
   PAIRS:
</P>
<P>
   Even if Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze had competed, they weren't
favored. China's Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo should have beaten them
last year and did beat them at the Grand Prix final. Poland's
Dorota Zagorska-Mariusz Siudek, Russia's Maria Petrova-Alexei
Tikhonov, and France's Sarah Abitbol-Stephane Bernardis will scrap
for silver and bronze. No chance for US champs Kyoko Ina-John
Zimmerman, who were ninth last year. If Tiffany Scott of Hanson,
Mass., and partner Philip Dulebohn can crack the top dozen, it'll
be a solid world debut.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE:
</P>
<P>
   The Russians haven't lost this event since 1991, but they will
this time. With Krylova-Ovsyannikov and Canada's Shae-Lynn
Bourne-Victor Kraatz both out, it's a walkover for France's Marina
Anissina-Gwendal Peizerat, the two-time runners-up. And if Italy's
Barbara Fusar-Poli-Maurizio Margaglio and Lithuania's Margarita
Drobiazko-Povilas Vanagas are on form, the Russians could be shut
out of the medals for the first time since 1968. US champs Naomi
Lang-Peter Tchernyshev, 10th last year, should climb up to eighth,
but no higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
