<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERSCHAMPIONSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON LEADS RAIN-DELAYED TPC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ For Hal Sutton, this morning's
breakfast will feature coffee, cereal, and a sand wedge from 82
yards.
</P>
<P>
   That is the shot that awaits him in his quest to put a stop to
Tiger Woods's domination on the PGA Tour. He was doing quite well
Sunday, thank you, until he ran into an opponent that is
unquestionably unbeatable _ Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   A severe thunderstorm moved in and pounded northern Florida late
in the afternoon, putting a stop to the final round of The Players
Championship. Sutton, after making 10 straight pars, drained a
cross-country birdie putt at the par-5 11th to get to 10 under and
led Woods by three shots when play was halted.
</P>
<P>
   When action resumes at 9, Sutton faces a short approach to the
358-yard, par-4 12th, with Woods already on the green staring at a
putt that doesn't exactly give him visions of birdies. ``A
straight-forward putt,'' said Woods, with a slight grin. ``I think
I saw it as either a double- or triple-breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   He could afford to be somewhat lighthearted, as his reputation,
shall we say, precedes him. It wasn't long ago that Woods came from
seven shots down with seven holes to play to win the AT&AMP;T Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am, and there is the small detail of 10 wins in
his last 16 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, (Sutton) is feeling pretty good at having a
three-shot lead,'' said Woods, ``but if I can go out there and hit
some solid shots and convert some putts, hopefully I can make this
thing a little interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The halt was disappointing, said Sutton, because ``everything
was going well. It was going the way I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention that it required an added round of questions
about his mind-set in taking on Woods, a subject that is beginning
to tax some Tour regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said this about as many different ways as I can say
this,'' said Sutton, carefully choosing his words. ``This is not a
Tiger Woods-Hal Sutton duel. You all can make of it what you want,
but I am playing the golf course. I am not going to say any more
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before rain rudely interrupted, he was saying it with his clubs.
As good a ball-striker as there is on Tour _ Woods included _
Sutton hit every green through 11 holes except one. And the one he
missed, the par-3 eighth, resulted in what could prove to be the
key shot if he prevails.
</P>
<P>
   His long iron to the 219-yard hole had come in hot and ran
through the green into the very back of a greenside bunker that
slopes forward. ``I couldn't even stand in the bunker to hit the
shot,'' said Sutton. ``I was thinking: `This could be big here.' I
just made sure that I stayed in the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He had all he could do to keep from falling forward, but Sutton
played it brilliantly. ``I just flushed it. It came out with some
really good spin on it,'' he said. ``I couldn't have dreamed it any
closer (10-12 feet) than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton had missed birdie putts inside of 15 feet on the first
five holes, but this time he nailed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great shot he played out of there,'' said Woods, who
followed that sand save by missing a birdie chance from about 9
feet. ``I completely misread the putt, and I consider myself a
pretty good green-reader. But I played it out there about a foot
and it broke 2 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods had read his putt at the first hole perfectly, a 15-footer
that dropped and tied him with Sutton at 9 under. Any thoughts that
it was an indication of things to come were quickly dashed as, at
the par-5 second, Woods missed a 5-footer for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   He dodged what could have been serious trouble at both the par-3
third and par-4 fourth, however, when Sutton could not convert
short birdie putts on top of bogeys that dropped Woods to 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looked like I was going to lose two shots (at the fourth),''
said Woods, whose approach was long and came to rest in thick rough
20 feet from the pin. When Sutton's 8-footer slid by, Woods, who
had done well to make bogey, breathed a sigh of relief.
``Definitely a gift,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps thinking he should return the favor, Woods _ now two
shots behind _ knocked it much closer than Sutton on the fifth,
sixth, and seventh holes, but failed to drain any of them. When he
didn't birdie the par-5 ninth or par-5 11th, Woods was stuck in a
gear to which he is unfamiliar _ neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously things aren't going exactly the way I wanted,'' said
Woods, staggered by Sutton's momentum until he was saved by the
horn to signal lightning, ``but I am only three back. There's a lot
of golf to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton is well aware of that. In 1983, he won this tournament
with a Monday conclusion. ``I was just thinking about that,'' he
said after play had been officially suspended. ``I don't know if
that has anything to do with anything, but it was nice to think
about, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   If he holds it together for seven more holes, there may be
something more enjoyable to think about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0108EST &QL; 
