<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOW PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ After five years of season-opening road trips, a pattern
is emerging. The Revolution project an image of being rejuvenated
and motivated, but experience some difficult circumstances and
return home with little to show.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern appears to be continuing. The Revolution lost, 1-0,
at Tampa Bay Saturday night and next will visit Los Angeles, which
crushed three-time MLS champion D.C. United, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution have some of the same weaknesses as in the
past, they appear to be developing an effective style of play.
Coach Fernando Clavijo is stressing a possession game, and the
Revolution appear comfortable with the philosophy. They dominated
the second half against Tampa Bay, but were disturbingly inaccurate
in the goal area, and surrendered a 51st-minute goal to Raul Diaz
Arce.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution seldom have dictated the tempo of a
match in such a skillful manner. This is a team that is not relying
solely on work ethic, but appears capable of playing a technical
game and varying the pace of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early in the season,'' captain John Harkes said.
``But our defense was sound and we moved the ball well. If we
continue to play like this, I have no worries about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution kept the Mutiny off balance until the final
seconds, pressuring the goal and remaining composed. The level of
their performance likely would have produced at least a tie in
previous seasons, but MLS opponents are becoming more settled
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dominating, we were aggressive, and we wanted it
more,'' Harkes said. ``We played the ball decisively out of the
back and created chances. But the name of the game is to put the
ball in the back of the net and we were unlucky. It could have been
2-nil in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are seeing is a mature team. We were patient. We
weren't rushing things. We weren't just kicking the ball anywhere,
but we were keeping possession. You are going to have games when
you are the better team and you walk away with nothing. But we
dominated a team which had won its last game, 5-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tampa Bay seemed eager to impose its Carlos
Valderrama-dependent game on the Revolution. And the Mutiny were
confident after a four-goal victory over Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Revolution must contend with the frustration of having
performed well twice, but gaining only one point in the standings.
They have two more road matches before the April 15 home opener
against D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles showed they can play,'' Clavijo said. ``But I like
our chances against them. We have a difficult schedule at the
beginning but we will grow as a team. This team will not get
discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will travel to Los Angeles Wednesday . . .
Eduardo Hurtado will rejoin the Revolution after the
Ecuador-Venezuela World Cup 2002 qualifier in Quito Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
