<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-4-ON-4-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GLAD 4-ON-4 OT ALMOST OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the entertainment buck, four-on-four overtime
hockey has produced the big bang the NHL craved. A five-minute
overtime period suddenly turns a 60-minute game of clutch-and-grab
into a dynamic speed-and-skills competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be more scoring chances and better scoring
chances,'' Stars goalie Ed Belfour said. ``So you have to be ready
for that challenge in overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Stars' perspective, it's time to bring on the playoffs
and bring back five-on-five overtime, where the ice shrinks instead
of expands and the checking becomes tighter, not looser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy it's not going to be played in the playoffs,
really happy, because we have had a tough year four-on-four,''
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said after yesterday's 2-1 overtime loss
to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche winger Milan Hejduk victimized the Stars with a fake
to get by Darryl Sydor, who went down for the block, and then fired
a quick wrister, sending the game-winner buzzing past Belfour with
1:43 left in overtime. It was vintage four-on-four hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's final odd-man rush followed a failed three-on-two
rush by the Stars. Shortly before that scoring chance, Brett Hull
and Joe Nieuwendyk led a two-on-one, but Nieuwendyk couldn't find
the handle on Hull's crossing pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good for the game and good for the fans,'' said
Stars forward Aaron Gavey, who was on the ice when Hejduk scored.
``It's unfortunate we lost. He made a great move, let's not take
anything away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had ample opportunities to prevent overtime in what
was a hotly contested and physical game. Hitchcock praised his team
for a hard-fought battle, accepted the point for finishing
regulation tied and otherwise had little use for the statistic that
says the Stars are 3-5-8 in overtime games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four-on-four is skill and speed,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
haven't had a couple of people like \RBlake\S Sloan, and \RJere\S
Lehtinen all year, and it showed again today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars haven't won an overtime game since downing the New
York Rangers, 4-3, on Dec. 29. Since then, the Stars have lost four
and tied three in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we get caught up in, trying to make the
conservative play rather than taking the gamble,'' center Mike
Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   And while the new overtime system is certainly fun to watch,
it's a faulty way of judging a team. Of the 10 teams who have the
best overtime records, only half are currently holding down playoff
spots.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Islanders rank second in the NHL with a 5-1-8
overtime record, but they aren't even sniffing the playoffs.
Calgary leads the league with 11 overtime wins, but is five points
out of a playoff spot. On the other side, the Edmonton Oilers
(2-8-16) have used the regulation-tie rule to remain in contention
for the Northwest Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the playoffs it shouldn't be in place,'' Stars defenseman
Derian Hatcher said. ``I don't even really like it right now. It's
fun, but I don't think a losing team should get a point.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
