<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-OSCAR-MAIN0327-COX     03-27 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-MAIN0327-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Beauty' of a night
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thank God nobody stole Billy Crystal and left him in a
dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oscars,'' Crystal began his telecast-saving work as host
of Sunday night's eerily ho-hum 72nd annual Academy Awards. ``Or as
ABC likes to call it: Regis' night off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This just in,'' Crystal deadpanned a little later. ``The pope
has apologized for `Deuce Bigalow, Male Gigolo.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just thinking,'' Crystal said after the ethnically tinged
appearances of Polish director Andrzej Wajda and presenters Chow
Yun-Fat and Salma Hayek. ``John Rocker must be going nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The night was ruled by ``American Beauty,'' which won five
awards, including best picture, best actor for Kevin Spacey (``This
is the highlight of my day'') and best director for Sam Mendes.
Hilary Swank won best actress (``Boys Don't Cry'').
</P>
<P>
   Crystal opened the show with a series of ``Gump''-like
appearances in a dozen different movies _ a tried-but-true device
that never fails to make us think that this year's Oscar ceremony
will be the one worth staying up for. Alas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godfather, I don't know what to do,'' Crystal said transported
into a scene from ``The Godfather,'' opposite Marlon Brando.
``These producers don't want any dance numbers. ... It's on a
Sunday, but it'll end on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced as if under water by Richard and Lili Zanuck (producers
of the Oscar-winning ``Driving Miss Daisy''), this year's awards
telecast threw out the dance numbers as part of a promise to move
things along. But with the dances gone, there was nothing to
replace them _ goofy or not, with the hilarious exception of Robin
Williams performing the nominated song ``Blame Canada.'' And the
show still didn't end until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Not only did these Oscars not give us much to love,
they didn't even give us much of what we love to hate. Even Cher
felt terrible for showing up, as a presenter, in the kind of thing
an Earthling might wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably noticed I've dressed as a grown-up,'' she
said. ``I apologize to the academy, and promise I will never do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jack Nicholson, called by Crystal ``still the coolest guy in
the room,'' was no longer that. With his spiked, receding hair and
bloated, neckless head, he looked headed toward the Mickey Rooney
zone of aging badly.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty was stuttering, sputtering and only occasionally
worth listening to while accepting the Irving G. Thalberg Award,
which Rooney, er, Nicholson presented.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked his wife, Annette Bening, due any second with their
fourth child, who, he noted, ``could actually join us any minute
right here in the second row if I don't wrap it up.''
</P>
<P>
   When Crystal wasn't joking, there was little to keep us watching
(``OK,'' Crystal joked just before midnight, with most of the major
awards still to be presented. ``We're halfway done.'').
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine was visibly moved by his supporting actor Oscar
for ``The Cider House Rules'' (though not nearly as moved as Hilary
Swank's husband, Chad Lowe, who bawled like a baby when she won for
best actress). Caine acknowledged his fellow nominees individually,
telling Tom Cruise (``Magnolia''), one of the highest-paid leading
men, ``Tom, if you had won this, your price would have gone down so
fast. Do you have any idea what supporting actors get paid?''
</P>
<P>
   Cruise nodded in his seat, and with wife, Nicole Kidman, by his
side, suddenly seemed very, very happy not to have won.
</P>
<P>
   The most moving moment came unexpectedly, when the Oscar for
documentary short was given to ``King Gimp.'' The subject of the
film, Dan Keplinger, who has cerebral palsy, slipped from his
wheelchair when the award was announced, then rolled and contorted
in ecstasy in the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fathered Dan Keplinger for 13 years,'' producer Susan
Hannah Hadary said as Keplinger continued to squirm in happiness in
his wheelchair. ``He's an amazing spirit in a body that society may
not have included. But tonight he is included and honored as an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   When it finally did end, around 12:40 a.m. today, Crystal noted
blearily, ``Thank you for watching the shortest Oscar show ... of
this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
