<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-COYOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS BEAT COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Twenty minutes into Sunday evening's game
versus the Phoenix Coyotes, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks looked like
dead ducks. Trailing by two goals Anaheim's playoff hopes appeared
to be all but dead.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to Oleg Tverdovsky's game-winning goal at 3:47 of
overtime the Ducks are still alive and kicking in the Western
Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The come-from-behind 4-3 victory before 17,174 at the Pond
vaulted Anaheim (78 points) into a ninth-place tie with Vancouver
and pulled them within three points of Phoenix, Edmonton and San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it as if it was do-or-die,'' said center Matt
Cullen, who found Tverdovsky in the slot after Teemu Selanne had
kept the puck alive in the Phoenix zone. ``We we lose and we are
done, we knew we needed two points.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky got the Ducks the much-needed extra point by snapping
a shot past Sean Burke for his 15th goal of the year. Burke had
denied the Ducks a victory in regulation when he made a brilliant
save to stop Selanne from the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy we came back (to tie), but we felt the job
wasn't done,'' said Cullen of the Ducks, who outshot the Coyotes
28-7 over the last 43:47 of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who were coming off an embarrassing 8-1 loss in
Vancouver on Friday night, looked like they might embarrass
themselves again Sunday when Phoenix scored at the 1:02 mark of the
first period and wound up taking a 3-1 lead to the dressing room
after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out slipping and that can't happen,'' said Tverdovsky.
``It's a good thing we woke up and showed some pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Ducks did shake themselves, the Coyotes could do
virtually nothing to contain Anaheim. The Ducks, led by an
inspirational effort from Teemu Selanne, totally dominated the
final two periods on the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, who just three shots in the last three games, had nine
shots, scored twice and assist on the other two goals as he
manhandled the Phoenix defense down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on a mission to get us a win,'' said Anaheim coach
Craig Hartsburg. ``That as strong one-on-one as I've seen him all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have lost seven straight games and 6-16-1-2 in their
last 23, and Sunday they squandered yet another lead. Benoit Hogue,
Trevor Letowski and Greg Adams scored in the first period when
Phoenix outshot the Ducks, 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne began to turn the tide in favor of Anaheim when he
scored his second goal of the game at 3:48 of the second. The Ducks
were able to get anything else past Burke in that period, but the
momentum had shifted for good and Fredrik Olausson scored on the
power play to tie the game, 3-3, at 1:17 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was all Phoenix could do to hang for overtime and the
one point that goes with it. And the reason they were able to do so
was Burke, who robbed Mike Leclerc, Kip Miller and Antti Aalto
before denying Selanne a hat trick with 21.5 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate we had to give Phoenix a point,'' said
Hartsburg. ``But the main things is that we get two points in all
of our games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have five games remaining and Hartsburg said he tried
to lift the spirits of his downcast team on Saturday by reminding
them a win would get them right back in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to move on and stay positive,'' said Selanne, who like
the rest of the Ducks now has something positive to think about for
the next five days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0131EST &QL; 
