<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF SAYS DISTRICT ATTORNEY TO BLAME FOR LAPD CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: This is a copyrighted story) 
By BETH BARRETT AND GREG GITTRICH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Formally responding to District Attorney Gil
Garcetti's recent charges, Los Angeles Police Chief Bernard C.
Parks categorically denies ever ordering investigators not to
cooperate in the Rampart Division scandal probe.
</P>
<P>
   The chief also accuses Garcetti of deliberately setting up the
controversy, the Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   In a detailed, 29-page confidential memo sent to the Los Angeles
Police Commission on Sunday, Parks claims Garcetti seized on the
chief's effort to move the investigation forward by expanding the
U.S. attorney's role. Garcetti did so by having four prosecutors
send memos to five different investigators on March 13 asking for a
long list of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information already was in the hands of prosecutors
or was being assembled by police when Garcetti went public with his
accusations before his letter of complaint even reached the chief,
the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo, a copy of which was obtained by the Daily News, is
largely a litany of details intended to prove Parks' contention
that Garcetti has dragged his feet in investigating the scandal for
more than a year and only took an interest when facing an uphill
fight for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chief of police at no time issued any order or in any
manner communicated to any person, public or private, in any
context whatsoever that the department would not cooperate with or
provide investigative assistance to the Los Angeles County District
Attorney in this or any other criminal matter,'' the memo states.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney's Office spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons disputed
the Parks memo and the suggestion prosecutors only recently began
requesting information.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not true,'' Gibbons said. ``We were requesting
information all the time. All I can tell you is that at one point
in time, the LAPD stopped sending us information.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parks memo was written in response to the investigation that
the Police Commission ordered Inspector General Jeff Eglash to
conduct into Garcetti's charge that Parks ordered the LAPD task
force probing the Rampart scandal to refuse to cooperate with the
District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real flurry of political-type requests rather than
investigative,'' a police source said. ``It was a set-up and leaked
to the L.A. Times before it even got to the chief.''
</P>
<P>
   In the memo to the Police Commission, Parks accuses Garcetti of
being slow to join the probe, of removing deputy district attorneys
who wanted to proceed with cases against officers suspected of
wrongdoing and of refusing to make the central figure in the
scandal _ former Officer Rafael Perez _ available in recent weeks
for police interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information regarding the emerging Rampart scandal had been
developed as early as February 1999,'' the memo said. ``Up until
late October 1999, only one deputy district attorney ... had been
assigned to work with the department.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Parks said the D.A.'s task force was increased to
six attorneys, a law clerk and secretary. Parks said the increases
to other prosecutors occurred only on March 9 and March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Parks said information was
provided to the District Attorney's Office, but that no action was
taken even though police had been informed that the task force was
prepared to file two cases.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said no charges were filed, however, after the deputy
district attorneys who were ready to proceed _ George Rosenstock
and Susan Chatsworth _ were removed from the task force and
assigned to other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Daily News has documented how Rosenstock had
developed what he felt was a strong case to prosecute several
officers in a station-house beating as well as how Deputy District
Attorney Michael Krauts' early warnings about Perez were ignored by
his supervisors and he was rebuked.
</P>
<P>
   The District Attorney's Office has backpedaled on statements
Garcetti made Friday that Rosenstock had asked to be taken off the
Rampart task force and that he did not aggressively seek to
prosecute rogue officers last month.
</P>
<P>
   Parks in his memo indicated his complaint that Garcetti was
going too slow in prosecuting cops and freeing framed suspects
became personal after the district attorney accused him and his
officers of refusing to provide information.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti's accusation of police refusal to work with his
officers came on March 14, when he faxed a copy of a letter of
complaint to Parks at 9:30 p.m. when the chief was out of town. A
story containing the accusations appeared the following day in the
Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is noted that Garcetti refers to an interview with Los
Angeles Times reporters 'late Monday evening' that would run on
Tuesday March 14,'' the memo says. ``The article was actually
published on Wednesday and contained a direct quote from Garcetti's
letter dated March 14, 2000, and not faxed to the Chief of Police
until 9:30 p.m. on Tuesday night.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks in which prosecutors had sought little information
from the LAPD, the memo notes the four deputy district attorneys
submitted requests for information on various cases on the same
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of some concern to investigators and managers in the
investigation is that all of the items requested in the letters was
for material that has been previously supplied or in some form made
available to the many and various members of the D.A.'s staff
assigned to assist in this investigation,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
