<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCAR-ANALYSIS-LADN &LR;      03-27 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
  
ACADEMY's STRUGGLES CONTINUE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 72nd annual Academy Awards came close to being the showdown
between Oscar-voters' ongoing struggle to really honor the best
that film can achieve and, well, to act like the stodgy old
academy.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Sunday's results, the struggle continues.
</P>
<P>
   Pulled inexorably in the direction of acknowledging ``American
Beauty's'' formal brilliance and relative boldness, and of Hilary
Swank's bravery and uncompromised empathy in the thematically
challenging ``Boys Don't Cry,'' the academy went with genuine
artistry in most of the top categories.
</P>
<P>
   Yet wherever they apparently felt they could get away with it,
the voters followed the path of least resistance to their more
sentimental impulses and outdated traditions.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the best film won the most Oscars, ``Beauty's''
near sweep of the major competitions _ best picture, best actor
Kevin Spacey, director Sam Mendes and Alan Ball's original
screenplay _ wasn't just earned. It was also bought. While rival
studio Miramax got most of the criticism for spending too much
money on its Oscar campaign for the sappy ``Cider House Rules,''
there is no denying that DreamWorks spent all that it could and
more to keep ``Beauty'' a ubiquitous presence on local airwaves and
periodical covers.
</P>
<P>
   And since fellow big spender Miramax's film was the only other
best picture nominee to win awards this year, it's sadly evident
that money drives these races now at least as much as merit.
</P>
<P>
   But the academy did recognize merit, this time in categories in
which the choices have often been embarrassments. Of course, they
could hardly deny the coolest Foreign Language film, Pedro
Almodovar's ``All About My Mother,'' since it has won practically
every other international movie award there is. Nor could they
ignore the kickiest genre film contribution, ``Sleepy Hollow's''
mood-drenched art direction.
</P>
<P>
   The two surprise awards for Mike Leigh's detailed look at
Gilbert and Sullivan's creative struggles, ``Topsy-Turvy,'' spoke
well to the academy's capacity for appreciating analytical cinema _
and to its often less-noble bias for films that flatter Hollywood's
own obsession with show business (in that way, it was a kind of
riposte to criticism of last year's ``Shakespeare in Love'' upset).
</P>
<P>
   No complaints about ``The Matrix's'' sweep of the high-tech
categories, either. Even in a year when George Lucas' ``Star Wars''
sequel achieved a kind of computerized aesthetic perfection, the
blazing energy and ingenuity of the cyberpunk upstart proved that
digitized filmmaking could be as lively as the human imagination.
</P>
<P>
   But then there were the lazy calls. Going with the obvious in
the supporting actress category, ``Girl, Interrupted's'' Angelina
Jolie, continued the academy's fetish for showy portrayals of
mental dysfunction. Still, young Jolie's work was as much a
career-perfect job as Spacey's, and it was fun watching those
famous lips quiver through that tremulous acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   An even easier way was taken in the supporting actor category,
where the most reassuring (if least exciting) choice won _
Hollywood favorite Michael Caine, as the man who loves cute orphans
in ``The Cider House Rules.'' Kudos to previous winner Caine for
rising to the occasion and giving the snazziest acceptance speech,
however.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest, it is never right to hand out awards
primarily on the basis of what the winner will say. That was
evidenced by ``Cider House's'' John Irving, whose meek screenplay
adaptation of his sprawling novel was not only the lamest runner in
that field, but whose drippy/demagogic pro-choice remarks belied
the way his film soft-pedaled the reproductive rights issue.
</P>
<P>
   Other middling decisions were made in the music categories. Phil
Collins' bland ``Tarzan'' anthem overcame Aimee Mann and Randy
Newman's much more affecting ballads, not to mention the real
killer toon tune, ``South Park's'' ``Blame Canada.'' And as fine as
John Corigliano's work for ``The Red Violin'' was, it was rather
unimaginative to choose the score for the film that was about
classical music.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the truly award-worthy (looking ahead to the Emmys,
anyway): Billy Crystal's opening montage, superimposing himself
into film classics _ and dragging Spacey, Stephen King and Elian
Gonzales along with him _ was a terrific way to keynote the tribute
to the century of cinema that the 1999 ceremonies closed out. The
world's greatest Oscar host outdid himself onstage throughout the
night, too; if it weren't for Crystal and statuette-finder Willie
Fulgear, there wouldn't have been half the reasons to even tune in.
</P>
<P>
   Well, those two and the Robin Williams' ``Blame Canada''
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   On a final note: Was there irony in the academy's decision to
present this year's honorary Oscar to Andrzej Wajda, whose films,
often made at risks Hollywood artists could never conceive of,
chronicled Poland's struggles against oppression throughout much of
the last century?
</P>
<P>
   Wajda was quoted in the clip presentation as wanting to make
audiences think. Considering this year's Oscar choices, a little
more than half of the academy's members believe that that's a
worthy goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
