<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: memo said. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There appears to be a common thread in all these letters: the
reference to a prior verbal denial by department employees of
access to this material,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo said there was a request made on March 9 for four
Internal Affairs investigations and the material was later provided
although there were several days of missed telephone calls between
prosecutors and police investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also asserts that prosecutors refused to give police
access to interview Perez, whose testimony as part of a plea
bargain on a cocaine theft charge started the entire Rampart probe.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said that also was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, he is scheduled to be interviewed on Monday (today)
or Wednesday,'' Gibbons said. ``It is a question of when we can
have his attorney present. He has to have his attorney with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parks memo said that on March 13, Lt. Pat Gannon of the
Internal Affairs group was meeting with Deputy District Attorney
Richard Rosenthal to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gannon ... expressed his concern that it had been three weeks
since his investigators had been allowed to interview Perez and
asked Rosenthal how soon Perez would be made available for
interviews,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosenthal said that the D.A.'s office would not allow
department investigators access to Perez as long as there was a
perceived lack of cooperation between the D.A.'s office and the
department,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo said efforts by the two to meet again were
unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
