<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WALL-STREET-PREDICTIO     03-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALL-STREET-PREDICTIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET DIDN`T SCORE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Wall Street Journal blew it.
</P>
<P>
   Its cry we were to accept that premise would it not be possible
to change the future, which is already the past? However isn't that
a bit close to playing God? Are there natural laws against it?
Unfortunately our understanding is so partial that we can tie
ourselves up in knots even thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   In his new novel Peter Delacorte explores some of these theories
and weaves them into a intricate fantasy centered round erstwhile
President Ronald Reagan. At first this may seem rather curious but
it is a perfect vehicle for a leap back and forth across time,
mingling actual people and events with fictional ones.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Prince, a travel writer in the throes of heartbreak,
meets another American in Paris who claims he has a time machine
and asks him to accomplish a mission. Jasper Hudnut is convinced
that the greatest ills in present day society stem from Reagan's
presidency and he wants Gabriel to go back in time and change the
course of history, to adjust things so that it never happens.
Gabriel manages to get back to 1938 but unexpected events conspire
to prevent the plan from going exactly smoothly. Some are the usual
little glitches that happen in anyone's life, like falling in love
and forming friendships. Others are rather more unsettling, such as
finding that knowledge of the future gives him unexpected talents
and powers, which please the ego and distract him from his purpose.
</P>
<P>
   However there is yet another, more sinister development. Gabriel
discovers that there are other time travelers with a claim on the
machine, ruthless men, who will stop at nothing to regain it.
Suddenly life becomes very complicated and he begins to wonder
which world he belongs to. There is the added difficulty that the
machine may run out of fuel and get stuck. Also there seems to be a
slight inaccuracy in the settings, sometimes by several years.
Perhaps time travel is not as simple after all and changing the
course of history merely a hopeless vanity.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Delacorte has a splendid grasp of his material and a light
and amusing touch in handling his characters. At the flick of a
switch we are transported back to Hollywood in the thirties. He has
researched the period well and has a feel for the headiness and yet
the innocence of the times. He provides a fascinating look at the
studio system in its early days, the power, utter crassness and
greed of the early moguls and the limitless possibilities of an
enormous industry still in its infancy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8871 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WALL-STREET-PREDICTIO     03-27 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALL-STREET-PREDICTIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET DIDN`T SCORE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
