<HEADER>
A8875 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      03-27 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEGANT, BUT STILL TOO LONG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What about that ``Matrix'' sweep, huh? That's what you'd be
talking about today if, like most reasonable folks, you only had
stomach or stamina enough to sit through about half the 72nd annual
Academy Awards ceremony broadcast live on ABC from the Shrine
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' the evening's big winner, didn't start
piling'em on until the last half-hour of a 4-hour, 9-minute show,
another record.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Lily Zanuck, as executive producers of the event,
brought an elan to the production in a number of subtle ways.
First, of course, was the already famous (and much-appreciated)
ditching of the inane dance numbers. They also helped spearhead the
elegant and only slightly garish set design and the welcome trips
behind the set to take in the backstage shmoozing and announcer
Peter Coyote's impersonation of an air-traffic controller.
</P>
<P>
   Credit them, too, with the interactive-entertainment-inspired
multiple-image screens, the artful transitions between clips of the
nominees, the hip-hop and ambient tinges to the music (it sounded
as if Moby scored the evening), and in general the upscale polish
of the production.
</P>
<P>
   But please, next year's goal _ shorten the damn thing.
</P>
<P>
   Host Billy Crystal was, as usual, smart and funny, with
scattershot barbs taking down Miramax and DreamWorks' spending _
and spitting _ match, Halle Berry's driving skills, ``The Green
Mile's'' (and the ceremony's) oppressive length and Erykah Badu's
headgear. If his opening sequence, which placed him in a number of
classic films, from ``The Gold Rush'' to ``Casablanca'' to
``Psycho'' to ``The Graduate'' to ``E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial,''
wasn't as funny as his previous similar montages (though the
``Godfather'' and ``Exorcist'' bits were amusing), it was largely
from overworking the concept. He did, however, pretty much earn his
night's pay during his trademark musical medley simply for his
smooth, rapid-fire delivery of ``The Insider's'' tongue-twisting
``60 Minutes Waltz.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining the Best Song nominees in a segment midshow, where
they were performed back-to-back and back-and-forth on the stage,
was artful _ until, of course, Robin Williams' comically xenophobic
production number ``Blame Canada'' _ and, again, made the evening
seem less like the tawdry Vegas revue it usually resembles. (The
Zanucks cannot be blamed for the fact that Phil Collins won.) The
Burt Bacharach-led medley of past Best Song nominees was
entertaining, too, but could've been ditched in favor of brevity;
the proliferation of movie clip montages _ there were four Sunday
night, including one head-scratcher on (usually dubious) Hollywood
history lessons _ was bewildering in their gee-whiz-ness.
Hollywood, Hollywood _ calm down, you've already got the job as
designated dream factory for the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The Zanucks backloaded the awards in the major categories. The
only big trophy handed out in the first 100 minutes was Best
Supporting Actress (and no, I don't want to know what the deal is
between Angelina Jolie and her brother), which probably forced
people to stay up later than they expected. They also pushed back
the direct competition between ``American Beauty'' and ``Cider
House,'' to delay revealing the former's sweep (which was further
deferred when John Corigliano beat both films for his gorgeous
``Red Violin'' score and ``The Matrix'' beat both in the editing
category).
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance speeches early on tended to be so short one
suspects the nominees were told snipers were perched in the balcony
of the Shrine Auditorium waiting to take out any winner who went
over 45 seconds. Then, of course, came extended, wearying
monologues from Michael Caine, Warren Beatty, Hilary Swank,
cinematographer Conrad L. Hall, director Sam Mendes and director
Pedro Almodovar, who was literally dragged offstage by Antonio
Banderas. Maybe winners !ital!should be encouraged to be political
in their acceptance speeches _ or anything, just to get away from
the dull laundry lists of thanks sprayed out to executives and
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, try as they seemed to, the Zanucks couldn't prevent the
inevitable, the much-expected (though minor by recent standards)
sweep by suburban satire ``American Beauty.'' This points up a
problem in general with the Oscars _ there's never much suspense;
it's more a coronation ceremony confirming what everyone has known
to be inevitable. In the past decade, virtually every film _ and
many actors and actresses _ were ordained Oscar winners a month or
two or more before the ceremony; even last year, when ``Shakespeare
in Love'' mildly upset ``Saving Private Ryan,'' most
prognostication pieces explained in trenchant detail why
``Shakespeare'' would win if ``Ryan'' didn't.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with films of quality coming from every direction, it
was considered a wide-open race for the gold. The first round of
Oscar voting, the nominations process that pared away most of the
adventurous material, largely destroyed what might have been a
truly suspenseful evening. From mid-February on, we were saddled
with a two-horse race between ``American Beauty'' and ``The Cider
House Rules,'' which no one had previously even mentioned as a
front-runner. Eventually, everyone realized that not even Miramax's
mighty marketing machine could drag the nag that was ``Cider
House'' over the finish line, and predictions of last night's
``Beauty'' pageant became more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a modest proposal: Shorten the Oscar season to two or
three weeks from nominations to awards. With most of Hollywood
wired, voting could be conducted online with a minimum of fuss (and
no ballots lost in the mail) and a maximum of swift efficiency,
meaning less shameless studio campaigning and covert tinkering with
the results. It'd mean the media prognosticators would have to be
darn fast on their feet to be right, and might also put the kibosh
on a lot of the meaningless interloper awards ceremonies that have
begun cluttering the late-winter landscape. With less time for the
attendant bluster, there might just be a surprise come Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pre-show documenting the arrivals, what can you say
about a half-hour of prime-time television in which Keanu Reeves
proves to be the most articulate and thoughtful interviewee?
Co-host Chris Connelly offered some of the most non-committal
opinions of the races anyone could muster, and this exchange pretty
much typifies the experience: Tyra Banks (so effusive, she put
entire cheerleading squads to shame), to Salma Hayek: ``What's your
secret to looking so hot all the time?''
</P>
<P>
   Hayek: ``I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 0215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
