<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8878 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     03-27 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SHORT SEASON FOR DODGERS, ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the spirit of the political season, I come to
the beginning of the baseball season mouthing the words of the
Republican nincompoop, George W. (Whoops) Bush: I'm a uniter, not a
divider.
</P>
<P>
   I want the best for the Dodgers and Angels, and that doesn't
mean small games toward a .500 season.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California has been absent from the postseason so long
that area fans have forgotten what it's like to see meaningful
baseball in the fall. We now set our sports clocks to Labor Day, at
which time we tell the kids to put their gloves away and keep Dad's
Sundays clear for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that neither team made the deals and moves
necessary to reach mediocrity. The Raul Mondesi for Shawn Green
deal was great, bringing Orel Hershiser back was a no-brainer, and
the Angels may have a bargain in rookie manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   But I quibble with everything else. Oddly, the two teams could
have helped each other if they had thought things through, and made
a few decisions so obvious a sportswriter could see them.
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold)The Dodgers should have gassed Kevin Malone and
Davey Johnson.(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   Former Warner Bros. CEO Robert Daly committed the franchise to
resurrecting Dodger Blue when the Foxies named him the new managing
partner, and I believe he's on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   But he should have given the GM and manager the boot. For
starters, the two aren't on the same page. They aren't even in the
same boat. Ask Malone about his relationship with Johnson, and
he'll speak for hours and make references to Freud, Nietzsche and
Stengel. Ask Johnson about Malone and he'll call him an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has no clue how to handle a major-market team, with
budgets of $70 million or more, and agents like Scott Boras and
Jeff Moorad have used him like a roll of toilet paper in Bobby
Knight's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson arrived with a reputation as a player's manager, but all
he did last season was butt heads with Mondesi, Eric Young and
others. The fact he still thinks Todd Hundley can be an everyday
catcher says all I need to know about his managing.
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold)The Dodgers should have replaced Malone and Johnson
with Dave Stewart and Davey Lopes.(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   Besides being ex-Dodgers, both are aggressive and have
experience with winning. Stewart has been a quick study as a GM in
waiting, and Lopes, just hired in Milwaukee, has been ready to
manage for five years.
</P>
<P>
   They also know that players don't have to love each other to
win. They also would have zero tolerance for players who go through
the motions.
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold)The Angels should have hired Malone as their GM.(end
bold)
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Expo Malone's strength is his ability to seek, sign and
develop young players, and the Angels' farm system needs as much
help as the Angels' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He is also skilled at operating a small-market team with a J.C.
Penney budget. I can envision Malone looking at the Angels' roster
and telling team president Tony Tavares, ``I can trim $20 million
in salaries before trimming the Christmas tree.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold)The Angels should have kept Chuck Finley and traded
Mo Vaughn.(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   A team can never have enough pitching. To a lesser degree,
losing Finley has the same dynamic as losing Nolan Ryan. The Angels
never needed Vaughn. An aggressive GM could have worked a deal
sending Mo to one of those teams with an unquenchable desire to
spend, like the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   (begin bold)The Dodgers should have moved Devon White and
Hundley regardless of cost, and set their sights on Fernando
Vina.(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   One needs to correct mistakes as soon as possible. White has hit
his age wall, and Hundley needs to go to the A.L., where he can DH.
Maybe the Cubs would have sent Terry Adams to L.A. for White. Vina,
who would up in St. Louis, is exactly what the Dodgers need most, a
quality defensive second baseman who bats leadoff and can run.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)The Dodgers should have traded Ismael Valdes and
Eric Young to the Angels for Jim Edmonds.(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   This deal would have made so much sense. The Angels would have
filled a need on the mound and at second, and the Dodgers would
have gotten a full-time left-handed hitting center fielder who can
hit anywhere in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine these lineups the teams could have rolled out next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers: 1, Vina, 2B. 2, Mark Grudzielanek, SS. 3, Gary
Sheffield, LF. 4, Green, RF. 5, Eric Karros, 1B. 6, Edmonds, CF. 7,
Adrian Beltre, 3B. 8, Angel Pena or Paul LoDuca, C. Rotation, Kevin
Brown, Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort, Hershiser and Eric Gagne or
Carlos Perez. Closer, Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Angels: 1, Orlando Palmeiro, LF. 2, Young, 2B. 3, Darin Erstad,
1B. 4, Tim Salmon, RF. 5, Garret Anderson, CF. 6, Troy Glaus, 3B.
7, Todd Greene, DH. 8, catcher platoon. 9, Gary DiSarcina, SS.
Rotation, Finley, Valdes, Ken Hill, Ramon Ortiz and Kent Mercker.
Closer, Troy Percival.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers and stuck with Hundley and White. Instead,
the Angels still have too many position players and not enough
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The season begins next Monday. Based on what we see today, it
will end in September. Early September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
