<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ALTAVISTA:  &LR; If Internet portals were compared to cars, AltaVista
would be a Volvo: respected and reliable to some, spartan and a
little out of date to others. Once a leading search engine,
AltaVista has stagnated in recent years, seemingly frozen in time
as competitors like Yahoo and Lycos prospered by transforming
themselves into shopping malls, travel centers and club houses. Now
it is sprinting to catch up.  &UR; BY VERNE KOPYTOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DIGISCENTS _  &LR; Quick, what does the Web really need? If you said
more eloquence and fewer dancing cursors, clearly you don't have
what it takes to be a high-stakes dot-com wheeler and dealer. The
right answer: Smells. So says an Oakland company that has invented
a computer add-on that can produce hundreds of odors on command.
With two sidebars. &UR; BY CAROLYN SAID &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN): &LR;  As scientists near their goal of mapping the
human genome, the first medical payoff is shaping up as a good
news-bad news situation. ``There will be this tidal wave of
diagnostic tests that will let you know your predisposition'' to
various disease, said Trevor Hawkins, deputy director of the Joint
Genome Institute in Walnut Creek, a Department of Energy laboratory
involved in genome mapping. That's the good news. The bad news is
that it will take years to find drugs or treatments, and get them
approved.  &UR; COLUMN BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OUTTAKES (COLUMN):  &LR; The pilgrimage to Silicon Valley continues.
Yahoo President Jeff Mallet says he recently entertained Disney
Chief Michael Eisner and NBC head Robert Wright (that ought to
start some merger rumors). Both were checking out Yahoo's new
broadcast studio.  &UR; Column By JAN BOYD AND STAN BUNGER &LR;
</P>
