<SLUG> BC-ALTAVISTA- </SLUG>
  
 ALTAVISTA SWITCHES WEB PORTAL INTO HIGH GEAR  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Internet portals were compared to cars, AltaVista would be a
Volvo: respected and reliable to some, spartan and a little out of
date to others.
</P>
<P>
   Once a leading search engine, AltaVista has stagnated in recent
years, seemingly frozen in time as competitors like Yahoo and Lycos
prospered by transforming themselves into shopping malls, travel
centers and club houses.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is sprinting to catch up. With hundreds of millions of
dollars in acquisitions, a big marketing effort that includes
actress Pamela Lee Anderson, and an initial public offer expected
in late April, AltaVista is trying to re-emerge from dormancy and
become an Internet leader.
</P>
<P>
   But the company must fight for attention in a sector crowded
with well-known adversaries and must win users without spending too
much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, AltaVista was one of the lost opportunities
on the Internet,`` said Barry Parr, an analyst for International
Data Corp. ``I think they have done good things to get going again,
but the problem is that they've done them very, very late.``
</P>
<P>
   What AltaVista has done in the past few months is to infuse its
Web site with bells and whistles like shopping, free Internet
access, an image library and breaking news reports. Like all
Internet portals, it is trying to give users more reasons to visit
than just offering a way to find information elsewhere on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy is a dramatic change. Until January 1999, its
site featured only an Internet search engine on a utilitarian Web
page adorned with simple yellow and orange graphics.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with AltaVista's transformation under way, Rod Schrock,
AltaVista's president and chief executive, said the company is
poised to dominate its target audience, the so-called ``Web
enthusiasts.``
</P>
<P>
   These are the people, Schrock said, who ``embrace the Web and
make it part of their lifestyle.'' He said that they spend more
time on the Internet and are more likely to shop online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Web enthusiasts are a very active audience that tends to be
very lucrative,`` Schrock said early this month at the company's
new Palo Alto headquarters, a sparsely decorated building filled
with gray cubicles in keeping with AltaVista's conservative image.
``In that target audience, we are No. 2 only to Yahoo.``
</P>
<P>
   To help capture the market, AltaVista has added several features
to its site. They include an ``advanced search engine`` that allows
users to look for information on the Web by date and a library of
MP3 music, video and photography files.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of overall Web users, however, AltaVista's ranking has
changed little for at least two and a half years. In February, it
was ranked 13th behind well-known and not so well-known portals
like Yahoo, ExciteAtHome, About.com and Real.com, according to
Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has managed to increase U.S. users since its
October 1999 relaunch, from 10.3 million in September to 12.3
million in February.
</P>
<P>
   The push has extended worldwide: AltaVista has created sites in
countries like Britain, France and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock, who joined the company in January 1999, said AltaVista
should be measured by its global audience. In that case, he said,
AltaVista is half the size of Yahoo, not one-fourth, as U.S. market
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ron Sege, executive vice president at Lycos, is
unimpressed with AltaVista's efforts. He said AltaVista's
``comeback'' is just an expensive marketing campaign that has so
far been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tough for folks who are in the second and third
tier to move into the top tier,`` said Sege, whose Lycos network is
ranked fourth in users. ``It's very difficult to buy traffic these
days. There's more marketing dollars being thrown in the
traditional channels and I think that consumers are getting
fatigued with it all.``
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista's origin has a lot to do with its predicament,
analysts agree. The AltaVista search engine was created in 1995 by
Digital Equipment Corp. to show clients how powerful the company's
computers were.
</P>
<P>
   But Digital Equipment never realized that its Internet showcase,
among the most powerful search engines of its era, was a
potentially lucrative business, analysts said. So the company never
spent much money to keep AltaVista competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The investment drought abated after Compaq, the personal
computer manufacturer, bought Digital Equipment in 1998. For a
time, Compaq considered rebuilding AltaVista, but then in August
sold 82 percent of it to CMGI, the venture capital company in
Andover, Mass., for $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under Compaq's and CMGI's stewardship, AltaVista went on a
spending spree. It bought the financial Web site Raging Bull and
the retail Web site Shopping.com.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista was also among the first Internet portals to offer
free Web access. So far, the service has lured 2 million
subscribers, all of whom are directed straight to AltaVista's home
page when they log on.
</P>
<P>
   Another major part of AltaVista's expansion plan is its debut on
the Nasdaq stock exchange. The company's initial public offering,
which will fund its continued development, is expected in late
April.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will almost certainly be looking to see whether
AltaVista eventually earns a profit. So far, it has lost money in
every quarter since it was started.
</P>
<P>
   Though AltaVista still trails many of its competitors, Schrock
is confident that his company can catch up. He said that AltaVista
will eventually broaden from its Web enthusiast audience to go
after every Internet user.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Schrock said, AltaVista's tardiness is irrelevant
in the long run given the history of media empires. For example, he
said, few people can recall which television network trailed in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me, was CBS three years ahead or behind of NBC?``
Schrock asked. ``No idea? So in the grand scheme of things, no one
will care in 10 years whether we were three years before or after
Yahoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Li, an analyst with Forrester Research, was not so
optimistic. She lauded Alta Vista's focus on Web enthusiasts and
e-commerce, but stopped short of predicting that AltaVista would
one day become the Internet's top portal for all users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a general search engine isn't enough to catch up to a
Yahoo because they are so far ahead,`` Li said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schrock at times seems to say that climbing just a few
rungs on the Internet ladder would be a victory. A company that is
among the top 10 or 20 in global traffic, he said, can still be
successful over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be No. 1 in scale to be a successful
player,'' Schrock said. ``There are easily 20 traditional media
companies across the world that are highly profitable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
