<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE: GENE MAPS MAY AID DIAGNOSIS, BUT THEY DON'T
SPEED  TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C. 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  As scientists near their goal of mapping the human genome,
the first medical payoff is shaping up as a good news-bad news
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be this tidal wave of diagnostic tests that will
let you know your predisposition'' to various disease, said Trevor
Hawkins, deputy director of the Joint Genome Institute in Walnut
Creek, Calif., a Department of Energy laboratory involved in genome
mapping.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news. The bad news is that it will take years to
find drugs or treatments, and get them approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the problem,'' Hawkins said. ``You'll be able to
tell people what's wrong with them, but you won't be able to do
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This gap between diagnostics and therapeutics is no secret to
biotechnology insiders. Eric Shulse, director of the molecular
diagnostics unit at PE Biosystems in Foster City, Calif., called it
the Humpty Dumpty dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Humpty Dumpty is crashed, that's your diagnostic,''
Shulse said. ``But it's a lot harder to put Humpty Dumpty back
together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Duster, a sociologist at the University of California at
Berkeley who has studied people's attitudes toward genome research,
said this diagnostics gap could undermine support for the
gene-mapping effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a kind of sympathetic response to this technology
eight to 10 years ago, but in the ensuing years there has been an
increasing skepticism,'' said Duster, whose studies have targeted
the people who know the most about genetics _ families with the
inherited diseases of cystic fibrosis, sickle cell anemia and
beta-thalassemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among this group of the informed lay population you find the
highest level of concern and skepticism,'' said Duster, because
they've already experienced what it's like to know in rich detail
what ails them, without having new therapeutic options.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, skepticism about genetic testing borders on
resentment. Stanford University bioethicist Mildred Cho has looked
at the controversy surrounding the test for Canavan disease, a
brain and nervous system disorder that afflicts one out of every
6,500 children born in Ashkenazi Jewish families.
</P>
<P>
   This inherited condition causes a toxic chemical buildup in the
brain that can lead to disabilities, blindness, seizures and even
death. In 1997, Miami Children's Hospital developed and patented a
test that discloses whether both parents carry the gene defect, and
thus stand a 1-in-4 chance of passing the disease to their
offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Cho said the test has been criticized several ways. First, it
may be priced between $60 and $300, including a $12.50 royalty to
the hospital. Second, critics say it should be licensed to more
laboratories in order to make it more available and bring down the
price.
</P>
<P>
   Then's there's the ownership issue. Cho said families with
Canavan sufferers provided blood samples, which researchers used to
discover the gene defect, and now resent that the hospital patented
the tests, giving it complete control over its use.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Children's issued a statement saying it had invested $5
million in the project and considered a moderate financial return
``only fair.''
</P>
<P>
   As gene data continue to gush forth, spawning tests far in
advance of cures, such frictions will inevitably mount, making
anxiety the most likely first byproduct of the genomics revolution.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTING SCENT? Oakland, Calif.'s DigiScents will announce that
it has filed a patent covering 125 of the genes that allow us to
recognize smells.
</P>
<P>
   DigiScents isn't alone in trying to solve the mystery of how we
detect the difference between fresh-brewed coffee and fresh-baked
bread. Ambryx Inc. in San Diego, Calif., is hot on the same trail.
</P>
<P>
   DigiScents chief executive Joel Bellenson and Ambryx scientist
Sergei Zozulya painted this picture of our most primitive sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We evolved as pond scum,'' Bellenson said. ``We had to be able
to sense nutrients. We thrived as life because we were able to swim
toward where the food was.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the nose was a gleam in nature's eye, primitive
organisms evolved receptors that could detect the chemical pattern
of nearby nutrient molecules. Over evolutionary time, these
receptors congregated deep in the nasal cavity, in a region called
the olfactory epithelium.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Zozulya said, some 300 to 400 receptors, each controlled
by a different gene, try to identify odor molecules as they waft
past. But smell isn't as simple as dogs make it seem. There is no
1-to-1 matchup between smell and receptors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans may be able to recognize 10,000 separate smells,''
Zozulya said. ``Each odor reacts with different receptors.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, two people bent over the same rose may use
different receptors to register the fragrance, or one may have a
sharper appreciation because their receptors are better tuned. This
complexity could complicate the issue of patenting olfactory genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody has a patent on a single receptor, it's hard to
say what it means,'' Zozulya said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, DigiScents is being cagey about its patent claims,
other than to observe that they cover a good chunk of the smell
receptor universe. Zozulya said between 100 and 150 smell receptors
are already in the public domain, put there by government-funded
research.
</P>
<P>
   As private researchers compete to patent whatever smell genes
remain up in the air, they point to a variety of uses for their
discoveries, like detecting dangerous gases in mines (sure to
provoke the canaries' union.)
</P>
<P>
   Creating smells to ship over the Internet is clearly the sexiest
part of DigiScents' mission. But Bellenson hints at medical
applications. Greater knowledge of the smell mechanism may suggest
ways to sharpen our sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high percentage of people are unable to smell something,''
he said. ``With science and software we may be helping create
corrective lenses for the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
