<SLUG> BC-OUTTAKES- </SLUG>
  
 OUTTAKES: Disney, NBC Bosses Pay Yahoo a Visit 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Stan Bunger &AMP; Jan Boyd &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage to Silicon Valley continues.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo President Jeff Mallet says he recently entertained Disney
Chief Michael Eisner and NBC head Robert Wright (that ought to
start some merger rumors). Both were checking out Yahoo's new
broadcast studio.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, broadcast studio. Yahoo has quietly launched a live
financial news broadcast airing every morning from 6 a.m. to 2 p.m.
The company converted the room usually reserved for media
interviews into a small studio with three cameras and
TelePrompTers.
</P>
<P>
   The control room looks like any found in your basic medium-sized
television station, with more than a half-dozen people staffing the
controls.
</P>
<P>
   The only notable difference from a regular control room is the
Globecaster computers from Sacramento, Calif.'s Play TV tucked
under the console, helping transform the action happening in the
studio into bits that can be shoved through the Internet to your
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting part of the Webcast isn't the content, it's
Yahoo's FinanceVision player, a bit of software you download in
order to see the show.
</P>
<P>
   Mallet says that thanks to the intense competition between Real
Networks and Microsoft, his company was able to cut an
unprecedented deal with Microsoft, &LR;  to license essentially raw code
of the Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filo (Yahoo co-founder David Filo) and his crew then went to
work,'' says Mallet. The technology isn't revolutionary but it
works well, downloads very easily and allows the viewer to access
all sorts of information.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is also running commercials in its show and, unlike
television broadcasters, is able to give its advertisers very
precise information about who watched those ads. The next step will
be direct purchase of an advertiser's product after viewing its
commercial _ just click and buy.
</P>
<P>
   Financial news is just the beginning. Yahoo has plans to branch
into other areas soon. Mallet won't say what will be next, but
sports could be a good bet.
</P>
<P>
   MORE BIG NAMES: Back to big names coming to check out Silicon
Valley's latest and greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton will tour the Women's Technology
Incubator this Wednesday in San Francisco. LevelEdge chief
executive officer Lisa Henderson will be there to greet the first
lady, and explain LevelEdge's Web site, which is aimed at
transforming the college athletic recruiting process. Then
Henderson will be out looking for a new home.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidized rent of the Technology Incubator has helped
LevelEdge get its start, but Henderson's company is rapidly
outgrowing its offices. So, she's doing a little shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Check out these figures -- a building in San Francisco, not on
the market yet, 30,000 sq. feet, 10-year lease required along with
$1.7 million deposit and monthly rent of $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Big bonus: The building comes with parking.
</P>
<P>
   She was given 24 hours to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   SETTING A GOOD EXAMPLE: You've built two big software companies.
You're worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   You have getaway houses in Hawaii and Lake Tahoe to go with your
big home in Santa Cruz County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   You have a fleet of racing sailboats, and hangars full of
airplanes, including a pricey executive jet.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, you're a bona fide digital success story.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do with your time?
</P>
<P>
   If you're Philippe Kahn, you keep working. Kahn, the founder of
Borland (now Inprise) and Starfish Software (now a Motorola
subsidiary) has a simple reason for continuing to lead and invest
in companies: his kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see their parents building stuff, doing other
things, just like I saw my own parents,'' said Kahn after landing
his Cessna Citation jet at the Watsonville airport. Kahn's late
father, an engineer in France who helped design the supersonic
Concorde's wings, maintained his career into his 80's.
</P>
<P>
   While he's not embarrassed about his wealth or his toys, Kahn
doesn't dwell on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an example, just sitting on the beach doing nothing,
being a consumer of things,'' he said. ``I don't think that's the
way to raise kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn is actively involved in Starfish, where he's still CEO, as
well as startup software companies Lightsurf (working on wireless
digital photography technology) and OpenGrid (creating software
tools to manage the growing flood of wireless communications).
There's also the Lee-Kahn Foundation, which funds environmental and
educational projects.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his work ethic rubs off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids need to learn about making things happen and
making a difference,'' said Kahn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
