<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clinton tilts at foreign windmills
 &HT;    (For release March 29, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Jefferson Clinton is embracing an almost quixotic quest
for a legacy that would put Monica Lewinsky out of our minds. It
won't happen. This not only is a lame-duck president but one with
baggage so heavy that other world leaders see no reason to
genuflect before him.
</P>
<P>
   In his last year as president, Clinton seeks a legacy, pursues a
Nobel Peace Prize that he never will achieve. Likely, if Monica had
not happened, he still would not be able to succeed in bringing
conflicting parties together; the hatreds run too deep.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad, indeed, that Clinton's libido came to dominate his
presidency, but he has no one to blame but himself. His quest to
throw a blanket over it is failing.
</P>
<P>
   He takes on the tobacco industry, the gun industry, educational
problems and the like as a fairly liberal president _ which puts
him at immediate odds with the Republican-dominated Congress. His
chance of pushing through meaningful legislation on anything is
meager.
</P>
<P>
   As he jets around the world seeking peace (and a peace prize),
Clinton finds that he cannot dictate terms or rapprochement. His
visits to India and Pakistan showed that. If that wasn't enough,
his failure to alter the rigid demands of Syria's Hafez Assad for a
peace with Israel not only showed Assad's intransigence but further
weakened Clinton's foreign-policy stature; he dealt with a man who
is on our list as both a supporter and instigator of terrorism. And
that man, Assad, rejected him!
</P>
<P>
   What was thought to be a Clinton-brokered peace in Northern
Ireland is not.
</P>
<P>
   He rescued the Albanians from the Serbs, and now has to rescue
the Serbs from the Albanians. He tempts Iranian favor with the
lifting of an embargo on pistachio nuts and caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere he turns, however, is there visible success. Perhaps
some seeds have been sown, but there will be no buds during the
Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy will not be peace in the Middle East, or on the Asian
subcontinent. His legacy will not be the condition of the domestic
economy either, although that is one of the few successes
attributed to his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy is, and always will be, Monica Lewinsky _ and others.
And the subsequent impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he took his first oath of office as president, he has
been hounded by his own foibles: first, Gennifer Flowers, then
Paula Jones, then Monica Lewinsky _ and maybe a couple of others in
between.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, his enemies were fixed and his sexual appetite
gave them further succor.
</P>
<P>
   Still a relatively young man as outgoing presidents are seen,
Bill Clinton must deal with his future. To enhance it, he'd love to
be remembered as a man who brought peace to ... you name the place.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that people still are wondering if Hillary will
dump him after the White House days, and whether he is going to be
disbarred from practicing law because of his lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, too. Bill Clinton is a bright man, highly
educated, with considerably good ideas. But his presidency is and
has been paralyzed by that exotic moment near the Oval Office; it
effectively ended the day he looked us in the eye and said he did
not have sex with that woman.
</P>
<P>
   His domestic agenda repressed, he turns to foreign affairs. He
needs a legacy and maybe it will come of that. But it doesn't. The
world is no more at peace today than it was when he became
president. In fact, it may be less at peace.
</P>
<P>
   He wanders the globe trying to find the breakthrough, but it
does not happen. In a way, Bill Clinton is a pathetic person. He
has all the mental talent to have been a great president. He is
capable of becoming a valued resource as the ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   Following Watergate, Richard Nixon eventually emerged as an icon
of foreign policy. It took many years, however. Whether Clinton's
transgressions _ the Gennifer/Paula/Monica affairs _ ever can be
overcome is unclear. He's got some books to write, some admissions
to make, some culpability to express.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, and not before, perhaps Bill Clinton can regain some
respect.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
