<P>
   The following is a menu for New America News Service stories
that are for release Fri., March 24, 2000, or anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   PAPAL APOLOGIES FOR ALL BUT GAYS. Recently, Pope John Paul II
celebrated Mass in St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. In an
unprecedented gesture he bowed his head and asked forgiveness for
sins committed by Roman Catholics. Those sins included religious
intolerance toward Jews, ``rejection and exclusion'' of women and
misdeeds committed against the poor, immigrants and indigenous
people. Columnist Chuck Colbert writes: ``It was an extraordinary
and timely admission, but there was one gaping omission: an apology
to lesbians and gays.'' (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-POPE-FORGETS-GAYS-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   CARL WARE'S ASCENSION TO LEADERSHIP AT COKE. Here, a profile of
Carl Ware, a veteran executive at the Coca-Cola Co., who had gained
almost legendary stature in the corridors of the world's leading
marketing company. Though he is the first African-American to
become so prominent at the company, his accomplishments transcend
race. Instead of retiring as he had planned, Ware was recently
promoted from group president to executive vice president. He now
sits on the powerful six-member Coke executive committee, which
guides the company's major decisions. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACK-COLA-EXEC-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   COCO MOTION. It's the eve of the stateside premiere of CoCo
lee's first American album, ``Just No Other Way,'' and she took
time out of her busy touring schedule to speak with Julia Wang,
contributing editor to A. Magazine. Haven't heard of CoCo? Well,
you will soon, if her label, Sony, has its way. The 23-year-old
Chinese-American songstress achieved blockbuster stardom in Asia.
Six weeks after its debut in October, her album went gold in Korea
and platinum in Singapore. In December, it reached No. 4 on
Billboard magazine's new ``Breaking Artist'' chart. A profile.
(slugged: BC-NEW-AMERICA-ASIAN-SINGING-SENSATION-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   FOR NATIVE-AMERICANS, A FIGHT FOR DIGNITY IN URBANA, ILL. ``Life
for the handful of American Indians living in the college town of
Urbana, Ill., was pretty quiet in 1988 B.C. Yes, 1988 B.C. _ Before
Charlene,'' writes columnist Tim Giago. Charlene Teters of the
Spokane tribe arrived on campus in 1988 along with Marcus Amerman,
a Choctaw, and Norman Akers, an Osage, as part of a recruiting
program by the University of Illinois to bring Indian students into
the arts program. Soon after they arrived, they noticed appalling
images around campus: caricatures of Indians on T-shirts, cars,
store fronts, parking lots and hotel lobbies. It was about the
school's mascot _ a white, middle-class boy dressed up in Indian
attire. In this commentary, Gaigo recounts the problems these three
Indian students faced while trying to earn their degrees _ and
their fight to kill the mascot. (slugged:
BC-NEW-AMERICA-FIGHT-FOR-DIGNITY-NYTSF)
</P>
