<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-POPE-FORG     03-27 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-POPE-FORGETS-GAYS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPAL APOLOGIES FOR ALL BUT GAYS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By CHUCK COLBERT  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Recently, Pope John Paul II celebrated Mass in St. Peter's
Basilica in Rome. In an unprecedented gesture he bowed his head and
said, ``We forgive ... and we humbly ask for forgiveness.''
 &HT;    His sweeping papal apology covered approximately 2,000 years of
sin and wrongdoing. He bravely acknowledged Roman Catholic sins
``committed by some of our brothers,'' which included religious
intolerance toward Jews, ``rejection and exclusion'' of women and
misdeeds committed against the poor, immigrants and indigenous
people.
 &HT;    It was an extraordinary and timely admission, but there was one
gaping omission: an apology to lesbians and gays.
 &HT;    I attended a local reflection of the Pope's pardon in Boston's
Cathedral of the Holy Cross. The evening's service were offered in
the spirit of reconciliation. Cardinal Law of Boston expressed
remorse for the shortcomings of Catholics in the Archdiocese of
Boston since 1808.
 &HT;    ``Now is the acceptable time,'' he said. ``The church should be
a sign of unity, of hope, of justice and of love.''
 &HT;    Law referred to the discrimination Catholics have suffered. ``We
ourselves have suffered as a community of faith the effects of
discrimination and prejudice. All the greater should be our
sorrow.''
 &HT;    Law openly spoke of ``intolerable situations,'' naming ``the
obvious cases of sexual abuse, which have seared us all.''
 &HT;    Calling on all Catholics to abandon exclusivity, he acknowledged
the presence of Orthodox Christians at the service, referring to
them as our ``beloved brothers and sisters with whom we are not yet
in full communion.''
 &HT;    His litany of acknowledgment continued: For ``our revered Jewish
brothers and sisters with whom we share the memory of
discrimination and persecution ... For our Islamic friends with
whom we share the memory of the crusades ... For brothers and
sisters from many racial, ethnic and national backgrounds.''
 &HT;    For everyone but gay and lesbian Catholics, his brothers and
sisters in Christ.
 &HT;    His jarring omission disheartened me _ a faithful gay Catholic.
 &HT;    A few blocks away stands the Jesuit Urban Center where hundreds
of gay Catholics worship each week. Nearby, another inclusive Roman
Catholic community confirms lesbian and gay men members of their
congregation. But these Catholics must hold their liturgical
celebration in an Episcopal church. They were banned from Catholic
church property years ago.
 &HT;    Many lesbian and gay Catholics attend mass in parishes
throughout the Archdiocese of Boston _ and all across America. Yet,
in a prayer service of reconciliation, our spiritual leader
bypassed an opportunity to express sorrow and seek pardon for the
ways in which gays remain the brunt of _ to use the cardinal's own
language _ ``harsh words, unjust treatment, prejudice and
discrimination.''
 &HT;    Out west, however, things were different.
 &HT;    In Los Angeles, Cardinal Roger Mahony's apology included the gay
and lesbian community.
 &HT;    ``I ask pardon of our Catholic homosexual and lesbian members
when the Church has appeared to be non-supportive of their
struggles or of falling into homophobia,'' he wrote in a Lenten
message to his archdiocese, dated March 6. ``The Archdiocese has
tried to make amends by establishing a special outreach ministry to
our homosexual and lesbian brothers and sisters, by including them
fully in the life of our parishes and by being attentive to
protecting their civil rights.''
 &HT;    Mahony instituted the ``Ministry with Lesbian and Gay
Catholics,'' which operates from his archdiocesan offices. In his
archdiocese, inattentiveness and homophobia have given way to
acknowledgment and redress.
 &HT;    Now is the acceptable time for gays in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Why not the Archdiocese of Boston? And the other dioceses and
parishes throughout the United States?
 &HT;    When will all God's children be embraced?
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert, a divinity school student at Weston Jesuit
School of Theology, Cambridge, Mass., serves on the board of the
National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Author's name 
