<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-FIGHT-FOR-DIGNITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NATIVE-AMERICANS, A FIGHT FOR DIGNITY IN URBANA, ILL.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate's NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE is for use only by arrangement
with New York Times Syndicate/Special Features. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By TIM GIAGO 
 &HT;    URBANA, Ill. _ Life for the handful of American Indians living
in the college town of Urbana, Ill., was pretty quiet in 1988 B.C.
Yes, 1988 B.C. _ Before Charlene.
 &HT;    Charlene Teters of the Spokane tribe arrived on campus in 1988
along with Marcus Amerman, a Choctaw, and Norman Akers, an Osage,
as part of a recruiting program by the University of Illinois to
bring Indian students into the arts program.
 &HT;    When the three Indian students arrived on campus, they strolled
the grounds looking for the Indian community. They asked about
Indian student organizations and Indian studies departments. There
were none.
 &HT;    They soon discovered that they made up the Native community.
According to Charlene, ``We stuck together like glue because we
soon began to feel out of place, even unwelcome.''
 &HT;    This uncertainty was brought about in part because of the images
of Indians they saw on and off the campus. They saw caricatures of
Indians on T-shirts, cars, store fronts, parking lots and hotel
lobbies.
 &HT;    They wondered what this was all about. Soon enough, they
discovered it was about the school's mascot _ a white, middle-class
boy dressed up in Indian attire. His name is Chief Illiniwek. The
university's sports and social life seemed to revolve around this
hideous impostor.
 &HT;    Over time, the Indian students observed fraternities and
sororities sponsor events like the Miss Illini Squaw Contest.
 &HT;    ``The neon sign at a local bar featured a dumb caricature of a
cartoon Indian with buck teeth and a bent feather, crosses for
eyes, falling down drunk over and over again,'' Charlene recalled.
``This is also the bar at which fraternity brothers donned their
colored paper headdresses and went to get drunk.''
 &HT;    The peaceful town of Urbana was permeated with such demeaning
caricatures of Indians. Any local event brought out the local
artist's interpretations of cartoon Indians _ usually of drunken,
fat and ugly Indian characters. These hideous pieces of art
decorated T-shirts, cars, businesses, sidewalks and any post or
pole that would hold a poster.
 &HT;    Marcus was the first to explode. When he saw Chief Illiniwek
used as a local celebrity to cut ribbons at mall openings and new
businesses or to greet visiting celebrities, he became incensed. He
wrote a letter to the local student newspaper: ``Perhaps the
inhumane treatment and near genocide of my people hasn't satisfied
your need to humiliate and destroy the image of the original
inhabitants of this country. It makes me wonder how members of
other ethnic and racial groups would react to an environment
saturated with derogatory caricatures of their people,'' he wrote.
 &HT;    Marcus became an immediate pariah. He was threatened and
harassed to such an extent that he left school in the middle of the
night without so much as a goodbye to Charlene and Norman.
 &HT;    One of the professors who helped recruit the three Indian
students broke the news to Charlene and Norman by singing, ``One
little, two little, three little Indians ... two little Indians are
left.''
 &HT;    ``We were crushed by the sheer insensitivity of what was
happening around us _ especially when we were told to keep our
mouths shut and get our degrees and then get out of here,''
Charlene said.
 &HT;    It wasn't in the nature of this Spokane Indian woman to remain
silent. Her children's self-esteem had been badly damaged by the
things they saw at basketball and football games. The constant
demeaning of themselves as Indians began to take its toll.
 &HT;    One day when Chief Illiniwek was giving a talk, Charlene showed
up and challenged him. The Daily Illini reported, ``A Native Indian
graduate student went on the warpath Wednesday,'' and other
newspapers and radio stations soon picked up on it, often making
Teters the butt of jokes.
 &HT;    Charlene soon became a target just as Marcus. Her phone rang off
the hook with obscene and threatening calls. She and her children
were harassed by the local police. Her school-age children became
the targets of other students.
 &HT;    Charlene couldn't go anywhere in this once peaceful town without
drawing the stares and the ire of the local population. She was so
discouraged she was ready to quit school.
 &HT;    She called me one day and we had a long talk because I had been
writing about the use of Indians as mascots for several years. She
also called Ken Sterns of the American Jewish Committee. We both
told her the same thing: ``Charlene, if you quit, they win.''
 &HT;    She stayed and fought. Soon banners began to appear around
campus on walls and vans. ``Keep the Chief. Shoot the Indians.''
Since there were only two Indians left on campus, they knew exactly
who the signs intended to disparage.
 &HT;    Despite her continued efforts, on Oct. 11, 1990, the Board of
Trustees voted to keep the Chief as their mascot.
 &HT;    Charlene graduated and left the campus in August of 1991.
 &HT;    Was her fight worth it? Drive around Urbana today at homecoming
and you no longer see the hideous displays that demeaned the Indian
people. You no longer see the Chief paraded around like some sort
of god. Her selfless efforts did bring about some degree of
sensitivity that did not exist, BC _ Before Charlene.
 &HT;    But as Charlene said this week, ``The battle is far from over.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji _ ``Stand Up for Them'') is an Oglala
Lakota. He can be reached by e-mail at giagobooks(AT)dtgnet.com.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 Tim Giago 
