<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8997 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NEW-AMERICA-ASIAN-SIN     03-27 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ASIAN-SINGING-SENSATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCO MOTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JULIA WANG  
 &HT;    CoCo Lee looks to be the happiest person seated in the lobby of
the Four Seasons Hotel in New York. After two months of touring in
Asia _ leapfrogging from Hong Kong to the Philippines, eight
countries in all _ she has finally returned to the states, which
explains her beaming expression. After all, for this globetrotting
California girl, the United States means home.
 &HT;    ``But I'm not really home yet,'' the 23-year-old says, a broad
grin spreading across her pixie face. ``My home is L.A. I miss my
bed so much.''
 &HT;    It's the eve of the stateside premiere of her first American
album, ``Just No Other Way.'' It took nine months to produce,
leading Lee to lovingly compare the making of the album to ``having
a baby.''
 &HT;    ``This album is the greatest challenge of my life,'' she says.
``My greatest challenge and my greatest achievement.''
 &HT;    Even though she has just come off a plane from Asia, the
Chinese-American songstress is already preparing to embark on
another whirlwind concert tour. That is, after she spends a few
weeks in her comfortable bed.
 &HT;    A skillfully crafted collection of urban beats, R&AMP;B ballads, and
soul-sister turns, ``Just No Other Way'' is Lee's debut on the Epic
550 label, and the first release in her unprecedented long-term
contract with Sony Music.
 &HT;    The number of Asian and Asian-American artists who've had
breakthrough pop careers in the United States can be counted on
exactly, well ... no fingers. But Sony is convinced that CoCo is
different _ that, given her undeniable beauty and talent, she'll be
able to convert her considerable success in Asia to blockbuster
stardom in America.
 &HT;    In January, radio stations across the country debuted the
high-energy dance track, ``Do You Want My Love,'' the first of
``Just No Other Way's'' 12 tracks. MTV has added the sleek video _
which puts Lee's toned torso front and center _ to its volume
rotation. And if the song's title sounds similar to the breakout
hit of another ``ethnic crossover'' diva _ Jennifer Lopez's ``If
You Want My Love'' _ maybe that isn't a coincidence. After all,
Sony is the music-industry superpower that successfully turned a
trinity of Latin talents _ Lopez, Marc Anthony and, yes, Ricky
Martin'' _ into an unprecedented international phenomenon.
 &HT;    As far as Sony is concerned, CoCo is on deck. They've put the
full weight of their promotional engine behind ``Just No Other
Way,'' and the album is already generating positive buzz. Six weeks
after its debut in October, it went gold in Korea and platinum in
Singapore. In December, it reached No. 4 on Billboard magazine's
new ``Breaking Artist'' chart.
 &HT;    Lee is quick to acknowledge the power of her Asian fan base:
``People there are very supportive; they see that I'm going to be
the first Asian to make this big crossover,'' she says. ``It's
become like a family thing _ they're rooting for me.''
 &HT;    CoCo was ``discovered'' by Michael Caplan, senior vice president
of A&AMP;R for Epic Records at a Sony International Music conference
held in Miami. Although she was already a hugely successful artist
in Asia, it was the first time Caplan had ever seen Lee perform,
and she bowled him over.
 &HT;    ``Even though she sang all her songs in Mandarin, I was really
amazed by her voice,'' Caplan recalls. In no time, he'd made
arrangements to bring her over to the American side of the pond,
already brainstorming a plan to cross CoCo over.
 &HT;    Caplan paired Lee with the industry's top dance and R&AMP;B
producers, among them Rick Wake, Ray Contreras and the ``Godfather
of House'' Frankie Knuckles.
 &HT;    The result was an album that showcases Lee's ability to both
groove and cool it down _ alternating dance tracks and slow jams _
while giving her the urban credibility she would need to break into
America's more jaded market.
 &HT;    ``We'd heard that she was a huge star in Asia, so we really
didn't know what it would be like to work with her,'' says
Contreras, who cowrote and coproduced ``Do You Want My Love.''
 &HT;    Contreras and his partner, Jimmy Greco, had listened to the only
other English-language album Lee has recorded, primarily consisting
of cover songs. They knew she could sing pop.
 &HT;    ``The question was, could she sing R&AMP;B?'' Contreras says. ``This
genre has a lot of improvisational singing.'' After a pause, he
adds: ``And she totally has the flavor.''
 &HT;    High praise for a young woman who never intended to be a singer
in the first place. In fact, Lee's original career goal was to
become a doctor like her mother, and she says it's still in her
game plan.
 &HT;    Born in Hong Kong, Lee emigrated with her family to San
Francisco at the age of 10, where she effortlessly mustered up the
academic chops needed to pursue her medical dreams. She graduated
fifth grade with top honors, despite having only been in the United
States for a year. She was nominated class president three years in
a row.
 &HT;    By the time she was a senior, she'd won the titles of Miss
Teen-age Chinatown and Winter Ball Princess. After graduating high
school with distinction, Lee was prepared to attend the University
of California at Irvine to pursue pre-med studies.
 &HT;    What happened next was a textbook example of overnight success.
In the summer of 1994, Lee, then 18, vacationed with her family in
Hong Kong. On a whim, her mother entered her in a singing contest,
which happened to be the Hong Kong equivalent of ``Star Search'' _
a launch pad for aspiring entertainers.
 &HT;    At high school singing gigs and weekend outings to karaoke
clubs, Lee was capable of belting out songs from her favorite
childhood artists, such as George Michael, Mary J. Blige and Mariah
Carey. But she'd never formally trained to be a singer, nor had any
singing aspirations.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `No way can I make it,''' Lee recalls. ``I had the
attitude that I just wanted to sing. I wasn't there to win.''
 &HT;    She didn't. She took second place instead, crooning Whitney
Houston's ``Saving All My Love.'' The following day, a Chinese
record label called to sign her up. The first-generation parents
who had encouraged Lee and her two sisters to ``study and get good
grades'' suddenly about-faced, advising the baby of the family to
pursue a singing career.
 &HT;    These days, Lee's mother, whom she says is her ``biggest fan,''
travels with her, acting as her advisor, critic and, of course,
personal physician. ``My mom flies with me all over the place and
takes care of me,'' Lee says.
 &HT;    It's a lot of responsibility for a girl in her early 20s. ``I
try not to think about all that,'' she says carefully. ``When you
start thinking about the pressure, that's when you start messing up
and you go off focus. Right now, it's all good.''
 &HT;    Still, she does concede that she's begun shattering some
misperceptions already.
 &HT;    ``There's always been something of a stereotype that when Asians
sing in English, there's an accent,'' she says. ``When I walk into
that studio, I want everyone to feel that even though I'm Asian,
Coco's got a voice.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Julia Wang is a contributing editor to A. Magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 A Magazine 
