<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-BLACK-COLA-EXEC-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARL WARE'S ASCENSION TO LEADERSHIP AT COKE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ERNEST HOLSENDOLPH  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Carl Ware, a veteran executive at the Coca-Cola Co., had gained
almost legendary stature in the corridors of the world's leading
marketing company. Though he is the first African-American to
become so prominent at the company, his accomplishments transcend
race.
 &HT;    He was the man who bailed the company out at crucial times, such
as in the early 1980s, when the company was challenged by Black
leaders for not providing more opportunities for African-Americans.
Later in the decade, he persuaded Coke and other American
industries to take on antiapartheid leadership.
 &HT;    Last year, when the company was hit by an embarrassing
discrimination lawsuit, Ware, who had urged the company previously
that it needed to do more to promote minorities in the supervisory
ranks, became co-chair of a new advisory committee on diversity.
 &HT;    Through his activities and his standing, Coca-Cola was able to
be one of the favored industries on the agenda of the young Mandela
administration, resulting in significant business advantages in
Southern Africa. Ware, personally, as president of the Africa
operation, was able to establish a model way of doing business on
the continent _ by including Africans in the operation of the
business.
 &HT;    With all of this background, who would have expected that Carl
Ware, of all people, would have been demoted, in effect, last year
by M. Douglas Nester _ and at a time when the company needed to
work on its image? Yet, that's what happened when Ivester, Coke
chairman and chief executive officer, called Ware in and said he
would no longer be reporting directly to the chairman as before.
 &HT;    Ware announced he would retire, moving down to his Coweta
County, Ga., farm where he grew up, to start a new life of writing
and lecturing. Publicly reported to be worth more than $15 million
in Coke stock, Ware didn't really need the aggravation. Just weeks
afterward, however, the tables were turned. Nester got the gate,
when the Coke board of directors stunned the global business
community with the announcement that Australian-born Douglas Daft
would become the next chief executive. Within hours after his
elevation, Daft knocked on Ware's door and sat down with his fellow
group president.
 &HT;    He sought Ware's thoughts and ideas about new directions for the
company, and he then invited Ware to stay on board to help launch
the new administration. Ware, promoted from group president to
executive vice president, now sits on the powerful six-member Coke
executive committee, which guides the company's major decisions.
 &HT;    He will oversee global communications, corporate external
affairs, governmental relations and corporate services. Ware
assumes his new role at a time en the company is trying to put
behind it a nightmare year of public relations embarrassments,
regulatory challenges, an equal employment lawsuit, stagnant sales,
and a long slide in the company stock price _ which undoubtedly
played a role in the company's ouster of Nester.
 &HT;    In his new role, Ware is challenged to formulate and carry out
policies that can begin to turn around the tarnished Coke image,
and its frayed relationships with customers and communities. He is
also charged with the task of revitalizing employee morale.
 &HT;    It is decidedly bigger than a public relations job, and much
bigger than the mere improvement of Black opportunity in the Coke
world.
 &HT;    ``My principal job is to see that our company is welcome
everywhere around the world, and out of all the things I do, that
is my primary, principal task,'' Ware says. ``We simply must
improve relations with everybody. ``I also hope to make Coca-Cola a
place where employees find this to be a more pleasing place to
work.''
 &HT;    Ware, who came to Coca-Cola 26 years ago from his position as
president of the Atlanta City Council, is an old hand at government
relations. But much more will be required of him in his new role,
and on a grander world stage.
 &HT;    Among his major tasks, Ware must be in touch with governments in
more than 200 countries where the company does business. Among his
challenges, he is to make sure the company no longer gets
blindsided _ as it was last year, when a product scare in Belgium
stirred fears across Europe that the company fiercely fought to
allay. Coke products bottled in Belgium were pulled from store
shelves in several countries after scores of consumers became ill.
 &HT;    Experts like Frank Mankiewicz, vice chairman of Hill &AMP; Knowlton,
say Ware appears to have the power and position to carry out his
role. Says Mankiewicz: ``I think he can make a difference _ he has
the keys.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Ernest Holsendolph is a contributing columnist to Emerge
magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Emerge magazine 
