w e BC-GEORGE-CLOONEY-IN-FAI     03-27 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-CLOONEY-IN-FAIL-SAFE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE WIRE: GEORGE CLOONEY DOES `FAIL SAFE' WITHOUT A NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a black-and-white slide of George Clooney in a scene from
``Fail Safe.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada before April 8. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's official: George Clooney has returned to television.
</P>
<P>
   But before viewers start picturing Doug Ross swaggering back
onto ``ER'' and setting up house with Nurse Hathaway and their
twins, the actor makes it clear that he's not returning to
television's most popular drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Clooney says affably. ``They haven't even asked me.''
</P>
<P>
   The project that brings Clooney back to the small screen is
``Fail Safe,'' a CBS television-movie remake of his
all-time-favorite film, the 1964 Cold War thriller starring Henry
Fonda, Larry Hagman and Walter Matthau. The remake will be
broadcast live _ and in black and white, no less _ on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, who has had a spotty record on the big screen, despite
the comparative success of his most recent films, ``Out of Sight''
(1998) and ``Three Kings'' (1999), says he came back to television
because it was the only way he could do ``Fail Safe,'' which he
felt driven to do.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the tense environment of the early Cold War, ``Fail
Safe'' traces the mounting tensions between the United States and
Russia after mechanical failures launch an atomic attack on Moscow,
cutting back and forth between American attempts to stop the
bombers and the president's frantic negotiations with the Soviet
premier to prevent World War III.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the movie a year or two ago, Clooney says, he was
struck by the idea that it was ``sort of made for live
television.'' A seed was planted, and before long Clooney had
convinced Walter Bernstein, who wrote the original, to pen an
updated script and had brought director Stephen Frears on board.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clooney stars as Col. Jack Grady, the bomber pilot
who, during routine maneuvers, is suddenly diverted toward Moscow
and ordered to drop the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   It's a meaty, dramatic role, all the more challenging because
Clooney has to pull it off while confined to his plane's tiny
cockpit for nearly every scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the trick of this is that the words play so well,
and the words are what do this,'' the actor says. ``We're telling a
great story here. It's really well written, so I don't think we'll
be focused on whether people are moving around or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney will be surrounded by a mostly male cast that includes
major big-screen names such as Harvey Keitel, Richard Dreyfuss,
James Cromwell, Don Cheadle, Sam Elliot, Hank Azaria and Brian
Dennehy.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the mix is a notable small-screen name, Clooney's former
``ER'' castmate Noah Wyle, who will play the president's
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noah and I are good friends,'' Clooney says. ``We play
basketball together. And we'd been talking about it for a long time
_ I used to screen that movie over at my house all the time and
make people watch it, and Noah and I talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men are familiar with the dangers and the thrills of live
television, having worked on the much-hyped live ``ER'' episode two
years back. That broadcast resulted in a ratings bonanza, but
Clooney wasn't happy with the results, particular when he viewed it
again before setting to work on ``Fail Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't necessarily work,'' he says, shaking his head, ``but
it could. And the trick is to do it really right. And that means to
start from the very beginning, building the sets and shooting it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story line for that ``ER'' broadcast included a visiting
documentary-film crew who could be conveniently blamed when things
went wrong _ a precaution that won't be available in ``Fail Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're flying a little bit more without a net,'' Clooney says,
``but we've also prepared differently. With any luck at all we'll
be able to do it better, and hopefully we're learning from things
we've done along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Clooney who insisted that this new version of ``Fail
Safe,'' like the original, be broadcast in black and white _
``which isn't taboo, necessarily,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if ``Fail Safe'' is a success, Clooney would like to do
a regular series of live-broadcast movies, mostly remakes of dramas
from the black-and-white era of 1950s television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure would be nice to be able to get somebody to give us
the rights to `A Thousand Clowns' (1965),'' he adds. ``It would be
nice to get some of the old classics, too. Maybe some old `Twilight
Zones.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clooney is bubbling over with ideas for future
television projects. About the only thing he isn't planning to do
is to return to ``ER'' _ despite persistent rumors to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' he says, ``I read I was going back for $52
million an episode _ which I'd like to go on the record as saying
I'd go back for $52 million an episode. I'm not an idiot!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been things that ballooned out of somebody making a
joke or something like that,'' he adds more seriously. ``I've never
talked to anyone about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he says, ``ER'' doesn't need his help, either for a
ratings bump or to add to the dramatic mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing is,'' Clooney says, ``they're not going, `Hey,
come on back' and trying to do a ratings thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juliana leaving will be a big enough story line, I think,'' he
adds. ``It's a big blow to that show when you lose Juliana
Margulies, much more so than losing myself. She's the real soul of
that show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show survives, though, because it's a good show and it's
smart writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clooney admits, he has so much going on these days _
including prepping for his next film, a remake of the Rat Pack
movie ``Ocean's Eleven'' (1960), in which he's assuming the Frank
Sinatra role _ that he seldom has time to watch the new episodes of
``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still sees his former castmates, mostly because he and
they have offices on the Warner Bros. lot _ but even that doesn't
get him itching for a return to his old stamping grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my friends almost every day, because my office is right
next door to them,'' he says. ``But I don't have any regrets about
not trying to keep reinventing the character that I was playing
after five years. I was kind of running out of stuff, and it was
sort of limiting as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's probably best that I got out when I did, before I
started doing headstands and things to try and think of something
different to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Fail Safe,'' consult the CBS
Web site at www.cbs.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
