</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIMMY-SMITS-IN-PRICE-OF-GLORY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GLORY' DAYS: JIMMY SMITS REVELS IN THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jimmy Smits in a scene from ``Price of
Glory.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The last we saw of Jimmy Smits, he and Bobby Simone were
checking out.
 &HT;    Smits was leaving his hit television series ``NYPD Blue,'' and
Simone was dying in a hospital bed, his heart finally giving out.
Truth to tell, while he talked a confident game at the time, Smits
now can admit that he had his share of doubts.
 &HT;    ``My final scene as Bobby Simone has a priest giving me the last
rites,'' the actor recalls. ``I insisted it (be) a real man of the
cloth, because I thought it would make it a little more realistic.
 &HT;    ``Quietly,'' he continues, ``I took the priest to the side and
said, `Listen, father, I've been in this bed for six weeks dying on
television. I'm going into the unknown after I leave the show.
Could you just give me a little blessing, please?'
 &HT;    ``It couldn't hurt,'' Smits says, laughing.
 &HT;    It may have helped, because since leaving the weekly grind of
series television, Smits has been in demand. He already has three
movies in the can, including the boxing drama ``Price of Glory,''
which will open on March 31. Then there's ``Million Dollar Hotel,''
starring Mel Gibson and due this summer, and ``Bless the Child,'' a
thriller co-starring Kim Basinger.
 &HT;    Not bad for a guy many fans think is dead.
 &HT;    ``Man, it's weird,'' Smits says. ``In airports, people still
come up and say, `Are you OK? Jimmy, are you really alive? We wept
when your heart transplant didn't work!'''
 &HT;    Smits laughs.
 &HT;    ``Once I had this older woman come up to me and say, `Jimmy, I
just love the way you die,''' he recalls. ``I said, `Ma'am, I cried
watching myself die, too.'''
 &HT;    The actor, who nowadays wears a tiny beard and, for a
Saturday-morning interview at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel,
dresses in expensive black slacks and a matching cashmere sweater,
understands how much ``NYPD Blue'' fans miss him, but he makes no
apologies for his departure.
 &HT;    ``Look, I fulfilled my commitment to the show,'' he says
matter-of-factly. ``And now I want to concentrate more on long-form
things.''
 &HT;    ``Long-form,'' of course, is code for ``movies.''
 &HT;    ``You have a 120-page movie script and you know you'll bust your
a-- and work really hard for three months,'' Smits says. ``And then
you move on to the next gypsy family and the next character. I like
the idea of moving on. That's why I got into this business _ I want
to show versatility.''
 &HT;    Smits shows that versatility as a tough father obsessed with
molding his three sons into champion boxers in ``Price of Glory,''
which has been dubbed a Latino ``Rocky'' _ much to Smits'
annoyance.
 &HT;    ``This film doesn't need labels,'' he says. ``It's a father-son
story, period. It's about people trying to win, and it's as
mainstream as any other movie.''
 &HT;    Smits loved the idea of playing against type.
 &HT;    ``This is not an idealistic, heroic guy,'' he says. ``He's
basically a man whose dreams have been frustrated in his own
life.''
 &HT;    Smits based the character a bit on his own father, a Surinamese
immigrant who lived with his Puerto Rican wife first in Puerto Rico
and then in Brooklyn, holding a job as a plant manager at a
silk-screen factory.
 &HT;    ``My dad was very strict,'' the actor says, ``but he didn't push
us to play sports. For my dad, the thrust for the family was
simple: It was all about education for him. I guess that has to do
with the fact that he and his family didn't have that advantage of
education.''
 &HT;    As a teen-ager, Smits had what he calls ``major rebellion
problems,'' which infuriated his father.
 &HT;    ``I remember vividly one summer in New York, I was collecting
airplane models,'' he recalls. ``A particular box I had didn't have
the right parts in it, so me and my buddies went to the department
store and opened up all the boxes. We started taking out parts _
and it worked until I got caught.
 &HT;    ``I came home in a cop car,'' he continues. ``My father came out
and grabbed me by the scruff of my shirt.''
 &HT;    He shakes his head.
 &HT;    ``His whole thing is, we didn't come to this country to be
embarrassed in this way,'' Smits says. ``It's this whole thing of
what it is to be American and not get in trouble with the law.
 &HT;    ``I got a whupping,'' he concludes. ``Today it would be child
abuse. Back then it was just a whupping.'''
 &HT;    His father was disappointed when young Jimmy, who already had a
degree in education from Brooklyn College, abandoned his plans to
study psychology and announced that he wanted to become an actor.
 &HT;    ``My father did not understand. He didn't get it,'' Smits says.
``Of course, my family doesn't have an entertainment background. My
Dad was like, `Jimmy, I like those plays, but why does everybody
talk funny in that Shakespeare thing? If you want to be an actor,
why aren't you doing something real, like a toothpaste commercial?
 &HT;    ```That to me is an actor.'''
 &HT;    But a 1984 job on the pilot for ``Miami Vice'' got Smits started
in television, and two years later he was cast in the career-making
role of fiery Victor Sifuentes on ``L.A. Law.''
 &HT;    Television opened some movie opportunities, but so far Smits has
generally been better than his material, and such films as ``The
Believers'' (1986), ``Old Gringo'' (1988), ``Vital Signs'' (1990),
``Switch'' (1991) and ``My Family'' (1995) have not added up to
much at the box office.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I have frustrated acting dreams,'' Smits says. ``But I
can be very hardheaded. I always think that your dream is just one
day away from coming true.''
 &HT;    He conveys that lesson to Taina and Joaquin, his children from
his first marriage, which ended in 1987. By his own account, he's a
tough parent, but he's avoided the kind of conflict that plagues
his character in ``Price of Glory.''
 &HT;    ``What I've tried to do with my children is be more
communicative,'' Smits says, ``which is something we didn't have in
my home. In my home you just did it. Why? `Because I'm telling you
to do it. Get in your room and do your homework.'
 &HT;    ``I took psychology courses,'' he adds. ``I know that you reap
much more if you actually talk to people, which is what I try to do
with my kids, because I want them to be able to talk to their own
children.''
 &HT;    For the last decade, Smits has been seeing actress Wanda De
Jesus, about whom he generally refuses to speak in public.
 &HT;    ``She is a great partner in life,'' he says. ``She is also a
great dancer.''
 &HT;    The two spend most of their time out of the public eye. In fact,
Smits says, he even watches his own reruns.
 &HT;    ``I've discovered that you could spend the day watching
back-to-back episodes of `L.A. Law' and `NYPD Blue,''' he says. ``I
see them every once in a while. My first thought is that I'd feel
blessed, but I realize there is a lot more for me to do
artistically.
 &HT;    ``My second thought is that I sit there and say, `Wow, I had so
much more hair in those days!'''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Price of Glory,'' consult the
official Web site at www.priceofglory.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
