<SLUG> BC-MINNIE-DRIVER-IN-RETURN-TO-ME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETURN' ENGAGEMENT: MINNIE DRIVER TAKES A CHANCE ON ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Minnie Driver with David Duchovny in a
scene from ``Return to Me.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Minnie Driver is multitasking.
 &HT;    Standing near a window at Los Angeles' Four Seasons hotel,
Driver sips from a bottle of water, takes a drag on a cigarette,
sings Christina Aguilera's hit song ``Genie in a Bottle'' and sways
to the music in her head. By the time she turns around to greet a
visitor, her face is just a bit flushed with embarrassment.
 &HT;    ``I love `Genie in a Bottle,''' she says. ``The song is so
catchy. What was that other song I liked? Oh, it was `I Think We're
Alone Now.' But I have a feeling Christina Aguilera's career will
last longer than Tiffany's.''
 &HT;    Driver smiles, strides over to a couch and settles in to talk
about her own career _ one that will probably last longer than
either Aguilera's or Tiffany's. Since winning over audiences with
her touching performance in ``Circle of Friends'' (1995), the
British actress has put together a string of movies that includes
``Big Night'' (1996), ``Sleepers'' (1996), ``Grosse Pointe Blank''
(1997), ``Good Will Hunting'' (1997), ``The Governess'' (1998) and
``An Ideal Husband'' (1999).
 &HT;    Beyond her films, Driver has received unwanted attention for her
personal affairs. She very publicly dated her ``Good Will Hunting''
co-star Matt Damon, a relationship that ended in an
even-more-public breakup. Now she's been linked with actor Josh
Brolin, son of James Brolin, but the mere mention of that
relationship or of Josh Brolin's stepmother, Barbra Streisand, has
been known to cause Driver to bolt.
 &HT;    ``It's nobody's business,'' the actress says simply.
 &HT;    The business at hand, then, is ``Return to Me.'' Due for
nationwide release on April 7, ``Return to Me'' casts Driver as
Grace, a gravely ill young woman who receives a new heart from
accident victim Elizabeth Rueland (Joely Richardson).
 &HT;    Time passes, and Grace and Elizabeth's widower husband, Bob
(David Duchovny), struggle to get on with their lives. And, as one
might expect of a romantic comedy/drama, Grace and Bob ultimately
find each other, with a little help from four crotchety old men
(Carroll O'Connor as her grandfather, Robert Loggia as her uncle
and Eddie Jones and William Bronder as cantankerous family
friends).
 &HT;    Schmaltzy as that may sound, the film works magic. Audiences are
laughing and crying in all the right spots, and Driver credits
director/co-writer Bonnie Hunt _ who also plays Grace's best friend
_ with constructing a film that has feel-good sleeper written all
over it.
 &HT;    And, she says, it's refreshingly free of schmaltz.
 &HT;    ``It's very easy to play that card when you're doing a romantic
comedy,'' says Driver, dressed casually in blue jeans and a denim
jacket. ``Fortunately, Bonnie is a very strong director with a very
good sense of humor and an edge.
 &HT;    ``I'm bookended by so much humor, by the wonderful old guys, by
Bonnie's character, by Jim Belushi (as Hunt's lug of a husband) and
by this very sweet, wry relationship she has with David's
character,'' Driver says. ``It's very emotional, but it's very
honest.
 &HT;    ``Getting too sappy was a concern,'' she admits, ``but if you
base everything in truth you can play any cliche and give it a
veracity and newness. If it's based in truth, the audience will
suspend its disbelief and believe in what you're showing them.''
 &HT;    Driver didn't know ``X-Files'' star Duchovny before signing on
for ``Return to Me.'' On the set, however, the two hit it off.
 &HT;    ``He's so good, such a good actor,'' she says. ``He's been doing
the same part for seven years, and it's got to be an enormous bore
to be the same person for seven years. It must have been a great
release to be someone so much lighter.
 &HT;    ``He's really great, so charismatic on screen,'' she adds. ``He
has that old movie-star quality as an actor. As a person, he could
not be funnier and drier, or more articulate or more fun to hang
out with.''
 &HT;    Later this spring, Driver will turn up in two more films,
``Higher Love'' with Rufus Sewell and Nigel Hawthorne, and the
Sally Field-directed coming-of-age drama, ``Beautiful.''
``Beautiful'' is especially important to the actress, who not only
stars but also produced the film with her sister Kate via their
company, Two Drivers.
 &HT;    ``The producing has really been to create work for myself,''
Driver admits. ``I don't like waiting around for things to come to
me.
 &HT;    ``I've been fortunate to have the limitless talents of my
sister,'' she says. ``I don't love the day-to-day of producing, I
love to find material and develop it. Kate is a great dealmaker _
she knows the ins and outs of the business end of producing. So I'd
like to think we complement each other very well.''
 &HT;    One film produced by Two Drivers, namely ``Slow Burn,'' turned
out so horribly that, Driver says, it probably won't ever be
released. And that's despite the presence of herself, James Spader
and Mr. Unmentionable himself, Josh Brolin.
 &HT;    ``We laughed ourselves silly, because everything that could go
wrong did go wrong,'' Driver says with an ``oh, well'' shrug. ``It
was just one of those awful, hilarious filmmaking experiences of
which I think everybody has one.''
 &HT;    Driver can live with the occasional flop _ she survived the
waterlogged ``Hard Rain,'' right? And, she adds, she can handle
fame.
 &HT;    ``I'm fairly comfortable,'' she says. ``I'd be worried if I were
really comfortable. I think one should always be wary of fame _
it's complete ephemera. It's illusory, and not the whole truth at
all. Those photos are airbrushed, you know?
 &HT;    ``There are only a few areas in which you can really utilize
your celebrity,'' the actress adds. ``One is giving your name and
time to causes you feel passionate about, and the other is being
able to do the projects that interest you. I have enough leverage
at this point to guarantee financing on a small picture, or maybe a
bigger picture if I'm with someone else.''
 &HT;    Driver smiles and tugs on her ponytail.
 &HT;    ``Every single part I take will enforce who I am so much more
than my protesting my nobility as an actor or my disinterest in
celebrity,'' she says. ``My work will do all my talking for me. I
have all confidence in that.''
 &HT;    Driver figures that, if she hadn't pursued acting, she might
have gone on to college and tried to make her living as a writer,
perhaps as a novelist or magazine journalist. She chose acting,
however, and admits to no regrets.
 &HT;    ``I think anything you put your passion and your heart into,
that you respect and feel useful in, is noble,'' she says.
``Whatever you do for a living, if you love it and honor it in some
way, then you're in the right profession.
 &HT;    ``By that standard, I think I'm in the right profession for me
and that acting is a noble profession.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
