<HEADER>
A9014 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-THE-RETURN-OF-STEELY-     03-27 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-RETURN-OF-STEELY-DAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWO' BY TWO: THE RETURN OF STEELY DAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Donald Fagen and Walter Becker of the
rock band Steely Dan) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Two decades after recording their most recent album as Steely
Dan, Donald Fagen and Walter Becker have decided, in the words of
their first hit, to ``Do It Again.''
 &HT;    ``Two Against Nature,'' the duo's new nine-song collection,
marks the first album of new Steely Dan music since ``Gaucho''
(1980). It was inspired by a heavy spate of touring the group did
during the 1990s _ ironic since, during much of its initial run
from 1971 to 1981, Steely Dan was a reclusive studio outfit that
shunned live performances.
 &HT;    ``When we were out in '96,'' singer/keyboardist Fagen says, ``we
were talking about how we needed some new stuff to play onstage. We
started feeling a little like the material was getting tired for
us. We both had some ideas for songs, so we decided to take some
time off to write and record.''
 &HT;    In typical Steely Dan fashion, that took a few years. In their
heyday Fagen, Becker and producer Gary Katz were known for their
meticulous ways in the studio, agonizing over every detail of their
songs and working with dozens of session players _ including future
Doobie Brothers Michael McDonald and Jeff ``Skunk'' Baxter, future
Toto members Jeff Porcaro and David Paich, rock-guitar heroes Mark
Knopfler and Rick Derringer, and instrumental luminaries Wayne
Shorter, Larry Carlton, Lee Ritenour and the Brecker brothers,
Michael and Randy.
 &HT;    The ends usually justified the means, however. From the early
1970s rock hits ``Do It Again'' and ``Reelin' in the Years'' to the
jazz-pop fusion of their masterful album ``Aja'' (1977), Steely Dan
made its mark with sophisticated arrangements, virtuoso
musicianship, clever _ if oblique _ lyricism and Teflon-smooth
production.
 &HT;    ``As jazz fans, it was amusing for us to play jazz harmonies on
these big, ugly electric guitars,'' says the 52-year-old Fagen, who
met Becker during the 1960s at Bard College in upstate New York,
where they played in a band that included future ``Saturday Night
Live'' star Chevy Chase on drums.
 &HT;    Fagen and Becker formed a songwriting partnership and moved to
Los Angeles, submitting songs for others before launching Steely
Dan during the early 1970s. The group's success peaked with the
multimillion-selling ``Aja,'' but by the time ``Gaucho'' was
finished both men were burned out by their exhausting working
method, drugs and personal neuroses.
 &HT;    They stopped working together _ though Fagen notes that ``Steely
Dan time is a whole different thing. To us, there was no break _
it's all on a continuum'' _ and pursued different therapies and
musical endeavors.
 &HT;    It was playing live that brought the two back together. Fagen
invited Becker, who was co-producing his solo album
``Karmakiriad,'' to join him in the New York Rock and Soul Revue's
North American summer tour during 1992, which led to several
full-fledged Steely Dan outings during the next few years and,
ultimately, the decision to go forward with a new album.
 &HT;    Even after 20 years, however, Fagen says he and Becker found
they still work in the same exacting way.
 &HT;    ``We kind of gravitated toward the way we used to do it,'' says
Fagen, who co-produced Becker's 1994 solo album ``11 Tracks of
Whack.'' ``We worked together on both our recent solo albums, so we
just rolled into it, really. I wish it could have been faster, but
that's how it goes.''
 &HT;    Longtime Steely Dan fans will be pleased to find that ``Two
Against Nature'' picks up where ``Gaucho'' left off, with the same
blend of jazz, soul, pop and blues conventions. The songs are built
atop slinky, sinewy grooves, usually incorporating a warm
combination of Rhodes and Wurlitzer pianos, cushy horn charts and
biting guitar licks.
 &HT;    The difference this time is that those guitar licks are played
almost entirely by Becker, rather than by the all-star corps that
populated previous Steely Dan efforts.
 &HT;    ``Walter had been playing really well, I felt, so I actually
encouraged him,'' Fagen says. ``Before, we'd start calling people,
but I said `Hey, look, why don't you try it?' He's a great guitar
player, but he always had kind of a low confidence level. We've
both improved a lot since the '70s, as far as our technique goes. I
thought he did a great job, and that gives more of a unity to it.''
 &HT;    As to achieving the familiar Steely Dan sound, Fagen says he and
Becker did talk about what the group should sound like after all
this time, and even discussed modern methods of record-making such
as sampling and electronic techniques.
 &HT;    ``But we never really had serious discussion about it,'' he
says. ``We ended up sort of gravitating to doing this very much the
way we used to, except for the fact of new technology, which
enables us to do the same things in a slightly different, and
usually quicker, way.''
 &HT;    Steely Dan's initial blast of promotion for ``Two Against
Nature'' was on television, including episodes of PBS' ``In The
Spotlight'' and VH1's ``Storytellers.'' Next up is a concert tour,
which will begin during May in Japan before coming to North America
for the summer and heading to Europe in the fall.
 &HT;    The repertoire, he adds, will draw heavily from ``Two Against
Nature'' but will also dig into Steely Dan material he and Becker
haven't touched on during their recent tours.
 &HT;    ``We're going to revive and perhaps spruce up some things we
haven't played onstage for awhile,'' Fagen says. ``I know we were
looking at `The Boston Rag,' which we haven't played onstage since
the '70s. We had kind of a funny arrangement of `Dirty Work' we
were looking at, too.
 &HT;    ``Some of the earlier things we did I don't think were
representative of the style that evolved,'' Fagen adds. ``There are
some things that I really didn't like the lyrics as they appeared
on the original records, so I've rewritten some words.
 &HT;    ``I don't think there's anything that, at least with some
rearrangement, we can't make interesting to play.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Two Against Nature,'' consult
the official Web site at www.steelydan.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
