<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fridge finds final, frosty farewell
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ All mechanical breakdowns are not created equal.
Telephones have gone from being serious business machinery leased
for home use to disposable plastic toys. Toasters, which used to
last forever, now come and go.
</P>
<P>
   But as you move up the food chain of home technology and into
the realm of what economists call ``durable goods'' (whether or not
</P>
<P>
   they prove to be all that durable), people get irrationally
attached to machinery. This is the point when mechanical failure no
longer
</P>
<P>
   feels like the inevitable result of planned obsolescence. It
feels like the inscrutable punishment of an angry god.
</P>
<P>
   The most durable goods of them all are cars, washing machines,
dryers and refrigerators. And on these objects, people get a little
</P>
<P>
   nuts. They give cars names like pets. They identify the sounds
particular to their own home not with the light sound of breezes or
</P>
<P>
   voices of children down the street but with the whir of
compressors and the shake, rattle and spin emitting from the
laundry room.
</P>
<P>
   And the most durable of the durable goods, the most faithful and
most central to home life is the refrigerator. It is the machine
people get most strangely attached to.
</P>
<P>
   Cold storage is to the modern home what the hearth was to homes
centuries ago. The central spot around which all home life spins.
With luck, one might spend an entire childhood leaving the door
open, staring into and emptying a single trusty refrigerator. If
you're not lucky, the switch over can be traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   Even cleaning a refrigerator is a task I associate with
unwelcome change. It is done before moving day, before company
arrives, after the storms when electricity has been off a day. If
you are as devoted to keeping change at bay as I am, you understand
that refrigerator-cleaning is bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there I was, before the open icebox squinting at expiration
dates (''October? October which year?'') and muttering to myself.
</P>
<P>
   My refrigerator, the only one my teen-aged kids had ever known,
was dead. I was kneeling between an ice chest and a garbage bag,
judging lukewarm frozen food. The bag filled faster than the chest.
</P>
<P>
   These were evil substances. The ones sealed airtight were the
most interesting both from an esthetic and scientific point of
view. How did life forms evolve so they could thrive on spaghetti
sauce in a dark, low-oxygen, low temperature environment? And what
cool, non-spaghetti-like colors they come in! The deeper I dug, the
more exotic the finds.
</P>
<P>
   But scarier than the stuff that yields to the natural forces of
decay is the stuff that doesn't. I found Halloween candy that had
Y2K problems. It looked the same as last year. Tasted the same.
What could it be made of? I have furniture that hasn't lasted as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The clean-out phase of abandoning a dead refrigerator puts one
in a utilitarian frame of mind. You are ready for the new. But this
resolve is tested as soon as you undertake the refrigerator magnet
roundup.
</P>
<P>
   I sorted out the damaged ones, picking out only the best for the
gleaming white door of the new unit. I carefully transferred the
one that looks like a space alien and the detailed representation
of the Empire State Building. I kept the one made out of seashells
by a Sunday school class.
</P>
<P>
   Easy enough decisions. But they were decisions that meant
sorting through the icebox's history. Back to its old ice ages.
This was the refrigerator door where I used to store bottles of
baby formula and now I was sending it to the end of the driveway,
never to return. It was all too sad.
</P>
<P>
   The magnets on this door held softball standings, the report
cards that could stand the light of day, crayon drawings of
balloon-like people and birthday party invitations for kids who are
now as big as I am and able to look vaguely dangerous when standing
in groups waiting to be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   A major link to the whole process of growing up: lost.
</P>
<P>
   But the new durable good looks both durable and good standing in
this old place of honor. And with its predecessor's magnets in
place, it already looks a little more homey than it did in the
showroom. When I found chocolate fingerprints on it within hours, I
felt better still.
</P>
<P>
   This may not take as long to get used to as I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
