<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mama makes up her mind
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Scientists have recently discovered a
thumb-size primate species that lived in China 42-million years
ago. It may help resolve missing links in the evolutionary pattern
as well as cast doubt on our exclusively African origins. The tiny
critter weighed only one-third of an ounce and ate bugs at night.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting stuff, but I can tell you right now my mother
wouldn't like it one little bit. If she were still around, she'd be
accusing those
</P>
<P>
   scientists of all sorts of reprehensible motives for their
studies as well as muttering a few ladylike but highly suggestive
comments about the origins of their ancestors. She didn't much like
folks messing with her firmly held opinions on anything, and not
being related to monkeys was definitely one of her firmest.
</P>
<P>
   In the barely post WWI years when Mother was at Queen's College
in Charlotte, N.C., where she majored in sorority and chapel organ,
young ladies attended few (if any) lectures on the theory of
evolution. But even if the study had been mandatory, Mother
wouldn't have bought into it. Information that didn't reconcile
with her firmly held notions would be partially processed and then
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do NOT confuse your mother with facts,'' I remember my father
frequently warning during my growing up years when he'd tired of
listening to the two of us heatedly debate everything from the
origin of the species to the color of my nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   Mother would make up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around my 12th birthday, Mother concluded I was
destined to become a problem drinker based on my refusal to sign an
alcohol abstinence pledge her church was circulating.
</P>
<P>
   There was no big moral issue involved. I was just an average kid
balking at being pressured into making promises I might someday
decide to break. It was a non-issue for me and I promptly forgot
the entire episode. Mother never did.
</P>
<P>
   One noon, 25 years later, she walked into my kitchen and sat
down at the table with my four-year-old son who was having his
lunch. ``What's that'' she demanded, pointing to the suspicious
brown bottle beside his cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginger beer,'' he answered innocently.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the old television series ``Sanford and Son'' And how
Fred, whenever he found himself in a situation he couldn't handle,
would slap one hand over his heart, stagger, and shout to the
heavens, ``This is it, Elizabeth! This is the big one!'' That was
my mother _ almost.
</P>
<P>
   She grabbed the bottle, marched to the sink, and was mid-pour
when my son spoke up, asking her to please give back his ginger
beer and explaining that if she wanted some, there was more in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle clattered into the sink as Mother swayed under the
strain. She made it back to the table muttering about heathen
children and unsigned pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only ginger ale, Mother,'' I said with little hope of
coming out ahead on this one. She ignored me and warned that my
predilection for strong drink was dooming my son to a lifetime of
brown bottles on bartops. I told her I'd never had a beer in my
life. She changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Mother called to remind us it was time to
enroll our son in Bible school. My husband told her he'd see to it
since I was in the hospital and wouldn't be driving for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Mother didn't ask what was wrong. All she said was, ``I hope
they can help with her problem.'' My husband asked what problem
that might be and my mother quickly answered, ``Her drinking, of
course. She never did sign that pledge, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, my husband told me he hadn't even tried to explain that
I'd hurt my back and was in traction. Her mind was made up and he
knew better than to argue.
</P>
<P>
   Same with evolution. She would dismiss all studies linking us
with apes, insisting that none of her relatives had ever lived in
trees _ at which point my father would always bring up her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I have no problem being linked to the cute little
critter I saw in the paper, but who knows? Unlike my mother, maybe
I've been confused by the facts.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
