<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web a rich source of sites for sore eyes (runny noses, too)
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is a time of year when even the grass blooms.
There are flowers, sunshine and enough pollen to sneeze at.
</P>
<P>
   The Web itself can't stop your eyes from itching or your nose
from running, but it can lead you to a number of places where
you'll get advice and help that may turn your red eyes back to
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Allernet at www.allernet.com/default.asp is a great place to
start because _ unlike some of the other sites we will visit today
_ it's totally devoted to allergies. If you had just one site to
visit for help, this would be the one.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there is a link to a section that explains just
what allergies are in simple terms. That may not stop you from
sneezing, but a basic knowledge of the condition will help you
treat it intelligently. You'll also find pollen forecasts so you'll
know what types of pollen are active now, as well as a section of
hints on treating allergies. There you'll learn that mold is often
a bigger problem for some people than pollen, and you'll find some
ways to avoid exposure to mold.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is at the Asthma and Allergy Foundation of
America's Web site at www.aafa.org/. One nice feature of this page
is a list of questions that you can answer _ sort of a mini-self
test _ that will help you determine if your problem is actually
caused by an allergy. Just as is true with computers and computer
viruses, there are times when other problems are actually blamed on
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   For some, a little in-person understanding and support is
needed. You'll find a link on this page that will take you to a
list of support groups that you can find in your area. If you are a
health professional eager to learn more about allergies, you'll
find a link to specialized material that provides more in-depth
information.
</P>
<P>
   When people think of medicine and disease, the Mayo Clinic often
comes to mind. The famous clinic has a Web site with a section that
deals with allergies. If you go to
www.mayohealth.org/mayo/common/htm/allergy.htm, you'll find what
seems to be a complete and well-organized section on allergies.
</P>
<P>
   POLLEN, MOLD AND FOOD
</P>
<P>
   One of the nice features of this site is the diversity of
allergy information. While _ especially this time of the year _
most people are thinking of pollen and mold allergies, that's
surely not the complete picture of what's out there. You'll find
information on this site about other kinds of allergies, including
allergic reactions to food.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry, you'll also find the expected _ information
about how to keep going when the pollen is flying. If you're a real
allergy maven _ you'll probably qualify if you visit each of the
sites listed today _ you may want to take the interactive allergy
quiz to find out just how much you do know about allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The American College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology runs a
terrific site at allergy.mcg.edu/. Since the site is run by
physicians, it's not surprising that one of the features here is a
locator service that will let you specify the area of the country
you live in and get a list of board-certified allergy physicians.
</P>
<P>
   One feature you'll find especially useful is the ability to
search the site. That way, if you're curious about a particular
condition or medicine or topic, you'll have a better chance of
either finding it or discovering immediately that it isn't covered
by this site.
</P>
<P>
   The site is fairly complete, however, and a search for the
medicine Claritin, used as a decongestant, produced four hits with
solid information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
