<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SAVVY0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mac's iBook a good step up
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki: I've had a Mac LC and HP printer since 1990,
and I'm awaiting a new iBook and Dell printer (a birthday present
from my parents). I have questions about the transition.
</P>
<P>
   _Jeremiah Gold-Hopton,
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Your folks are happenin'. Graduating from a slow, but
sure, LC to a shiny new iBook is a good leap. Your questions are
relevant to lots of people going from older Macs to sleek iBooks
and iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah: I mainly do word processing. What's the best way to
transfer my data from LC to iBook? Is there a way to connect them,
or do I use floppies? My LC can't get online, so e-mail isn't an
option.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Moving data can be as easy as buying an iBook floppy drive
(about $85). The floppy generation is on its way out, but the drive
still will be useful down the road. If your files are big, or there
are gobs, try File Sharing. It lets you move items by networking
Macs. Because your LC and iBook don't share common network
connectors (the iBook has USB and Ethernet; the LC has serial), you
need a device to make a ``bridge.'' Look for a Localtalk/Ethernet
bridge or adapter to connect the Macs (about $90 to $100, cables
included).
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Yeah, the bridge lets them see each other. Hang with me
through these steps. Connect a serial cable from the bridge to the
modem or printer port on the back of the LC. Run the USB or
Ethernet cable from the bridge to the iBook. On the LC, turn on
File Sharing in Control Panel. Then, ``allow guests to connect'' in
the Users and Groups Control Panel. Click on the LC hard drive icon
on your desktop. Pick Sharing from the File menu. Next, via the
Appletalk Control Panel, tell your iBook how it's hooking to the
bridge (USB port or Ethernet). Open the iBook's Chooser. Click
AppleShare. Double-click the LC icon. Log in, and an icon will
appear on the desktop. Whew! You can finally start draggin' and
droppin' files to the iBook.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah: What software do you suggest for my iBook? I do word
processing and use databases and spreadsheets. Price is key. I'm a
grad student on a limited income.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Nowadays, most new computers come with bundled software.
Your swift little iBook has AppleWorks. It's a jack-of-all-trades
app that does all three. It also has nifty paint and graphics
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah: How do I erase my old data, and where can I donate my
LC and printer?
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Don't drag files to the Trash. Someone could ``untrash''
them. Lots of file-trashing apps exist. Surfing turned up
SafeDelete for $10.
(www.macinsearch.com/infomac2/disk/safe-delete-128.html). It'll
work on the LC and iBook. Get free Internet access and download the
application to the iBook. Transfer it to your LC, and start
zapping. To donate equipment, ask schools, churches and charities.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
