<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Purveyors of online news let you personalize the look
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's nothing more annoying than a TV newscast or
nightly newsmagazine that uses enticing teases so you'll stay tuned
for a great story later in the program.
</P>
<P>
   You sit and you wait for the news you want while newscasters
drone on about all kinds of things which, however newsworthy, just
don't interest you.
</P>
<P>
   If you surf the Web for news from the big sites like CNN, MSNBC
or ABCNews.com, things are slightly better. The news story you want
is there _ you just have to point and click a few times to get to
it. Yes, it is a better mousetrap for a quick news hit. The Web
gives you the ability to get the latest headlines without waiting
for the networks or even CNN Headline News to get to it.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any Silicon Valley billionaire will tell you, the key to
a successful Web site is personalization. The more personal the
connection between the user and the Web site, the more likely it is
that users will come back. Order just one book from Amazon.com, and
you will always and forever receive a cheery quasi-personal
greeting. We all know it's just a pile of technology programmed to
remember who we are and what we like, but it does serve a purpose _
to provide users with a personalized experience they won't find on
TV or in most brick-and-mortar department superstores.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get news you can use from the Web is to
personalize your online experience. Give up a little information
about yourself, and you'll get the news or the products you want
without wading through pages of things you don't want or don't care
about.
</P>
<P>
   If you give MSNBC your ZIP code, it will give you your local
weather forecast and a few local news headlines in addition to the
national stories it regularly features. It will also track three
stocks and provide local sports news if you select either option.
No registration is required, and there's no danger in letting MSNBC
know your ZIP code. If you don't play the market or hate sports,
you can tell MSNBC you don't want that information, and zap, it's
gone faster than you can say ``reload.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN will allow you to personalize your start page, too, as do
most of the major search engines. Yahoo, Snap, Lycos and even
Internet service providers such as EarthLink let you personalize a
start page with only the information you want, whether it's news,
sports, music, stocks or even horoscopes and a currency converter.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites will personalize news, weather and sports with just a
ZIP code, but if you want specifics, you have to register.
Registration usually means handing over your name, birthday and
e-mail address to the search engines. They'll also ask you if they
can send you information or give your name to their advertisers so
they can try and sell you things.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do to keep the prying eyes of advertisers and
search engines away is remember to uncheck all the pre-checked
boxes asking for your approval.
</P>
<P>
   After you wade through the registration process, you'll go right
to your personal page, but it's not personal yet. Now is the time
to decide what kind of news you want and from whom. Do you want
just sports scores for teams in your area, or do you want to add
some different ones? Do you want your horoscope daily, or would you
rather see how your stocks are doing?
</P>
<P>
   Among the personal start pages found on search engines, each
offers a variety of news and tools you can add to your page. Snap
is best for online content, with snippets of news from a variety of
publications ranging from Salon to U.S. News and World Report to
Athlete Daily.
</P>
<P>
   At the top corner of nearly every start page, you are offered
options, and every box of information can be edited.
</P>
<P>
   The range of choices can be mind-boggling. If the bright yellow
that Lycos uses as the default color on its personal page is
working your nerves or your eyeballs, you can just point and click
and change it.
</P>
<P>
   Designing your own personal start page is a bit like editing
your own online newspaper. You can decide what color scheme you
want, or how big you want the information boxes to be, or how many
news items you want to see at one time. Do you want to put the list
of local theaters and times ahead of the ski and snow report? Or
maybe you want your search function on top followed by world news
then local news headlines. This kind of thing can keep you busy for
hours. You can tinker with these pages once a year or once a day as
your interests change.
</P>
<P>
   Web skeptics may argue that giving any site, even your own
access provider, any information about yourself or your habits
online isn't a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you do have to tell these sites a bit about yourself before
you can proceed. But in return for letting them know who visits
their site, you get a page tailor-made for you. If you don't want
to wait for traffic on the threes or weather on the eights, it's a
reasonable trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
