<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The mundane isn't so blah, academic journal discovers
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is hard to remember that what we see on television
is not reality, but a small chunk of it.
</P>
<P>
   Stay home sick some day and watch TV. Teenage hookers and their
pimps. Moms who hit on their daughters' boyfriends. A woman who
married a millionaire stranger on prime time television complaining
about losing her privacy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not convinced by lunch that this is a Jerry Springer
nation, you'll know by Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it helps to stem the flow. Turn off the television.
Put down the tabloid rag. Don't listen to talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often, you'll have to do more than just ignore the
noise. You'll need to feed the normal stuff.
</P>
<P>
   That's where The Journal of Mundane Behavior comes in.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal Web site (www.mundanebehavior.org/), hosted by the
Sociology Department at California State University, Fullerton, is
``devoted to the study of the `unmarked' _ those aspects of our
everyday lives that typically go unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Issues can be read online or downloaded in Adobe Acrobat reader
format. The Adobe software can be downloaded, for free, from the
site.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to the first issue, Managing Editor Scott
Schaffer, a Cal State Fullerton professor, says, ``Most of us don't
live Jerry Springer lives. We get up at some ungodly hour, commute
an insane distance to work, live in a 6-foot by 6-foot cubicle for
eight or more hours, reverse the insane commute and go home to `our
lives.' This amounts to probably 60 percent of our lives, and the
editors here think that this vast amount of energy, effort, and in
some cases, sheer drudgery, deserves some attention. But this is
not the only part of our lives. ... The editors of Journal of
Mundane Behavior believe that the everyday, the earthly, the
worldly, represents a part of what is sacred about our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   With their attention to minute, mundane detail, the submissions
tend to read like failed Nicholson Baker novellas. They are written
by scholars with a similar audience in mind, so they are not for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue contains a piece on Japanese elevator etiquette.
Americans apparently barely acknowledge fellow elevator passengers,
staring straight ahead and waiting for their floor to arrive or
carrying on conversations with a friend in front of strangers. The
Japanese, however, see elevators as recess, according to the piece.
A chance to break from their culture's otherwise strict mold.
Another piece looks closely at the relationship between spatial
organization and social action as it relates to looking for a book
in a library.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting (read: accessible) pieces looks at
what facial hair, and a man's tendency to let it grow, says about
masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   Or, according to the introduction, it is an ``analysis of the
ways in which `masculinity' as a gender construct and a politicized
tool of identity formation are presented through a person's facial
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   If you thought a beard was just a beard, think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many are the men who grow beards to compensate for a receding
hairline, or a balding pate, resexualizing the image they present
to the world, just in case the world thinks they are starting to
flag. ... `I am a man,' says the beard, even before the man himself
has opened his mouth, a gaping hole in a hairy surround, grunting
his joy and his sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beard has never been without political significance. In
simple terms man presents his face to the world and it is known by
the hair that can grow upon it (and similarly women present their
faces to the world and they are known by their hairlessness).
Biology has little to do with the ways in which such attributes are
displayed; in fact it is conformity to a structured image which is
actually put on show.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
