<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inventor hopes seat belt indicator will save lives
 &HT;    By Glenn Evans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GILMER, Texas _ Ronald Slaughter has an idea he hopes will be
hitting the road soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've been working on for the last 2 1/2
years,'' the Gilmer resident said before demonstrating the Ace
Safety Device, for which a patent is pending and on which he
anticipates the U.S. Patent Office to bestow full blessing during
2000.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of Slaughter's invention installed inside his
Cadillac lets him know whether the seat belts inside the car are
being used. Each buckle includes sensors wired to four tiny red
lights mounted on the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   Another four lights, these yellow, are mounted on the rear
windshield. These tell people outside whether the people inside the
car are buckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the number of belts you have, that's the number of
lights you would have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost a brother who was not wearing his seat belt during a
1995 traffic accident, Slaughter's mind naturally steers toward
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The device is named in honor of his brother, Angelo Eugene
Slaughter, whose nickname was Ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the wreck) was the week before the seat belt law was
enforced in Texas,'' Slaughter said, describing the evening his
brother's car pool from Lone Star Steel encountered a semi-trailer
truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one sad story after another. This idea came to me on
Sept. 22, 1997, and I call it a gift from God. I went to my
computer and drew it up, and that's where I got my start.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter said every state has a different approach to seat
belts, and auto manufacturers await a national safety belt bill
before they will be willing to seriously discuss the added feature.
Meanwhile, he said Bill Clinton announced the Presidential
Initiative for Seat Belt Use in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are talking about saving lives,'' he said. ``When a
drunk driver gets in a car, the last thing he is thinking about is
fastening a seat belt. ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter, a native of Gary, Ind., moved to Gilmer 27 years ago
with the bride he met at Wiley College. Mary Jo Slaughter, a
third-grade teacher at Daingerfield Elementary, is from the Buckeye
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call her my co-inventor,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   (photo available)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
