<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special Newsweek tells how to employ Net as career tool
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More and more people are turning to the Web to find a
job. The Internet is full of sites that offer classified ads, help
with writing a resume and job tips.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a maze navigating all the various sites, and some are
excellent while others are just a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a special edition of Newsweek, called ``How to Use
the Internet to Choose or Change Careers,'' is worth your time.
You'll discover the magazine's views on the hot cities of the new
economy and find job-search tips and ways to make an e-mailed job
query work for you.
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails and you find that you need to change careers,
you'll find an article that offers a guide to various graduate
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Are there days when you are stuck in traffic and get the crazy
desire for back roads and deserted highways where you can safely
put the pedal to the metal?
</P>
<P>
   Well, they're harder to come by _ besides, it's dangerous. But
there is a computer game that lets you drive fast, take crazy
chances and still keep your life and your auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The game is called ``Rally Championship,'' and it comes from
Electronic Arts. You can read about it at
www.ea.com/rallychampionship, or just drop by your favorite
software store and pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need a Windows PC with a 266-megahertz or faster
processor and a burning desire for speed.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   There are Web sites that offer jokes, weather forecasts and even
the population of Des Moines, Iowa. Plenty of sites also want to
sell you something.
</P>
<P>
   But humanitarian groups also have a presence on the Web. While
the pages may not be as flashy, there's a lot of socially conscious
information to be had.
</P>
<P>
   One page in particular, the Human Rights Watch World Report 2000
at www.hrw.org/wr2k/, may be of interest if you have a world view.
</P>
<P>
   You can simply click on the country that interests you and find
out about the political climate there and of any abuses. Like most
activist groups, there is a definite point of view here. But it
makes for fascinating reading whether or not you agree.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you're in San Francisco, you may find the world
famous Exploratorium, a really nifty hands-on science museum and
exhibit, worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   But if you'd like to take a sneak peek right now, you can check
out the Web site at www.exploratorium.edu.
</P>
<P>
   You'll actually be able to participate in some of the exhibits,
including one called the Fading Eye.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the link for that on the page, along with plenty of
other family-rated activities, including the online store where you
can buy unusual gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
