<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You needn't upgrade all your computer components at once
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The trouble with loving gadgets is that I have a
difficult time resisting them. So my house is beginning to look
like a second-hand electronics shop, with ham radio gear in the
basement, stereo stuff on the first floor, and the big-screen TV
and its assorted amplifiers and speakers up on top.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that _ with all the money I'm spending _ I'll be
scrounging for partially eaten cabbages in the trash bin behind the
Kroger store. Since some of you might be in the same boat _ after
all, we nerds seem to hang out together _ I thought we'd talk today
about some ways to save some money when it comes to computers.
We'll do it by bucking a trend in computer retailing.
</P>
<P>
   If you walk down the aisles of a computer store, you'll see that
most of the systems are bundled. You end up getting the computer,
monitor, all sorts of accessories, a printer and sometimes a
scanner. The system also is packed with software and sometimes
comes with a free Internet offer.
</P>
<P>
   All that sounds good, but in some ways, it's like going to the
grocery store to buy a roast to cook for Sunday and ending up with
a package deal that includes the plates, glasses, some wine and
even the knives and forks.
</P>
<P>
   The smart way to buy computers _ and this will help you stay up
in a world where today's fastest machine is a techno-dinosaur by
tomorrow _ is to treat a computer system like a stereo outfit.
Today you might buy a really good set of speakers, then replace the
amplifier in a year or so, each time getting really good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   You can do the same thing with computers. By buying just one
component at a time and gradually replacing the weak links in your
system, you can spread out the cost.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a lot more advantages than that to my system.
</P>
<P>
   Since all of us have different ways we use a computer, by
replacing your system a component at a time, you can gradually
create a system that is tailored to your needs.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you a few ``for instances.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's say I'm a computer gamer. I'd want to spend most of my
money on a high-end video card to handle the graphics and maybe a
really terrific monitor, but skimp on things like a printer and a
scanner.
</P>
<P>
   Or if my thing were the Internet, I could buy a low-end
processor and spend money for a fast connection (either DSL or a
cable modem). What I'm saying is that a computer system is just
that _ a system _ and you can assemble the components that suit the
way you use it.
</P>
<P>
   There's still another leg to this strategy: Identify the
components you won't likely have to replace every year or so and
spend money on top-end components that are unlikely to go out of
date.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some of you might want to look into a really cool
flat monitor, or a regular monitor that's 19 to 21 inches. If you
get a good monitor now, it'll probably last you through three or
four computers.
</P>
<P>
   Printers also are a relatively stable component. Inkjet printers
have gotten a lot better over the past three or four years, and the
top-end models today are liable to last for a long time. It's the
same with scanners and digital cameras _ both are much improved,
and one that is good today is likely to remain usable for years.
</P>
<P>
   If you follow my strategy, you'll soon be in the position of
just replacing your computer processor, as needed. If you get a
midrange computer as far as speed, it may well last you for two or
three years if your prime use is e-mail, letters and simple tasks
like figuring your taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Try my system. I have a selfish motive, of course. If I can save
you some money, maybe there won't be as much competition at the
trash bin behind Kroger for those cabbages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
