</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle over Elian: What's next?
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The United States government told Elian Gonzalez's
relatives in Miami to speed up their court fight over trying to
gain custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   If they refuse, the government could return the 6-year-old to
Cuba immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a branch of the U.S. government ordered Elian
returned to his father in Cuba. The boy's Miami relatives filed a
lawsuit to keep him in America. A Miami court dismissed their
lawsuit last week.
</P>
<P>
   The family has said it will take the case to an appeals court in
Atlanta. That court could review and overrule the other court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government says it doesn't want to keep the boy away
from his father longer than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was found in November clinging to a raft off the coast of
Florida. The boy and his mother were trying to escape Communist
Cuba and made a dangerous voyage across the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS FOUND
</P>
<P>
   Willie Fulgear didn't win best actor or best director at the
Academy Awards on Sunday, but he was honored for his honesty last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old salvage man was given $50,000 for recovering the
Oscar statues that were stolen two weeks ago. He found 52 Oscars in
a trash heap. Three are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody says honesty don't pay, send them to me,'' Fulgear
said.
</P>
<P>
   A truck driver who worked for the company that delivers the
awards has been charged with stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the front page of the Living section to see who did
win the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
