<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, March 28, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Scientists have recently
discovered a thumb-size primate species that lived in China 42
million years ago. It may help resolve missing links in the
evolutionary pattern as well as cast doubt on our exclusively
African origins. The tiny critter weighed only one-third of an
ounce and ate bugs at night. Interesting stuff, but I can tell you
right now my mother wouldn't like it one little bit. (Schuett, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA, Fla. _ All mechanical breakdowns are not
created equal. As you move up the food chain of home technology and
into the realm of what economists call ``durable goods'' (whether
or not they prove to be all that durable), people get irrationally
attached to machinery. This is the point when mechanical failure no
longer feels like the inevitable result of planned obsolesce. It
feels like the inscrutable punishment of an angry god. (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ A civil union has nothing to do
with religion. It has to do with contracts and commitments.
Seemingly everyone who values social responsibility would encourage
what a civil union represents. (John Young is opinion page editor
for the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FRIDAY,
</P>
