u e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     03-27 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 2)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CRIES UNHEARD: Why Children Kill. The Story of Mary Bell &LR;  By
Gitta Sereny. Owl/Holt, $16. Drawing on extensive interviews with
an Englishwoman who murdered two boys in 1968 when she was 11, the
author examines the troubling question of how society should deal
with children who commit violence. ``This is an extraordinarily
important and powerful work,'' Alex Kotlowitz wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1999. ``It will agitate, provoke and poke and
prod your preconceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLIZZARD OF ONE: Poems &LR;  By Mark Strand. Knopf, $15. In this
Pulitzer Prize-winning collection, the eminent poet approaches the
universal through the universal, apprehending a snowflake, for
example, not in its particularity but as linked to a continuum of
snowflakes outside and inside the reader's consciousness. His
magisterial verse evokes a godless world that returns our gaze with
a blank stare, and he offers only small consolations and rare
``spectral glimpses'' of poetic epiphany. ``Strand's willingness to
grapple at this dim frontier has a salutary, lone-wolf quality that
makes him more interesting as his voice mellows and ages,'' Deborah
Garrison wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PRAYER FOR THE DYING &LR;  By Stewart O'Nan. Picador USA, $13. The
sheriff of a small Wisconsin town is driven to the brink of madness
by a crisis brought on by twin plagues: a diphtheria epidemic and
advancing brush fires that threaten the lives of the quarantined
townspeople. Last year the reviewer Patrick McGrath called this ``a
fine, terse novel about the circumstantial nature of evil and the
terrible fragility of man.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDING IN A RIVER WAVING A STICK &LR;  By John Gierach.
Fireside/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13. This literate collection of
fly-fishing essays resembles an angler's book of days. ``It is as
fine a representation of outdoor writing as you're likely to find _
wise, funny and well wrought,'' Jeff MacGregor wrote in The New
York Times Book Review last year. ``Gierach is sly and smart and
writes a clean, purposeful line of prose.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRIEF INTERVIEWS WITH HIDEOUS MEN &LR;  By David Foster Wallace.
Back Bay/Little, Brown, $13.95. Moral fervor bubbles through these
unconventional stories about male selfishness, which are populated
by ``monstrous, parodic versions of Updikean characters,'' Adam
Goodheart said in 1999. ``Even when Wallace's postmodernist
chemistry projects simply fizzle out, there is always at least a
whiff of genius.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FARM SHE WAS &LR;  By Ann Mohin. Bridge Works, $13.95. This
poetic first novel about a tenacious 90-year-old woman struggling
to endure on her family's farm in upstate New York celebrates the
sounds and sensations of the barnyard. ``The particulars of her
seemingly humble life ... make her about as entertaining as any
real person could be,'' Sally Eckhoff wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLAYING FOR KEEPS: Michael Jordan and the World He Made &LR;  By
David Halberstam. Broadway, $14. In canvassing the dazzling career
of the basketball superstar, Halberstam depicts his subject as not
only a top-flight hoopster but a top-flight pitchman. ``Halberstam
delivers ... insight, balance, analysis'' and hard-dug facts, Ira
Berkow said in 1999. ``He skillfully skirts hagiography.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; MICHAEL JORDAN AND THE NEW GLOBAL CAPITALISM &LR; , by Walter
LaFeber (Norton, $12.95), a historian uses Jordan's popularity and
the worldwide profitability of the sportswear maker Nike to issue a
polemic on the corrosive effects of American capitalism abroad.
Last year the reviewer Jay R. Mandle said LaFeber begins with
``sound premises'' but fails to make a very persuasive case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OF CABBAGES AND KINGS COUNTY: Agriculture and the Formation of
Modern Brooklyn &LR;  By Marc Linder and Lawrence S. Zacharias.
University of Iowa, $21.95. This timely study of the effects of
unchecked suburban sprawl charts the transformation of
turn-of-the-century Brooklyn from a rural community into a tightly
packed urban center. The result is a ``thoughtful and well-written
history,'' Keith Schneider wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU MUST REMEMBER THIS: An Oral History of Manhattan From the
1890s to World War II &LR; , by Jeff Kisseloff (Johns Hopkins
University, $19.95), is a sweeping collage of voices drawn from 10
city neighborhoods. In 1989 the reviewer Meredith Tax said
``Kisseloff is a sensitive interviewer'' and his book ``has
wonderful passages.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MODEL BEHAVIOR &LR;  By Jay McInerney. Vintage Contemporaries, $11.
A young magazine writer gets dumped by a beautiful model and
searches for meaning amid the decadent glamour of New York. Sound
familiar? In 1998 the reviewer A.O. Scott found this return to the
terrain of ``Bright Lights, Big City'' to be a mixed bag.
``McInerney is a gifted and exasperating writer,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SINKING OF THE ODRADEK STADIUM &LR;  By Harry Mathews. Dalkey
Archive, $11.95. In a series of madcap letters, an American
intellectual in Miami Beach and his Asian wife, who is living in
Italy, chronicle their fitful search for a treasure supposedly lost
off the Florida coast in the 16th century. In 1975 the reviewer
Edmund White called this futuristic novel ``a comic masterpiece.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
