<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, April 2)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending March 18 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. BITTERSWEET, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman copes with a midlife crisis: Should she
</P>
<P>
   pursue her old career as a photojournalist?
</P>
<P>
   2. CERTAIN PREY, by John Sandford. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Davenport pursues a woman who is a longtime
</P>
<P>
   successful hired killer.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   4. FALSE PRETENSES, by Catherine Coulter. (Signet, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal suffered by a New York society woman after her
</P>
<P>
   husband's murder.
</P>
<P>
   5. A SEASON BEYOND A KISS, by Kathleen E. Woodiwiss.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14.) In the early 19th century, a woman's marriage
</P>
<P>
   to a shipping magnate is endangered by the cruel rumors
</P>
<P>
   that bedevil him.
</P>
<P>
   6. RAIN, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket, $7.99.) A girl who
</P>
<P>
   has grown up in the Washington ghettos is sent to live
</P>
<P>
   with a wealthy family.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE CIDER HOUSE RULES, by John Irving. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Life in a Maine orphanage in the first part of
</P>
<P>
   the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   9. SEND NO FLOWERS, by Sandra Brown. (Bantam, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young widowed mother embarks on an affair with an
</P>
<P>
   enigmatic man.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) WITNESS IN DEATH, by J.D. Robb. (Berkley, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eve Dallas investigates the onstage stabbing
</P>
<P>
   of a leading man.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE GIRL WHO LOVED TOM GORDON, by Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $6.99.) A girl who is a fan of the
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox gets lost in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   12. SSN, created by Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $7.99.) World War III as experienced by
</P>
<P>
   a nuclear submarine's captain.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) A CERTAIN SMILE, by Judith Michael. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) An American clothing designer finds love when
</P>
<P>
   she travels to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE HOURS, by Michael Cunningham. (Picador USA, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   The lives of two modern women converge with the life and
</P>
<P>
   work of Virginia Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) SUSPICION OF BETRAYAL, by Barbara Parker. (Signet,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A vengeful killer threatens a Miami lawyer and her
</P>
<P>
   daughter.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) H.M.S. UNSEEN, by Patrick Robinson. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) A fanatical terrorist hijacks a Royal Navy submarine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   3.THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. BLACK HAWK DOWN, by Mark Bowden. (Penguin, $13.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The bloody battle between American forces and Somali
</P>
<P>
   street fighters in Mogadishu in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $15.) A presentation of superstring
</P>
<P>
   theory, which attempts to mediate between
</P>
<P>
   quantum mechanics and general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   8. TRAVELING MERCIES, by Anne Lamott. (Anchor, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A chronicle of the author's journey toward faith.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A counselor tells how she turned painful
</P>
<P>
   experiences into hope. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   14. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking
</P>
<P>
   the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) MURDER IN GREENWICH, by Mark Fuhrman. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The former detective probes the murder of a teen-age
</P>
<P>
   girl in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways
</P>
<P>
   to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S DIET, by Rachael F. Heller
</P>
<P>
   and Richard F. Heller. (Signet, $6.99.) A program for
</P>
<P>
   weight loss. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. LIFE STRATEGIES, by Phillip C. McGraw. (Hyperion,
</P>
<P>
   $11.95.) How to find what matters in your life and
</P>
<P>
   what to do about it. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. WHAT TO EXPECT WHEN YOU'RE EXPECTING, by Arlene
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg, Heidi E. Murkoff and Sandee E. Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   (Workman, $12.95.) Advice for parents-to-be. (b)
