<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAVANA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ELOQUENT STASIS, HAVANA AWAITS A NEW ERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By MIRTA OJITO   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Havana, everything waits. Forty-one years after Fidel Castro
came down from the hills to claim Cuba's then-vibrant capital, the
island has become, says photographer Stephen Crowley, ``a giant
waiting room.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, Cuba has lost its place in the
superpower confrontation and lost its life-sustaining subsidies
from the Soviet Union. Virtually no Latin American governments look
admiringly on Castro or his regime anymore. Instead, 11 million
people live out the tail end of a revolution, on an island cut off
and no longer of vital interest to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   So Cubans have made lives out of waiting. They wait for a house
to move into, for their turn at the bread line, to buy newspapers
that later in the day will be used as toilet paper. They wait for
dollars, for a visa to the United States, for a ride, for a package
with life-saving medicines, for the lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   There is neither joy nor community in their desuetude.
Contemplating the length of another day, people sit on the curb or
listlessly stand next to each other, isolated, wrapped up in their
own worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Under the harsh tropical light, only the architecture seems
alive. The sensuous curves of Art Deco and the concrete and steel
of a later era are unexpectedly fluid. Whole buildings seem to
change by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   But the people of Cuba, together, yet alone, wait as if
suspended in time, in the calm before the storm. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
