<P>
   BAHAI-RADIO (Hemingway, S.C.) _ Williamsburg County, a rural
slice of the Bible Belt an hour's drive from the Atlantic coast, is
just the place one expects to find religious radio. Yet it is this
setting that makes WLGI, a radio station outside this small town,
such a surprise. To listeners, WLGI is known as ``Radio Baha'i,'' a
15-year-old project of one of the world's newer religions, a
monotheistic faith that emerged in 19th-century Persia. By Gustav
Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
