<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-RADIO-GURU-TEXT-REVIE     03-27 1667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-GURU-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING JEAN SHEPHERD: PECULIAR RIFFS ON AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl) 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's start with a supportable thesis, and duly credit a master:
For pure listening satisfaction it's hard to improve on the
seductive intimacy of radio.
</P>
<P>
   From 1956 to 1977, Jean Shepherd held weeknight seminars on
WOR-AM in New York that were part Kabuki, part commedia dell'arte,
part Uncle Remus. In his flat, nasal Indiana twang, playing all the
parts, and the occasional kazoo, he oozed into the darkened
bedrooms of East Coast America on the battery power of cheap
Japanese transistor radios. The meandering stories he told _ they
always came back to the point,  &UR; always &LR;  _ were usually about him.
But they also seemed to be about us _ about the old man, family car
trips, the Catch-22 Army and a cast of playmates from childhood and
adolescence, through whom all the complexities of life on earth
would be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   What was he? Social commentator? Cult leader? Or just a manic
kid from a blue-collar background discovering his subversive id in
the age of Eisenhower? It was Shepherd, after all, who alerted
America to the scourge of ``creeping meatballism,'' the postwar
rush to a conformist society where happiness meant cars with tail
fins and a refreshing, ice-cold bottle of Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing department at WOR never deciphered his demographic
silhouette. The station fired him in 1977, over frustration with
his format. Shepherd continued to write books (``In God We Trust,
All Others Pay Cash,'' ``Wanda Hickey's Night of Golden Memories
and Other Disasters'') and went on to make films for public
television and delve into other broadcasting venues from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
   His death last October at age 78 proved a catalyst for a
memorial by his admirers, among them the humorist Harry Shearer and
Art Silverman, associate producer of ``All Things Considered'' on
National Public Radio. With others they put together a two-hour
show of reminiscences as well as generous chunks from Shepherd's
programs. The result, ``A Voice in the Night,'' was broadcast last
Christmas Eve on KCRW-FM in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in April, the program will be distributed to public
radio stations around the country to schedule as they wish. In New
York, WNYC-AM will broadcast the show May 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an insatiable appetite for one-way conversation,'' said
Silverman, recalling some off-the-air encounters in which he felt
more like audience than companion.
</P>
<P>
   It is a common refrain among those who knew Shepherd, one that
may help explain why he worked alone, with rarely anything more
than a newspaper clipping in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the radio tribute follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CHARLES STRUM
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Shepherd essays cannot easily be excerpted;
their point may not become evident until the very last moments of
the show, when his equestrian musical theme, ``The Bahn Frei
Polka'' by Eduard Strauss, kicks in over his peroration. The
following is his prelude to a piece about how he _ a child of
meatloaf and mashed potatoes _ came to taste his first plate of
escargot, and thus his first taste of the wider world: (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   At a certain age in life, when you're _ oh, I'd say _ roughly
between 15 and 19, possibly, although that, you know, is subject to
change, you really believe you know what it's about. You really,
seriously think you've got life by the you-know-what. And you
really know what it's about. And you can't figure out why all these
other people, usually older people, keep saying that things are not
what they seem to be. What do you mean they're not? They are. You
really believe it.
</P>
<P>
   And then, then, of course, as you get older, you begin to have
faint inklings, faint inklings of what an ignoramus you have been
up to this point in life. And it's just beginning to dawn on you
what an unbelievable ignorant slob you are now.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Another opening gambit: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be _ wouldn't it be fascinating if we had preserved,
actually preserved, really preserved just, just the way he was, you
see, with his armor on and everything, a Roman gladiator? . . .
</P>
<P>
   Well, let me tell you this: that you will be just as great an
attraction 2,000 years from now. If we could preserve you, any one
of you _ even, even the nothingest of us, me, any of us, you know _
we'd be fascinating to a guy 2,000 _ here's a real 20th-century
man, just the way he was, sitting there with that funny look on his
face, kind of sad, obviously suffering from post-Ed Sullivan shock,
just sitting there with a limp old copy of TV Guide in his hand,
one shoelace open.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, you know how, like we really are, you know, with a hole
in the sock. The whole business. Sitting there. You'd be a real
specimen. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And after a thousand years, you'd be great. Really, you'd be _
you'd be famous, you'd be in a museum in a case. And after 2,000
years, you'd be bigger than the Rosetta stone. And you're nothing
now, you know that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-RADIO-GURU-TEXT-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: know that. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) On civic virtues and his discontents: (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I think Americans are the only people in the world today, I
really do, who really, literally, spend most of their time _
whether it's in politics, whether it's in satire, art, fiction, you
name it _ breast beating, baring its soul and proclaiming to the
heavens how rotten it is. And of course everybody around agrees.
You go to England, you go to France, they all agree loudly, 'cause
it lets them off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   They've been plugging all day long, on the air, that you should
get out and vote. Well . . . this is one guy who says there's a lot
of you who shouldn't. I've heard a lot of you discuss politics and
I'm worried, when I think of you guys voting. I'm really serious.
You know, they seem to think here in America that voting in itself
is a positive virtue. In fact, I heard one spot by some friendly
lady who does a program here on WOR that seemed to say in spite of
the fact you don't know anything about it, and don't let that stop
you, get out and vote, and thereby you will nullify the vote of
somebody who does know something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right, I'm just merely saying voting itself, friends,
is not a virtue, and if you don't know anything about it, stay
away. You're liable to get us all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) When seeing is not always believing: (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   One of the secret desires that all kids have is to be invisible
and to, you know, to sneak somehow, nobody would see you, see. And,
well, of course, not only kids want to do that. But this is a kid
thing, and this leads to all kinds of things. For example, there
used to be a thing advertised in the back of Popular Mechanics, and
also Boy's Life, when I was a kid, and it said See-Through X-Ray
Eyes. Ever seen that thing? It said see through bones, and it shows
a hand that says look through and see your very own bones. This
see-through X-ray eye device enables you to see through anything at
will. Send 10 cents to Johnson &AMP; Johnson. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And about three months later this thing came back, this little
round tube, you know. And it's got what looks like frosted glass or
something on the end of it, see. And the instructions came with it,
a little smudgy piece of paper that showed a kid, you know, looking
through this thing, holding his hand up, and you can see the bones.
And it says the see-through X-ray eye device is very simply worked.
It is worked by placing it to your eye, as shown in diagram A, and
then holding your hand up to the light, as shown by diagram B. Then
if the light is properly adjusted, one will see the bones through
the eyepiece marked C in diagram D. End of instructions.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Eventually, he sees the bones of his hands.
But at school, when he tries to look through the dress of a
classmate, Esther Jane Alberry, he sees nothing: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I've been had. All of my life I'm going to walk around seeing
the bones of my left hand and my right hand, nothing but the bones
in my mitt. It does not look through flowered print dresses.
</P>
<P>
   So kids, don't believe everything you see. Don't believe every
ad you read.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Reflecting on his participation in the 1963
civil rights march in Washington: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   We left 47th Street. I rode on a bus with maybe 200,000 other
people all riding on buses towards Washington, D.C. And one of the
great things that happened was not, oh, not more than 15 or 20
minutes after we got on the road with the bus, other buses started
to pass us in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   We had a very old, terrible bus. And you know, I'll tell you,
have you ever ridden on a bus, a crosstown bus, all the way to
Washington? I'm serious. A lot of people did. The bus that was with
us was a crosstown bus. They just took the crosstown sign out and
everybody sat on those plastic seats and went all the way to
Washington and back. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I had talked with guys who were planning to go and arranging
this thing. I had all kinds of ideas in my mind about the way it
would be, just like all of us have ideas in our head about what
history is. I'm sure you have ideas about how it must have been
like to be in Germany in the '20s. Well, it wasn't. Not the way you
think it was.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you probably thought _ you have ideas of how it must
have been like at the time Washington was crossing the Delaware.
Forget it. It wasn't. It wasn't the way you think it was. I was not
there. Just know one thing: It wasn't the way you think it was.
</P>
<P>
   And I affirm that VERY FEW THINGS ARE THE WAY YOU THINK THEY
ARE. I say that in caps.
</P>
</TEXT>
