   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS (Undated) _ There is speculation, and then there are
foregone conclusions. The reporting team at the Wall Street Journal
that cold-called 1,400 members of the Academy Motion Picture Arts
and Sciences (and got 356 to discuss their votes in the six major
categories) projected that ``American Beauty'' would win the Oscar
for best picture at the 72nd annual Academy Awards. Lo and behold
it won best picture _ and four more of its eight categories. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-OSCARS (Undated) _ instead of stealing the Oscar statues,
couldn't somebody have stolen an hour out of the broadcast? The
72nd Academy Award presentation was a whole lot like most of the
ones that preceded it: bloated, self-indulgent, richly anticipated
but ultimately not nearly as rewarding as the movies themselves. By
TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SURGICAL-SUTURES (San Francisco) _ The families of a San
Francisco school counselor, a San Jose, Calif., homemaker and an
Oklahoma rancher _ each killed by infections after routine
operations _ have filed wrongful death lawsuits against Ethicon
Corp., the world's largest manufacturer of surgical sutures. By
LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-PRIVACY (San Francisco) _ Now that the Census 2000 form
has reached 115 million households, lots of people are wondering
why the federal government needs to know if you or anyone in your
family has difficulty dressing, bathing or getting around inside
the home. They think the census form is too personal. By The San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-SCHOLARSHIPS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Colleges are increasingly
making student grants based on performance instead of need. The
move toward merit-based rather than need-based awards is an example
of how government policies are being played out in homes,
classrooms and college admission offices across the nation. By RICK
KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-SCIENTIST (San Francisco) _ Amid concern nationally about
the scarcity of women in the high ranks of major research centers,
a University of California-San Francisco scientist is charging that
the male power structure on campus has made it impossible for her
to work there. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   GENOCIDE-SUSPECT (Lardeo, Texas) _ A Rwandan clergyman accused
of genocide was extradited from the United States last week after
spending nearly three years in the county jail here. Elizaphan
Ntakirutimana arrived in Tanzania on Friday to face an
international war crimes tribunal, a staffer with the U.S.
secretary of state said. By BONNIE PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEME-WEDDINGS (San Francisco) _ Why simply tie the knot when
you can do it with a twist? That's the question prompting a growing
number of couples to transform their weddings around
tradition-defying themes. The trend is flourishing in Northern
California, where experts now say at least one in every 20 weddings
is a themed concoction _ be it a Roman toga feast, a cowboy
barbecue hoedown or a you-name-it. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ One pitfall for workers is the
feeling that they have to be The Champion or else they're failing.
Not everyone wants to be a CEO, certainly, but often there is this
internal pressure to be the top producer or get the stock options
or join a Big Six firm. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco 49ers have lost
their No. 1 fan. Lido Starelli, who missed only one Niners home
game since 1946 and was officially named the team's top fan in
1998, has died of cancer. He was 79. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A stunning letter from the
American Fisheries Society calls California Fish and Game director
Bob Hight irresponsible for settling for anything less than
complete eradication of northern pike at Lake Davis in the Sierra
Nevada. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's not just seeing new
people and new lands that is the reward of overseas travel, but
also what you sometimes discover about your own country. So it was
with five weeks touring New Zealand and Australia recently. By
HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
</TEXT>
