Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on Cuban Boy
</P>
<P>
   The international custody battle over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
seems to be nearing a conclusion. After a federal judge in Miami
concluded that only Attorney General Janet Reno can grant the boy
asylum, Reno said Elian should be reunited with his father in Cuba
in a prompt, orderly fashion. Lawyers for both sides wrangled over
just how, and if, that would be accomplished. The government wants
lawyers for Elian's relatives in Miami to agree to a speedy
timetable for any appeal of the ruling, but the lawyers have
balked.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   '60s Militant Arrested
</P>
<P>
   H. Rap Brown spent the last 25 years effacing his reputation as
one of the most militant black radicals of the 1960s. He changed
his name to Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, became the imam of his mosque
in Atlanta and helped clean up his impoverished neighborhood. But
his peaceful obscurity was shattered when he was accused of the
shooting of two Atlanta sheriff's deputies, one of whom died.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was captured after a shootout in Lowndes County, Ala.,
and he claimed to be the victim of a ``governmental conspiracy.''
His trial is likely to be a death penalty case.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
<P>
   Decoding the Fruit Fly
</P>
<P>
   At their annual meeting, biologists who study the Drosophila
fruit fly got a gift: a CD-ROM, courtesy of Celera Corp.,
containing the DNA code for the fly's 13,601 genes. The decoding of
the fly's genome validates a bold strategy that Celera is confident
will work on the human genome. The understanding of the fly's
genome will be of major help in interpreting the human genome.
Wings aside, the organisms have a surprising amount of genetic
equipment in common.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Court Rules on Student Fees
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment protects the right to speak _ and sometimes
the right not to speak. No one can be forced to salute the flag,
for example. Conservative college students have argued that they
should not have to support causes they disagree with through
mandatory student activity fees.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting that argument, the Supreme Court said the overall
quantity of speech at universities mattered more. Unbounded debate
is central to a university's mission, the court said, and mandatory
fees are constitutional as long as the money collected is
distributed without regard to viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Record Sex-Bias Award
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of America, the government-run radio service that
broadcasts news about the United States abroad, and its parent
agency agreed to pay a record $508 million to 1,100 women to settle
a sex discrimination case. If the settlement is approved by the
judge overseeing the case, each woman will get at least $450,000.
The suit, which was filed 23 years ago, charges that the women were
denied jobs and promotions with the service.
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: IRVIN MOLOTSKY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grisly Discoveries in Uganda
</P>
<P>
   The corpses of more than 150 people were found by the Ugandan
police buried under a building used by a doomsday cult involved in
a fire on March 17 in which 500 of its members died.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were found about 40 miles from the church at Kanungu
where the 500 members of the cult perished when their church was
set ablaze, the police said. The police said the discovery shed new
light on the Kanungu blaze, which they said they were treating as a
mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction in Subway Murder
</P>
<P>
   A New York jury convicted Andrew Goldstein, a schizophrenic man
who threw a woman to her death in front of a subway train last
year, of intentional murder and rejected his insanity defense. The
case has prompted scrutiny of how the mentally ill are cared for in
New York. A law named for the victim, Kendra Webdale, allows courts
to compel the mentally ill to submit to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JULIAN E. BARNES
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes Drug Withdrawn
</P>
<P>
   Two widely used drugs, blamed for deaths among patients, are
being taken off the market. The diabetes drug Rezulin, linked to 63
deaths from liver failure since 1997, was withdrawn by Parke-Davis.
The 500,000 Americans taking the drug were urged not to stop until
they get other treatment. Janssen Pharmaceutica, the maker of the
heartburn drug Propulsid, which has caused 80 deaths from heart
problems, said the drug would also be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Gay Bias in Military
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon report found that anti-homosexual harassment in the
U.S. military remains widespread, especially in the form of
offensive remarks and gestures. The survey, ordered after a gay
soldier was beaten to death last July at Fort Campbell, Ky., also
found that an overwhelming majority of service members believe
their superiors and colleagues tolerate harassment ``to some
extent.'' The survey suggested that despite repeated efforts to
prohibit such behavior, negative attitudes toward gays remain a
pervasive part of military culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   Good News for the Elderly
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted unanimously to repeal a Depression-era
provision that forced Social Security recipients to give up all or
part of their retirement benefit if they earned more than $17,000 a
year. The House passed the same measure this month, and President
Clinton said he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was intended to discourage older people from
remaining in the work force. But with employers complaining about a
shortage of workers, the political case for abolishing the earnings
limit became overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Move on Internet Drug Sales
</P>
<P>
   In its first action against foreign Internet sites selling
prescription drugs to American consumers, the U.S. Customs Service
joined Thai authorities in raiding online pharmacies in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane E. Henney, the commissioner of food and drugs, has sent
warnings to 13 Web sites in other countries, saying they could be
violating federal law by selling prescription drugs to U.S.
citizens without valid prescriptions. Such drugs may be dangerous,
she said, because there is no assurance they were properly
manufactured or stored.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-GLOBALIZATION-CONFLIC     03-27 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBALIZATION-CONFLICTS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE TRADE MEETS THE LURE OF THE GUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For seven years now, Bill Clinton has been chanting
the mantra that countries that invest in education and focus on the
Web are far more likely to prosper than those that measure their
power in kilotons and argue over bleak pieces of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   He made the case again last week in India and Pakistan while his
top aides were delivering variations on the theme in Beijing. A
third major flash point, the Middle East, was on his agenda for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the argument that seemed so reasonable just a few years ago
_ that plugging into a dynamic world economy will bring prosperity
and tame nasty nationalistic tendencies _ is proving a hard sell as
Clinton races around the globe in the last 10 months of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The world's most economically isolated nations, like Pakistan
and Syria, see no hope of catching up with their more economically
advanced competitors, and those well on the road to global
competitiveness, like India, China and Israel, believe more than
ever that their economic potential must be married with military
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Take India's Parliament, which swooned when Clinton talked
excitedly of the booming software houses of Bangalore and when he
predicted that, as India makes the inevitable choice between ``the
hand loom or the hyperlink,'' its standard of living could sextuple
in the next two decades. Yet as soon as Clinton suggested that
India's economic progress is being undercut by its nuclear testing
and territorial battle over Kashmir, his hosts got their backs up.
</P>
<P>
   Just because our future is etched on a silicon chip, they shot
back, in effect, don't think we're about to give up the Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, meanwhile, hard-liners were using the election of an
independence-leaning president in Taiwan to bolster their case that
it was time for ``economic integration'' with the world to take a
back seat to the assertion of China's sovereignty over what they
see as a breakaway island. It is still unclear whether the generals
will retake the upper hand from those who argue that the real
business of the Communist Party is business.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Syria's president, Hafez Assad, whose waffling on
a peace accord with Israel prompted Clinton to schedule a
face-to-face meeting Sunday in Switzerland. For years now Clinton
has been sketching out his vision of the Middle East's economic
potential if only it could stop arguing over security and
territory. But now a great deal of that vision hinges on his
ability to persuade a reclusive and ailing Syrian leader
increasingly preoccupied with creating a family dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those disputes, of course, is driven by its own
emotional history of ugly conflict. But they all serve to
illustrate the dangers of too simplistic a faith in the lure of the
market when nationalistic impulses flare up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Americans often see a rigid tradeoff between economic
success in an age of globalization and increasing your old-style
military power,'' said Paul Bracken, a Yale professor whose book
``Fire in the East'' (HarperCollins, 1999) explored the growing
nuclear threats in Asia and the Middle East. ``The rest of the
world doesn't see it that way. And in fact, their growing
nationalism is a counterweight, in their minds, to the other
strains they are feeling as their worlds are changed'' by
borderless competition.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalism isn't the only factor at play. All three flash
points are made more complex and unpredictable by the fact that
nervous authoritarian regimes are facing off against some variety
of democracy _ a mix that can produce political miscalculation when
one side misunderstands how the other makes its decisions. Witness
how China's heavy-handed threats, aimed at intimidating Taiwan's
voters, backfired to the point that the Taiwanese elected the
candidate who until recently had talked of asserting independence.
</P>
<P>
   And in each dispute, Washington's own motives are suspect.
Americans often view themselves as neutral arbiters, only seeking
to spread peace. But from Delhi to Shanghai to the Persian Gulf,
suspicions are greater than ever these days that the sole military
and economic superpower is using its ``neutral'' role to create a
world that plays to Washington's commercial and geopolitical
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Why has a seemingly persuasive argument _ that it's wiser to
invest in education and broadband networks than in nuclear
reprocessors _ run up against such opposition both in unplugged
nations and in the most plugged-in?
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and Syria are good places to start. Both are about as
disconnected from the world economy as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   But, while both countries harbor enormous reservoirs of native
talent, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the leader of Pakistan, and Assad in
Syria understand the nature of the poison pill: if they took
Clinton's advice, the medicine that would be good for the country
would eat away at their own holds on power. Among major
authoritarian regimes at the turn of the century, only China's
Communist leaders have made the bet that they can loosen controls
on the economy, allow in the Internet and still exert iron control
over the nation's politics.
</P>
<P>
   So Pakistan holds on to nukes for the same reason that NATO did
in Europe: as a guarantee against a much larger force across the
border. Add to that nationalistic pride. But what about India?
Doesn't it see that a nuclear arms race drains resources that could
be better spent conquering new cybermarkets?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-GLOBALIZATION-CONFLICTS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: new cybermarkets? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the opposite,'' says Jeffrey Garten, dean of the
Yale School of Management, who as a top Commerce Department
official peddled a lot of Clinton's networks-not-nukes message.
``In the first half of the 20th century, countries wanted
well-rounded power. The Cold War, though, created an odd sense that
only a couple of countries would be both economic and military
powerhouses. Now the pendulum is swinging back.''
</P>
<P>
   So India wants both. As does Israel, and both China and Taiwan.
Indeed, countries look at the one nation that was supposed to
exercise ``soft power'' through economic and technological prowess
alone _ Japan _ and they see a pitiful excuse for a superpower.
Once the economic magic went away, so did the global diplomatic
influence.
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect between analog and digital nations is worsened
when the former are authoritarians and the latter are some variety
of democracy. This has long been a problem in the Middle East.
Assad's rhetoric regularly frays the fragile coalition keeping
Prime Minister Ehud Barak in power in Israel. Nothing new there.
But Barak has long promised that any peace deal with Syria will be
put up to a national referendum in Israel, and that means final
adoption could be unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   But for real miscalculation, pop back and forth between Beijing
and Taipei. China's leaders have what one senior U.S. official last
week called a ``near-perfect ability to miscalculate'' the effects
of their words on the Taiwanese electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Yu Maochun, a professor at the U.S. Naval Academy who
specializes in cross-straits relations, was sitting in a noisy
Taipei restaurant earlier this month when the television broadcast
a warning to Taiwan from China's premier, Zhu Rongji. The mainland,
he said, was willing to ``spill blood'' to prevent independence.
``People stood up and yelled'' in the restaurant, Yu said, making
vivid the backlash that was felt throughout Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a man as sophisticated about the world as Zhu, China's
leading economic reformer, make such a blunder?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communist Party, when it comes to big problems, is
elitist,'' says Yu. ``It is accustomed to sitting down behind
closed doors with a Nixon or a Kissinger and solving a problem. Now
it is faced with a whole different kind of foreign policy
challenge. And they can't handle the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Democracies miscalculate, too. It was India that inflamed the
long-running sore with Pakistan two years ago when it uncorked
nuclear tests. Some Indian elites now concede that the nuclear
grandstanding _ a great crowd pleaser at home _ paved the way for
the rise of General Musharraf in Pakistan, who had engineered some
of the horrors in Kashmir, then took command in a coup. Now, U.S.
officials believe, he figures that if the war at the top of the
world gets splashed on enough front pages, India will be forced to
accept what it has long rejected _ outside mediation from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The general may be proved wrong, but maybe not. With not much to
do at home, Clinton is moving from hot spot to hot spot, arguing
that all involve areas in America's strategic interest. The problem
is that Clinton envisions himself as an umpire, while the rest of
the world sees Washington as a player with its own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   There is suspicion in Beijing, for example, that America is
using all its weapons _ from the Seventh Fleet to its influence
over the World Trade Organization _ to contain China's power. The
Indians share a similar suspicion, even as they flocked to shake
Clinton's hand.
</P>
<P>
   And so for all the happy talk, the Indians had no intention of
signing on to Clinton's non-proliferation agenda. After all, they
said, that other great symbol of democracy _ the U.S. Senate _
rejected the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty last year, proving
that even the most powerful economy on earth wasn't willing to
forgo its nuclear options.
</P>
<P>
   So why, they asked, should they?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
