</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,300-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE AFTER `THE BOOK': SAVANNAH IN BLACK AND WHITE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photos of Savannah are available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (th) 
 &HT;    Terese Loeb Kreuzer is a free-lance writer whose travels have
taken around the globe.
 &HT;    
 By TERESE LOEB KREUZER 
 c.2000 Terese Loeb Kreuzer 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   In Savannah, Ga., when people say, ``The Book,'' they're not
talking about the Bible. They're referring to the best-selling
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' John Berendt's gossipy
expose of the hanky-panky behind Savannah's white-glove facade.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Book was published in 1994, tourist appetite for
all things connected to it shows no sign of abating. Every few
minutes, tour buses or horse-drawn carriages pull up in front of
the places mentioned in ``Midnight'' _ Clary's Cafe, Miss Emma
Kelly's night club and, most riveting to tourists, the Mercer
mansion, where Jim Williams killed his lover, Danny Hanford,
perhaps in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   The closed, louvered shutters of the mansion, where Williams'
sister still lives, express the impatience that many Savannah
residents seem to feel about this intrusion on their privacy. But
there's no denying it's been good for business.
</P>
<P>
   Savannah, with a population of 150,000, now attracts more than 5
million tourists a year. There probably always have been lines in
front of Mrs. Wilkes' Boarding House, where a $10, all-you-can-eat
family-style lunch is served five days a week, but these days, it
can take 30 minutes to an hour to get inside. Other restaurants are
also doing a booming business. The City Market section of town hops
at night.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants such as Garibaldi's, Bistro Savannah and Sapphire
pull in an eclectic crowd of students from the Savannah School of
Art and Design, tourists and locals out for a good time. For a
night cap, they may wander over to nearby Club One where drag
queens sashay across the stage, lipsynching to cranked-up music,
and suburbanites in shorts vie with muscle men in undershirts for
the honor of pushing bills into their cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Most nights, the cover charge for this entertainment is $5, but
when the Lady Chablis is in town, the entrance fee goes up to $22.
(Tour-bus operators titillate their gray-haired passengers by
telling them that the Lady Chablis' real name is Frank, and by
repeating some of her risque patter.)
</P>
<P>
   Although many people in town are cashing in on Midnight while
the going is good, this is just a blip in Savannah's long and
fascinating history. Georgia, including the city of Savannah, was
founded by James Oglethorpe in 1733 as a haven for debtors.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Catholics and lawyers, everyone was welcome in the
intrepid settlement on the Savannah River where pioneers shared
space with alligators, gnats and fever-breeding mosquitoes.
Savannah now has the gnats and mosquitoes under control, but
alligators still sun themselves on the golf courses just outside of
town.
</P>
<P>
   At first slavery was outlawed in the new colony but by 1753,
slaves accounted for nearly one-third of the population.
</P>
<P>
   If following ``The Book'' trail in Savannah palls, Sunday
services at the First African Baptist Church on Franklin Square,
the oldest black church in North America, can be highly
recommended. The church was founded in 1777, and the present
building was erected in 1859 by enslaved blacks. They worked 12 to
16 hours a day for their masters, but they still found the time and
resources to build a handsome structure and to decorate it with
gilded carvings and stained glass.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since some of the slaves were the master craftsmen and
builders who erected Savannah's finest houses, the church is simple
but just as resplendent. A small museum in the basement of the
church includes silver baskets donated to the sanctuary in 1814 by
the sisterhood, who somehow managed to collect money for this
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday services are a fervent affair. Men dazzle in their white
suits, women, in lacy white dresses topped with magnificent hats. A
gospel choir sings hymns, beating out the rhythms on tambourines.
The preacher elicits an ecstatic response from the congregation as
he leaves the pulpit and walks in the aisles. Sometimes there will
be a baptism in a pool behind the pulpit in which the person to be
baptized and the preacher descend into the water.
</P>
<P>
   This church played an important role in the history of Savannah.
On the lower level is a wooden floor with holes in it. Beneath the
floor is a 4-foot-high crawl space, part of the Underground
Railroad that enabled slaves to escape to freedom in the North.
More recently, beginning on March 16, 1960, high school and college
students prayed in the church before fanning out through downtown
Savannah to sit in at lunch counters in their attempts to bring
about integration.
</P>
<P>
   A diorama at the Ralph Mark Gilbert Civil Rights Museum on
Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard re-creates this period of black
history in Savannah and recounts other aspects of the black
experience in this city. The museum is open from Monday through
Saturday, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., with a small admission fee.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks are not the only minority group to have played a special
role in the history of Savannah. In 1733, the first Jewish
congregation in the South was established in this city. A memorial
stone at the corner of Bull and Oglethorpe streets, the center of
old Savannah, marks the Jewish graveyard. And Temple Mickve Israel
which dates from 1776-1778, displays letters from Washington,
Jefferson and Madison as well as the congregation's original Torah
scroll, which the settlers brought with them when they fled the
Portuguese Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The Wesley brothers (Charles and John) also found a temporary
haven in Savannah. John is known as the central founder of
Methodism and Charles as the author of hymns including ``Hark the
Herald Angels Sing.'' Their sojourn in Savannah was short and
unhappy, but the city still remembers them.
</P>
<P>
   John left town in a hurry after it was reported that both he and
his brother were ``dangerous snares to many young women.'' A statue
of John adorns Reynolds Square, and Trinity Methodist Church,
housed in a handsome 150-year-old Greek revival building on Telfair
Square, bills itself as ``John Wesley's American Parish.''
</P>
<P>
   Savannah's squares are the city's single most distinguished
physical feature and make this town a wonderful place in which to
walk. Oglethorpe himself came up with a plan for these symmetrical
parks, each with public buildings on one side and houses on the
others.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the buildings have pillared entrances, fanlights over
the doors and wrought-iron trim. Some are fitted out with 18th- and
19th-century furnishings and are open as museums.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 21 squares with statues, fountains, trees
festooned with Spanish moss and glorious arrays of flowers in
spring. People stroll through the squares, lounge and read under
the shady trees, hold parties, and get married with passers-by
looking on.
</P>
<P>
   On the riverfront to the north of the old part of town, cotton
warehouses rise from the river's edge to the bluff above. Now they
house shops, bars and restaurants, and draw a convivial crowd,
especially on evenings and weekends. This area, known as Factors
Walk, is the site of an arts and crafts festival that takes place
on the first Saturday of each month.
</P>
<P>
   There are many charming inns and guesthouses in Savannah, among
them, the Ballastone, an 18-room bed and breakfast which is
centrally located on Oglethorpe Street next to the Juliette Gordon
Low house, where the founder of the Girl Scouts was raised. At one
time, the Ballastone (built by a merchant in 1838), was used by the
Girl Scouts for administrative offices but before that it was a
brothel, a boarding house and an apartment house for immigrant
workers.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the checkered story of this now lavishly and lovingly
decorated inn encapsulates the history of Savannah. It's had its
ups and downs, but plumped by tourist dollars generated by ``The
Book,'' Savannah now shines.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   The Ballastone Inn is owned by Miss Jean Hagens, a fifth cousin
of Jefferson Davis, who has schooled her staff in southern
hospitality. Nothing is too much trouble. Room rates start at $275
in spring, with breakfast and afternoon tea included. For more
information, call (800) 822-4553 or fax (912) 236-4626.
</P>
<P>
   At Mrs. Wilkes Boarding House, you can dine family-style on such
Southern staples as Brunswick stew, creamed corn, collard greens,
fried chicken, black-eyed peas and buttermilk biscuits. For a
different kind of dining experience, try the charming Gryphon Tea
Room, owned by the Savannah College of Art and Design and housed in
what was once a turn-of-the-century drug store. The menu includes
soups, sandwiches, salads, dessert and afternoon tea. The Olde Pink
House, so-called because of its startling exterior paint job, is a
Savannah landmark. It was built around 1771 and serves an elegant
dinner in its candlelit dining rooms. A ghost is said to be in
residence.
</P>
<P>
   For information about Savannah, call the Savannah Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau at (877)-Savannah, or go to www.savcvb.com on the
Internet.And while in Savannah, visit E. Shaver Booksellers
(912-234-7257) for antique maps, local cookbooks and fascinating
volumes about the history of Savannah and the South.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
