<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-MOLDS-LIFEBEAT-ART-800-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE CHOCOLATE MOLDS STILL INSPIRE COLLECTORS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Photos of
chocolate molds available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Ellen M. Plante writes about antiques for ``Country Living.''
 &HT;    
 By ELLEN M. PLANTE 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   ``We know of one collector who travels to Belgium, France and
Holland several times a year just to search for unique chocolate
molds,'' says Bob Wade, who with his wife, Barbara, owns Once Upon
a Time Antiques in Cold Spring, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon after the reunification of Germany,' he says, ``this
gentleman discovered a bakery that was selling its entire inventory
of prewar chocolate molds _ dozens of wonderful examples. That's
any collector's dream come true!''
</P>
<P>
   What today has become something of a collecting craze began
during the golden age of the corner candy shop _ 1880 to 1940 _
when the production of decorative chocolate molds was in full
swing. After the Second World War, however, the candy maker's craft
succumbed to the relative ease and lower expense of mass
production.
</P>
<P>
   These whimsical artifacts of yesterday's kitchen are collector's
delight. ``There's just such a wide variety out there,'' Wade says.
``People can collect for years and still find a design they haven't
seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers in Europe and the United States produced detailed
molds made of tin, pewter and copper. The stamped-metal molds of
bunnies, sheep, turkeys, dogs, cats, hearts, eggs, Santas and other
motifs were intended both for commercial bakeries and individual
homes.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1908 book, ``Household Discoveries,'' author Sidney Morse
devoted an entire chapter to making sweets: ``Candy making should
be taught and acquired as one of the most useful of womanly
accomplishments,'' he wrote, adding, ``each household should have
on hand a small stock of fancy molds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has been collecting chocolate molds for about 30
years,'' says antiques dealer Jean Van Kuren, of Ruth's Antiques in
Clarence Center, N.Y., ``and we must have a few hundred examples
throughout the house. What I love most about them is that they are
so very detailed.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Van Kuren, who also sells molds at antiques shows
around the country, detailing is one of the major factors affecting
the value of a piece.
</P>
<P>
   Small molds with limited detail, for example, can still be found
between $10 and $25, while more desirable pieces featuring
extremely fine blades of grass, strands of hair, creases in
clothing or other decorative elements sell for up to $100 or more.
Pieces made by the German firm Anton Reiche, of Dresden, are
particularly intricate, Van Kuren says.
</P>
<P>
   Size is another important factor that can affect the value of a
chocolate mold. ``Value typically increases as molds get larger,''
says Wade. ``A manufacturer may have produced a good number of
6-inch molds but probably only turned out a handful of molds that
were 3 feet tall.''
</P>
<P>
   The smallest molds that collectors will encounter stand 3 to 5
inches tall, and the most common examples range from 6 to 12 inches
in height. Larger molds range from 15 to 20 inches in height while
the rarest, tallest examples top off at 2 to 3 feet. Molds of this
size, Wade reports, have sold for as much as $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest in these pieces has really increased in recent
years,'' Barbara Wade points out. ``Only 20 years ago, you could
pick them up for a song, but that's no longer the case. Today these
pieces are in high demand and the prices reflect that trend.''
</P>
<P>
   The best places to search for vintage chocolate molds include
antiques shops (especially those specializing in kitchenware),
holiday collectibles fairs and flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   When inspecting a stamped-tin mold, look closely to see if it
has all its companion parts _ including clamps, straps and clips.
Reproductions do exist, says Wade, but they generally stand out
when compared to authentic pieces: Vintage examples tend to be made
of heavy-gauge tin, display greater attention to detail and have
small nicks and dents consistent with repeated use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beginning collectors should get a feel for the quality of the
workmanship that went into making the original pieces,'' Wade
advises.
</P>
<P>
   In the home, period chocolate molds make an eye-catching display
on shelves, sideboards and mantels, but beauty and whimsy alone
have yet to surpass function. As it turns out, many candy-mold
collectors are cooking and kitchenware enthusiasts to begin with,
and they use their vintage molds to create old-fashioned
confections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our family uses them to make chocolate figures to give as
gifts and display in our home for festive occasions,'' says Jean
Van Kuren. ``It's become a special tradition for us because it also
gives us a connection with the past.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
