<SLUG> BC-EPHRON-NOVEL-Q&AMP;A-LIFEBEAT-ART-800-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELIA EPHRON DISCUSSES LIFE, DIVORCE AND HER LATEST NOVEL
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Delia Ephron is available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Joan Smith is a senior editor of ``Redbook.''
 &HT;    
 By JOAN SMITH 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Delia Ephron was in East Hampton, N.Y., reading the police log
in the local paper. There was a geranium thief on the loose, but
the best item was about a woman complaining that someone had pulled
in and out of her driveway three times in 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so divine,'' says Ephron, who like everyone in New York
City is both dazzled and bemused by the relative simplicity of life
outside the five boroughs. ``I knew this was the beginning of a
book for me _ about a woman living in a small town where there is
no real crime and then a real crime happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But if she was going to write a murder mystery _ and because
she's Delia Ephron, it would be a funny murder mystery. She wanted
``something really meaty, that affects all women, at its heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ephron, who helped write some of sister Nora Ephron's films
(their most recent collaboration was ``Hanging Up,'' starring Meg
Ryan and based on Delia's first novel), loves children and has
written seven books for and about them. So she decided that the
heart of her new novel, ``Big City Eyes,'' would be a maternal
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Davis leaves Manhattan and moves to a small town on Long
Island because she is worried about her 15-year-old son, Sam: He
seems withdrawn and friendless, she thinks he's sneaking out to
Manhattan nightclubs, and she's found a steak knife in his
underwear drawer.
</P>
<P>
   But the knife, she understands, is a defensive weapon, much like
the missiles he drew in a picture of himself when he was 6. Sam,
she concludes, still feels unsafe, nine years after his parents'
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Big City Eyes'' is also a romance with a twist. Lily has
to decide whether she has a right to be with the man of her dreams
(who wants to leave his wife to be with her) if it means that, like
Sam, her lover's children will have to live with the pain of their
family's dissolution.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why did you decide to write about the impact of divorce on
children?
</P>
<P>
   A. I really identify with children and their vulnerability. I
helped raise two stepchildren and experienced their grief, and I
interviewed a lot of single mothers and children for my book
``Funny Sauce.'' When parents get divorced, children get their
hearts broken.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does this mean parents should stay together for the sake of
their children?
</P>
<P>
   A. The weird thing is that divorce, like skirts and dresses,
goes in and out of fashion. When I divorced my first husband, the
women's movement was in full flower and everyone was doing it.
Which made it a lot easier, because divorce is the hardest thing
you can do. It's like burning the ground beneath your feet.
</P>
<P>
   But if you need to get divorced, you need to get divorced. And
when you need something that badly, you tend to delude yourself
into believing that there's not going to be a cost. But the cost is
what happens to your kids.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about the mother in ``Hanging Up,'' who abandons her
kids completely?
</P>
<P>
   A. To me that's unforgivable. Lily leaves her husband, but she
is a very conscientious mother. But another thing that interests me
is how motherhood seems to conflict with sexual passion. Raising
children is not the most romantic situation, and everyone knows how
hard it is to switch gears and get romantic.
</P>
<P>
   Q. And isn't it the first time since adolescence that you find
yourself hiding your sexuality from people you love?
</P>
<P>
   A. Exactly. You simply don't want to walk around your house
feeling and acting sexual. I remember my mother going to a
department store and getting one of those free makeovers. She came
home looking rather glamorous and asked, ``How do I look?'' And I
said, ``You look awful.'' She looked great actually, but I was a
teen-ager and she didn't look like my mom.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Was it hard being a stepmother?
</P>
<P>
   A. Very. The children were 4 and 6, and I wanted to be their
mother, which was not appropriate. I couldn't have children of my
own, which made it more painful, and I moved too fast for them. But
I was completely devoted and now we all love each other and it
works great.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, being a stepmom really prepares you for being a
screenwriter, because if you want the child to change in any way
you can never just make them do it. You have to lobby the real
parents. And when you're a screenwriter and you want something for
the movie, you have to lobby the director. So it was the best
training I ever had.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
