<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CAMPAIGN FINANCE RULES NECESSARY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Reform'' is a positive _ and therefore
subjective _ word that is overused. It implies an improvement in
something, but what is viewed as ``reform'' by one person may be
considered a pox on society by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   This distinction particularly holds true when people discuss
``reform'' of the political system. Ask a trial lawyer, for
example, if the ``tort reform'' movement is misnamed.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this problem by an e-mail message commenting
on a recent column, which discussed George W. Bush's and Al Gore's
conversions _ maybe _ to the cause of campaign finance ``reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader doubted that limiting campaign contributions would
improve the system because, he reasoned, the less money candidates
have to spend, the less voters would learn about them.
</P>
<P>
   And, he suggested, people with ``great power and influence''
would adjust their tactics and ``try to maintain influence under
any system that can be devised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you refer me to anything that will go beyond chanting
`reform, reform' and help me understand where that reform might
take us?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure where any ``reform'' will eventually lead because
the reader is correct. People wanting a political edge will seek a
new way to circumvent restrictions. But tight, new campaign finance
rules with stiff sanctions against violators are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   I have mixed feelings about one alternative _ public financing
of political races. Although it is an option for presidential
candidates, I suspect that most people strongly oppose using tax
dollars to finance state and local campaigns in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign contributions must be completely and timely reported,
and limits should be set on both direct contributions to candidates
and on indirect donations through political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, with Bush's support, took an important step
last year with a new law requiring most state candidates to file
finance reports electronically.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers, in the interest of protecting privacy on the
Internet, excluded addresses of donors from the electronic
postings. That is a mistake that the Legislature should correct,
because addresses are essential information. People who value their
privacy that much shouldn't give to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Texas law sets no limits on contributions in state races, except
for judicial offices. Federal law limits contributions in federal
races to $1,000 per election for individuals and $5,000 per
election for political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   In a congressional race, there can be as many as three elections
per cycle _ a party primary, a runoff and the general election.
That means a person can give a candidate as much as $3,000 _ $1,000
for each election _ and a PAC can give as much as $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be unreasonable to raise the federal limit on
individual donations to $5,000 per election. Perhaps the PAC limit
also could be raised, but not by much. Limits of some kind,
meanwhile, also should be set on contributions to candidates for
all state and local offices.
</P>
<P>
   Strict limits or outright bans also should be imposed on ``soft
money'' contributions to political parties, which bypass the
existing federal donation limits and are used to buy ads benefiting
candidates. Bush has proposed banning soft money from labor unions
and businesses, but his plan has a big loophole _ he would allow
soft money contributions from wealthy individuals. They also should
be banned or limited.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of change argue that restrictions on
contributions to political candidates and parties are an
unconstitutional infringement on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But a majority of the U.S. Supreme Court refuted that argument
two months ago when it once again upheld state limits on campaign
contributions as a means of fighting real or perceived political
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave the perception of impropriety unanswered, and the
cynical assumption that large donors call the tune could jeopardize
the willingness of voters to take part in democratic governance,''
the court majority wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It also noted, ``There is little reason to doubt that sometimes
large contributions will work actual corruption of our political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, big money in politics often talks, and that's
why it must be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
