<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SWEATSHIRT-CAPITAL-$A     03-27 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATSHIRT-CAPITAL-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN THEIR HOME TOWN, ECONOMIC CHANGE MEANS HARD TIMES
 &HT;    850&AMP;add. Moving in (a) national and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, April 2.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Slide in a buck and punch 24-12 on the
Hyperbeam Laserdisc juke box in the bar at the Best Western motel.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen pops on, singing the sad truth:
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreman says these jobs are going, boys, and they ain't
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``To your home town.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Willie Martin's home town. He was born and reared in
this blue-collar community of textile mills and furniture factories
in the shadow of the Blue Ridge Mountains. Played defensive end on
the high school football team. Hired on at the plant that made Sara
Lee brand clothing. Never wanted to live anywhere other than this
hilly settlement of 16,000 people in modest brick houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is home,'' he proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is 36 now. When he was growing up, Martinsville boasted
of being the ``Sweatshirt Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the Sara Lee plant closed about seven years ago, he soon
got a job at Tultex Corp. making sweatshirts and sweat pants and
T-shirts and shorts for Sears, Nike, Reebok and other brands as
well as for Tultex's own Discus Athletic and Track Gear lines. He
worked the night shift, 7 p.m. to 7 a.m., four nights one week,
three nights the next. He liked the hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a morning person,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   Tultex paid about as well as any other employer in the region _
$11 to $12 an hour for the average worker.
</P>
<P>
   Then, three weeks before Christmas, Tultex declared bankruptcy.
Willie Martin was among 1,100 workers terminated without warning.
No severance check. No holiday bonus. No more company insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just dumped us out like we were nothing,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, there were no jobs awaiting laid-off workers. The
Sara Lee closing had been a harbinger. DuPont moved out of
Martinsville in 1998. Pluma closed its clothing plants here last
fall. Ashmore Industries shut down shortly thereafter. Then Hampton
Industries closed its sewing plant for sleepwear.
</P>
<P>
   In two years, the area lost about 3,400 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Now nearly one out of every five adults in Martinsville is
looking for work. The 18.4 percent unemployment rate could even go
higher when the last Tultex workers, now cleaning out the plants
and shipping out the final products, are let go.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell folks hereabouts about America's boom times. They
smile bitterly when asked about the Federal Reserve Board raising
interest rates to slow a surging economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Greenspan ought to come down and visit us for a while,''
said Mary Minter, a 54-year-old grandmother who is looking for a
new job after being laid off at Tultex.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   In the new Southern economy that stretches from America Online
Inc.'s headquarters in Northern Virginia to Dell Computer Corp.'s
headquarters outside Austin, it's easy to overlook the old Southern
economy in places like Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the textile industry, located largely in Dixie, has
lost more than 100,000 jobs, leaving it with about 550,000. In the
apparel industry, the situation is worse, with nearly 300,000 jobs
lost in the same seven-year period, leaving fewer than 700,000 at
work making clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In Martinsville, folks blame the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA), which took effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   They believe that their jobs went to Mexico, where manufacturers
pay less for labor. Now President Clinton has asked Congress to
give China the same permanent trade benefits granted most other
nations. If that happens, workers here warn, the remaining textile
and apparel jobs are headed to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is more complicated than that, explained Gary
Shoesmith, an economist at Wake Forest University in Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Automation has replaced about as many textile workers as foreign
trade has, he said. U.S. textile shipments have actually increased
slightly since NAFTA opened the continent's borders. Wages have
increased for the Southern textile workers in new high-tech mills.
</P>
<P>
   In the less automated apparel industry, dependent on people who
cut and sew, more jobs are headed to countries where labor costs
are lower, he predicted. But he says it would have happened with or
without NAFTA or permanent trade privileges for China.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, the textile and apparel industries will be wide open
worldwide, said Shoesmith. Free trade will benefit the overall
Southern economy, he said. Already, yarn spun in automated Carolina
mills is being used to make clothing in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   While Dixie's textile and apparel industries have historically
paid relatively low wages, Shoesmith said, workers of the future
will be paid according to what they know and what they're willing
to do. They'll have to retrain several times over a lifetime of
work and be more mobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the 50-year-old man who walks out of the textile mill for
the last time, where does he go?'' asked Shoesmith. ``If he is
resistant to retraining, he may end up on the graveyard shift at
the 7-Eleven. Those are the sad stories.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Mary Minter lives one of those sad stories.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 years at Tultex, she was late only twice. Both times, she
was delayed when deer smashed into her pickup truck while she was
driving to work. Two of her four sons, as well as a brother, also
lost their jobs when Tultex abruptly shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine had worked there for 40 years. She had gone
to Tultex straight out of high school and had a year and a half
till she could retire. They told her that she had 20 minutes to
gather up her things and get out of the building,'' Minter
recalled. ``It was like a slap in the face to people who had worked
so hard for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that she's squeezing a living from an unemployment check of
about $200 a week, the grandchildren ``want to know why Nanny can't
buy'' any more Matchbox cars or Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, John, is disabled. He had a heart attack one
Christmas Eve in the parking lot of K-Mart and has since had
open-heart surgery and several operations on his back. They're
worried about how to pay for the pills that regulate John's
heartbeat. Their health insurance had been provided by Tultex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting more desperate as the weeks go by,'' said Mary.
She has put in applications at businesses all over the area, but so
have hundreds of other job seekers.
</P>
<P>
   She's looking forward to the NASCAR season opening at the
Martinsville Race Track, where she can earn some money working in
the concession stand on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The signs marking Martinsville's city limits now feature a
checkered flag motif rather than sweatshirt production. The city
council has offered to give away land to companies that will invest
in the community and create new jobs. So far, there are few takers.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Bassinger is worried.
</P>
<P>
   She worked in the cutting room at Tultex for nearly 13 years
until, at the age of 36, she lost her job ``with no warning or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bassinger tells it, for decades the town was run by a few
families who owned and operated textile mills or furniture
factories. They resisted other industries coming in because they
wanted to keep wages low. Eventually, the local textile owners sold
out to national corporations. Beset by foreign competition, the
corporations pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   But Bassinger doesn't want to pull out. She grew up in
Martinsville. Her parents still live here. Her three teenage
children are immersed in their high school. Her husband has a job
at a tire dealership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have roots,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's putting in job applications at furniture factories in
North Carolina. Sitting in the sunny back yard of her small brick
house, Bassinger said she's willing to drive an hour each way if
she can find a job. She doesn't want to move away from
Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   This is her home town.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
