<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CABINET RESHUFFLE, PRIME MINISTER BRINGS IN RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After weeks of sinking ratings in the polls, Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin announced a shake-up in his Cabinet Monday,
including the appointment of one of his main rivals, former Prime
Minister Laurent Fabius, as finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin has faced a torrent of criticism for lackluster
performance on several fronts, including the failure of his
administration's school and tax reforms. Cartoonists have depicted
him as a man who has run out of steam halfway through his five-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to counter that image, Jospin added two of France's
most dynamic left-wing politicians, Fabius and Jack Lang, a former
culture minister, to his administration. Lang will take over the
troubled education ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as Jospin's administration is preparing for the
local elections next year and the presidential elections of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius' appointment was generally praised by economists, who do
not expect him to make any drastic changes to the overall direction
of the finance ministry. Under Jospin, the ministry has endorsed
market-friendly policies and overseen the privatization of many
state assets.
</P>
<P>
   But political analysts had mixed assessments. Some regarded the
appointment of Fabius, 53, as a move that could lead to an internal
power struggle, while others saw it as an effort to pull the party
together.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius, a protege of the late President Francois Mitterrand and
his prime minister from 1984-86, has had a long, bitter rivalry
with Jospin. In recent years his own political career stalled when
he was accused of a role in allowing unscreened blood to be given
to hemophiliacs at the national transfusion center in the
mid-1980s, causing some of them to contract AIDS. He was acquitted
of criminal negligence and manslaughter charges last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has recently criticized the Jospin administration for not
cutting taxes more sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin said that the changes, the first big Cabinet reshuffle
since he formed a coalition joining his Socialists with Communists
and Greens in 1997, would reinforce his government's ``capacity to
act.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, he said, ``will continue its reform policies
inspired by left-wing values in the service of the country and with
the same main goal _ _ growth and jobs for more justice.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During most of Jospin's two and a half years in office he has
enjoyed almost unprecedented popularity for a prime minister, at
times surpassing the ratings of the Gaullist President Jacque
Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since Jospin was hit in the back of the head by a stone
thrown by Palestinian protesters last month, he has been in
trouble. First, polls indicated that the French people disapproved
of his trip to the Middle East and believed that he should not have
meddled in foreign policy, which is usually Chirac's domain.
</P>
<P>
   Then his domestic problems began to grow. He so mishandled a
$7.5 billion surplus that it began to hang around his neck like a
dead albatross. Weeks went by as the French waited for him to
explain how the money would be used.
</P>
<P>
   And then two of his administration's major efforts, school and
tax reforms, foundered as teachers and tax inspectors took to the
streets in protest, eventually forcing the plans to be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Jospin tried to get his political house back in
order. Fabius will replace Christian Sautter, who was appointed
when the far more dynamic Dominique Strauss-Kahn resigned over
corruption allegations. Lang is to replace Claude Allegre, a
long-time friend of Jospin's whose efforts to streamline the school
system ran into opposition from both teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin also announced changes in two other major posts.
Catherine Tasca replaced Culture Minister Catherine Trautmann, who
had been expected to leave after bungling a plan to reform
advertising on public television.
</P>
<P>
   A former finance minister, Michel Sapin, replaced Emile
Zuccarelli, the civil service minister, who had failed to persuade
the vast bureaucracy to accept Jospin's flagship policy of cutting
the work week to 35 hours from 39 hours in an effort to create more
jobs and cut unemployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
