<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CENSUS-PRIVACY-HNS &LR;      03-27 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CENSUS RAISES PRIVACY COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SHERRY SYLVESTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ An unsuccessful candidate for Congress has filed a
lawsuit saying some of the questions on the 2000 Census are an
invasion of privacy. And the radio airwaves have been buzzing with
complaints that the government is prying into their lives by asking
too many questions.
</P>
<P>
   The head count, held every 10 years, often raises questions of
privacy. But this year, with the federal government and local
jurisdictions across the country urging people to fill out the
forms, the count is stirring questions and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Messer, the fiery talk show host at radio station KTSA in
San Antonio, said callers have been burning up the phone lines to
his station complaining that the census is invading their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People find the questions invasive and insulting,'' Messer
said. ``Bathrooms? Income? Isn't the census supposed to count
heads?''
</P>
<P>
   Messer said the complaints particularly focus on the long form,
which includes 53 questions.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ashwood, operations manager and director of talk
programming at radio station WOAI in San Antonio, said national
talk shows, including Rush Limbaugh and Lionel, have received high
numbers of calls on the census forms.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brewer, a failed Republican congressional candidate, filed
a lawsuit in federal court Thursday in Houston against the U.S.
Census Bureau, charging the U.S. Commerce Department and the Census
Bureau with invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   At his weekly briefing last Tuesday, Census Bureau Director
Kenneth Prewitt called the reaction against the long census form
part of the country's ``civic disengagement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we live in a time when there is a growing
mistrust of government,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt insists the public should be angry with its
congressional representatives, not the Census Bureau, because all
the long form questions were required by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez, D-Texas, said the information from the
census is crucial to lawmakers. ``Government is only going to be as
responsive as it is knowledgeable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hofeller, redistricting director for the Republican National
Committee, said both Democrats and Republicans are pushing for an
accurate count, since census figures are used in congressional
redistricting and in apportioning federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Hofeller said Republicans are not behind the Brewer lawsuit,
which he predicted would go nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Ellis Smith, editor of the Privacy Journal and a
longtime privacy advocate, said the public is right to object to
many of the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long form is actually a marketing survey for American
businesses,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that while Congress asks for some questions to be
included on the census forms, businesses have a greater influence.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll released March 13 found that half of those
surveyed did not believe the Census Bureau would prohibit other
government agencies from using census information and 60 percent
said they believe the Census Bureau could not protect the data even
if it tried.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, said the Census Bureau has an impressive record
in guarding its data on individuals. Even recent charges that
Census Bureau data may have been used to identify Japanese-American
neighborhoods in World War II do not suggest individual household
records were handed over to the military.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-27 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLAY THE JOB GAME WELL AND WIN THE CAREER TOURNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you have not gotten excited about anything at
work in the past month, there is something seriously wrong with
your office. Where is your spirit? Where is your sense of
accomplishment? Where is your NCAA basketball pool?
</P>
<P>
   The 63 games that make up the men's college basketball
championship tournament are perfect for a little wagering (which
is, of course, totally illegal and completely appalling, especially
if you picked Stanford to win the championship). Research and
street smarts are the keys to winning, but never underestimate the
importance of freak accidents and blind luck.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a lot like your career, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Here are some lessons from March Madness that you can apply to
career insanity:
</P>
<P>
   _ There are many definitions of success.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges like Jackson State and Winthrop and Iona know they
can't really compete for the championship, but they are still proud
to be a part of the tournament. Even though there is only one
official winner, just participating is a victory for them.
</P>
<P>
   One pitfall for workers is the feeling that they have to be the
champion or else they are failing. Not everyone wants to be the
chief executive, certainly, but often there is this internal
pressure to be the top producer or get the stock options or join a
Big Six company.
</P>
<P>
   Those are admirable goals, as long as they are yours. The
problem is that people don't stop often enough to consider whether
the ambitions they had 10 years ago are still appropriate today.
When you are young, landing a job with a prestigious company sounds
like the most impressive career path, but you are usually too naive
to appreciate the sacrifices involved to make it to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For every star at a prestigious company, there are dozens of
benchwarmers, people whose talent gets lost in the shuffle. It's
easy to become a faceless cog when there are dozens of people who
do your job just as well as you do.
</P>
<P>
   It also is easy for your priorities to change, without you even
realizing what is going on. You start a family or develop
wanderlust or gradually stop pushing yourself as hard as you used
to.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have the desire, you have to take a hard look at
whether you are talented enough to be on top. You can work hard to
build your skills, but an awful lot of people just don't have the
inherent talent necessary to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Players from Jackson State and Winthrop and Iona probably didn't
leave the tournament disappointed; they landed a spot with the big
organization, but realized they would never make it beyond the rank
and file. They met their goals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, players from Indiana probably were
disappointed. Their school has a rich history, even though things
have been relatively shaky for several years. They have upper
management ambitions and rank-and-filer talent. That is a mixture
for frustration.
</P>
<P>
   And many people's definition of success doesn't involve the big
organization at all. An obvious example from college basketball is
that women's teams don't compete with the men. They put their
talents to better use by creating a tournament of their own, which
is smaller, but still successful.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate mentality doesn't suit a lot of workers from
either sex, but there are all sorts of jobs in small businesses, or
you can create a corporation of your own. If you are still in a
large corporation and it hasn't dawned on you that you are not a
good fit, though, you will be as frustrated as a women's team in
the men's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reputation can help you get in.
</P>
<P>
   A mediocre team from a well-respected conference like the Big
Ten will make it into the tournament a lot more often than a
mediocre team from a weak conference.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderfully talented people can make it to the top no matter
where they went to school, or whether they went to school at all.
But don't underestimate the importance of snob appeal. For young
people in particular, a degree from a prestigious university or an
internship with a top-ranked company can open a lot of doors.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't go to a big-name university, consider whether it
is worth your time to try for a fellowship or master's degree from
a more prestigious place. A lot of universities are offering
programs on line, so you might not have to leave work or choose a
nearby institution.
</P>
<P>
   The snob appeal degree goes along with the most basic rule of
career success: If you can make yourself stand out from the masses
in a favorable way, do it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to make the matchups work in your favor.
</P>
<P>
   Some basketball teams do best when the game is played at
breakneck speed, but others like to slow it down. Some play a zone
defense, others man-to-man. There is no ``right'' strategy; it
depends on the talent you have.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are great at everything, but you should be talented
at certain aspects of your job. Focus on getting the most out of
those skills. Could you help the company more if you restructured
your job? Is there another place that would be a better fit for
you? Being a great man-to-man defender doesn't do you a lot of good
if your team plays a zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes life is brutally unfair.
</P>
<P>
   The best team doesn't always win. A few good teams don't get
invited to the tournament, and some great teams can't be at their
best because a key player is injured.
</P>
<P>
   Your career won't always be fair, either. You will have a boss
who doesn't appreciate you or an inept colleague who gets promoted
ahead of you or a company that crumbles around you.
</P>
<P>
   But referees also will make mistakes in your favor, and good
colleagues will support you more than you probably deserve. The
breaks have a way of evening out, as long as you play the game
well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
