<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-27 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CONVICTS AMONG US 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's not just seeing new people and new lands
that is the reward of overseas travel, but also what you sometimes
discover about your own country.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with five weeks touring New Zealand and Australia
recently. Sights of nature compelling in their unique attraction,
people viewed in their own national setting and exposure to the
cultures specific to these countries were ample reward for the time
and money spent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the good travel engenders, there is hubris that
might go with it: the presumption of observations based on slight
experience.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealanders and Australians, though different from each other
in ways immediately apparent, are similarly friendly to visitors,
as they are with their countrymen. They have a good humor and
openness with each other that long ago disappeared from every day
life in America.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the niceness, they are helpful in everyday discourse,
displaying courtesies long neglected in American life. Ask an
employee of the Sydney monorail how to cope with the ticketing and
for help to get where you want to go, and you get a full-blown and
kindly explanation that solves your problem and leaves you feeling
good.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly striking is the cleanliness of the big cities, with
populations in the millions, which manage nevertheless to be tidy.
A civic morale is in play in both countries that we Americans
should envy. More than that, we should work to emulate it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a secret to Americans that they are much liked in both
New Zealand and Australia, in part because the United States in
World War II shielded them from Japanese invasion while their
fighting forces were engaged in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Australians (as do New Zealanders) take their wars seriously.
Each city, each town, each village has a memorial to the war dead,
put in place for the bitter sacrifices of their young men in World
War I at Gallipoli and augmented to note their participation in
subsequent wars.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps just as binding as America's wartime help was America's
history. Each place we visited in Australia, we were made aware by
our lecturers and guides of the country's short history.
</P>
<P>
   Their beginning as a European settlement came in 1788, with
arrival of the First Fleet, which plays the role in Australian
history and national mythology that the Mayflower does in ours. To
have an ancestor on the ships that arrived then is to possess a
superior pedigree. There is special poignancy in the fact that
unlike those who sailed on the Mayflower, those in the First Fleet
were convicts expelled by Britain to exile on the other side of the
world and their keepers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those ancestors deemed criminals in their own time are
proudly remembered by their progeny as the people who pioneered
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Australians connect to Americans because they believe, as a
national credo, that if it hadn't been for that dust-up in 1776,
many of them would be living in the United States. Time and again
we visitors were reminded that it was only because the American
Revolution stopped Britain from exporting convicts to its American
Colonies that the First Fleet sailed 12 years later for that land
so far away.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans listened to this version politely and with some
amusement for hardly anyone of the 30-odd on the tour recollected
the role that British convicts were supposed to have played in our
country's early settlement.
</P>
<P>
   It was pointed out to our lecturers and instructors that if the
export of convicts to America had occurred, it escaped Thomas
Jefferson as a problem about which to complain in our proudest
national document. In the Declaration of Independence, which is a
catalog of grievances against the depredations of the British king,
not a word about convicts appears.
</P>
<P>
   However, historical documents show that the Australians knew
what they were talking about. Although none in our group recalled
the mention of this salient fact in our early schooling,
one-quarter of the early British emigrants in America were
convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Americans resemble their Australian cousins in that they
thoroughly absorbed these convicts into the national culture,
although they formed a lesser part of the whole than they did in
Australia. Unlike the Australians, we appear to fail to recollect
what brought them here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Australians recollect their forebears fondly, reciting the
crimes for which they were transported. Americans are taught that
settlers came for religious and political freedom or the chance to
make a living. The convicts among our early settlers are widely
ignored, as if it were something to be embarrassed about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
