<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GARBAGE IN AMERICA: MORE RECYCLING AND MORE WASTING
 &HT;    With GARBAGE-DATA.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans are recycling trash and garbage like
never before _ but the tonnage of discarded waste has also started
to grow after several years of decline.
</P>
<P>
   Increased economic activity, which enabled Americans to buy and
use more products and materials, appears to have been largely
responsible for the generation of 217 million tons of municipal
solid waste in 1997, the most recent year for which statistics are
available.
</P>
<P>
   That's the largest amount since the data have been collected,
according to the most recent update of the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency's continuing report, ``Characterization of
Municipal Solid Waste in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   From this record garbage pile, roughly 61 million tons of trash
found its way to recycling centers in 1997, also the largest
quantity in history.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to statistics posted on the Internet by
EPA, is that 156.3 million tons of municipal solid waste went to
the country's landfills and incinerators in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While significantly lower than the 172 million tons discarded in
1990, the 1997 total represented an increase of 4.4 million tons
from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by state and federal mandates, recycling and composting
of municipal solid waste have increased dramatically over the past
decade. There were more than 9,000 curbside recycling programs in
America in 1997, and 12,000 drop-off centers for recyclables.
</P>
<P>
   Waste News, a solid waste industry publication, reported
recently that in little over a decade, California cities and towns
have recycled enough waste to fill a line of garbage trucks that
would encircle the Earth four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA has established a target recycling goal of 35 percent by
the year 2005, while maintaining the per capita generation of solid
waste at 4.3 pounds per person per day,'' said consultants who
prepared the waste report. ``The nation appears to be on track to
meet that goal, but it will take continued commitment from
business, industry, government and the public to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But citing the 1997 upturn in the national tonnage of discarded
waste, two recycling advocacy groups said Monday the federal
government should invest more in recycling and stop ``subsidizing''
the use of virgin materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our present pattern of using resources is not sustainable,''
said the Athens, Ga., GrassRoots(cq) Recycling Network and the
Institute for Local Self-Reliance in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a period of increasing recycling rates and decreasing
wasting rates in the early 1990s, wasting is now increasing and
recycling gains have slowed,'' the groups said.
</P>
<P>
   In a jointly issued report titled ``Wasting and Recycling in the
United States, 2000,'' the two organizations said local governments
and taxpayers spend $43.5 billion a year ``collecting and disposing
of municipal discards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, disposing of municipal discards is an unfunded
mandate,'' the report declared.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA report projects that between 156 million and 163 million
tons of solid waste will have to be incinerated or sent to
landfills in 2005, depending on recycling trends.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
