<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-THEME-WEDDINGS-HNS &LR;      03-27 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-WEDDINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COUPLES TIE THE KNOT WITH EXTRAVAGANT TWISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICKI HADDOCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Why simply tie the knot when you can do it with
a twist?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question prompting a growing number of couples to
transform their weddings around tradition-defying themes. The trend
is flourishing in Northern California, where experts now say at
least one in every 20 weddings is a themed concoction _ be it a
Roman toga feast, a cowboy barbecue hoedown or a you-name-it.
</P>
<P>
   Among recent examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ When two diving enthusiasts took the plunge off the Monterey
Coast, guests who wanted to witness the underwater vows had to
likewise submerge themselves. The bride was radiant in an ivory wet
suit, now routinely offered as a wedding accessory by two
manufacturers of scuba gear.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Berkeley couple staged a masquerade Halloween wedding,
hosting guests who came disguised as gypsies, Civil War soldiers,
sultans and a ``friendly'' ax murderer. The bride and groom
contemplated but ultimately nixed the notions of trick-or-treat
stations and a bubbling caldron of witches' brew. Instead,
invitations evoked a classic All Hallow's Eve and noted ``elegant
please  &Cx1f; _ no gorilla costumes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A Mill Valley pair decided to let the good times roll with a
jazzy Mardi Gras wedding, where guests were showered with Carnival
beads and served hurricane cocktails with corn bread, Chilean sea
bass and collard greens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Renaissance romance was the theme for the nuptials of a Sonoma
bride whose green and gold period wedding gown was created by the
costumers at the American Conservatory Theater. Nearly all the 180
wedding guests likewise donned Renaissance garb to watch as the
groom serenaded them with his lute rendition of ``A Lover and His
Lass.'' The minister, dressed as the ``King of the Realm,''
officiated by touching the bowed couple with his outstretched
sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our friends said it'll be hard for them to plan their
weddings after ours, that we set the standard too high,'' said
Aaron Leventhal, who married Laura Ackerman in the Halloween
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think theme weddings can be a very good thing and a lot
more interesting because they're a little unpredictable,'' he
added. ``Ours allowed all of our creative friends to express
themselves and really be a part of the whole process of our
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledges, not everybody is sold on the idea of
nuptials as a participatory sport. Some relatives thought the theme
idea was nuts. And Miss Manners, he grants, ``would definitely not
approve of the ax murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my wedding. It was like a fairy tale come true,'' said
Marcia Gerbode of her Elizabethan spectacular in St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both drawn to the Renaissance because people were so
zestful and lusty then _ they really knew how to live,`` sais Frank
Gerbode, the groom. ``That was exactly the theme we wanted for our
life together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wedding planners sniff at the mention of elaborate theme
weddings, saying they trivialize the dignity of the marriage
ceremony. One San Francisco bridal consultant who requested
anonymity said they tend to be ``totally kitschy. If you want
Disneyland, go to Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   But professionals who disdain theme weddings increasingly do so
at their peril, said Gerard J. Monaghan, president of the
2,200-member Association of Bridal Consultants, based in New
Milford, Conn. He estimates that theme weddings have doubled in
popularity in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they turn up their nose, they're missing a lot of
business,'' he said. ``Couples today want to personalize things.
They don't want their mother's wedding. They don't want to have to
mold their special day to somebody else's ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tired of going to weddings where the only difference
is the color of the bridesmaid's dresses. Why not have a part
that's unique to them?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Monaghan has his limits.
</P>
<P>
   Example: the wedding where the bride wore a black gown and
exchanged vows in a cemetery at midnight. ``Without wanting to
characterize people,'' he said, ``that's strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's strong economy is contributing to the unusual weddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what influences the trend toward theme weddings is,
frankly, money,'' said Kristen McCormick of An Entertaining Company
in Santa Rosa. McCormick coordinated the Renaissance wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Extravagance certainly was a prerequisite for the couple who
tented the tennis courts of a Stanford University estate, rolled
out Persian carpets and welcomed sari-costumed guests for an
India-themed wedding. Not to mention the Roman wedding couple who
arrived via a horse-pulled chariot.
</P>
<P>
   But for daring couples on a small budget, there is always the
Internet. Various sites now offer do-it-yourself kits for couples
desiring an intergalactic, Egyptian, gangster or rock 'n' roll
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and Ackerman pulled off their Halloween masquerade
wedding without the use of consultants _ relying on friends who
joined brainstorming sessions and even helped make masks for
favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may get to return the favor soon,'' Leventhal said. ``Two
of our friends are thinking of doing a Roaring '20s or Gay '90s
theme for their wedding. They are now inspired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1436EST &QL; 
