<SLUG> BC-TRV-LODGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME IN THE FOREST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Sidebar to Sequoias main story) 
(Eds: Lodge photo to move March 27) 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
Photo by Eric Noland/Los Angeles Daily News 
Captain: The new Wuksachi Lodge complex in Sequoia National Park is
constructed of cedar and blends well with its surroundings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEQUOIA NATIONAL PARK _ When the rustic cabins at Sequoia's
Giant Forest Village were removed over the last few years, the park
service heard a few scattered expressions of nostalgic regret. But
the overriding purpose of the project _ protecting the groves of
ancient sequoias _ was widely embraced, according to national park
spokeswoman Kris Fister.
</P>
<P>
   And when longtime visitors find their way to the new Wuksachi
Lodge, located a respectful distance from the sequoia zone, they
probably won't be surprised to learn that the accommodations
benefit from the sins of the fathers. Constructed by the park
concessionaire, Delaware North Parks Services, the lodge design
reflects obvious respect for its setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuksachi is set well back from the Generals Highway as the
road winds west toward Cedar Grove and adjoining Kings Canyon
National Park. If you don't want to see the buildings, you don't
have to.
</P>
<P>
   The lodging units are divided among three structures that are a
good distance from the main building. The complex is connected by
forest pathways that are unobtrusively lighted. (Important tip:
Pack a flashlight. On a January visit, I didn't, and regretted it
on a cloudy night while walking to dinner through a light dusting
of snow.)
</P>
<P>
   Even the parking lots are segregated from the rooms, hidden down
the slope of a slight hill. It means lugging bags over considerable
distances, but it was done so that guests could look out a window
and see trees, not a Wagoneer with an aluminum row boat tied to the
top.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are constructed of cedar, with river-stone skirts,
and thus blend in well with their surroundings. The rooms are spare
and dimly lit rather than luxurious, but somehow that feels
appropriate here. Be prepared to make special requests, though: My
room had a writing table, but it lacked a lamp ... and a chair.
(Rooms are priced at $75-$105 in winter, Sequoia's slack season.
Once June arrives, that range climbs to $110-$155.)
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are not equipped with TVs. The proprietors want people
to be able to open their windows in summer without being assaulted
by the disembodied voice of Regis Philbin. Unfortunately, on my
visit, the people in the next room had obviously gotten advance
word of this unthinkable deprivation. They packed a TV and VCR to
administer a nightly fix, the sound of which was thoughtfully
shared with me through the thin walls.
</P>
<P>
   More gentle forms of diversion can be found in the main lodge.
Board games and books are stocked just inside the front door, and
on chilly nights, a wood-burning stove throws off comforting
warmth. Unfortunately, there is adequate reading light at only a
few of the lounging chairs. One evening, a 50ish couple had jumped
two of them. He read a paperback, she worked at a laptop computer,
they took turns rocking their sleeping baby in the stroller at
their feet _ the 21st-century family.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuksachi dining room, meanwhile, will be embraced warmly by
everyone who choked down the slop that used to be served at the
Giant Forest Village cafeteria _ the only dining option in the area
in winter.
</P>
<P>
   The offerings here, reasonably priced from $10 to $20 (including
soup or salad), are hearty _ appropriate after a day of tramping
through the mountains _ while still reflecting some imagination:
chicken Pompeii ($14.50), prepared with provolone, mozzarella and
gorgonzola cheeses and a heavy marinara sauce; medallions of pork
tenderloin marsala ($15).
</P>
<P>
   In winter, you're forced to set your body clock on mountain time
_ they stop serving dinner at 8:30 p.m.! And in the morning,
patience will serve you well; service at breakfast was numbingly
slow during my visit.
</P>
<P>
   But the setting mitigates any annoyances. The vaulted ceiling
rises to perhaps 25 feet, held up by massive, rough-hewn timbers.
Picture windows overlook a forested slope in the foreground, the
snow-tipped peaks of the Great Western Divide in the distance. At
night, a continuous blaze is maintained in the tall, stone
fireplace. This is the poor man's Ahwahnee _ but with a much better
view.
</P>
<P>
   Winter came late to Sequoia this year, and came with a
vengeance. Snow is 70 inches deep in some tourist areas. This does
not mean guests have to stay huddled inside, though. The park
service conducts snowshoe tours of an area of the Giant Forest on
weekends. Snowshoes are provided to those who don't own them for a
nominal charge of $1.
</P>
<P>
   The walk is less than a mile, on relatively flat ground, and
takes about two hours, said Fister. ``It's more stopping and
talking than walking,'' she added. It's not recommended for kids
under age 10, and reservations are recommended: (559) 565-3782.
</P>
<P>
   Given the heavy snow layer, the snowshoe treks will probably be
offered through April, but with the thaw they'll be replaced by
ranger-led walks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
