<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-LEAVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR IS PRESSED TO TAKE PATERNITY LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's not as if Prime Minister Tony Blair doesn't have
enough on his mind, what with the peace process in Northern Ireland
stalled and his handpicked candidate in the upcoming London mayor's
race trailing badly in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But it all pales in comparison to the pressure Blair is feeling
at home as his wife, Cherie, pregnant with their fourth child,
approaches her May due date.
</P>
<P>
   Under government policy, Blair is, like any new dad, entitled to
take paternity leave, as much as 13 weeks off without pay. His wife
wants him to take at least some of it, and many in his Labor Party
say it is incumbent on the incumbent of 10 Downing St. to show that
what's good for the people is good for the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking leave would be an excellent signal to other men and
other employers that no job is so important that you can't afford
time off to spend with a newborn child,'' said Mary-Ann Stephenson,
director of the Fawcett Society, a group that lobbies for gender
equality in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair is, like his hard-charging lawyer wife, something of a
workaholic and doesn't exactly relish the idea of relinquishing the
reins of power that he worked his whole life to grasp, no matter
how many brownie points he can score with the public, especially
women voters.
</P>
<P>
   The British public isn't of one mind on the matter, anyway. For
someone who gets accused of making policy with one eye on the polls
and one finger testing the prevailing winds of public opinion,
Blair is in a pickle.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Conservatives and their cheerleaders in the
right-wing, anti-Blair press, led by the Daily Telegraph and Daily
Mail, are poised to pounce if Blair gives the slightest indication
he wants to become the New Age Dad of British politics.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Blair is keeping his options open. He acknowledges that
his wife wants him to take some time off, but as he put it, ``I
have got to make sure that the country is properly run, too. I have
got a country to run, and I think people would expect me to be
doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a European Summit in Lisbon to the ITN television
network, Blair said, ``I'm going to have to sit down and discuss it
with the family first. That's the right place to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics are gleefully suggesting part of the dilemma facing
Blair is that he and his spin doctors are terrified at the prospect
of leaving the day-to-day running of the country for any extended
period to John Prescott, the deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   While a competent administrator, Prescott has a habit of, as the
British say, making a bottle of things.
</P>
<P>
   Prescott is in charge of transportation, and a central plank of
the Labor Party is to encourage drivers to leave their cars at home
and use public transportation. Imagine the guffaws then when, after
announcing that policy at Parliament two years ago, Prescott left
Westminster in a chauffeur-driven Jaguar. He added to his legend
last year when he and his wife were chauffeured all of 300 yards
from their hotel to the hall where the Labor Party was holding its
annual conference.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said his hesitation has nothing to do with his confidence
in Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a lack of confidence in anyone. I just haven't made
up my mind,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Blair told the BBC he needs more time to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I want to take some time with the baby when he or
she comes, but I honestly don't know what to do. I will have to
find a third way through,'' said Blair, lightheartedly referring to
his vaunted ``Third Way'' philosophy of merging social spending and
pro-business policy, which left-wing diehards abhor and
right-wingers complain he stole from them.
</P>
<P>
   While in Lisbon, Blair may feel the urge to give a dope slap to
his Finnish counterpart, Paavo Lipponen, who hasn't made things any
easier for Blair. Having just returned from his second paternity
leave, Lipponen has become the poster boy for Europeans who want
men to put family first.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Blair spoke approvingly of Lipponen recently, saying, ``I,
for one, am promoting the widespread adoption of his fine
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the resolute Mrs. Blair, who uses her maiden
name, Cherie Booth, in her work as a lawyer, say her praise of the
Finnish prime minister means this is a done deal and that her
husband will have to take at least part of his allotted 13 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Female parliamentarians in the Labor Party, who once called
themselves ``Blair's Babes,'' say the imminent arrival of the new
Blair babe, who will be the first child born to a sitting prime
minister in some 150 years, will help them in their campaign to get
Blair to push for paid paternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders are appalled at that prospect, and Blair's
political enemies will make considerable hay if he betrays even the
slightest sympathy for it.
</P>
<P>
   As he ponders the next two months, Tony Blair may be forgiven
for asking why someone once dubbed all this ``the blessed event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
