   CZECH-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ Lincoln Center is paying tribute
to the Czech Republic by presenting what it is calling the Prague
Festival, the heart of which is a three-concert visit by the Czech
Philharmonic and Vladimir Ashkenazy, its chief conductor since
1997. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   TITO-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ ``La Clemenza di Tito,'' the
opera Mozart wrote for a coronation in Prague a few months before
he died, was long undervalued but now seems absolutely immediate.
Not only is it filled with great and glorious music _ strongly
presented in this New York City Opera production _ but it speaks to
concerns that are ours. Reviewed by Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-POET-FRANCE (Les Maquignons, France) _ With the publication
of his third novel, ``The Fly-Truffler,'' wider recognition has
suddenly come to Gustaf Sobin, a poet and novelist who left Boston
for France 40 years ago. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   BOHEMIAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Weird Like Us: My Bohemian
America,'' Ann Powers argues that bohemianism is not only alive and
well, it is thriving, and whatever inroads it makes into the
mainstream only provide evidence of its power and vibrancy.
Reviewed by Jenny Lyn Bader
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOODTIMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, A Moyers Report:
``Surviving the Good Times.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
