<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURGICAL-SUTURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUTURE COMPANY FACES NEW LAWSUITS OVER ALLEGED CONTAMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., N.J., Okla., Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The families of three people who died of
infections after routine operations have filed wrongful death
lawsuits against Ethicon Inc., the world's largest manufacturer of
surgical sutures.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuits, the families claimed their loved ones died
because surgeons unknowingly used sutures that allegedly were
contaminated with infectious bacteria during a processing accident
at an Ethicon factory in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints regarding the deaths of William Carpenter,
retired school counselor from San Francisco; Virginia McMillan, a
homemaker from San Jose; and Tom Schroeder, a cattle rancher from
Freedom, Okla., were contained in lawsuits filed last month in San
Francisco and Alameda County courts.
</P>
<P>
   The three new lawsuits were filed on behalf of 52 surgical
patients who said they had suffered grievous injuries because their
doctors unknowingly used contaminated sutures in operations.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, more than 100 patients in California
and 15 other states have sued Ethicon in connection with infections
that they blame on breakdowns in a new sterilizing system at an
Ethicon plant in San Angelo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Four fatalities have been blamed on the sutures in lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicon, a division of the Johnson &AMP; Johnson Co. that is based
in Somerville, N.J., has denied that its products made anyone ill.
Company spokeswoman Susan Odenthal said she was not aware of the
new lawsuits and had no comment on them.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the victims who have sued said they were alerted to the
contamination incident _ and, thus, to the alleged cause of their
maladies _ by stories on the sterilizing system breakdown that
appeared in the San Francisco Examiner last year.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration prodded
Ethicon into issuing a voluntary recall for 3.6 million of the
company's trademark Vicryl dissolving sutures.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of the sutures were not recovered,
according to the FDA. Meanwhile, surgical patients around the
country began blaming Ethicon sutures for fierce post-surgical
infections, many caused by staphylococcus and a rare bacteria
related to tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to Congress and in response to lawsuits, Ethicon has
acknowledged problems with the sterilizer unit, but contended that
all the sutures it sold were safe.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, the company has made confidential
settlements with 22 victims who blamed the sutures for their
infections, according to public records.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaints, the three patients who died all had
operations involving the dissolving Vicryl sutures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carpenter, 72, died of a staph infection after surgery, in
October 1995, for replacement of a heart valve.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schroeder, 75, had heart surgery at an Oklahoma City hospital
in 1994. Four days after the operation, the former rodeo cowboy's
chest burst open from a serious staph infection, medical records
show. He lived four more years, but was an invalid frequently
subject to infections that required urgent care, said his daughter,
Carlene Culver of Ashland, Kan. He died in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ McMillan, 48, had a heart valve replacement in June 1994. She
also suffered a serious infection and ultimately died, according to
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuits, the plaintiffs accuse the Ethicon Inc. of
seeking to conceal the risks posed by the sutures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While earlier lawsuits have focused solely on alleged
contamination of Ethicon's dissolving Vicryl sutures, the products
that were the subject of the September 1994 recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But a another lawsuit filed in Alameda County contended that
Ethicon also shipped contaminated sutures made of silk and a
synthetic, Prolene.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1994, the company voluntarily recalled 2,600
packages of Prolene and silk sutures, according to the lawsuit
filed by Sacramento lawyer Wendy York on behalf of eight California
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that those sutures, like the Vicryl ones
subject to the later recall, had been contaminated during
processing and caused the patients to suffer serious postoperative
infections.
</P>
<P>
   York said the foil packages containing the silk and Prolene
sutures had been improperly sealed, leading to fears that the
products were contaminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
