<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BARTERING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE TOWN USES ITS OWN SOCIAL CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KURIYAMA, Japan _ Like many Japanese, the residents of this
town, population 15,500, worry that the things that have long made
this orderly, polite society function are crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning in the newspapers, they see the face of the new
Japan: rising crime, corrupt police, increasing child abuse,
violent schools, and youth who are just plain rude.
</P>
<P>
   But the people of Kuriyama think they may have found a simple,
though radical, solution to the ills of modern Japan: printing
their own money.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of reinforcing community values, Kuriyama has embarked
on an experimental barter system where its residents ``sell'' their
services _ ironing, for example, or snow shoveling, or dog-walking,
or just talking to a lonely person. In return, they get a currency
called kurin, which they can then use to ``buy'' a service someone
else is offering.
</P>
<P>
   They aim to create a town in which people know and more
importantly, in which they take care of one another, says Masahiro
Hanada, 43, the official heading the program. ``With this project,
I wish to make Kuriyama a little like it was when I was young,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The program began in February on a two-month trial basis.
Municipal officials put an ad in the newspaper, hoping to draw 50
or 100 people. They wound up with more than 250 participants.
</P>
<P>
   Mieko Kadoya, 81, is one of them. Her husband has died, and none
of her three children live in town, so she gets lonely. She gave
kurin to Saburo Okada, 39, to come to talk to her. Okada in turn,
used his kurin to learn a software program from Naomi Mizuguchi,
24.
</P>
<P>
   Mizuguchi used the kurin she got to learn to make traditional
Japanese pickles from Setsuko Hanada, 66, who speeds up the
process, which usually takes days, by using a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Like many older Japanese, Hanada the young have lost their
respect for the elderly, and hopes the kurin can bring the
generations together. ``We older people have knowledge to offer,
and the younger people have energy,'' said Hanada, who has used her
kurin to pay someone to shovel her walk.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to help out Japan's aging population was the main
engine driving Kuriyama's decision to try the barter experiment.
The town is the face of what Japan will be in a few years: one in
four people are over 65, a proportion the entire country is
expected to reach by 2025. That'll put a strain on Japan's pension
and health care systems, and deprive it of a work force large
enough to keep the economy growing.
</P>
<P>
   Towns in other countries, including the United States, have
embarked on variations of a barter system, but most, like the Hours
system developed in Ithaca, N.Y., are more designed to defend local
retailers against national chain stores.
</P>
<P>
   No other project has been designed to deal with an aging
population, an issue many developed countries are facing as birth
rates decline. Kuriyama hopes it can serve as a model not just for
other Japanese towns, but for other countries as well.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the experiment is an admission of just how much
community and family ties _ things on which Japan has long prided
itself _ are breaking down. Many young Japanese seek an
increasingly individualistic lifestyle, which means fewer of them
live with parents or grandparents. Japan's growing numbers of
elderly are increasingly left to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Town leaders say that so far the trial is a success in providing
basic services to the elderly and in creating a sense of community.
They plan to widen it to 1,000 participants in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the scheme's effectiveness is limited to small,
select towns and could never be replicated in any grand scale.
Hidehiko Sekizawa of Tokyo's Hakuhodo Institute of Life and Living,
says it is a well-meaning project designed to ``transform
capitalism into a gentler system.''
</P>
<P>
   Toshiharu Kato, who developed the barter project in his spare
time, acknowledges that his scheme is a rather warm and fuzzy
utopian idea. ``You can describe me as a dreamer, but it's
important to dream, to realize the ideal type of community,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's perhaps fitting that the very local Kuriyama barter program
was dreamed up by Kato, a government bureaucrat in Tokyo. Localism
is a radical idea in Japan, where everything from street signs to
building designs is centrally planned.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say a barter system could be particularly useful
in Japan, where money is considered almost dirty; for instance,
even in the simplest purchase, money almost never is directly
handed to anyone, but rather placed in a small tray. So it would be
unseemly to pay someone to teach a recipe or read aloud, things a
family member might do.
</P>
<P>
   Before they turned to the barter scheme, Kuriyamans attempted
another way to reinvigorate the town: it tried to attract more
children. Officials offered a better health care package for
youngsters, and built a baseball field and soccer stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Result: The town exhausted its funds paying for all this, and
the effort was a total failure. In fact, one of the town's five
elementary schools was forced to close.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriyama's population continues on a slow decline as young
people move away in search of more excitement and better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same problem all over Japan. Young people go and
leave their families. It's not the way it should be,'' said Seiichi
Hasegawa, an administrator at the Red Cross Hospital who has spent
his life in the town.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa has gotten his daughter involved in the barter project
_ she buys groceries for an elderly lady _ in hopes of instilling
in her a sense of community and family responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   He would like her to stay in Kuriyama, to raise her family here
and see him through his old age. The problem, he said, is ``I can't
force her. That is her freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
