<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      03-27 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD-TO-REACH HIDDEN TREASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  KISANGANI, Democratic Republic of Congo _ A block down from
the Assemblies of God clothing store, a policeman in Cub Scout
yellow and blue directs traffic from a wooden scaffold set in the
middle of a four-way intersection.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only way to keep all the bicyclists from colliding.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the coming weeks or months, the United Nations will
arrive. Kisangani is one of four towns in Congo where the
international community will send observers and peacekeepers to
monitor compliance with a cease-fire negotiated, signed, and
repeatedly violated by the belligerents of this country's 20-month
war. The UN will bring cargo planes, helicopters, and a convoy of
white vehicles. Foreign development and relief organizations will
probably follow, each with their own fleet of all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic will thicken, and Kisangani and its people will become a
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, the streets are largely empty of cars, most
of them having been stolen and driven off during successive wars,
and clogged with ``tolekas,'' the local name for bicycle taxis.
Translated, it means ``we go.'' The bicycles are all the same,
standard black one-speeds with rod-lever brakes, but individualized
with patterns of colored tape and rear-wheel mudguards bearing
catchy phrases that usually evoke God or Jesus. They cost little to
ride _ a few bills of late-Zairian issue or new Congolese francs
with too many zeroes to carry much value.
</P>
<P>
   While tolekas set the pace on Kisangani's wide and once-splendid
lanes, pirogues, or dugout canoes, ferry life on the near-mythical
Congo River.
</P>
<P>
   Originally named Stanleyville, after the indefatigable but
brutal explorer Henry Morton Stanley, Kisangani was the last great
river outpost establishing Belgian King Leopold II's reign over the
Congo basin. The town lies in the middle of this vast country,
surrounded by dense rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the roads connecting Kisangani to other cities are
impassable, either damaged by war or overgrown with neglect. In
fact, the town has never been easy to reach, but it has always been
a draw. Two airports make it a strategic port in war, and Kisangani
has been sacked in successive conflicts against former Zairian
president Mobutu Sese Seko and the current Congolese leader,
Laurent Kabila. Pope John Paul II spent four days here during his
first tour of Africa in 1980. Diamond traders flock to dig in the
sandbars hidden in the dense surrounding forest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of two foreign armies and three rebel
factions, all flexing self-declared authority, the town hums with
its own brand of insouciance.
</P>
<P>
   The central market, once called 24 November after Mobutu's rise
to power but renamed 13 March for the day Kabila swept through,
bustles in a town square ringed by bullet-pocked buildings. Entire
streets are lined with the kitschy facades of prospecting diamond
dealerships _ named Willy's, Jihad, or Christ is Rich.
</P>
<P>
   Some mornings Kisangani awakens to the bells and baritone choir
of the Cathedral of our Lady St. Rosaira on the Congo's banks. Dusk
sets off a chorus of frogs, so numerous it is almost impossible to
walk without stepping on them, on the far and less developed side
of the river.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad that Congo, chronicled a century ago by Joseph Conrad,
still bears the insulting label from the title of his most famous
work, ``Heart of Darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congolese are a kind and patient people, with a curious
penchant for purple lounge suits. Like any place, Kisangani has its
swindlers and cheats, but also its heroes and saints. The most
respected man in town is a meek English professor from the local,
impoverished university.
</P>
<P>
   Well-thumbed Bibles aren't hard to find. Nor is the yearning for
peace. Zuzi Batetianto runs a stall at the 13 March market, selling
_ with a straight face _ pink and purple trousers in just about any
size and cut. He has heard the UN is coming, and he's willing to
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now Congo will get out of its present difficulties,'' he
said. ``We have had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Kurt Shillinger, who is based in Johannesburg, covers southern
Africa for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9282 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DOCTOR-PLEA-ART-2TAKE     03-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-PLEA-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DOCTOR SEES CARE FROM THE OTHER SIDE _ AND CRIES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Isatu Olivia and Nanah Kylie, two girls from
war-torn Sierra Leone, came into the life of Dr. Sondra S. Crosby
last year, the nine-year veteran at Boston Medical Center suddenly
found herself on the other side of the waiting-room door.
</P>
<P>
   In a whirlwind of events that eventually reshaped her life,
Crosby sought compassion from her profession, but found little.
During one week alone, when Isatu's and Nanah's pediatrician was
out of town, the girls' HIV tests were botched, frazzled clerks
were uncaring, and the future seemed as uncertain as the girls'
ages, which no one could pinpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated and with no one to talk to, Crosby sat at her
computer at midnight one night and poured out her frustrations.
Then, without a second thought, she clicked a button and sent her
words to the Journal of the American Medical Association, which
published her essay earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``A Mother's Prayer,'' Crosby's piece is part mea culpa,
part raw assessment of her experiences, and part plea to do
something about a medical industry directed more by profits than
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the constraints of 15-minute visits and productivity
quotas, I can't remember the last time I asked a patient `How are
you, really?' and meant it,'' she lamented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to get beyond the next mammogram, Pap smear,
cholesterol or viral load results,'' she continued. ``I have never
even thought to consider patients' experiences in the waiting room,
or what happens to them when I go on vacation. How do they get
through the impossibly complicated medical maze?''
</P>
<P>
   Since it was published, Crosby said the most common reaction has
been a quiet pat on the back and a knowing glance. The biggest
surprise was that there was no surprise: Most doctors privately
agreed with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the core of medicine is empathy with patients,'' said
Dr. Steffie Woolhandler, who practices internal medicine at
Cambridge Hospital. ``And the more the patient becomes referred to
as an industrial commodity, the harder it is to maintain that core
of empathy and compassion, and that's part of what she's talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby's essay may have provoked mild talk around hospital
cafeterias, but its message was felt most deeply by its 40-year-old
author, who has quietly vowed to come to terms with the realities
of working in an increasingly MBA-driven profession, while reaching
out to others as best she can, one patient at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know what it feels like to be in so much pain and not
know where to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sondra Crosby first heard of Isatu and Nanah in a letter from a
Maine adoption agency seeking families for children whose lives had
been torn apart by strife.
</P>
<P>
   The news came just months after she and her husband, Alan, had
begun building a family when they adopted a 1-year-old girl,
Madison, from China.
</P>
<P>
   A cherub-cheeked toddler with a passion for Barney the purple
dinosaur, Madison was an easy child to adopt. Her medical history
was known, her status constantly monitored since birth. But
yearning for more children, Sondra and Alan received pictures of
two wiry girls with cropped hair and faint smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Isatu and Nanah could hardly have been more in need of
parenting: with distended bellies from malnutrition and faces that
hid a host of fears, the girls' adoption from Sierra Leone would be
both a challenge and a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But then things grew worse.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the girls' pictures were sent abroad, their orphanage
was attacked by rebels on Jan. 12 last year. The building was
burned to the ground, forcing all 17 children and their leaders
into the thick African bush. After months of near constant
communication, there was suddenly nothing but silence as two months
slowly passed.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16 last year, the silence broke. Reports from Africa
and Maine said the small band of teachers and orphans had made it
to Guinea after trudging for two months and 90 miles in the bush.
</P>
<P>
   It was good news, but it was then that Crosby's fears began to
build. She wrote that she knew nothing of the girls' medical or
family history. She did not know what they had seen, what horrors
they had experienced. Isatu would later talk of smelling burning
flesh and of being forced to beat a young boy, while Nanah suffered
from poor teeth and mysterious rectal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Crosby said she was falsely confident. ``After
all,'' she wrote in her essay, ``I am a physician and I work in the
inner city. I treat patients with parasitic diseases, hepatitis,
HIV, and post-traumatic stress, as well as those who have
experienced domestic and street violence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1525EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DOCTOR-PLEA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-27 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-PLEA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... street violence. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``But what I failed to understand,'' she continued, ``was simply
how to be a mother, and how to share and experience my girls' pain
in a very personal way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the new family finally arrived home in Canton, Crosby
turned to the medical profession for answers and, where there were
none, for some help making sense of her new daughters' conditions.
Tests for human immunodeficiency virus, malaria, hepatitis, sickle
cell anemia, syphilis, and lead poisoning were administered.
</P>
<P>
   But from the start, the process turned chaotic: During one blood
test, one of the girls soiled her clothing. During another visit, a
clerk rudely asked Crosby where the girls' mother was. She had
problems contacting doctors and getting answers to basic questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never before felt so helpless or out of control,''
Crosby wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One day last year, Crosby said, her frustrations gave way to a
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of her fears over Isatu and Nanah, when it all
seemed to be spiraling out of control, a woman called out to Crosby
from across the crowded lobby at BMC.
</P>
<P>
   Desperately sobbing and noticeably drunk, the woman was a former
patient, a recovering alcoholic and diabetic. She told Crosby she
was scheduled that day to testify against a man accused of shooting
her son. Terrified over retribution for her testimony, she had
slipped off the wagon and did not know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   With that cry for help, time stopped for Crosby. Of all the
people to turn to, of all the places to go, this woman had come
seeking her. And within this woman's pain, Crosby said, she saw her
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was me,'' she said. ``I suddenly knew where that woman
was coming from. Looking at her, I knew what it feels like to be in
so much pain and not know where to go. I tried to understand this
before, but I didn't really understand it the way I do now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crosby flung herself into her work at BMC, where she spends long
hours while carrying a ceramic coffee mug adorned with a picture of
her new family. The mug is usually filled with cold coffee. On the
back of the mug is a crayoned picture of a smiling face and
widespread arms with the caption: ``We love our Mommy this much.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby's clientele is a rare mix of the city's displaced and
downtrodden. Most of her patients have no regular medical care, no
phones, and often no homes. She has been treating such patients
since she was in her residency.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as part of her vow to pay more attention to her patients,
Crosby gives her beeper number out liberally, a cure for impersonal
phone systems. And while the visits are still quick and the pace of
her day nonstop, she said she is making an effort to stop, to
listen to what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am suddenly finding out things about their lives I never
knew, but should have known,'' Crosby wrote. Her daughters, she
said, ``have thankfully influenced what had become a businesslike
approach to my own medical practice: I am reminded why I went into
medicine in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital's urgent care clinic, where Crosby spends some
of her week, the door opens and closes on a host of maladies and
stories.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, with only one other doctor helping out,
the clinic had taken in 43 patients by 3 p.m. The two doctors see
as many as 85 to 100 patients between 8 a.m. and 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m., Crosby and Dr. Stelios Maheras had had no break since
8 a.m. No lunch. And the waiting room seemed perpetually filled.
There was a man newly arrived from Cameroon with malaria and a
homeless patient with a bruised hand whom Crosby has sporadically
cared for since her residency.
</P>
<P>
   At her primary practice the next day, Crosby saw an HIV-positive
man from South Boston whom she met in the urgent care clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I started to be treated for HIV, I've had four
doctors,'' said the man. ``The first doctor, I had absolutely no
use for. The second doctor was great but he was transferred
somewhere else. And he referred me to another doctor who seemed
more concerned about his image as a doctor than about treating
patients. And Dr. Crosby, she's an extremely caring doctor, a
caring person, period.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, on a beautiful morning hinting at spring, three
girls in matching dresses walked into the Norfolk County Courthouse
before an attorney handed them each a helium-filled balloon adorned
with a ballerina bear.
</P>
<P>
   When their turn came, the girls, their father, mother, and
grandparents were escorted into a quiet courtroom that was all
their own. The girls drew pictures of houses on the blackboard
before the judge came out, introduced himself, and escorted the
three beaming girls behind the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Holding Madison on his hip, shuffling documents in his free
hand, and directing Isatu and Nanah to bang his gavel at the
appropriate time, the judge solemnly bequeathed each girl a new
name, all of which now end in Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   There were no plans for celebration. Sondra said she hoped she
and Alan would sip champagne when the house grew quiet that night,
and a large family meal was planned for this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But on this warm day _ a bright end to all the pain and
introspection that began less than a year ago _ Alan and the girls
headed home while Sondra strapped two beepers around her neck,
located her missing stethoscope, and once again headed back to
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2TA     03-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE BREWING OVER RIGHTS TO INTERNET CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Over the past 200 years, a rough balance has evolved in
this country between the rights of the owners of intellectual
property and those of the public who want access to their work. But
a sizable body of legal experts now believes that technology being
developed to protect intellectual property on the Internet _
``code'' in Web vernacular _ may shatter this equilibrium and
marginalize much of traditional copyright law.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader scale, a trifecta of code, aggressive licensing
contracts, and recent federal legislation has buttressed owners'
rights at the expense of public access. Leading this wave have been
record companies and movie studios incensed over the piracy
flourishing on the Net that costs them millions of dollars each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the tension between open content advocates who
consider the Net nirvana and owners who find it a free fire zone on
their creative work has elevated the arcane world of copyright law
to marquee status.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the movement in this field has been toward content and
then encryption at the expense of Fair Use,'' says Terry Fisher, an
intellectual property specialist at Harvard Law School. Fair Use is
the doctrine that provides exceptions to exclusivity of copyright
protection for criticism, commentary, news, teaching, scholarship,
and research.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that is at risk,'' adds Jessica Litman, an intellectual
property law specialist at Wayne State University in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   John Perry Barlow, cofounder of the nonprofit Electronic
Frontier Foundation (EFF), which is dedicated to open Net access,
has emerged as one of the field commanders waging rhetorical
warfare against corporate intellectual property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was previously considered a common human resource,
distributed among the minds and libraries of the world,'' he
writes, ``is now being fenced and deeded. It is as though a new
class of enterprise had arisen, which claimed to own air and
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsefeathers, counter record and movie executives. ``If you
can't protect what you own, you don't own anything,'' says Jack
Valenti, the longtime president of the Motion Picture Association
of America (MPAA), which represents the major studios. ``Society
doesn't say you can copy anything you want. Fair Use is still very
much alive. We have no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a culture clash between those who believe content on
the Net should be free and the content community who says, no, what
we do has value,'' adds Cary Sherman, general counsel of the
Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA), which represents
more than 500 companies in the music business.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Era of Promiscuous Publication, a phrase that
captures the unsettling ability of the Net to transmit anything
instantly and indiscriminately. ``Today,'' Sherman told Congress in
1997, ``one individual, in less time than it takes me to read this
testimony, can send a full-length album to more than 50 million
Internet users.''
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree on one thing: Nothing is safe on the Net today.
``If you handed me a 100-page book, I could give you a digital copy
in about two hours,'' says Michael Segroves, an executive at
peanutpress.com, the Maynard-based e-book publisher that
participated in the online distribution this month of Stephen
King's latest work. ``What then has that done to the intellectual
property?''
</P>
<P>
   To staunch the flow of illicit traffic, the RIAA has filed a
spate of well-publicized lawsuits recently against Web sites such
as MP3.com and Napster alleging massive copyright infringement.
While Sherman said he admires the genius of MP3 software, which
compresses a CD to allow fast and easy storage on a hard drive, he
remains livid at both sites for finessing the permission from
artists and record companies required under copyright law to use
their music.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com makes copyrighted music available to users, providing
they can demonstrate possession of the CDs they want to hear. Thus
far, it has amassed upward of 80,000 from which to choose. Napster
allows users to link their own music archives to those of others.
While Napster doesn't offer any music of its own, it facilitates
access to a huge trove from other participants. Napster, which
Sherman calls ``a giant piracy machine,'' is an example of a
network externality. In plain English, this is something that
becomes more valuable the larger it grows.
</P>
<P>
   When MP3 software surfaced in the late '90s, the recording
industry reacted ``like a parent to a freshly mohawked teenager,''
according to a precis drafted at Harvard Law School's Berkman
Center on the Internet and Society and the EFF. It was just a
phase, record executives concluded. Wrong. Last year, according to
the document, ``MP3'' replaced ``sex'' as the Internet's most
searched term. And Napster use has so overloaded college systems
that it has been banned from many campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are huge. According to a recent report by Jupiter
Communications, the Net music business alone will swell to $1.6
billion by 2002. Many legal experts expect the recording industry
to prevail in its suits. But a larger question looms: Can
intellectual property on the Net ever really be controlled?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
