<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-US-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      03-27 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TROOPS IN KOSOVO NAVIGATE CALDRON OF HATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJILANE, Yugoslavia _ When Velko Gjorevic's medication ran out,
he picked up a pitchfork and started chasing his family around
their farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, the guy's so old he couldn't catch any of them,'' US
Army Staff Sergeant Lee Sodic said as the 70-year-old Gjorevic sat
quietly in the back of a Humvee, heading back home after two nights
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hunter, Gjorevic was the potentially hunted, and so, at
US taxpayer expense, he was driven home by a heavily armed escort
of six US soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this a lot,'' said Sodic, a 28-year-old from Boise,
Idaho. ``Six months ago, a Serb was released from jail and the
Albanians followed him home and jumped him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year Army veteran and experienced peacekeeper, having
served in Somalia and Bosnia, Sodic has no illusions about his job
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop these people from killing each other,'' he
said, pausing briefly to spit chewing tobacco juice into an empty
plastic water bottle. ``And these people would like nothing better
than to kill each other. They hate each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Sodic turned to face a reporter in the back seat of his Humvee,
to make sure his point hit home. ``I mean, really hate each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 100,000 Serbs left in Kosovo, about half of them
live in the southeast sector controlled by 6,000 US troops. Keeping
the majority of ethnic Albanians from killing their Serb neighbors
in retaliation for the Serbian government's ethnic cleansing which
led to NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia is the biggest job facing US
troops.
</P>
<P>
   But few Serbs seem to appreciate the protection. As a US patrol
trundled through a Serb enclave outside Gnjilane, children flashed
three-finger Serbian salutes, while sullen men and dour women
stared contemptuously at their supposed protectors. Sometimes they
throw rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also have to deal with a small but persistent
group of ethnic Albanians who want to continue the war that
supposedly ended last June.
</P>
<P>
   In the Presevo valley, along the border with Serbia, former
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army have restyled themselves as
the Presevo, Medveda, and Bujenovac Liberation Army, referring to
the areas where about 70,000 ethnic Albanians live under Serbian
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that part of Serbia as ``eastern Kosovo,'' the rebels
have ambushed Serbian police, who have killed civilians in
retaliation. US Army officials say the Albanians are trying to
provoke an overreaction by Serb forces, such as the atrocities
against civilians that triggered the war last year, or to draw
American fire on the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   US Army Lieutenant Cliff Keller met with the rebels and told
them to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they're on their own, that we're not getting
involved in that, and if they think they can draw us in they're
wrong,'' said Keller, a Tennessean.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the political representatives of the fledgling
rebel group vowed to seek a political solution, but US troops say
they will continue to be vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, American soldiers have staged high-profile searches of
border area homes, taking weapons from ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   First Lieutenant Scott Olson said the Americans mean business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to tolerate the Albanians killing Serbs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is only so much American soldiers can do. About 20
Serbs have been murdered in Gnjilane since US troops arrived here
last June, and there are about a half-dozen attacks on them every
week.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Dr. Josef Vasic, a moderate and one of only two Serb
physicians left in Gnjilane, was gunned down in the city center at
9:30 a.m. &UR;  &LR; as US soldiers stood nearby. His killer escaped in the
crush of people, none of whom would help the peacekeepers identify
the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   As US Army Specialist Jason Nelson, a baby-faced 22-year-old
from El Paso, guided their Humvee down the narrow, dusty roads on
the outskirts of Gnjilane, Sergeant Sodic said many former Kosovo
Liberation Army members are trying to reinvent themselves, either
as die-hard patriots or get-rich-quick gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many organizations, I can't keep 'em straight,''
Sodic said. ``But if they've got weapons, we take 'em. The Serbs
think they're being picked on, the Albanians say we're not doing
enough. Our job is to be impartial and control both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ethnic Albanians are not actively seeking revenge or trying
to stir up trouble along the border with Serbia. They waved
cheerfully as the American ``presence patrol'' passed. Children, in
particular, flock to the American GIs. But having seen how friendly
locals in Somalia quickly turned on US soldiers, Sodic is wary,
taking the adulation with a huge pinch of salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, people like having us here,'' he said.
``But eventually, like Somalia, people will probably begin to see
us as part of the problem. When you hold people back from carrying
out the revenge that they think is their God-given right, you get
caught in the crossfire. We expect things to get worse as it gets
warmer. During the winter, most people are just trying to survive.
They're not thinking about killing someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials worry about the crossfire scenario, which is
why US troops were pulled out of the divided northern city of
Mitrovica after Serbs attacked them as they searched houses for
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Of two dozen US soldiers interviewed here, all of them said they
believed the peacekeeping mission here will go on indefinitely
because the hatred they see is so intense, and because they have
little faith in the United Nations to establish a modern,
multiethnic democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no opinion on the UN,'' Sodic said diplomatically,
before adding, almost under his breath. ``I saw them in Somalia.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two US bases in Kosovo. Camp Bondsteel, the bigger of
the two, has about 4,000 soldiers, while Camp Monteith here has
2,000. US jets purposely avoided bombing the Yugoslav Army base
here that has been transformed into Camp Monteith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before the war started, we knew we were coming here,''
Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of hammering, as permanent buildings go up, suggests
that the US Army plans to be here a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson parked outside the police station so Sodic could go in
and get a local farmer who found a minefield on his land. The plan
was to have the farmer point out the area so they could mark it off
with warning tape and bring in a contractor who clears minefields.
As Nelson waited, a little boy rode up on a rusty bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason, Jason!'' 10-year-old Doni Becini called out to Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up, Doni?'' Nelson said, climbing out of the Humvee,
tousling the boy's brown hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you, my friend,'' Doni sang in broken English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big news, big news,'' Nelson told him. ``I'm going home in 20
days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You go where, Jason?'' the boy asked, sounding confused.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson knelt down on one knee so he could look his young friend
in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home,'' the soldier said gently, ``I'm going back to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was crestfallen, his knuckles white as he gripped the
handlebars tightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, why Jason? Why you go home?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My job here's finished, Doni,'' the American GI said, putting
his hand on the boy's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, Jason, no,'' the little boy said, shaking his head,
sounding almost hopeful. ``Your job here is never finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Doni Becini may be more prescient than anyone dares to believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
