<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9287 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2TA     03-27 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE BREWING OVER RIGHTS TO INTERNET CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Over the past 200 years, a rough balance has evolved in
this country between the rights of the owners of intellectual
property and those of the public who want access to their work. But
a sizable body of legal experts now believes that technology being
developed to protect intellectual property on the Internet _
``code'' in Web vernacular _ may shatter this equilibrium and
marginalize much of traditional copyright law.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader scale, a trifecta of code, aggressive licensing
contracts, and recent federal legislation has buttressed owners'
rights at the expense of public access. Leading this wave have been
record companies and movie studios incensed over the piracy
flourishing on the Net that costs them millions of dollars each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the tension between open content advocates who
consider the Net nirvana and owners who find it a free fire zone on
their creative work has elevated the arcane world of copyright law
to marquee status.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the movement in this field has been toward content and
then encryption at the expense of Fair Use,'' says Terry Fisher, an
intellectual property specialist at Harvard Law School. Fair Use is
the doctrine that provides exceptions to exclusivity of copyright
protection for criticism, commentary, news, teaching, scholarship,
and research.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that is at risk,'' adds Jessica Litman, an intellectual
property law specialist at Wayne State University in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   John Perry Barlow, cofounder of the nonprofit Electronic
Frontier Foundation (EFF), which is dedicated to open Net access,
has emerged as one of the field commanders waging rhetorical
warfare against corporate intellectual property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was previously considered a common human resource,
distributed among the minds and libraries of the world,'' he
writes, ``is now being fenced and deeded. It is as though a new
class of enterprise had arisen, which claimed to own air and
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsefeathers, counter record and movie executives. ``If you
can't protect what you own, you don't own anything,'' says Jack
Valenti, the longtime president of the Motion Picture Association
of America (MPAA), which represents the major studios. ``Society
doesn't say you can copy anything you want. Fair Use is still very
much alive. We have no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a culture clash between those who believe content on
the Net should be free and the content community who says, no, what
we do has value,'' adds Cary Sherman, general counsel of the
Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA), which represents
more than 500 companies in the music business.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Era of Promiscuous Publication, a phrase that
captures the unsettling ability of the Net to transmit anything
instantly and indiscriminately. ``Today,'' Sherman told Congress in
1997, ``one individual, in less time than it takes me to read this
testimony, can send a full-length album to more than 50 million
Internet users.''
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree on one thing: Nothing is safe on the Net today.
``If you handed me a 100-page book, I could give you a digital copy
in about two hours,'' says Michael Segroves, an executive at
peanutpress.com, the Maynard-based e-book publisher that
participated in the online distribution this month of Stephen
King's latest work. ``What then has that done to the intellectual
property?''
</P>
<P>
   To staunch the flow of illicit traffic, the RIAA has filed a
spate of well-publicized lawsuits recently against Web sites such
as MP3.com and Napster alleging massive copyright infringement.
While Sherman said he admires the genius of MP3 software, which
compresses a CD to allow fast and easy storage on a hard drive, he
remains livid at both sites for finessing the permission from
artists and record companies required under copyright law to use
their music.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com makes copyrighted music available to users, providing
they can demonstrate possession of the CDs they want to hear. Thus
far, it has amassed upward of 80,000 from which to choose. Napster
allows users to link their own music archives to those of others.
While Napster doesn't offer any music of its own, it facilitates
access to a huge trove from other participants. Napster, which
Sherman calls ``a giant piracy machine,'' is an example of a
network externality. In plain English, this is something that
becomes more valuable the larger it grows.
</P>
<P>
   When MP3 software surfaced in the late '90s, the recording
industry reacted ``like a parent to a freshly mohawked teenager,''
according to a precis drafted at Harvard Law School's Berkman
Center on the Internet and Society and the EFF. It was just a
phase, record executives concluded. Wrong. Last year, according to
the document, ``MP3'' replaced ``sex'' as the Internet's most
searched term. And Napster use has so overloaded college systems
that it has been banned from many campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are huge. According to a recent report by Jupiter
Communications, the Net music business alone will swell to $1.6
billion by 2002. Many legal experts expect the recording industry
to prevail in its suits. But a larger question looms: Can
intellectual property on the Net ever really be controlled?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &QC;
</P>
