<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2ND     03-27 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PROPERTY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... really be controlled?  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the feverish efforts by the RIAA and MPAA, the answer
may be no. If so, the anxiety flourishing in academic circles is
unwarranted, at least for now. The recording industry association
has sent out hundreds of cease-and-desist letters to rogue Web
sites alleging copyright violations. The sites disappear into the
ether like moonshiners in the hills of Appalachia, who simply move
their stills to another site when authorities approach.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he believes efforts to control intellectual property
on the Net by tightening existing law are doomed. ``Those will all
fail because it is ineffectual to halt the ingenuity of hackers or
the pace of technological innovation,'' he says. ``Ultimately,
copyright owners and their representatives are going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The second way to attempt control of intellectual property on
the Net _ an intermediate step in Fisher's view _ is through
contracts a user must agree to when signing up for a particular
program. These may be ``click-on agreements'' on the Net or
``shrink-wrapped'' ones in which a user agrees to terms
accompanying software to be installed in a computer. But their
legal standing is murky.
</P>
<P>
   A third way, the use of code, offers the best chance for
intellectual property owners to control their work on the Net.
Essentially, code provides techniques to limit or channel the uses
of information through encryption technology. Big content owners
like Disney and Sony can use it without public debate or
legislative fights. Eventually, walls of seamless protective code
may rise from the Net landscape like the towers of a Tuscan hill
town _ a specter that terrifies Barlow and others.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a change from traditional copyright enforcement,
where owners such as record companies have always tolerated a
degree of ``leakage.'' Before the advent of the Net, attempts to
make and distribute bootleg cassettes of music, for example, were
of no consequence because the quality of such reproduction was poor
and the process cumbersome. The lost revenue simply wasn't worth
pursuing. No more.
</P>
<P>
   Code also brings to mind the axiom of Jonathan Zittrain,
executive director of the Berkman Center: Technology always has two
phases _ It's Too Early To Tell and It's Too Late To Do Anything
About It. The only way to avoid the second is to focus on the
first.
</P>
<P>
   If code is indeed where the action is, then who writes it and
toward what end loom as the key questions. Consider the Secure
Digital Music Intiative (SDMI), a worldwide consortium of about 200
organizations associated with the music industry struggling to
develop a global encryption standard available to music content
providers. SDMI is far from reaching its goal, but its very
existence provides a glimpse into the thinking of the recording
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want the amount of freedom to reproduce speech to be
defined solely by the owner, who normally looks only at the
market?'' asks Zittrain about SDMI. ``There is not one user sitting
at that table. I don't want to rely on business models to give me
rights from copyright law. I don't know why I should have to go
down quietly on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness too the hoopla around the recent online release of
Stephen King's latest piece of fiction. Through code, the 66-page
novella entitled ``Riding the Bullet'' was made available only on
computer and hand-held instruments like the Palm Pilot. Most
salient, it cannot be copied. This limitation is at odds with the
First Sale Doctrine, a rule embedded in copyright law that allows
people to lend or resell a hard copy after they have purchased it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the tight access is obvious to owners. ``If I put
intellectual property in a browser, it is almost impossible to
protect the security of that text,'' says Segroves. Adds
peanutpress.com cofounder, Mark Reichelt: ``The publishers want to
be damned sure that what happened to the music industry won't
happen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the King experience going to be the future of digital
publishing? ``Absolutely,'' says Segroves. It is but one example of
the new reality that Zittrain calls ``privication'' _ where code
enables the distribution of information to a large audience while
not releasing it into general circulation.
</P>
<P>
   While some panic, others counsel caution. Pamela Samuelson, an
intellectual property specialist at the University of California at
Berkeley's law school, Boalt Hall, may have it right when she says
that despite ominous signs, ``We're in a transitional period where
Fair Use still has a future.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston University Law School professor Maureen O'Rourke agrees.
``The question is, does the law need to intervene at this point or
wait for the market to evolve?'' she asks rhetorically. ``It is
premature to do anything to stop the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But few outside the recording and movie industries, including
O'Rourke, are happy with the Digital Millennium Copyright Act of
1998, a leviathan federal law that made it a felony for someone
merely to attempt circumvention of protective code. Mark Lemley,
Samuelson's colleague at Boalt Hall, calls this ``unilateral
technology disarmament'' in which one side uses code to build a
wall, but the other side cannot use technology to crack it.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 act has already triggered an important legal fight. In
January, Norwegian authorities detained a 16-year-old youth who
hacked his way through the DVD encryption code and then posted his
program, called DeCSS, on the Net. The seven major studios that
comprise the MPAA then filed federal suits in New York and
Connecticut under the DMCA, alleging copyright infringement against
individuals who exploited the DeCSS technology.
</P>
<P>
   The movie industry moved fast to avoid the mayhem that hit the
RIAA ranks. ``We watched the savaging of the music industry. They
were first in the line of fire,'' says MPAA spokesman Richard
Taylor. ``There were lessons to be learned.''
</P>
<P>
   But new problems may arise from the DMCA. Jane Ginsburg, an
intellectual property specialist at Columbia Law School, worries
about the inability of code to identify motives behind the copying
of a film in the wake of the DMCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same device that could stop me from copying a whole movie
could also stop me from copying a small amount of the movie to show
to my class,'' says Ginsburg. ``In that case, the copy would be
locked up and I couldn't circumvent the lock because of the DMCA.
Here is where the existence of an alternative copy is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other sources, says Valenti, such as
Blockbuster Video and cable television. But will Blockbuster even
sell ancient technology like VHS cassettes a decade from now?
``These alternatives are only available at the pleasure of the
publisher,'' said Zittrain.
</P>
<P>
   Big content owners claim they are simply protecting what they
own. But they are short on credibility. These are the folks, after
all, who brought us the Sonny Bono Copyright Act of 1995 that
extended copyright protection to an astonishing 95 years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that law, the operating system code of an
antediluvian laptop Radio Shack TRS-80, already ensconced in the
Smithsonian Institution as a museum piece, won't be in the public
domain until 2075. Go figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
