<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-OPERATOR-BOS &LR;      03-27 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OPERATOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSPARING LOOK AT A MOGUL'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE OPERATOR 
David Geffen Builds, Buys and Sells the New Hollywood. 
By Tom King. Random House. Illustrated. 670 pp. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1941, Budd Schulberg came out with his novel ``What Makes
Sammy Run?'' The story of Sammy Glick, an amoral movie producer who
clawed his way to the top on the back of a talented writer, caused
a sensation. Glick lied, cheated, and stole his way to Hollywood
fame and fortune in Schulberg's cautionary tale. For the better
part of 50 years, readers, particularly those in the movie
business, were appalled by Glick's tactics. But for the past decade
and more, it's been an introductory textbook on how to succeed in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Operator,'' Wall Street Journal reporter Tom King's
well-researched, compellingly documented biography of media
billionaire David Geffen, reads like a factual version of
``Sammy.'' Except that Geffen's rise makes Glick seem like a
candidate for sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   On a superficial level, Geffen's life story seems to have
blossomed full blown from one of those old MGM Mickey Rooney-Judy
Garland movies. Here's the bright and cheery Hollywood version: At
13, after growing up on the edge of poverty, the son of Abraham and
Batya Geffen reads ``Hollywood Rajah,'' the story of Louis B.
Mayer's rise from poverty to head MGM itself, and sees that as a
plan for his own life. After a mediocre high school career and
after flunking out of both the University of Texas at Austin and
Brooklyn College, Geffen takes a job in the mailroom at William
Morris, and starts working his way up.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, a lack of academic success might be a serious
roadblock, but not for the eager, ambitious Geffen. When it seemed
that lacking a degree might hurt his chances for advancement,
King's book says, Geffen forged a letter from UCLA saying he
graduated. In one of a series of spectacular ironies, he eventually
used his friendship with Linda Rondstadt who used her friendship
with then-California Governor Jerry Brown to obtain a seat on the
California board of regents. And that was just the beginning of his
rise.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Geffen made his first million as a record executive. His
list of friends and clients eventually read like Liz Smith's
Rolodex: The Doors, Elton John, Cher, the Eagles, Joni Mitchell,
Bob Dylan, Donna Summer, Jackson Browne, Crosby, Stills, Nash and
Young. In 1980, he produced John Lennon and Yoko Ono's ``Double
Fantasy'' album. In 1982, he established the Geffen Film Co., which
produced movies such as Tom Cruise's ``Risky Business'' and Albert
Brooks's ``Lost in America.'' Geffen coproduced Broadway shows,
including ``Cats'' and ``Dreamgirls.'' By 1990, Geffen Records was
making $46 million in profits a year, and its namesake hardly had
enough wall space to hang his 50 gold and 31 platinum albums.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? Buy a new home. In 1990, Geffen purchased the
Beverly Hills mansion of Jack Warner, another legendary studio
mogul, for $47.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Grover, in a 1992 Business Week profile, characterized
Geffen this way, ``. . .the reason David Geffen emerged (in 1991)
as the richest man in Hollywood is his uncanny ability to discover
raw talent, feed it through his Rolodex, and parlay it into rivers
of money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the relentless nature of that course also left a residue of
isolation in its wake. King, in one of the book's most stunning
scenes, writes how during the trial of O.J. Simpson, Geffen and
onetime super-agent Sue Mengers sat in his Malibu beach house
watching the proceedings on television, by themselves. The moment,
like a riff on Gloria Swanson and William Holden in ``Sunset
Boulevard'' (1950), strongly suggests the sort of eventually lonely
``friendship'' that money sometimes buys.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this biography began with Geffen's full
cooperation. The mogul, responsible for making so many astute
decisions and parlaying them into vast wealth, opened his door, and
all of his associates' as well, to King.
</P>
<P>
   So, if he's so smart and rich, how did he ever let a journalist
as savvy and incorruptible as Tom King get this close to him?
Perhaps the answer comes through a mixture of self-deception and
the fact that the press has always tread softly around Geffen. But
not King.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have suggested that King received major access
over three years in part because he and his subject are gay and
because Geffen thought the Wall Street Journal connection had a
certain cachet, worthy of someone of his stature. But there may be
more to Geffen's reasoning. Geffen had spent so much of his life
re-creating the story of his life _ and getting away with it _ that
maybe he just saw King as a more formidable challenge than pulling
the wool over the eyes of the entertainment press. Well, if that's
the case, he woefully underestimated the writer.
</P>
<P>
   King has been criticized in some quarters for merely providing
the facts of Geffen's life without drawing definitive psychological
conclusions. But because King's reportorial skills keep his
analytical bent in check, that becomes one of the book's primary
virtues. He trusts the readers to draw their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The pivotal moment, for me, occurred when Geffen was 18, and he
and his brother, Mitchell, were riding in a limousine on the way to
the cemetery to bury their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Mitch, nobody knows we're not rich,'' said David.
``We could be rich riding in this limousine.'' Now, he assuredly
is.
</P>
<P>
   But the book leaves readers with one really obvious question _
just what has a billion dollars purchased for Mr. Geffen?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1536EST &QL; 
