<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, REGIS, HERE ARE SOME REAL QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Jeopardy'' host Alex Trebek complains that the questions on
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' are too easy. Sour grapes, some
might say, since Trebek's comments came on the heels of Regis
Philbin signing a contract in the $20 million range to host
``Millionaire.'' Still, Trebek isn't the first critic to point out
that the questions are a tad on the simple side.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what's needed aren't tougher questions but a different
sort of question altogether. For example:
</P>
<P>
   How can I get my 15-year-old son out of bed in the morning?
</P>
<P>
   Or if that sort of question is too challenging, maybe they could
try questions that might compel contestants and viewers alike to
reflect, however briefly and superficially, on the meaning of
modern life. For example:
</P>
<P>
   How does Jerry Lewis fit into the generally accepted belief that
the universe is a better place with human life than without it?
</P>
<P>
   In a utopian world, would there be any need for Dr. Laura
Schlessinger?
</P>
<P>
   Does the question ``Got milk?'' presuppose an answer?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this sort of question doesn't lend itself to multiple
choice answers. Maybe the producers would agree to give every
contestant the $1 million just for showing up and grappling with
questions like these:
</P>
<P>
   If we can have knowledge of only what is true, how can we decide
which candidate to vote for in the presidential election?
</P>
<P>
   Does the phenomenal popularity of the World Wrestling Federation
tend to support Spengler's theory about the decline of Western
civilization?
</P>
<P>
   If, as Plato maintained, the unexamined life is not worth
living, what keeps Kathie Lee Gifford going?
</P>
<P>
   Is the phrase ``Viva Las Vegas!'' a legitimate example of the
timeless present?
</P>
<P>
   If not to decide is to decide, has John McCain given George Bush
his answer?
</P>
<P>
   If, as Hegel contended, only mind is real, to what extent were
Rick Rockwell, Darva Conger, and everybody else associated with
``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' wasting their time, and
ours?
</P>
<P>
   Is CNN news a legitimate example of Nietzsche's doctrine of the
eternal recurrence of the same events?
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to reconcile the concept of a supreme being with
the continuing success of David Geffen?
</P>
<P>
   If we accept the definition of a miracle as an event that
violates the ordinary course of nature, what _ if anything _ should
we conclude about the Miracle Bra?
</P>
<P>
   How many angels can dance on a PIN?
</P>
<P>
   Does Dick Vitale's commentary on ESPN reflect Wittgenstein's
view that the primary function of language is not to describe?
</P>
<P>
   Does the success of the Internet mean that entropy doesn't apply
when it comes to information systems?
</P>
<P>
   Is Sports Illustrated's prediction that the Red Sox will win the
World Series an example of ambiguous optimism? Is it an appropriate
probability statement? Or is it just nuts?
</P>
<P>
   If the concept of immortality presupposes physical death, how do
we account for the existence of show-biz immortals, so called, who
are still living?
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you accept the concept of collective guilt, are we all
responsible for the success of Andre Rieu and his magic violin?
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal society, would everyone have an equal chance to be a
contestant on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''?
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
