<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-KENNEDY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADRIENNE KENNEDY IS FRAGILE AND FEROCIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Adrienne Kennedy has a problem. A visitor wants to sit
in on her playwriting seminar at Harvard, and she really wants to
accommodate. But she frets: What about the students? ``That's a lot
of pressure on them,'' she says, hands fingering an invisible
string of worry beads. ``They're so very. . . .'' She pauses,
sighs. ``They're so very fragile, you see.''
</P>
<P>
   Fragile, in fact, would be a good way to describe the
68-year-old playwright, who at 5-foot-1 weighs in at barely 100
pounds. There's something delicate about her, a sort of dreaminess
that gives her an almost ethereal quality. She tends to get a
faraway look when recalling youthful fantasies about breaking bread
with the Bronte sisters or hanging out with Hemingway at some Paris
bar. Her laugh is gentle, almost girlish.
</P>
<P>
   Her plays, however, are another thing entirely. In a body of
work written over the last four decades, Kennedy has created a
surreal world in which romantic innocents are threatened by the
persistent presence of racism. Rage lurks beneath the surface. Time
is all topsy-turvy. History is fluid. Violence is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   How can the same woman who fusses about her students create such
harrowing dramas? ``It does seem like two different people,''
Kennedy confesses. ``There's the person getting ready to walk out
now and teach, and there's the person who writes the plays. I don't
know that person, although I've come to trust her. I'm a mystery to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She explores that mystery in ``The Ohio State Murders,'' a
one-act play that opens a two-week run Friday at the Hasty Pudding
Theatre in Cambridge. Produced by the American Repertory Theatre,
it stars Denise Nicholas. In the piece, a writer named Suzanne
Alexander returns to her alma mater to deliver a lecture and, in
the process, unearths the devastating secrets of her own past. ``I
was asked to talk about the violent imagery in my work,'' the
character begins. ``Bloodied heads, severed limbs, dead father,
dead Nazis, dying Jesus.'' By the end of the play, the source of
that imagery is all too clear.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Kennedy to define the source of the violence in her own
work and she hesitates _ at first. After all, she doesn't know the
mysterious woman who writes the mysterious plays. She does allow
that she's always been filled with anxiety and dread. She also
recalls her own shattering experience as an undergraduate at Ohio
State in the early 1950s, when, as one of only a handful of black
students in a gigantic dorm, she was treated like a dust mote
intruding on an all-white decor.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, she remembers the stories she heard on her
mother's lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a little girl, but I was totally my mother's
confidante,'' she recalls. ``We would sit and talk, very often in
the early evening in the winter, and I know for a fact that my
plays have the same tone as her stories.''
</P>
<P>
   What kind of stories? ``Oh, she'd say, `When I was a little
girl, my stepfather was killed crossing a railroad track. He was
electrocuted.' Or she might say, `When I was growing up in
Montezuma (Georgia), black people were not allowed to walk on the
white side of town. One day, I made a mistake, and I walked beyond
the post office, and this white man came out and said, `You little
yellow bastard, what are you doing here?' Stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright quietly repeats more of her mother's sagas, never
raising her voice or altering her calm tone while recalling tales
about ``Whites Only'' signs and segregated drinking fountains and
cemeteries where blacks weren't allowed to have tombstones on their
graves. ``My mother was quite violent in her language, so I grew up
feeling that blacks were hated people. I still feel that way. Very
much so,'' she says gently.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy pauses, then smiles. ``My mother totally had my
attention on those wintry evenings,'' she says. ``To get someone's
attention that way is part of my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Delicate pieces
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Kennedy's plays have captured more attention in
the halls of academe than on the stages of the American theater.
Her work is regularly taught on college campuses, and the
playwright is a frequent guest lecturer at such universities as
Yale and Harvard, where she taught this winter. She has a devoted
academic following, but her experimental plays are rarely produced.
Her first play, ``Funnyhouse of a Negro,'' won an Obie Award in
1964, but she went decades without a New York production until the
Signature Theatre Company devoted an entire season to her work in
1995. Two of her early plays were staged by David Wheeler's Theatre
Company of Boston in the 1960s, but she hasn't been produced
locally since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her plays are very delicate and sensitive pieces of writing,''
says ART artistic director Robert Brustein. ``They're not
blockbusters or powerhouses, so she is not produced that often.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy tries to be philosophical about her career. ``Sometimes
I would become very, very sad _ I think I was the saddest in the
'70s,'' she says. ``But over a period of time, it's become clear
that my plays tend to be taught in colleges and are the subjects of
dissertations and papers at conferences. I've come to be happy and
grateful for that because I could be just totally forgotten.'' A
pause. ``That doesn't mean that when I read that David Mamet is
opening again on Broadway that I don't feel sort of . . . well,
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Stylistically, the plays reflect the personality of the
playwright. ``She is the work,'' says Marcus Stern, who is
directing the ART production. ``She is both incredibly delicate and
very beautiful with the appropriate amount of rage about racist
atrocities. She is like the quiet watcher who absorbs so much, and
we're not even aware of how much she sees and understands until she
produces it in her plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the playwright has always been demure, even as she was
digesting her mother's stories. Apart from those haunting tales,
Kennedy looks back wistfully to a charmed childhood in Cleveland.
Named after the movie star Adrienne Ames, she and the other
children in her mixed-race neighborhood fell in love with
Hollywood, restaging favorite films in their backyards. Her parents
were college-educated professionals _ her father a social worker,
her mother a teacher _ who were active in civil-rights work; at
home, Kennedy was instilled with a grounding in black culture and
history, and at school, she devoured the classics of European
culture, particularly the romantic poets. ``I was a very quiet
person, and I became very caught up in this idea of being a writer.
I read `Jane Eyre' and I wanted to be Charlotte Bronte. But I never
would have told that to anyone. I was expected to be a second- or
third-grade teacher and that was going to be my life. I kept those
secrets buried inside me, and I guess that heightened it.''
</P>
<P>
   In her autobiography, ``People Who Led to My Plays,'' Kennedy
pays tribute to a broad range of influences, from Langston Hughes
and Lena Horne to Clark Cable and Gene Kelly. But along with the
usual adolescent crushes on movie stars and the occasional poet,
she also harbored a fascination with the dark side of life from an
early age. She admired Abraham Lincoln, but noted that he had ``a
mad wife.'' She cherished a great aunt even though she was
``touched in the head.'' She worshiped glamorous movie stars but
was also perversely fascinated by the Wolf Man, an ordinary fellow
by day who turns into a monster at night. Her daydreams, it seems,
were tempered by dread.
</P>
<P>
   That anxiety heightened at Ohio State, where she was one of only
300 blacks on a campus with about 27,000 students. Accustomed to
the hodgepodge of her Cleveland neighborhood, where her best
friends were a mix of blacks, Jews, and Eastern European
immigrants, she was suddenly an outcast, an Other. Blacks weren't
allowed to join clubs or major in literature. Her dorm mates
sneered or pretended she didn't exist. ``There's violence in that
kind of behavior,'' Kennedy recalls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1543EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
