<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ANGEL-BOS &LR;      03-27 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ANGEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCING ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BLUE ANGEL 
By Francine Prose. HarperCollins. 314 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like its step-sibling, the newsroom novel, the academic satire
has always seemed to promise more than it delivers. It's a
wonderfully self-contained genre _ all those ideas and parodies of
ideas, bordered by the hedges of pastoral restraint _and yet the
same qualities, used to ill effect, can make it somewhat beholden
to form. The Brits have set high the bar, what with Kingsley Amis's
seminal ``Lucky Jim'' and David Lodge's hilarious ``Small World.''
But it's taken the American extremities of the past few decades _
protests and deconstructionists and teddy-bear campus love-ins _ to
take the groves of academe to new vistas of poetic possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Francine Prose, no wimp when it comes either to irony or
to scrutiny, and a writer who's presided over her share of college
classrooms. With her formidable analytic mind and her penchant for
bumbling anti-heroes, she knows how to be wicked and literary at
once. Certainly that's a trait her own Ted Swenson would
appreciate, were he given the occasion to encounter it. But he's
trapped running a Beginning Fiction seminar somewhere in the
perilous wilds of upstate Vermont, where the only thing more
troubling than the oppressive ennui of Euston College seems to be
his students' proclivity _ ah, creativity! _ for workshop stories
about bestiality.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't get this way overnight, of course, neither
Swenson's own desperate cynicism nor his wannabe novelists'
rhetorical artifice. The critically acclaimed author of a couple of
novels _ his first, ``Blue Angel,'' was inspired by the 1930 German
film classic _ Swenson has been trying for years (he's 47) to live
up to his own promise. But the Muse governing his current
Stendhalian manuscript (tentatively titled ``The Black and the
Black'') is as hauntingly reticent as Euston's rumored ghosts,
lurking in the periphery of one's consciousness but never showing
up at the door. His students, on the other hand, have only age on
their side; they're young and earnest and achingly untalented,
convinced that solipsism and moral superiority are easy
replacements for literary depth. This is the life to which Swenson
has become accustomed, until he stumbles onto the idiosyncratic
literary gifts of a disingenuous, overly pierced woman-child named
Angela Argo _ who, like Marlene Dietrich's Lola Lola, eventually
turns her beleaguered don into a drooling buffoon.
</P>
<P>
   So: Angela's Ashes, in other words, since we know from the first
that this ``Blue Angel,'' like its namesake, is headed for
incendiary ruin. But Prose is too savvy to head straight for
parallelisms. She has instead given us a satire that's also a map
of the entire academic campus _ a place where the metaphors and
endowments are rich, but the more essential resources of integrity
and character are paltry indeed. There are no heroes in ``Blue
Angel,'' save Swenson's wife, Sherrie, who, despite her husband's
shenanigans, is more wiseacre-weary than martyred. Nor are we long
on morally defensible positions: The Cotton Mather-type judges who
condemn Swenson for his idiocies are hardly the peers you'd want to
stand before, from Euston's hypocritical dean to the gender
theorist of what used to be known as the English Lit department.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Prose has given us one hero: literature. It's there in
the shadows of Stendhal and Flaubert and Tolstoi, hovering in the
wings but doing what the Euston ghosts could never do _ affording
someone a reason to go on living, teaching, writing. It's what
drives Swenson, what made him first notice odd little punked-out
Angela when she approached him bearing a battered copy of ``Jane
Eyre.'' ``What I like,'' Angela tells her prof, ``is how pissed off
Jane Eyre is. She's in a rage for the whole novel, and the payoff
is she gets to marry this blind guy who's toasted his wife in the
attic.'' Take that, Mr. Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Angel'' is a wicked novel, but it is also, to its credit,
quite sad; buried amid the jokes and send-ups of a terminally
righteous academic milieu is the more poignant tale of a man whose
foibles have eclipsed his dreams. Abandoned by his own college-age
daughter, scarcely idealized by his beloved wife of two decades,
Swenson sees his own future every day before him: ``Age and death _
the unfairness of it, the daily humiliation of watching your power
vanish just when you figure out how to use it.'' And if that's a
prototypically existential definition of a midlife crisis, there
are far less deadly tonics for it than pursuing a student for whom
you feel equal parts lust and envy. But Swenson's literary fate is
to hurl himself, unshaven and unrepentant, upon that old
metaphorical funeral pyre. What else can a creative writing
professor do? This is a guy who, faced with ignominy and his own
mug in the mirror, reflects upon the tragic falls of Anna K. and
Emma B.
</P>
<P>
   The sweetest prism within ``Blue Angel'' is its multi-layered
comprehension of the truths and falsehoods of fiction; no one who
has given two thoughts to that subject _ as teacher, writer, or
patron _ will fail to relish the parallel between creativity
(writing a novel) and psychosis (imaginary friends, all day long!).
Prose is equally adept at creating the Academic Dinner Party from
Hell, or at least purgatory, where your best bet is to wait it out
_ accompanied by the other regulars trapped at the table,
``simultaneously rescued and menaced by dessert.'' Lacking the
hubris of either Swenson or Angela, Prose has not set out to give
us Stendhal or Flaubert; she has instead managed to be funny,
piercing, and dry as Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Let loose in fiction, intellect has a way of bullying
creativity, and at times in ``Blue Angel'' I felt the heft of
Prose's analytical mind taking over a scene where it ought to have
stayed quiet: where character or psychic dimension, say, would have
been far more revealing than mere humor or allusion. And
occasionally, as Swenson dug himself ever deeper, I found myself
troubled by what the professor himself would call the plausibility
factor: Would a half-decent guy (not to mention tenured professor)
really risk everything, especially for a frail, tattoos 'n' chains
girl whom nobody much likes? Then I remembered the day Monica
Lewinsky's name hit the presses, when my first thought had been
that Bill Clinton couldn't possibly be that stupid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      03-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT WHAT IF THE WRITING IS A CRIME, TOO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should we expect a mystery or detective novel to be well
written? If we do, on the whole we will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   What do we mean when we say a book is well-written anyway? It's
clear? Compelling? Evocative? Showing a sensitivity to words, a
sensitivity that includes an awareness of place, time, class,
ethnicity, nationality, gender, whatever?
</P>
<P>
   Too much of this sensitivity can destroy the narrative drive
that attracts many readers to the genre; too little makes a reader
with any awareness annoyed; being tone deaf kills credibility. Was
Agatha Christie a ``good'' writer, or simply an effective writer
who never lost sight of her main goals: to entertain, to mislead,
to be lean and brief, to sell really, really well?
</P>
<P>
   I was brooding on these questions as I looked over the books
chosen for review in this month's column. Two of them are
well-written by my lights, though they are very different; two are
adequately written to serve their purposes; one is badly written,
and yet I read, and for the most part, liked it. How important to
me, then, is it that a book read well?
</P>
<P>
   Fairly important. Robert Barnard is an old hand at the mystery,
and ``A Murder in Mayfair'' (Scribner, $23) is his 32d mystery. It
is written in his usual clear, calm manner, deceptively simple,
attractively spare, moving in a direct line that still admits
frequent surprises, what Americans often mean when they say a book
is ``very English.'' Barnard once taught English and has written a
biographical study of Christie, and while he does not try to
mislead a reader as she did, he does seek to deceive, very
successfully. Several of his books have been about a person's
discovery that they are not who they believe themselves to be.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Colin Pinnock has become a junior minister in a new
British government, pretty clearly Labour, and among the
congratulatory messages he receives is one that simply asks, ``Who
Do You Think You Are?'' At first he thinks someone is warning him
not to be arrogant, but he soon suspects otherwise, and with
precision and a very dry wit, Barnard takes us on a journey of
discovery with Pinnock that is intriguing and quite satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   A journey of discovery, self- and otherwise, is also at the
heart of ``Lost Girls,'' by Andrew Pyper (Delacorte, $23.95).
Beautifully written, claustrophobic despite being set in a rainy
northern Ontario town that flows outward into a land of deep lakes
and few people, this is a first novel that has done very well in
the author's native Canada. It deserves to be widely read in the
States as well.
</P>
<P>
   A young attorney, Bartholomew Christian Crane, is assigned to
defend a teacher accused on purely circumstantial evidence of
having killed two girls who were the members of the teacher's
``literary society.'' Crane is a habitual user of cocaine, and the
reader cannot be certain whether some of the bizarre occurrences
are real or in his mind. The brooding atmosphere is
well-maintained, and the book is a good bit better than its
dust-cover tag line, ``a novel of psychological terror,'' suggests.
It is frequently quite funny, and there are rewarding character
insights along the way to a resolution that falls just short of
being truly surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnight at the Camposanto,'' by Mari Ulmer (Poisoned Pen
Press, $23.95), also is a first novel, and while it shows the hands
of a beginner in its rather wooden construction, it also has
frequent attractive set pieces and draws on the ethnic communities
of Taos, N.M., with skill and compassion. It begins with the
killing of a ``penitente,'' relates this to skullduggery at Los
Alamos and, after a rather didactic start, relaxes into a
convincing and intelligent story about interesting people.
</P>
<P>
   Don Flynn writes a punchy prose meant to imitate deadline
journalism, quite successfully in his ``Fitz'' Fitzgerald mystery,
``A Brand X Murder'' (St. Martin's Minotaur, $23.95). Fitzgerald
works for the New York ``Daily Press.'' A good friend, Bobo Watson,
piano player, is murdered. Fitz is assigned a nothing story by his
city editor and feels he must investigate the murder instead, and
though he makes a remarkable number of mistakes, he finally solves
the mystery. The writing is of the old ``Black Mask'' style in
which body blows go ``Thunk!'' in conscious homage to a time now
gone. I'm not sure whether the style is a sendup or not, but I
enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   I am even less certain about Christopher Reich's stylistic
intentions in ``The Runner'' (Delacorte, $26.95), in which a
sedentary interrogator for the International Military Tribunal,
charged with investigating and trying war crimes at the end of
World War II, searches for Erich Seyss, an elite member of Hitler's
SS, a former Olympic sprinter, who escapes from an American
prisoner-of-war camp in order to carry out a mysterious but clearly
peace-destroying final mission. Real people play important roles
here, including General George Patton and OSS Director ``Wild
Bill'' Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   The language often seems ill-considered, Seyss escapes far too
many times, one is inclined to conclude that the interrogator,
Judge Devlin, is only barely competent, yet one keeps reading. I
guess that's what this game is all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
