<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``Cotton Mary'' Madhur Jaffrey is haunting as a woman of
Anglo-Indian parentage pathetically seeking to identify with Brits
who have no sympathy for her at the end of colonialism. But Ismail
Merchant's second effort as a director doesn't put enough around
her to make the film seem anything more than overextended domestic
drama. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Gun Shy'' In this black comedy in the new
macho-man-with-mushy-center genre, Liam Neeson plays a
disillusioned DEA agent embroiled in a messy mob sting. His life
out of control, he joins a men's therapy group and falls for Sandra
Bullock, an offbeat nurse who helps temper his fears. (R) (Loren
King) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Here on Earth'' A town-gown romance that leaves its
appealing performers woefully undersupplied. Leelee Sobieski is a
romantic local girl, Chris Klein is a rich twit who destroys her
family's diner and is sentenced to stick around and rebuild it,
Josh Hartnett is the local boy she drops. Dated moves and a cop-out
ending put this one out of the running. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Romeo Must Die'' Jet Li continues his quest to succeed
Bruce Lee and Jackie Chan and become the king of Hollywood
chopsocky. Like the best Hong Kong action stars, he's got moves no
American has. The producers wrap some dumb gangland-feud stuff
around him, but it's his acrobatics in the fight scenes that make
the rest of the film worth sitting through. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Such a Long Journey'' The first film made in India by an
Icelandic director (Sturla Gunnarsson) has a satisfying weight and
amplitude. It's built around Roshan Seth's performance as a
refined, humane Bombay family man trying to get by, despite some
treacherous problems of loyalty and politics on the eve of India's
1971 war with Pakistan. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !! ``Waking the Dead'' This worthy attempt to fuse the politics
of the '70s and '80s with a ghostly love story can't successfully
pull its parts together into a satisfying whole. It settles for
being a mood piece, with Jennifer Connelly's half-saintly,
half-smug crusader tantalizing Billy Crudup's idealistic young
lawyer turned pol, trying not to fall victim to his own pragmatism.
(R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``Whatever It Takes'' The producers of this would-be teen comedy,
in the apparent belief that it doesn't take much to succeed in this
business, settle for formulaic who'll-take-whom-to-the-prom stuff.
With its girl's-locker-room scene and brain-dead mayhem, it's
novocaine for the eyes. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
