<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In Search of Black America'' by David J. Dent (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $26). A journalism professor talks to middle-class
African-Americans about their lives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle for God'' by Karen Armstrong (Knopf, $27.50). This
chronicle of Jewish, Christian, and Islamic fundamentalism is
well-told, intriguing, and always respectful. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mysteries Within'' by Sherwin B. Nuland (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$24). A surgeon's tour of our bodies' inner landscapes, and of how
we came to understand them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suburban Nation'' by Andres Duany, Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk,
and Jeff Speck (North Point Press, $30). A brisk and often witty
manifesto laying out the problems of sprawl and the principles of
planning our way out of it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in This Country Must'' by Colum McCann (Holt, $21).
A novella and two stories by a modern Irish master of lyrical
melancholy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing Al Gore'' by Bill Turque (Houghton Mifflin, $25). An
excellent unauthorized biography, tracing the personal history that
shaped the probable Democratic nominee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Barbarians Are Coming'' by David Wong Louie (Putnam,
$23.95). Both hilarious and moving, this first novel traces the
journey toward wisdom of a Chinese-American son of immigrants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mountains Walked'' by Kate Wheeler (Houghton Mifflin,
$23). A remarkable first novel about a young American woman's
discovery of herself in Peru.
</P>
</TEXT>
