<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE CAUTION ON RISKIER FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I am debating what to do with this fund, since it has not
done well lately. I was considering rolling the 401(k) into an IRA
in Janus Enterprise and Janus Global Life Science and Janus Global
Technology, and possibly into a couple of the PBHG funds.
</P>
<P>
   R.H., San Diego, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. So Vanguard's Index 500 hasn't done much for you lately?
After five consecutive years of annual returns in excess of 20
percent, ranging as high as 37.4 percent in 1995, you've decided
the champ has fallen. As this is written, the fund has a 1.93
percent year-to-date total return, although it was indeed in the
red in the early months of the year. Including this year's stumble,
the five-year record shows 26.92 percent average annual growth.
</P>
<P>
   As the hillbilly comic Jerry Clower used to say, I think you're
fixing to mess up.
</P>
<P>
   Very simply, you need to view that five-year performance as
extraordinary and recognize that the future will bring considerably
lower _ but nonetheless solid _ returns. Certainly, if you had gone
back through those past five years and sought out the hottest
sectors of the market, investing in them would have produced better
results. But if you had guessed or calculated wrong as to when a
particular sector would shine, you probably would have done worse
than the broad market average that the Index 500 fund tracks so
well. This year and last, the hot sector has been technology, and
not surprisingly many of the funds you have identified tend to
focus in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Although these funds' recent results have been spectacular, led
by the 211.6 percent 1999 returns of Janus Global Technology, you
have to remember that along with such returns comes a lot of risk.
The portfolio price-to-earnings ratios of the Janus funds you
mention go as high as 58.1 (for Janus Global Technology), compared
to 37.3 for the Index 500 fund. Needless to say, in sour markets
the portfolio, which is backed by a good stream of cash earnings,
is likely to hold up better than a portfolio of stocks that have
been valued based on unproved prospects of strong future earnings,
rather than an established record.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it another way. The funds you are looking at can add a
lot of spark to a portfolio, but they are simply too risky for most
people to bet the farm on. That's why most investors who use such
funds limit them to small percentages of their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you leave the lion's share of the 401(k) money in the
solid, boring, old Vanguard Index 500, putting no more than a total
of 25 percent in these spirited but risky funds. I'd put 12.5
percent each into Janus Global Life Sciences and Janus Global
Technology, thereby at least dividing your bets between two market
sectors, health care and technology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've been less than satisfied with my 401(k) plan and have
decided to move 95 percent of my contributions to the large-cap
index fund and 5 percent to the international fund. Should I change
the allocation of my 401(k) funds based on my other investments?
</P>
<P>
   A.B., Boston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, right off the bat, I would reverse your savings
pattern. Currently you are putting taxable money into the riskier
sector-dominated funds that you were formerly using in your 401(k)
account, and you are now are putting your tax-deferred money into
broad-based funds. As a general rule, index and broad-based funds
will be more tax-efficient than funds that focus on a particular
market sector. If you are going to invest in the more narrowly
defined funds that you now have in your taxable accounts, it stands
to reason that you consider that these sector plays will deliver
above-average long-term results but will be balanced by the steady
performance of the stock index fund.
</P>
<P>
   So why not reverse the procedure, putting the entire $1,250 a
month that is now going into the taxable accounts into a Standard
and Poor's Index 500 fund, such as Fidelity Market Index or
Vanguard Index 500? The taxable distributions of sector-oriented
funds tend to be substantial and unpredictable, whereas those of
index funds more moderate and slightly more predictable. Moreover,
if you hold these sector plays within the 401(k), you will be in a
position to sell the holdings with no immediate-term tax effect
when the sector appears to you to have had its run.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, I would suggest that you diversify your portfolio a
bit more by resuming small contributions to the Davis New York
Venture fund within the 401(k). This would give you some exposure
to the value end of the market. I'd also keep my eye on Davis
Financial fund, but would withhold contributions at this time. The
price-to-earnings ratio of 19.2 for this funds portfolio is
attractive, but its 4.5 price-to-book ratio still gives me pause.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect of all of these moves would be that you would put
your entire $1,250 monthly contribution to taxable accounts into a
stock index fund, move all contributions to the funds you now have
in taxable accounts to the 401(k) account, dollar for dollar,
maintain your $75 monthly contribution to the international stock
fund in the 410(k), and contribute $100 and $75 a month,
respectively, to the stock index and New York Venture accounts in
the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all I'm suggesting is moving 5 percent of the
contributions from the stock index fund to Davis New York Value,
but changing the tax status of your investments should pay big
dividends over the years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be 70 on Oct. 15 and will take my IRA withdrawal this
year, so as to avoid two withdrawals in 2001. It is the math I am
concerned with. I am a widow, so I have my three children as my
beneficiaries, who will be 46, 49, and 51 when I turn 70. Does the
IRA figure these ages into the formula, or do they just use me? I
don't really need the money that will be represented by the IRA
withdrawals. Maybe I should give each child $10,000 per year. What
do you think?
</P>
<P>
   M.W., Madison, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With multiple IRA beneficiaries, the rules require that you
focus on the oldest for the purpose of determining the joint and
several life expectancy. Moreover, if the eldest beneficiary is
more than 10 years younger than you are, you must for the purposes
of calculating the mandatory distribution treat that person as
being only 10 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if you take your first distribution this year, you would
look at the ages 70 and 60 and determine that the balance of your
IRA accounts would be divided by 26.2 to determine the required
distribution. Each subsequent year, the level of the divisor falls,
and accordingly the amount of your required withdrawal will rise.
</P>
<P>
   However, the requirement for mandatory withdrawals involves the
year in which you reach age 70 1/2 rather than 70. You need take no
distribution at all this year. You will reach 70 1/2 on April 15,
2001, and you are not required to receive the first distribution
until April 1 of the year following attainment of that age.
</P>
<P>
   You could delay the first distribution for another 11 1/2
months. But then you would (as you correctly note) end up taking
two withdrawals in tax year 2002: one for the year 2001 in which
you turned 70 1/2 and another for tax year 2002. It would probably
be best to take a distribution in 2001, with a single distribution
in each subsequent year.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether you would be better off giving each
child $10,000 a year _ which would trigger no gift tax consequences
_ involves a lot of variables that go beyond taxes. They include
but are not limited to the question of whether you feel they would
be better off with a series of gifts over many years or access to a
larger pool later on, when they are closer to their own
retirements.
</P>
<P>
   If each of your children inherits a third of your IRA, they must
continue taking distributions at least as rapidly as you were
taking them.
</P>
<P>
   Note: I have answered your question directly, but there are also
other ways to determine IRA distributions and/or establish bequests
to your children, and it may pay for you to go to discuss them with
a tax professional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
