<SLUG> BC-LATINBANK-SUMMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES NEEDED TO BETTER COMBAT POVERTY IN LATIN AMERICA, U.S.
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Monday
that he favors sweeping changes in the way international aid
organizations combat poverty in Latin America amid signs that
robust economic growth there has left more people behind than many
economists expected.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, in a speech to Latin American finance ministers and
development experts at the annual meeting of the Inter-American
Development Bank, said the United States wants the bank to do a
``full review'' of its lending programs, raise the interest rates
it charges its wealthiest borrowers and adopt more effective ways
of raising education levels and fighting poverty. The
Washington-based bank, which is funded by the major industrial
nations, makes about $7 billion in development loans to Latin
America each year. Along with lending by the World Bank, it is the
main vehicle for the United States and other wealthy nations to
help alleviate poverty in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Though Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and other major Latin American
countries are performing better economically than most economists
anticipated a year ago, poverty and inequality have stayed
stubbornly high, and by some measures may even be increasing, bank
officials and development experts here said.
</P>
<P>
   They said the persistent income gap threatens the consensus that
has brought Latin American economies closer together in the past
decade, especially at a time when globalization is under attack by
labor unions and some private interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America's economic success in recent years has not been
associated with a reduction in inequality,'' Summers said in an
interview. ``The pressing economic problem for Latin America is to
create an environment in which all have a chance to benefit from
growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
