<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     03-27 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYERS PUTS HUMAN FACE TO DEPRESSING ECONOMIC REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Moyers has done it again. Over the years, he has earned a
reputation and a growing fandom among televiewers for revealing the
real-life human dramas behind America's most impersonal statistics.
He does this, moreover, in good taste _ without pandering or
preaching.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Moyers fan, or if you just like an honest,
undoctored, unslanted picture of American life as it's really being
lived, here's a special treat.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, PBS will present what may be Moyers' very best work
to date. ``Surviving the Good Times'' is an absorbing 90-minute
chronicle of current American life, 10 years in the making. Look
for this piece and tune it in. I predict you'll be rewarded. This
isn't escape stuff, but you'll find it far more gripping than
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   It's the true story of two fairly typical American working
families, in the 1990s, told in their own words and filmed exactly
as it was happening.
</P>
<P>
   You watch the children grow and the young parents become
middle-aged. You experience the gamut of their human emotions _
their elation when the eldest goes on to college, the near-panic as
a bank threatens foreclosure on the family home, the strains on the
marital bonds caused by a husband's declining self-esteem when his
wife has to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   This is real. It could follow no script. The stories of these
two middle-income families, the Neumanns and the Stanleys, unfold
with the honest vicissitudes of real life. They begin in the summer
of 1991 in Milwaukee when two old-line manufacturing companies
dismiss much of their workforce, one to move its workshops to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Tony and Terry Neumann are white; Claude and Jackie Stanley
African-American. Both have children. Set adrift by the layoffs,
each works hard to recover lost ground. After 10 years of
intermittent unemployment, extra schooling, second jobs and family
forays into entrepreneurship, both are struggling to regain the
economic status they enjoyed when the decade began.
</P>
<P>
   To reveal more of what happens would spoil the suspense. But be
prepared for poignant, funny and triumphant moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surviving the Good Times'' will make you think. Here, in
graphic human detail, is the overlooked story. The grim reality
behind the giddy statistics of soaring stock market values, overall
economic growth, low unemployment and stable prices includes the
declining lot of many hardworking households as familiar industrial
jobs with secure salaries and benefits continue to disappear.
Average wage earning families have a difficult struggle keeping
their heads above water.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Wilde once wrote that a mark of the truly educated person
is to be deeply moved by statistics. But most people comprehend a
statistic better if it wears a human face. Moyers' latest
production provides the faces.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Bill Moyers makes no political argument
about what should be done. I'll offer none here. Solutions can come
only when we understand the dimension of the very real problem
faced today by America's working men and women. Here, from studies
by the Economic Policy Institute and other think tanks probing the
financial health of America's labor force, are a few hard facts:
</P>
<P>
   _ During the '90s, while the real income of the upper
one-twentieth of America's families grew by 15 percent, real hourly
wages, measured against inflation, fell by four percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among workforce members without a college education, average
real wages plunged from $11.21 an hour in 1973 to $8.22 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even people with four years of college enjoy slightly less
buying power in hourly compensation ($18.38) than they had in 1973
($18.60). Only those with master's degrees and above are averaging
more than their counterparts one generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ To compensate for lost buying power, middle-income families
work 256 more hours yearly than in 1979. The average working wife
today spends 15 hours a week more on the job than she did in 1979.
One of the things we see in this film is the added strain and
stress this puts on the raising of a family.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty-nine million Americans (one in five) live in households
that regularly have trouble meeting at least one important family
need, such as food, electricity or medicine.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is more job anxiety in the workplace today. In 1992,
even with the recession, only about 17 percent said they were
afraid of losing their jobs. By 1997, that figure had risen to 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty-five million Americans today have no health insurance
and approximately 30 million more are inadequately covered. The
percentage of those without is rising steadily as more and more
corporations downsize their workforces and outsource their work to
satellite companies to avoid the costs of providing coverage to
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is imposing more stress on American families.
Outsourcing, downsizing, and moving to other countries for cheap
labor tell America's working people, ``You're on your own!'' What
has happened to the old basic American idea that we're all in this
together?
</P>
<P>
   Every business entity in this country has three types of
stakeholders. Two of them are not stockholders. They are the
company's workforce, and its customers. Without them, no business
could exist. Ultimately, business itself must rise or fall upon the
buying power that permits people who work for a living to purchase
the goods and services that America's businesses turn out. Moyers
doesn't bore us with these statistical arguments. He lets the human
story tell itself.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
