<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE DOESN'T SOLVE RACIAL ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost overnight, the tone of her letters changed.
</P>
<P>
   When they first began arriving, the writing was warm and
flattering, sometimes detailing the things we had in common, like
children and our Mississippi heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every week they arrived via e-mail. I'd read them,
smiling sometimes, and then I'd respond. Sometimes, we carried on a
dialogue by exchanging several letters.
</P>
<P>
   Then I wrote a column saying I supported affirmative action.
This did not sit well with my new-found friend, and she told me so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we finally disagree, big time,'' she wrote. ``If it was
1968, not 1998, when I was reading your article I would have said,
Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen then made her case against affirmative action. That was
June 7, 1998. I responded the way I always had, but this was the
last time I would hear from my ``admiring white e-mail friend,'' as
she called herself.
</P>
<P>
   I found this odd and wondered why she needed to remind me that
she is white.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered Kathleen the other day when another such e-mail
arrived from an Arlington, Texas, man accusing me of ``fanning the
racial flames'' because I questioned how the jury in the Amadou
Diallo case could've acquitted the four New York City cops accused
of killing him. The cops were white and four members of the jury
were black.
</P>
<P>
   ``It causes people like me, little by little, to trust
African-Americans less and less,'' he wrote. ``It tells us what you
really think of us. It causes me, personally, to think twice these
days before I go out of the way to perform an act of kindness
toward an African-American. And that's the shame of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember if he has ever written to me before, but I
responded, telling him shame on him because nothing he did or said
to me could cause me to withhold a kindness from someone white.
</P>
<P>
   Reading his note, remembering Kathleen's, I couldn't help
thinking how being candid can impose a terrible loneliness,
especially when dealing with issues of race.
</P>
<P>
   For those who would like to believe racism is a thing of the
past, it's much easier to accuse me of perpetuating anger,
self-pity, victimization and, yes, racism. I understand that.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't change the way many African-Americans view the
world in which we live, that often African-Americans are the last
to be hired and the first to be fired, viewed through a criminal
lens, and denied loans by lending institutions.
</P>
<P>
   If you think those things only happen in Mississippi, think
again. For all the progress we've supposedly made, there's no evil
worse than the one you can't see, the racism _ often unspoken _
just beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   I wish there were something new I could add, something to turn
the light bulb on in the hearts and minds of some people. But I
simply shake my head. If there are words to put this in its proper
perspective and put this issue to rest once and for all, they
escape me.
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced we will never arrive at a place of understanding
if we are unwilling to point out the injustices, regardless of
whether doing so is considered too sensitive or not politically
correct. Avoiding these issues has only led to more lies.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a plea to get us talking more about race. There's
been an ongoing dialogue for years about the way that we treat one
another.
</P>
<P>
   It's time now to start listening to each other.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
