<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     03-27 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT BLACKMAIL AGAINST A LEGAL PRODUCT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No self-respecting gun fighter would have done what Smith &AMP;
Wesson did to its industry colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   They shot 'em from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson went maverick on all the other gun manufacturers
when it broke ranks and cut its own deal with the U.S. Department
of Housing and Urban Development to get out from under dozens of
pending lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, gun manufacturers had been negotiating with the feds
for months in an attempt to reach a compromise on issues such as
trigger locks, background checks and multiple purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson, in an act described by company CEO Ed Shultz as
a move to ``save itself,'' secretly met with HUD Secretary Andrew
Cuomo in a series of meetings that culminated in last week's widely
publicized agreement. Shultz agreed to a ``code of conduct'' that
includes guns with built-in trigger locks, developing ``smart
guns'' within three years and a number of other concessions; Cuomo
promised that at least 10 of the 29 cities and counties suing
Shultz's company for negligent marketing of a defective product
would drop the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Heralded by gun control advocates as an enlightened move by the
gun maker to change the way business is done in America, the
settlement is little more than extortion disguising itself as
policy making.
</P>
<P>
   For people who respect the Constitution, which clearly says laws
are supposed to be made in the state house and not the White House
or the court house, this capitulation to a threat to bankrupt the
company is viewed as one more back-door attempt to legislate by the
executive branch. The Constitution's explicit separation of
governmental powers is once again bruised and battered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real goal of the litigation was to bypass the legislative
process which, despite the scourge of high-profile multiple
killings, has been remarkably unreceptive to a variety of gun
control measures,'' said Robert A. Levy, senior fellow in
constitutional studies for the Cato Institute. ``So if the
legislature doesn't cooperate, just commandeer public resources to
file suits across the nation until gun makers cry uncle. That's no
better than blackmail masquerading as law.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a choice, cry the gun control advocates. If Smith &AMP;
Wesson officials thought they were standing on firm footing, then
the company should have had its day in court.
</P>
<P>
   My, but isn't the high ground dry when you aren't facing
economic ruin.
</P>
<P>
   These suits are nuisance litigation. When it's brought by
entities that have bottomless bank accounts _ funded with public
dollars, no less _ then the playing field becomes more than a
little muddied.
</P>
<P>
   Think that's an overstatement? Then read the words of New York
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer: ``We have the capacity to squeeze
manufacturers like a pincers and hurt them in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   What a twisted nation this has become _ strong-arming companies
that manufacturer legal products because some amorphous ``we''
doesn't like what happens when the products are misused.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of folks compare these lawsuits to the ones filed against
the tobacco industry. The similarity is the fact that legal
businesses which Congress has chosen not to mess with are being
threatened with extinction by having to mount financially crippling
legal defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The huge difference between tobacco and firearms is how they've
been marketed. Tobacco officials for years swore that nicotine was
not addictive, and that the health risks to habitual smokers were
non-existent. They lied to the American people. Tobacco kills.
</P>
<P>
   Gun manufacturers have never said their products were anything
but lethal _ someone pulls a trigger and that little piece of metal
leaving the barrel at a very high velocity is going to put a hole
in whatever it hits _ a paper target, a white-tail deer, a human
being. When used properly, it can kill. But it can also save lives.
Studies completed by statistical academicians who have nothing to
gain or lose by their findings show that firearms are used anywhere
from 1.5 million to 2 million times a year to thwart crime _ many
times without firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, and where the focus of this entire debate should
remain, is on the purpose of the person pulling the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Every honest gun owner in America wants to find a way to keep
firearms away from people who shouldn't have them. Age limits for
purchasing firearms are reasonable. Permanently revoking the right
to gun ownership from anyone convicted of a crime involving a gun
is reasonable. Background checks on all sales at gun shows are
reasonable, as long as they occur instantaneously. Selling trigger
locks with each new firearm purchase is reasonable, but don't come
after me as the felon if someone breaks into my childless house and
steals a gun _ trigger locked or not _ to use in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to put gun manufacturers out of business by
governmentally sanctioned blackmail is not and never will be
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
