   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-TALKS (Vienna, Austria) _ OPEC oil ministers stumbles in a
bid to reach a deal to increase production. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT (Washington) _ Microsoft's last-minute
offer to settle an antitrust lawsuit is not enough for government
lawyers, who are now expecting the case's trial judge to give his
verdict Tuesday. By MARK HELM. (Also will be filed in the ``f''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WELFARE (Washington) _ The federal government's refusal
to pay welfare benefits to poor legal residents survives a Supreme
Court challenge. Without comment, the justices let stand a lower
court ruling that says Congress has the constitutional authority to
change welfare law, as was done in 1996, and deny food stamps and
other benefits to non-citizens living legally in the United States.
By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LaROUCHE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that the
Democratic Party lawfully refused to count votes cast for political
extremist Lyndon LaRouche in the 1996 presidential primaries.
LaRouche is on the Democratic Party ballot again in several states
this year. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   FLAG-AMENDMENT (Washington) _ The Senate begins debate of a
constitutional amendment to ban desecration of the flag,
legislation that has consistently failed to get the required
two-thirds vote. The measure has been approved by the House. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
