incredibly brilliant, casting shadows on the ground,'' Evans
recalled. ``You could have read a newspaper by it. That was the
most stunning thing I've ever seen. It just lit up the landscape.''
Fireworks of a similar kind, alive in shimmering waves of color and
brilliance, may soon be visible around the globe as the Sun
approaches the peak of its 11-year cycle of storms. The heavy rain
of solar particles, interacting with Earth's magnetic field, will
light up the skies as the aurora borealis materializes in places
where most people never expect to see it. By William J. Broad.
