<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUP ACCUSES SAUDIS OF EXTENSIVE HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ In a sharply worded report, Amnesty International
on Monday accused the government of Saudi Arabia of widespread
human rights abuses including arbitrary arrests, the torture of
detainees and the barring of prisoners' access to family members or
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it had received and published graphic accounts of
mistreatment, discrimination against religious minorities and
suppression of political dissent in the gulf kingdom for years. But
Saudi Arabia has escaped international condemnation for its record,
Amnesty officials added, because oil-dependent nations like the
United States have not wanted to offend the kingdom's rulers.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials, who rarely respond to outside critics, this
time reacted swiftly, emphatically rejecting Amnesty's findings as
biased and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to hide in human rights,'' said Prince Turki
bin Mohammedi, the deputy foreign minister responsible for
international organizations, in a telephone interview from the
Saudi capital Riyadh. ``There is no harm in having their point of
view, but they have to be more accurate in their information.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of Amnesty's U.S. affiliate, William F.
Schulz, said the human rights organization will try to spotlight
the Saudi record through a worldwide publicity campaign this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amnesty International does launch one or two major campaigns a
year aimed at countries with particularly serious human rights
violations,'' said Schulz. ``In the case of Saudi Arabia, the
country has gotten away with arbitrary detention and torture for
years, while escaping international scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will begin on Tuesday with a truck-mounted
billboard _ the most aggressive tactic ever used by Amnesty's
American office _ that will be driven around Washington. The
billboard will feature an amputated hand over the slogan: ``This
suffering is the secret of Saudi justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amnesty report consolidated accounts of mistreatment of
detainees and more general human rights abuses that it said it had
received or learned through media reports about Saudi Arabia during
the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this research clearly reveals is that people who are
arrested in Saudi Arabia for whatever reason find themselves
trapped in a criminal justice system that provides them with no
information about their fate, allows them no prompt contact with
their families or a doctor, and offers them no hope of contacting a
lawyer,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the organization's report concerned the broader Saudi
system itself, which bans political parties as well as criticism of
the royal family and government. Amnesty maintained that extralegal
torture and arrests take place and that even the country's legal
forms of punishment violate international norms in their cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   The critique ventures into the sensitive issue of how the rulers
and religious leaders in the tightly controlled and insular kingdom
interpret Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi legal system is based on its leaders' strict
interpretation of Shariah, or Islamic religious law, undiluted by
any attempt to reconcile it to modern sensibilities. Death
sentences are carried out by a firing squad for women and by
beheading, often in a public square, for men. Capital crimes range
from murder and drug smuggling to apostasy and moral corruption.
The punishment for repeated thievery is the amputation of one or
more of the convicted person's limbs.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of these penalties, the Amnesty report said, is
made worse by a lack of safeguards to guarantee fair trials and
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a request for comment on the Amnesty report, the
Saudi Foreign Ministry said the country's laws already provide
stringent guidelines for how police and security officials should
deal with prisoners and people they arrest. It also said that
contrary to the human rights group's report, most trials are open
to the public, according to Saudi law, and prison conditions are
fair.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, in its annual report on human rights
practices in various countries around the world, has carefully
raised criticisms of life in Saudi Arabia similar to those cited in
the Amnesty report. Most Middle Eastern countries, in fact, are
faulted in the yearly summaries for their treatment of prisoners,
conditions of detention and discrimination against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The recently published 1999 State Department report on Saudi
Arabia said the government ``commits and tolerates serious human
rights abuses.'' It noted arbitrary detention of citizens and
foreigners and credible reports of torture by security forces,
heavy-handed censorship, and violence against religious minorities
and women.
</P>
</TEXT>
