<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ULSTER-UNIONISTS-BOS &LR;      03-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-UNIONISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMBLE'S THIN MARGIN EXPOSED SKEPTICS IN PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ When David Trimble staved off a challenge to his
leadership of the Ulster Unionist Party on Saturday, his margin of
victory was described as narrow and a major disappointment to him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 57 percent of the votes from the 860-member Ulster
Unionist Council that Trimble drew marked only a 1 percent drop in
what he got last November when he received a cautious endorsement
of his decision to form a power-sharing government with Sinn Fein,
the IRA's political wing, before the IRA began disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Saturday's unenthusiastic endorsement of Trimble's
leadership gave empirical evidence that many middle class
Protestants in Northern Ireland remain deeply skeptical about the
peace process, and especially about again sharing power with Sinn
Fein until the IRA begins turning in its hidden arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   It was Trimble's willingness, stated in Washington two weeks
ago, to re-form the suspended power-sharing government without IRA
disarmanent up front that precipitated Saturday's challenge to his
leadership. Luckily for Trimble, his challenger, Martin Smyth, a
68-year-old Presbyterian minister, could neither stir the masses
nor offer a viable alternative to the Good Friday Agreement of
1998, which was supposed to end Northern Ireland's long-running
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth has always opposed the historic compromise in which
Protestant unionists who want to maintain the union with Britain
agreed to recognize the legitimacy of Irish nationalist aspirations
for reunification with the Irish Republic, while nationalists
accepted that Northern Ireland would remain part of the United
Kingdom until a majority voted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Like Smyth, many of those who want to see Trimble go are
reactionaries who long for the days when unionists could
unilaterally dictate to Catholic nationalists. But more worrying to
Trimble is the coalition between the old guard and a younger, more
cynical generation. The Young Unionist organization and its leader,
Peter King, backed Smyth's insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the peace process even more than the flagging
support for Trimble was a motion passed by the council which
stipulates the party will not rejoin the power-sharing government
unless the British government reverses its decision to change the
name of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the RUC, had pleaded with the
party not to endorse such a motion, saying it would politicize his
force by aligning it with one party and one political tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But so angry are most unionists over what they see as the
British government's appeasement of the IRA that they ignored both
Flanagan's and Trimble's warning that such a motion would allow
nationalists to claim that the RUC, despite pledged reforms,
remains the military wing of unionism.
</P>
<P>
   During the St. Patrick's festivities in Washington, Trimble
scored big points with the White House and the rest of the
international community by saying he was willing to resume the
power-sharing government that was suspended last month even before
the IRA begins turning in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But what is seen as statesmanship outside Northern Ireland is
often seen as treason within. Some unionists were outraged at
Trimble's offer, saying he has compromised so often on principle
that his party's word means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Elected as party leader in 1995 because he was the most
uncompromising of the candidates, Trimble has reinvented himself as
a resourceful, resilient politician who is willing to call Irish
republicans on their bluff _ to challenge whether those who for 30
years tried to destroy Northern Ireland with violence are truly
committed to reforming it through democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Trimble has been lauded internationally,
sharing the Nobel Peace Prize with John Hume, the pacifist
nationalist leader. But inside Trimble's own party, the Nobel Prize
is sneered at by some as proof of an international conspiracy that
sides with nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Trimble has made unionism more respected
internationally, slowly deconstructing the stereotype that
unionists are intransigent, anti-Catholic bigots. And yet the more
successful Trimble is at improving the image of unionism abroad,
the more he undermines himself with those inside his party who
believe he is sliding down the slippery slope to a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists are at a crossroads, unsure of whether to go forward
on the uncharted path of the peace process, or retreat to the
well-trodden trail of ``No Surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble may eventually become a victim of his own success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
