<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-OSCARS-NYT &LR;      03-27 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OSCARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: GROWING PAINS AS THE OSCARS PLAY TO JADED
STARGAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can't blame Canada for this one. When Robin Williams sang
``Blame Canada'' from the ``South Park'' movie, joined by a chorus
line dressed as Mounties, it was the highlight of this year's
Academy Awards show and a revelation. The evening's first
production number, this all-singing, all-dancing extravaganza was,
significantly, a parody of the inadvertently hilarious routines the
Oscar show has made famous.
</P>
<P>
   Coming an hour-and-a-half into the ceremony on Sunday, it was
also the night's last sign of hope that the new producers, Richard
Zanuck and Lili Fini Zanuck, might make good on their promise to
transform the event into something sleek and contemporary.
Conceptually, they got the idea. So why did the four-hour show turn
into a zombie, as if some pod creature had sucked the life out of
it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer has everything to do with how the entertainment
industry has changed. How big a deal is it, after all, to see Kevin
Spacey or Annette Bening or even Tom Cruise dressed up and ready to
act humbly grateful these days? After the Golden Globes and the
Screen Actors Guild awards, after all the movie plugs on late-night
talk shows and the Oscar campaigns chronicled by ``Entertainment
Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood'' as if they were the Middle East
peace talks, not very big. The overload of star presence makes
every appearance ordinary, and that's what the producers of the
Academy Awards can't bear to admit: however prestigious and
powerful the Oscars may be in the film industry, in our
celebrity-saturated television age stargazing is just not special
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   On some level old Hollywood understands that change, but doesn't
know what to do. That is clear in the mixed messages sent by the
Oscar show and the pre-and post-shows surrounding it. The show the
Zanucks produced for ABC came with a savvy understanding of the new
rules. They kept what was best from Oscars past. The deft and funny
host, Billy Crystal, sang his traditional medley about the
best-picture nominees, turning the ``Green Acres'' theme into ``The
Green Mile.'' But the hokey banter between presenters was kept to a
minimum and the best-song nominees were compressed into one
no-frills sequence. There were enough Halloween-ready fashions to
keep viewers entertained: Erykah Badu's pea-green dress and
matching mile-high turban made her look like the Jolly Green Giant,
and Angelina Jolie came dressed as Morticia Addams. Everything
started out swift and bright.
</P>
<P>
   And the show tacitly acknowledged being part of a larger showbiz
world. The announcer used to be a disembodied voice; this year
Peter Coyote was shown backstage, a move that played to the
viewers' sense of being insiders. When he announced that American
Express was a sponsor, the tag line resonated with a similar
flattering attitude: ``Whether you're seeing a movie or making one,
we can help you do more.'' Even the commercials blended with the
show into one seamless package, as Sally Field made fun of her
``You like me'' Oscar acceptance speech in an ad for the investment
company Charles Schwab. This is far from the days when moviegoers
worshiped stars from afar.
</P>
<P>
   But before the show was halfway through it became bloated with
tributes that the Academy clings to: segments on dead people, child
actors and a Burt Bacharach sequence of old nominated songs.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's identity crisis extended to the fusty pre- and
post-Oscar shows. Joan Rivers, who made a reputation for being
snarky about fashion on the E! channel special, now has arriving
stars groveling for her approval. Groveling in return, she asked
Michael Mann, the director of ``The Insider,'' why his film
flopped: ``Is it too intelligent?''
</P>
<P>
   Too much intelligence was not anyone's problem on Sunday. ABC
now has its own lame pre-show. This year its giddy host was
Meredith Vieira of ``The View,'' who capped the half-hour by
dashing into the auditorium and sitting on Clint Eastwood's lap.
Trying desperately to be cute and irreverent, the show flashed this
information on the bottom of the screen as Cruise was interviewed:
``Tom can be seen in his underwear in eight of his films, including
`Magnolia.'''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC show ignored the evening's only truly outrageous stunt,
which the Rivers special had the wit to include. The best-dressed
men of the evening were the creators of ``South Park.'' Trey Parker
arrived in a copy of the pink prom gown Gwyneth Paltrow wore last
year, and Matt Stone wore a knockoff of Jennifer Lopez's
cut-to-the-navel Grammy Awards dress.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's supposedly irreverent ``Politically Incorrect'' went in
the other direction, getting serious in its post-Oscars show and
asking the conservative critic Michael Medved about gender-bending
roles and family dysfunction in the movies. It was a wrongheaded
approach, especially at 1 a.m., but a suitable ending to
Hollywood's big confused night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
