<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-COLLEGE-SCHOLARSHIPS-     03-27 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-SCHOLARSHIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WEALTH OF COLLEGE MONEY AVAILABLE, EVEN TO THE AFFLUENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICK KARLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ One of the 15 or so college scholarships that
Heidi Schumacher is pursuing is the Seth Hokanson Memorial
Scholarship for students of Scandinavian extraction who have a
musical bent.
</P>
<P>
   She read about the $1,000 scholarship in the Swedish American
Newsletter, which her parents receive, and figured her Swedish
lineage and her participation in traditional Scandinavian music
pageants made her well-qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Yelena Biberman, a fellow Albany High School senior and Jewish
immigrant from Belarus, is applying for about 10 scholarships,
including a $1,500 award from the Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society. She
also is hoping for money from the Chinese American Alliance, which
she heard also tries to help immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these Albany High School students have high grade-point
averages and are near the top of their class. They also are seeking
berths in the Ivy League schools, with Biberman hoping to go to
Princeton and Schumacher looking at Yale. For their second choices,
Schumacher wants to attend Duke University, and Biberman is looking
at Wellsley and the State University of New York at Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to all the outside scholarships such as the Hokanson
and Immigrant Aid awards, the schools to which they are applying
may offer grants or scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a big difference between the two students.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher's parents are physicians, and while she has another
sister in college and a younger brother in private school, she says
her family could probably afford to pay most if not all of her
college costs.
</P>
<P>
   Biberman is part of a single-parent family _ her mother works as
a nursing home clerk and studies English in most of her spare time.
She has virtually no money for college and will be relying heavily
on grants and scholarships to get her through. Princeton may be
farther off for her than Yale is for Schumacher due to the simple
fact that Ivy League schools tend to dole out less grant money.
</P>
<P>
   That is a change from the way things used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Up until a few years ago, it would go without saying that
Biberman could get a lot more money than Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, schools are making awards based on performance
instead of need. And the grants from schools are typically larger
than the various scholarships, such as the Hokanson or Immigrant
awards, noted Jill Rifkin, who runs College Options, a Delmar-based
advisory service for college applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The move toward merit-based rather than need-based awards is an
example of how government policies are being played out in homes,
classrooms and college admission offices across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It started in the 1980s in Georgia when then-Gov. Zell Miller
started the Hope Scholarship, which awarded free tuition to state
schools for students with B averages or better.
</P>
<P>
   The concept caught on nationally, said Tom Mortenson, an
Iowa-based researcher who follows college finance issues. Many
states, including New York, now offer some kind of award to top
students.
</P>
<P>
   The shift from need to merit also is a byproduct of the fierce
competition among colleges and universities to get the best
students they can in order to boost their standing in various
rankings, such as U.S. News and World Report college surveys and
other similar venues, Mortenson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of simple math.
</P>
<P>
   If a school has $10,000 to award, it can give it all to a needy
but smart student.
</P>
<P>
   Or it can split the money among four or five students who may be
less needy but just as smart. That way, the school boosts its
number of high-achieving students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strong inclination among the financial aid people is to go
toward merit,'' Mortenson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
