<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     03-27 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETRACING JESUS' STEPS IN JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Taking a pilgrimage in Jerusalem, one of the great
religious cities of the world, can be difficult. There are too many
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to retrace the path of Jesus and the disciples as they
proceeded on one of the most earthshaking journeys in religious
history.
</P>
<P>
   Great idea, but not original. Pilgrims coming to this holy city
have been doing it for thousands of years. Still, I wanted to try
it for myself.
</P>
<P>
   My plan was to begin at the top of the Mount of Olives, walk to
the Garden of Gethsemane, where Jesus agonized over his coming
death, and then follow the Via Dolorosa, the street of sorrow that
Jesus took on his way to his Crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   My climb to the top of the Mount of Olives along a narrow paved
path progressed without interruption until I ran into Alli Kumbar,
who makes his living showing people around the area. He motioned
for me to come through an iron gate into the ancient Jewish
cemetery that covers much of the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to show me a great view of the city. The vista was as
breathtaking as he promised.
</P>
<P>
   He then handed me a small stone that he had picked up off the
hillside and instructed me to place it on top of a marble slab at a
grave site. Hundreds of other stones were already on the grave,
each in memory of victims of the Holocaust in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   When I left, Kumbar asked for a contribution, and I gave him
some shekels. As I was leaving, the congenial Kumbar turned his
attention to about 20 other tourists and began showing them around.
</P>
<P>
   Near the top of the Mount of Olives, I encountered a sign
indicating that this was the site of the tombs for the prophets
Haggai and Malachi.
</P>
<P>
   I was looking into a deep pit when Fareda Othman appeared,
picked up a kerosene lamp and took me and a German couple into a
cave that holds 50 graves. Two of the graves are marked with
symbols identifying them as tombs of the two prophets.
</P>
<P>
   To escape the chill and wind, I sat at a patio overlooking the
city and drank a cup of strong black coffee that Othman offered
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that Othman lives on the site, which her family has
owned for more than 100 years. Her laundry was hung out to dry near
the patio. She told us that the cave where Malachi and Haggai are
buried was originally covered by a large stone.
</P>
<P>
   When I finally made it to the top of the Mount of Olives,
hundreds of tourists were being photographed there.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing along the accepted path of Jesus and his disciples, I
stopped at the Garden of Gethsemane, the most impressive spot of my
pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   In A.D. 379, the Byzantines built a church over the place where
Jesus was believed to have prayed before he was crucified. The
sanctuary there now, the Church of All Nations, was built between
1919 and 1924. But the flooring of the original Byzantine church
can be seen through glass at some locations.
</P>
<P>
   The large stone identified by the earlier church as the place
where Jesus agonized before his death is at the altar. It is
encircled by ironwork resembling a crown of thorns.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people were kneeling and kissing the rock when I
arrived. I also kneeled and prayed there.
</P>
<P>
   Outside are gnarled olive trees that look old enough to have
been there during the lives of Jesus and his disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Around the garden of olive trees are signs reminding us of what
happened there. One cites a verse from the book of Matthew: ``Could
you not watch with me for one hour? Watch and pray that you may not
enter into temptation.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Garden of Gethsemane, I walked through St. Stephen's
Gate, also called the Lion Gate because of the figures carved into
its stone face. From there, I continued down the Via Dolorosa.
</P>
<P>
   On my way to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, I stopped at
chapels and churches that mark events leading up to Jesus'
Crucifixion. For example, the Church of the Flagellation identifies
where Jesus is believed to have been scourged and crowned with
thorns.
</P>
<P>
   At some of the 14 stations of the cross, it is difficult to
concentrate because merchants hawk their wares and tour guides are
talking in many languages.
</P>
<P>
   I finally arrived at the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, which
marks the place where Christ is believed to have been crucified.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, who was in Israel all last week, prayed at
the Garden of Gethsemane and its church and followed the Via
Dolorosa for a distance in a trimmed-down popemobile _ the
glass-enclosed vehicle in which he frequently travels _ and then
prayed at the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
</P>
<P>
   For him, I am sure, it was an inspirational moment.
</P>
<P>
   And the only distractions were the thousands of pilgrims trying
to get a glimpse of him.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
