<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     03-27 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY LIFTS SHROUD FROM CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: NYT Photo i(NU)5 s being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is rare indeed for commercial television to produce a program
of such high quality and importance as the two-and-a-half-hour
documentary, ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution,'' to be aired at 8
p.m. Eastern time March 30 on HBO. Produced and directed by Joseph
F. Lovett, five of whose family members had cancer and four of whom
died of it, the film is at once realistic and hopeful about the
life-and-death battles being waged daily against this disease.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the need for as many Americans as possible to view
this extraordinary, information-packed effort by Lovett, who is
also the film's host, HBO is making it available to all cable
subscribers, even those who do not have access to HBO, and will
show it three more times: on April 5 at 4:30 p.m., on April 8 at 10
a.m. and on April 17 at 2:30 p.m. If you do not have cable, I urge
you to visit a friend who does or ask someone to tape it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because there is not a family in America that has not been
or will not be touched by cancer. Because most people, when given a
diagnosis of cancer, fly into a panic that gets in the way of clear
thinking. Because many doctors initially consulted by cancer
patients are not up on the latest and most effective treatments for
their disease.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is widespread misunderstanding of the nature of
clinical trials and the enormous potential they offer for improving
cure rates and long-term survival. Because there is help out there
and hope for every cancer patient, even those with rare diseases,
if only people know how to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Take Gary Schine, for example. Told by his doctor that there was
no cure for hairy cell leukemia, the 46-year-old businessman from
Providence, R.I., sought a second opinion and discovered a new
treatment in a clinical trial in San Diego that has kept him
cancer-free now for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Another who refused to accept an imminent death sentence was
Arnold Sitton. With the help of the only oncologist in his rural
community, he went to France for an experimental drug treatment for
his advanced colon cancer that bought him nearly two years beyond
his initial prognosis of months to live, a total of two-and-a-half
years of quality time for himself and his wife, along with their
children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is little Jessica Turri, who at 10 received a
diagnosis of acute lymphoblastic leukemia. Jessica, an extremely
articulate, practical and charming child, cannot help but bring
hope and moral support to every family facing childhood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows her through the course of her treatment at St.
Jude Children's Research Hospital in Memphis and documents the
day-to-day trials _ and rewards _ of coping with cancer and its
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A head-in-the-sand attitude toward cancer is tantamount to a
death sentence should you get the disease. And one woman in three
and one man in two in this country will at some point develop a
potentially life-threatening cancer. Each year, 1.2 million
Americans are found to have cancer (not counting the more than one
million cases of superficial skin cancer) and 560,100 will die of
the disease this year.
</P>
<P>
   But as Dr. Richard Klausner, director of the National Cancer
Institute, notes in the film, Americans are plagued by ``an
alarming myth that a diagnosis of cancer is a death sentence.'' To
the contrary, he says, ``Now the majority of people diagnosed with
cancer will not die of that cancer.'' In fact, there are now more
than eight million Americans alive who have had cancer (again, not
counting superficial skin cancer), and most of them will beat the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Have we made significant progress against cancer? You bet.
Especially against childhood cancers. In the early 1950s, only 20
percent of children with cancer survived. Today, more than 70
percent are being cured, including 80 percent of children with
acute lymphoblastic leukemia. And in the last decade, a revolution
in cancer genetics has unfolded that explains both the origins of
many cancers and offers the possibility of new and more effective
treatments, comparable to the drug Herceptin that is now improving
survival of breast cancer patients with a particular genetic
defect.
</P>
<P>
   Even without any new discoveries, people already know how to
eliminate at least one-third of cancer deaths: by eliminating
cigarette smoking and other forms of tobacco consumption. Another
one-third of cancers might be prevented by other changes in living
habits, namely dietary improvements, increased physical activity
and achieving and maintaining a normal body weight.
</P>
<P>
   It is also known how to prevent at least two common cancers,
colorectal cancer and cervical cancer, through detection and
treatment of precancerous conditions. And it is known how to
maximize the chances for cure through early detection of breast
cancer, the most common cancer in women, and prostate cancer, the
most common cancer in men. The HBO film spells out all these
possibilities graphically and tells viewers how to reach the people
and groups associated with the techniques described. How to Become
a Winner
</P>
<P>
   Over and over again, the film emphasizes the importance of
taking an active role as a patient, of seeking out as much
information as possible about one's disease, finding the best
available treatments and obtaining a second opinion if the first
offers little long-term hope or recommends an outdated therapy. As
the father of a cancer patient states in the film, ``The care you
get is largely dependent on you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Schine, for example, the treatment that saved his
life had been published in a major medical journal just three weeks
before his leukemia was diagnosed, but the first doctor he
consulted knew nothing about it. Little Jessica's advice to other
children with cancer, ``Never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Also important is a willingness to be a guinea pig for
experimental cancer treatments. As Lovett so accurately notes,
nearly every bit of progress made against cancer has come out of
clinical trials in which patients were randomly assigned to receive
either the best available therapy of the day or a promising new
treatment. Participants in many clinical trials are treated at
government expense and are given the most careful and caring
treatment available.
</P>
<P>
   As for the common objection that the doctors who run clinical
trials are ``more concerned about their data than about you,'' Dr.
Michele Donato of the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston,
asserts: ``My primary obligation is to the patient. The goal is not
for the patient to benefit the trial, but for the trial to benefit
the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The film clearly recognizes that even with the very best
treatment, not every cancer patient will make it. While it does not
go into depth about end-of-life issues, it shows how hope can be
maintained even as life ebbs and how preparation for the end can
ease the agony.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that the experimental treatment was no longer
working, the Sittons used their remaining time to get their affairs
in order, to plan for the future and to enjoy as much of the
present as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the phone numbers and Web sites listed in the
film, access to all the organizations and resources named can be
obtained through the Web site www.HBO.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
