<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9354 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-HOPKINS-GENES-ART     03-27 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HOPKINS-GENES-ART-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING HOPE AND BEAUTY IN MUTATED FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(Eds: The word EQUALS in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ ``Fresh new life!'' Dr. Nancy Hopkins
exulted. ``These are the ones I love. They look so innocent,
somehow. Did you notice you can see right through their brains?''
</P>
<P>
   She was peering through a microscope at a day-old zebra fish
that resembled a speck-sized, transparent iguana wrapped around a
beach ball _ one of about 150,000 zebra fish that make her
Massachusetts Institute of Technology laboratory look in places
like a pet store overrun by its guppies.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later she was consulting with her visiting fish-food
man about the price of brine shrimp. Moments after that, she poked
in a fridge and pulled out, ``Ah, bubble brains from Friday!'' and
a ``bleached blond,'' another mutant fish, equally beautiful to
Hopkins in that its mutation was instantly visible: ``Born Saturday
_ three days later and you can tell by eye,'' she said. ``Now
that's my kind of screening.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, her kind of screening is much more complex than that.
In the race to identify genes that typify this dawning genomics
era, her lab has developed a technique that uses retroviruses to
induce mutations of single genes in zebra fish.
</P>
<P>
   The technique allows for quick isolation and cloning of the
mutated genes and, Hopkins said, should ultimately help define a
kind of ``construction kit'' of the genes necessary to make, say, a
heart, or a brain, or a whole baby fish.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Hopkins said, her lab is cloning three genes per
week for a total so far of 44 _ when all other labs combined have
cloned only about 30 and taken months or years on each one. The lab
used to celebrate each gene it cloned with a bottle of champagne,
she said, but now she can barely decide when to party.
</P>
<P>
   As the zebra fish genes roll in, this is an especially jubilant
time for Hopkins, 56, who is the Amgen professor of biology at MIT.
She laughs about the fungal fish-tank infection that stalled her
work for months, or the time half her postdoctoral students and
technicians were jumping ship in disgust, or how an administrator
told her she would not like running a large lab and should not try.
</P>
<P>
   But for years Hopkins was struggling on two related fronts. She
was engaged in the scientific fight to gain the time, resources and
knowledge to take unproven methods and make them work, and she was
waging something of a guerrilla battle along with a small band of
other senior women in science against sex discrimination at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, she seems to have won. But neither fight looks
really over.
</P>
<P>
   Though her science is a continuing source of joy to her, Hopkins
said, it also breeds a kind of parental anxiety. Every day, she
said, ``I get up and worry about the health of our fish.'' If
anything goes wrong with the fish, she said, ``It's over _ the
project is done.''
</P>
<P>
   The fish will have totaled more than 1 million by project's end.
Hopkins is aiming to isolate 1,000 of the 2,500 genes believed to
be necessary to make a normal fish, she said, and needs another
year and a half to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert A. Bosselman, the senior research director for Amgen
Inc., which stepped in to support Hopkins when federal grant-givers
said her work was too risky, said that her work looked quite
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a probability, although a small one, that she will
find some genes that are significant,'' Bosselman said. ``She has
characterized less than 10 percent of what she eventually hopes to
reveal through this approach, and I think we should just wait and
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sex-discrimination front, Hopkins and her comrades
created a national splash last year when they issued a report
saying they had documented a pattern of largely unintentional but
pervasive discrimination against women in the MIT School of
Science, and top administrators, including the dean and the
university president, backed them up.
</P>
<P>
   They found discrimination in areas that included hiring, awards,
promotions, inclusion on important committees, and allocation of
laboratory space and research money.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins was deluged with ``Here, too!'' e-mail messages from
women at other institutions, and with invitations to speak. She was
even invited to the White House, where the Clintons thanked her on
behalf of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been something of a backlash as well, including a
Wall Street Journal editorial in December calling the MIT study and
others that have followed ``junk science'' used to ``advance group
demands,'' and a report by Judith S. Kleinfeld, a University of
Alaska psychology professor who has also challenged studies that
found that schools shortchanged girls. She criticized the MIT study
as lacking data (the data were not made public, because they were
confidential) and said it amounted to ``little more than a
political manifesto.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins, though, stands behind the study. And while she praises
high-level administrators like President Charles M. Vest, who
backed her, she remains concerned about university life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you put women in positions where they're
decision-making, I don't think you can change this problem,'' she
said. Hopkins also calls for a re-examination of the structure of
science jobs designed for men with full-time wives at home.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James D. Watson of double-helix fame, who turned Hopkins on
to biology when she was an undergraduate at Radcliffe, and who
still speaks highly of her, noted, ``Changing MIT is sort of like
changing the Citadel.'' Women have gotten in, even risen high, but
``that doesn't mean your battles are over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he added, men face similar battles, and in general,
scientists seeking resources are ``like chicks trying to get food
from the mother; the one who's biggest will get the most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a scrapper,'' Watson said. ``Nancy was brought
up to treat people well, and that isn't necessarily the way men
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, raised in New York, where she absorbed a slight British
intonation from her grandmother, Hopkins does seem to have learned
late how to really scrap.
</P>
<P>
   She did not demand to have it all. ``I knew it was out of the
question to have children and do this job,'' she said, ``and
probably out of the question to marry and do this job. If I hadn't
gotten divorced, I would have maybe become a mother and been very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she embarked on an intense and successful career
studying tumor viruses, and remained in virology for 17 years, part
of a surging area of research that was delving into areas that
could bring some understanding of the genetic factors in cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember where you were standing when someone first told
you about oncogenes, just as people remember where they were when
JFK was shot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, however, after 17 years in virology, Hopkins
wanted to shift focus. She decided on genetics. The zebra fish,
that staple of home aquarium stores, was in its infancy as a model
organism for genomics and developmental biology. The fish offered
clear advantages _ they had fast life cycles, and as vertebrates
they resembled humans more than, say, fruit flies did.
</P>
<P>
   They were also, to Hopkins, ``very cute.'' If one could just
develop the right molecular tools, she thought, how much fun it
would be.
</P>
<P>
   It is often hard to make the transition from one field of work
to another, riskier one. But when Hopkins tried, it began to seem
more than expectably hard _ it seemed, even, suspiciously hard. She
fought for more than a year to persuade her administrator to give
her even 200 square feet of work space, she said, even though she
calculated that she had less space than assistant professors did in
her building, and half of what full male professors had. Finally,
she had to go above the administrator's head.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more of the same, and in 1994 she got mad. She
turned to other senior women professors to see if the resistance
she was meeting was her imagination. It was not, they said. The
committee on women was born.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, Hopkins combined her scientific work
with activities like, as she likes to put it, tiptoeing around with
tape measures to compare men's space with women's space.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, when Hopkins ran the women's committee, she
asked for nothing for herself; but later, she said, when a
colleague was running it and her own need for space became
desperate, she appealed to the dean, who, already educated by the
committee and impressed by Hopkins' ability to raise money, helped
her.
</P>
<P>
   Her work on fairness for women only multiplied the risk of her
scientific work: If her science failed, it would seem only right
that administrators had denied her support.
</P>
<P>
   But by the fall of last year, she could tell that her technique
of inserting viruses to make the fish mutate was working; on a time
line that she sketched to chronicle her progress, she wrote,
``Sept.-Oct. (EQUALS) high point of my scientific life to date _ it
worked!!!''
</P>
<P>
   To tour Hopkins' lab is to understand why space mattered so
much. The fish tanks take up room, and scale matters in the great
genomics rally that is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Christiane Nusslein-Volhard, a Nobel Prize winner from
Germany, has performed a similar gigantic screening on zebra fish,
but using chemical agents rather than viruses to produce the
mutations, so it remained tremendously difficult to isolate the
gene that had mutated.
</P>
<P>
   That ``is like knowing you're a millionaire but being unable to
find the million,'' said Dr. Phillip A. Sharp, another Nobelist
and, as chairman of the MIT biology department from 1991 to last
year, a backer of Hopkins. ``Now Nancy, at the same time she
identifies the million, she's putting a bread crumb there'' _ a tag
that marks the gene _ ``that allows her to find it quickly, and
that's what's new about her work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, he said, such work is meant to lead to an
understanding of how organs are formed that could, in turn, lead to
approaches to fight problems like kidney failure or to regenerate
neurons.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins is aiming for a sweeping picture of the genes necessary
to make an embryo, but individual members of her team and other
collaborators are focusing on specific organs _ the ear, the heart
and more. Under her deal with Amgen, the company gets a look at the
sequence of a gene before she publishes it, to see whether it is
worth patenting, she said; so far, no genes have qualified.
</P>
<P>
   She is also sharing her fish with five other laboratories that
are doing their own screenings, she said, and exploring possible
large-scale collaboration with others eager to adopt her retroviral
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Such scientific progress, in the end, is what Hopkins wants to
be known for. So the fact that the public knows her better for her
anti-discrimination work brings some interesting ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that if these 15 tenured women at MIT make the
lives of a generation of women scientists easier, that would be a
wonderful thing,'' she said. ``But my passion is really science.''
So she worries, she said, ``Will this work I've done, which is
amazing, be recognized for what it is?''
</P>
<P>
   Watson was blunter. ``The victory is hollow unless you use it to
show that you're as good and generally better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone says, `Who's doing exciting work here?' `Nancy!'
That's the real victory, doing what she wants to do, which is
science.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
