<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FERTILITY: American Sperm, as Hardy as Ever
</P>
<P>
   For some years now, scientists have been debating whether there
is any evidence to show that environmental problems may be causing
a significant decline in the quality of human sperm, posing a
threat to fertility.
</P>
<P>
   New findings by researchers at the University of Southern
California's Keck School of Medicine suggest that, at least for
American men, there may be no grounds for worry.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the journal Fertility and Sterility, the researchers
say they examined 1,347 men over three years and found that their
sperm quality was similar to that seen in men in a landmark study
59 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers made their observations after studying a group
of men who, with their wives, were seeking treatment for fertility
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a much-cited study reviewed 25 years of data involving
men who reported that they were fertile; it concluded that there
had been a significant decline in sperm concentration. The authors
theorized that this could have been the result of environmental
toxins. Later studies had conflicting results.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the group studied would be expected to have sperm
problem, Dr. Rebecca Z. Sokol, lead author of the report, said,
``We do interpret that it gives added credence to the idea that the
counts aren't changing.''
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to know how many men in infertile relationships
had sperm problems. They found that about half the group had at
least one abnormality, usually involving the sperms' ability to
propel
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Adding to the Risk for Teen-age Drivers
</P>
<P>
   The greater the number of passengers in a car driven by a 16- or
17-year-old, the higher the risk of a fatal car crash, a new study
reports. The findings appear in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, and the authors urge greater use of graduated
licensing systems that restrict young drivers' ability to carry
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author, Li-Hui Chen of the School of Public Health at
Johns Hopkins, said researchers could only speculate about
explanations, but the study noted earlier research that linked
reckless driving and peer pressure. Her study did not determine how
many of the teen-agers had been drinking or the precise role the
passengers might have played in the crashes.
</P>
<P>
   For a 16-year-old carrying one passenger, the risk of death per
10 million trips was 39 percent higher than for a 16-year-old
driving alone. With two passengers, the fatality rate was 86
percent higher than with no passengers, and with three or more
passengers, it was 2.8 percent higher than with no passengers. The
figures were similar for 17-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Car crashes are the leading cause of death among American
teen-agers. The increased risk of death reported in the study was
significant across the board, regardless of time of day or the sex
of the driver, although it was especially bad for male drivers and
late at night.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers reached their conclusions after reviewing
federal statistics on road deaths.
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION: A Lifesaver That Often Goes Unused
</P>
<P>
   In a world of heart bypass surgery, angioplasty and beta
blockers, maybe aspirin just doesn't have the high-tech cachet that
patients want.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, a new study has determined that only a
quarter of patients with heart disease are regularly taking
aspirin, even though experts agree that it helps prevent new heart
attacks and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report published in Circulation, the journal of
the American Heart Association, taking aspirin cuts heart patients'
risk of future problems  &QC; by one-third by interfering with blood
clots.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association recommends that people who have had heart
attacks and those who suffer from unstable angina take aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   But because taking aspirin can bring about its own set of
problems, among them ulcers and allergic reactions, patents are
urged to discuss the situation with their doctors first.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital, the Harvard
affiliate, found that in 1996, three-quarters of those people who
might have benefited were not taking the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the study did find that from 1980 to 1996, aspirin use
among heart patients rose to 26 percent from 5 percent. The
conclusion was based on a review of 10,942 doctor visits by people
with heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   More men than women were found to use aspirin (29 percent,
compared with &QC; 21 percent), as well as more people under age 80 (28
percent, compared with 17 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologists' patients were the most likely to report using
aspirin, with 38 percent saying they did so, compared with 12
percent for general practitioners' patients.
</P>
<P>
   STANDARDS: 6 of 13 Herbal Brands Fail a Label Test
</P>
<P>
   A test of 13 brands of a popular herbal product, Sam-e, found
that only seven had contents in keeping with the label, according
to Consumerlab.com, an online independent group that tests
supplements sold in this country. A synthetic version of a chemical
that naturally occurs in the body, Sam-e is used to treat
depression and osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The mislabeled brands had lower amounts of Sam-e and some had
far lower, said Dr. Tod Cooperman, the group's president. Cooperman
said he could not be sure whether dishonesty or simple ignorance
was behind the mislabeling. But he said it was one of the worst
cases his group had seen. Details of the testing are available at
www.consumerlab.com, the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
