<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAY-NYT &LR;      03-27 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GAMMA-RAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMMA RAY CRAFT EXITING IN BLAZE OF GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Compton Gamma Ray Observatory's days are numbered. After
nine years of orbiting Earth, the $670-million, truck-size
spacecraft has lost one of its steering instruments and so will be
brought crashing back over a remote area of the Pacific Ocean on
June 3 while it can still be controlled to avoid smashing into
populated lands.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the decision last week, officials of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration emphasized that this was a
prudent safety measure and noted that the spacecraft had already
far exceeded its expected lifetime. They acknowledged that the
imminent loss would not be popular with scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pleasant day when you have to make a conscious
decision to stop doing world-class, forefront research,'' said Dr.
Edward J. Weiler, the associate administrator for science. ``How
much science is worth the risk of even one human life?''
</P>
<P>
   Since its launching in 1991, the Compton observatory has
provided the first comprehensive view of the most powerful but
enigmatic fireworks in the universe. Gamma ray astronomy has become
a vibrant field promising new insights into cosmic evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``New discoveries made by Compton changed our view of the
universe in fundamental ways,'' said Dr. Alan Bunner, NASA's
director of cosmic studies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, astronomers lamented that the spacecraft's loss would
leave them with as many mysteries as discoveries, and they are not
likely to solve the mysteries without replacement spacecraft.
Earth's atmosphere absorbs incoming gamma rays, which is fortunate
for all living things but prevents direct ground-based
observations.
</P>
<P>
   Though invisible to the human eye, gamma rays are
electromagnetic waves with energies far greater than visible light,
ultraviolet radiation or even X-rays. They must be coming from the
most violent of cosmic phenomena: the shock waves of stellar
collisons and explosions, the rapid spin of extremely dense dead
stars, the awesome power of those gravitational sinks known as
black holes or something as yet unimagined. The sky is aglow in
gamma rays, some beaming steadily and others appearing at random in
brief bursts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Compton observatory's four telescopes has recorded
more than 2,500 of these mysterious gamma ray bursts from deep
space. Astronomers suspect that these intense bursts come from the
most powerful explosions known since the Big Bang, the theorized
explosion at the creation of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Other Compton instruments have detected and charted more than
400 examples of steady emitters of gamma rays, 10 times as many as
were previously known. The observations generally are not precise
enough to identify any objects as the sources of these radiations.
But a surprisingly large number of the sources appear to be in the
Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, as the decision to end Compton's mission was
being made, scientists reported the discovery of an apparently new
distinct group of unidentified gamma ray sources. Their findings
are described in the current Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are objects we've never seen before,'' said Dr. Neil
Gehrels, the Compton mission's chief scientist at the Goddard Space
Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., and the lead author of the journal
article. ``We can't make out what they are yet, but we know they're
strange and, boy, there's a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   These gamma ray emissions are steady and come from within the
Milky Way galaxy. Of the 170 yet-unidentified stable gamma ray
sources in the galaxy, about half lie in a narrow band along the
galactic plane. The other half, the ones in the newly recognized
class, are closer to Earth, a few hundred light-years away. They
lie off the galactic plane in the Gould Belt, a region filled with
gas clouds and massive stars.
</P>
<P>
   Here as in most other cases, astronomers are unable to determine
the nature of the phenomena producing the gamma ray emissions
because they cannot find any conspicuous objects shining in other
radiations near these locations.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary accompanying the Nature report, Dr. Isabelle A.
Grenier, an astrophysicist at the University of Paris, said that
the Compton scientists had shown that the gamma ray sources in the
Gould Belt ``are distinct in their intensity and spectral
properties from the sources in the plane'' of the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   These findings, Grenier concluded, ``provide compelling evidence
that the belt is an important birthplace of gamma ray sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists can only speculate on what is causing these powerful
radiations. They could be from jets of particles accelerated by
black holes. They could be from clusters of pulsars, the rapidly
spinning dense objects known as neutron stars. Or they could be
produced by huge stars 10 to 20 times as massive as the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Such stars may be ejecting high-velocity particles in the
surrounding space, and when the particles slam into gas atoms, they
could produce gamma rays. The Gould Belt is thought to be the
remnant of a violent event millions of years ago. As gas and young
stars expanded outward from the violent event, they collided with
the interstellar gases, creating shock waves bringing about the
birth of massive stars and perhaps black holes and pulsars.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists may have to wait five years for some answers to the
mysteries uncovered by the Compton observatory. The most ambitious
replacement spacecraft, the Gamma Ray Large Area Space Telescope,
or Glast, is to be launched in 2005. But astronomers pointed out
that Glast would lack the broad survey capabilities of the Compton
observatory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1706EST &QL; 
