A9364 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DIGISCENTS-HOWITWORKS     03-27 0172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGISCENTS-HOWITWORKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOW DIGISCENTS' ISMELL WORKS  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just like a printer, DigiScents' iSmell is a small device that
attaches via cable to your PC.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of graphics software that instructs a printer how to mix
red, blue and yellow inks to create the right shade of cherry red,
the DigiScents software tells the iSmell how to blend up to 128
``fragrance elements'' or ``primary odors'' to synthesize the scent
of cherries.
</P>
<P>
   But for the software to know what cherries, or anything else,
``smells'' like, someone at the firm has to digitize that specific
scent by analyzing its molecular structure and sensory properties.
This information is used to create a kind of recipe for the iSmell
to generate that odor.
</P>
<P>
   DigiScents says it has digitized about 1,000 scents so far, but
its fragrance elements potentially could generate as many as 10 to
the 128th power of odors _ far more scents than the most
sophisticated nose could recognize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1707EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
