<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9365 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PARALYSIS-CHIP-NY     03-27 0258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PARALYSIS-CHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROCHIP HELPS A PARALYZED MAN WALK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)  (Science Times) 
(af) 
By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With an electronic microchip implanted in his back, Marc Merger,
of Strasbourg, France, is now able to take a few halting steps for
the first time in 10 years. Merger, 38, had been immobilized since
his spinal cord was severed in a car crash. In a project involving
six European nations, the IBM Corp. and French scientists, Merger's
leg muscles were stimulated by electronic charges fired by a
program stored in the chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first step was very difficult _ to get those muscles
moving after all that time,'' said Dr. Charles Lebesnerais, head of
IBM's laboratory in Corbeil-Essonnes, France. ``The goal,'' he
said, ``was to give people the possibility of standing and walking
a little in their apartment. Merger will have to have a great deal
of training, and we still face problems in programming the chip
with all the intelligence that goes into walking.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time paralyzed patients have been assisted
in ``step'' walking, in which leg muscles are made to respond to
electric stimuli rather than to brain impulses.
</P>
<P>
   But medical researchers said the effort to program the proper
muscle movements of walking and the electronic impulses that
trigger them was laudable. ``If 10 years down the road our efforts
to repair the spinal cord itself are not successful, a patient
might opt for this,'' said Dr. Evan Snyder of the Harvard Medical
School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STRESS-HORMONE-COX     03-27 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRESS-HORMONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researchers find stress, blood pressure link
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBORN, Ohio _ The researchers weren't poring over data or
peering into microscopes when they made their discovery earlier
this month. They were just talking in a room where there were
laboratory mice when one of the researchers dropped a notebook.
</P>
<P>
   The noise when it landed was loud enough to startle the mice,
certainly. Mice ordinarily respond to that kind of stress with a
sudden surge in blood pressure, the same way a person would react
to an unseen firecracker going off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we noticed in these animals there was no change in their
blood pressure,'' says Mariana Morris, a Wright State University
professor who chairs the medical school's department of
pharmacology and toxicology.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious reason probably jolted her own blood pressure. These
mice had been genetically engineered to knock a hormone out of
their systems, called oxytocin. It is associated with maternal
behavior, usually thought of as a ``women's hormone,'' but in both
mice and humans, males and females have equal amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very exciting,'' says Morris, who confirmed the
observation with data and plans to publish the finding with her
research associates. ``It's the first time, using a genetic model,
that anyone has been able to completely remove the effect of stress
on blood pressure. This could eventually give us insight into the
whole scheme by which stress affects the cardiovascular system.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris has spent her career studying how the brain regulates
blood pressure, and the implications that has on high blood
pressure. Hypertension, as it's called, affects as many as 25
percent of the American population, putting them at increased risk
for heart disease and stroke without offering symptoms to warn
them. Scientists have figured out how to control hypertension in
some people with drugs that act on the brain, but Morris says the
process that causes it still has not been fully discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The field has changed dramatically in the last five to 10 years.
Advances in biotechnology have made her work possible by providing
ways to delete or add certain proteins in animals by changing their
genes. ``This allowed us to ask the critical question,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a ``different environment'' for women in research, she
says. Morris came to Wright State from Wake Forest University in
1997 as a department head, welcoming the chance to expand and
develop the department and its research. One thing she established
was a varied team of experts in genetics, molecular biology and
pharmacology. Another was the creation of one of the first labs to
focus on how genes influence cardiovascular physiology.
</P>
<P>
   She also supplied the lab with instruments that could measure an
animal's blood pressure without disturbing it, enabling the
researchers to continuously monitor conscious mice. ``Not many labs
are looking at that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The continuous measurements enable scientists to look at how
certain genes affect the whole body, from food and water intake to
kidney and heart function, and also to examine why heart attacks,
for example, are more likely to happen in the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   And without the constant monitoring, Morris says, the
researchers might not have noticed how stress didn't upset the mice
without oxytocin.
</P>
<P>
   Research isn't day after day of forehead-slapping moments
shouting, ``Eureka!,'' but even when the results are more
incremental, Morris says, ``You're always discovering something
new. I think we have the best job in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Morris' work has explored the impact of stress and salt
intake on the brain functions that affect blood pressure. She has
looked extensively at renin and angiotensin, hormones critical in
regulating blood pressure. They're the target of some drugs for
treating hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is interesting that some animals are very sensitive to salt
intake,'' she says. We already know that's the case with humans.
Some people can reduce their high blood pressure simply by taking
salt out of their diets. It also turns out that giving salt to
salt-sensitive mice makes their blood pressure all the more
responsive to stress.
</P>
<P>
   This information could eventually make it easier to pinpoint not
only which people can't tolerate salt, but also why they can't.
Morris says it's a step to learning how changing a gene _ through
new drugs if not new genes _ could change a person's reaction to
salt or to stressful conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to interpret results from the data is the most fun part
of the job,'' Morris says. ``You have to emphasize to students that
any finding is valid, even if it's against whatever dogma you're
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important part of research, says Morris, is picking the
right question to ask. In the case of oxytocin, it was part of an
endocrine system that blood-pressure researchers have largely
overlooked. But Morris says ``I'd always been interested in the
oxytocin axis'' because any kind of stress causes oxytocin levels
to rise. The next logical thing was to look at what happens to an
animal without it.''
</P>
<P>
   She resists calling herself an explorer, but she agrees the
human body is as uncharted a frontier as the globe was 500 years
ago. ``When you're faced with the problems of how little we know
about the human body, about how drugs work, it gives you a sense of
awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Morris think it's more than a coincidence that it took
a woman researcher to zero in on this ``women's hormone.'' She's
just a scientist, like her father the Texas oil chemist and her
grandfather, the family doctor she used to visit at her dad's
childhood home in Dayton. Among Morris and her four sisters, she's
one of two with Ph.D.s and another one's a physician.
</P>
<P>
   In the boys' club that is scientific research, she says, ``I
just had to become a member of the boys' club.'' Although the
situation is improving, men still tend to play the leadership roles
nationally, and a recent study showed they still dominate medical
school department chairs out of proportion to their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only about five or six women (out of 125) chairing
anatomy departments,'' says Jane Scott, who heads Wright State's
anatomy department and joins Morris among the medical school's four
women in senior management. But at least it's no longer common for
women researchers to be asked when they're going to start a family
and how much money their husbands make, as it was when Scott was
beginning in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to look at you as a gamble,'' Scott says. ``They'd
invest this money to educate you and you would drop out of the
career track. Now people realize we can have both families and
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   So whatever prejudice still exists hasn't stopped Morris from
helping to organize a national conference on gene therapy in Boston
this June. That's an area that excites her because she believes
gene therapy might some day be used for controlling blood pressure
in humans, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way to there from the mice in her laboratory, but as
Morris puts it, ``First you have to understand how the genes
normally control physiology.'' That's her job.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
