u a BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-NYT &LR;      03-27 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK HOLES SUSPECTED AT GALAXIES' CORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers at Ohio State University have photographed feeding
frenzies at the hearts of a score of galaxies, images of gas and
dust draining into what may be black holes like water spiraling
down a bathtub drain.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard W. Pogge and Paul Martini used an infrared camera on
the Hubble Space Telescope to take pictures of the centers of 24
bright nearby galaxies suspected of harboring black holes and
combined them with visible-light images in order to compensate for
the brightness of the stars and to bring out the faint dust clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting images of 20 of the galaxies show dust swirling
around a center where, presumably, a black hole is gobbling it up.
</P>
<P>
   The research, Pogge said, will give theorists something to work
on. ``Nobody's ever done a systematic assay of the centers of these
galaxies,'' he said. ``We're seeing structures we would expect for
what the theorists tell us would be plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   Among many questions, Pogge said, is why material falls into
these black holes and not into others (including the black hole
that is thought to be at the center of the Milky Way). The spiral
arms of the clouds may be evidence of some kind of shock that
occurs that robs the dust of enough of its orbital energy so that
it starts to fall inward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
