<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-ECCENTRICS-TEX     03-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ECCENTRICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'M OK, YOU'RE ... ODD: A GUIDE TO ECCENTRICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if there were not enough to sort out in life, now comes this:
How do we know if we are merely odd, truly eccentric or completely
insane?
</P>
<P>
   And is eccentricity a steppingstone to total madness?
</P>
<P>
   Those are the questions raised in the recently released book
``The Mammoth Book of Oddballs and Eccentrics'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf
Publishers, $11.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``As (normal) human behavior ranges from rigid conformity at one
end of the scale to utterly bizarre nonconformity at the other, how
do we know whether someone is eccentric, quietly neurotic or
completely barking mad?'' asks author Karl Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw sets up a three-tier categorization of weird behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Most extreme is madness, which is behavior that would be
considered insane no matter which era. It may have eccentricity as
one of its outward signs, but it is different. It is often tragic
and hopeless. In this category, we could file the chilling example
of Jeffrey Dahmer.
</P>
<P>
   Next is eccentricity, which according to Shaw is compulsive,
usually with the eccentric entirely unaware or indifferent to the
fact that his or her behavior seems weird.
</P>
<P>
   Eccentricity flourishes in tolerant environments, thus often is
the hallmark of the powerful or the secluded. With tolerance as a
prerequisite, eccentricity occurs more frequently among men than
among women, Shaw writes. Under the category of eccentrics, think
of Matthew McConnaughey playing the bongos naked in his Austin-area
home.
</P>
<P>
   Subcategories exist. On one level, we have those who are
blissfully unaware. On the other, we have those who carefully
cultivate their eccentricities. Salvador Dali's walking his ocelot
on a leash is considered by Shaw to be a studied form of
eccentricity, kind of a funny public relations attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes mere oddness, a kind of going against the flow of
current decorum or trends. Think of the unisex bathroom on TV's
``Ally McBeal'' (although the cast itself is a study in
eccentricity).
</P>
<P>
   Shaw amasses 483 pages describing the acts of history's
dysfunctional rulers, strange scientists, peculiar performers and
unhinged politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Here, from Shaw's books, are several comforting examples that
may make you feel you aren't so odd yourself:
</P>
<P>
   Legal eccentrics: Texas state District Judge Charles Hearn of
Houston, who signed a death warrant and next to his signature drew
a happy face. A defense attorney in 1993 complained, saying the
happy face was akin to saying ``Have a Nice Death,'' but Hearn said
he had always included happy faces next to his signature as an
expression of his Christian beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Also: In 1972, a Los Angeles judge awarded $4,500 in damages to
the owner of an elephant called Bimbo. The judge ruled that as a
result of injuries received in a road accident, Bimbo had
completely lost interest in dancing and water skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Religious eccentric: The Shrine of the Weeping Shirley MacLaine
is situated in the Beta Israel Temple in Los Angeles. It was
inspired by a vision a man had while traveling in the actress's
private jet. He said he saw a large photograph of him with
MacLaine, and she was shedding tears.
</P>
<P>
   Creative eccentrics: Gustav Mahler (1860-1911) was famous for
his funeral marches. He wrote his first when he was 6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand Flocan (1800-66) made it his life's ambition to render
the French Civil Code more accessible by turning all 22,891
articles, statutes, amendments and annotations into a 120,000-word
poem. He died in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican entertainer Ramon Barrero played the world's smallest
harmonica until 1994, when in midperformance he inhaled a D-minor
and accidentally choked to death.
</P>
<P>
   Eccentric genius: Alexander Graham Bell tried to teach his dog
to talk. He also kept his windows permanently covered to keep out
the ``harmful rays'' of the full moon.
</P>
<P>
   Political eccentric: Charles Watson-Wentworth served as prime
minister of England during the reign of King George III. He was an
eccentric gambler who once organized a race from Norwich, England,
to London between five geese and five turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Also, U.S. President Chester A. Arthur owned 80 pairs of
trousers, changed clothes several times a day and was known as
``Elegant Arthur.''
</P>
<P>
   Criminally eccentric: In Toronto, Canada, in 1993, one man beat
another to death after an argument got out of hand over which of
them had the longer criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a German filmgoer was beaten to death by ushers in a
Bonn cinema because he had brought his own popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
