<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9377 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CORAL-REEFS-ART-N     03-27 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CORAL-REEFS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS DEVISE A PLAN TO RESCUE CORAL REEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN FILES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government has issued a long-term plan
to save coral reefs along the coast of the United States and its
territories, setting aside many sites as ecological preserves over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for 20 percent of all coral reefs in
American-controlled waters to be designated ecological preserves by
2010, protecting them from pollution, fishing and other activity
that could harm the reefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting 20 percent of all U.S. reefs and other decisive
actions called for in the new plan is crucial because two-thirds of
the world's reefs may be dying,'' said D. James Baker, the
undersecretary for oceans and atmosphere at the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``If current conditions continue,'' Baker said, ``an alarming 70
percent of the world's reefs may be gone by 2050. This rapid
decline represents a serious threat to businesses, consumers,
communities and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Corals are tiny plant-like animals that thrive only in clean,
clear water with plenty of sunlight. They gradually build coral
skeletons that form the elaborate reefs that then become home to
thousands of fish, lobsters, sea turtles and other species.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has about 6,500 square miles of coral reefs,
mostly off Florida, Texas, Hawaii and around American territories
in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The reefs are particularly vulnerable because they prosper in
shallow water near shore, which exposes them to pollution from
marine debris and chemicals, overfishing and destructive actions
like fishing with cyanide and dynamite, vessel grounding and
anchoring, and even global climate change.
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget contains the first federal money directed
toward saving the coral reefs: $6 million to the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration and $5 million to the Interior
Department. President Clinton has requested $25 million for the
2001 budget.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate effort, the National Park Foundation, a nonprofit
partner of the National Park Service, is studying the effectiveness
of transplanting healthy fragments of coral to damaged reefs in the
waters of the Virgin Island National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to jump-start reef recovery by transplanting
healthy, naturally occuring, broken-off pieces of fast-growing
coral species to new locations where they are more likely to
survive,'' said Ginger Garrison, the project's principle
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Coral reefs and their ecosystems support billions of dollars of
tourism each year, federal officials said, with over a billion
dollars generated in the Florida Keys alone. The reefs' value of
the reefs for commercial and recreational fishing is nearly $200
million a year. In all, reef-related activities generate as much as
$375 billion annually, the Commerce Department says.
</P>
<P>
   They are also considered as possible sources of new medicines.
</P>
<P>
   And, they are natural buffers along shorelines protecting
against erosion and property damage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ecological preserves, the plan sets goals for
mapping all coral reefs in the United States by 2009. The oceanic
administration also wants to create a national monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
   But commercial and recreational fishing interests, concerned
about fishing bans, are seeking alternatives, possibly including,
catch-and-release policies in protected areas.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Cameron, a tournament fisherman from Morehead City, N.C.,
said a ban on fishing and other activities would be too extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need to protect the resources,'' said Cameron, who
fishes extensively along the coasts of Virginia, North Carolina,
Florida and Texas. ``But a ban would be devastating for the people
who fish and dive on the reefs. It would absolutely devastate the
Keys.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger T. Rufe, president of the Center for Marine Conservation
in Washington, applauded the action, but he said that more needed
to be done to combat water pollution, including legislation that
would provide sufficient money for a plan ``to ensure complete
protection and conservation'' of coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sobel, a program director at the center, pointed out that
for a resource that provides many billions of dollars of revenue,
the money proposed in the plan was ``limited and shortsighted,''
only a first step toward appreciating ``the real value of the coral
reefs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
