<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MUBARAK-TECH-0328-COX     03-27 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUBARAK-TECH-0328-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MUBARAK: EGYPT OPEN FOR HIGH -TECH BUSINESS
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERNDON, Va. - Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Monday said he
wants to establish his country as a leader in the Middle East's
push into the new, Internet-driven economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this major crossroads in human history, the peoples of the
Middle East cannot be by-passed or marginalized,'' Mubarak said.
``They are determined to be integrated in the global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of a week-long visit to Washington D.C., the Egyptian
leader visited the high-tech hotbed of Northern Virginia. Speaking
at a luncheon attended by hundreds of tech industry executives and
local congressmen, he called the United States a ``most qualified
and trusted partner'' in business matters, and urged Americans to
strengthen economic ties to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   These ties have already worked well for Egypt's Middle East
neighbor, Israel, which has won global recognition as a high-tech
hotbed.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mubarak pointed to several reasons why his country
would make a good home for technology-driven companies.
</P>
<P>
   First, ``our society has become aware of the need for
information technology'' and is eager to use it. A high-tech
business that invests there will not only find eager customers, but
will gain access to a larger regional market. ``Egypt is a gateway
to the Middle East and Africa,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Egypt is rich in human resources,'' he said. Last
year, colleges there graduated 154,000 people. ``These graduates
are the most important components of a successful information
technology industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak also said his country offers packages of tax breaks and
other incentives to investors.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, he noted that the government is creating national
databases and information networks to better link the country to
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to progress is long and difficult,'' he said. ``But
we are lucky; we have the resources and we have the will and we
have the friends'' in the United States to help make technology
blossom in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   (Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
