<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9383 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BUCHANAN-AZR &LR;      03-27 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL PAT BUCHANAN'S MESSAGE FIND APPROVAL IN ARIZONA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUBEN NAVARETTE  
 (EDITORS: STORY WILL ALSO MOVE IN THE ``K'' CATEGORY.) 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ With John McCain off the bus and back in the
Senate, and George W. Bush back in Texas and off to try to avenge
his father's 1992 defeat, reporters with time on their hands are
musing about whether Bush can woo McCain voters.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Bush had better hurry. Someone else has his eye on them.
Patrick J. Buchanan, the fearless storyteller, is known for
stirring the pot, challenging convention and going against the
grain. Now pursuing the presidential nomination of the Reform
Party, Buchanan is targeting the followers of McCain, who built a
presidential campaign on stirring the pot, challenging convention,
and going against the grain. A recent ``Newsweek'' poll suggests
that McCain voters are up for grabs. Only 41 percent of McCain
voters said they would support Bush, while 48 percent sooner would
back Al Gore. So much for the allure of campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alibi Al'' outdid himself when questioned about 45 illegal
phone calls made from his office. Gore, who has denied a
``controlling legal authority'' over the calls, told investigators
that he drank iced tea during briefings and could have been in the
men's room when the law was discussed: The vice president's defense
has gone from no legal control to no bladder control.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's control over McCain supporters is just as weak. Chaos
brings opportunity, and Buchanan sees in such chaos an opportunity
to market himself as the reformer in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan began the marketing campaign at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government. Gone was the humorless, combative and
intolerant firebrand who in 1992 declared the country engaged in a
``culture war.'' In his place, stood a kinder and gentler Pat
Buchanan eager to discuss what he called the ``only real issue'':
campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Like a boxer alternating between rights and lefts, Buchanan
rattled off abuses by both parties. Moving from Maria Tsia to the
Wyly brothers to the Buddist Temple, he confused the audience,
which must have felt like booing one minute and cheering the next.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Washington is hooked on money, and neither party
can kick the addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Beltway party is going to drain this swamp, because to
them it isn't a swamp at all, but a protected wetland and their
natural habitat,'' he told the audience. ``They swim in it, feed in
it and spawn in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan called for campaign contributions to be voluntary and
come from individuals, not corporations or unions. He also said
members of Congress should have to raise half of their funds within
their districts.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of students tried to use Buchanan's own words against
him with questions about things he had written. That was easy. The
guy's paper trail is a four-lane highway. Self-identified Democrats
who in 1992 excused Bill Clinton's marijuana use and draft-dodging
as youthful indiscretions rushed to judge Buchanan for words
scribbled 20 years ago. Buchanan didn't flinch, equivocate or claim
that he was in the bathroom. Asked about a column in which he wrote
that ethnic Catholics and Christians are underrepresented and
discriminated against at Harvard, Buchanan tossed the grenade back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply because you're at Harvard does not exempt you from the
same kind of rules and regulations that Harvard lovingly imposes
upon the rest of America,'' he said. ``Pat Buchanan is not a
beloved figure in America, but neither is Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan didn't take any guff from the Ivy Leaguers. And they
loved it. Given that a recent poll by the school's Shorenstein
Center found that 87 percent of respondents believed politicians
will say anything, Buchanan scored points for saying what he
believed and challenging listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Who does that sound like? No wonder Buchanan thinks he has a
shot at McCain supporters. If America really wants straight talk,
then the talk doesn't get any straighter than coming from Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The inference will be unsettling to McCain, who has been a harsh
critic of Buchanan. The lads can't even agree on World War II.
After Buchanan raised the question of whether the United States
needed to go to war against Hitler, McCain, whose grandfather
commanded operations in the Pacific, fumed. Asked by a reporter if
he thought Buchanan should leave the Republican Party, McCain said,
``Mr. Buchanan has already left my Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   When Buchanan did leave, McCain wished him good riddance with
the words of a country music song: ``Thank God and Greyhound,
you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The similarities, and differences, between the two men raise a
question: If Buchanan gets the Reform Party nomination, how will
his third-party candidacy go over in McCain's back yard of Arizona?
In a state divided into haves and have-not, Buchanan's populist
reform message may play well with those who feel disconnected from
the political process, like the poor, the young, and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast, says a former Arizonan who attended Buchanan's
speech. Anthony Chavez, a 1997 graduate of Arizona State University
and now a public-policy student at the Kennedy School, acknowledges
that Buchanan's message of reform, limited government and
protection for the working class might appeal to some in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Buchanan's makeover as a reformer can't cover up
his views on immigration, English-only or affirmative action _
views that will hurt him with Arizona Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   As will his criticism of government: To a lot of Hispanics,
government is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government helps people achieve their goals, and Buchanan's
anti-government rhetoric isn't likely to help him with those kinds
of voters,'' Chavez said. True enough. Buchanan's dug his grave
with some folks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Arizona and across the country, voters aren't as
easily shocked as they used to be. They're tired of politics as
usual and of the usual politicians. As McCain proved, they don't
want pandering, but honesty and leadership. They want a change from
Clinton-Gore, but they may not be ready for another George Bush.
They do want choices. After years of going against the grain,
Patrick Buchanan now may be coming along at just the right time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Navarrette Jr., a former Republic columnist and author of
``A Darker Shade of Crimson: Odyssey of a Harvard Chicano''
(Bantam), is a student in Public Administration at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government. Most recently, he is a contributor
to the bestselling ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' book series.
``Chicken Soup for the Writer's Soul'' is due out in June. He can
be reached at www.navarrette.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
