<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9385 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      03-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: THIS FEATURE IS ALSO MOVING IN
 &UR; THE ``E'' CATEGORY) &QL; 
Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE TIPPING POINT'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Malcolm Gladwell (Little, Brown, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were skeptical when we picked this up, having become adept
over the years at detecting books that aren't about anything
(they're like the emperor's new clothes _ they try to dazzle you,
but there's nothing to them). It wasn't long, however, before we
were hooked. If the premise does grow a bit thin _ Gladwell sounds
at times like an author inventing reasons to rattle on _ for the
most part it is thought-provoking and presented with an appealing
eye toward popular culture. The ``tipping point'' of the title is
the moment at which something becomes an epidemic, a word Gladwell
applies to fashion trends, fads, crime statistics, the success of a
bestselling book. His examination of how this happens is
dumbfoundingly interesting, and it includes discussion of the
resurgence of Hush Puppies (the shoes) in the mid-1990s, the
phenomenon of ``Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' (the book)
when it was released in paperback in 1998, and the ``word-of-mouth
epidemic'' created by Paul Revere (the silversmith) in 1775.
Gladwell works for ``The New Yorker,'' in which the tipping-point
theory made its first appearance. &QL; 
 &UR; ``I WILL BEAR WITNESS: A DIARY OF THE NAZI
 &UR; YEARS, 1942-1945'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Victor Klemperer (Random House, $29.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Jewish rumors: There had been mass murders in Poland in
the course of withdrawals. On the other hand, Jews had been allowed
out of Hungary after a Hungarian agreement with the USA. We
consider Point 1 very likely; Point 2 can be correct only if
Hungary has broken away from Germany. Did it? We are tapping in the
dark.'' Klemperer, the son of a Berlin rabbi, wrote this in his
diary during the hot, humid summer of 1944, as he and his wife
lived through the Nazi terror in Dresden. His remarkable diaries
(the first volume, which covers 1933 to 1941, was published in
1998) re-create the confusion, fear, humiliation and emotional
claustrophobia that ruled the lives of German Jews. Included in
this volume are rumors of the crimes at Auschwitz and other camps,
the fragile link to survival that Klemperer's marriage to an
``Aryan'' afforded him and an account of the bombing of Dresden.
It's a riveting and invaluable glimpse of what life was like for a
Jew living in Nazi Germany. Klemperer died in 1960. &QL; 
 &UR; ``A GARDEN IN LUCCA'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Paul Gervais (Hyperion, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone left in America who does not own a villa in the
hills of Tuscany? Certainly the American literati have established
a presence there, the better to write books that make the rest of
us back home weak-kneed with envy. A prerequisite of this new life
in Italy, it seems, is that the villa in question must need work _
Frances Mayes and her boyfriend renovated theirs in her book
``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' and now Gervais (his novel
``Extraordinary People'' was nominated for a PEN/Faulkner award in
1991) and his companion do it here. The twist Gervais offers is
that the huge house they bought in 1982 in the small town of Massa
Macinaia in Lucca province came with its own huge, run-down garden.
This was new to Gervais, who grew up in New England and who knew
nothing of gardening, so he learned on the job, making lots of
mistakes until he hit upon a plan. We know he was successful,
because his book opens with a California horticultural foundation
booking his garden for its next tour. That's right _ foundation
members traveled 7,000 miles to see it. This is not as seductive as
the Mayes book, but it will make you jealous just the same.  &QL; 
 &UR; ``GOOD BREEDING'' &QL; 
 &UR; Photographs by Yann Arthus-Bertrand (Abrams, $49.50)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do not laugh. No, do not laugh. Yes, those are pigs on the cover
and they are handsome devils, don't you think? All of the animals
in this book are handsome, because they are bred to be.
Arthus-Bertrand offers grand portraits of prizewinning domestic
livestock (sheep, cattle, goats, horses and swine) posed with their
very proud owners, breeders or trainers. The creatures are
astonishing. They are also a little _ well, odd, to the untrained
eye. Huge in just about every respect, if you know what we mean.
Dauntingly larger than the human beings who stand with them
(there's a Blonde D'Aquitaine bull on Page 47 that looks like it
could take out Manhattan). Muscled, veined, groomed and dandy, they
pose as if they are fully aware of just how excellent they are.
This is, in case you have not surmised it by now, a strange but
endearing book. You might be tempted to laugh (but don't) as you
look through it, but you quickly get caught up in the spirit of the
thing. Except when you see the pigs. You can laugh at them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
