<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LAND-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI INTERIOR MINISTER PLEDGES TO RETURN LAND TO ARAB VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Interior Minister Natan Sharansky announced Monday
that he would restore to an Israeli Arab village part of its land
that had been taken to develop a neighboring Jewish town.
</P>
<P>
   The move was the first of its kind, and it has potentially
far-reaching implications. The action contradicts decades-old
policies under which Arab-owned land had often been expropriated to
build Jewish communities.
</P>
<P>
   The step was intended ``to strengthen the democratic character
of the state of Israel and to provide equal opportunity to all
citizens,'' Sharansky, a former human rights campaigner who had
been jailed in the Soviet Union, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the move said that it set a dangerous precedent and
that it would encourage Israeli Arab villages and towns across the
country to demand that land lost to neighboring Jewish communities
be returned to them.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was another step toward equality for the 1 million
Arab citizens in Israel. This month, the Supreme Court ruled that
an Israeli Arab couple could not be barred from a community that
had been built just for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky said he had decided to restore 250 acres of vacant
land that had been taken from Kafr Kassem, northeast of Tel Aviv.
The land was seized decades ago for what were described as security
reasons but was later turned over to the neighboring Jewish town of
Rosh Haayin for an industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
   After residents of Kafr Kassem had pressed to recover the land,
an Interior Ministry committee recommended in 1997 that the area be
restored to the village. But the interior minister at the time, Eli
Suissa of the Orthodox Shas Party, did not carry out the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky said that he had decided to restore the land after the
mayor of Rosh Haayin had rejected a proposal that the area be
jointly developed by both communities as a shared industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
   Kafr Kassem could now use the site to set up its own industrial
zone and benefit from the income, Sharansky said, adding that his
decision was meant to promote ``social justice'' and to help
``close gaps'' between Arabs and Jews in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Yigal Yosef of Rosh Haayin warned that returning the area
to Kafr Kassem would lead other Arab communities to demand that
their boundaries be redrawn at the expense of neighboring Jewish
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asserting historic rights, but if we accept this claim
the whole country will be theirs,'' Yosef said. ``The whole
ideological basis of setting up a Jewish state is slipping away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Community leaders in Kafr Kassem, the site of a massacre of 49
villagers by Israeli border guards who were enforcing a curfew in
1956, welcomed Sharansky's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State of Israel owes a special debt to Kafr Kassem because
of the tragedy of the massacre,'' the chairman of the local
council, Sami Issa, said. ``I hope this will be the start of a new
policy of planning for the Arab sector that will solve its
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli Arab towns and villages are short of land for
expansion. Large areas have been expropriated over the decades for
Jewish communities.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Abdullah Nimr Darwish, a leader of the Islamic Movement in
Israel who lives in Kafr Kassem, said Sharansky's past as a Soviet
dissident had made him sensitive to the needs of Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person who suffered repression,'' Darwish said, ``he
knows that injustice breeds hatred.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
