</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS CHALLENGE TO WITHHOLDING WELFARE FROM LEGAL
IMMIGRANTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill.)   (Eds: Will be updated.) 
(nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday refused to hear a
challenge to portions of the 1996 welfare law that made legal
immigrants ineligible for various kinds of federal welfare
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The justices turned down an appeal by the city of Chicago, which
was supported by New York and other cities, of a federal appeals
court's ruling that the disqualification did not violate the
immigrants' constitutional right to equal protection because it was
not ``wholly irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the overhaul of the welfare system, the provisions
aimed specifically at immigrants received relatively little
attention, but greatly angered officials of the cities where,
because of sizeable populations of impoverished or elderly
foreign-born residents, the elimination of food stamps,
Supplemental Security Income and other benefits would be most
sharply felt.
</P>
<P>
   The full impact of the 1996 law will be delayed because, after
initially eliminating supplemental security income and food stamps
for noncitizens, Congress the next year restored benefits for some
immigrants who were in the country when the law took effect on Aug.
22, 1996. That shifted the impact to those who arrived after that
date.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law also imposed a 5 year waiting period before
noncitizens could receive Medicaid benefits or Temporary Assistance
for Needy Families, the new program that replaced the cash grants
of the old welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   The law, and the case challenging it, had nothing to do with the
debate over illegal immigration. All the provisions at issue apply
to lawful permanent residents, admitted into the country with the
right to remain and to work.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, Chicago said the federal government ``is solely
responsible for the presence of lawful noncitizens in the country''
and ``should not be allowed to shirk all responsibility for their
welfare.'' Chicago said the law had the effect of an ``unfunded
mandate,'' while New York City, in its brief supporting Chicago's
appeal, said the 1996 law ``is really about shifting the financial
and social burdens of immigration to state and local governments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
