<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9411 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-NANOTUBES-ART-NYT     03-27 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NANOTUBES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MICROSCOPIC FOREST BLOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6, NYT13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about a fast-growth forest: A research team at Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute in Troy, N.Y., has created tiny ``trees''
using flashes of extreme heat to deposit carbon atoms in piles on a
graphite surface.
</P>
<P>
   The structures, which average about one one-hundredth of an inch
in height and can be as narrow as five-millionths of an inch in
diameter, are made by a process called chemical vapor deposition,
in which a graphite electrode is rapidly heated in a pressurized
atmosphere of methane and helium.
</P>
<P>
   As the temperature rises to between 2,000 and 4,000 degrees
Fahrenheit, carbon atoms from the methane are deposited directly on
the surface of the electrode, forming nodules that build into
towers through successive heating cycles. The effect is something
like making a sand castle by dribbling wet sand into a spire.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical vapor deposition is a well-known technique, but other
researchers have generally used metal particles on the electrode as
a catalyst to promote deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with using a catalyst is that you always end up
with a metal particle in the structure,'' said Dr. Pulickel Ajayan,
an associate professor of materials science and engineering at the
institute and the leader of the research team. Their work was
reported in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Ajayan said he and his colleagues had been looking for a way to
grow the structures without using a catalyst, and through
experimentation came up with the flash heating technique. ``We
found that by tuning the conditions, we could create these
fascinating morphologies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As carbon falls on the surface of an electrode, Ajayan said, it
tends to form islandlike structures. Under more normal heating
conditions, the islands link to create a thin continuous layer.
``But if you do it fast enough, there's no real time for these
islands to merge,'' Ajayan said. ``The only way to grow is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they can be observed only with electron microscopes,
the trees are still larger than nanotubes, those cylindrical
molecules of carbon that have been the subject of so much recent
research. Nonetheless, the trees may have some of the same
potential applications, if they can be produced on a commercial
scale. The trees have hollow portions and are porous, Ajayan said,
making them good candidates for gas storage and for use in
displays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
