<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A potent low-pressure system will drag a cold front across New
England on Tuesday, bringing a steady rain to parts of Maine and
northern New Hampshire. Farther south, a second surge of cold air
will cross the Middle Atlantic states. Ahead of this chilly air, a
line of showers and a few thunderstorms will develop, with small
hail and gusty winds likely. Behind this second cold front,
flurries and snow showers will fall in the northern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms, some of which will be strong, will
develop in the Red River Valley later Tuesday as low pressure and
its attendant warm front push onto the southern Plains. Farther
south, it will be very warm in Texas under mostly sunny skies.
Mountain snow and valley rain showers will accompany a cold front
as it sweeps across the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WINTER'S COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the mercury soared to a record 58 degrees in
Marquette, Mich., as southerly breezes directed warm air to the
Canadian border. March 2000 has been warm in the Great Lakes,
especially in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, where Marquette has
set temperature records on a quarter of the days this month. But
Monday, the warmth was in retreat as winter made a comeback.
Wind-driven snow accumulated several inches at Marquette. A cold
low-pressure system will hold steady over Ontario on Tuesday,
insuring further delivery of snow showers and cold air to Northern
Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
