<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-SALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOBBY LOBBY BUYS FORMER AMBASSADOR UNIVERSITY CAMPUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A last-minute buyer purchased the 2,220-acre Ambassador
University campus in East Texas last week, pre-empting an April 4
auction where the assets would have been sold piecemeal to the
highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The wooded campus, which includes dorms and classrooms as well
as an airstrip, radio station and two lakes, had been closed since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Worldwide Church of God announced during the weekend that
Hobby Lobby, an Oklahoma City retailer, bought the campus and will
lease it to the Institute of Basic Life Principles.
</P>
<P>
   That organization is led by Bill Gothard, a minister from
Oakbrook, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The sale price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled that we were able to sell the campus intact,''
said Bernard Schnippert, chief financial officer of the Worldwide
Church of God.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gothard's ministry, Schnippert said, ``We don't know
about anything about them except in our dealings with them in this
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Gothard's ministry plans to offer an orphanage on campus, as
well as to expand its program of training men to respond to
emergencies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency response teams have responded to tornadoes in
Oklahoma and Arkansas and the 1998 floods in Seguin and New
Braunfels, said Maj. Steve Nix, who works with the response teams
in Watersmeet, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we first looked at this property a little over two
years ago,'' Nix said. ``We currently have this program up here
near the Wisconsin border and we had a need for more space.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, Gothard has conducted seminars for more than
2.5 million people, according to the ministry's Web site. He also
created the ``Character First'' curriculum that has been taught to
businesses and schools, with religious references omitted.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have said that he teaches blind obedience to
authority figures and instructs women to be subservient to men.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Hobby Lobby couldn't be reached for comment, but
Nix said that the retailer has helped the institute previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've just been a real friend to the ministry,'' Nix said.
``The owners are strong, committed Christian men. It was just
something they chose to do with their money. There was no
solicitation.''
</P>
<P>
   By next fall, Nix said the institute will have about 300
students and staff at the campus. It should expand in upcoming
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale came after the Worldwide Church of God dramatically
changed its views after the death of its founder in 1986. Moving
from beliefs in two Gods and a doctrine that they were the only
true Christian church, the Worldwide Church now holds beliefs
similar to evangelical denominations and has been accepted by most
of those groups.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
