<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADONNA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADONNA MIA! PREGNANT POP STAR PUSHES THE ENVELOPE _ AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1985, when Madonna paraded through the video for her hit,
``Like a Virgin,'' often touching herself, it was OK.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, when she played the role of a stripper in the
clip for ``Open Your Heart,'' it was, again, OK. Same goes for her
steamy ``Sex'' book. Lesbian pictures of Madonna? OK.
</P>
<P>
   She's the mother of one (Lourdes, 3), and now at 41 _ getting up
there for motherhood _ she announced she has another on the way.
She is not married to either Carlos Leon, her former personal
trainer and father of Lourdes, or Guy Ritchie, British film
director and pop of the forthcoming tot. Nor, according to Madonna,
does she plan on marrying either.
</P>
<P>
   And it's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since she burst onto the music scene in the early '80s,
Madonna has not only altered the climate of pop culture with
fashion and musical trends, she has mastered the art of mastering
us, the media. Whatever Madonna does, we approve, calling it
brilliant, and making you, the public, feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   Racy videos? We call it pushing the envelope. Image makeovers?
Growing up. Having a couple kids without marrying? It's just being
independent and proving to other women that they, too, can raise
kids without the everyday influence of a father.
</P>
<P>
   Bad movies? We don't hold them against her, either.
</P>
<P>
   We crown Madonna cool because, well, we don't have much choice.
She's one of the only female artists to relentlessly push buttons _
fashion, social and sexual. Others _ from Cher to Patti Smith to
Liz Phair _ may have had their precedent-setting moments _ but only
Madonna has been consistently adventurous, always lurking around
the corner with another surprise that the media absorbs and makes
you approve.
</P>
<P>
   Credit that to her savvy manipulation of the media _ she's had
plenty of practice, alternately battling and kissing up to us since
the early '80s. Credit it to the people behind Madonna _ the
publicists, the managers, the image-makers, the agents, the
decision-makers. Credit us for recognizing _ and championing _
someone who's not afraid to go against the grain.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever she does, however she looks, it doesn't matter. All we
care about is: What's next for Madonna? And we _ and you _ can't
wait to find out.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
