<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-OSCARS-TV-BOS &LR;      03-27 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEDIUM AND CRYSTAL JABS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Billy Crystal pointed out, Regis Philbin took the night off
so ABC could squeeze in a more anticipated set of final answers.
</P>
<P>
   And so Crystal opened the 72d annual Oscarcast with the final
answer in digital trickery, as the shtick-spouting comic was
inserted into classic movies from ``The Graduate'' to ``The
Godfather.'' Along with Crystal's musical homage to the nominated
pictures, it was a brisk beginning to the long Oscar night, but it
wasn't witty stuff, unless you think getting spewed with green
vomit by Linda Blair, or hearing ``Green Mile'' sung to the tune of
``Green Acres,'' is the final answer in funny. And it didn't help
the bulk of Oscar 2000 pass any faster, or end any earlier, as the
event wandered to its final moments just after the four-hour mark,
at 12:35.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal's strengths _ what made first-time Oscar producers
Richard and Lili Fini Zanuck beg him to return for a seventh gig _
are his mensch demeanor and his soft jabs, both of which were in
full bloom Sunday night. Noting that a missing Oscar was hiding in
Erykah Badu's hat, quipping that ``If Roberto Benigni gets out of
hand, I've got the stun gun,'' and, of course, chitchatting with
the sun-
</P>
<P>
   glassed Jack Nicholson from the stage, he delivered the big fat
smirk that is his trademark. He made it clear that the Zanucks were
going for safety and likability, and not the envelope-pushing of
last year's host, Whoopi Goldberg, when they hired him.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was Oscarcast as usual, with unnecessary clip
collages, static song performances, and forced presenter humor. Oh,
and, of course, viewer bribery, as a disproportionate number of
important awards got held back until the final half-hour to keep us
hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Zanucks' promise of a swifter event, featuring
hipped-up music from Burt Bacharach and Don Was, the hours plodded
by with all the expected pomp and bloat.
</P>
<P>
   Even the night's anticipated controversy, Robin Williams'
rendition of ``Blame Canada,'' the expletive-laced song from
``South Park,'' went off without sparks as Williams simply left out
the offending language. After pulling a piece of tape off his
mouth, he sang and danced with a stageful of cartoony characters
who looked like refugees from ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,''
plus a line of leggy Mounties.
</P>
<P>
   And the Oscars seem to move even slower these days, as they come
on the heels of so many other movie awards _ the People's Choice,
the Golden Globes, the Writers Guild, the Directors Guild, the
Screen Actors Guild, the Independent Spirit _ all of which feature
the same nominees uttering the same words of gratitude and pride.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions to the rule of Oscar tedium?
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his supporting-actor statue after a standing ovation,
Michael Caine used his precious time to pay homage to each of the
nominees one by one. Addressing Tom Cruise, he said, ``If you had
won this one, your price would have gone down fast. Have you any
idea what supporting actors get paid? We only get one motor home, a
small one.'' It was a heartfelt and gracious gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting his Irving Thalberg award, Warren Beatty delivered a
remarkably real thank-you speech, looking hard at the audience and
acknowledging the friends who helped him through his solitary
years. He also honored his ``treasure,'' wife Annette Bening, to
whom the camera couldn't seem to get close enough.
</P>
<P>
   And while Hilary Swank delivered her thank-you's for her
best-actress Oscar, noting ``we have come a long way'' for
celebrating a small, controversial movie like ``Boys Don't Cry,''
and ``this movie could not have been made 2 1/2 years ago,'' the
camera cut to her husband, Chad Lowe, with tears streaming down his
face. It was a sweet moment.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the Oscar pre-shows, on E! and then, at 8 p.m., on
ABC? If cleavage were soap, Hollywood would have been squeaky
clean.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-shows were rich in exposure, to say the least, as the
glittery actresses inched their way down the bright red carpet and
into the Shrine Auditorium under the bulging eyes of the press.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the royal family _ princess Nicole Kidman and lady in
waiting Charlize Theron _ went the posterior cleavage route, with
colorful backless numbers. But the predominant motif was very Erin
Brockovich. From the low-key Chloe Sevigny and the frothy Cameron
Diaz, whose black Versace plunged nearly to her belly, to a
scrunched-up Winona Ryder, who arrived Matt Damon-less, the theme
was full frontal.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Girls, Very Busted.
</P>
<P>
   The most eye-popping cleavage, though, was wielded immodestly by
a trio of ironic semi-celebrities named Matt Stone, Trey Parker,
and Marc Shaiman. They're the fellows behind ``South Park: Bigger,
Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' and they arrived dolled up in long gowns.
Greeting them on E!, Joan Rivers was undaunted, of course, as she
admired the boys and asked them to do a swirl for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Looking more Grammy than Oscar, the ``South Park'' dudes were a
welcome relief from the rest of the Hollywood men, dully dressed in
variations of stiff black and white.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
