<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOHEMIAN-BOOK-REVIEW-     03-27 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHEMIAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEIRD LIKE US: MY BOHEMIAN AMERICA': CHALLENGING THE NORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface words in 8th graf are meant to be italicized.
Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Jenny Lyn Bader is co-author, with Bill Brazell, of ``He Meant,
She Meant: The Definitive Male-Female Dictionary.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ann Powers has been a record store clerk, a radical scholar on a
Ph.D. track at Berkeley and an editor for The Village Voice. And
for as long as she can remember, she has been a bohemian. In
``Weird Like Us: My Bohemian America,'' she argues that bohemianism
is not only alive and well, it is thriving, and whatever inroads it
makes into the mainstream only provide evidence of its power and
vibrancy.
</P>
<P>
   Part cultural history, part personal memoir and part
sociological theory, ``Weird Like Us'' is a rebuff to anyone who
thinks bohemia is over. (Those who apparently consider it dead
include bohemians in denial, cynics from the suburbs, and left-wing
thinkers who say alternative culture is dead because nowadays it
gets commercialized faster than you can say grunge Barbie.)
</P>
<P>
   For Powers, who writes pop music reviews for The New York Times,
being bohemian means more than wearing rumpled clothes in cafes; it
embodies a set of beliefs and ideals that not only can but also
should influence the norm. She states that both new values and new
tastes historically emerge from bohemia and writes passionately
about the outsider values she believes should trickle in, for the
sake of social progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird Like Us'' begins on the occasion of the author's first
acid trip, an event that feels mystical and sad, funny and tender.
The reader is immediately hooked on the intimacy of this writing,
which soon gives way to patches of soapbox preaching and
sociological theorizing. But the book remains at its finest when it
is most intimate. Powers has a gift for telling personal histories,
and for making history personal, and her chapter on the history of
rock music moves swiftly through everything you ever wanted to know
about psychedelic art punk, the rave scene, alternative and indie
rock. Her interview subjects are usually her friends, who take ``an
indie-rock approach to life.'' She writes poignantly of the pains
of adolescence, of the high school loners who strive to turn
weirdness into an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Powers has lived in the bohemian trenches. In high school, she
wore hot pink vintage New Wave outfits, followed punk bands and
wrote poetry. After dropping out of college, she lived in a group
house in San Francisco in a building ``the color of cat food,''
with a Violent Femmes poster on the wall and 20 roommates, not
counting the mice who lived in the oven. She experimented with
drugs and life choices with friends she viewed as a surrogate
family. ``We'd gather regularly for Sunday dinners,'' she writes,
``though our Sundays sometimes fell on other people's Wednesdays.''
</P>
<P>
   She is wonderful at invoking the details of her life and the
lives of those around her, from sex radicals to zine editors to
junk culture mavens. Powers takes her lifestyle choices seriously.
It is clear that she is in favor of rhinestones and recycled furs,
whimsical vintage hats and legalizing marijuana. She is against
conformity, wearing suits and the Crate and Barrel catalog.
</P>
<P>
   But she also has a keen sense of irony. In one laid-back group
house, a pair of intense bohemians write a lengthy statement of
purpose about the house and its values and interview prospective
roommates as if they were job applicants. Powers introduces us to a
lap dancer who also works as an accupressurist, a bisexual sex
worker who maintains a strict vegan diet, and a woman named
Cassandra who tries heroin for the first time on the eve of Ronald
Reagan's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Powers is wickedly funny and original on the drug culture. When
she was attending Blanchet High School in Seattle, a boy named
Claude, tripping on drugs, walked through a plate-glass sliding
door. She describes how she and her friends explained away the
incident: ``He had taken PCP _ angel dust, an animal tranquilizer
favored by crazed criminals. A  &UR; bad drug &LR; . Twenty years after that
September, I have still avoided angel dust. Never mind that within
months of Claude's disappearance from Blanchet I was downing
bottles of Robitussin in a juvenile effort at mind expansion, and
by junior year I was dropping acid and drinking cupfuls of mushroom
tea. Those were all  &UR; good drugs &LR; , favored by gentle hippies and
genius bands like the Butthole Surfers, promising bliss and
visions, not permanently warped frontal lobes.''
</P>
<P>
   She reveals more layers of hypocrisy as she discusses those who
just say no to pot but are addicted to Prozac, explores the death
of an acquaintance who was a heroin addict and explains why her
high school buddies thought cocaine was good but speed was only
sometimes good.
</P>
<P>
   Powers even possesses that rare commodity in a cultural
memoirist, self-irony. After a preachy passage, she confesses,
``I'm getting a little evangelical here, and I know that isn't
cool.'' And one of the funniest moments in this book comes when she
is planning her wedding ceremony. (She wore orange and incorporated
elements like handfasting, a neopagan custom in which the couple's
hands are bound together by a cord.) She admits: ``I was earnestly
discussing my ideas with a lesbian friend who is quite opposed to
marriage, relating all the different ways we felt our ceremony
could critique the institution. I went on and on until she
interrupted me: It is going to be fun, too, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed the reader occasionally empathizes with said lesbian
friend, wondering why a book about vibrant, defiant communities of
independent souls cannot be just a little more fun, why stories
from the bohemian front must be interrupted by textbook moments
like ``the baby boomers' legacy of commodified youthfulness.'' But
then the stories continue, and they make Powers' case more
eloquently than any manifesto could.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `WEIRD LIKE US'
</P>
<P>
   My Bohemian America
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Powers
</P>
<P>
   287 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
