<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAKE DAVIS' PIKE PROBLEM IS JUST BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A stunning letter from the American Fisheries
Society calls California Fish and Game director Bob Hight
irresponsible for settling for anything less than complete
eradication of northern pike at Lake Davis in the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay-Delta's population of salmon, steelhead and several
endangered species would be put at risk if pike escape the lake and
find their way downstream into the spawning grounds of the San
Joaquin Delta, DFG scientists and managers have previously
testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe any action less than eradication is in violation of
state law, and biologically and ecologically irresponsible,''
writes Michael Meinz, director of the Fisheries Society, in a
letter to Hight. ``The plan, by suggesting otherwise, clearly
demonstrates a total lack of knowledge and understanding of fish
population dynamics. This fatal flaw alone destroys the scientific
credibility of the entire plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hight announced last month, that pike would be ``contained and
controlled'' at Lake Davis. That reversed a 10-year, hard-line
policy of eradication of the predator fish, which look something
like an alligator mouth connected to a tail. Through several
assistants, Hight refused an interview request this past week
regarding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martarano of the DFG defended the new policy, and said
that the department is open to suggestions on how to minimize the
pike threat, short of poisoning the lake or draining it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing the Fisheries Society doesn't realize is that we
consider this a work in progress,'' Martarano said. ``We're trying
a lot of different things, and we're open to suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Martarano said that poisoning the lake to end the pike threat is
out of the question, a strategy that was successful at Frenchman
Lake near Chilcoot but botched three years ago at Davis. Draining
the lake has been considered and rejected, he said, because with
the current mechanics at the dam, it would take two years to drain
the lake and longer to refill.
</P>
<P>
   Since the reversal of policy was first announced in February,
Hight has been under widespread attack.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter to Hight, Ronald LaForce, president of United
Outdoorsmen, described the Susinta River drainage in Alaska where
pike were introduced 20 years ago in a lake and then escaped
downriver. Today the pike inhabit 90 lakes and 44 river systems in
the region, destroying runs of silver and sockeye salmon and 60
percent of the rainbow trout populations.
</P>
<P>
   The DFG's pike plan is available on the Internet at
www.dfg.ca.gov/dfghome.html.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
