<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREADING THE WORD ON DIABETES _ AND ITS BREAKTHROUGHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixteen million Americans have diabetes, but 5.4 million of them
do not know they have it.
</P>
<P>
   An Arlington, Texas, woman first learned she had diabetes when
she developed a severe fungal infection in her sinuses following
the extraction of an abscessed tooth. Her high blood sugar fueled
the infection, which spread quickly, killing tissue around her eyes
and nose. Her right eye and cheekbone were removed. Still in the
hospital, eight weeks after diabetes was diagnosed, the woman died
of complications of the disease. She was 57.
</P>
<P>
   A Fort Worth man's diabetes was diagnosed while he was under
anesthesia for cardiac bypass surgery. His blood sugar soared so
high that he went into a diabetic coma, and doctors informed his
family that he was in danger of death, not from the heart surgery,
but from diabetes. Why, the surgeon asked, had he not been told
about the diabetes?
</P>
<P>
   Why, the patient asks today, had he not been told that he has
diabetes?
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes is often a silent disease. Over the years _ even before
you know you have it _ diabetes can harm the eyes, kidneys, nerves
and heart. It is a leading cause of blindness, kidney failure and
amputation. It kills 180,000 people in this country each year.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic gold medalist Gary Hall Jr. this week is joining the
American Diabetes Association in sounding an alert about the
seriousness of diabetes and the importance of finding the millions
of Americans who have it and don't know it.
</P>
<P>
   America's top freestyle sprint swimmer, Hall, 25, won two gold
and two silver medals at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and is training
for this year's Olympic games in Sydney, Australia. He found out
last March that he has diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are almost 6 million Americans with diabetes who don't
know it. I was one of those people,'' Hall said in a phone visit
last week . ``I was experiencing fatigue and dizziness, which I
wrote off as overwork in my training, and my eyesight was becoming
blurry, but I attributed that to the chlorinated water. Finally,
one day I was so dizzy I thought I was going to faint. The next day
I was diagnosed with insulin-dependent diabetes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall says he was very scared when he first learned the symptoms
were caused by a life-threatening disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a frightening experience, and even very young children,
even babies, can be diagnosed with diabetes. It's not limited to
any age group or type. It can happen to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so strongly that if I was able to overcome it and swim
better than ever before with diabetes, I could give a sense of hope
to others. You can go out and achieve greatness even with this
disease _ but if you have it, you must know it so you can control
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he hopes to help raise awareness about the seriousness
of diabetes, its risk factors and its complications through
tomorrow's American Diabetes Alert Day, an annual call to action
for people to find out if they are at risk for the disease and to
inform them about the various new tools available to control it.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the alert is type II diabetes, by far the most
common form. Type II develops very slowly and mainly affects people
over age 40, whose cells become resistent to the insulin they
produce. Sometimes it becomes necessary for them to receive insulin
injections, but often their disease can be controlled with diet,
exercise and oral medications that make their cells more sensitive
to the insulin produced by the pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   Type I, formerly known as insulin-dependent diabetes, usually
develops in childhood or adolesence, often in people with no known
risk factors. The body produces little or no insulin, the hormone
that enables the body's cells to absorb sugar glucose from the
blood and use it for energy.
</P>
<P>
   Primary risk factors for Type II include being overweight,
underactive and over the age of 45 and having a family history of
diabetes. African-Americans, Hispanics, American Indians and women
who have had babies weighing more than 9 pounds at birth are at
increased risk.
</P>
<P>
   Most people with Type II diabetes do not notice any symptoms,
and many patients found to have it are estimated to have had the
disease seven to 10 years before its discovery.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you are very thirsty, urinate often or lose weight
without trying, you should call your doctor right away, says
Christine Sammer, certified diabetes educator with the Huguley
Health System.
</P>
<P>
   ``Screening is so important because the symptoms can be so
subtle and can be attributed to many different disease
conditions,'' Sammer says. ``People rationalize and decide they are
thirsty because of the hot Texas weather and that they have to get
up several times during the night to use the bathroom because they
drink so much water.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammer points out that there are many tools available today to
help people control their blood-sugar level, including drugs,
monitors and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important component is education. We teach people all
the important keys to managing their diabetes _ meal planning,
exercise, stress management and medications if needed,'' says
Sammer.
</P>
<P>
   While diabetes is still an incurable disease, new forms of
insulin and monitors to help maintain proper blood-sugar levels are
now giving many people with diabetes much better control over their
disease, and much research is being done on islet cell transplants,
which offer hope of a real cure.
</P>
<P>
   New, improved forms of insulin such as the rapid-acting Humalog,
which is a combination of two types of insulin that can come
pre-mixed in a pre-filled pen for ease and convenience, and
delivery systems, like the insulin pump, which is implanted under
the skin and delivers a slow trickle of insulin when it is needed,
help patients maintain control over fluctuating blood-sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   Also, new, painless ways to measure glucose levels without
pricking the skin are being developed, and at least one is expected
to be on the market in a few months. In December, the Food and Drug
Administration recommended approval for the GlucoWatch Monitor,
which collects fluid from the surface of the skin to measure the
amount of sugar in the blood. The fluid is absorbed by a small
disposable pad, and the watch automatically checks glucose levels
every 20 minutes for 12 hours. An alarm sounds if the blood glucose
gets too high or too low. The watch is expected to cost about $300,
with collection pads an additional $4 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, researchers reported this month on the first human trial
of a noninvasive technique that uses ultrasound to monitor glucose
levels.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
