u f BC-DAIMLER-MITSUBISHI-1S     03-27 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-MITSUBISHI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER INVESTS IN MITSUBISHI MOTORS CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add details and clarify: lede to add that DaimlerChrysler
is 3rd-largest automaker; adds new 2nd graf; 3rd graf to clarify; 
 4th-graf changes `German' to `German-based'; adds news 6th graf
with share prices (bgng `The deal had...');   7th graf to delete
`by a factor of five'; 10th graf to clarify;   2nd, penultimate and
last grafs of optional trim to clarify.) 
 (js) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ DaimlerChrysler AG, the world's third-largest maker of
motor vehicles, signed an agreement Monday to invest in Mitsubishi
Motors Corp., finally securing the toehold in Asia that it has long
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.1 billion deal would leave Toyota and Honda as Japan's
last major automakers without big foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler will buy newly issued shares that will give it a
33.4 percent stake in Mitsubishi, enough to guarantee it board
representation and limited veto power.
</P>
<P>
   The German-based car company said that the alliance would give
it entree to Asian markets and access to small-car technology that
it would use to expand its Smart car brand. DaimlerChrysler said
Monday that Mitsubishi will supply transmissions and direct
injection gasoline engines for Smart cars, cutting its development
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have closed the circle,'' Juergen Schrempp, chairman of
DaimlerChrysler, told reporters at the company's headquarters in
Stuttgart Monday. ``We have covered all the markets of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal had been expected for the last few weeks, when word
that both sides were close to an agreement first began circulating.
But the official announcement and terms of the partnership still
helped push up Mitsubishi's share price 12 percent Monday, to 470
yen, or $4.40. &UR;  &LR; DaimlerChrysler shares eased 31.25 cents in New
York, closing at $67.1875.
</P>
<P>
   For Mitsubishi, the agreement means survival. With debts that
outweigh equity and a history of poor profitability, the company
needed a partner.
</P>
<P>
   In a span of two years, 7 of Japan's 11 automakers have taken
foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of Japanese automakers, this was the last one
available,'' said Christopher Richter, an analyst at HSBC
Securities in Tokyo. ``Toyota is too big, Honda has no apparent
interest in an alliance and competition for the Korean automakers
is intense.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Monday raised the question of whether
DaimlerChrysler is paying a price for walking away from a deal with
Nissan Motor Co. nearly a year ago. Since then, DaimlerChrysler has
talked with PSA Peugeot Citroen, Fiat and others but failed to
clinch a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding its truck business, which is not part of the
agreement, Mitsubishi has a much smaller product line than Nissan,
and debt accounts for a bigger portion of its balance sheet than
did Nissan's debts.
</P>
<P>
   And it is an integral part of a tightly knit business cluster,
the Mitsubishi Group, which has resisted political and financial
pressure to dismantle itself, unlike other Japanese conglomerates.
Mitsubishi Group companies own, and will continue to own, a larger
portion of Mitsubishi Motors than members of the Fuyo Group held in
Nissan, according to Richter.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kentaro Aikawa, the former chairman of Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, Mitsubishi's biggest shareholder, is famous for saying
that shareholders do not matter. ``The notion that accrued profits
belong to shareholders is an American one,'' Aikawa said in 1997.
``In Japan, these profits go to paying employee salaries, even when
the work dries up.''
</P>
<P>
   While Aikawa has since taken an advisory role at the company,
his sentiments have continued to color perceptions of Mitsubishi
Motors, which was once part of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the biggest challenges here will be providing
DaimlerChrysler with the management access and participation it
wants while keeping the existing management team in place to keep
the Mitsubishi group happy,'' said Steven Usher, an analyst at
Jardine Fleming Securities in Tokyo. ``I think that will be very
touchy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nissan announced a year ago that it had sold a
similar-sized stake to Renault S.A. of France, it was clear that
the company had resigned itself to the management of its partner.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Ghosn, a senior executive of Renault, had been identified
at the news conference announcing the deal as Nissan's new chief
operating officer, and he began his job almost immediately. He was
quickly followed by 40 other Renault executives, who made it clear
that they were in charge.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler had no version of Ghosn on hand Monday. Instead,
Katsuhiko Kawasoe, who has tenaciously guarded Mitsubishi's
independence for the last two years, remains as president, or
``shatcho,'' a title that confers a great deal more authority and
weight here than it does in the United States. Ghosn will gain that
title at Nissan in June.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that Daimler will be a passive partner at
Mitsubishi. It has forcefully demonstrated its ability to wield
management control over Chrysler, which has seen a veritable flood
of executives depart in the wake of the merger more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether Mitsubishi Motors will give DaimlerChrysler as big a
market in Asia as DaimlerChrysler believes is another question.
Mitsubishi Motors has an impressive distribution network in the
region, and its market shares there are higher than Nissan's if its
truck operations are taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitsubishi Motors signed a deal with Volvo last year that
gives the Swedish company a 19 percent stake in Mitsubishi's truck
business, and Volvo has said it is not interested in selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been a lot more attractive for DaimlerChrysler
if trucks were part of it,'' Richter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
