<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAG-REVIEWS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE &AMP; WEBSITE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE
 &UR; MISSED THIS FEATURE; ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muller takes a quick look at some current magazine issues
and a website:
</P>
<P>
   ``KMT'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Egypt 'R' Us. If seeing ``The Mummy'' just wasn't enough, check
out this quarterly publication, subtitled ``A Modern Journal of
Ancient Egypt.'' (KMT is the spelling of the name for Egypt in
ancient Egyptian.) The spring issue includes a story on the Museum
of Mummification in Luxor (Egyptian city, not Vegas casino).
Article notes that only the most independent traveler stumbles on
Luxor's best-kept secret, the first museum of its kind, dedicated
solely to the ancient art of preserving bodies (the Dick Clark wing
is a must-see). Turns out that mummification was not limited to
humans. The Egyptians also preserved animals, including crocodiles,
cats and apes. Also includes an interesting piece on the
restoration of six tombs in the Valley of the Kings, with color
photos of the brilliantly painted interiors, pillars and
sarcophagi. Of course, the exhibits are limited to items not swiped
by the British, who carted away Egypt's antiquities by the boatload
around the turn of the 20th century. Blimey! &QL; 
 &QL; 
``MOTHER JONES'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're all fired up to vote for George W. Bush this fall, you
might skip this month's issue, in which Molly Ivins knocks Dubya
off his pins with an adaption from her book, ``Shrub: The Short But
Happy Political Life of George W. Bush.'' With more clarity and
brevity than the recent tree-killer in ``Harper's,'' Ivins manages
to outline how Bush parlayed his family name into big money by
bouncing from loser company to loser company, always to be bailed
out in the end. ``In oil, as in politics, Dubya's MO is
consistent,'' Ivins writes. ``Leverage the family name and a small
investment into really big money, always provided by others.''
Ivins also notes that Bush flipped his oil companies, unloaded
stock as a corporate insider before the price plummeted and walked
away with ``more money than Bill Clinton ever dreamed of making on
a little real-estate deal now known as Whitewater.'' Still, she
says, Texas will forgive him as it did the likes of John Connally,
Lloyd Bentsen and Phil Gramm. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``VANITY FAIR'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is our favorite issue every year, the one full of those
cool photographs of Hollywood stars in Annie Leibovitz-type poses
(even though many of the photos are not taken by Leibovitz this
year). Best photo reunites the cast of ``American Graffiti.''
Amazing special effects allow George Lucas' ego to somehow fit in
the frame. Another favorite is Chuck Jones (OK, I'll admit it, I
thought he was dead), popping up out of a ``wabbit'' hole in the
desert. And then there is George Clooney, looking eerily like Clark
Gable (dead, we checked). Low point is Demi Moore naked with her
kids. Make the bad woman go away! The cranky guys over at ``Slate''
(www.slate.com) called this issue as ``hagiographic as ever,'' and
once we consulted a dictionary (www.dictionary.com) to figure out
what that means (worshipful biography) we have to agree. The
Slaters must be having one of those secret staff contests to get
obscure words into print. They also managed to work in the word
odalisque (harem girl), last used by Tennyson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``WIRED'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cover story is frightening piece on the future of the human race
written by Bill Joy, chief scientist at Sun Microsystems, inventor
of UNIX and Java and all-around genius-boy. Joy paints a picture of
homo sapiens dominated by a robot population of their own creation.
It sounds far-fetched until Joy makes his eloquent case, noting
that technology soon will be able to create extremely advanced,
self-replicating robots that could make old-fashioned biological
organisms obsolete. Quoting the Unabomber (ironic, because Joy was
once a prime target of the anti-technology terrorist), Joy warns of
unintended consequences that could spring from robotics, genetic
engineering and nanotechnology. ``By 2030,'' he writes, ``we are
likely to be able to build machines, in quantity, a million times
as powerful as the personal computer of today _ sufficient to
implement the dreams'' of those who imagine a world of robot
servants. If you want to know how this works out, rent the film
``The Forbin Project.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEBSITE &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` 50.lycos.com'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Want to know what everybody else wants to know about? Check out
this Web site, which keeps a running tally of the 50 most popular
subjects on the Internet, ranging from Pokemon cards at No. 1 to
prom dresses ('tis the season) at No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The list, based on a count of search words punched into Lycos
each day, is perfect for those who want to find something on the
Web quickly without a lot of searching. For example, as tax time
nears, the IRS site is steaming up the charts, landing at No. 8
last week.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good way to gauge public opinion. For example, with
Major League Baseball about to start, you might think that people
would be pouring into the MLB sites. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the top sports-related sites included, at No. 2,
March Madness (NCAA basketball tournament); at No. 6, the WWF
(wrasslin' and, no, we don't want to get into that argument); and,
at No. 16, NASCAR (vroom, vroom). Baseball was No. 40.
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence that the Internet is dominated by
14-year-old boys, a number of top sites involve popular Web pinups
such as Britney Spears, Jennifer Lopez, Anna Kournikova, Jenny
McCarthy, Carmen Electra and, of course, Pamela Lee.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to plug into pop culture and you don't have a lot of
time on your hands, Lycos 50 is the site for you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
