<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LEESON-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-27 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEESON-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BIZARRE IS THE POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ At first glance, the commercial seemed like a spoof, a
comedy skit that could appear on ``Saturday Night Live.'' Nicholas
Leeson, the rogue stock trader who caused the collapse of Britain's
oldest merchant bank, Barings PLC, is appearing in a campaign that
promotes a Swedish dot-com stock trading company. It may sound as
bizarre as having the captain of the Exxon Valdez endorse Bounty
paper towels, but the commercial's creators said bizarre was very
much the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds strange if you're not here in the market,''
said Johan Almquist, chief executive of TBWA Stockholm, who came up
with the concept of using Leeson as an endorser. ``We always do odd
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Leeson, 32, is infamous for racking up a staggering $1.4 billion
in losses while wildly trading futures at Barings' Singapore
office, sinking the bank, which was later sold for 1 pound to ING
Group of the Netherlands. After four years in jail in Singapore,
Leeson returned to London last summer just after his story was
released as a film called ``Rogue Trader,'' based on his memoir,
which was published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   When Almquist began brainstorming advertising ideas for his
client, Matteus.com, the online trading company, he wanted to
differentiate the site from rivals that were setting up shop in
Sweden, including ETrade of the United States. Because Matteus also
serves as a traditional brokerage house providing financial
planning and stock advice, TBWA crafted a campaign that points out
the risky side of gambling in the stock market on the Internet and
portrays Matteus as the best alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought to ourselves, `Who could warn people that this is a
dangerous game?''' Almquist said. ``It occurred to us that Nick was
the best example.'' Getting Matteus' executives to go along with
using Leeson as an endorser was the easy part _ ``They laughed a
lot and said, `Of course,''' Almquist said _ but getting Leeson to
agree to appear was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Because Leeson still owes 100 million pounds, or $159 million,
to Barings' liquidators, all appearance fees have to be negotiated
by an army of lawyers. All fees are divided in half _ 50 percent
going to Barings and 50 percent going to Leeson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick gets offers all the time for endorsements,'' said Ian
Monk, Leeson's agent, who also represents Barings' liquidators.
``We wanted to do something socially responsible. He's the world's
best example of how things can go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   To TBWA's surprise, Leeson agreed to do the ad. ``We thought
there was an outside chance,'' Almquist said. Both TBWA _ part of
the TBWA Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group _ and Monk refused to
divulge how much Leeson was paid for his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, which is in English with Swedish subtitles, begins with
clips of news footage from when Barings collapsed and Leeson was
arrested. The commercial then cuts to a somber _ if not deadpan _
Leeson against a white backdrop staring at the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me four years and 2000 prison meals ago,'' he says in a
way reminiscent of a public service announcement. ``Barings went
bankrupt. I lost my life. It's a very risky business. You can make
a lot of money fast, but we all make mistakes. It's easier than you
think to lose everything overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The television commercial, which just finished its initial
three-week run, is scheduled to be repeated this spring and summer.
A separate print ad that included a picture of Leeson and his saga
ran in large Swedish daily newspapers and financial magazines and
is also scheduled for a second run. TBWA declined to disclose the
cost of the campaign, which is running only in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Leeson spent three days in Stockholm, Sweden, filming the
advertisement. ``He's a regular guy,'' Almquist said. ``We talked
about football and girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Almquist said the campaign had received a positive response,
``and of course a lot of press.'' He said the audience in Sweden,
which has one of the highest Internet-use rates in the world,
appreciated the commercial for its message, not simply as a gag.
</P>
<P>
   As for ING Barings' response, a spokesman who couldn't contain
his laughter said, ``No comment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
