<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TITO-OPERA-REVIEW-ART     03-27 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITO-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LA CLEMENZA DI TITO': GRANDEUR IN UNDERVALUED MOZART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``La Clemenza di Tito,'' the opera Mozart wrote for a
coronation in Prague a few months before he died, was long
undervalued but now seems absolutely immediate. Not only is it
filled with great and glorious music _ strongly presented in the
new City Opera production _ but it speaks to concerns that are
ours. An era is passing away, and all that people feel they can
trust is the world of private emotion. How, though, are they to
tell the formal gesture, the attitude, from the native impulse of
the heart? And can the machinery of a state go on under these
circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   Right from the first, at Sunday afternoon's opening performance,
the musical caliber was high. Harry Bicket, the conductor, had the
overture played with a light touch, speedily and exactly, and the
orchestra remained deft and adroit. The choruses, marches and other
evocations of grandeur were swift and simple, without pomposity.
The important solos on clarinet and basset horn were beautifully
phrased by Laura Flax.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Hunt Lieberson, in the central role of Sesto, asked for
the audience's understanding because of a viral infection, but it
is impossible to imagine how she could have sung better. In
``Parto, parto,'' the aria in which Sesto agrees to execute a
palace revolution on behalf of his beloved Vitellia, Hunt
Lieberson's vocal presence and coloring conveyed all the
character's determination and deep underlying regret. Her
impressive performance here gave her confidence and propelled her
into powerfully expressive singing in the accompanied recitative
before the first-act finale. In the second act, her big aria was
again a masterpiece of phrasing and feeling, the two working
together with the help of rich color, perfectly molded sound and a
wide dynamic range.
</P>
<P>
   As Vitellia, Marie Plette had a few problems with the coloratura
in the first act, but in ``Non piu di fiori,'' where she at last
sets aside her imperial ambitions, she was magnificent, her sound
warm and beautifully placed, her demeanor serene. No longer aiming
for the throne, she became majestic.
</P>
<P>
   Tito, the emperor so much plotted against and loved, was sung by
Kurt Streit, with the ringing timbre, lightness and energy that
have made him one of the most sought-after Mozart tenors. His sound
seemed affected more than the others by the amplification.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Tucker, as Sesto's friend Annio, created the image of a
noble youth with creamy yet fresh tone, sensitively phrased and
colored. Tracy Dahl was a bubbly Servilia and Jake Gardner a fine
Publio, at once sound and suave in his singing.
</P>
<P>
   The much traveled production, by Stephen Wadsworth, sets the
piece at the time of its composition, in front of ancient, high,
windowless brick walls that are there throughout and challenge the
lighting. There are some nice moments, especially in how principals
are placed among or against the chorus, but the essential action is
sentimentalized.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LA CLEMENZA DI TITO' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opera in two acts by Mozart, libretto by Pietro Metastasio,
adapted by Caterino Mazzola; conductor, Harry Bicket; stage
director, Stephen Wadsworth; sets by Thomas Lynch; costumes by
Dunya Ramicova; lighting by Peter Kaczorowski. At the New York City
Opera.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Kurt Streit (Tito Vespasiano), Marie Plette (Vitellia),
Tracy Dahl (Servilia), Lorraine Hunt Lieberson (Sesto), Laura
Tucker (Annio) and Jake Gardner (Publio). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-KENNEDY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-27 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-KENNEDY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... Kennedy recalls.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Ohio State Murders'' is a semiautobiographical tale based
on that experience. The lead character reenacts her student years,
a time when she was so tense, she injured the flesh on her head.
Her dreams are left to decompose at the bottom of a lonely ravine.
</P>
<P>
   While many details are factual, Kennedy says the story itself is
fiction. ``When I went to Ohio State, I met my husband-to-be and
clung to him for dear life,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her character, the playwright got married in the
mid-1950s and moved to New York, where her husband, Joseph, was a
graduate student at Columbia University. (They've since divorced,
but remain friends.) Still a daydreamer and a hopeless romantic,
she longed to mingle with the movie stars and the serious writers
of the day and yearned to see her name appear in the gossip columns
of the local tabloids. ``Oh, I was very romantic about
everything,'' she recalls. ``I was this young housewife with a
baby, and I wore these little cotton dresses and had this vague
idea in my mind that I wanted to be a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing life
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She didn't find herself as a writer until she accompanied her
husband to Africa in the early 1960s. All the hallucinogenic images
that had been swirling around in her mind jelled during that trip,
and she fired off ``Funnyhouse.'' The playwright Edward Albee
produced it off-Broadway in 1964. In the play, a college student is
haunted by images of Jesus, Queen Victoria, and the slain African
leader Patrice Lumumba.
</P>
<P>
   Her plays often unfold on that sort of surreal landscape, where
racial hatred can turn an innocent daydream into a vicious
nightmare. Racism is the underlying force of ``Sleep Deprivation
Chamber,'' a play she co-wrote with her son, Adam, that won an Obie
Award in 1996. The play is based on a real incident when Adam, now
38, was beaten by a police officer who followed him home to his
father's house in a tony Virginia suburb. ``It happened in my
husband's front yard,'' Kennedy says. ``I think of all those years
he worked to buy this white house with yellow shutters and a forest
behind it. It was his dream house, but somehow I realized we were
living in a kind of dream world. It was a shock for this to happen
to my son, a real shock.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't like to talk about the incident in too much detail:
Her emotional response is recorded in the play, which depicts a
mother's worst nightmare. After all, the teacher preparing to meet
her students still astonishes herself when that other woman _ the
one who writes the plays _ dredges up such blood-curdling images.
``I still get very upset,'' she says gently before heading to
class.
</P>
<P>
   She decides to allow the visitor to observe the seminar. In
class, one student reads a synopsis of her play, painting harrowing
images of a Christlike figure in a train station, a suicide, a dead
baby, a troubled woman with a troubled past. The student is a timid
type, and Kennedy urges her to be protective of her apocalyptic
vision. ``You have to be careful about listening to other people
because you don't want to get too logical,'' she tells the student.
``You have to be careful with this material because it's very
fragile.'' In those few moments, Adrienne Kennedy the teacher could
be addressing Adrienne Kennedy the playwright. In those brief
moments, she becomes the benevolent teacher she never had at Ohio
State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
