<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT28-COX     03-27 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOCUS SHIFTS TO 'REMEDIES' AS MICROSOFT RULING NEARS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an out-of-court settlement of the federal antitrust suit
against Microsoft Corp. remained uncertain Monday, the focus
shifted to the penalties the company could face if a federal judge
rules it has flouted antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson told attorneys for
both sides last week he was prepared to issue a ruling as early as
Tuesday unless settlement talks mediated by another federal judge
in Chicago showed substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
   There was little sign of such progress by Monday evening. But
there were reports that Jackson might delay his ruling so that some
of the 19 state governments that have joined the federal government
as plaintiffs could further study a complex settlement proposal
that Microsoft offered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson does issue a ruling on ``conclusions of law'' in the
case, it is widely expected to be unfavorable to Microsoft. In
``findings of fact'' he issued last year after an earlier phase of
the trial, Jackson said Microsoft enjoyed a monopoly with its
Windows operating system and had used that monopoly to restrict
competition, stifle innovation and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's next step after ruling would be to hear further
arguments from both sides as he weighs ``remedies'' for Microsoft's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Jackson would have to choose between ordering
changes in the company's business practices, as proposed by
Microsoft, or the breakup of the software giant, as favored by some
members of the prosecutorial team.
</P>
<P>
   A breakup could divide the company into several competing firms,
or could sever Windows from the rest of the company.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Microsoft has already sent a clear signal of what
it believes the remedies should be in the settlement offer it
transmitted last week through Judge Richard Posner, head of the 7th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and the key mediator in the case.
</P>
<P>
   A central aspect of the Microsoft plan is to no longer offer
preferential discounts for Windows products to hardware makers it
considers partners. The company has also offered to open up its
Windows source code, which would make it easier for rivals to to
make their own programs work smoothly with the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is reportedly also willing to sell a version of
Windows without a bundled Web browser. This has been a prime
objective of the government. Previously, Microsoft held the browser
was locked into the code and could not be removed without damaging
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concessions, continuing disagreement in the
prosecutorial camp could make to more difficult for Jackson to
frame a clear-cut proposal, said University of Baltimore Law School
professor Bob Lande.
</P>
<P>
   Transcripts of bench conferences during the trial indicate that
Jackson will insist that the Justice Department and the 19 state
attorneys general present a common brief on remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be unreasonable to assume that were some
hard-liners among the states who were willing to take their chances
with Judge Jackson,'' said William Kovacic, a George Washington
University Law School professor who has followed the case closely.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is likely to give both sides a month or so to submit
briefs and rebuttals. The key legal players will then appear in
court for the final time to present their oral arguments on what
should be done.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by past practice, Jackson will be inclined to also seek
the advice of outside experts in intellectual property law and high
technology before deciding Microsoft's fate. At his option, he
could eventually adopt or ignore the proposals suggested by the
litigants.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would then remain free to appeal, all the way up the
Supreme Court, a legal process that could consume several years.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
