<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-LAROUCHE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
RULING A BLOW TO LaROUCHE 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday struck a blow to fringe
presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche, upholding a lower court
ruling that the Democratic Party legally refused to count votes
cast for him during the 1996 presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   LaRouche said the party violated the federal Voting Rights Act
by discounting electoral support he received in Arizona, Louisiana,
Texas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The voting rights law requires these states, due to a history of
discriminating against minority voters, to get approval from the
Justice Department or a federal judge before they change their
methods of tabulating votes. LaRouche argued that the states
ignored that requirement in allowing the Democratic Party to void
votes cast for him.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., dismissed
LaRouche's claim. The court said the Voting Rights Act does not
apply to political parties, which have a constitutional right of
association to exclude undesirables from their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who considered the appeal directly from the
district court, issued no opinion in upholding the decision but
simply issued a one-line statement saying they affirmed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   LaRouche has run unsuccessfully for the Democratic presidential
nomination in every election year since 1976, including while he
was serving five years in prison for mail fraud and conspiracy
during the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
