<HEADLINE>
$ADV03 
 ARE TONSILS NECESSARY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., APRIL 3, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM MEN'S HEALTH) 
 By the Editors of Men's Health 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: When I was a kid I had my tonsils removed. Didn't I
need them for something? _ J,D., Waukegan, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: They're your first line of defense against germs, but
you can get by without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonsils are made of lymphoid tissue and exist to fight
infection,'' says Dr. Ralph Wetmore, associate professor of
otolaryngology at the University of Pennsylvania school of medicine
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But in battling bacteria the tonsils can become infected,
swollen and irritated, and that can make you even sicker than the
germs can. In the past, infected tonsils were often removed. Today,
antibiotics are the treatment of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Being tonsil-free isn't a big deal, Wetmore says. The back of
your throat has lymph nodes that perform the same function as the
tonsils.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My face turns beet-red after I drink half a glass of
alcohol. I'm Asian, and I've noticed that this happens in other
Asian men. What causes this, and is there anything I can do about
it? _ D.C., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: See your general practitioner or a dermatologist before
you start looking like W.C. Fields. It sounds as if you may have
rosacea, a chronic skin condition that occurs in Asians but is more
prevalent in people of northern European or Celtic descent, says
Dr. Sherwin K. Parikh, a dermatologist at New York-Presbyterian
Medical Center. People with rosacea experience flushing in response
to sun, hot water, alcohol or eating spicy foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol is a common trigger, so is exercise,'' Parikh says.
``But I don't recommend giving them up completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Facial flushing is caused by dilated blood vessels, and the
extra blood at the skin's surface causes the reddish hue. If your
doctor diagnoses rosacea, he may prescribe topical creams
containing sulfur or cortisone or oral antibiotics to help keep the
skin calm and under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also ease rosacea by knowing your triggers, rinsing
your face with cool water after exercise and using sunscreen,''
Parikh says.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm a machinist and am on my feet for 10 hours a day,
five days a week. At the end of the day my feet, ankles and knees
are killing me. How can I stop them from hurting? _ A.A.,
McKeesport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: Make the ground you're standing on a little softer. Put
in a request for a contoured mat, says Justin Wernick, professor
and chairman of orthopedic sciences at New York College of
Podiatric Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be much easier on your feet than standing on a hard
concrete floor,'' Wernick says.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you probably need to change what's on your feet. Buy a
pair of shoes specifically designed for industrial use _ not
sneakers, no matter how comfortable they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletic shoes are designed for movement, not long periods of
standing, so they compress quickly and wear out fast,'' Wernick
says. ``Red Wing, Coleman and Drew are three companies that make
good industrial footwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Your shoes should be leather with a firm heel cup and a flexible
crepe or Vibram sole that bends with your foot. You're better off
if you buy ankle-high shoes, which provide more support than
lower-cut ones. You might also want to line your shoes with a
contoured insole. They're available at drugstores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Ask Men's Health, 33 East Minor St.,
Emmaus, PA 18098. Or visit the Men's Health web site
(www.men'shealth.com) to send questions electronically. Questions
of general interest will be answered in this column.  &QL;
</P>
