A9468 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RODALE-KEEPING-FIT-AD     03-27 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODALE-KEEPING-FIT-ADV03-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV03 
 GET A KICK OUT OF EXERCISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., APRIL 3, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION) 
 (Includes electronic art.) 
 By MARGO TROTT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the birth of her third child seven years ago, Perri
Newell, 44, of Huntington Beach, Calif., was looking for a fun way
to get back into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a team activity, not something solo where your
only goal is fitness,'' Newell says.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper article about a local women's soccer league and her
daughter's participation in the sport sparked her interest. It
wasn't long before she caught soccer fever.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Newell's love of the game did more than just keep her
fit. It also helped her cope with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept focusing on looking forward to playing again, and my
teammates were very supportive,'' she says. Today, Newell is back
on the soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   Newell is not a lone star. Since the U.S. women's victory in the
1999 World Cup, the number of adult women's, men's and coed leagues
is increasing, with first-time players _ many in their 30s, 40s and
50s _ coming out to get exercise, learn a new sport and socialize.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FUN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not only a soccer mom, but a soccer-playing mom,'' says
Sue Emerson, 44, of West Friendship, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 12-year-old son coaches me and watches me play. He thinks
it's great that I'm out on the field, and it gives us something in
common to talk about, especially as he gets older.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many women of her generation, soccer wasn't an option when
Chris Curran, 42, of Cincinnati, was growing up. But while coaching
her daughter's soccer team, Curran was drafted by other parents to
play. Being part of a team has made exercising easier _ and more
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a social aspect connected to exercise, you're
more likely to show up,'' Curran says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO EXPERIENCE? NO PROBLEM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a superstar to play,'' Newell says.
</P>
<P>
   The team works together, so novices get support from experienced
players. There are teams for all levels of ability _ from
recreational teams for beginners to more competitive, premier teams
for the experienced. In recreational leagues, no one expects you to
be Pele, so don't fret if you can't bounce the ball off your head
or juggle it from knee to knee.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on running and kicking. Let your legs do most of the work.
Soccer requires some stamina, so if you're looking to get back in
shape safely, start by being a substitute player, going in for a
few minutes here and there. This gradually improves your endurance
and helps the team by letting others take a break.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to volunteer to coach or referee. You'll learn
the game, get some exercise and have fun working with the kids.
Most leagues are happy to have new volunteers, and they'll gladly
train you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10 REASONS TO TRY SOCCER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. So much fun _ it doesn't feel like exercise. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Improves endurance. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. Builds self-confidence. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. Helps you meet new people. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. Burns about 476 calories an hour (based on a 150-pound person). &QL; 
 &UR; 6. Helps you bond with your kids. &QL; 
 &UR; 7. Strengthens and tones legs. &QL; 
 &UR; 8. Sparks friendly competition. &QL; 
 &UR; 9. Teaches team skills. &QL; 
 &UR; 10. Makes you feel adventurous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO GET IN THE GAME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Find a team: Check with your local parks and recreation
department, youth soccer leagues, local sporting-goods stores or
try the yellow pages under soccer for adult leagues. You can also
go online at www.womensoccer.org. Fees to play in an organized
league are about $35 to $60 per season.
</P>
<P>
   To find the right team for your skill level, ask the following
questions. Can you substitute or practice with the team before
joining? What division is best for first-timerscoed, over-40,
over-50 or women's only? Is there someone available to teach you
how to play?
</P>
<P>
   Gear: Cleats for outdoor play ($20 to $60), soccer flats or
cross-training sneakers for indoor play ($20 to $110), shin guards
($7 to $20), knee pads for indoor play ($5 to $20). All are
available at most major sporting-goods stores. &QL;
</P>
