<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, March. 28 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-REACT (Washington) _ Assessing the reaction among political
donors and fund-raisers to Vice President Al Gore's latest campaign
finance proposal. Gore on Monday proposed the elimination of the
unlimited donations known as soft money and creation of a $7
billion endowment to finance all general election campaigns for
Congress, using tax-deductible contributions from the corporations,
unions and individuals that now underwrite most political
campaigns. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ The city and the Brooklyn
Museum settle a dispute arising from the Sensations exhibit. The
city agrees to back off, in accordance with a temporary restraining
order obtained by the museum, and make the capital repairs it had
hinted it might not be kindly disposed toward. Each side pays its
own legal fees. By Alan Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN (Trenton, N.J.) _ Running against motherhood
or apple pie you could understand. But running against the boom?
With much of New Jersey awash in prosperity it seems like an odd
strategy. But in New Jersey's U.S. Senate contest, unlike any major
political race in the country, unusual circumstances have
transformed the Democratic primary into a race that has put the
economic boom on trial. Jon Corzine, the former co-chairman of
Goldman Sachs, has said that his work on Wall Street helped New
Jersey companies create and retain hundreds of thousands of jobs.
Those arguments have prompted his opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio,
to warn voters that a dark cloud has been obscured by the economic
silver lining. On issues ranging from Social Security and pension
funding to corporate mergers, trade policy and government
borrowing, Florio has hammered his opponent with the kind of
class-based attacks Democrats usually aim at Republicans. By David
Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   NY-FOSTER-CARE (New York) _ Thousands of young adults in New
York City's foster care system, many of whom were neglected or
abandoned during the height of the city's crack epidemic a decade
ago, have been ``aging out'' of the system in recent years, left at
age 18 to fend for themselves, often with little in the way of
education or financial resources. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-FARMERS (Ackley, Iowa) _ Rising before dawn for Sunday
chores, Darwin Hoffmeister fed the pigs, checked the cows and
mended a trampled fence. But he could not tie his shoes.
Hoffmeister, a 50-year-old Iowa farmer, lost four fingers and the
use of his left arm in a combine accident five years ago, the kind
of dreadful mishap that makes farming one of the nation's most
dangerous professions. He is one of thousands of farmers in America
with disabilities who have triumphed over physical adversities, a
survival made possible by technological advances and the changed
nature of farming, which today relies more on brain power and
computer skills than mere brute strength. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT23,24.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Pope John Paul II flew away, and
this is how the morning after looked in Israel: diminished
prospects for peace with Syria, the opening of a politically
explosive criminal investigation into a leading rabbi, and five
separate Parliament votes of no confidence in the government. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   GUYANA-HAMMOCK-WEAVERS (Lethem, Guyana) _ This village in the
remote southern savannah could easily be taken for one of those
far-flung places untouched by the digital revolution. It had no
phones until two years ago, and the concept of paying with money is
still quite foreign to many residents. But it was here that an
organization formed by indigenous women of two tribes revived the
ancient art of hand-weaving large hammocks from locally grown
cotton _ and then took their exquisite wares online. They hired a
young member to create a Web site. And last year, they sold 17
hammocks to people around the world for as much as $1,000 apiece,
gigantic sums in these parts. But the foray into electronic
commerce created tension between the weavers and the traditional
regional leadership. Threatened by the women's success, regional
leaders moved in and took control of the weavers' organization. The
woman who created the Web site quit in a fury, and the group has
been struggling since then to get by. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
