<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crescendos of hype raise expectations for markets
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There have always been losers and winners in the stock
market. But never before has Wall Street raised expectations so
high, and never before have the media been cheerleaders and
stock-pushers, Business Week (April 3) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasts from the floor of the New York Stock Exchange have
propelled once-obscure financial journalists to celebrity status
and has made CNBC to investors what ESPN is to sports fans, the
magazine notes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, says Professor Bing Liang of Case Western Reserve
University, is that when ``experts'' recommend a stock in the
media, the resulting abnormal returns and trading volumes are
driven by ``noise trading from naive investors.'' On average,
investors following these recommendations lose 3.8 percent over six
months.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as the bull market roars forward, Business Week says
the press releases will spew forth, the brokerage ads will offer
images of easy money, the business-TV pundits will pontificate _
and the public, with its growing propensity for short-term trading,
``will continue to lap it up.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report (April 3) engages in a bit of what
Business Week was talking about with an article on ``market
mania,'' which offers ``some help'' to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine suggests a set of ``new tools'' that investors can
use in their decision-making, replacing the ``old tools'' of the
old market. For example, the magazine says the price-to-earnings
ratio, used to value share price against profitability, can be
replaced by a ``business model'' that looks at such items as
advertising as a percentage of sales.
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE-FRIENDLY PROFESSION
</P>
<P>
   TV journalism may be hype to Business Week, but Working Woman
(April) sees it as an avenue of success for women. It profiles
Willow Bay of CNN's ``Moneyline'' as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of years ago, she was co-hosting a Saturday
basketball program on NBC. ``Now, the former model and wife of
Disney bigwig Bob Iger is making her market as the highest-profile
financial reporter on CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting is not the only outlet for women, says the
magazine, citing 10 women who run multimillion-dollar Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   A FORD IN FORD'S FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   William Clay ``Bill'' Ford Jr. is a fourth-generation descendant
of Henry Ford. But when he decided to claim the job of chairman at
Ford Motor Co., he had to battle Chief Executive Alex Trotman, says
Fortune (April 10). The big question, the magazine asks, is can the
younger Ford ``jump-start this Old World auto company and keep
employees, customers and investors happy?''
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FASHIONED STILL WORKS
</P>
<P>
   In today's dot-com world, it's easy to assume that new ideas
only come from young kids working in basements. Not necessarily,
says Inc. (May), which profiles profitable brick-and-mortar
companies that are also winners in the online world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
