<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-U.S.-POET-FRANCE-ART-     03-27 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-POET-FRANCE-ART-1175(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DREAMS ARE INDUCED BY LIGHT, LAND AND TRUFFLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LES MAQUIGNONS, France _ Almost 40 years ago, as if summoned by
the ghosts of successive generations of American writers who made
their names in Paris, an aspiring young poet called Gustaf Sobin
left Boston for the French capital, seemingly persuaded that being
an expatriate was a key to literary success. Certainly it was a
form of exile that had worked for two of his favorite writers,
Ernest Hemingway and Ezra Pound, fixtures of the Left Bank scene
between the wars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no sooner had he arrived in Paris in 1962 than his plans
were disrupted by a chance meeting with Rene Char, a French poet
whom he much admired. ``If you love my poetry,'' Char told him,
``you must visit Provence, because my poetry comes out of the
earth, the land, the light.'' Sobin traveled to the south and fell
under its spell. The next year he bought an abandoned stone
building on the edge of a Provencal village and made it his home,
forever.
</P>
<P>
   In Provence, he had found a sense of place that had eluded him
during his upbringing in New England. And now, able to survive on
$2,000 per year, the income from a trust fund, he was in no hurry
for success. He continued to write poetry, as he had from the age
of 20, but it went unpublished until 1972, when he was 37. In 1988,
by now respected as a poet, he turned his hand to prose, but his
first two novels, ``Venus Blue'' and ``Dark Mirrors,'' went largely
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his third novel, ``The Fly-Truffler,'' published in
January, wider recognition has suddenly come his way. And he is a
bit taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I didn't write novels for the attention,'' the
64-year-old writer said shyly, sipping apple juice in his home,
which was enlarged over the years to accommodate his wife,
Susannah, a painter, and their two now-grown children, ``but it is
certainly a pleasure to receive.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for a man who opted for a rural life of isolation and
reflection, attention in some distant city remains all too abstract
a concept. More real is the repetitive rhythm of his daily life in
the unchanging landscape of Vaucluse, 20 miles east of Avignon.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn, as peasants head for their fields, he goes to work in a
tiny studio on a nearby ridge. And from its window, he looks across
a vineyard, above the tiled roofs of Les Maquignons and over a
sprawling valley toward towering Mount Ventoux. His muse _ this
land and its lore _ is all around him.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, since he moved here 37 years ago, Provence has changed.
Centuries-old farms and cottages have been taken over by northern
Europeans, whose very invasion was symbolized and stimulated by
Peter Mayle's huge 1990 best seller, ``A Year in Provence.''
</P>
<P>
   And the ancient Provencal language, once routinely heard in
village cafes, is now spoken only by old peasants and a handful of
intellectuals. ``The Fly-Truffler'' does not turn back the clock,
but it is Sobin's poignant hymn to a vanishing Provence.
</P>
<P>
   Its central character, Philippe Cabassac, a loner nearing 50,
lectures at the University of Avignon on the Provencal language,
itself an exercise in linguistic archaeology and conservation.
There he meets Julieta, a beautiful student half his age who is
writing her dissertation on silkworms, another lost feature of
Provencal life.
</P>
<P>
   Julieta moves in with Cabassac, at first seemingly for
convenience, then sharing his bed and soon, pregnant, exploding
with passion. But she loses her child, slowly disconnects from life
and dies.
</P>
<P>
   Sobin's 155-page novel actually tells the story differently,
more as a flashback relived by Cabassac through dreams provoked by
eating truffles. The truffle season is short, at most December to
February, and it is then that Cabassac wanders his property looking
obsessively for the golden flies that identify truffles growing 1
or 2 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual is important. He keeps the dark tubers for three
days, and then dices them into ``perfect little rounds'' that he
adds to three beaten eggs. After eating the omelet he retires to
bed and picks up his previous night's dream of Julieta. He is happy
only when in this truffle-induced reverie, and his ordinary life
falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing what he called Sobin's ``marvelous, mesmerizing new
novel'' in The New York Times last month, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
wrote: ``It is one of those rare, haunting novels that you consume
in a single sitting and that you put down wondering what day it is
and where you are, as if awakening from one of Cabassac's
enrapturing dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobin said he set out to write a book that he, as its first
reader, would find persuasive. ``One has to fall almost into a
hypnosis, the hallucination one has created,'' he said. ``And if
one doesn't, no one else will.''
</P>
<P>
   Having plotted out his book, however, he still had a problem.
How could truffles induce dreams? ``You can't put that one over, I
thought, it's impossible,'' he recalled. ``And I asked a young
peasant friend, by consuming the truffle, could one have a
beautiful dream? He said something so delicate: He said no, but it
could put you in the disposition to have a beautiful dream. This
word, `disposition,' was the click. I knew I had my novel.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a novel in which Cabassac's excavation in search of
truffles aptly symbolizes Sobin's own relationship with Provence.
The writer laments the popularization of Mayle's ``superficial
glitzy vision of Provence'' and tries to counter it by digging ever
deeper to find, like Cabassac, a form of redemption. ```The
Fly-Truffler' isn't about a year in Provence,'' he said. ``It's
about an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   This eternity is all too present in another book that Sobin has
recently published, ``Luminous Debris: Reflecting on Vestige in
Provence and Languedoc,'' which comprises 26 essays inspired by
remnants of earlier life in the region, from prehistory through
Roman times.
</P>
<P>
   It is a life extant outside his very home: He looks out over a
vineyard where a Roman villa once stood, and in an adjacent
dry-stone structure that resembles a beehive he once found a stone
altar to the Celtic god of wind.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, wind and light are Provencal eternals that have
also influenced what Sobin likes to call his ``poetry of
celebration of desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistral, which rushes down the tunnel of the Rhone Valley,
is a dry, sterile male wind, harrowing, exhausting, exhilarating,''
he said. ``Then, we have the marinade that comes out of the south,
wet and warm and richly fertilizing for the earth. These winds are
pure opposites, yet there is this wonderful coexistence between
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Light, too, is a defining spirit here, drawing generations of
painters to its illuminated colors. ``Some people even consider it
divine, this beautiful diffused luminosity, without any mist,
uninterrupted by tall trees,'' the writer said, recalling his
excitement many years ago at the thought that Picasso could be
painting in the same light. ``You're really under the eye of God or
whomever. It can be quite cosmic, quite metaphysical, quite
overwhelming.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Again, then, there is the sense of place. ``All my poetry starts
with the physical presence of being here,'' he said. ``And
curiously, the more rooted it is in place, the more it rises out of
place, that is, the more anchored in specifics, the more I can rise
to a higher level.'' Indeed, when he turned to prose, his
sustenance remained Provence, even though ``Venus Blue'' and his
next novel, ``For Her Lashes Alone,'' are not set there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Provence is continuously nourishing for work, reflection,
thought,'' he said. ``I'm here and there is enough here for the
poetry and prose and essay writing for 10 lifetimes. I don't need
to move except for wonderful field trips into the mountains or down
to the sea. But I find that everything is here, at least within the
breadth of my imagination and the limits of my intellect, enough
for 10 lifetimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes it all possible is the instrument of language, in
his case the conciseness of poetry that gives intense sensuality to
his prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``As so, choosing one word over another,'' he writes of Julieta
in ``The Fly-Truffler,'' ``hesitating here, precipitating there,
editing her own speech a bit everywhere, she offered Cabassac a
portrait of herself _ of her wayward existence _ in which the
words, seemingly, had far more consistency than the events
themselves.'' In the end, then, for Sobin too, it is the words that
count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
