<SLUG> BC-BASS-EXPANSION28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bass Hotels targeting Latin America
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts is expanding its family of
midmarket hotels in Latin America and plans to double its presence
in the region within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Arasi, president of Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts, the Americas,
said the global lodging giant plans to increase the number of
Holiday Inn, Holiday Inn Express, Staybridge Suites and Crowne
Plaza hotels. The upscale Inter-Continental brand, which Bass
acquired in 1998, already has a significant presence there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take that existing operating base and use it to
grow through the other price segments,'' Arasi said. Latin America
``is a market that has a lot of international and domestic demand.
This is a market of growing importance for us.''
</P>
<P>
   London-based Bass maintains headquarters for its Americas
operations in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Scott D. Berman, a partner with PricewaterhouseCoopers in Miami
and an expert in the lodging industry, said the Latin American
market is ``screaming for an affordable choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America presents a tremendous opportunity for midmarket
hotel brands because so few exist today,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Arasi said Bass is targeting major markets in countries such as
Brazil, Argentina, Chile and Ecuador. The company plans five new
Holiday Inns each in Brazil and Argentina during the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil will be the site of a Staybridge Suites by Holiday Inn,
an extended stay hotel. Staybridge will open a 356-suite, 18-story
hotel in mid-2002. A 100-suite Staybridge Suites is to open in
Brasilia as part of a project that will also house an
Inter-Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Bass is primarily interested in managing and franchising brands
in Latin America, with no company-owned hotels planned.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bass signed a deal with a major Mexican
hotel company to triple the number of Crowne Plaza hotels in that
country over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
