<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-LABELS-BOS &LR;      03-27 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LABELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABELING GM FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This page supports the genetic modification of crops as a
service to mankind and believes that most of the protest against it
is unscientific and wrong. However, for an industry rightfully
confident of the safety of its products, biotech companies are
surprisingly resistant to requirements that foods carry labels
identifying genetic modification. The industry's fear that a
gene-modified label will become a symbolic ``skull and crossbones''
and hurt sales only reflects the challenge facing the industry to
better educate consumers. The answer to consumer ignorance is not
more ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   As safe as every test examined by the Food and Drug
Administration, the Department of Agriculture, and the
Environmental Protection Agency has shown these foods to be, the
public has a right to know what goes into its corn flakes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being more up-front about the fact that a third of
all US-grown corn and about 55 percent of all soybeans are already
gene-modified, the industry has treated this change as a slight
adjustment in fertilization schedules. It isn't _ it's a revolution
in the way crops are developed.
</P>
<P>
   Used primarily until now to give crops built-in protection
against pests or weed-killers, the technology offers the promise of
substantially increasing the nutritional value of foodstuffs.
Already, there is talk of ``golden rice'' bolstered with
beta-carotene to combat Vitamin A decifiency, a major problem in
many developing countries. Ultimately, a genetically modified tag
on a grocery item is likely to be a selling point, just as the
label ``pasteurized'' on milk has long been.
</P>
<P>
   Many European countries already require the labels. The industry
has fiercely resisted labeling in this country, but it shouldn't.
By not acknowledging the role of bioengineering in modern
agriculture and arguing for its merits in public forums, the
industry runs the risk of a backlash by a public that thinks it has
been hoodwinked.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late for industry to adopt a full disclosure
policy, both on labels of GM products and to the public of what
this ultimately beneficial change in food production is all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-PROBE28-COX     03-27 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-PROBE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EX-OFFICIAL FACES GRILLING OVER DEALS TO FORGIVE MEDICARE DEBT
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former top Clinton administration official will
appear before a congressional panel Tuesday to answer allegations
that Medicare improperly forgave more than $200 million owed by
three of the nation's biggest health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vladeck, who headed the Health Care Financing
Administration from 1993 to 1997, was expected to challenge the
findings of an eight-month investigation that he pressured his
staff to negotiate the settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The three deals, settling $332 million in debts to Medicare,
were so lenient that they were kept secret, partly so they would
not become precedents for other health care providers, said a
report by the U.S. General Accounting Office, the investigative arm
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said the debt settlements were never reviewed by
government lawyers. In fact, one official working under Vladeck
told the GAO that he avoided consulting attorneys because he feared
the ``deals would go up in smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, said Monday that ``the evidence
suggests that HCFA staff short-circuited the routine process
because of pressure applied by'' Vladeck.
</P>
<P>
   Collins chairs the Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations,
which will question the major players in the controversy Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said the HCFA agreements may have violated the
Federal Claims Collection Act, which requires most debt settlement
plans over $100,000 to be cleared by the Justice Department.
Moreover, the investigation faulted Vladeck for having an
appearance of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck had previous ties with two of the health care groups
involved. Before joining the Clinton administration, he served on
the board of directors of the New York City Health and Hospitals
Corp. The corporation negotiated its $155 million debt for improper
past billings down to just $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   He also had sat on an advisory committee for the Visiting Nurse
Service of New York, which won an agreement to repay $67 million of
the $98 million it owed Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In the third settlement, HCFA accepted $28 million as repayment
for $79.4 million in debts owed by the Department of Health
Services in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   The debts dated as far back as 1991. Under Medicare procedures,
reimbursements are reviewed, and Medicare seeks repayment for
services that are found to be improper or undocumented. The three
cases represented some of the largest owed Medicare during the past
decade. All were settled during Vladeck's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Anello, an attorney who was helping Vladeck prepare for
his testimony Tuesday, said Monday that the former official
``endeavored to convey the message, inside the agency and out, that
the primary responsibility of HCFA was to ensure that its
beneficiaries had access to high-quality health care when they
needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements at issue, which he did not negotiate, did just
that. They ensured continued and uninterrupted health care to
millions of this countries' poorest citizens and among some of its
sickest.''
</P>
<P>
   HCFA, responding to the investigation, has said that it has
begun its own review of the debt settlement issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident there has been no violation of the Federal
Claims Collection Act,'' said HCFA spokesman Chris Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he said the agency has hired a certified public
accountant to oversee debt collection and has developed ``a number
of new checks and balances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
