</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER28-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST LEDE WRITE-THRU
 &HT;    Adds REFORM PARTY GIVEN OVER TO CHOATE as 2nd brief; updates 7th
brief
 &HT;    
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore gives campaign finance reform plan a
twist
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore acknowledged Monday he was an ``imperfect messenger''
for campaign finance changes as he offered new proposals _ a
``Democracy Endowment'' and strict disclosure rules _ to attract
John McCain supporters and inoculate himself against George W.
Bush's repeated attacks on Gore's past fund-raising abuses. Gore
announced his plan at a campaign appearance in Milwaukee:
Elimination of soft money and the creation of a $7 billion national
endowment to provide public financing of federal political
campaigns, beginning in 2008. ``The real wounds will be to our
democracy itself unless we address this problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY GIVEN OVER TO CHOATE
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party chairmanship belongs to Pat Choate, Ross
Perot's 1996 presidential running mate. That's what a federal judge
decided Monday in a tug-of-war that had weakened the party's
standing in the 2000 campaign. U.S. District Judge Norman Moon in
Lynchburg, Va., ordered Jack Gargan, who had fought Choate for the
chairmanship, and Treasurer Ronn Young to stop all activities
relating to their previous positions, including soliciting
donations on behalf of the Reform Party, spending the party's
money, operating an official Web site and planning the party's
convention. ``This will now allow us to go forth and mount a
competitive race for the White House this fall,'' Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   ROBB IN FOR ANOTHER TOUGH FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Charles Robb, whose 1994 race in Virginia
against Iran-Contra figure Oliver North was one of that year's most
bitterly contested, kicked off his campaign for a third term
against another former governor of the state. George Allen has
built a sizable lead in fund-raising and started his campaign
months ago, but Robb warned him that he faces a tough fight for the
only statewide elected office that Republicans do not control.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK ACTIVIST QUITS GOP
</P>
<P>
   A black Republican activist who had been vice chairman of a
high-profile GOP effort to recruit minorities says she has left the
party because a ``pattern of racial blunders'' left her feeling
abandoned. Faye Anderson quit the GOP, according to Gannett News
Service, with no explanation in a terse March 13 letter to Patricia
Harrison, co-chair of the Republican National Committee. Anderson
had been vice chairman of the New Majority Council, which the GOP
established in 1997 to reach out to minorities. But in her weekly
column for politicallyblack.com, Anderson said she switched from
registered Republican to independent because she no longer believes
that party leaders were serious about inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   NOT THE RIGHT KIND OF GAYS?
</P>
<P>
   The Log Cabin Republicans, according to ABCNews.com, are
``disappointed by reports'' that George W. Bush has decided not to
meet with the organization and are ready to take their case to the
public. Said Log Cabin spokesman Kevin Ivers: ``It appears from the
latest comments that we are not the right kind of gays, and that we
were McCain supporters _ both of which seem to disqualify us from
even consideration of being part of this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ONLY THE CENSUS BUREAU WILL COUNT HIM
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled Monday that the Democratic Party
lawfully refused to count votes cast for political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche in the 1996 presidential primaries. The court, upholding
lower court rulings, rejected LaRouche's argument that the
Democratic Party's rules should have been cleared by the Justice
Department under the federal Voting Rights Act. Monday's ruling was
issued without an accompanying opinion. The justices merely
affirmed what a federal appeals court had previously ruled.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP A CLOSER EYE ON THE MONEY, GUYS
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission says the Reform Party needs to
keep the government better informed of where the organization's
millions of taxpayer dollars are kept. Nearly $2.5 million in
public money that was given to the third party for its nominating
convention was not stored in the Martinsville, Va., bank that party
officers had named in their funding application. Instead, according
to the FEC, the money was spread among at least four bank accounts
from Virginia to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE REFORM NAME IN VAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party of New Hampshire announced it will sue Pat
Buchanan's presidential campaign for $10 million, alleging wrongful
use of its name in a recent mailing to the group's members. John
Talbott, the group's acting state chairman, said he also will seek
federal mail fraud charges against Buchanan Reform, the name of
Buchanan's national campaign. Talbott said a pamphlet mailed by
Buchanan's campaign promoted an April 1 meeting in Manchester as
the Reform Party's state convention. He said the Buchanan campaign
does not have the authority to use the party's name or elect state
delegates for the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP(TON) KNIVES COME OUT
</P>
<P>
   If Rudy Giuliani's handlers could have their way, his opponent
in this year's New York Senate race would not be Hillary Rodham
Clinton, but Hillary Sharpton Clinton. Giuliani's aides are doing
everything they can to create the perception that she and Al
Sharpton are siblings in spirit, if not in blood. In campaign
fliers and in public comments, the mayor and his advisers have
stopped just short of portraying the activist minister from Harlem
as a person who advises an attentive Clinton in ways that would set
the republic on the path to perdition. They have begun to respond
to any criticism of the mayor's actions by throwing out one name:
Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING THE TABLES ON CARPETBAGGING
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani is planning three fund-raising events in
Tennessee, and state Democratic leaders say he is ``carpetbagging''
for money. Giuliani has three such events set for April 5 in
Knoxville, Nashville and Memphis. The Tennessee trip ``is a bit of
carpetbagging'' to raise money, a term often applied to Hillary
Rodham Clinton's Senate bid in New York, said Greg Wanderman, head
of the Tennessee Democratic Party. ``I don't know that Rudy has
ever stepped foot in Tennessee except to raise a dime,'' Wanderman
said.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY WELCOMES SMALL PARTY'S SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton picked up the first political party
endorsement of the campaign. ``I consider this the beginning of a
partnership,'' Clinton told the convention of the Working Families
Party, a small, labor union-backed third party. She promised to be
``a voice and a vote'' in the Senate for working families. The
Working Families Party was created in New York two years ago to
push the Democratic Party toward the left, and to help Charles
Schumer against Republican incumbent Sen. Alfonse D'Amato. Schumer
won that race.
</P>
<P>
   GOP'S FIRST BABY BOOMER
</P>
<P>
   Youthfulness and a generational shift represent a changing of
the guard for the Republican Party. George W. Bush, whose birthday
is July 6, will be 54 years old when he wins the his party's
presidential nomination in August, as expected. That will make him
the GOP's youngest presidential nominee in 40 years. It also will
make him the first Republican nominee in more than 30 years who is
almost the same age as his Democratic rival _ Al Gore will be 53 at
the Democratic National Convention _ and the first who was born too
late to have had any involvement in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   IMPORTANCE OF STAYING ON FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   Extensive polling and campaign analysis by the Annenberg Public
Policy Center pointed to the value of intensive primary campaigns
to voters and the worth of hammering home what a candidate would do
if elected. If the primary season appeared to hurt George W. Bush
and help Al Gore, the study suggests that Bush's intense fight to
win the Republican nomination, consistent tax-cutting message and
critical focus on Al Gore could pay dividends, said Kathleen Hall
Jamieson, a lead researcher at the Annenberg center at the
University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
