<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-REZULIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE FOR CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the brave new world of accelerated drug approvals by the US
Food and Drug Administration, the case of the diabetes medicine
Rezulin is a cautionary tale. Introduced in 1997 as a way to lower
blood sugar by making the body more sensitive to its own insulin,
Rezulin was pulled off the market last week after its use was
linked to 90 cases of liver failure and 63 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, this would seem to be an indictment of the
process that approved the drug after tests in 2,500 patients. In 2
to 4 percent of patients, there were liver abnormalities, but no
cases of actual liver failure. It was only when Rezulin began to be
prescribed in great quantities _ 1.9 million people have used it _
that its full risks became known.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is really more in the failure of regulators to
require close liver monitoring from the first use of Rezulin. While
doctors from the start were advised not to prescribe it for
patients with liver problems, it was only after the first cases of
liver failure were reported that the FDA actually recommended liver
monitoring. Eventually, the FDA required monthly tests.
</P>
<P>
   For some diabetics Rezulin is so effective that the FDA might
not have withdrawn it were there not two promising and apparently
safer replacements available. What the Rezulin case best
demonstrates is that, since many drugs have serious side effects,
their introduction into the market must be accompanied by more
stringent precautions, such as close screening of patients
receiving the new drug and frequent monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the lesson in the decision last week by another
pharmaceutical manufacturer to withdraw a drug for severe
heartburn, Propulsid, from the market this summer. Propulsid has
been associated with 80 deaths and 341 heart-rhythm abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for regulators, drug makers, physicians, and
patients is to balance the severity of the condition the drug
treats with the frequency and gravity of side effects and the
availability of alternatives. And always they must err on the side
of caution in requiring close screening and monitoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
