<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUBCONTINENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TILTING TOWARD INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's visit to the Indian subcontinent, the first
by an American president in a generation, accomplished little in
the short run but reflects a historic, long-range shift in US
national interests.
</P>
<P>
   The president failed to get either the Indians or the Pakistanis
to give up their atomic weapons or to ameliorate their quarrel over
Kashmir. Nevertheless, the proportionality of the five days in
India and the five hours in Pakistan signified the shift in
American priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades following the birth of independent India there
had been a certain antagonism between the United States and India.
Indians found Americans overbearing and obsessed with Cold War
politics. Americans found Indians insufferably sanctimonious. India
may have been ``the world's bigget democracy,'' or so went the
cliche, but India's adherence to socialism went down badly in
Washington, and India's close friendship with the Soviet Union was
worse. Indians could never understand why the United States was so
interested in China and so uninterested in cultivating their
country.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the United States pick up Pakistan, India's archrival,
with whom India would fight three wars, as an American client. The
Pakistanis weren't particularly democratic, but they were a
straightforward Cold War ally. When India went to war with Pakistan
over Bangladesh, then-President Nixon ordered a ``tilt'' toward
Pakistan. When it came time to organize a resistance to the Soviet
invasion of Afghanistan, Pakistan and the United States again
worked closely together.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now. Pakistan is no longer needed
in the Cold War struggle, and its undemocratic, near-dysfunctional
state has become an embarrassment. India, on the other hand, with
its great size, its democratic institutions, and, perhaps more
important, its new industrial strength in computer sciences, is
beginning to loom large in Washington and in board rooms across
America.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Indians and the Pakistanis understood the message
behind Clinton's visit, even though he did not articulate it
directly, proving the old adage that nations don't have friends,
only interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
