<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OSCARS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-27 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR VICTORY FINALLY LIFTS THE CLOUD OF DREAMWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 20-22, 25,26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(EDS: See also TV-OSCARS) 
(jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ A long line of limousines waited to send their
passengers onto a red carpet bathed in television lights and
leading to a black canvas tent sprawling across Canon Drive in
Beverly Hills, closed to traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, red rose arrangements decorated the tables, waiters
passed through the black-tie throng with trays of Champagne and
pink-hued cosmopolitans, Hollywood's hot cocktail of the moment. In
the adjacent Spago restaurant, to which the tent connected,
hundreds more mingled and munched and applauded the arrival of
Oscar winners clutching their lustrous trophies like power totems.
</P>
<P>
   And on the outside of the tent, every few feet, the same word
was emblazoned over and over: DreamWorks ... DreamWorks ...
DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after this mini-studio was founded by Steven
Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen and only three years
after it began releasing movies, DreamWorks SKG had at last risen
to the top of the pecking order, for one night, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The studio's ``American Beauty,'' a relatively low-budget ($15
million) comedy about dysfunctional suburbanites, was the big
winner at Sunday night's Academy Awards, taking honors for best
picture (to its producers, Dan Jinks and Bruce Cohen), best actor
(Kevin Spacey), best director (the first-time filmmaker Sam
Mendes), best original screenplay (Alan Ball, also a first-timer)
and best cinematography (Conrad L. Hall, who last won an Oscar, his
first, for ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'').
</P>
<P>
   It was sweet vindication for the studio, which last year saw its
heavily favored ``Saving Private Ryan'' lose the best-picture Oscar
to Miramax's ``Shakespeare in Love,'' although Spielberg won the
award for best director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a compliment to be considered to be in rivalry
with Miramax, which has been around doing great work for quite a
while,'' said Walter Parks, head of the motion picture division at
DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a few eyebrows raised in October 1994 when
the three principals announced they were forming Hollywood's newest
movie studio. The skepticism increased when several years passed
before the first film (``The Peacemaker'') was released by the
studio, when plans to build a new studio complex near Los Angeles
International Airport were shelved and when Spielberg, the studio's
most notable filmmaking asset, went on a two-year hiatus from
directing.
</P>
<P>
   But DreamWorks officials contend that the awards are a sign of
the fledgling studio's growing strength and the sense that it is
finally coming together.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that the wins for `American Beauty' does,''
said Parks, ``is it continues a shift in focus in the company away
from being just about our three very visible founders onto where we
all think it was always meant to be: on all of our filmmakers and
the movies they make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the simplest level,'' he said, ``I hope the fact that a
traditional Hollywood studio would not only make a movie like
`American Beauty' but would know how to market it aggressively and
would act as a magnet for a certain kind of filmmaker we'd love to
work with the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the ``American Beauty'' Oscar triumph mean that DreamWorks
has at last turned the corner and begun to jell? Its executives say
yes, pointing to a new film lineup that includes Russell Crowe in
Ridley Scott's ``Gladiator,'' Will Smith and Matt Damon in Robert
Redford's ``Legend of Bagger Vance'' and ``Chicken Run,'' the first
animated feature by Nick Park, the three-time Oscar-winning
short-film director of the ``Wallace and Gromit'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only dark cloud for DreamWorks on Sunday night came
when Annette Bening, nine months pregnant and sitting in the Shrine
Auditorium here after watching her husband, Warren Beatty, win the
academy's Irving G. Thalberg Award, lost the best-actress Oscar to
25-year-old Hilary Swank.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it announced the potential arrival of a major new
star. The relatively little-known Swank not only won the award for
playing a young woman who pretends to be a man in ``Boys Don't
Cry,'' but she also did it in a relatively small, independent film
and beat out one of Hollywood's most popular actresses.
</P>
<P>
   With ``American Beauty'' going into the awards as such an early
favorite, much of the inevitable Dreamworks-versus-Miramax
controversy was muted. So Oscar had to look elsewhere for its
dustups.
</P>
<P>
   Many were wondering whether Spacey's victory over Denzel
Washington, the early Oscar favorite for his critically praised
performance in Norman Jewison's ``Hurricane,'' had resulted partly
from the uproar over the accuracy of the film, based on the life of
the boxer Hurricane Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest post-Oscar fuss seemed to be swirling around the
documentary award. For years, there were complaints from
documentary filmmakers that the voting process was skewed to favor
academy insiders and often resulted in awards to films few had
seen. In recent years, the rule was changed to allow all academy
members to vote in the category, but only if they had seen all five
nominated films.
</P>
<P>
   This year's contenders included two films, ``Buena Vista Social
Club'' and ``On the Ropes,'' that were widely released in theaters.
But the winner, ``One Day in September,'' about the murder of
Jewish athletes at the 1972 Olympics, was screened for academy
members in New York, Los Angeles and San Francisco and once in
Boston but not widely released.
</P>
<P>
   So producers of the other films were saying Tuesday that despite
the rule changes the system could still be exploited by an insider
_ it was the third victory for the filmmaker Arthur Cohn _ by
greatly reducing the voting pool. ``Because voters have to see all
five films, the film which is seen by the fewest number of people
thereby has as much of a chance as `Buena Vista Social Club,' which
grossed millions of dollars,'' said Wendy Lidell, a vice president
of WinStar Cinema, the distributor of ``On the Ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Academy Award for documentary feature is going to help
documentaries succeed in the theatrical marketplace, which is very
difficult, then re-examining what constitutes a theatrical release
is perhaps what needs to be done,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Lidell said, ``It always seems to be the film that
nobody's heard of that wins.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday Cohn said that the complaints were
``sour grapes.'' He said he had released it as soon as he was able
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   All of the ``American Beauty'' winners took pains to thank
DreamWorks for, as Parks said, making the dark little comedy and
then marketing it into a $100-million-plus hit and orchestrating an
ambitious and ultimately successful Oscar campaign for it. Mendes
said he was grateful to DreamWorks for giving a first-time film
director whose background was on the British stage a chance to
direct a comedy about American suburbanites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have done this movie for free, and I practically
did,'' he said, gesturing toward Spielberg. ``He owes me a couple
of quid, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 1853EST &QL; 
