<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-27 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROBERT STRAUSS, ETERNALLY YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Living legends in the nation's capital are rare.
The rich and powerful tend to burn out early or give up on the
political wars, and sometimes they go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   But one man has outdistanced practically everyone, friend and
foe alike. Superlawyer Robert Strauss is the ultimate insider, an
influential adviser to both Republican and Democratic presidents.
He is a wheeler-dealer of the old school who is as much an
institution hereabouts as the Senate's wonderful bean soup.
</P>
<P>
   Now a vigorous 81 years old, Strauss proved again in a speech
last weekend before a gathering of big-name journalists that he has
lost neither his fabled sense of humor nor his remarkable political
savvy. He first spoke at the Gridiron Club dinner 25 years ago. He
was then Democratic National Committee chairman and he gave his
party's response to a speech by Republican Vice President Nelson
Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss outclassed Rockefeller that night in 1975, and on
Saturday he also triumphed over his newest partisan competitor at
the podium, former Republican National Committee Chairman Haley
Barbour. Strauss uses humor to make his points, but he knows the
difference between mockery and malice.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, now a high-priced influence peddler like Strauss,
doesn't have that knack. His jokes had more bile than bite.
Strauss, however, concluded his remarks by noting, ``Civility does
not have to be something that only old men like me recollect.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, a Texan and protigi of former Gov. John Connally, rose
in the Democratic ranks the hard way. He earned his fame through
loyalty to his conservative mentors and a skillful mix of politics
and business interests. For years he labored behind the scenes as
an obscure fund-raiser and back-slapper.
</P>
<P>
   He took over the Democratic Party after George McGovern's
disastrous left-wing presidential campaign in 1972 left the party
in ruins. Strauss shoved the leadership back toward centrist common
sense. But he has always had friends and allies across party lines,
as any good mover-and-shaker must. Bob Dole is a buddy, as is
former President George Bush, a fellow Texan who appointed Strauss
ambassador to the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss ran Jimmy Carter's presidential campaign and became
Carter's special trade representative and Middle East envoy.
Between government jobs, he returns to the law firm he helped to
found, one of the most powerful in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss was not born to great wealth, but he has it now. He has
not neglected his own bank account in his love for politics.
Self-sacrifice is not included in his business code. He is
successful at what he does, which is mostly a corporate law
practice that puts the right people together with other right
people. Nothing wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once joked that ``he makes his living giving people
advice on how to undo the advice he gave someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all his closeness to power and money, Strauss has
maintained a reputation for keeping his own hands clean.
Politicians of both parties trust his word. Media types, at least
those of us of the older generation, think he's by far the best of
his breed.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss is famous for getting money out of heavy Democratic
givers, which the Gridiron Club duly noted last weekend in a song
dedicated to the fine art of fleecing the rich. Vernon Jordan, his
latest protigi and President Clinton's golfing chum, is a law firm
partner and Strauss's potential successor as premier Democratic
deal-maker.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Strauss jovially noted that he and Jordan were
recently discussing politics. ``I asked him, `Who in the hell
coined that phrase `Clinton fatigue?' Jordan said, `Mrs.
Clinton.'''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss' jokes were carefully bipartisan. ``George W. thought
that Fettuccine Alfredo was the president of Italy,'' he said. But
he also ribbed Vice President Al Gore's tendency to exaggerate.``I
had no idea he saved John McCain's life in that prison camp!''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Strauss do it? How does he keep going at the top of
his game decade after decade?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how:
</P>
<P>
   Lace everything with a dollop of humor, some of it
self-deprecating, some of it of a put-down nature, which targeted
recipients take in jolly spirit. Do everything with warm
enthusiasm, making companions feel truly wanted and your presence
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your word. Keep your mouth shut about the embarrassing
stuff. Stick to your friends when they are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Be practical. Forget the ideological traps and deal with the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   Like everybody and they will like you. Make the right friends.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cheat. Play it straight, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   And never be a shrinking violet. A little chutzpah goes a long
way.
</P>
<P>
   I think Bob Strauss is great, but don't ask me to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For inexplicable reasons, in a recent column I promoted Rep.
John Edward Porter, R-Ill., to chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee. He is chairman of the Appropriations Committee's labor,
health, human services and education subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
