<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      03-27 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE-BUSH CLASH OVER CAMPAIGN MONEY MAY NOT SPELL ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The clash between Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush over reforming the financing of federal
election campaigns pushed the arcane issue front-and-center in the
presidential campaign Monday but offered little prospect for
immediate, comprehensive action.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Ornstein, a scholar at the American Enterprise Institute
who studies Congress, said the lone chance for quick congressional
action will be a tactical political decision by Bush and his Senate
allies to have the Republican-led Senate endorse watered-down
reforms to protect Bush from criticism that the GOP has done
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Rules Committee Chairman Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has
begun hearings on various proposals but he does not plan to craft a
final version of Senate legislation until mid-May. The House
approved legislation to overhaul campaign financing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show Americans have little interest in the
issue. A nationwide ABC News-Washington Post survey completed in
January showed that campaign finance ranked at the bottom of the
list of seven issues discussed in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 percent of the 1,007 adults surveyed said they considered
campaign finance reform the ``single most important issue'' in
deciding which candidate to support.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' battle over the issue will ``heighten interest
and get the debate going,'' Ornstein said, adding that the ongoing
debate ``will continue to draw the contrast between Gore who has a
bold plan and Bush who says the current system is just dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to court supporters of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and
inoculate himself against criticism for his 1996 fund raising by
announcing an ambitious proposal to finance House and Senate
campaigns beginning in 2008 with a $7.1 billion tax-free endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told students at Marquette University in Milwaukee that he
will ``lead'' and ``fight'' to ``redeem the soul of our
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore hoped to bolster his appeal to supporters of McCain's
failed presidential campaign by appearing with Sen. Russell
Feingold, D-Wis., who co-sponsored landmark campaign finance
legislation with McCain. Gore promised to submit their legislation
to ban soft money donations on his first day in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not give up, I will not back down, I will not walk away
until McCain-Feingold, the people's will, is the law of the land,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who unveiled his own plan to revamp the campaign finance
laws to undercut McCain during their hard-fought contest for the
Republican nomination, scoffed at Gore's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a taxpayer-financed government takeover of campaigns that
replaces individual spending decisions with decisions made by an
unelected government committee,'' Bush said in a statement issued
in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ought to ``live by and enforce the laws we currently have
on the books'' before undertaking a new commitment to ``reforming
the fund-raising practices of others,'' Bush added, in a reference
to fund-raising practices in 1996 that forced the Democratic Party
to return almost $3 million in donations from foreign donors.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain said he welcomed ``any good faith proposal
to reform our broken campaign finance system.'' But McCain added
that Gore has to ``convince a skeptical public that his efforts are
sincere and not an election-year conversion'' by supporting ``a
complete and open investigation of 1996 campaign finance
irregularities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has struggled to defend his party's questionable
fund-raising practices in 1996, including the party's acceptance of
$2.8 million from foreigners that was subsequently returned and his
own attendance at a fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in
California where $55,000 in donations was funneled through ``straw
donors.''
</P>
<P>
   Existing federal election law provides a loophole to campaign
donation limits to candidates by permitting corporations, unions,
special interests and wealthy individuals to donate unlimited,
unregulated ``soft money'' contributions to political parties for
so-called ``party building'' purposes. Both parties have deftly
used the money to support issues closely associated with a
candidate, or to attack an opponent's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal would outlaw the contributions as well as
discourage independently financed ``issue ads'' by guaranteeing
targeted candidates with equal time to respond. Gore also would
require special interest lobbyists to disclose their activities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal would ban soft money donations to parties by
corporations and unions; index the permitted $1,000 per-person
contribution to inflation; bar registered lobbyists from making
campaign donations to members of Congress while Congress was in
session; and require ``near instant'' disclosure of contribution on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address at stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
