<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MONSTER-AD28-COX     03-27 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSTER-AD28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ad raps with an old meter, sticks
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A woman is at the crossroads _ a
bustling big-city street corner _ and she's unsure which way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, strangers approach. They take turns speaking to her _
powerfully, passionately. They have the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two roads diverged in a yellow wood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And sorry I could not travel both.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And be one traveler, long I stood... ''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute! What is this? Rappers ripping off another oldie?
Bad flashback to high school English?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, just a commercial. Just another hip, mysterious,
what-the-heck-are-they-trying-to-sell-me TV spot, except this one
is so stark, so surreal and so slick you just have to watch.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ad for Monster.com, a worldwide Internet clearinghouse
for job listings. Compared with Budweiser's ``Whassup?''
commercials, and the fast-cutting ``Do The Dew'' ads, the spot is
downright cerebral. This is no jingle. This is classic American
poetry _ ``The Road Not Taken,'' by Robert Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that poem from somewhere,'' says Edward
Boches, chief creative director at Mullen, the agency that created
the commercial. ``We tested (the poem) in focus groups, and it was
interesting: Out of 10 people, 10 had heard the phrase `the road
less traveled by,' and eight knew it was a poem. Only one or two
out of 10 remembered the poet was Robert Frost. But it didn't seem
to matter. It still seemed to resonate with people.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Frost's poem _ taking the less-popular path in life
_ is compelling. And it fits perfectly with the image Monster.com
is going for, Boches says: a serious, sensitive approach to finding
a job.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Frost is getting some free _ albeit posthumous _
advertising in all of this. Not that it's working. There seems to
be ``absolutely no'' resurgence in his popularity, according to
local bookworms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only book we have by Frost is `In the Clearing,' and it
hasn't been checked out since last fall,'' a librarian at the Lake
Worth city library admits. Ditto for bookstores: ``No one's brought
it to my attention,'' says one apologetic employee at Barnes &AMP;
Noble Booksellers in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   High school teachers say the same thing. No students have
mentioned the commercial to them, and no classroom discussions have
been sparked by the poem.
</P>
<P>
   But Monster.com isn't disappointed. The commercial debuted the
night before the Super Bowl and was repeated for the game. For 24
hours afterward _ from Jan. 31 to Feb. 1 _ more than 4.4 million
job searches were conducted on the site.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the 24-hour period, Monster.com was getting 5,600
searches per minute. More than 19,000 online resumes also were
submitted. And then there's the e-mail. Lots of it. It's still
coming in, and all of it's praise, says Anne Hollows, senior vice
president of global brand strategy at Monster.com.
</P>
<P>
   According to Monster and Mullen, it was risky going ``serious''
for the Super Bowl. The game is the highest-visibility venue,
well-known for high concepts, high comedy, and what Hollows calls
``shock-vertising,'' that in-your-face commercial style that leaves
you talking.
</P>
<P>
   Monster wanted something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the production stage, we said, `We don't want to do
something traditional, we don't want to recycle an old rock song,
we don't want to follow what everyone is doing for the Super
Bowl,''' Boches says. ``And that poem is the antithesis of those
more-expected advertising solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up a good point. What's the next big thing for
advertisers? History lessons? Biology labs? Algebraic equations? X
 &QC;  Y not buy this?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Hollows says Monster.com saw an opportunity and
grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' she says. ``There are only four really big
things in life: Your health, your religion, your family and your
work. If you can't say something sophisticated about one of those,
then you're probably missing an opportunity. We didn't want to miss
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Not Taken,'' by Robert Frost
</P>
<P>
   Two roads diverged in a yellow wood,
</P>
<P>
   And sorry I could not travel both
</P>
<P>
   And be one traveler, long I stood
</P>
<P>
   And looked down one as far as I could
</P>
<P>
   To where it bent in the undergrowth;
</P>
<P>
   Then took the other, as just as fair,
</P>
<P>
   And having perhaps the better claim,
</P>
<P>
   Because it was grassy and wanted wear;
</P>
<P>
   Though as for that the passing there
</P>
<P>
   Had worn them really about the same,
</P>
<P>
   And both that morning equally lay
</P>
<P>
   In leaves no step had trodden black.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I kept the first for another day!
</P>
<P>
   Yet knowing how way leads on to way,
</P>
<P>
   I doubted if I should ever come back.
</P>
<P>
   I shall be telling this with a sigh
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere ages and ages hence:
</P>
<P>
   Two roads diverged in a wood, and I _
</P>
<P>
   I took the one less traveled by,
</P>
<P>
   And that has made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
