NYT-03-27-00 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAY-BRADBURY-NYTR &LR;      03-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAY-BRADBURY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY BRADBURY IS ACTIVE AGAIN, FOLLOWING STROKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERRY PACE   
 TimesDaily, Florence, Ala.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Bradbury was a struggling, unknown writer when he proposed
to a young Los Angeles bookstore clerk named Marguerite McClure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in love with books and with each other,'' said
Bradbury, the creator of ``The Martian Chronicles,'' ``Something
Wicked This Way Comes'' and other classic works of literary magic
and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her friends said, `For God's sake, don't marry Bradbury _ he's
going nowhere,''' the writer recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her: `My dear, your friends are wrong. I'm going to
the moon, and then I'm going to Mars. Do you want to come along?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradburys are now in their 53rd year of marriage, and books
by the beloved author are recommended reading in high schools and
colleges across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived a good life,'' said Bradbury, who turns 80 in
August. ``I've done all the things I've wanted to do. I like to
encourage people to do likewise, to follow their hearts and be
endlessly excited about the things they love.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury is continuing a remarkable recovery from a stroke last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the hell out of me,'' he said. ``At the time, I
wasn't sure I would make it, but I did make it. Along the way you
lie awake and think, `Good God, is this the last night of my life?'
Then morning comes, and then the next day and the next night.
Finally, slowly, you come out alive again.''
</P>
<P>
   He is now adding the finishing touches to a new mystery novel,
``Let's All Kill Constance,'' and he resumed his touring schedule
in late January. In lectures, Bradbury shares his ageless lust for
life _ a philosophy he calls ``optimal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to encourage people to stay in touch with the passion
and wonderment that starts when you are very young,'' he said.
``I've learned a very good lesson along the way I learned just to
be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be in Sheffield, Ala., on May 21 for a stage anthology
called ``The World of Ray Bradbury.'' The showcase, which runs May
19 through 21, features seven Bradbury works, adapted by the
author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the immediacy of theater,'' said Bradbury, who has
lived in Los Angeles for the past 56 years. ``It's incredibly
rewarding to have flesh-and-blood actors act out characters you've
had in your head for years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular collection brings together plays based on a
few of my short stories and selected scenes from a couple of longer
works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The production blends fantasy, science fiction, horror,
adventure and satire with journeys through ``The Foghorn,'' ``To
the Chicago Abyss,'' ``Kaleidoscope,'' ``The Third Landing'' from
``The Martian Chronicles,'' ``The Veldt,'' ``Pillar of Fire,'' and
``The Book People'' from ``Fahrenheit 451.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to write what I want to write, not what someone
else wants me to write,'' Bradbury said. ``People always come up to
me and say, `Why don't you write realistic fiction or something
political?' I tell them, `Don't ask me to play the tuba when I play
the violin.'''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Waukegan, Ill., Bradbury had childhood passions
encompassing Lon Chaney's grotesque silent-screen roles and Willis
O'Brien's stop-motion movie dinosaurs, the spectacle of circuses
and sideshows, and the fantastic space adventures of John Carter on
Mars and ``Buck Rogers in the 25th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was madly in love with Buck Rogers comic strips,'' Bradbury
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I collected those Buck Rogers strips, day after day, the
summer of my ninth birthday,'' he said. ``In the fifth grade, all
the kids were contemptuous of me and my collection. They made such
fun of me that finally, one afternoon, I tore up all my comic
strips.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the boy burst into uncontrollable tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself: `Why am I crying? Who died? Whose funeral am
I attending?''' Bradbury said. ``The answer was: `Yours, you fool.
You killed the future. You tore up the very thing that was the
center of your life. Now what can you do about it?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to collecting Buck Rogers again,'' Bradbury said.
``That made my life whole, and I've never listened to another damn
fool since.''
</P>
<P>
   (Terry Pace is entertainment editor for the TimesDaily in
Florence, Ala., which is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
