<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN     03-27 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN CENTER PRESIDENT TO LEAVE AFTER 17 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and NYT9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nathan Leventhal announced Monday that he would step
down as president of Lincoln Center in December after nearly 17
years in the job, through which he helped bring jazz, an
adventurous summer festival and al fresco swing dancing to a
bastion of opera, ballet and classical music.
</P>
<P>
   His departure, which he said he had discussed with friends over
the last few years, comes at a crucial time for the center, which
is considering a $1.5 billion campaign to upgrade its 40-year-old
11-acre campus. Leventhal, 57, said he felt it was right to pass
the decadelong construction project into new hands and that he had
long hoped to change his work-intense life. He spoke of spending
more time at his Connecticut country house and working at a variety
of other pursuits, none full time.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Sills, Lincoln Center's chairman, said Monday she
planned to form a search committee to find a replacement and that
she would propose that Leventhal join the board on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was far too early to think about candidates for the
president's job, the center's $525,000-a-year senior management
position, overseeing an annual operating budget of more than $60
million. ``As his friend, I understand exactly what he wants to do
and his need to do it,'' she said. ``As his collaborator, it's a
devastating loss, and I don't intend to deal with it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the legendary tensions between Lincoln Center for the
Performing Arts Inc., the organization that manages the arts
complex and sponsors its own artistic events, and its 11 often very
powerful constituent groups _ including the Metropolitan Opera and
the New York City Ballet, each of which is represented on the board
_ one might suspect that Leventhal had simply grown tired of the
job.
</P>
<P>
   But sitting for an interview with Sills, 70, in his office
Monday, Leventhal, while acknowledging the pressures, said he had
long ago planned to scale back his workload and had enjoyed good
relations with the constituent groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who know me know I had always said that if I were ever
in the position to do so, I would have a lifestyle that was not so
chock full of work,'' Leventhal said. ``I think the organization is
particularly well positioned now. It all seemed right.'' With the
time he will gain, Leventhal said, he plans to spend more time at
his country home, to which he is building an addition, play tennis,
and resume piano lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal, a lawyer who served as deputy mayor for operations
under Mayor Edward I. Koch and special assistant to Mayor John V.
Lindsay, said he was also considering making a connection to a
university or law firm or doing some consulting. ``If I wanted to
stay working full time, I'd stay right here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having overseen the construction of the $150 million Samuel B.
and David Rose Building, which includes student housing, studio and
rehearsal space and administrative offices, Leventhal said it made
sense for the next major construction effort to be led by someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said he would also use his remaining time in the job
to get the project off the ground. ``For the next nine months it's
business as usual,'' he said. ``We've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the joint interview both Sills and Leventhal characterized
their relationship as close and constructive, despite reports of
tension from time to time. Although Leventhal was resented by some
constituent groups as the personification of Lincoln Center Inc.,
he generally seems to have earned respect for running the complex
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``By searching out the kinds of presentations that would not
ordinarily be at Lincoln Center, he brought a new audience,'' said
Schuyler G. Chapin, the city's commissioner of cultural affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Leventhal is credited with bringing productions
to Lincoln Center stages that once were dark during the summer and
with trying to bring in new audiences with nontraditional
programming. Jazz at Lincoln Center, for example, has become a
major operation and soon will have its own space in the former
Coliseum site at Columbus Circle. And for the last decade Midsummer
Night Swing has drawn crowds to dance in the open air of Lincoln
Center's plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything I wanted badly that we weren't able
to accomplish,'' Leventhal said.
</P>
<P>
   There have nevertheless been rough spots. Last year the board
came under vehement criticism for endorsing the sale of a
monumental painting by Jasper Johns that has hung in the lobby of
the New York State Theater for 35 years. The board ultimately
decided not to sell the painting, which had elicited offers of more
than $15 million. (Leventhal and Sills declined to discuss the
incident.)
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said he had shared his decision-making with Sills.
When he handed her his letter of resignation Monday, she asked him,
``Is this your final answer?'' But other cultural experts and
Lincoln Center executives seemed caught off guard by his
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somewhat surprised, but not completely,'' said Martin E.
Segal, chairman emeritus of Lincoln Center, who brought Leventhal
on board in the first place. ``He's been in the job a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal said he himself was not even sure he would make the
move until until this past weekend. ``I'm prepared for a huge
decompression and feeling of loss when I realize what I've done,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
