A9512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WONDERLAND-REVIEW28-C     03-27 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-REVIEW28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ER' meets `Cuckoo's Nest' in new ABC hospital drama
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A deranged man shoots a cop on a crowded
Times Square street. A man attempts suicide because his wife is
leaving him. A pregnant doctor is stabbed in the stomach. A son
bites off his mother's finger _ and eats it.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the grim world of ``Wonderland,'' an intense new
series about life in a New York City mental hospital. The ABC
drama, a cross between ``ER'' and ``One Flew Over The Cuckoo's
Nest,'' certainly won't win ``The Feel Good Show Of The Year''
award. Watching the often distressing series, created by former
``Chicago Hope'' star Peter Berg, is like getting kicked in the
stomach over and over. It's not pretty and it hurts. Shot in an
in-your-face documentary style, ``Wonderland'' practically puts you
in the middle of the action.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point. Many years ago, Berg, who played headstrong
Billy Kronk on ``Hope,'' saw a documentary about a Boston
psychiatric hospital. It was, he says, the most personal experience
he ever had watching a film. His mother also volunteered at a New
York psychiatric hospital when he was a kid. So the idea of making
a series about what those facilities are like always percolated in
the back of Berg's head. ``There has never been a realistic show
that explores the human mind,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The actor-director certainly did his homework. For eight months,
he spent time in New York's famed Bellevue Hospital. He talked with
patients. He interviewed doctors. He observed. ``That gave me a
real appreciation of how large the scope of mental illness is and
how heroic many of this psychiatrists are,'' Berg says. ``Movies
always paint them as villains.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, ABC is a villain. ``Wonderland'' airs on
Thursdays at 10 p.m. In case you forgot, another highly successful
medical series airs at the same time. But Berg refuses to trash ABC
(publicly, at least) for the tough time slot. ```ER' who?'' Berg
jokes. ``Hopefully we can garner some critical success.''
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be too hard. ``Wonderland'' is blessed with a
first-rate cast led by Michelle Forbes (``Homicide: Life on the
Street'') as a caring administrator and Ted Levine (``Silence of
the Lambs'') as the head of the hospital's forensic psychiatry
department.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many dramas, most of ``Wonderland's'' stories won't be
wrapped up in a neat, 60-minute bow. Berg hopes viewers won't find
the lack of tidy endings frustrating. ``We don't have clear-cut
resolutions that television audiences are used to being provided
with,'' he says. ``In a typical cop show, the bad guy is either
caught or he gets away. On a hospital show ... a patient either
lives or dies, is cured or not cured. In the world of psychiatric
hospitals and the mentally ill, the resolutions are much more
ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in ``Wonderland's'' case, possibly more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
