<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9520 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-27 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH STAFF SAYS ABSENT GOVERNOR STILL KEEPS TABS ON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's quest for the White House
has left him with little time to spend on state business in the
Texas Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   According to the governor's official calendar and records kept
by his campaign, during the 25-week period from Oct. 1 through
March 23, Bush spent 103 days out of the state campaigning and 20
days in his state office doing the job he tells voters qualifies
him to be president.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign funded that travel. But taxpayers have picked up
the tab for the governor's security detail, provided by the Texas
Department of Public Safety: an estimated $1.3 million this year,
twice that amount in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's calendar, which tracks his Monday-through-Friday
work week, shows Bush was in his office just one day each in
January and February, three so far this month, three in December
and six each in October and November.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush began his campaign in June, he generally has spent 10
or fewer days a month in his state office, according to his
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   But aides note the calendar provides less than a complete
picture of the time Bush spends taking care of Texas business.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't track weekends, days he shows up unscheduled in his
office, meetings he has had at the Governor's Mansion, or time he
has spent keeping in touch on the telephone from around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it illustrates the time it takes to be a presidential
candidate, particularly during peak periods such as the hectic
early primary season in February.
</P>
<P>
   Previous governors who have run for president _ including Bill
Clinton of Arkansas and Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts _ have
faced the same balancing act, as have other officials, such as Sen.
John McCain, the vanquished Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 4 1/2 months of 1992, for example, when Clinton was
campaigning for the Democratic Party nomination, he was absent from
Arkansas for all but 22 days.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, after winning the nomination, Dukakis initially tried
to spend two or three days a week in Massachusetts tending to state
business. But he came under criticism for not spending enough time
on his presidential campaign, and his time at the Statehouse was
reduced to a single day by his campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public understands anyone who is running for president
just about has to give up their day job,'' said Larry Berman, a
political scientist and author of ``The New American Presidency.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, Bush's day job is governor,'' Berman said.
``John McCain's was senator. When Bill Clinton ran in 1992, his was
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush's Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, has
said he realized it was more important to speak for himself as a
presidential candidate than concentrate on being the best possible
vice president, Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the governor's campaign schedule, Bush and his staff
said he has kept an eye on the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the way communications work today, it's easy to stay in
touch,'' Bush said recently in a combination staff meeting-photo
opportunity in his Capitol office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the governor has kept in
close contact with his staff and makes good use of his time when he
is in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a relatively short period of time that he has been
gone a large number of days,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas House Speaker James E. ``Pete'' Laney, a Democrat, and
Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, the acting governor when Bush is
absent, also said Bush keeps in touch with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in the early 1900s a governor being gone that long would
have a negative impact on the state,'' Perry said. ``With the
communications that we have, George Bush knows everything that's
going on in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bush is out of state from midnight to midnight on a given
day, Perry gets the governor's daily salary of $316.01. That
happened on 59 days last year and 43 this year, as of March 23.
</P>
<P>
   Bush voluntarily forfeits his state salary on the days Perry is
paid for doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Bush's campaign travel has increased, so has the state's cost
of providing security.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, for example, before the governor announced plans to
seek the presidential nomination, the Department of Public Safety
spent $285,873 on his security detail.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, when the governor began his campaign, the cost jumped
to $2.65 million.
</P>
<P>
   From January through March 20 of this year, the DPS spent almost
$1.3 million on security.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of DPS security is expected to decrease now, because
Bush came under the protection of the U.S. Secret Service on March
15. But it won't be eliminated, DPS spokeswoman Tela Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still charged with providing security for the
governor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Peggy Fikac can be reached by e-mail at
pfikac(at)express-news.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
