<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODTIMES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVING THE GOOD TIMES': TRACKING A RECESSION'S TOLL ON 2
HARD-HIT FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review; time listed is for New York;
check local listings) 
(jt) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a decade, Bill Moyers has been tracking the downs and ups of
two blue-collar Milwaukee families, the Neumanns and the Stanleys.
Both were hit hard in the early 1990s, after Tony Neumann and
Claude Stanley lost their jobs at Briggs &AMP; Stratton, which, like
other industrial mainstays, gave way to recession. The company cut
some 4,000 jobs in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The Neumanns are white and the Stanleys are black, but when bad
times struck, color proved less decisive than economics. Suddenly
the recently well-paid workers found themselves scrambling for
minimum-wage jobs as bills mounted. They ran behind on mortgage
payments and had to accept handouts of food.
</P>
<P>
   Along with battling to make ends meet, both families watched
their neighborhoods deteriorate, with increasingly dangerous
streets posing risks to their children. A bout of illness could
play havoc with the household budget; a fever sent Claude Stanley
to a hospital for two months in 1997, leaving him with a $30,000
bill not covered by insurance. Raising college tuition for an
ambitious son, the first Stanley to get a college degree, required
juggling credit-card debt at an interest rate of 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Neumann and Jackie Stanley pitched in, but earning $6 an
hour while they paid $1.50 an hour for child care didn't ease
matters. The children _ five Stanleys and three Neumanns _ felt the
impact as they tried to help out with odd jobs and adjusted to
homes with both parents working and with domestic tensions rising.
</P>
<P>
   The choice facing both women, as Terry Neumann puts it, was
``Either we make ends meet, or we stay home with the kids.'' She
found a job at a school cafeteria, which paid only $20 a day, but
allowed her to get home before her children. Working a double
shift, Tony Neumann hardly saw them or Terry. ``We don't sleep
together anymore,'' he tells Moyers. ``It stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's title, ``Surviving the Good Times,'' is a comment
on the gap between an America that was prospering during the heady
1990s and hard workers like the Neumanns and Stanleys who were not
able to share in the prosperity. But this report is also a tribute
to the resilience of their close-knit families and the efforts of
all members to pull together. Terry Neumann became a truck driver;
Jackie Stanley went into selling real estate, not easy for a black
woman whose potential clients are limited to the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   As the program ends, the Stanleys are hopeful but still haven't
caught up to what they made in the Brooks &AMP; Stratton years.
Prospects are brighter for the Neumanns, with Tony making $18 an
hour and Terry looking ahead to a Teamsters job at $19 an hour.
``If the money's there,'' she says, ``that's where I'll be.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `SURVIVING THE GOOD TIMES'
</P>
<P>
   A Moyers Report
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night, PBS, 9 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Public Affairs Television, Inc. with Okapi
Productions, LLC. Judith Davidson Moyers and Judy Doctoroff
O'Neill, executive producers; Bill Moyers and Moyers, executive
editors; Tom Casciato and Kathleen Hughes, producers and directors;
Andrew Fredericks, editor; Gregory Henry, associate producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
