<SLUG> BC-HMO-TEXAS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aetna's sale of managed-care plans approved by state
 &HT;    By Amy Schatz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc.'s plans to sell a managed-care subsidiary in Texas
have received a boost from the state Department of Insurance, which
approved the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna was forced to sell managed care company NYLCare Health
Plans in Texas to win federal approval of its $1 billion purchase
of Prudential Health Care. Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Texas
agreed in September to buy NYLCare, which has about 531,000 members
in Texas, for $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators had antitrust concerns about Aetna's keeping NYLCare
because it was the state's largest HMO provider and NYLCare was the
second-largest. Combined, the company would have controlled about a
third of the Texas market.
</P>
<P>
   While NYLCare operates in Austin, the sale will be more keenly
felt in Dallas and Houston, where NYLCare has the bulk of its
members. NYLCare has about 43,000 members in the Austin area,
according to the latest Department of Insurance figures. By
comparison, Blue Cross, which operates locally under the name of
Rio Grande HMO Inc., has about 15,800.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is expected to be finalized by the end of the first
quarter, a Blue Cross spokeswoman said. The company declined to
discuss further details.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will make Blue Cross the state's largest health
insurer, with about 21.8 percent of the HMO market, according to
the Department of Insurance, which approved the sale Friday. Blue
Cross said its total membership in the state will be about 2.7
million, including 806,000 HMO members.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Amy Schatz at aschatz(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
