<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-FAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIDO STARELLI, INVETERATE 49ERS FAN, DIES AT 79 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and AL CORONA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco 49ers have lost their No. 1
fan.
</P>
<P>
   Lido Starelli, who missed only one Niners home game since 1946
and was officially named the team's top fan in 1998, has died of
cancer. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli was the subject of numerous profiles focusing on his
lifelong love of the Niners. He was a 21-year-old construction
worker when the team played its first game at Kezar Stadium on
Sept. 1, 1946, against the long-defunct Chicago Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   His boss in the plastering trade had given him tickets to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all it took,'' he said in a 1996 interview. ``From
there I just went.''
</P>
<P>
   Starelli attended the games alone for the first 10 years of the
Niners _ four in the All America Football Conference and then,
beginning in 1950, the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one ticket,'' Starelli said. ``I couldn't afford two.''
</P>
<P>
   Starelli stuck with the team through many years of losses. He
followed the Niners through up and down years and teams led by
Frankie Albert, Y.A. Tittle and John Brodie, then the glory years
of Joe Montana and Steve Young, and, finally, last fall's losing
squad led by Jeff Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   To many Niners fans, recorded history began in 1980 with the
rise of Joe Montana and continued through five Super Bowl victories
in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Starelli told reporters that his favorite football games
were played back before the NFL dominated television sets every
Sunday from September to January.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite era was the '40s and '50s,'' Starelli said. ``It
was like my first love. You never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Starelli said he was superstitious: He took the Municipal
Railway to every game, wore the same clothes to every game, and
would enter through the same gate, handing his ticket to the same
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Like most true Niners fans, his favorite moment was The Catch:
December 1981, when Montana threw a touchdown pass to a leaping
Dwight Clark to win a playoff game against the Dallas Cowboys. The
ensuing Super Bowl victory ended decades of also-ran status for the
Niners.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Clark made that catch, I was crying like a baby,''
Starelli said. ``Tears of agony had become tears of ecstasy.''
</P>
<P>
   The only game Starelli missed was on Dec. 5, 1959 _ the day his
father died.
</P>
<P>
   But Starelli still got the program to that game. Over the years,
he not only kept programs from games he attended but managed to
track down those from every single Niners away game.
</P>
<P>
   He kept them all, believed to be the only set of its kind, in a
basement room of his San Francisco home that became a shrine to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli also collected every 49er media guide, lapel pin,
stationery Christmas card and pocket schedule from the last half
century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he was named by the team as their No. 1 fan and won a
free trip to the pro football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio. He
traveled there again last year after learning that he was ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Receiving the No. 1 fan award was the thrill of his life,''
his son John said Sunday. ``He lived and breathed the 49ers since
1946.''
</P>
<P>
   During his life, Starelli said that his vast collection would
never be sold _ that he would leave it to his son in hopes it would
someday end up in museum or library.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to go somewhere where it can always be appreciated by
people,'' Starelli said in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   John Starelli said he would not continue collecting programs but
he would continue collecting memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Italian town of Lucca, Starelli moved to San
Francisco as a boy and started in the building trades as a young
man, eventually becoming a journeyman plasterer. He was a 47-year
member of Local 66 of the plasterers' union.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli is survived by his wife of 55 years, Frances; his son
John Starelli and daughter-in-law Michelle; his daughter Gloria
Bruno and her husband John Bruno; and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be at 10 a.m. Thursday at St. Elizabeth's
Roman Catholic Church at 450 Somerset St. in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
