<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAZERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trail Blazers spinning out of control
 &HT;    Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly a month after swallowing a shot of reality served by the
Los Angeles Lakers, Portland still nurses the world's longest
hangover.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers, hosts to San Antonio tonight, have lost seven
of their last 13 games. The decline began with a loss to the Lakers
in Portland on Feb. 29. Portland, now barely visible in the Lakers'
rear-view mirror, trails by seven games in what is no longer a race
for the No. 1 seed for the Western Conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich, whose own team struggles
while trying to mount a defense of its NBA championship, does not
consider the situation hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one team playing the way we were last year,''
Popovich said. ``The rest of us are floundering around, not
separating ourselves from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago there were two. For the first two-thirds of the
season, the Lakers and Portland were title contenders 1A and 1B, in
no particular order. L.A. had the two most talented players,
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant. Portland was two deep at every
position.
</P>
<P>
   A half game separated them, Portland in the lead, when the
all-star break ended on Feb. 15. The Blazers seemed to have an
advantage in scheduling: seven more home games than the Lakers
during the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the Lakers arrived in Portland for the last of
their four regular-season meetings. Each had a 45-11 record, having
won 11 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers left with a 90-87 victory and didn't stop until their
streak reached 19 games. The Blazers were left with a lot of
self-doubt. In mid-March, Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy said, ``We
haven't played well since the Lakers loss. We've made a lot of
mental mistakes. We're soft overall.''
</P>
<P>
   That condition has not changed after another two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly when you have a big loss, there is a residue to
it,'' Dunleavy said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy might need a back-hoe to remove all the residue. The
Blazers had won 16 straight at home before the Lakers arrived. The
defeat started a 2-5 streak in the Rose Garden, including three
consecutive losses. Toronto won by 19 in Portland six days after
the Lakers. New York left Portland with a victory on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Portland can't attribute its problems to any one factor. The
Blazers' leading scorer, forward Rasheed Wallace, is often
unstoppable when he gets going. He is also uncontrolable, the
league-leader in technical fouls with 32. Now he has company, other
Blazers who frequently complain to the refs.
</P>
<P>
   Portland has become careless on offense, ranking 16th in
turnovers. The Blazers still are among the top defensive teams,
allowing 91.2 points a game, third fewest in the league. But they
are prone to lapses, including a rash of blocking and holding fouls
that suggests they have been a step slow. During a recent five-game
stretch, including four defeats, opponents averaged 106 points
against the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to concentrate more,'' starting center Arvydas Sabonis
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis won't have to worry about that for a while. He will miss
two to three weeks with a sprained right foot.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blazers put him on the injured list, they activated
former starter Brian Grant, now a key reserve behind Wallace and
Sabonis. Grant missed 12 games, except for eight minutes in one of
them, with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Blazers nor Spurs are in top form for the game
tonight, both beset by injuries. But the game should nevertheless
provide a guage of where these potential playoff opponents stand.
There is a decent chance they will meet in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is not among the injured, and he has enabled Portland to
give the Spurs fits this season, winning by 14 at home and by 10 in
San Antonio. Tim Duncan, who averages 23 points for the Spurs, was
limited to 21 in two games by Portland. Wallace, an inch shorter
than Duncan at 6-11, guards the Spurs' star with help from several
long-armed teammates.
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT SHAKES OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have 12 games left, eight against teams that will
reach the playoffs and one with Orlando, which would be there if
the postseason began today. San Antonio will meet Portland, the
Lakers and Sacramento twice apiece and Utah once. The Spurs are 2-7
against those teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
