<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOILET STRATEGY AIMS FOR RESPECT  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Globalization'' is one of those words that I avoid using
because I don't know what it means.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to guess, I'd probably say it had something to do with
the Internet or maybe skinny Indonesian children gluing athletic
shoes together for 25 cents a day so Michael Jordan can buy a
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that globalization is really all about toilets.
Not crummy toilets that look like they were installed (and probably
last cleaned) sometime during the Eisenhower administration; I'm
talking about nice toilets. Toilets with heated seats. Toilets
situated in rooms decorated with tasteful paintings and flower
arrangements. Toilets so special that people sign up for guided
tours and maybe even meet for a spot of tea.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a good alternative to Disney World? Well, of course
it does, but before you make your motel reservations you might want
to know that these designer toilets are located in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   According to News of the Weird columnist Chuck Shepherd, South
Korea has thrown open the doors to 580 plush public restrooms as a
means of garnering greater world respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era of globalization,'' said a government cultural
official, ``it is important to become the leader in the world in
the cleanest bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   I definitely think the South Koreans are onto something here,
and it probably has nothing to do with any nerve gas the North
Koreans have sent across the border. There is unquestionably a
worldwide shortage of clean, tastefully decorated restrooms and I
see no reason why South Korea should not become a leader in this
pioneering industry.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think I'm being unpatriotic when I say that the average
American's experience with public restrooms is not always pleasant.
About the best you can hope for is a roll of toilet paper and a
less than an inch of water on the floor; forget about the heated
seats, violin music and flower arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Although the restrooms sound terrific from a South Korean
standpoint, some adaptations might have to be made for the U.S.
market. For one thing, I can't see people meeting in restrooms
after work for a cup of tea. A beer, maybe, or coffee or a soft
drink, but definitely not tea.
</P>
<P>
   The violin music might also be a problem. American taste in
music tends to run more in the direction of Top 40 or rock or
country. It doesn't really make a difference as long as it has a
beat. Violin music might be a little too relaxing to the point that
people will fall asleep, possibly causing damage to the heated
toilet seats.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the idea of a clean, sophisticated, globalized restroom
to American business managers may also pose some problems. Their
thinking is likely to be that an employee who is heating his seat
while admiring tasteful paintings and floral arrangements is an
employee who is not stamping out widgets or, more appropriately in
today's economy, microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   The trick will be to convince management that a relaxed,
warm-bunned, tea-laden employee is more productive than one who is
forced to use a restroom with less elegant furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that workers and management work out their differences
by holding a meeting. Preferably in a South Korean public restroom.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
