<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-27 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BLESS MY SOUL, LIDDY DOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, everybody is talking about vice-presidential
candidates. Robert Rubin? Colin Powell? Can we bring back John
McCain and Bill Bradley? Tom Hanks seems like a nice person.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Al Gore and George W. Bush make campaign stops these
days, they're asked whether the local governor/mayor/senator is on
the short list. The answer is always yes, because the short list is
incredibly long right now. In fact, people, if none of your elected
officials are being talked about as potential veeps, there is
probably something wrong with your state, and you should consider
moving elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have some time _ three or four months _ before
they really need to focus on this. We've started speculating early
because the alternative is debating whether Gore is right in
claiming that the Bush tax plan is ``risky,'' or Bush is more
correct in dubbing it ``bold.'' (Friends, when you get right down
to it, does not all boldness contain an element of danger? Is it
possible to have progress while remaining risk-free? And is it not
questions like these that drive us right back to debating the
vice-presidential karma of Gov. Tom Ridge vs. Sen. Chuck Hagel?)
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything lacking in the current crop of potential
running mates, it's that there's not a single off-the-wall
candidate. A couple of months ago the nation's Mentioning Class was
perfectly happy to theorize that the American people might be
interested in letting Jesse Ventura, Donald Trump or Warren Beatty
near the nuclear button. But nobody suggests that the political
parties would make less-than-somber choices for Number Two.
</P>
<P>
   The columnist Robert Novak was thinking outside the box recently
when he promoted the freelance ethicist William Bennett as Bush's
running mate (``a brainy, street-smart Catholic who has never been
accused of immaturity''). On the Democratic front, Mario Cuomo was
quoted by an Italian newspaper as saying that making his son,
Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Andrew Cuomo, the first
Italian-American vice president would be ``the best way to debunk
so many odious prejudices against us Italians.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo says his comments lost something _ well, a great deal _ in
the translation. But if either of the candidates wants to strike a
blow for vice-presidential diversity, there's plenty of
opportunity. We've never had a Jewish, Hispanic, African-American
or Asian vice president either. There has never been a woman,
although the Democrats were good enough to nominate Geraldine
Ferraro in 1984, when their chances were so minimal a Hail Mary
pass seemed appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   We have had a Native American vice president (Charles Curtis,
1929-33), and it's possible that we had a gay vice president in
1852, when Franklin Pierce chose William King as his running mate.
King, the only bachelor vice president, was the former roommate of
James Buchanan, the future only-bachelor president, and the two of
them were known as ``the Siamese twins'' because they went
everywhere together as a couple. However, given the fact that King
was dying in Cuba when he was elected, and never even made it back
to Washington, I think we can all agree that whatever his sexual
persuasion, homosexuals still have debunking claims.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush are both presumed to be looking for people who
will balance their weaknesses. On the Republican side, that might
mean a Catholic war hero who knows a lot about foreign policy but
isn't so very bright as to make the top of the ticket look dim.
Gore seems to be in the market for someone who _ how can we put it
delicately? _ has a lot of character.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of strategizing goes way back. Martin Van Buren, who
was burdened with a reputation as a luxury-lover, teamed up in 1836
with Rep. Richard Johnson of Kentucky, who was widely believed to
own only one set of clothes. Johnson had allegedly killed the great
chief Tecumseh during the Indian wars, and when supporters of Gen.
William Henry Harrison cried ``Tippecanoe and Tyler, too,''
Democrats were supposed to retort ``Rumpsey dumpsey, Colonel
Johnson shot Tecumpsey.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a good idea at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, how about Denzel Washington? He lost the Oscar, and he
deserves to get something.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
