a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      03-27 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EH-OH! CHILDREN'S TV HAS A BIT OF A TUMMY ACHE  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I suppose I ought to put on some shoes and join the posse
chasing after those sneaky, sidewinding, no-account Teletubbies,
but I'm probably giggling too much to hold a torch safely. As much
as I'd like to get in on the fun, I think I'll just have to sit
this one out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of children's health advocates, including a
couple of prominent psychiatrists from Harvard Medical School,
urged the Public Broadcasting System to yank the eh-ohing little
freaks off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teletubbies,'' for the uninitiated, is the popular PBS show
starring Tinky Winky, Laa-Laa, Dipsy and Po. You may recall them
from a year ago when televangelist Jerry Falwell declared that Mr.
Winky is gay.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Uncle Jer, I don't spend much time thinking about the
sexual preferences of stuffed animals. I am suspicious of the
Tubsters for other reasons _ they were designed specifically for
tots under the age of 2, a ``demographic'' that TV's wizard
programmers deemed neglected.
</P>
<P>
   The Teletubbies, as their name implies, have TV sets for
tummies, and their lives revolve entirely around watching TV. Gee,
how subtle is that?
</P>
<P>
   The good docs from Harvard and others say the show warps the
mission of public television and exploits babies to sell toys and
junk food.
</P>
<P>
   They're especially upset that the show's creators have signed a
licensing agreement with Burger King and McDonald's. The burger
joints give away Teletubbie toys in hopes of persuading toddlers
and their parents to eat more burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Peddling stuff to children via TV is a hallowed American
tradition, of course. As a kid, I made regular demands of my mother
to buy cereal just to get the cheap trinket inside. But targeting
babies? Even at age 7, I might have recognized that's a little
lowdown and underhanded.
</P>
<P>
   Are fast-food execs so greedy they have to shake down the 0- to
24-month set? Shouldn't they be concentrating on finding enough
kids in the 15- to 18-year-old crowd who can make change well
enough to run the register?
</P>
<P>
   Two things set me to giggling about the Teletubbies furor. One
is the reaction of PBS Vice President Tom Epstein, who says the
protest is by ``a very narrow special interest group that is not
representative of mainstream thought.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS officials clearly are spending too much time on Capitol Hill
groveling for cash. They're starting to talk like congressmen.
Epstein, in a bit of truth-wrestling unworthy of PBS, says the
burger deals ``build an audience and expose more children to the
best educational noncommercial programming on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so it's french fry philanthropy, eh? Super-size that, would
ya?
</P>
<P>
   I'm also giggling about this because I'm a member of that ``very
narrow special interest group that is not representative of
mainstream thought.'' I'm the proud pappa of an 18-month-old girl,
and I nurture a naive hope that her mom and I can keep Phoebe out
of the marketing clutches of Teletubbies, Barney and such a little
while longer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not one of those vociferous Barney haters. I'm allergic to
the ``I Love You, You Love Me'' song, but other than that, I can
accept the Saccharinosaur in my house.
</P>
<P>
   Partly by accident, partly by design, my little girl has never
seen Barney on TV. But on her birthday and again at Christmas,
relatives and friends gave her Barney paraphernalia, including a
stuffed doll.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, Phoebe showed little interest in any of it.
Then one day, as I pushed a shopping cart down the toy section of a
grocery store, I was startled to hear her scream, ``Buy me! Buy
me!''
</P>
<P>
   Criminy, I thought, she's awfully young to demand that I buy her
stuff. I tried to keep moving, but she kept gesturing at the toys.
</P>
<P>
   I followed her pudgy little fingers and studied the display for
clues. Slowly it dawned on me that she wasn't hollering ``Buy me!
Buy me!'' She was yelling, in toddler-speak, ``Barney! Barney!''
</P>
<P>
   There was an array of purple toys lining the aisle. She'd
spotted her friend and wanted me to know it.
</P>
<P>
   So there we stood, father and daughter, caught up in admiration
of the Barnster. To her, he was just a cuddly stuffed animal _ not
a TV star, not an elaborate marketing ploy, not the subject of a
multimillion-dollar licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but I would have thought that was too old-fashioned, too
dull, too subtle to work.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com. The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
