<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BUSINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AND INVESTORS HOPE PUTIN ACTS QUICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-POLITICS, RUSSIA-U.S.) 
(lb) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After hearing Vladimir Putin's pre-election plans to
create a sounder economy and a friendlier investment climate,
foreign investors and local business people say the new Russian
president must take decisive action in the next few months for the
country to see marked increases in investment.
</P>
<P>
   The tasks Putin faces are daunting, partly because years of
neglect under the government of Boris Yeltsin have deepened so many
problems. Business people are counting on his carrying out
long-delayed initiatives like tax and customs reform.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, Putin has to nurture an environment where
business people feel they are treated fairly. That means reducing
Russia's corruption and the profound influence that powerful
business people, domestic conglomerates and upstart regions have on
the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generally more favorable economic situation in Russia
helps,'' said Andrea Rutherford, a director of Brunswick Warburg, a
Moscow brokerage firm. ``There's a budget surplus, revenues coming
in from higher oil prices, all of which mean that the government
doesn't have to spend its time putting out fires and can now
address real structural changes. People feel that Putin has the
power and the chance to enforce things.''
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the guarded hopes investors have, Rutherford said,
is the return of some Russian money to the stock market, which last
week lifted the main Russian Trading System index to its highest
levels since May 1998. ``Foreigners understand that the Russians
understand this place better than they do,'' she said, ``so if they
feel comfortable bringing some of their money back, that's a good
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   But after an initial surge, the market ended 1.7 percent lower
Monday, as investors reassessed how much Putin would be able to do
quickly. Many Westerners still feel they have not heard enough
detail to judge how he plans to revitalize the economy. To them, he
remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever initiatives Putin envisions will have to wait until he
is inaugurated in early May. Still, people are carefully watching
whom he picks for his inner circle and the names that surface for
the prime minister's post. So far, Putin has chosen as close
advisers former comrades from the KGB, but if respected economists
are brought into the Cabinet and other posts and afforded real
authority, business confidence could rise.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming the corruption endemic to Russia will require a
tremendous effort from Putin. He may have to dismiss many ministers
and bureaucrats, and when commercial conflicts arise, he will have
to stop the state from intervening on behalf of its favorite
business people.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Putin has the desire and wherewithal to establish the
rule of law in Russia, the work may consume much more time than
investors have patience for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's most likely that things will move ahead gradually,
without radical change, because this is a man who has never taken
any revolutionary steps,'' said Charles Blitzer, chief
international economist for the brokerage firm Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``So if one has diminished hopes for the Putin
presidency, one will be satisfied, but anyone with great hopes is
sure to be disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
