<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONGRATULATES PUTIN ON ELECTION VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-POLITICS, RUSSIA-BUSINESS) 
(lb) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton congratulated President-elect
Vladimir Putin on Monday on his victory in the Russian election,
but also reiterated in a brief telephone conversation the White
House's concerns about Russia's continuing conflict in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton placed the call Monday morning after it became clear
that Putin had received enough votes in the balloting on Sunday to
avoid a runoff next month against Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist
leader, who finished a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks reflected the administration's optimism about
Putin but also its wait-and-see attitude to the former intelligence
officer who had spoken of being a reformer and integrating Russia
into the world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``President-elect Putin has an opportunity to translate his
electoral mandate into concrete steps to advance economic reform,
to strengthen the rule of law, to intensify the fight against crime
and corruption, and to join with us on a broad common agenda of
international security including arms control, nonproliferation and
regional peace and stability,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He added that during his 15-minute conversation he ``emphasized
the importance to Russia and the world of strengthening the
foundations of Russia's democracy and deepening its international
integration.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen, according to administration officials,
is whether Putin follows through on his plans to reform the Russian
tax system and judiciary, introduce land reform and fight
corruption, and whether he institutes law and order without
cracking down on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's conversation did not delve into the key issues between
the two nations, like the administration's effort to persuade the
Russians to modify the Anti-ballistic Missile Treaty. But on the
subject of Chechnya, where the brutal fighting continues, Clinton
said he did raise his concerns about Russian aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stressed to President-elect Putin the importance of
launching impartial and transparent investigations of reported
human rights violations and providing prompt and full access for
international organizations and the press,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin, whose tough handling of Chechnya was considered an
asset in the campaign, gave no signs of altering Russia's military
policy, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders last spoke on New Year's Day after President
Boris Yeltsin announced that he was stepping down and that he was
appointing Putin, then prime minister, as acting president. Clinton
and Putin met face to face last year in Oslo, Norway, and New
Zealand.
</P>
</TEXT>
