<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9543 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRV-SEQUOIAS-LADN &LR;      03-27 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRV-SEQUOIAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING OLD GRACEFULLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
(Eds: See ``Lodge'' sidebar and Lodge/Sequoias photos on NYT
wire.) 
 
 
 
 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEQUOIA NATIONAL PARK _ At the new Wuksachi Lodge in Sequoia
National Park, a musty book is tucked in among the reading
selections in the lobby: Hammonds' Illustrated Nature Guide. It
doesn't appear to get much attention from guests, probably because
of its age _ it was published in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Look up the tree species for which this park is famed and you'll
read this entry: ``For how many centuries or millennia our present
sequoias will go on living nobody knows; their chances seem
excellent as they are almost indestructible.''
</P>
<P>
   Irony fairly spills off the page.
</P>
<P>
   Indestructible? Exactly five years before this book was
released, park rangers determined that a sequoia in nearby Giant
Forest Village, leaning ominously, was in danger of flattening some
cabins if it were to topple over. So they lifted the cabins with
jacks, rolled them out of the way, and felled the tree. Cut it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Then they counted rings in the trunk. The tree was more than
2,200 years old. It first poked through the ground and shed its
seed coat in 261 B.C., about the time Roman legions were tangling
with Carthage in the first of the three Punic Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bill Tweed, Sequoia's chief naturalist, can only shake
his head. ``There was a symbol there,'' he said. ``We were cutting
down sequoia trees to make it safe for visitors to come to see
sequoia trees. In the long run, that just didn't add up right.''
</P>
<P>
   The stewardship of the park now conforms to a much different
philosophy, and visitors will notice it the instant they wheel in
among these towering trees _the largest living things on Earth _ in
California's western Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, nearly all the development has been
removed from the Giant Forest Village. Cabins, parking areas, side
roads. Tourist lodging and services were relocated to an area a bit
farther along the road, just past the Lodgepole region, in an area
of pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuksachi Lodge, which opened there last spring, accommodates
visitors with 102 rooms, a main lodge building, a restaurant and
bar, a small gift shop. Its most impressive feature: It is safely
removed from any of the sequoia groves that dot these western
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   These are truly magnificent trees. They're not as tall as
redwoods or as old as bristlecone pines, but no organism on the
planet can match its volume. The General Sherman tree here, which
is 275 feet tall and 103 feet around, is estimated to contain
52,500 cubic feet of wood, enough to build 40 houses.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive immune systems enable these trees to grow so tall,
gain such bulk and last so long. Their bark is virtually devoid of
pitch, which creates the equivalent of an asbestos suit, impervious
to fire. Their bark and heart wood is also laced with a bitter
tannin, such that insects attempting to bore in become afflicted
with acute indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   And yet these giants have feet of clay _ quite literally. The
sequoia spreads its roots outward in shallow soil, and it has no
tap root. Thus, if its root system is damaged or if its surrounding
soil is eroded, it simply topples over.
</P>
<P>
   The tree can usually hold its own under natural circumstances.
But it faces the fight of its life when trenches for water pipes
are dug nearby, when road beds alter normal drainage, when
pollutants work their way into the surface water. This was the
sequoias' plight after a village was built in their midst in the
early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Most of it was removed over the last three years. A couple of
structures deemed historic remain, notably the market that served
Giant Forest. They're to be converted to a museum and a learning
center, due to open next spring.
</P>
<P>
   In one year's time, the forest has already made a remarkable
recovery. Most of the development in the area had been small cabins
dotted among the trees, not sprawling lodge complexes that would
have required extensive bulldozing. Once the cabins were plucked
out, the ground was smoothed over, covered with mulch, planted with
seedlings and interlaced with irrigation tubing. It regained the
look of natural forest floor rather quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to know if irreversible damage was done by man's
100-year handprint (a tent camp went up in 1899, the last cabins
were removed in 1999). ``Did we do damage that will take a while to
show?'' said Tweed. ``Quite likely, yes. But you have to change
your thinking from human time to sequoia time.''
</P>
<P>
   A given tree might topple prematurely, but that could happen in
100 years, 500 years, he said _ only a fraction of a life that can
span 30 centuries.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Tweed does not impose a harsh judgment on his
forebears in the park. ``It's not that people were in any way evil
or shortsighted,'' he said. ``Sometimes it just takes time to see
the impact of what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the development was in the `20s and `30s. We've later
seen that it was located in sensitive areas. When most of the
national parks were in development _ Yosemite, the Old Faithful
area of Yellowstone _ visitation was a fraction of what it is
today. No one knew how mobile the society would become.''
</P>
<P>
   If you visit today, and you venture out on your own in the
sequoia zone, you'll be a member of a distinct minority. Most
tourists, it seems, are content to observe the trees from behind
their windshields on a drive along the Generals Highway, making
only an obligatory stop at the General Sherman tree.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherman tree, the largest living thing on Earth, is only
steps from the main road, and has its own parking lot. Visitors who
stop here quickly learn that they can't backpedal far enough to
capture its 275-foot height in their camera viewfinders.
</P>
<P>
   From the edge of the parking area, you can embark on the
Congress Trail, a relatively easy, 2.1-mile loop that is kind of a
sequoia civics lesson _ trees or clusters of trees are named for
such institutions as the presidency, the Senate and the House, and
the individuals honored include William McKinley and Robert E. Lee.
(The Sherman tree honors the Union general who put the torch to the
South because James Wolverton, the cattleman who named it in 1879,
had served under William Tecumseh Sherman in the Civil War.)
</P>
<P>
   Another intriguing route that branches off the Congress Trail is
the Trail of the Sequoias. It is a 5.1-mile loop that wends its way
around, under and even through fallen giants, skirts three meadows
and takes in Tharps Log, a cabin built into a hollow fallen sequoia
by an eccentric cattle rancher in the 1800s. (In this literal log
cabin, there are a table, benches, stone fireplace _ and enough
head room for an NBA forward.)
</P>
<P>
   This trail is impeccably maintained and very well marked. You'd
have to work pretty hard to get lost while navigating it. It was
also utterly deserted on a Saturday afternoon in January, just
before the season's snows arrived. Visitors don't seem inclined to
stray far from their cars or the paved roads.
</P>
<P>
   At least the makeover of Sequoia National Park has forced them
to get out of the Giant Forest before they lie down to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   A cross section of the tree sacrificed to tourist comfort in
1950, by the way, is on display today. It is turned on its edge
near the General Sherman tree. Black marks in the rings signify
fires it survived during its lifetime, and a sign chronicles them _
one roughly coinciding with William the Conqueror's arrival in
England, another with Columbus' landfall in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beginning to lean,'' said Tweed. ``The primary cause of
death for sequoia trees is that they eventually fall over. They're
resistant to fire and disease, but they develop balance problems.
Maybe the next year, maybe the next 100 years or 200 years, it was
going to fall over.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in the distant future, naturalists will examine the
trunk of a stately giant sequoia that toppled over from natural
causes. Imagine them assessing the rings in the trunk and drawing
these conclusions: Survived fires of 699 and 980, made it through
drought of 1258, recovered from sewer-line trench of 1961 ...
flourished for another three centuries. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
IF YOU GO: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: Sequoia National Park, which lies south of
Yosemite and due east of Fresno in the western Sierra Nevada, is a
233-mile drive from Los Angeles. After proceeding north via I-5 and
Highways 99 and 65 to Lindsay, the route jogs and twists a bit
before picking up Highway 198 into the mountains and the park;
simply follow the signs for ``Sequoia'' or ``National Park.'' It's
a good idea to allow between four and five hours for this drive,
particularly if there is snow on the sharply curving roadway above
Three Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   COSTS: Admission to the national park is $10 per vehicle, good
for seven days. It is $5 per person for cyclists and visitors on
foot.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: The new Wuksachi Lodge has three room categories,
graduated according to view and space. Rates are $75, $90 and $105
until June 1, at which time they'll rise to $110, $125 and $155 for
the summer peak. Rooms are simply furnished but comfortable, and do
not have TVs. Reservations: (888) 252-5757. Front desk: (559)
565-4070. Web: www.VisitSequoia.com.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: The Wuksachi serves breakfast, lunch and dinner in a
vaulted-ceiling dining room with impressive views through picture
windows. The fare is both tasty and reasonably priced _ dinner
items in the $10 to $20 range. Nearby, the Lodgepole market, closed
for renovations through most of the winter, is scheduled to reopen
Saturday. Never leave picnic items locked in your car unattended _
the bear-proof car door or window has yet to be invented.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Lodgepole Visitors Center, which lies between
the Giant Forest and the Wuksachi Lodge, can be reached at (559)
565-3782. The National Park Service maintains an office in Three
Rivers. Phone: (559) 565-3341. Web: www.nps.gov/seki.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
