<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OPEC-ART-1STLD-WRITET     03-27 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC MINISTERS STILL UNDECIDED ON AMOUNT OF OIL PRODUCTION
INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete writethru of early version; restructures and
adds details and background.) 
(See also OIL-INFLATION) 
(js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ The Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries adjourned its ministerial meeting here Monday night
without an agreement on modest production increases, and delegates
agreed to reconvene Tuesday. But as they grappled with how to reach
an accord, one question loomed behind almost all their talks: is
anybody really in control of oil prices?
</P>
<P>
   Though U.S. consumers have been shocked to see gasoline surge
from an average of $1.27 a gallon six months ago to $1.59, oil
producers in and out of OPEC have been on a roller-coaster, moving
output both up and down in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the mystique of private meetings between
Middle-Eastern sheiks and technocrats from the likes of Mexico and
Venezuela, the 11 nations of OPEC produce only 40 percent of the
world's oil and have been repeatedly blind-sided by market forces.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles to price ``stability,'' a buzzword embraced as
warmly by the United States as by Saudi Arabia, have been numerous:
chronic cheating within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries on its self-imposed output restrictions; inaccurate
estimates of demand and inventories; poor forecasting; and the
inevitable surprises induced by weather, war and other calamities.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1997, Saudi Arabia convinced OPEC to increase production
by 1 million barrels a day. Prices then sank to the low teens in
1998 and hit $11 a barrel one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Panic-driven production cuts of 4.3 million barrels a day in
1998 and 1999 helped prices climb back. They surged to $34 in early
March.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have slipped back to about $28.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, fear of causing another steep price plunge prevented
OPEC members from completing a deal to increase their daily
production quota by 1.5 to 1.7 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   After several informal and then formal meetings, oil ministers
adjourned with plans to meet again Tuesday morning. Officials on
all sides of the debate publicly predicted that they would agree on
a plan to raise production, but Iran continued to push for less
than the 1.7 million barrels that Saudi Arabia and other Persian
Gulf states want to add.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not opposed to an increase,'' said Iran's oil minister,
Bijan Namdar Zangeneh, shortly before oil ministers met at OPEC
offices here Monday evening. ``I won't talk on numbers, but we
don't want a market shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   Many OPEC leaders now say their target price is $25 a barrel,
and U.S. officials have implied they can accept that.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger question remains unanswered: Does OPEC, or any
other group, have enough influence to keep oil prices within a
tight range?
</P>
<P>
   ``Total world production is 75 million to 78 million barrels a
day, but sometimes all you have to do is be off by a million
barrels,'' said Joseph A. Stanislaw, president of Cambridge Energy
Research Associates, a consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``That's
how much they increased production in 1997, but they increased
right when demand was about to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The memories of that miscalculation are still vivid for many oil
ministers here, especially those who felt themselves dragged into
the increase by Saudi Arabia's power as the world's largest
producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk about these questions with the Saudis, I ask them
if they think their forecasts are better this time than back in
Jakarta,'' said Sheik Saud Nasser Al-Sabah, Kuwait's oil minister,
referring to the 1997 OPEC meeting in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials admit they miscalculated, principally because
they failed to anticipate that the Asian financial crisis would
reduce world oil demand as sharply as it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to avoid volatility, but this is something that
you cannot guarantee,'' said a senior Saudi official here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the unpredictability of the world economy, data about the
oil market and even something as simple as OPEC production itself
is often inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC members chronically overshoot their official quotas, though
the price collapses of 1998 and 1999 prompted them to adhere to
discipline more closely than they had done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Cheating on quotas is so persistent and so important to oil
prices that numerous organizations make monthly estimates by
monitoring oil tankers and pipeline activities.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC itself does not even have its own statistics on its
production, partly because members don't trust each other to
provide reliable data. As a result, OPEC officials rely on research
provided by outside companies and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely watched estimates are those of the International
Energy Agency, a research organization in Paris funded primarily by
the United States and other western countries.The agency estimates
that OPEC countries are cheating by about 1 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   But estimating cheating is still a nebulous art, prone to
errors. Even more difficult is the job of estimating oil
inventories, which are held by oil producers around the world as
well as petroleum refiners, traders and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The International Energy Agency, as well as private researchers,
admit they seriously overestimated the reduction of inventories in
January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
