<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-INFLATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER OIL PRICES WILL NOT SPUR U.S. INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article does not have a byline) 
(js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, said
Monday that higher oil prices are not generating inflation in the
United States, and that the country is better able to absorb rising
energy costs than it was two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not, as yet _ I emphasize as yet _ see any significant
indication that crude oil price increases are in the process of
embedding themselves in other areas of the economy and inflating
the general price structure,'' Greenspan said in response to a
question at a hearing before a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said that as long as average oil prices remain roughly
where they are now, he doubted that they would be sufficient to set
off a surge in inflation. But he warned that a big, sustained jump
in prices could still be harmful to the U.S. economy, as well as,
in the long run, to the oil-producing nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
