  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: BLOODY SUNDAY INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   The British government opened a new investigation into the 1972
shooting of Catholic civil rights demonstrators by British soldiers
on a Londonderry street. Shortly after the event, a tribunal
exonerated the soldiers and implied that the 14 people killed had
been involved in terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: OPPOSITION TRANSFORMED
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party voted itself out of existence, re-emerging in
Parliament as the Canadian Alliance. The new party, Canada's
second-largest and the official opposition in Parliament, seeks to
create a conservative coalition to battle the Liberals in next
year's elections. It will choose a leader in June.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS: NARROW ESCAPE
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary General Joseph Connor said that the United
Nations had managed to step back from the brink of financial
disaster at the end of last year, in large part because of U.S.
payments totaling $452 million. But he warned that this year is
likely to see a sharp rise in peacekeeping bills, to nearly $2
billion, and that could overrun the earlier gains. The United
States still owes about $1.6 billion in back dues.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: REBEL OFFENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a separatist ethnic Tamil
group, said they had begun a sea and land assault against army
bases in the northern part of the island. This comes as the
country's two main political parties _ long bitter rivals _ are
trying to agree on a peace plan that would give Tamils greater
regional autonomy but which the rebels call a ruse to give the
government time to bolster its military strength.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: LEADER AFFIRMED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad won the nominations of 133 out
of 165 of his governing party's local divisions, assuring him of
retaining the party's leadership and thus the post of prime
minister. His deputy, Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, was reported to have
secured enough nominations to retain the No. 2 spot in the party,
known as Umno, when it meets later this year.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: SUED BY OKINAWA
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Japanese island of Okinawa filed a lawsuit
against the governments of the United States and Japan seeking
$56.2 million in damages for noise pollution and other disruptions
related to U.S. military bases. The lawsuit comes as a political
embarrassment to Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who hoped to hold a
trouble-free meeting of the world's leading economic powers in
Okinawa in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
