<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      03-27 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MICROSOFT DECLINE HELPS PULL MARKETS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major stock market averages moved lower Monday,
dragged down by declines in financial service and bank stocks and
by a big decline in Microsoft, which slumped on reports that the
software company remains far from an agreement that would settle
the government's antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, a component of the Dow Jones industrial average, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index and the Nasdaq composite index, fell 7
5/8, to 104 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Its decline was responsible for 37.9 points of the 86.87 decline
in the Dow. The blue chip index closed at 11,025.85, down 0.8
percent from the close on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.60, or 0.2 percent,
to 1,523.86. The decline in Microsoft shares was offset in part by
gains in a number of other large technology issues, including
America Online and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index closed at 4,958.56, down 4.47 points,
or 0.1 percent. Gains in stocks like Qualcomm, Yahoo and Nextel
tempered losses in JDS Uniphase and CMGI, as well as Microsoft. And
the Russell 2000 small stock index dipped 3.6, or 0.1 percent, to
573.66.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts said there was no real trend to Monday's
action. Activity was light, the end of the first quarter is fast
approaching and there is little in the way of economic news to be
reported this week that seems likely to move financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one theme, it is that the larger capitalization
stocks are dominant again,'' said William Meehan, chief market
analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the bond market really falls apart, the stock market is
likely to do all right until first-quarter earnings reports start
to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   The bond market was fairly quiet Monday, with little or no
change in interest rates. But that did not prevent stock traders
from pounding bank and brokerage stocks.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, a Dow component, fell 5 11/16, to 131 1/8.
Citigroup, which is also in the Dow, lost 1/2, to 60 1/16. Chase
Manhattan dropped 1 1/2, to 94 11/16. And Mellon Financial declined
7/8, to 30 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said that troubles at Finova Group may have offered
encouragement to sell bank stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the lender to midsize companies warned that it will miss
first-quarter profit goals because of a bad loan. The company also
said its chief executive is retiring for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Finova's stock price slid sharply, closing at 19 7/8, down 12
1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks, which have been red hot lately, slumped.
</P>
<P>
   The group was led lower by Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette, which fell
9 9/16, to 57 3/4, after the stock was downgraded by a Morgan
Stanley analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley was one of the biggest losers of the S&AMP;P 500. The
stock closed at 90, down 5 13/16. Charles Schwab slumped 5 3/16, to
59 13/16. And Paine Webber Group fell 3 1/2, to 43 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   A number of big technology companies were immune from the
problems that plagued Microsoft, and moved higher.
</P>
<P>
   IBM closed at 126 9/16, up 5 9/16. Hewlett-Packard gained 3
15/16, to 146 5/16. And Intel rose 3 43/64, to 142 47/64.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Canelo, an investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and a longtime optimist about the direction of stock prices,
issued an even brighter assessment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opened Canelo raised his estimates for both
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the Nasdaq composite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think oil prices have clearly peaked, and will fall to the
mid-$20-a- barrel range,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, bond yields have fallen to the level where they are not
competitive with stock market earnings. And I am positive about
earnings. We have raised our earnings estimates for the S&AMP;P 500 to
15 percent from 12 percent for the current calendar year.''
</P>
<P>
   Canelo said the market was likely to broaden beyond technology
stocks into energy, financial services, capital goods and cyclical
stocks that will benefit from an improving global economy.
</P>
<P>
   By midsummer, he projects that the S&AMP;P 500 index will be
comfortably above 1600. And he added that the Nasdaq composite has
the potential to rise another 10 percent from current levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
