<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-AUDREY28-COX     03-27 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDREY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hewitt's doubts in her dream role echo Hepburn's own
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's face it: Jennifer Love Hewitt's
breasts are as famous as she is.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder some Hollywood insiders snickered when Hewitt
wanted to play the glamorous, stick-thin Audrey Hepburn in a TV
movie. After all, Hepburn was flat-chested. Hewitt is, well... we
all know what Hewitt is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's been something since I did those `I Know What You
Did Last Summer' movies where I wore those tiny tops, and stuff,''
Hewitt says, giggling.
</P>
<P>
   While filming ``The Audrey Hepburn Story,'' ABC's three-hour
biography debuting Monday, Hewitt wore a sports bra and an ace
bandage in several scenes to keep her assets hidden. ``Costume
designers have all the technology the aerospace industry has,''
jokes director Steve Robman. ``They did a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   But will viewers think the former ``Party of Five'' star is
wonderful as the legendary actress?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about turning on a new generation to Audrey
Hepburn,'' says Kimberly Rubin, the film's executive producer. ``We
think people will take (Hewitt) seriously and not just as a teen
queen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an easy job. Hepburn, who starred in such classics as
``Roman Holiday,'' ``Sabrina,'' ``Love in the Afternoon,'' ``Two
for the Road,'' ``Funny Face'' and ``Breakfast at Tiffany's,'' was
one of film's most beloved icons. With her eye-catching Givenchy
flair, she practically created the chic gamine. Her incredibly
influential look also helped set the style for the reedlike fashion
models so popular today.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the one woman who had every single thing a woman should
be,'' the 21-year-old Hewitt says. ``She was goofy, funny,
beautiful, smart, elegant, graceful, sexy. Any word you could think
of, she was it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hewitt wasn't sure if she could play Hepburn. She read the
criticism. And it stung. A lot. ``Two weeks before the movie
started, I was bawling and crying because all these stories were
coming out saying I couldn't pull it off, I wasn't talented enough,
I wasn't pretty enough, how dare I play Audrey Hepburn and there
was the whole chest thing,'' she remembers. ``I have thick skin,
but not that thick. It was hurtful to me and I told my mom, `I
don't think I'm pretty enough and I'm afraid of what people are
going to say.' That's when she took out the script and pointed out
a line with me as Audrey saying, `I don't think I'm talented
enough, pretty enough and I'm afraid of what people are going to
say.' She said, `For Audrey's sake, you have to do this movie and
you'll be great in it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who is co-executive producer of the film, has idolized
Hepburn ever since her mom showed her ``Breakfast at Tiffany's''
when she was 7. ```This is who you should grow up to be,''' Hewitt
recalls her mom saying about Hepburn's character, the ever-charming
Holly Golightly. ``I was absolutely captivated. I didn't understand
the story, but I could tell you every word she said and every move
she made. I was hooked ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, starring in ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' has been
Hewitt's dream project for years. Fortunately for Hewitt, Kimberly
Rubin, a veteran TV movie producer, had the same dream. Rubin
pitched the idea to several networks for eight years, but all of
them passed.
</P>
<P>
   But when Rubin met Hewitt to talk about a different project, she
was delighted to learn both were fascinated with Hepburn's
Cinderella life story. Once Hewitt signed on, ABC gave the $7
million film (most of which was spent on Hewitt's salary and the
enormous costume budget) the green light. ``Had we not had Love
Hewitt, I don't know if this movie was going to be made,'' Rubin
says.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, ABC chose to only focus on the first 32 years of
Hepburn's life. The network didn't seek cooperation from Hepburn's
family, however. ``There are Byzantine legal complications when you
do that,'' director Robman explains. ABC did show the final version
to Sean Ferrer, Hepburn's oldest son. ``He said it respected and
celebrated his mother's memory,'' Robman says.
</P>
<P>
   The film starts with Hepburn shooting ``Breakfast at Tiffany's''
famous opening scene in which she's munching on a sweet roll in
front of New York's famed jewelry store. But Hepburn gags the
moment she bites into it. Truman Capote (Michael J. Burg), who
wrote the novella on which ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' was based, is
visibly upset with Hepburn's performance, saying he would rather
see Marilyn Monroe star in the film because she knows how to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The film movingly deals with the Belgian-born Hepburn's
traumatic childhood during the Nazi occupation of Holland during
World War II (she worked as a courier for the Dutch resistance);
her rise to international film stardom; her torrid on-screen
romance with William Holden; her marriage to Mel Ferrer (a miscast
Eric McCormack of ``Will &AMP; Grace''); and her never-ending search
for the love of her father, a Nazi sympathizer who abandoned the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge in making the film, says Robman, was
upholding Hepburn's much-earned legacy, not only as an actress but
as a humanitarian. ``This woman is a cherished figure,'' says
Robman, who directed Hewitt often on ``Party of Five.'' ``We wanted
to respect that. We weren't interested in finding a dark, terrible,
awful secret. And there are none. People needed to believe Jennifer
was filled with grace and dignity like Audrey.''
</P>
<P>
   They also needed to believe Hewitt, who lost 11 pounds for the
film, imitating Hepburn's distinctive, yet unidentifiable accent.
Her mother was Dutch. Her father English. Hepburn grew up in
Holland and England. To help Hewitt, ABC hired a dialect coach.
``It took her about a half-day to get it right,'' Robman marvels.
``She's a singer and has an unbelievable ear. She approached it
like memorizing a melody.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Hewitt does nail the accent to near perfection. But
as she notes, it wasn't easy. ``It was the hardest thing to do,''
she says. ``A lot of times, the performance was right, but you
couldn't move on to another shot because part of the accent wasn't
there. Every day I was scared to death in that accent. There was
even talk of not doing the accent, but it wouldn't have been the
same movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt hopes she won't be viewed as the same actress after ``The
Audrey Hepburn Story'' airs. Instead of being cute and perky, she
wants to be serious ... and sexy. ``I've always been the cute
Gidget vs. Marilyn Monroe,'' she says, sighing. ``There are times I
wish people would say, `Jennifer is sexy and so hot,' not just
perky and cute all the time. But I'm much more the Gidget type and
you just have to live with it and face it. But I would like to
prove there's more depth to me than just laughing and a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
