<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT-     03-27 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MICROSOFT AND U.S. TALK WITH DEADLINE LOOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Editors: Also filed in ``f'' category.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Microsoft Corp. and the U.S. Justice
Department continued negotiations Monday on a possible settlement
to the government's landmark anti-trust lawsuit, but government
officials expressed skepticism that a deal could be made before
Tuesday's expected ruling in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, U.S. officials rejected a last-minute proposal
by the software giant, saying it didn't meet enough of the
government's demands.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson warned both
sides last week that he would issue his ruling Tuesday unless he
saw progress on the settlement talks, giving rise to speculation
that he might postpone the Tuesday deadline as long as both sides
were still negotiating. The judge's ruling would be on the question
of whether Microsoft's business practices were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision by Jackson to postpone his ruling would be
influenced by the views of Judge Richard Posner, chief judge of the
7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago, who has been mediating the
case since last November when Jackson asked him to help both sides
reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft nor representatives of the Justice Department
and the 19 states that brought the suit in 1998 had any official
comment on where things stood Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If he issues his ruling, Jackson is expected to deal harshly
with the Redmond, Wash.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, Jackson issued his ``findings of fact'' that said
Microsoft had used its monopoly power to stifle innovation, reduce
competition and hurt consumers by bundling its Internet Explorer
browser with its Windows operating system. A computer's operating
system is the core program that allows other programs, such as word
processing applications, to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Because Windows runs 95 percent of all computers, Jackson said,
Microsoft's bundling, or tying together, of its operating system
and its browser means that browser competitors _ such as Netscape _
would be at a severe disadvantage when it comes to selling their
own browsers. This led to less competition and less innovation,
which hurt consumers, he said. Microsoft contends that the browser,
which allows users access to the World Wide Web, is not a separate
product but an ``integrated feature'' of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The November findings represent Jackson's conclusions about
which side presented the most compelling and believable case during
the year-long hearing that opened in his court on Oct. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will use those findings to determine whether Microsoft's
actions actually broke the law. But since Jackson's finding of
facts were against the company, many antitrust experts say they
expected he will conclude that Microsoft's actions added up to
violations of antitrust law. Assuming Jackson's ruling goes against
Microsoft, the case would then move to its final phase: the penalty
stage. During the penalty stage, Jackson would determine what to do
to Microsoft to ensure the company doesn't break anti-trust law
again.
</P>
<P>
   The most drastic remedy being considered is breaking up the
company into separate parts to end its monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's latest proposal to settle the case reportedly would
allow manufacturers of computers or software to modify the Windows
source code to attach rival products, such as Internet browsers, to
the operating system. The company also would offer a version of
Windows that wouldn't feature Microsoft's own Internet Explorer
browser.
</P>
<P>
   In the proposal, Microsoft also reportedly offered equal pricing
and shipping terms to all computer makers who use its Windows
operating system software. Such a move would end Microsoft's
ability to offer pricing breaks to computer retailers that favor
other types of Microsoft software, such as Microsoft Word, over
competing products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea here would be to preclude Microsoft from punishing
companies that are cooperating with their competitors,'' said
William Kovacic, an anti-trust expert at George Washington
University who has followed the case.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing uniform pricing on Microsoft has one huge advantage:
It's a legal remedy that's easy to enforce and would require
minimal policing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Justice doesn't want is a decree that requires constant
supervision and regulation, which is difficult for both the
government and the company,'' said Ronald Cass, anti-trust expert
at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers reviewed Microsoft's proposal over the
weekend but decided it lacked enough assurances that the company
would not bundle future software products to Windows, government
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   While backing away from proposals to break up the company, the
Justice Department was expected to demand that Microsoft limit the
number of software products that the firm can add to Windows.
Justice officials believe that Microsoft uses this strategy to take
away market share of rival products, leading eventually to their
demise.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic said Microsoft has tremendous incentive to stop the
lawsuit before Jackson issues his verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's findings of fact showed that he found the government's
case against the company credible and that he rejected as
``specious,'' as he stated in one part, virtually all of
Microsoft's arguments. As a result, the company can reasonably fear
that Jackson's final verdict would find Microsoft guilty of
maintaining its monopoly by unlawful means.
</P>
<P>
   With a half-dozen private antitrust suits now filed against
Microsoft, Gates has strong incentives to strike a deal. Otherwise,
plaintiffs' lawyers would be able to use any negative ruling by
Jackson as a potent weapon in their civil suits against the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft doesn't want to give all these other lawsuits that
kind of ammunition,'' Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
