<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-COMM28-COX     03-27 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COMM28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox merger with Seagram a `market rumor'
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications and its parent firm spent about $12
billion on acquisitions last year to solidify their position in the
media and telecommunications industries, but adding Canada's
Seagram Co. to the mix isn't part of the plan, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not afraid to be aggressive and to be acquisitive,''
said Brian Farley, spokesman for Cox Enterprises Inc., which owns
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and holds a majority stake in Cox
Communications Inc., the No. 5 U.S. cable television company.
</P>
<P>
   But Farley said a report in London's Sunday Telegraph that Cox
Communications was planning to join with Vivendi SA in a merger
with the Montreal-based Seagram was ``total news to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications denied that it had been approached by either
company about a possible three-way merger, alliance, or any other
business ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no discussions in any way, shape or form,'' said
Ellen East, spokeswoman for Atlanta-based Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Paris-based Vivendi, which owns stakes in European pay-TV
operators, also denied that it was in merger talks to create a new
media company akin to the planned merger of Time Warner and America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   The pending Time Warner-AOL merger will create one of the
world's most powerful media companies, uniting communications and
media firms ranging from AOL's online service to Time Warner's
Fortune, Time and People magazines and CNN news channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of been prevalent thinking in the cable
industry,'' to unite communications channels with so-called
``content'' producers, said East.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's shares have risen more than 40 percent on speculation
that it would be sold after news reports that it was involved in
talks with a number of companies, including Comcast Corp., News
Corp., Walt Disney Co., and Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday Telegraph reported that Vivendi planned to pay up to
$32 billion for Seagram and an undisclosed amount for Cox
Communications, whose Class A shares had a market value Monday of
$27.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think quite literally Seagram has talked to everybody out
there'' following the Time Warner-AOL deal, said Michael Palmer,
beverage analyst for First Associates Investments in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But he said any potential merger could snag on Seagram's $11
billion acquisition of PolyGram at a time when the growing volume
of free music on the Internet is creating an uncertain future for
the music business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pet theory is there's going to be a lot of (merger) smoke
and no fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Any potential merger plans with Cox Communications would
certainly fizzle without the backing of Cox Enterprises, said East.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Enterprises owns almost 66 percent of Cox Communication's
Class A shares and all of its Class C shares, giving it control of
more than 76 percent of the company's shareholder votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cox Enterprises has said they're very happy with us,'' said
East. ``We did $10.2 billion worth of acquisitions last year
alone,'' she said, adding four cable television companies with
networks in seven states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very comfortable with our size,'' she added. ``We feel
like we're the size we need to be to be a player in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Cox Communication's acquisitions, privately-held Cox
Enterprises added about $12 billion worth of new businesses last
year, and it has another $1 billion worth pending, said Farley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's more acquisitions than we've seen in a year's
time, ever,'' he said, adding that ``we're always interested in
looking at businesses where we think there's a strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   But a deal with Vivendi and Seagram is not one of them, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rumor, a market rumor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
