<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ An appointed mediator
continued working feverishly Monday evening to work out an
11th-hour settlement in the antitrust case against Microsoft. But
opinions among some of the government officials who filed the suit
appeared to be hardening, setting up the likelihood that the trial
judge would issue a verdict as soon as Tuesday. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-PATENT (Boston) _ A legal showdown began here Monday
that could determine whether some of the biotechnology industry's
most lucrative drugs will be vulnerable to lower-priced
competition. On one side is Transkaryotic Therapies Inc., a tiny
company with technology that could allow it to circumvent patents
on drugs produced by genetic engineering. In partnership with
Aventis, the big European drug company, it wants to sell its own
version of Amgen Inc.'s Epogen, the biotechnology industry's
biggest drug with worldwide sales of about $4 billion. Amgen has
filed a patent infringement lawsuit aiming to protect its product.
By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
