<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PARTIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTYING ALL NIGHT LONG
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what do you serve up after an endless Oscar show? Right, an
endless Oscar party. Or at least a party that doesn't need to end
until the last guest has found his or her limo.
</P>
<P>
   A late evening is precisely what the hosts of the Governors Ball
_ the on-site post-Oscar fest thrown by the academy _ were aiming
for. Better to keep their guests chowing, dancing and schmoozing
into the wee hours rather than settling for a token appearance
before the stars head out to studio-thrown bashes in Hollywood and
Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The show's late ending certainly meant that Oscar winners and
their family members arrived a little later. Celebrities spotted
well past 10 p.m. included Warren Beatty, Annette Bening, Kevin
Spacey, Michael Clarke Duncan, Lucy Liu, Queen Latifah, Clint
Eastwood, Hilary Swank, Eric Clapton, Faith Hill and ``The Sixth
Sense'' director M. Night Shyamalan.
</P>
<P>
   Show producers Richard and Lili Fini Zanuck were congratulated
by practically every person they encountered. After spending the
telecast in a truck with the telecast director, Lili Zanuck seemed
ready to party.
</P>
<P>
   For the occasion, the Shrine's Exhibition Hall was decked out
with white parachuting that lit up with colorful, rotating
projected images, courtesy of David Smith and Show Pro. Now it's
blue, now it's red, now it's yellow. The largely dark tones even
encouraged the use of a sparkling party favor: a flashing red ring
that looked like something out of a comic book or a cereal box.
Even best actress nominee Julianne Moore wore one as she posed for
pictures before heading for the exit on the arm of director beau
Bart Freundlich.
</P>
<P>
   The main course of Wolfgang Puck's menu was a roasted chicken
breast with a wild mushroom risotto and black truffles. But the
repast's most souvenir-worthy item came from the desert tray: a
chocolate scroll bearing a detailed rendering of the five best
picture nominees. Folks not looking to preserve the treasure sank
their teeth into Tom Hanks' face (from ``The Green Mile'' poster)
or into the bare midriff from the ``American Beauty'' image.
</P>
<P>
   Newly won Oscars took their place on tables to be fondled and
admired by family and colleagues. One slightly irreverent winner
joked that she hoped to win a second statue in the near future so
she could simultaneously do bicep curls with both arms.
</P>
<P>
   Others won't even keep the statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it back to my mother and father (in Capetown),''
said Trefor Proud, co-winner with Christine Blundell of the best
makeup Oscar for ``Topsy-Turvy.'' ``They'll look after it for
me.'' &QL; 
___ By Evan Henerson &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
_________ &QL; 
MIRAMAX'S MEDIOCRE MASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night at the Beverly Hills Hotel, Harvey Weinstein
was overheard summing up Miramax's inability to snatch the Best
Picture Oscar from DreamWorks two years running: Miramax trumped
``Saving Private Ryan'' with ``Shakespeare in Love'' last year, but
SKG's ``American Beauty'' stomped ``The Cider House Rules'' this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Harvey, fresh from his semi-secretive hospitalization,
shruggingly philosophized: ``We're (expletive) mortal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Miramax's runners-up ball 2000 was nothing near the
depressing dirge last year's DreamWorks party was, even though the
mini-major only copped a couple of trophies, one for ``Cider House
Rules''
</P>
<P>
   Best Supporting Actor Michael Caine and another for its
screenwriter-author, John Irving. True, the no-shows (Meryl Streep,
GwynethPaltrow, Jude Law, Matt Damon, Ben Affleck, Sheri Lansing)
were far more celebrated than many of the attendees (Don Rickles,
Malcolm McDowell, Harvey Keitel, Michael Madsen). The odd pockets
of glamour (Ashley Judd, Roberto Benigni, briefly; Anthony
Minghella, even more briefly; a reported but unseen Jane Fonda)
were difficult to suss out amid the heavy wannabe and
fashion-victim contingent.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with John Irving, who said the number of drafts in
his novel version of ``Cider House'' approximated the number of
drafts in his screenplay, both years in the making; the only
difference was, with the screenplay: ``I was getting notes from a
number of other people, so I had some idea what I was doing.'' His
next project: Adapting his book ``A Son of the Circus'' (he's
allowing another book, ``A Widow for a Year,'' to be adapted
without his input, he'll finish but the first draft of his next
novel within a month, then subject it to his usual rounds of
revisions until his wife-agent tells him to surrender it to an
editor).
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Tarantino, the long-mute Oscar-winning tyro (``Pulp
Fiction''), promised, more or less, that the final draft of his
next script _ a World War II flick _ would be forthcoming within
the next few months; his hand fluttered spastically, indicating his
approximate level of pleasure with the progress of his writing.
Which was worse _ working on the script or fielding endless
questions about his next film's ETA? Tarantino laughed: ``That's
not been so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarantino at one point loudly insisted to honcho Weinstein that
attendee Tobe Hooper (``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre'') represented
the pinnacle of `70s independent filmmaking. He was also part of
one of the evening's most unique tableaux: trading loud insults
with Keitel, Madsen, Rickles and McDowell, while no more than a
yard away stood venerable TV newsman Walter Cronkite. Tarantino et
al. were a challenge to approach; Cronkite, the man America trusted
with its life for a couple of decades, was readily accessible.
</P>
<P>
   He was invited, he showed up, the erstwhile anchor pragmatically
explained. Did he think Miramax's offering represented the best of
Oscar's offerings? Walter, frankly: ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were winding down; though Weinstein invited winner Caine
to spend the night at the party, staffers were rolling the booze
away a quarter till two. We caught up with ``South Park: Bigger,
Longer and Uncut'' mastermind Trey Parker, who was !ital!robbed in
the Best Song category (``Blame Canada'' lost to whatever lame bit
of kiddy self-empowerment Phil Collins slapped together).
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who attended the awards in a parody of the Jennifer
Lopez Grammy dress (which was not seen at any point during the
ceremony), laughed that he was pretty sure that whoever was in
charge had strict orders not to get him on camera. He added he was
pleased with Robin Williams' performance, and glad that viewers saw
```80s Robin Williams, not `Patch Adams' Robin Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker was so friendly and accommodating, we decided to try to
irk him. ``Phil Collins !ital!deserved to win,'' we declared.
</P>
<P>
   Parker replied: ``(Really filthy expletive) Phil Collins up the
(anatomical region) five times,'' he said, not really betraying any
true malice. &QL; 
___ By David Kronke &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
