<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    newsweek says boomers aren't slowing down now that they've hit
big 5-0
 &HT;    Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and more baby boomers who have been racing along the fast
track for years are beginning to hit the big 5-O speed bump. Rather
than slowing down, says Newsweek ($3.50) in a special report, they
are simply taking detours that their security-conscious parents
never would have dared to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going quietly into their senior years, boomers are
switching careers and spouses, starting their own companies, and
cashing in on huge inheritances and 401K plans. Many are reordering
their priorities, Newsweek says, and attempting to recapture
deferred dreams. ``Your realize that life is very short,'' says
Terry Patten, a 49-year-old California entrepreneur who divorced
his wife, sold his company, and is doing yoga and lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting sidelight is an excerpt from David Brooks' new
book, ``Bobos in Paradise: The New Upper Class and How They Got
There.'' Brooks contends that the bohemians of the '60s have become
the bourgeoisie. Now, he says, ``you can't tell an espresso-sipping
potter from a cappuccino-drinking banker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nothing but blue skies: Who would have thought television
viewers would want to watch 24 hours of weather reports? New Yorker
($3) correspondent John Seabrook talks to executives at the
Atlanta-based Weather Channel about how they turned what seemed
like a bad idea at the time into a multimillion-dollar business.
``People watch weather on TV because it seems real,'' Seabrook
says, ``in a way that political scandals and stock-market gyrations
sometimes do not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Political views: George ($2.95) is not only surviving after
the death of its founder John F. Kennedy Jr., it's getting more
interesting. This month's issue features a cover story on
celebrities and their causes, an excerpt from Peggy Noonan's book
on Hillary Rodham Clinton, an essay by Pulitzer Prize-winning
author Jane Smiley on why she will miss Bill Clinton, and David
Halberstam's assessment on the legacy of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
