u f BC-BLACK-ANGELS28-COX     03-27 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-ANGELS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Symposium to match money with minority-run start-ups
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Brian Ransom needed additional working capital
for his downtown eatery, he bypassed the banks and sought the help
of an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Not the heavenly kind, but a wealthy private investor he met
through a networking forum that matches entrepreneurs with
deep-pocketed investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It afforded us the opportunity to continue developing the
concept of the restaurant,'' said Ransom, an Atlanta sports agent
who prefers to talk about the culinary side instead of the cash
side of the restaurant, 201 Courtland.
</P>
<P>
   Noted for its chili-crusted salmon and crawfish pie, the
restaurant is also owned by the Washington Redskins' Marco Coleman,
a former Georgia Tech football player, and Carlos Rogers, a
basketball player with the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   While Ransom regularly comes in contact with wealthy sports
figures, chances are slim that most aspiring entrepreneurs will
ever come in contact with a wealthy investor willing to back their
ideas. It's virtually unheard of for most minorities, who don't
travel in the same circles as many of the venture capitalists
they're trying to find.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of minority athletes, entertainers and entrepreneurs
is trying to change that by matching private investors with
minorities who want to start or expand businesses. The national
networking session will be in Atlanta the second weekend in April.
The Access to Capital Symposium and Millionaires Ball will be held
April 7 and 8 at the Ritz-Carlton Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing what the television show `Star Search' did for
entertainers,'' said Michael Chatman, a Miami businessman involved
with the conference. ``We're launching the promising careers of
start-up companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a chance to rub elbows with the rich, the symposium
will feature discussions on setting up a business plan, raising
money for business ideas regardless of personal credit history,
finding private investors to back your plan and learning more about
the multimillion-dollar venture capital industry.
</P>
<P>
   Access to Capital conducts seminars at the symposium in
association with Angel Investors Networking Forum for U.S. Emerging
Markets, a Dallas-based group of minority angel investors. Angel
investors are usually private individuals who prefer to remain out
of the public eye. They generally get a stake and say-so in the
company in exchange for their investment.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, venture capitalists continue to pour money into new
ventures, mostly high-tech start-ups. Much of that money is making
its way to Georgia. In the last three months of 1999, Georgia firms
attracted more than $372 million of venture capital, according to
PricewaterhouseCoopers' national MoneyTree survey. That number is
up more than 660 percent over the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few of the dollars reach the hands of minorities who need
the money to start or grow businesses, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, minorities and women are awarded lucrative
contracts to do work, but often what happens is they don't have the
capital to fill the order. So they wind up losing the business,''
said Chatman, vice president of the Access to Capital Group.
</P>
<P>
   The group does not provide the money to businesses. Instead, it
acts as a matchmaker between would-be business owners and angel
investors. It also screens potential business ventures before they
are presented to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be minority entrepreneurs, Chatman added, have
``tended to congregate among ourselves and not attended the events
where the big boys and big girls are. We have not found those seed
and early-stage investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stumbling block is the wall of silence many
entrepreneurs invoke when asked to talk about their business and
how it's financed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a source of frustration,'' Chatman concedes. ``Many
African-American businesses don't want to give the perception that
it is a black business. They feel like they'll lose business.
They're quick to say they don't want to be pigeonholed. But my
argument is that if you're competent enough to run the business,
color shouldn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Often for many venture capitalists such as Alan Taetle, the only
color that matters is green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some minorities, (but) we'd love to see more,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chatman, Taetle noted, ``The paths (of minorities and
potential investors) don't cross that often.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the absence is particularly evident at the university
level, where many of the ideas for start-up businesses are born. At
an Atlanta presentation on venture capitalism aimed at colleges and
universities last fall, the representation of the predominantly
black colleges was small in comparison to others. Taetle's firm,
Noro-Moseley Partners, sees about 200 companies a year and backs
about 20. When deciding whether to invest in a company, Taetle said
his firm looks at four criteria:
</P>
<P>
   _ The company needs to target big markets, which can yield
revenue of $1 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Management should really know the industry it wants to serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ The prospect should show proof that customers want what the
company is selling.
</P>
<P>
   _ The management team doesn't have to be experienced, but it
should have lots of energy and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The Access to Capital symposium is interested in linking
investors with people who have a broad range of businesses or
ideas. In the past three years, angel investors with the symposium
have invested from $50,000 to $5 million in various businesses,
Chatman said. Those businesses have included restaurants, real
estate firms, hair care products companies, Internet start-ups and
video distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
   Access to Capital has identified angels who want to provide seed
money in the earliest stages of the business development. ``This is
somewhat riskier than other venture capitalists, who wait for a
solid track record before investing,'' Chatman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Access to Capital symposium was started in 1998 by former
Seattle Seahawks linebacker Darrin Smith as a way to help minority
start-up companies find capital. The symposiums were
invitation-only in the past. But this year's event, along with the
Millionaires Ball, is being opened to investors and those seeking
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since our founding, we've attracted some of the most prominent
names in America,'' Smith said. ``The event is considered to be one
of the best events for African-American, Hispanic, Asian and women
entrepreneurs and investors looking to invest in start-up
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Some past symposium participants have included television
producer and actor Tim Reid; actor Blair Underwood; Hollywood
director Kevin Hooks; singer Howard Hewitt; and Atlanta
entrepreneur Bernard Bronner of Bronner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Chatman is quick to point out that while the symposium draws
many of black America's elite, some of the celebrities and athletes
are there seeking capital themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gain knowledge, expertise and networking information _
things you don't normally get in our community,'' Ransom noted.
``It's relationship development. It's (about) helping people
understand the business needs of acquiring money.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the symposium's investors are what Chatman calls
``cashed-out entrepreneurs'' who have sold their companies or
people who have inherited wealth and are looking to invest.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event has attracted the interest of more than 300
investors and entrepreneurs, 65 percent of whom are seeking
financial backers, from across the country. Atlanta is the only
city so far where the symposium has been held, Chatman said, but
one of the concerns symposium organizers have had is the relatively
low representation of metro Atlanta companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chatman said he doesn't know exactly how many people have
received angel financing through the symposium, but he noted, ``We
normally have 15 businesses that make presentations each year at
the symposium. The majority are start-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   About the event
</P>
<P>
   For details and registration, call (877) 408-1ACG. The cost is
$395 for the weekend or $150 for the Millionaires Ball. Atlanta
area residents have until Monday to register.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
