<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UGANDA-CULT-ART-NYT &LR;      03-27 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-CULT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER 80 BODIES FOUND AS INVESTIGATION INTO UGANDAN CULT GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda _ Another 80 bodies were exhumed Monday from a
mass grave discovered over the weekend on a rural plot of land once
owned by a leader of a doomsday cult, which now appears to be
linked to the deaths of at least 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the people found Monday, like the 159
unearthed last week from other mass graves, had been slain, said a
police spokesman, Eric Naigambi. ``There is no other reason why 80
people would end up in a mass grave,'' Naigambi said late Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's unearthing of corpses, in the village of Rugazi, was
the third such discovery since March 17, when at least 330
followers of the cult, the Movement for the Restoration of the Ten
Commandments of God, died in a fire set by some members in a chapel
on the cult's isolated compound in Kanungu, about 200 miles south
of Kampala, the capital. The cult believed the end of the world was
to come on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rugazi is simply the latest site to be searched by police as
they try to piece together what happened on March 17 and determine
who was responsible. So far their searches have only added more
questions.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the fire, investigators pulled six bodies from
a pit latrine on the cult's compound in Kanungu, just steps away
from the charred wreckage of the chapel. The six people, who could
not be identified, had been slain.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Friday, in Rutoma, a village about 30 miles from
Kanungu, the police unearthed the bodies of 153 people buried in
mass graves on a plot of land used by the cult. The people had been
slashed to death or strangled during the past several weeks, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators arrived in Rugazi, which is also about 30 miles
from Kanungu, during the weekend, and on Sunday discovered the
remains of a human being buried in a grave, police said. Digging
was halted immediately, and a team of senior investigators was
summoned from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the police department's head of criminal investigations,
the team, which includes a government chemist and a government
pathologist, was expected to arrive in the village late Monday, a
police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The search of the site was not supposed to resume until
Wednesday when the experts arrived from the capital, Naigambi said.
But inexplicably the local officials resumed the search Monday
afternoon and soon discovered that the lone body found on Sunday
was far from the only one.
</P>
<P>
   A local doctor examining the bodies said at the scene that the
victims appeared to have been dead about a month, according to The
Associated Press, which reported that some of the bodies appeared
to have stab wounds while others had pieces of cloth tied around
their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Why the digging began before the team from the capital arrived
and why the bodies were re-buried before being examined by that
team are just the latest questions in what has been a troubled
investigation from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently overwhelmed by the number of bodies, the authorities
here have conducted only cursory autopsies before reburying the
dead in mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   The order to halt digging and wait for the experts to arrive was
supposed to have been a step toward straightening out the
investigation. ``We don't know what happened,'' Naigambi, the
police spokesman, said when asked why the search had proceeded
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The property where the bodies were found Monday was owned until
recently by Dominic Kataribaabo, a disgraced former priest who was
one of the cult's leaders and is believed to have perished in the
fire at Kanungu, another police spokesman, Assuman Mugenyi, said.
The house was apparently used by the cult for seminars and meetings
until about a month ago when Kataribaabo sold it to his brother,
Mugenyi said.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the sale, only weeks before the deadly inferno at
Kanungu, is another piece of circumstantial evidence suggesting
that many of the cult's followers knew something momentous was
about to happen. Only hours before the fire in Kanungu, cult
members set fire to all five buildings in the compound in Rutoma
before leaving for Kanungu, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The mounting evidence that the events of March 17 were carefully
planned, plus the discovery of more bodies, has forced the police
to pursue the case as a murder investigation. The cult's two most
prominent leaders, Joseph Kibwetere and Credonia Mwerinde, are
among the prime suspects, the police said. No one knows whether
either of them is alive, but the police here are operating on the
assumption that they are and are on the run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
