<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush clash over Gore's proposal to ``break the link
between money and political influence'' with a $7.1 billion
endowment to pay for House and Senate campaigns. Bush charges that
the plan would be ``a taxpayer-financed government takeover'' of
the campaigns. Experts see little chance of an overhaul this year.
By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ State records show that Gov. George
W. Bush has spent few days at the Texas Capitol tending state
business as he devotes time for his presidential campaign. By PEGGY
FIKAC. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-TALKS (Vienna, Austria) _ OPEC oil ministers stumble in a
bid to reach a deal to increase production. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-FUJIMORI (Lima) _ Amid fierce criticism from opposition
politicians and independent monitors that he is trying to rig the
country's upcoming election, President Alberto Fujimori insists
that Peru's electoral process has been free and fair. He says in an
interview that the sudden emergence of a strong challenger in the
April 9 election is proof of a level playing field. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT (Washington) _ Lawyers for the Microsoft
Corp. and the U.S. Justice Department continue negotiations on a
possible settlement to the government's landmark anti-trust
lawsuit, but government officials express skepticism that a deal
could be made before Tuesday's expected ruling in the case. By MARK
HELM. (Also filed in ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WELFARE (Washington) _ The federal government's refusal
to pay welfare benefits to poor legal residents survives a Supreme
Court challenge. Without comment, the justices let stand a lower
court ruling that says Congress has the constitutional authority to
change welfare law, as was done in 1996, and deny food stamps and
other benefits to non-citizens living legally in the United States.
By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LaROUCHE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes a blow
to fringe presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche, upholding a lower
court ruling that the Democratic Party legally refused to count
votes cast for him during the 1996 presidential primary. By STEVE
LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FLAG-AMENDMENT (Washington) _ The Senate begins debate of a
constitutional amendment to ban desecration of the flag,
legislation that has consistently failed to get the required
two-thirds vote. The measure has been approved by the House. By
GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PLANT-BLAST (Houston) _ An explosion rocks a Phillips Petroleum
Co. chemical plant in nearby Pasadena, sending at least 50 workers
to area hospitals. At least one worker is listed as missing. A
blast at the plant killed 23 people in 1989. By RUTH RENDON and
JENA MORENO.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LOTTO (Austin, Texas) _ A plan that would make it harder
to win the Texas Lottery's biggest jackpots is back. And so are the
protests. Stymied by sluggish Lotto ticket sales, the agency in
charge of the games has revived a plan that was ditched last fall
because of an outcry from players. The plan calls for adding four
more numbered balls to the 50 that are used to draw the lottery
numbers for the twice-a-week jackpots. By JOHN GONZALEZ. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PLAYERS (Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.) _ Hal Sutton holds off a
late charge by Tiger Woods to win the Players Championship by one
stroke as players complete the rain-delayed final round. By EDDIE
SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NL CENTRAL (Mesa, Ariz.) _ A preview of the National League
Central focuses on the Chicago Cubs under new manager Don Baylor.
By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Robert Strauss, a longtime adviser
to presidents of both parties, shows at age 81 that he is still the
ultimate Washington insider. At a press organization dinner last
weekend he proved he has not lost his sense of humor or deft
political touch. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ ``Reform'' is a positive _ and
therefore subjective _ word that is overused. It implies an
improvement in something, but what is viewed as ``reform'' by one
person may be considered a pox on society by someone else. By CLAY
ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
