<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FRIENDLY'S-CLOSINGS-B     03-27 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDLY'S-CLOSINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENERABLE NEW ENGLAND RESTAURANT CHAIN TO REORGANIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When America watched The Mickey Mouse Club on TV and Buicks were
heavy with tailfins and chrome, New England families often visited
a Friendly's Ice Cream Shoppe for the comfort foods of summer.
</P>
<P>
   But times _ and diets _ have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Amid intense competition from everyone from large national
rivals to the diner down the street, Friendly's has spent the last
15 years mostly shrinking and struggling to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bad news for a one-time regional icon came Monday
when Friendly Ice Cream Corp., based in Wilbraham, Mass., said it
had just closed 80 of its 683 restaurants, with plans to close 70
more over the next two years. Among those that were closed are 11
in Massachusetts. By way of comparison, about 850 Friendly's dotted
the Northeast in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's reorganization didn't just close restaurants; it also
is expected to result in the elimination of 110 management and
administrative jobs, Friendly's said. Waiters and waitresses will
be transferred to other restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a retrenchment mode,'' said Andrew Ebersole, a bond
analyst with KDP Investment Advisors in Montpelier, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago when many baby boomers were still children and
few adults had ever heard of cholesterol, tofu, or celebrity chefs
on TV, many New England families had two options when it came to
eating out: Friendly's or Howard Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the measure of a restaurant was its dessert menu.
If a chain didn't offer at least a dozen varieties of ice cream and
frozen desserts, many consumers weren't interested.
</P>
<P>
   But today's consumer is far more health conscious. And consumers
have far more restaurant choices than 30 years ago. When Friendly's
is only one choice among many restaurant options, it can compare
poorly to rivals, said John Macht of the Macht Group, a Boston
consulting firm that includes restaurants among its clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be wonderful,'' he said. ``It just lost its way.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Friendly's thinks otherwise. Its small, older
shops are outdated, the company readily concedes, but a new larger
version of Friendly's shows much promise.
</P>
<P>
   With about 165 seats, these new restaurants are about 2 1/2
times larger than the old ice cream shoppes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides burgers, tuna melts, and Oreo sundaes, the bigger
kitchens at these new Friendly's also can serve up quesadillas,
salads, and veggie wraps.
</P>
<P>
   By closing underperforming older restaurants so it can focus on
larger, newer ones, the company said it looks to pursue a
``brilliant-at-the-basics'' strategy that emphasizes quality,
service, and value to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This move is a crucial step toward strengthening the company's
core restaurant business,'' said Friendly's chairman and chief
executive Donald N. Smith, whose company bought Friendly's in a
1988 leveraged buyout from Hershey Food Corp. and took the chain
public in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Average sales at the Friendly's stores that just closed lagged
far below the company's chainwide 1999 annual average of $958,000,
noted Friendly's spokeswoman Vivian H. Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, nearly all stores were company owned. Now 100
stores are owned by franchisees, and franchising is a big part of
Friendly's growth strategy moving forward, she added.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the restaurant closings, Friendly's plans to take
a pretax asset writedown of about $18 million and a pretax
restructuring charge of about $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Friendly's seems to be a great idea _ a place where
families and seniors can enjoy reasonably priced meals at a
full-service restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's restaurant landscape, Friendly's may be occupying
a niche that's getting squeezed from both above and below, some
industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   On the low side, there are fast-food chains where consumers can
eat for about $4. Just above Friendly's are chains such as Chili's
Grill &AMP; Bar, where consumers can pay between $10 and $15 for a
meal.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it would seem that there might be room for a
restaurant where customers can pay about $6 for a meal, the amount
Friendly's said is the size of its average tab.
</P>
<P>
   But restaurant chains in this price range sometimes have had a
tough time in the 1990s, according to Technomic Inc., a Chicago
consulting firm that tracks the restaurant industry.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to picking a family restaurant, many consumers
seem to be opting for either a cheap and cheerful outing at
McDonald's or a minisplurge at Chili's.
</P>
<P>
   That's one theory. But it's hard to pin down any one reason why
Friendly's long-promised comeback story has been delayed once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't point to one single thing,'' said analyst Ebersole,
who cited competition from many rivals and rising labor costs as
two factors hurting Friendly's at a time when a booming economy has
many consumers dining out more often.
</P>
<P>
   After a disastrous 1995, when Friendly's lost $58.7 million on
revenue of $649.2 million, there has been progress. For the fiscal
year that just ended, Friendly's finally made its way back into the
black, earning $400,000 on sales of $709 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company seems to have stalled once again, possibly
hurt by its heavy debt load. Investors also seem to have lost
patience. Monday Friendly's shares dipped 12.5 cents to close at
$3.875 on Nasdaq, near a 52-week low of $3.0625.
</P>
<P>
   With so many changes in the way consumers eat, restaurants must
innovate constantly to survive, consultant Macht said. Having a
proud local history may not be a good enough reason for today's
consumer to choose Friendly's over the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Said Macht, ``There may not be a need for a place like this to
exist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Brooks strongly disagreed. ``We have a strong
concept, with ice cream as our point of difference,'' she said.
``This brand still has tremendous potential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
