<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNIPER-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNIPER NETWORKS PLANS TO UNVEIL FASTEST INTERNET ROUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its march into the data networking market, Juniper
Networks Inc. intends to announce Tuesday that it is shipping what
appears to be the fastest electronic switch for Internet
information.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major communications carriers that have agreed to
purchase Juniper's new system are MCI WorldCom Inc.'s Uunet unit,
the world's No. 1 Internet carrier; Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC of
Britain, which controls the former MCI's United States Internet
operation; and the European joint venture between Qwest
Communications International Inc.; and KPN, the Dutch
communications company.
</P>
<P>
   Uunet in particular seems so enamored of Juniper's new creation
that it intends to announce Tuesday that it will use the product to
upgrade much of its network to higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Systems like Juniper's, which direct Internet information from
one point to another, are known as routers. As demand for Internet
service grows, communications carriers are continually on the
lookout for faster routers. Juniper's new router appears to be the
first that can reliably and consistently manage Internet flows of
10 billion digital bits a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only box we've been able to qualify for use in the
backbone'' at this rate,'' Michael D. O'Dell, Uunet's chief
scientist, said Monday in an interview. ``Without naming names, let
me just say that most people trying to sell into this space make us
aware of their product offerings and the Juniper box is the only
one we've been able to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Juniper, based in Mountain View, Calif., has skyrocketed to
prominence among investors and communications professionals as it
has successfully challenged the dominance of Cisco Systems Inc. in
the market for ultra high-performance Internet routers. With barely
$100 million in revenue last year, Juniper now has a market value
of about $43 billion. After first offering stock to the public last
summer for $34 a share, the company's shares closed at $276.4375
Monday, up $7.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic cards within Juniper's new system that are similar in
concept to those inside a personal computer can each handle two
traffic streams of 10 billion bits a second, forming one circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Eight such cards fit into the new router's chassis, which is
about the size of a small refrigerator that might be found in a
dormitory room. So the new product, called the M160, can route a
total of 160 billion bits of digital information each second.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's most powerful router occupies about twice the space of
the M160 and has a total capacity of 80 billion bits a second.
Juniper currently has the lead over Cisco largely because Juniper's
electronic cards can handle individual flows of 10 billion bits a
second, while Cisco's are now limited to 2.5 billion bits a second.
</P>
<P>
   Building on its acquisition of the privately held Nexabit
Networks last summer, Lucent Technologies Inc. is now working with
communications carriers in trials of an Internet router that can
manage traffic flows of 10 billion bits a second. But that system
has not yet become generally available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is largest, fastest device ever created for the
Internet,'' Scott Kriens, Juniper's chairman, said Monday in an
interview. ``It's the next generation of Internet performance and
it delivers a backbone which allows the entire network to scale
from today's capacity, which supports about 250 million users, to
tomorrow's demand, which is for 1 billion users.''
</P>
<P>
   But its sheer capacity was not the only reason the new Juniper
system was selected by Uunet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the drawbacks of traditional Internet technology is that
it does not differentiate between digital flows that require
first-class treatment, like phone calls, and those that can travel
bulk freight, like Web surfing. Along with other companies
including Cisco and Lucent, Juniper is using new technology that
can allow Internet routers to transmit different digital bits with
different levels of priority.
</P>
<P>
   That can allow communications carriers to simplify their
networks, eliminating other technologies that were needed just to
assure that certain bits were treated better than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we can keep scaling the network,'' said O'Dell. ``We
have to keep making more capacity, and I mean lots more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
