<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES RULE BENEFITS CAN BE DENIED TO FOREIGN-BORN U.S.
RESIDENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government's refusal to pay welfare
benefits to permanent residents who are not U.S. citizens survived
a Supreme Court challenge Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the justices let stand a lower court ruling
that Congress acted constitutionally when it changed federal
welfare laws in 1996 to deny benefits to foreign-born U.S.
residents until they have lived in the United States for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago and legal U.S. residents in the city had unsuccessfully
challenged the 1996 amendment as violating the Constitution's
guarantee of equal protection. They said the amendment denied to
indigent legal permanent residents the same benefits, such as food
stamps and Medicaid, the federal government provides to poor U.S.
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's failed appeal was the first major Supreme Court
challenge to the constitutionality of the 1996 Personal
Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, popularly
referred to as the welfare-reform law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the statute, the federal government must withhold welfare
benefits to new permanent residents for five years. States and
cities, however, may still provide benefits but without financial
help from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent residents, as defined by the federal government, fall
in the legal gap between immigrants authorized to be in the United
States for temporary assignments, such as students, and U.S.
citizens, who enjoy all the rights, benefits and duties of American
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law, aimed at encouraging welfare recipients to find
work, had the backing of congressional Republicans and President
Clinton but was roundly criticized by members of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats regarded the act's restrictions on welfare
payments as an abandonment of the Democratic principle of helping
the needy. Three senior members of the Department of Health and
Human Services, which administers the federal welfare program,
resigned in protest shortly after Clinton signed the reform measure
into law in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the act, including the Children's Defense Fund,
note that 570,000 permanent residents who were otherwise eligible
for federal food stamps last year did not receive the benefit
because they were not U.S. citizens, according to the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's refusal to hear Chicago's appeal of the 7th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' decision sets no national legal
precedent. But the justices action is binding in the three states
governed by the 7th Circuit, Illinois, Indiana and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th Circuit ruled last year that the Constitution permits
the federal government to extend greater benefits to U.S. citizens
than it does to legal residents provided the government has a
``rational basis'' for doing so. In its decision, the 7th Circuit
accepted the federal government's argument that the denial of
benefits was a rational method for keeping public expenditures down
and discouraging immigration to the United States by people
primarily interested in exploiting the country's welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The National League of Cities, in its brief to the justices,
said Congress' decision to stop paying welfare benefits to legal
residents has left local governments with the high cost of
supporting poor people without any federal help. The National Law
Center on Homelessness and Poverty added that these costs will rise
as the number of indigent permanent residents increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration, in successfully urging the
justices to reject the appeal, argued that the federal government
has wide constitutional authority to deny benefits to legal U.S.
residents that it extends to U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
