<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CROSS-BURNING28-COX     03-27 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSS-BURNING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cross purposes: Why was symbol burned on woman's front yard?
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, Ga. _ Lawanda Holmes was so eager to see her new
dinette table that she hurried past the smoldering cross in her
front yard without a glance.
</P>
<P>
   But her boyfriend, Travis Gammage, smelled gasoline and realized
that the small cross had been burned a few feet from Holmes' front
door. Earlier that evening, helping deliver the table, he'd found a
note with a racial slur on the door.
</P>
<P>
   When Holmes saw the charred cross, she burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking it was the KKK,'' the 20-year-old black woman
said. ``I was terrified. I thought of all kinds of stuff: churches
being burned, bottles being thrown through windows, houses being
set on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes was stunned when authorities charged three of her closest
neighbors, including Richland City Council member Roy ``Pete''
Cobb, with the Feb. 16 cross burning.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb, 46, lives a few doors from the house Holmes rented a few
months ago; their families have known each other for generations in
tiny Richland, 35 miles south of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mama used to nurse Pete Cobb and his brothers,'' said
Holmes' grandfather, Richard Rhine, 64. ``He really fooled me. I
really know him.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, slowly shaking his head. ``Or I thought I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got me guilty and I haven't done anything,'' he said.
``This is something that's got blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Charged along with Cobb with criminal trespass and making
terroristic threats are Frank Anderson, a 41-year-old sawmill
worker, and Cobb's brother's stepson, Kenneth Royal, 26, a welder.
The three men are white.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson could not be reached for comment. Royal declined to
answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney John Parks, whose circuit includes Stewart
County, said it will be September at the earliest before he can
present the cases to a grand jury because the rural county holds
court only twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects also could be prosecuted under the federal
hate crimes statute, although no federal charges have been filed to
date, said Pam Lightsey, spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office
in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Lightsey said she could neither confirm nor deny a federal
investigation into the incident. Several Richland residents said
they have been questioned by an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-collar neighborhood where the cross burning occurred is
just off a busy highway. The pale blue concrete block house Holmes
rented is directly across a narrow street from small houses that
Anderson and Royal rent.
</P>
<P>
   The short street seems safe enough. Children's colorful toys are
scattered in yards; laundry flaps from clothes lines.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb's son, Roy Jr., his wife, Sandi _ both ministers in the
Pentecostal Evangelical Church _ and their three pre-schoolers live
next door to Holmes. Sandi Cobb said she and Holmes were friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd invited her to come to Bible study at my house, and we'd
prayed together,'' she said. ``I was shocked when this happened. My
husband was, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the cross burning, Holmes has been staying with her
mother, Ingrid Jose; she is fearful, she said, of returning to the
mostly white neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-burning episode shocked everybody, black and white, in
rural Stewart County, said Sheriff Larry Jones, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like this has ever happened here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said he does not believe the Klan or other hate
groups were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three arrested appeared to be drunk that night,'' Jones
said. ``If they hadn't been drinking, it probably never would have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities found the remains of a rocking chair from which the
cross was made in Anderson's yard, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Stories conflict about a possible motive. The sheriff said he
was told the cross was burned to frighten Holmes away because
someone else wanted to rent her house. Others said Holmes had
late-night visitors who may have disturbed one of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Cross burnings are not rare, according to Mark Potok of the
Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery, Ala., which counted more
than 200 cross-burning episodes nationwide between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the first cross was burned atop Stone Mountain, Ga., in
1915, the technique has become the best-known of the Klan's many
tactics of intimidation,'' Potok wrote in a recent article for the
center's Intelligence Report. ``Today, a cross is burned nearly
every week, most typically at the homes of interracial or black
families.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP will keep a close eye on the Stewart County case, said
Edward Dubose, district coordinator and Columbus branch president
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue we will follow all the way,'' he said. ``In
my opinion, this is about more than being drunk. This was a hate
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred in a part of Georgia plagued by poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart County ranks among the poorest in the state. Its
population, in steady decline since 1930, has dwindled to about
5,300 residents, more than two-thirds of whom are black. The
county's infant mortality and high school dropout rates are among
Georgia's highest.
</P>
<P>
   Area attractions include the Chattahoochee River, which forms
the county's western border before emptying into the giant Walter
F. George reservoir. Near Lumpkin, the county seat, is Providence
Canyon State Park, a 150-foot deep gorge carved by more than a
century of erosion. The canyon's steep sides are layered in sunset
colors of russet, rose and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   But poverty is evident in Richland, population of about 1,700,
where paint peels from empty houses and the blank windows of vacant
buildings overlook an all-but-deserted downtown main street.
</P>
<P>
   At Cobb Enterprises, the council member and another son, Robert,
sell discount furniture and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Cobb said he has been ``humiliated'' by the charges
against him. He opened his checkbook and pointed out a $25 donation
he made to the NAACP on March 16, a month after the cross burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I do that if it's racial?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   That's a question many Richland residents are asking. Cobb, who
began his first term in January, owes his election and his
livelihood to blacks, said Holmes's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet you he didn't get 20 white votes,'' Rhine said. ``Most
of his customers are black.''
</P>
<P>
   Many blacks also considered Cobb a friend, Jose said. Before the
cross burning, she often stopped by his store just to sit and talk
to him, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Cobb is a highly respected businessman that black people
just loved,'' Jose said.``Just to think that he had something like
this in him is shocking. It is really shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
