<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker reports `not true,' Expos say
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The trade rumor mill was in high gear Monday,
but judging by the reaction at spring camp, that's all it was.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports Monday that the Expos and Braves were on the
verge of a trade that would send closer John Rocker to Montreal for
closer Ugueth Urbina, who led the National League with 41 saves
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true, absolutely not true,'' Expos owner Jeffrey
Loria said. ``I've heard for weeks now about Rocker, Urbina. ...
There's nothing on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz also dismissed it,
saying, ``That's an old story. It's not even part of our camp.
We're concerned with how John's pitching and how our pitching staff
is coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, the day arbitrator Shyam Das reduced Rocker's
suspension and sent him to camp, Schuerholz acknowledged listening
to offers, but he wanted to give Rocker some time to prove he could
fit in well with the team following his angry slurs in Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said Monday that he's satisfied, and pitcher Tom
Glavine said he is, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fine,'' Glavine said. ``If it comes down to making
us a better team, that's one thing, but if you're doing it to
alleviate a problem ... I don't think that problem exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal players anonymously let their objections to a potential
Rocker trade be known when they photocopied an article on the
subject with a mug shot of Rocker from the Palm Beach Post, drew a
circle with a slash through it in red ink and posted copies around
their clubhouse. The Braves plan to keep him in extended spring
training for the first two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if this spring had been normal, Rocker said:
``Absolutely. I see no difference except the difference that the
media has tried to make. If some outside person could walk into
this clubhouse, they would not know anything had happened ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
