<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-INQUIRY-BOS &LR;      03-27 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-INQUIRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLOODY SUNDAY' INVESTIGATION OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland _ An ambitious if belated attempt
to review one of the worst chapters in recent Irish history began
here Monday with the opening of a public inquiry into the killing
of 14 civil rights demonstrators by British paratroopers on what
became known as Bloody Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Coming 28 years after the event, the public tribunal opened as
the power-sharing government that brought Catholics and Protestants
into a new Northern Ireland administration remains suspended and
the political process lies stalled. Dissident paramilitary groups
are spoiling for a return to violence.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the tribunal began sitting in the city hall
Monday showed that part of the peace process is independent of
politics, and that it continues to forge ahead even as the
politicians bicker.
</P>
<P>
   If the refusal of the British government to acknowledge what its
soldiers did here on the streets of the Bogside neighborhood helped
fuel the Troubles that convulsed Northern Ireland for much of the
last 30 years, many hope that the attempt to right that wrong will
go a long way toward ending the conflict once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   The process will not be quick, however. The probe, which already
cost some $25 million, will last at least two more years.
</P>
<P>
   The original British investigation into what happened on Jan.
30, 1972, concluded that soldiers panicked and, believing they were
being shot at by militants of the Irish Republican Army, opened
fire on the demonstrators in the confusion. The soldiers were
officially exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   But most people here, and many international observers, have
maintained that the initial investigation was a whitewash, that
what happened on Bloody Sunday was cold-blooded murder by soldiers
who were whipped into a frenzy by their superiors and who carefully
targeted and shot unarmed Catholic nationalists. In all, 27 people
were shot that day, five of them in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The killings, the IRA's and the British government's response to
them, and the attempts by the British to portray the victims as
terrorists, rather than unarmed demonstrators, was a major turning
point in the Troubles. It polarized the two communities, escalated
the violence, and ended any chance that the dispute in Northern
Ireland would be addressed principally by a nonviolent campaign
modeled on the American civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA was flooded with recruits and stepped up its violent
campaign. The British tightened their grip, alienating many
innocent Catholics harassed in the crackdown. More than half of the
people killed during the Troubles died in the five years following
Bloody Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the annals of atrocities committed by the state against its
own people, Bloody Sunday takes its place alongside India's
Amritsa, South Africa's Sharpeville, Mexico's Tlateloco and
America's Kent State,'' British journalists Peter Pringle and
Philip Jacobson argue In their new book, ``Those Are Real Bullets,
Aren't They?.''
</P>
<P>
   The dry, lawyer-like language delivered in the sterile
surroundings of the Guildhall (city hall) did not capture how
viscerally the events of Bloody Sunday shaped this city and the
whole island.
</P>
<P>
   In a place where memories are long, and history is often wielded
as a weapon, the tribunal must do its work in the yawning gap
between two communities, one Protestant and loyal to the union with
Britain, the other Catholic and Irish nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, which began Monday and is expected to
last up to four weeks, the tribunal's chief counsel, Christopher
Clark, said the inquiry's job is to divine the truth from the two
diametrically opposed views of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeking the truth, not the truth as people see it, not
the truth as people would like it to be, but the truth pure and
simple. Those who have campaigned for so long to establish this
inquiry seek no more. Parliament, which set up this inquiry, seeks
no less. Without it, the many concerns which led to this inquiry
cannot be laid to rest,'' said Clark.
</P>
<P>
   On the 20th anniversary of Bloody Sunday, then Prime Minister
John Major of Britain acknowledged the victims were innocent. But
Major stopped short of an apology and rejected calls for a new
inquiry. But his successor, Tony Blair, ordered a fresh look, the
first time a British government ever reopened a public inquiry,
saying it was an essential part of the peace process. Blair
acknowledged the original Widgery Tribunal was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was established two years ago, the tribunal headed by
Lord Mark Saville, a senior British judge, has been gathering
evidence in private, interviewing nearly 1,500 witnesses. Clark
said investigators have traced witnesses down on every continent
except Antartica, ``from as far west as Nevada and as far east as
Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   By spending whatever time and money it takes to establish what
happened on Bloody Sunday, the British government seems willing to
compensate for its previous failings. And as Clark showed Monday,
the tribunal will try to put what happened in historical context.
The next two years will be part justice, part history lesson, all
of it hopefully cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   Potential witnesses include the famous and the powerful, such as
former Prime Minister Edward Heath and General Michael Jackson, who
led NATO troops into Kosovo last year and who was on the streets
with the paratroopers in Bogside 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the witnesses will be ordinary people like Kay
Duddy, whose 17-year-old brother Jackie was gunned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have ever wanted was the truth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Duddy and about 80 other relatives of the victims sat
in an area specially cordoned off for the families. They watched
stoically, many with their arms crossed, their body language
suggesting they will reserve judgment on the money and attention
being lavished on a review they fought 28 years for.
</P>
<P>
   The Guildhall has been transformed into a huge courtroom. The
proceedings are being broadcast on the screen of a nearby theater
that seats 900 people. Joining Lord Saville are two other judges,
William Hoyt of Canada and Sir Edward Somers of New Zealand, whose
international background is aimed at ensuring impartiality.
</P>
<P>
   There remain lingering disputes. The relatives are angry that
the soldiers who testify will enjoy anonymity and limited immunity.
The army maintains this is necessary for their safety, but the
relatives say this shows the preferential treatment still afforded
the army.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike South Africa, where the secrets of a brutal conflict
between the government and apartheid foes were catalogued by a
truth commission, there is no consensus here about the cathartic
value of exposing human rights abuses by paramilitary groups and
state forces.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland is still a divided society in which each side
tends to view the suffering of the other with a sense of
ambivalence, detachment, and even resentment. Gregory Campbell, a
leading hardline unionist here, says there should be inquiries into
slaughters of Protestants by the IRA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
