<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9582 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DISABLED-FARMERS-ART-     03-27 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-FARMERS-ART-702(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING DISABILITIES, BUT STAYING ON THE FARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 23,24 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACKLEY, Iowa _ Rising before dawn for Sunday chores, Darwin
Hoffmeister fed the pigs, checked the cows and mended a trampled
fence. But he could not tie his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmeister, a 50-year-old Iowa farmer, lost four fingers and
the use of his left arm in a combine accident five years ago, the
kind of injury that makes farming one of the nation's most
dangerous professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, being a farmer always meant being independent, able to
do whatever needs to be done,'' said Hoffmeister, a lanky,
soft-spoken man with a square jaw, as he looked down at the kitchen
floor and shook his head. ``Now I can't even handle a shovel or a
pitchfork.''
</P>
<P>
   But while such a disability would once have driven a farmer out
of business, Hoffmeister has been able to keep farming by modifying
his machinery and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of thousands of farmers in America with disabilities
who have triumphed over physical adversities, an achievement made
possible by technological advances and the changed nature of
farming, which today relies more on brain power and computer skills
than strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the accident, plenty of people offered to take over the
farm,'' said Hoffmeister, whose crops were harvested after the
accident by more than 50 neighbors who showed up at the farm,
offering their help. ``But farming is all I've ever done. And I
wanted to prove to myself that I could still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has proved it. Hoffmeister still does about 90 percent of the
work on the farm, raising pigs, cows, corn and soy beans on a
400-acre spread of rolling land along a gravel road here in deepest
Iowa, about 40 miles west of Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Terrible accidents have always been a familiar sorrow of farm
life. In a radius of no more than 20 miles from here, Hoffmeister
knows farmers who have lost an arm, broken a neck, seen both legs
severed below the knee. He now spends time talking on the telephone
to Iowa farmers who have recently suffered such injuries, just as
other farmers called to counsel him after the metal fan in the
combine forever changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Easter Seals, which runs a project intended to
help disabled farmers stay on the land, Hoffmeister changed the
ladders on his combine, put guard rails atop his grain bin and
adapted to a special hammer with a magnetic plate that holds a
nail. The charity also bought him a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the accident in October 1994, Hoffmeister had
noticed that the fan in the combine was clogged. He climbed down
from the cab in the darkness and stretched a hand into the
mechanical innards of the powerful machine, trying to sweep away
the excess grain. He was in too much of a hurry to shut off the
machine. The spinning metal fan caught his hand, crushed his
fingers, and then wildly rotated his arm like a windmill, before
knocking him backward 20 feet into a corn field, where he lay
covered in blood.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Darin, a junior in high school at the time, who was
driving a tractor behind him, ran to help his father. The teen-ager
fastened pliers around his father's bleeding arm for a makeshift
tourniquet, and then helped him to the kitchen of the farm house.
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance with sirens wailing soon rushed Hoffmeister to
Ellsworth Municipal Hospital in Iowa Falls, 13 miles away. Doctors
there fashioned a genuine tourniquet, but could do no more to help,
and sent him in an ambulance to Mercy Medical Center in Mason City,
another 45 miles down the highway.
</P>
<P>
   After being examined at Mercy, Hoffmeister was quickly
transported by helicopter to St. Mary's Hospital in Rochester,
Minn., part of the Mayo medical complex.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two weeks in St. Mary's, Hoffmeister went through
three operations, which included taking flesh and blood vessels
from other parts of his body to save the arm. In the end,
Hoffmeister's arm was saved, although it was virtually useless.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me I was going to get angry at God for letting
this happen to me,'' said Hoffmeister, a fifth-generation farmer.
``I never did. I just got mad at myself for being so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, about 1,300 farmers a year are injured badly enough to
require a doctor's attention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, special wheelchair lifts have been installed to
raise a farmer to the cab of a tractor or combine. Foot controls
are made workable by hands with special poles. Ladders with guard
rails are installed on grain bins. There are special hand tools for
people who are missing fingers or a hand, and even elastic
shoelaces, like the kind Hoffmeister uses, which tighten as they
are pulled and do not need to be tied in a knot.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs can be considerable. A wheelchair lift, for
example, costs $4,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   In Hoffmeister's case, difficulties on the farm after the
accident were worsened by a steep drop in hog prices. And he could
not qualify for disability payments as long as he held a
controlling interest in the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a purely financial standpoint,'' he said, ``we would have
been better off to sell the farm four or five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Now facing financial pressures, quite apart from his physical
disability, Hoffmeister has been forced to consider taking a second
job, off the farm. For a man who has never done anything but farm,
except for two years as a student at Ellsworth College 30 years
ago, it is a bitter pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down to take the aptitude test, and there are plenty of
things I'm able to do,'' Hoffmeister said, his voice breaking with
emotion. ``But in a rural area like this, you can't get more than
$6 or $7 an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone r who has watched the agriculture business steadily
move into the hands of big corporations, Hoffmeister has written
editorials for farm journals expressing frustration over the plight
of the farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our small towns, churches and schools are quickly
disappearing,'' he wrote in a recent issue of Iowa Farmer Today.
``Have we stood by too long? Am I beating a dead horse? Does anyone
really care?''
</P>
<P>
   Darin Hoffmeister, 22, who had intended to join his father on
the farm, has decided instead to become a high school math teacher.
The young man said he knew he could never make a decent living on a
modest farm.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmeister wonders how much the terrible accident, and the
anguish of seeing his father battered by the combine, had to do
with turning his son away from farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, Darin had a hard time going near the
combine,'' Hoffmeister said. ``He said it smelled like blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury has left Hoffmeister a changed man in many everyday
ways. He can wheel a car around the farm, but whenever he goes to a
city, his wife, Rhonda, 47, must drive.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the passenger side, Hoffmeister said, is ``not a very
macho thing'' for a farmer who always felt in control.
</P>
<P>
   When he goes out in public, Hoffmeister says he feels
self-conscious about people staring at his withered arm, which
hangs rigidly from the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He has severe bouts of phantom pain, feeling his deadened arm
being crushed and burned, a sensation so overpowering that he paces
in circles around the kitchen table until it passes.
</P>
<P>
   A confident and easygoing man at one time, Hoffmeister said he
now has terrible cases of nerves. He quit teaching Sunday school at
the old country church outside Ackley, he said, because standing in
front of a group of people, even children, made him too
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   But he still gets up early every morning and goes out to the
barns and fields. He pulls four white tube socks over his left hand
to guard against frostbite and scratches, since his arm and hand
cannot feel anything, even when he has scraped against barbed wire
and blood is trickling down.
</P>
<P>
   He tries to remain stoic, reminds himself that plenty of people
have it worse, and keeps the faith that maybe, someday soon, corn
and bean prices will finally rise to profitable levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You accept what you are given in life,'' he said, ``and hope
that it somehow makes you stronger in the end.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-ART-N     03-27 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: OPEC OIL PRICE REDUX 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also OPEC, moving in `i' category.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the oil ministers met in Vienna, Austria, there was great
concern about whether the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries would give the rest of the world a break and do something
to restrain high oil prices. Reporters were hanging on every word
from the ministers, some of whom had felt intense American
diplomatic pressure. Iran took a militant position, while Saudi
Arabia was more accommodative, and the meeting was extended as
agreement proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
   So it was nearly 20 years ago, when OPEC met in the fall of
1980. And so it was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But there are important differences between then and now. Then,
inflation was widely feared in the developed world, and it was
believed that oil prices were sure to continue rising for years to
come. Then, widespread efforts at energy conservation were having
an effect, and oil companies were intensifying their search for new
oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Now all those factors have changed. Complacency has replaced
urgency on Main Street, on Capitol Hill and in the executive suites
of major oil companies. All expect prices to fall, and therefore
see little need for action.
</P>
<P>
   In part those changes reflect the way the world economy has
changed in the intervening years. Oil is less important to economic
growth in the Information Age than it once was, and inflation has
declined dramatically. We have seen that cartels are very hard to
hold together, and that widespread cheating on oil production
quotas has often made it very hard for oil exporters to keep prices
up.
</P>
<P>
   But while many things have changed, the fact is that relatively
high oil prices have persisted many months longer than the experts
forecast, and they could continue to do so _ particularly if there
continues to be little indication of a determination to act to
fight high prices.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, four things helped to end the era of high oil
prices. Recessions and sluggish growth in the developed world
helped to reduce demand. So did energy conservation efforts,
including government-mandated fuel economy standards. The world's
energy companies spent heavily to find new oil supplies and to seek
alternative sources of energy. And oil producers cheated on their
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, only one is still around. There is reported to be
cheating on the OPEC quotas, of around 1 million to 1.5 million
barrels a day. So far efforts to agree on a quota increase have
failed, although some agreement is expected Tuesday. Whether or not
cheating will increase in coming months, assuming there is a deal,
will be a subject of widespread speculation.
</P>
<P>
   But the other factors are all gone. In 1980, oil companies were
earning profits that one politician called obscene and their share
prices reflected wild enthusiasm. Drilling for oil was going on at
a formidable rate, with 3,099 oil rigs operating in this country,
according to figures from Baker Hughes. Now oil profits are also
good, but share prices have shown little strength, in large part
because it is generally believed that the profits will fade as oil
prices inevitably fall.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the lesson that the oil companies have learned from
recent history is that they would be foolish to ramp up their
exploration efforts. They did that in 1997, when oil prices were
above $20 a barrel, only to suffer when prices plunged. Exploration
budgets are being held down across most of the industry. Budgets
are up a bit from 1999, but ``we're well below the 1998 level of
spending,'' said Frederick P. Leuffer, an oil analyst at Bear,
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. rig count, at 768, is less than it was in the summer of
1998, when oil prices were half what they are today. But the
companies are announcing large repurchases of their own shares, and
some are expected to raise shareholder dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the atmospheric difference greater than in
Washington. In 1980, there was debate about raising gasoline taxes
and taking other steps to limit demand for gasoline. In fact, by
then the rising price of gasoline had prompted Americans to search
for vehicles with better fuel economy. Now, Sen. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., the majority leader, is suggesting that federal gasoline
taxes be temporarily removed, the better to ease the pain for
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   That pain is real, but so far it has not done much to affect
consumer behavior. In a booming economy, most motorists are willing
to spend more rather than move to more fuel-efficient vehicles.
Sport utility vehicles, which are far from fuel efficient, now make
up 17 percent of total sales of cars and light trucks, up from
under 2 percent in 1980. The average fuel economy of cars and light
trucks sold in the 1981 model year was 24.1 miles a gallon. In the
1999 model year, the latest for which figures are available, it was
23.8.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices now are about 25 cents a gallon higher than they
were in September 1980. But those figures are not adjusted for
inflation, and in real terms the price of gasoline is far lower.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, when oil climbed above $24 a barrel, there was
virtual unanimity that the price could not hold. The futures market
forecast that oil prices would fall 13 percent within six months.
Instead, they rose, peaking above $34 earlier this month before
coming down to $27.79 Monday, on expectations that the OPEC meeting
would raise production. But one thing has not changed much. Prices
are now expected to fall 11 percent over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices went up for a variety of reasons. Weather was part of
the story, as was economic strength. So too was a widespread belief
that prices would come down due to OPEC cheating. That left the
entire industry, from international companies down to neighborhood
fuel oil dealers, hesitant to maintain high inventories that were
likely to decline in value. When things did not go as expected,
those low inventories accelerated the price rise.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, it is in the interests of Saudi Arabia in
particular to avoid letting oil get so expensive that it stimulates
the search for alternative fuels and leads consuming countries to
slash their demand. But for now, there is no sign that either is
about to happen. As a result, oil prices could stay relatively high
far longer than most experts anticipate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
