</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE POPE GONE, ISRAEL RETURNS TO POLITICS-AS-USUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change `karma' to `aura' in lead; to delete last two
words, in peacemaking, from 5th graf; to delete all of 23rd graf,
`Barak issued ... mutual respect.')  
(HLW) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ And so Pope John Paul II flew away and took his
positive aura with him. This is how the morning after looked in
Israel: diminished prospects for peace with Syria, the opening of a
politically explosive criminal investigation into a leading rabbi,
and five separate parliament votes of no confidence in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit did produce a salutary ripple, though, buoying
the Israeli government's image internationally, the Israeli
public's state of mind and Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political
stature, at least temporarily. This afforded something of a cushion
when they fell back to earth from their pope-inspired contemplation
of the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow came on Sunday night, hours after the pope
boarded an El Al plane to return to the Vatican. Despite high
expectations, President Clinton failed to revive the Israeli-Syrian
peace talks in a Geneva summit meeting with Hafez Assad, the
president of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction here on Monday ranged from dire pessimism, which
included anxieties about another flare-up in the war zone in
southern Lebanon, to a kind of forced hopefulness that this was
just another disappointment that could be overcome. The
middle-of-the-road position was the glum assessment by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's security adviser, Danny Yatom, that it was
hard to imagine junior-level diplomats bridging gaps after the two
presidents failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel and Syria traded blame for who was at fault,
Israelis, including the left, believe that Barak had made it clear
that he wanted to make a deal and was willing to make significant
concessions. Some here said that in contrast to the past, Israeli
intransigence could not be blamed this time for derailing a peace
effort. Israelis, from right to left, increasingly believe that
Assad is so reluctant as to be an untrustworthy partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make a peace agreement, each side has to climb inside
the skin of the other side and try to understand him,'' said Matan
Vilnai, a Cabinet minister and a dovish former general. ``President
Assad still does not do this. In the end, because our interest
remains strong, we will get to this,'' to peace. ``But maybe it
won't be with President Assad.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barak has pledged to withdraw Israeli troops from
southern Lebanon by July, and he hoped to do so as part of a peace
agreement with Syria. So the highest-ranking military official on
Monday urged the government not to abandon efforts to find a way
back to the negotiating table. The fear is that Syria, the power
broker in Lebanon, will sabotage an Israeli withdrawal by fostering
violent attacks in southern Lebanon or into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to seal the issue and say it's over,'' said Lt.
Gen. Shaul Mofaz, the army chief-of-staff, uncharacteristically
venturing an assessment about a diplomatic issue. ``It's possible
it will still change. Everyone in Israel and especially in the army
would prefer leaving Lebanon within the context of an agreement.
And from Israel's point of view, the door is still open'' to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Although the possibility of violent confrontation is unpleasant,
Barak might draw temporary political advantage from the failed
summit meeting. It is now difficult for him to be portrayed by the
opposition as willing to sell out Israel for a deal; while
flexible, he clearly was making some demands that Syria was
unwilling to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, the interior minister, who has said his Russian
immigrant party will leave the government if Barak returns the
Golan Heights to Syria, on Monday complimented the prime minister
for not ``giving in'' to Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Barak now has some breathing room, diplomatically and
politically, to focus on the Palestinian peace track, and to tackle
intense political disharmony within his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, his most balky coalition partner,
loses a lot of its potential power if a deal with Syria and a
national referendum on a deal is not imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs Shas as his ally going into a national vote on his
peace efforts. Shas' value, relative to the trouble it causes,
momentarily decreases if such a vote is not on the immediate
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why political chaos did not immediately
follow Monday morning's decision by the attorney general to open a
criminal investigation into Shas' spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef. The Torah sages who guide Shas' 17-member delegation in
Parliament, Israel's third largest, decided Monday night not to
bolt the government _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of Shas supporters gathered outside Yosef's home
in Jerusalem. The rabbi addressed them from behind bars covering a
window, leading them in singing, ``Please oh Lord redeem us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yosef, who is seen as a political kingmaker in Israel, is being
investigated because of a recent sermon in which he issued a
blistering attack _ including a curse _ on the leftist education
minister, Yossi Sarid. In the sermon, which was broadcast to his
followers, he described Sarid as Satan, said his name and memory
should be obliterated, and said that just as God ``extirpated
Amalek,'' the biblical tribe that attacked the Israelites after
their exodus from Egypt, ``so may he extirpate'' Sarid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance will be visited upon him,'' the rabbi said, ``just
like vengeance was visited upon Haman,'' the ancient Persian enemy
of the Jews whose death by hanging is celebrated in the festival of
Purim.
</P>
<P>
   Yosef will be investigated on charges of ``praising or
encouraging violence that could lead to death or injury,''
insulting a public employee and slander.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his decision to open the investigation, the
attorney general, Elyakim Rubenstein, noted that he had declined to
do that last year after the rabbi insulted Supreme Court judges.
Among other things, Yosef had said that the judges ``fornicated
with impure'' or menstruating, women, which is proscribed in a
strict interpretation of Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sensitive issue,'' the attorney general said,
``primarily because we exhibit self-restraint in using a criminal
tool in a case of expression because of the special status of the
freedom of speech. Naturally, the status of Ovadia as a leading
Torah scholar and as the spiritual leader and political
decision-maker of a large political party, also did not make the
decision any easier, to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rubenstein said the rabbi's statements could be heard by his
followers as an incitement to violence against Sarid, whether he
intended them that way or not. ``What is the meaning of the
vengeance that is to be visited upon Sarid, heaven forbid?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Given the political sensitivity, the police asked Rubenstein to
delay announcing his decision until after the pope left. They have
increased security around the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the right decision,'' said Sarid, who has been feuding
with Shas over the reorganization of their large, indebted
religious school system.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Yishai, Shas' leader, decried the investigation as
``racist'' and ``anti-religious,'' since it singled out the leader
of a movement representing ultra-Orthodox Sephardic Jews of Middle
Eastern origin. He noted that the rabbi had clarified his sermon,
and specifically instructed his followers not to resort to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the parliament, there is a tendency to use extreme measures,
like votes of no confidence in the government, to make political
points. Among Monday's five motions, the most serious one attacked
Barak's presumed intent to give away neighborhoods abutting
Jerusalem to the Palestinians and his policy on Jerusalem in
general. All five motions failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
