<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH28-COX     03-27 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education tops candidates' agendas
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush will be in Virginia today to talk
about education. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Bush was at Little Rock's historic Central High
School, where he called education ``the next frontier of civil
rights.'' Al Gore, meanwhile, was at a Michigan middle school,
where he participated in drama exercises, wolfed down pizza in the
school cafeteria and proclaimed that there is ``no higher
priority'' than education.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in recent memory, education is at the top of
the agenda in a presidential campaign. Both Bush and Gore seem to
care passionately about the issue, and each has offered a detailed
plan for improving the nation's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates' interest also is rooted in political
reality: Polls consistently show that education ranks near the top
of voters' concerns. It particularly resonates with married women,
the so-called ``soccer moms'' who were critical to Clinton's
victories. If Bush can win over the soccer moms, he might be able
to close the ``gender gap'' that the Democrats have enjoyed in
recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   But he is banking on an issue that is inherently problematic for
a Republican running for president. The federal government has a
limited role in education, and the GOP in particular has resisted
efforts to centralize a system that is based largely on state and
local control. As recently as 1995, Republicans in Congress were
calling for the elimination of the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who have been less squeamish about federal
involvement and more apt to spend federal money on education
programs, have long viewed the issue as a political strength. Polls
have consistently shown that people trust Democrats more than
Republicans on education.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Bush was evident last Friday at Central High
School. Bush repeated his calls for higher standards and greater
accountability, but the Central High principal was looking for
something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government can be more than a cheerleader,'' said
Rudolph Howard. ``I want something very tangible in place that
would be encouraging for those of us who have to carry the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   At various points along the campaign trail, Bush himself has
highlighted the limits of presidential influence on education. At a
South Carolina town meeting, he advised a high school student to
``write your governor'' when she asked what could be done about the
state's low scores on college entrance exams. More than once, Bush
has said that he's ``not running for national superintendent of
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Bill Clinton was able to neutralize welfare and
crime as Republican strengths, Bush clearly believes he can seize
education for the GOP. He may be making some headway: A recent Pew
Research Center survey found that on education, voters had slightly
more confidence in Bush than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Education also is a big part of Bush's efforts to portray
himself as a ``compassionate conservative'' who is closer to the
center than some of the firebrand Republicans in Congress. At
Central High, where in 1957 President Dwight Eisenhower deployed
federal troops to integrate the school, Bush tied education
improvements to the civil rights struggles of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access is universal, but excellence is not. All can enter our
schools, but not all are learning,'' Bush said. ``There is a
tremendous gap of achievement between rich and poor, white and
minority. This, too, leaves a divided society. And whatever the
cause, the effect is discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   In emphasizing education, Bush is playing to a strength: He has
a solid record to run on. During his five years as governor, the
state's schoolchildren _ and especially minority students _ have
made significant gains on national tests.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bush must share the credit for Texas' successes.
Some of the state's most critical education reforms, such as
smaller class sizes and a revamped school finance system, predated
Bush. He didn't initiate standardized testing or the state's
vaunted accountability system, either, though he has supported and
toughened both.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did push for legislation that stiffened academic standards;
helped pass a $32 million reading initiative; and followed through
on his promise to end social promotion, the practice of passing
failing students to keep them with their peers. Armed with his
Texas record, Bush is better prepared for an education fight with
the Democrats than other recent GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plan, schools that get money from the federal Title
I program, which targets schools with high numbers of low-income
students, would have to annually test those students on basic
academic skills. If the low scores persisted after three years, the
Title I money _ about $1,500 per student _ would be given to
parents for tutoring or transfer to other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also would combine dozens of federal aid programs into
block grants and give states more flexibility on how to use the
money. He would push for national standards at certain grade
levels, allowing states to devise their own tests to determine
whether they are met. Bush also promises to make reading readiness
a bigger part of Head Start, and offer federal loan guarantees for
the building of charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   In total, his education plan would cost about $1.1 billion over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Gore's education plan would cost roughly $115
billion over 10 years. He promises to attract better teachers by
raising salaries and offering scholarships and grants. New teachers
would have to prove their qualifications to teach their subjects,
and the renewal of their licenses would be subject to periodic peer
review.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce class sizes and refurbish rundown schools, Gore would
cover the interest on $25 billion in bonds issued by local
communities for school construction. He also promises to make Head
Start universally available.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Wilkins of the Education Trust, an education reform group in
Washington, said Bush and Gore each are about half right.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``really does talk a very good game about accountability.
We're glad he's talking about ratcheting it up and bringing it to
the federal level,'' she said. Wilkins used to work for the
Democratic National Committee, so the Bush campaign hasn't been
bashful about publicizing her praise of his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (Bush) is not talking about putting the resources in,''
she continued. ``They've both got half the loaf: Bush (proposing)
more money would get him into trouble with his right wing. Gore
saying more accountability would get him in trouble with his left
wing. And kids are getting lost in the sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman staff writer Jena Heath contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
