u p BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;      03-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DEFENDS HIS ROLE IN FUND-RAISING EXCESSES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GORE-REACT) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE, Wis. _ Even as he outlined a plan to revamp the
campaign finance system, Vice President Al Gore on Monday
strenuously defended his role in the fund-raising excesses of the
1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He asserted that he and other Democrats had to ``push the system
to the breaking point'' to defend core Democratic programs and
values against a Republican assault.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the offensive on an issue that many Republicans consider
his greatest weakness, Gore used a 40-minute speech at Marquette
University to introduce his proposed endowment fund to finance
congressional campaigns, to appeal to independent voters and to
slash at what he called the phony reforms of his Republican rival,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Gore tried to shore up his credentials as a
reformer. Besides explaining his actions in 1996, he invoked the
efforts of his father to overhaul campaign finance when he was a
senator from Tennessee in the 1950s and noted the campaign finance
legislation he himself had sponsored in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore argued that in 1996 he was faced with a choice of
``unilaterally'' disarming by not aggressively raising money _
thereby ceding the election to Republicans _ or playing the
fund-raising game with equal ferocity in order to protect
Democratic policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions of people out there who depend on those who
care about the public interests to fight for them, and not to
abandon the field of battle,'' Gore said. ``Millions who would be
the ones hurt most if advocates for the public interest
unilaterally disarmed and left the field of battle to those who
oppose both the public interest and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the choice I felt I faced in 1996,'' he continued.
``It was a battle to defend Medicare from deep cuts, to preserve
our national commitment to education, to prevent our environmental
laws from being rewritten by the big polluters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush expressed skepticism on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any promise to reform our campaign finance system will ring
hollow unless it is grounded in credibility, credibility based on
consistency, integrity and disclosure,'' Bush said in a statement.
``We need an attorney general, a president and a vice president who
will live by and enforce the laws we currently have on the books.
Unless the vice president stops withholding information about his
own fund-raising excesses, the American people will question his
commitment to reforming the fund-raising practices of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, whose calls for campaign finance
reform fueled his run against Bush, said on Monday that both
candidates have flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Gore, McCain said, ``He does have a credibility
problem that's very large, but so does Governor Bush.'' Bush ``has
not proposed a credible plan, of course not, everyone knows that,''
McCain added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not directly refer to the actions that have sparked so
much criticism against him: his appearance at a 1996 fund-raiser at
a Buddhist temple in Los Angeles and his phone calls from the White
House soliciting campaign contributions. The Justice Department
reviewed those incidents, and Attorney General Janet Reno had
determined that there was not enough evidence to appoint an
independent counsel to investigate further.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Maria Hsia, a friend of Gore, was convicted of
violating federal laws relating to her role in organizing the
Buddhist temple event.
</P>
<P>
   Those actions have also come under scrutiny by congressional
Republicans and have drawn criticism from advocates for campaign
finance reform, including some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Though the vice president defended his 1996 actions largely on
partisan grounds, he repeatedly appealed on Monday to independent
voters who, polls have shown, favor campaign finance reform and who
fueled the insurgent campaigns of Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota;
former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival in the Democratic primaries,
and, particularly McCain. Gore warmly praised each of those men at
least once on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He called Bradley a friend, a word Bradley had refrained from
using in describing Gore, and in one breath praised both Bradley
and McCain for helping ``to put this issue at the forefront of this
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said his first act as president would be to
send to Congress legislation co-sponsored by McCain to ban
so-called soft money, the unlimited contributions to political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat who has co-sponsored
the soft money bill with McCain, went further in trying to wrap the
vice president in McCain's reform mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, John McCain's success was a public referendum on
political reform,'' Feingold said on Monday in introducing Gore.
``John has made it clear to me that he is returning to the Senate
and renewing the fight for true campaign finance reform. But he
does so with the strong support of only one of the two remaining
presidential candidates, Vice President Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeatedly attacked Bush's campaign finance proposals, and
ridiculed the governor's claim to be a ``reformer with results.''
``Governor Bush talks a lot about being an outsider,'' Gore said.
``But being an outsider is about more than where you live; it's
about who you're fighting for. Believe it or not, Governor Bush
wants to open the floodgates even wider to special interest donors
and big money. That's not just defending the status quo, it's
setting it in stone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
