<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-OWNERS28-COX     03-27 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis still Ravens' pick
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Baltimore Ravens coach Brian Billick said
Monday that the uncertainty over All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis won't
affect the team's strategy in next month's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who led the league in tackles last season, is scheduled
to stand trial in May for the Jan. 31 murders of two men outside an
Atlanta nightclub. He is free on $1 million bail and participating
in the team's voluntary conditioning program in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens have two first-round picks in the April 15-16 draft,
including the fifth choice, which they acquired from the Falcons in
a trade last year. Billick said the team probably will address
concerns at running back and receiver with the two, Nos. 5 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take a linebacker at any position, and if anybody
construes that as us not having faith in Ray Lewis being with us
this fall, it would be a mistake,'' Billick said at the NFL owners
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to move along and take the best player
available,'' he said. ``We'll let this process play itself out with
Ray, and we'll have faith that he'll be with us this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick, the former Minnesota Vikings offensive coordinator, is
one of three head coaches scheduled to participate in a Wednesday
discussion about off-field violence. Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy and
Seattle's Mike Holmgren also will participate in the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a stage where we need to be careful,'' Dungy said.
``We don't need to turn people off. Not everybody gets to do what
we do. I think it's a privilege to work and play in the NFL. We
can't jeopardize our integrity and popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens could draft a middle linebacker after the first
round. Brigham Young's Rob Morris could be the only player drafted
at the position during the first round, but Arizona's Marcus Bell
and Penn State's Brandon Short could be chosen in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Billick said the Ravens are close to finishing a new contract
for receiver Qadry Ismail, an unrestricted free agent who rejected
the team's last offer of a four-year, $8 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   If Ismail re-signs, the Ravens might be inclined to draft a
running back with the fifth pick, possibly Virginia's Thomas Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running back and wide receiver positions have a lot of
potential (in the draft),'' Billick said. ``That's the good thing
about where we're at. If we say we're going to take a receiver at
fifth, then there will probably be a good running back available at
No. 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
