<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE AT THE PUMP
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of a new series of TV ads made by Epinion.com _ which allows
consumers to check out the opinions of other consumers on 100,000
products _ featured a woman using a breast pump. She is wearing a
blouse; unlike the parade of actresses whose assets were displayed
during the Oscar ceremonies on Sunday, March 26, nothing of her
breast shows.
</P>
<P>
   KGO-TV in San Francisco, the same station that broadcast the
Oscars, was one of several stations around the country that have
refused to run it. Epinion co-founder  &UR; Mike Speiser  &LR; told Personals
that the station told him that the image was ``offensive'' and
``disrespectful.'' KGO didn't return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The La Leche League, which promotes and advocates
breast-feeding, jumped into the fray. ``Our society needs to change
how it looks at nursing women. The breast was made to feed a
nursing baby, not to sell beer or other products, as is often the
case with advertising,'' said  &UR; Kim Cavaliero &LR;  of the league.
</P>
<P>
   The company must have known the ads would be controversial,
however, when that particular product _ one among 100,000 _ was
chosen to be featured.
</P>
<P>
   An unofficial Personals review of images featured in TV ads
reveals that fluids can go in (got milk?) but can't go out, with
the exception of tears and sweat in ads for athletic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AFTER YOU'VE GONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At last, the opportunity to rest in peace and still nag your
friends.
</P>
<P>
   FinalThoughts.com is a Web site devoted to making ``planning for
the inevitable less scary,'' founder &UR; Todd Krim  &LR; told Wired
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   You register, obviously, before you kick the bucket. You prepare
a bunch of messages to send to your friends and family members
(``Don't forget to walk the dog''; ``Stay away from fried foods'';
``I want you to know I always despised you'').
</P>
<P>
   Then, after you die, when a designated ``Guardian Angel''
informs the site that you're gone, the messages are dispatched
electronically. Krim told Wired that he's hoping to make the site
``a full-service death portal,'' offering caskets, links to
genealogy sites and all manner of related material.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; RAISING THE DEAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Giddins &LR; , who is writing a biography of  &UR; Bing Crosby  &LR; for
Little, Brown, told Talk magazine that his opinion of his subject
changed as his research deepened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I set out, I believed that Bing Crosby was probably a son
of a bitch. What I discovered was that he was a man of enormous
decency. Everybody I interviewed adored him....
</P>
<P>
   ``He was much more like the figure that everybody in the country
assumed he was when he was alive than he's been made out to be
since his death.''  &UR; Gary Crosby &LR; , son of Bing, who had written a
memoir describing his father as ruthless and uncaring, admitted to
Giddins that much of his book had been exaggerated, and that he _
who was alcoholic when the book was written _ couldn't remember
much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bing had an Augustinian change in midlife. He became
enormously morally sober in his later years. His butler told me he
used to see Mr. Crosby on his knees praying before he went to bed.
He had a second chance, and he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Lee Glickstein &LR; 's Magnetism, a Journal for Transformational
Speakers, suggests that  &UR; Al Gore  &LR; would be a better speaker if he
stopped trying to cover his bald spot, an action he said is a
barrier to Gore's ``authenticity. When you reveal, you become real.
Al, celebrate your balding head and you can rest at the White
House.'' And  &UR; Linda Pitney &LR; , a Toronto handwriting expert, told
Wireless Flash that  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 's signature suggests that he
is pessimistic and that he needs a relaxing massage.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Rich Morrison &LR;  heard a TV commentator at the NCAA basketball
tournament describe one of the players: ``The reason he's so strong
is because of his strength.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I went out and started working with designers when they &LR; 
 &UR; didn't want to work with me; I went to fashion shows before that &LR; 
 &UR; was trendy. In fact, the first fashion show I went to, I wasn't &LR; 
 &UR; invited by the designer, I wasn't outfitted by them _ I bought &LR; 
 &UR; my own dress. Now it's changed.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Actress &UR; Salma Hayek &LR;  telling Elle about the hard times at the
beginning of her career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
