<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      03-27 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN TELLS ADVISERS TO PREPARE `WEIGHTY' ECONOMIC PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-BUSINESS) 
(ms) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On the day after his decisive victory in a field of 11
candidates in Sunday's presidential election, Vladimir Putin told
his cabinet Monday that it was time to put ``all our work'' on a
new economic program into one ``weighty document'' by the time he
is sworn in and appoints his new government in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's reference to an economic blueprint that he steadfastly
refused to discuss during the campaign was a pointed reminder that
planning was well under way for his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Putin met with former President Boris Yeltsin and
received warm praise from the patron who plucked Putin from
political obscurity last fall as the head of the country's
intelligence agency, appointed him prime minister, and then
announced that the 47-year-old ex-KGB officer would make a good
successor. Yeltsin resigned on Dec. 31, appointing Putin acting
president.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 95 percent of the vote counted, Putin had polled
nearly 53 percent of the ballots. The Communist Party candidate,
Gennadi Zyuganov, was a strong second in the crowded field with
almost 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A number of world leaders, including President Clinton,
President Jiang Zemin of China and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, spoke with Putin by telephone Monday, extending
congratulations and expressing their hopes for Russia's future.
Clinton urged the new Russian leader to strengthen democracy and
its international ties, while Jiang urged him to deepen the
``strategic partnership'' between Russia and China. The New China
News Agency said Putin had agreed to visit China this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also expressed the hope that Putin would carry out
``impartial and transparent investigations of reported human rights
violations'' during the military campaign Russia has waged in the
breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin met with his security advisers for an update on the war in
Chechnya. He also sent greetings to the Interior Ministry troops
who, along with the Russian army, have been fighting in Chechnya:
``Your bravery and dignity are a safe guarantee that this region
will be freed of the bandits and that peaceful life will be
restored there.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong showing by the Communist candidate, Zyuganov, drew
considerable notice here. A number of commentators saw it as
evidence of the enduring strength of the Communist opposition,
which has consistently garnered close to a third of the national
vote, and suggested that Putin might seek a collaborative
relationship with it.
</P>
<P>
   Putin will need to avoid political conflicts that would hamper
efforts to move forward with difficult reforms of the banking
system, taxation and land ownership. The Communists, for their
part, are interested in sharing power and attracting new partners
after losing the coalition through which they dominated Parliament
in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Leonid Dobrokhotov, an adviser to Zyuganov, said Monday night
that the Communist Party would consider working with Putin's allies
in parliament if the president accepted the party's demands on
``raising the living standards'' and strengthening industry,
agriculture, and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popularity of the Communist Party is the result of the
suffering of the people,'' Dobrokhotov said. ``We don't want to
fight with the party in power. We want to solve the social problems
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Boris Makarenko, deputy director of the Center for Political
Technology, a consulting firm, said Monday the new government would
be more centrist, with the Communists as a ``junior partner,''
adding, ``This is a new role for the Communists.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the poor showing of Grigory Yavlinsky, the
Yabloko Party leader, who polled less than 6 percent of the vote,
reflected the disarray of Russia's liberal politicians. It
suggested that Yavlinsky's personal base of support was shrinking,
and reflected the fact that many liberal voters fell in behind
either Putin or one of several liberals who ran as independents,
including Konstantin Titov, the progressive governor of the Samara
region, or Ella Pamfilova, the Women's Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest new liberal forces is the Union of Right
Forces, which made a surprisingly strong showing in parliamentary
elections in December. But its leaders, who include prominent
reformers from Yeltsin's governments, decided not to field a
presidential candidate, and then quarreled publicly over whether to
endorse Putin, as most eventually did.
</P>
<P>
   In general, most Russian political organizations other than the
Communist Party have usually been groupings around specific
leaders, and not national parties. Putin has not identified himself
with any of those, though last fall the Kremlin helped form the
Unity Party, an amalgam of mayors, governors and other regional
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the only party with longevity, ideology and a national
following remains the Communist Party. Michael McFaul, senior
associate of the Moscow Carnegie Center, called this circumstance
``sad progress for democracy and its legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   By any normal standard, Putin's victory with nearly 53 percent
of the vote, compared with just under 30 percent for Zyuganov,
would be considered a landslide. But the fact that Putin's
popularity, which had hovered around 60 percent this winter, sagged
in the final weeks of the campaign while the Communists rallied
left a haze of uncertainty over the Kremlin, where Putin and his
advisers were trying to figure out what kind of mandate they had
received.
</P>
<P>
   But it also appeared that Putin's victory was broad-based. Where
Yeltsin in 1996 managed to carry only 57 of Russia's 89
administrative regions, Putin won majorities in all but six,
including Zyuganov's home district.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is victory,'' said Aleksandr Voloshin, the
presidential chief-of-staff, putting the best face on the results
in an interview with the newspaper Izvestia to be published on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
