u a BC-NY-FOSTER-CARE-ART-NY     03-27 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOSTER-CARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS LEAVE FOSTER CARE WITHOUT COPING SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of young adults in New York City's
foster-care system, many of them neglected or abandoned during the
height of the city's crack epidemic a decade ago, have been pushed
out of the system in recent years, forced when they are as young as
18 to fend for themselves, often with little education or financial
resources.
</P>
<P>
   The city's child-welfare system, whose legal obligation to
foster children ends when they are not much beyond adolescence,
does not, by its own admission, give the departing youngsters much
to work with: a handful of classes in things like cooking and
resume writing, a check for $750 and up to three years of modest
stipends for rent.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while the growing exodus of children from foster care _
roughly 1,200 in 1998 _ has helped relieve the strain on a system
that had in the early 1990s been forced to deal with a
near-doubling of its population, it has created another kind of
crisis, according to child-welfare experts and the foster children
themselves, as a wave of poorly prepared teen-agers, many with
children of their own, venture out by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It is a crisis that, at minimum, reflects the fact that the
city's foster-care system too often fails to adequately address and
surmount the myriad problems afflicting children who have been
removed from harmful homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the research suggests that this is a group at high risk of
incarceration, homelessness, public-assistance dependency,
out-of-wedlock childbearing, and victimization _ being sexually and
physically victimized,'' said Mark E. Courtney, a professor of
social work at the University of Wisconsin at Madison, whose study
of children in Wisconsin last year is regarded as one of the most
comprehensive studies of children leaving foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, when Sherrell F. turns 18 on Aug. 5, her passage into
adulthood will be unlike that of most girls her age. By then, she
will have two children to care for _ Tamara, 2, and a baby due in
June _ and a 10th-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Sherrell's outlook is a mix of bravado and grim,
practical reckoning. She lives in a foster group home in the Bronx,
and is scouring the city for ``For Rent'' signs. She says she can
support her family on $685 a month in government disability
benefits, plus food stamps and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But if that does not work out, she said, she can always turn to
the city's homeless shelters. ``They have to take you,
regardless,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Homelessness is a common fate. At the Covenant House teen
shelter in Manhattan, 80 percent of the roughly 400 teenagers who
stay there nightly are former foster children. Many come directly
from the jails at Rikers Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the closest to the best thing _ it got me an
apartment,'' Shanetta C., 18, declared of her decision to enter the
city's homeless-shelter system. Applying for public housing
otherwise would mean a long wait. ``You go to a shelter, you get in
much quicker,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the share of adolescents in care has grown in
recent years: In 1998, youngsters between 12 and 21 made up a third
of the city's caseload, compared with less than 25 percent in 1990,
according to city figures.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to those leaving the system, the city's
foster-care caseload has shrunk, to 35,000 last fall from 49,000 in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The city's legal obligation to youths leaving the system because
of age is limited. At 18, foster children are on their own, unless
they are enrolled in school or a vocational program. In those
instances, the city continues to provide care until age 21.
</P>
<P>
   For those set to leave the system, whether at 18 or 21, the city
is required to provide 16 hours of classes a year on topics such as
career counseling, apartment hunting and budgeting. Under a plan
known as the independent living program, the young adults are also
entitled to a one-time $750 check and housing subsidies of a
maximum of $300 a month for up to three years.
</P>
<P>
   But foster-care agencies and the youngsters and their advocates
say many of them get neither the instruction nor the financial
support. Many do not know about the help. Others ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney's study of former foster children in Wisconsin found
that within 12 to 18 months after leaving care, a quarter of the
boys ended up incarcerated, and one in 10 girls reported being
raped. A third of the youths had not finished high school. Fewer
than a fifth reported receiving any job training or help in signing
up for medical benefits before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we presume to do better than their parents and do in fact
replace their parents for a considerable time, sometimes many
years,'' Courtney said, ``then we have to look critically at what
we as parents are responsible for.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are exceptions, typically those who have had a
stable foster parent in their lives. Quantwilla Johnson, 20, and in
college, is one of the fortunate ones: she has lived with her
foster mother in Brooklyn since she was 3. ``She's not a foster
parent, she's a parent,'' Johnson said. ``She's concerned about my
education. She wanted to make sure I did what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Johnson, a sophomore studying communications, is not
unlike her peers at State University of New York in New Paltz. She
lives in the dormitories and goes home for Christmas. Her foster
mother scolds her when her grades slip. She has a part-time job.
``I'm starting to learn all of the things my mother was telling
me,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
