<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      03-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME QUESTION CLINTON'S APPROACH ON ISRAEL-SYRIA PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton met Syrian President Hafez
Assad on Sunday at a lakefront hotel in Geneva, the Syrian leader
expected that Clinton would be relaying an Israeli plan to give
back the entire Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had no such deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have anything _ except the president's prestige, his
stature and the hope that at this time in his career he could have
a little more leverage,'' said a US official, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in many senses, a replay of the Israeli-Syrian peace
talks in January in Shepherdstown, W.Va., when analysts widely
assumed that the two sides wouldn't meet until they had nearly
wrapped up an agreement in secret talks beforehand. The assumptions
then and on Sunday proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Now some are questioning Clinton's strategy of hoping to achieve
breakthroughs in Middle East peace by sheer force of his will and
the power of his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have done more harm than good by going there without
something in hand,'' said Richard W. Murphy, a former US ambassador
to Syria and Saudi Arabia and now a senior fellow at the Council on
Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day before the event there was a lot of talk that this was
the last chance for the Clinton administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who has been strongly supportive of Clinton's tireless
efforts for Middle East peace, said the president may have ``given
it the good college try, but if this isn't the last chance, it's
getting damn near the last chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In a not-so-discrete public criticism of Clinton's strategy,
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa said in comments published
Monday that Clinton offered nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised that the US president was not carrying
anything new from the Israeli side, but was asking from Syria what
might help Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in his difficult
position, which we think is of his own making,'' Sharaa told
Lebanon's As-Safir newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet Tuesday with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
to discuss ways to rekindle Israel-Syria talks as well as moving
ahead with the Israel-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Mubarak, who early on Sunday expressed optimism that for an
Israeli-Syrian deal, didn't hide his disappointment Monday about
the lack of a breakthrough in Geneva. ``For the time being, there's
nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said in an interview
Monday that it wasn't time yet to lose hope on the Israel-Syria
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope what happened in Geneva was one of those stoppages,
setbacks, but it doesn't mean at all that the Syrian track should
be abandoned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Let's see what will come out in the next few days,
by way of continuing the American role on the Syrian track.''
</P>
<P>
   The US official predicted that the ``primary focus'' in Middle
East peacemaking will shift toward the Israeli-Palestinian track.
``Now, there's a chance for moving ahead. Besides, what else is
there?'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are expected to end eight
days of talks Wednesday at Bolling Air Force Base in Washington,
D.C., and return for new meetings in a few weeks, said State
Department spokesman James Foley.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are talking about the third and final Israeli
troop withdrawal from the West Bank, scheduled in June, as well as
setting up a framework by May on how to talk about the most
important and difficult issues separating them _ Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees, water rights, Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assessment of the talks is that they have been serious,
intensive and, indeed, productive,'' Foley said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lack of a breakthrough Sunday remain uppermost on the
minds of Middle East experts, who had been thinking not just about
peace between Israel and Syria, but also about Israel making deals
with Lebanon and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, rosy scenarios were replaced by grim ones, especially
if Israel withdraws its troops from southern Lebanon by July
without any Syrian deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the possibilities is that there could be a flare-up of
violence,'' said Lewis Roth, assistant executive director of
Americans for Peace Now, a pro-peace lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that with an absence of a peace agreement, we
wouldn't see a freeze, but a bit of a deterioriation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
