<HEADER>
A9610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MONTENEGRO-ART-(TRIMS     03-27 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADER OF MONTENEGRO ACCUSES MILOSEVIC OF PLANNING OVERTHROW 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ The leader of Montenegro on Monday
accused the president of Yugoslavia, Slobodan Milosevic, of using
the national army to try to force him from power.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegran president, Milo Djukanovic, said in an interview
that relations with Yugoslavia were deteriorating. He accused
Milosevic of recruiting a special army battalion that would be used
to overthrow Montenegro's government.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is the smaller of the two republics remaining in
Yugoslavia, which is dominated by the other republic, Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's government has been cautiously drawing away from
the Yugoslav government in Belgrade and is now feeling the pressure
as Milosevic moves to counter that drift.
</P>
<P>
   Under a tightened trade and economic blockade imposed by
Milosevic's government, Montenegro, a small mountainous territory
of only 650,000 people, is facing increased economic difficulties
and shortages, officials there say.
</P>
<P>
   It is also feeling the weight of the military. During the
weekend, under pressure from Belgrade, Djukanovic said, his
government agreed to allow the Yugoslav army to join Montenegro's
police at border posts with the separatist Serbian province of
Kosovo and with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the West, Djukanovic is quietly trying to draw his
republic out of the international isolation it suffers as part of
Yugoslavia while avoiding open confrontation. But it has no
security or economic guarantees from the West.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic broke with Belgrade two years ago and has opted for
democratic reforms and openness to the West. His refusal to
denounce the NATO bombing over Kosovo and his willingness to
provide refuge to Serbian opposition figures defined his break with
Milosevic permanently.
</P>
<P>
   At home he faces opposition from the pro-Milosevic Socialist
People's Party. The parties will test their strength in local
elections in two regions of Montenegro, including the capital, in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic described the agreement over border controls as a
``gesture of good will.'' But it was greeted with skepticism by
Montenegro's leading daily Vijesti, which said the agreement
underlines how little say Djukanovic has in how the military
conducts itself in his republic.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic said he opposes the creation of a special military
police unit within the 2nd Army, based in Podgorica, numbering
about 1,000 men, Montenegrans led by Serbs loyal to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in fact a paramilitary unit and their party
association is unanimous,'' he said. ``They are devoted to Mr.
Milosevic. Over 50 percent of them have criminal records. They are
not being retained to protect the country but to overthrow the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic said Milosevic is using the army in Montenegro to
reassert control over the republic, as he did during the NATO air
campaign last year when the Yugoslav army attempted to seal
Montenegro's borders and impose controls equivalent to martial law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We resisted that, and we managed,'' Djukanovic said. ``Now it
is happening a second time, but we are not in a state of war _ this
is peacetime. The situation is rather tense but we are not taking
any risks to lay ourselves open to Milosevic, because if we did we
would give him an alibi for a fifth war in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's political opponents dismiss his accusations. ``He
is attacking the army and provoking it,'' said Pedrag Bulatovic of
the Socialist People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   Jabbing his finger scathingly at a newspaper carrying
Djukanovic's photo, Bulatovic contended that Djukanovic had built
up his own police force to confront the army. ``This man has 20,000
police, 10,000 more than he should have,'' he said. ``The danger is
that this guy uses these people to create a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the agitation in Montenegro may be just talk, but
numerous little incidents are nudging the republic toward
confrontation. A disagreement between police and the military in
December over the Montenegran police's plan to build a helicopter
hangar at the Podgorica airport led the army to close the airport,
making the police abandon the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In November the Montenegran government made the German mark
legal tender, saying it wanted to protect its population against
inflation as the Yugoslav dinar plunged. Belgrade reacted by
stopping all transfers of money and stepping up enforcement of its
trade blockade of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The blockade is already hurting two of Montenegro's key
manufacturers, Djukanovic said, and is causing shortages of
medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Montenegro lived largely off its tourist industry
thanks to the beauty of its Adriatic coastline, but that income has
plummeted during 10 years of war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic said he will keep trying to forge a workable
relationship with Serbia, but that he may have to lead his country
to independence if Milosevic stays in power.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls indicate mixed feelings about independence. In one
recent poll, 45 percent of those polled favored independence, 37
percent were opposed, and the rest undecided.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the government has indefinitely postponed a
referendum on the issue and is ducking around the provocative
swipes from Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A recent report by the International Crisis Group, an
independent research institute, advocates stronger action from the
West to provide more financial support to Montenegro, more evident
political support, and a commitment from NATO that it will meet any
attempt to overthrow the government in Montenegro with a forceful
military response.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro has received some economic support from the United
States, but the republic's prime minister, Filip Vujanovic, said he
recognizes that security guarantees from NATO or the West have not
been forthcoming and that Montenegro would have to defend itself.
Hence the large police force, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
