<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE RULES CHOATE SHOULD HEAD REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clearing up one feud within the Reform Party but leaving it with
plenty of festering troubles, a federal judge ruled Monday that Pat
Choate, an ally of Ross Perot's and Pat Buchanan's, was the party's
legitimate chairman, not Jack Gargan, an ally of Gov. Jesse
Ventura's, who was ousted at a raucous party meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Norman K. Moon of District Court in Lynchburg, Va.,
found that Choate and his supporters had violated no party rules in
seizing control of the party from Gargan at the meeting, in
Nashville, Tenn., on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan testified at a two-day court hearing last week that the
Choate coup succeeded only because numerous rules governing the
scheduling and conduct of party meetings had been violated. He said
the actions of the Choate forces had threatened to weaken or even
destroy the party just as it was gearing up for this year's
presidential election, an election in which the Reform nominee will
receive $14 million in federal campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was Gargan who seized control of the party, in a
coup masterminded in part by Ventura of Minnesota. The governor was
then the party's highest-ranking elected official, but he has since
abandoned the party, labeling it ``dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Choate-Gargan feud, a number of lesser feuds between
party factions in various states have riven the party lately.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, for example, some Reform leaders are
threatening to take Buchanan supporters to court on grounds that
they are wrongfully using the party's name in their mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, the current favorite to win the Reform nomination, is
threatening to go to court should the Commission on Presidential
Debates exclude him from its events if he does not score at least
15 percent in public opinion polls _ more than double what he is
currently drawing.
</P>
<P>
   And in still another sign of trouble for the party, the Federal
Election Commission says party leaders must do a better job of
keeping the government informed of how they are managing the
party's money.
</P>
<P>
   Choate, Perot's running mate in the presidential race in 1996
and a close ally of Buchanan's, agreed with Gargan in last week's
court hearing that feuding was hurting the party. But he blamed
Gargan for the turmoil and insisted that no party rules or
procedures had been violated at the Nashville meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Moon concluded that while the Tennessee
gathering could ``euphemistically be described as `boisterous,'''
there nevertheless was no credible evidence that any party rules
had been violated by the Choate forces.
</P>
<P>
   He then ordered Gargan to ``immediately cease and desist from
any and all activities on behalf of the Reform Party'' and
instructed him to turn over all party papers and money to Choate.
</P>
<P>
   The case was tried in Virginia because some of the party's money
is in a Virginia bank.
</P>
<P>
   Choate hailed Moon's decision as one that would enable the party
to ``go forth and mount a competitive race.'' But Gargan expressed
deep dismay.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would abandon the party and concentrate his energies
on ``something more constructive,'' though he did not elaborate. He
also predicted that there would be a ``huge exodus'' by other party
members.
</P>
<P>
   Perot said he would have no immediate comment on Moon's
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
