<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AND CUBS PREPARE FOR BASEBALL BEFORE BREAKFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related BBO-BASEBALL-ABROAD) 
(ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ While the Mets and the Cubs try to shrug off jet lag,
the American population gets to share their pain Wednesday morning.
Anybody who wants to catch that grand old tradition of opening day
will have to get up bright and early.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Cubs will open the regular season in the Tokyo
Dome, but the game will be broadcast live in New York, where it is
14 hours earlier. To be specific, the first pitch will take place
at 5:05 a.m. Wednesday in New York and one hour earlier in Chicago,
not exactly normal viewing hours for most people.
</P>
<P>
   This is a time when sleepwalkers are ostensibly being
entertained by old Barbara Stanwyck movies, or perhaps, yet another
showing of the classic, ``The Day of the Triffids.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the national pastime doing in the wee small hours of the
morning? For the record, baseball is also the national pastime of
Japan _ probably even more so _ and they were the fans who counted
in this equation.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the commissioner of Major League Baseball, claimed he
had been surprised when he heard of the rather early starting time
for loyal fans back in the Eastern and Central time zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make the decision, but it was done for the Japanese
people,'' Selig said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Getting up very early (or, staying up very, very late) to see
Mike Piazza and Sammy Sosa open the season could put New Yorkers
and Chicagoans out of whack for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   But this odd hour will allow American fans to relate to the Mets
and Cubs, who have flown halfway around the world to play two
exhibitions against top Japanese teams and then two games that will
_ as the saying goes _ count in the standings come October.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got their feet on the ground Monday afternoon with an
8-1 victory over the Seibu Lions in an open-sided dome in the
distant suburb of Tokorozawa, two hours by bus from downtown.
Monday evening, the Cubs were shut down by the Yomiuri Giants, 6-0,
in the Tokyo Dome. The two American teams would switch opponents
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The players are insisting they do not feel uncomfortable playing
14 or 15 hours ahead of their internal clocks. They are athletes,
after all, and most at home when they don a uniform and work up a
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan may not be the problem. Teams from the National Hockey
League opened the season with two games in Tokyo, and some players
said they were still feeling it two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, they're wimps,'' Mike Piazza declared with a disarming
smile, but then he added: ``I really don't think it's going to be a
problem. We know it's not going to be easy, but we've all been
through it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the players have less disdain for this part of the
schedule than for the regular-season schedule, which seems to have
been designed by the Marquis de Sade.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of flying,'' muttered John Franco, in one of the more
printable responses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights in May are back-to-back night games in San
Francisco and Florida, and later the basic San Diego-St. Louis-Los
Angeles road trip.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Mets may wish they were back in Japan. After
Mark McGwire blasted the concept of international games, the
players have been virtually diplomatic, playing down the impact of
jet lag, which has been known to leave normal civilians blithering
and staggering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day was a little strange,'' said Bill Pulsipher, who
was scheduled to pitch Tuesday against the Giants. ``I slept a lot
on the plane so I stayed up late at the hotel. But last night, I
slept from 7:30 p.m. until 6 a.m. and had a regular breakfast, and
then I threw on the side and I felt fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, who will pitch the Wednesday opener, said: ``It's
baseball, whether we play in the U.S. or Japan. The field is the
same. We'll be playing a talented Cubs team. I'm looking forward to
the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The first exhibition began on a bizarre note. Rickey Henderson,
who has been grousing that he did not want to fly all this way to
play ball, stood in the batter's box for a mock ``first pitch,''
thrown by Kyotaka Nambara, a comedian who normally operates with a
sidekick, like the old Martin and Lewis routines. Nambara
low-bridged Henderson, and the two of them staged a wrestling match
near home plate, before hugging to show the fans that it was all in
good fun.
</P>
<P>
   The game was surprisingly low-key, with fans occupying no more
than a third of the 50,000 seats in the Seibu Dome. There was no
evidence of the cheering sections that accompany Japanese league
games. Apparently, Yoshiaki Tsutsumi, the team owner and one of the
scions of the huge Seibu empire of hotels, railroads and
departments stores, chose to have his employees work a full day at
their jobs rather than cheer during an exhibition. Tsutsumi has
done his bit to encourage the use of his railroad by cleverly
placing the Seibu Dome so far in the countryside that it takes
several hours to return to downtown Tokyo by car or bus. It is not
the jets that will wear down the Mets and Cubs, it is the trip to
the Seibu Dome. The fans in New York and Chicago will never have to
undergo this torture, but by joining the dawn patrol, they will be
able to commiserate with the logy ballplayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
