<SLUG> BC-FLAG-AMENDMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEBATES LEGISLATION TO PROTECT FLAG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate opened debate Monday for the third time
in 10 years on a constitutional amendment that would prohibit
desecrating the U.S. flag.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure aimed at protecting the nation's most treasured
symbol from burning or other acts of desecration was expected to
narrowly fall short in a scheduled vote Tuesday. Sixty-seven votes
are needed in the Senate to adopt it as an amendment to the
Constitution. The House passed a similar measure in June.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., would add
a one-sentence addition to the Constitution that would give
Congress ``power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators opposed to the measure said its
passage would represent a violation of the First Amendment right of
free speech and would require the creation of a ``flag police'' to
help determine what constitutes flag desecration.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the senators offered their
own ``flag protection'' bill that would impose jail sentences and
fines for flag burning designed ``to incite violence,'' but only if
the inciteful act involved the use of flags stolen from the
government or taken from somewhere else and burned on federal
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no sympathy for those who desecrate the flag,''
McConnell said, calling them ``malcontents.'' But he added that
``the best treatment for someone who desecrates the flag might be a
punch in the nose rather than a visitation on the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the amendment also got help from retired Gen. Colin
Powell, the former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman, who wrote a
letter to senators urging that they reject the effort to add a
flag-protection amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rightfully outraged when anyone attacks or desecrates
our flag,'' Powell wrote. But he described it as the destruction of
``a piece of cloth'' rather than the destruction of ``our system of
freedom which tolerates such desecration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not amend that great shield of democracy to hammer a
few miscreants,'' he added. ``The flag will still be flying proudly
long after they have slunk away.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the flag amendment marked the third time since
1990 that the Senate has taken up the issue. It failed to muster
the necessary two-thirds support in 1990 and again in 1995, when it
was narrowly defeated by three votes. The measure is expected to
fail again Tuesday by a margin of two or three votes.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome in the House, however, has been different. A similar
amendment was approved by more than a two-thirds vote in 1995, 1997
and 1999. But an amendment requires passage by both houses of
Congress before it can be sent on for ratification by the states.
At least 40 states would have to give it their stamp of approval
before it could become part of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Smith noted that every state with the exception
of Vermont has already signaled its intention to ratify the
amendment if Congress approves it. He suggested that lawmakers who
insist on ``splitting hairs'' over free speech issues are
contributing to what he called ``the moral decay in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our duty to protect the one treasured symbol of America.
That flag is the essence of America and we ought to pass a
constitutional amendment that it not be desecrated,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He called flag burning ``just one symbol of what's wrong with
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're falling apart at the seams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But where Smith saw a threat to the nation's ability to survive,
other Republicans saw ``a non-existent problem,'' as Utah Sen.
Robert Bennett put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is burning the flag today in any discernible numbers,''
Bennett said, adding that the Smith amendment would have been more
timely in the 1960s when flag burning was a ``more serious issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me ... this is 30 years behind the times,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents of a flag-burning amendment sought to kill it by
adding a provision authored by Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., that would give Congress the power to
establish reasonable limits on campaign fund-raising. The
Hollings-Specter measure has already been rejected twice by the
Senate, and it is likely to fail again Tuesday by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
