<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TOBACCO-SUIT-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNITIVE DAMAGES ADDED IN SMOKING-CASE VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A San Francisco jury on Monday ordered two cigarette makers to
pay a total of $20 million in punitive damages in the first case
decided in favor of a person who started smoking after the federal
government required the tobacco industry to put warning labels on
cigarette packages.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-person state-court jury ordered Philip Morris Cos. and
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings to each pay $10 million in punitive
damages to Leslie Whiteley, a California woman who developed lung
cancer. Last week the same jury ordered the companies to pay a
total of $1.7 million in compensatory damages to Whiteley and her
family.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes at a critical time for the tobacco industry,
and arguments in the case may foreshadow those in a Miami court
where a jury is hearing a class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of
all smokers in Florida. Punitive damages in that case, if awarded,
are expected to reach tens of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds said the companies
would appeal both decisions in the California case. But legal
experts said the verdict was significant because Whiteley began
smoking after the government ordered that warnings appear on
cigarette packages.
</P>
<P>
   Those labels, which first appeared in 1965, were strengthened by
Congress in 1969. The U.S. Supreme Court held in 1992 that the 1969
labeling requirements pre-empted state juries from awarding damages
to smokers on the grounds that they had not been adequately warned
about tobacco dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies have long used that ruling as part of their
defense against smokers' claims. But Madelyn Chaber, a lawyer in
San Francisco who represented Whiteley, surmounted that hurdle by
arguing that producers had engaged in fraud by conspiring to
misrepresent the hazards of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are able to show these higher levels of wrongdoing,
then the warning issues don't make that much of a difference,''
said Stephen Sugarman, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second major victory against tobacco producers by
Chaber, who has based her cases in part on industry documents
uncovered during the recent round of lawsuits brought by states
against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year another San Francisco jury awarded one of her clients
$51.5 million in compensatory and punitive damages against Philip
Morris, which is the United States' largest cigarette maker. That
award, which the company is appealing, has been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Chaber had asked the San Francisco jury to award Whiteley and
her family $115 million in punitive damages, meant to punish a
company for wrongdoing and deter such conduct in the future. A
lawyer for Philip Morris had argued that punitive damages should be
$5 million or less because cigarette producers had changed their
practices as a result of recent legal settlements between the
industry and the states.
</P>
<P>
   Under those settlements, the industry agreed to pay $246 billion
over the next two decades to the states that had sued to recover
costs incurred in treatment of smoking-related ills. The companies
have also agreed to change some marketing and advertising
practices. The settlements did not bar class-action lawsuits or
claims by individual smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry analysts like Martin Feldman of Salomon Smith
Barney Inc. have said that they expected that punitive damages, if
awarded, in the Florida class action could reach ten of billions of
dollars. And on Monday, Feldman said that he expected the industry
to also argue in that case, if needed, that it had changed its ways
as a result of its settlements with states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits to a T the argument they will make in Florida,''
Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the Miami jury began hearing closing arguments in the
cases of three people chosen to represent the entire class of
Florida smokers. Last year that same jury found that producers had
conspired to conceal tobacco's hazards.
</P>
<P>
   If the jurors find that cigarettes caused any one of the three
representative smokers to become ill, they will next decide whether
to award punitive damages to all the participants in the suit. The
precise size of that group is not known but it is estimated at
300,000 people or more.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco company officials are barred by court order from
discussing the Miami case, but William S. Ohlemeyer, a lawyer for
Philip Morris, said that, generally speaking, the punitive-damage
arguments made to the California jury were ``a small piece of what
could occur in a larger and a more difficult case.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday in her office, Chaber displayed four photographs of
Whiteley who started smoking in 1972 when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1975 photograph, Whiteley wore a red bandanna in her long
blond hair. In another photograph taken last September, her head is
shaved bald and a scar is visible where an incision was made to
insert metal pins for use in a surgical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteley, whose cancer has spread to her liver and brain, only
briefly attended the trial. The bulk of her testimony was given in
a taped deposition. She had brain surgery two week ago, but Chaber
described her client, who is married and has four children, as
happy with the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's thrilled obviously, but it's a mixed joy,'' Chaber said.
``She's happy her children are going to be taken care of, but she's
not going to be around for their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was a sharp one for Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds,
because they had worked hard to shore up the industry's defenses
after the early loss to Chaber in California and a victory last
year by an individual smoker in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oregon case, a state jury ordered Philip Morris to pay
$81 million to the family of a man who smoked cigarettes for four
decades before he died. That award has since been reduced by about
one-half.
</P>
<P>
   Sugarman, the law professor, said he believed the string of
defeats showed that cigarette companies had failed thus far to come
up with a way to fight off the damaging documents that had emerged
during the state lawsuits, and to combat jury sentiment against
them. Feldman, the analyst, agreed with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially these cases are being lost because the plaintiffs
are making better use out of the industry's own documents than the
industry is,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles A. Blixt, general counsel of R.J. Reynolds, said he
believed that the company had presented a strong defense. Also he
said he did not feel that juror sentiment was against producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one jury in one court,'' said Blixt. ``I don't expect
that this is an indication of any change in fundamental
sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlemeyer, the Philip Morris lawyer, said that the company's
appeal would be based in part on the fact that while the jury may
have found that the cigarette makers had made fraudulent
statements, there had been no evidence put forward that Whiteley
had relied on such statements in making decisions about smoking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
