<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-SUIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI QUITS CASE AGAINST MUSEUM OVER `SENSATION' EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani agreed Monday to abandon his
months-long campaign to evict the Brooklyn Museum of Art and cut
its city financing for having mounted an exhibition last year that
he deemed offensive and sacrilegious.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Giuliani promised to restore the city's
monthly payments to the museum and to drop, once and for all, his
suit to evict it from a city building and remove its board of
trustees because of last fall's ``Sensation'' exhibition, which
included a painting of the Virgin Mary adorned with elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, in turn, dropped its First Amendment lawsuit against
the mayor, who was scheduled for a deposition in the case as early
as this week. The deal also resolved a lingering budget dispute
that had been put on hold during the months of squabbling.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials immediately welcomed the settlement, saying
that they were particularly pleased that the city had ended the
budget standoff by agreeing to pay $5.8 million over the next two
years to help repair the museum's entry hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the past six months have only made our
institution stronger and more dedicated to our mission,'' said
Robert S. Rubin, chairman of the board of trustees. Officials at
the museum, he said, ``are proud of what we have done, happy with
this resolution, and are now eagerly looking forward to the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The city also said that it was happy with the agreement, though
Giuliani administration officials took pains at a news conference
Monday afternoon to stand by the mayor's original objection to the
exhibition. In a series of indignant public statements, Giuliani
had said that he found the exhibition to be pornographic and
anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very gratified with the settlement,'' said Michael D.
Hess, the city's corporation counsel. ``The exhibit is closed, and
at this point it was time to end the hostilities on both sides in
terms of court proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hess said, ``part of that exhibit was obviously
religion-bashing, and the mayor took exception to that, and rightly
so.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement Monday made permanent a temporary court order
issued in November by Judge Nina Gershon of U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn. When the order was first handed down, Giuliani ridiculed
it and promised to appeal, accusing Gershon of `'the usual
knee-jerk reaction of some judges.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's decision to drop his appeal followed several months
in which he seemed to have dug in his heels against the museum and
its lawyers, including Floyd B. Abrams, the First Amendment expert.
``Mayor Giuliani has done the right thing today,'' Abrams said
Monday. ``I think he should have done it earlier, but he was faced
with an insupportable legal position and a policy which is directly
at war with well-established First Amendment principles.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hess adamantly denied that the mayor had capitulated. ``I am
not saying it is a victory for anybody,'' he said. ``It is happy
that it is over, at this point. It is not a question of anybody
backing down. It is not backing down at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess said that the $5.8 million that the city had agreed to pay
for capital improvements was far less than the $11 million that the
museum had sought. He also noted that both sides would pay their
own legal expenses. The museum had sought to have the city pay its
$1 million in fees, Hess said, adding that the city's expenses were
nowhere near that much.
</P>
<P>
   The city, which provides about a third of the museum's annual
$24 million operating budget, began withholding the museum's
monthly subsidy of about $500,000 in October. All of the $3.5
million withheld during previous months has been paid back, and the
city _ as well as Giuliani personally _ could face contempt of
court charges should the money be kept from the museum again.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement seeks to ensure that the museum will be treated
fairly in the years to come by forbidding Giuliani from reducing
its public financing by any amount ``disproportionately greater''
than that of seven other museums, including the Metropolitan Museum
of Art and the American Museum of Natural History, that receive
city money. The agreement is binding on him until he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff began when Giuliani announced his distaste for the
Virgin Mary portrait by Chris Ofili, a Roman Catholic of Nigerian
descent, and other works in the exhibition. ``Sensation,'' which
opened Oct. 2 and closed Jan. 9, originated in Britain and was
drawn from the collection of Charles Saatchi, the advertising
magnate.
</P>
<P>
   The case had legal implications for publicly financed art
institutions across the country, Abrams said, making them less
vulnerable to censorship by public officials. ``This sends a
message that the museum community is willing to fight back,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
