<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-REEVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR REEVE ENCOURAGES SCIENTISTS ON GENE RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Before a ballroom packed with geneticists and
biotechnology executives, the most famous paralyzed man in America
took the stage Monday night with the message he has urged for five
years: That he must walk again, and they must help him.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Reeve, frozen in the public mind as Superman before
a 1995 accident left him a quadriplegic, got an emotional standing
ovation from the audience at the Bio2000 conference as he hailed
recent breakthroughs in stem cell research and genetic coding that
could someday lead to spinal cord regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   Make a profit, he told the audience. Conduct business. But as
legions of patients struggle with diabetes, Alzheimer's and
Parkinson's disease, to say nothing of spinal cord injuries, don't
forget to tell the patients what you're doing so they can be
encouraged by the progress of their own cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many people still can't get past the psychological
barrier that their life has been ruined,'' said Reeve, speaking at
the world's largest gathering of biotechnology industry officials.
``It's important to give them hope _ not to give them false hope,
but to go back to what really is the American mantra, and it is a
realistic mantra, that nothing is impossible. Let them know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his accident, Reeve has become one of the nation's
highest-paid and most sought-after speakers. He also has thrown
himself into the role of a professional spur to science, raising
unprecedented amounts of money for spinal cord injury research and
repeating his hope to walk again before his 50th birthday in 2003.
Meeting with a wheelchair-bound teenaged victim of the Columbine
shootings this spring, he promised her, ``You're going to be
walking. I'm serious, you're going to be walking,'' according to
the Rocky Mountain News in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of promise that has made him a favorite figure
among researchers _ and a more ambiguous one among people with
similar disabilities, who complain that Reeve could just as easily
encourage people with paralysis to accept their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tightrope walk along a sword,'' said John Fioritti, a
program director at the Greater Boston chapter of the National
Spinal Cord Injury Association. ``On one hand, you want to have
hope for the future, and on the other hand, you don't want false
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the crowd at the Hynes Convention Center, who are more
inclined to think along a scientific timeline, Reeve's vision did
not seem as suspect. Within the last six months, two teams of
scientists have made breakthroughs: In November, a team of Canadian
scientists announced that they had regenerated spinal cord tissue
in mice using stem cells extracted from the brain or bone marrow.
In January, from Switzerland came news that a lab had discovered
the gene that inhibits regeneration of the brain and spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the physical presence of a patient such as Reeve
awaiting a cure is exactly what scientists ``working at the lab
bench doing gritty research work'' need to inspire them, said Carl
B. Feldbaum, who as president of the Biotech Industry Organization
helped select Reeve as a speaker. Feldbaum added that, if he was in
Reeve's position, he would hope to be equally passionate about
curing his condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may feel more comfortable with the goal of accommodation,
and others need to go for broke. That's what Chris Reeve is
doing,'' Feldbaum said. ``He can't do all things for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were many in the community of people with similar
injuries who didn't make an effort to see Reeve speak _ and who
have, over the years, angrily tuned him out. John Kelly, a Brandeis
University graduate student who is quadriplegic, was busy writing a
want ad for a home care assistant whose $9.50 an hour wage would be
paid by the government. He complained that the problem besetting
most people with disabilities is ``poverty and oppression,'' not
the wait for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   And Pam Burkely of Hyannis, Mass., who has been a paraplegic
since 1973, said she had expected Reeve to temper his message to
include more emphasis on accommodation and services as the years
went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd give Christopher two years to work through that
I-will-walk-again thing and then see him come back into reality
with more of an emphasis on resources,'' said Burkely, who works at
the Cape Organization for Rights of the Disabled. ``The message he
gives out is dangerous. What he's doing isn't bringing attention to
my reality. For every two steps forward, we take a step back. I
don't think he's forcing us backward, but he slows down the second
step.''
</P>
<P>
   But all that complexity meant little to 4-year-old Devin Keppel,
who was hit by a car when he was 2 and is one of about a dozen
children in the country who have the same injury as Reeve. Around
lunchtime Monday, his mother piled him into the car and drove in
from Manchester, Mass., so Devin could see the real hero of the
movie he has watched _ by his own account _ upwards of 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devin knew Superman before the accident,'' said Sian Keppel,
his mother. ``So we can tell him, `Superman had a (tracheotomy
tube) and a vent. And Superman's off the vent. And so is Devin.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
