<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FEW MARCH STARS, BUT PLENTY OF PARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It doesn't take much to make an old Tar Heel bleed
Carolina blue. North Carolina will be in Indianapolis this weekend,
and though Matt Doherty has his own Final Four business to conduct
in New York, he couldn't resist the opportunity to defend an old
mentor and friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to give Bill Guthridge a hard time, but he's
coached three years and now he's gotten to two Final Fours,''
Doherty said Monday before heading off to Madison Square Garden to
prepare Notre Dame for its National Invitation Tournament semifinal
Tuesday night against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge, who slid into the Chapel Hill hot seat when Dean
Smith retired, was recently under siege, when the North Carolina
faithful had to bow their heads on selection Sunday and say their
prayers. Thirteen-game losers, the Tar Heels were fortunate to make
the big tournament, and their name value for the sake of a network
ratings point didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Wisconsin doesn't exactly inspire dynastic memories
of UCLA, while a young Florida team dangled on the edge of
first-round oblivion against Butler. Even Michigan State, the
favorite going into Indianapolis, has trailed during the second
half in three of its four games.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, once-upon-a-time teammate of Michael Jordan, James
Worthy and Sam Perkins on the 1982 national champions, knows that
the era of superstar-laden college basketball teams is expiring,
slowly yet surely, like one of those tournament games dragged on by
timeouts and fouls. The exodus of young stars to the National
Basketball Association is clearly turning March into a much more
democratic method of madness. ``It's all about execution, making
shots, biorhythms, the stars and the moon,'' Doherty said. He added
that he truly does believe in astrological explanations, at least
more than in Dick Vitale's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty cited the side jumper that his star sophomore, Troy
Murphy of Morristown, N.J., missed that would have won a Big East
Tournament game against Miami. ``That's his shot, and in the first
round of the NIT against Michigan, he was in the exact same spot
and he made it,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Murphy made the shot against Miami _ who knows? Maybe Notre
Dame is Wisconsin, or North Carolina. Instead of Doherty, maybe
Bill Guthridge would have been sampling the chicken Monday at the
NIT luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty, 38, out of Holy Trinity High School in Hicksville,
N.Y., got the Notre Dame job after spending seven years next to Roy
Williams at the University of Kansas. Williams, of course, studied
under Smith, one seat to the left of the longtime first lieutenant,
Guthridge. From Williams to Doherty, George Karl to Larry Brown,
all of the head-coaching Heels will be burning up the phone and fax
wires over Guthridge's reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faxed him before the tournament and I will again before the
weekend,'' Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   From as far away as South Bend, Ind., he knew enough about North
Carolina's season to recount the injuries that put Guthridge's team
on the tournament bubble. He hated the idea that one of the game's
true gentlemen was hung out by knee-jerk critics and spoiled fans.
</P>
<P>
   The old-time college powerhouses had better realize that the
days of taking anything for granted are ending. There is no turning
backing the clock, and even more of those diaper dandies will
toddle off to the pros when the NBA gets its developmental league
going.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Odom, the Wake Forest coach who plays North Carolina State
in Tuesday night's other NIT semifinal, pointed out that his team
waxed Wisconsin by 20 this season and beat North Carolina twice.
Excepting Michigan State, Odom contended that you could flip-flop
the two Final Fours and see little or no qualitative difference. He
guessed that more No. 8 seeded teams like North Carolina and
Wisconsin will in the coming years find the March stars properly
aligned, if they have a few heady seniors like the Tar Heels'
Brooklyn point guard, Ed Cota.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons I became so excited about this
job,'' Doherty said of Notre Dame. ``I looked at the success of
Stanford. With so many kids leaving early, they've been able to
play juniors and seniors against young kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience didn't help Stanford in its ``upset'' loss to North
Carolina, but Doherty likely made a wise career move. Notre Dame
could be a player in the changing world of college basketball,
which, contrary to doomsayers like Billy Packer, isn't going to die
without the majority of future sneaker pitchman. The tournament
works because of its formula, more than who is playing in it. Fame
is not a necessary requirement for television drama, as Regis now
reminds us several nights a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
