<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9626 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-REACT-2TAKES-NYT     03-27 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-REACT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S CAMPAIGN FINANCE PLAN DRAWS LUKEWARM REACTION FROM
FUND-RAISERS
</HEADLINE>
   (With GORE-FUNDRAISING) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Political donors and fund-raisers approached Vice
President Al Gore's latest campaign finance proposal warily,
concerned that it would diminish their influence with candidates
and create an unwieldy new government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Calling big-money contributions to politics a ``cancer on our
democracy,'' Gore on Monday proposed the elimination of the
unlimited donations known as soft money and creation of a $7
billion endowment to finance all general election campaigns for
Congress. The fund would be financed with tax-deductible
contributions from the corporations, unions and individuals that
now underwrite most political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would radically reshape the financing of federal
elections and curtail the money chase that now consumes candidates'
time and energy and which landed Gore in political and legal
distress after the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would obliterate the direct tie between private
contributors and federal officeholders and the two political
parties. ``The views of the donor will have absolutely no influence
on their views of the recipient,'' Gore said in a speech in
Milwaukee. ``In this way, we will break the connection between the
giving of money and the gaining of influence in these election
contests.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president used his speech to defend his role in the
fund-raising excesses of the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign, saying
that he had to ``push the system'' to defend core Democratic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   And he took the opportunity to attack his Republican foe, Gov.
George W. Bush, as an enemy of campaign finance reform who has
treated the issue as a ``political shell game.''
</P>
<P>
   One question that remains unanswered about his plan is what
incentive donors would have to contribute to a large bipartisan
endowment that would serve as the vehicle for public financing of
campaigns. Many big donors now contribute to a particular lawmaker
or political party because they want access, have a specific
legislative problem, or a partisan or ideological agenda. The plan
also does not address the need to raise money to run a primary
election campaign, presumably from the same sources that now fuel
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican fund-raisers alike suggested that
donors would be reluctant to contribute to a fund from which
candidates of both parties could draw.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Eudy, the top fund-raiser for the presidential campaign of
Sen. John McCain, called the Gore plan ``disastrous.'' She said
that current Republican donors would be loath to give $1,000 or
$100,000 to a fund that would help finance the campaigns of
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I want to contribute to a fund that could be giving
money to help elect Ted Kennedy?'' she asked. ``Al Gore is only
proposing this because he wants to be John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour, one of the Republican Party's most prominent
money men and a key fund-raiser for Bush said, ``I don't believe
small business, big business, agriculture or much of anyone else
wants a government-run election system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't want to pay for politicians' campaigns,''
added Barbour, who contributed more than $21,000 in his own name to
40 Republican candidates last year. ``This is going to be paid for
with taxpayer dollars and no matter how much lipstick you put on it
this pig ain't going to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Gore's backers expressed skepticism. A top
Democratic donor, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Gore's
plan violates the competitive spirit of politics. ``It will be hard
to get people to give if they are giving to a fund that both
Democrats and Republicans will benefit from,'' the donor said.
``People give to elect one party and defeat the other party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Grossman, a top Democratic contributor and former
party finance chairman, welcomed the proposal as a tonic for a
democracy in distress. He said that the public had become cynical
and indifferent to politics, in part because of a popular view that
moneyed interests had hijacked the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I be willing to take all the dollars I contribute and
reallocate them to a democracy endowment fund? In a heartbeat,''
Grossman said. ``As a former state and national party chair, a
major donor, a fund-raiser and first and foremost a citizen, I
would do so to engender a sense among citizens that they can take
back their political system.''
</P>
<P>
   One major fund-raiser for Gore, who insisted that his name not
be used, said that many political contributors would be happy to
consolidate their donations in one check to a national bipartisan
fund. But he also said that the plan was unlikely to win passage by
members of Congress who owe their seats to the contributions of
thousands of individuals and political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the reason Gore is proposing it,'' this fund-raiser
said, ``I'm skeptical it's the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also questioned the proposals, particularly given Gore's
direct involvement in the 1996 fund-raising excesses. ``Any promise
to reform our campaign finance system will ring hollow unless it is
grounded in credibility, credibility based on consistency,
integrity and disclosure,'' Bush said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an attorney general, a president and a vice president
who will live by and enforce the laws we currently have on the
books. Unless the vice president stops withholding information
about his own fund-raising excesses, the American people will
question his commitment to reforming the fund-raising practices of
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats and Republicans expressed doubts about the
practicality and political appeal of the Gore proposal. Several
noted that only one in eight Americans now checks the box on their
annual tax returns to devote $3 to paying for presidential
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The fund covers only a fraction of the money that the candidates
receive _ $67 million for the major party nominees for the general
election this fall, and more than $30 million in primary matching
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of a number of corporations that make large political
donations either declined comment on the Gore proposal or did not
respond phone calls seeking reaction to the Gore proposal. A
Microsoft official said the company would not comment. Several
others, including United Parcel Service, SBC Communications, AT&AMP;T
and the American Financial Group, did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's proposal drew a warmer response from some of the
Democratic party's largest labor contributors. Several unions
endorsed the plan as a means to balance the Republican party's
historic fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Stern, president of the Service Employees International
Union, one of the largest sources of Democratic soft money
contributions, called Gore's finance plan innovative and
comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we believe that elections and government should be about
the right of individual citizens to participate and not have their
voices drowned out by corporations and wealthy individuals, our
first instinct is to be enthusiastically in favor,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald H. McEntee, president of the American Federation of State
County &AMP; Municipal Employees, the Democratic party's largest single
donor last year, also praised the Gore plan. ``When the business
community outspends us 16 to 1,'' he said, ``it's a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that his union, which gave $1.4 million in soft money to
the Democratic National Committee in 1999 alone, would in all
likelihood contribute to a non-partisan fund like that proposed by
the vice president. But in an illustration of the plan's
incompleteness, he said the union would also continue its spending
on political activity outside the system as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore proposal would not affect the independent spending on
political advocacy and organizing by unions, corporations,
individuals or interest groups. But the plan would require more
complete disclosure of the sources of funding of issue advertising
60 days before an election and provide equal time for candidates
who are the targets of such independent expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Gore consulted with a number of advocates of revisions in
current campaign finance law, including members of Congress and
leaders of independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the plan he announced on Monday was borrowed, but the
centerpiece of the plan, the so-called Democracy Endowment, was the
vice president's own idea although it bears some similarities to a
plan proposed some years ago by Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin,
according to aides and others whose advice he sought.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, candidates for the House and Senate would
receive funding from the endowment for their general election
campaigns if they agree not to accept any other sources of money.
Candidates competing against each other would receive equal
amounts, which would vary by state or district, depending on
population and cost of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who made overhauling the campaign finance system the
rallying point of his now-suspended presidential campaign, said
Gore's proposal _ and its author _ were flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very workable,'' McCain said in a telephone
interview. ``You can't even get Americans to check off a dollar any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have no motivation to contribute to a fund that
dilutes their influence, he added, and the public is skeptical of
Gore, whose enthusiasm for campaign finance revisions appears to
many to be an electoral ploy. McCain said that troubling questions
still remain about possibly illegal fund raising by the
Clinton-Gore campaign of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not condemning it,'' McCain said of Gore's plan. ``I
appreciate very much that he's taken up this issue, but in order to
prove his credibility, he'd have to call for a complete
investigation and renounce soft money now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
