<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TREASURY SECRETARY URGES A FOCUS ON LATIN POVERTY
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers called for sweeping changes
in the way international aid agencies combat poverty in Latin
America, amid signs that robust growth there has left more people
behind than many economists expected.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the Inter-American Development Bank, Summers
said the United States wanted the bank to raise the rates it
charges its wealthiest borrowers and adopt more effective ways of
improving education and fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER TO BUY 33.4 PERCENT OF MITSUBISHI
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, the world's third-largest automaker, agreed to
acquire 33.4 percent of Mitsubishi Motors, finally securing the
toehold in Asia it had long wanted. ``We have closed the circle,''
Juergen E. Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's chairman, said at a news
conference. ``We have covered all the markets of the world.'' The
$2.1 billion deal leaves Toyota and Honda as Japan's last major
carmakers without big foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
   $20 MILLION AWARD IN TOBACCO CASE
</P>
<P>
   A jury in San Francisco ordered Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds
to pay a total of $20 million in punitive damages in the first case
decided on behalf of a person who started smoking after the
government required that warning labels appear on cigarette
packages.
</P>
<P>
   JUNIPER HAS NEW SWITCHING SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its march into the data networking market, Juniper
Networks intends to announce Tuesday that it is shipping what
appears to be the fastest electronic switch for Internet
information. Several leading communications carriers have agreed to
buy the new system.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SLIDE, LED BY MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   The three main stock gauges slumped, dragged down by declines in
financial service and bank stocks and by a big decline in
Microsoft. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 86.87 points, to
11,025.85. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.60 points,
to 1,523.86, while the Nasdaq composite index dropped 4.47 points,
to 4,958.56.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE MANAGEMENT POSTS A LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, the United States' largest trash hauler,
reported a fourth-quarter loss because it spent $360 million to fix
its accounting and computer systems and invested in landfills and
new garbage trucks. The company lost $114.7 million, or 19 cents a
share. Excluding the one-time costs, the company would have earned
$200 million, or 32 cents a share, just shy of expectations. Shares
of Waste Management rose 68.75 cents, to $14.25.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN URGES PAYING OFF DEBT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
sought in Senate testimony to bolster Congress' resolve to save
huge government surpluses to pay down the national debt. Nothing
would have more effect on the nation's ability to meet the expenses
of baby boomers' retirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-POWER RADIO PLAN MOVES AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators pressed ahead with plans to issue low-power
FM community radio licenses despite efforts by commercial
broadcasters to block the program.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES ROSE 6.7 PERCENT IN FEBRUARY
</P>
<P>
   Americans pushed up sales of existing homes in February by 6.7
percent after two consecutive months of declines.
</P>
<P>
   ROGUE TRADER SEEN IN SWEDISH ADS
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Leeson, the rogue stock trader who caused the collapse
of Britain's oldest merchant bank, Barings, is appearing in a
campaign that promotes a Swedish online stock-trading company.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS HOPE PUTIN ACTS QUICKLY
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors and local business people say the new Russian
president, Vladimir Putin, must take decisive action over the next
few months for the country to see marked increases in investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
