<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9630 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-2T     03-27 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW JERSEY, A SENATE CANDIDATE RUNS AGAINST THE BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Running against motherhood or apple pie you
could understand. But running against the boom?
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's economic expansion entering its 109th
consecutive month and much of New Jersey awash in prosperity, it
seems like an odd strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But in New Jersey's U.S. Senate contest, unlike any other major
political race in the country, a convergence of unusual
circumstances has transformed the Democratic primary into a race
that has put the economic boom on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jon S. Corzine, the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
has swathed himself in the flag of prosperity, asserting that his
work on Wall Street helped New Jersey companies create and retain
hundreds of thousands of jobs. If elected to the Senate, Corzine
says, he will use his business acumen to spread that wealth to the
poor by offering a banquet of expansive social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Those arguments have prompted his opponent, former Gov. Jim
Florio, to warn voters that a dark cloud has been obscured by the
economic silver lining. On issues ranging from Social Security and
pension financing to corporate mergers, trade policy and government
borrowing, Florio has hammered his opponent with the kind of
class-based attacks Democrats usually aim at Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He has accused Wall Street titans of raking in billions of
dollars in profits at the expense of poor and working-class
Americans, and has blamed Goldman, Sachs for underwriting corporate
mergers that cost more than 75,000 Americans their jobs under
Corzine's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Florio has also cautioned voters not to let Wall Street's
blazing performance in recent years lure them into accepting the
Clinton administration's proposal to invest some Social Security
money in the stock market, an initiative Corzine supports.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan would result in billions of dollars in investment
fees for Wall Street firms, Florio argues, but leave low-income
retirees at the mercy of volatile market fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week, you hear stories about economic disparities in
this boom period, with more and more people in the top end doing
better and people in the lower end doing worse in terms of
purchasing power,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the exchanges are two starkly different visions
of the economy and of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine (pronounced kore-ZYNE) is convinced that the economic
expansion has brought benefits to enough people that his Wall
Street resume will inspire confidence in working-class voters.
Florio believes that the Democratic Party's traditional base in New
Jersey _ factory workers, union stewards, minimum-wage employees
and retirees _ is inherently wary of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Hughes, dean of the Edward J. Bloustein School of
Planning and Public Policy at Rutgers University, said the race was
a test case of how prosperity may have shifted the political
landscape within the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a question of new economy vs. old economy,''
Hughes said. ``What proportion of new economy workers, information
economy workers, financial services employees, the people
benefiting from the boom are going to vote in a Democratic
primary?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the national Democratic and Republican Parties have
debated whether Ronald Reagan or Bill Clinton deserves credit for
the soaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates like Hillary Rodham Clinton have occasionally
suggested that some pockets of the country, like upstate New York,
have not shared equally in the boom.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has critiqued the economy's performance as directly,
or as harshly, as Florio, said Larry Sabato, a political science
professor at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robert H. Frank, a Cornell professor who has written extensively
about the inequities and excesses of the 1990s, said Florio's
argument may be a tough sell to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of any other candidate out there arguing against
the boom,'' Frank said. ``The Republicans aren't going to come out
against an economy that has benefited their supporters, the rich.
For Democrats, there is a case that Florio is making. But why make
that case when you can just say we're responsible for greatest
economic expansion of all time?''
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat surprising that such an appeal is being attempted
in a place as prosperous as New Jersey. The state's per capita
income is the second-highest in the nation. Nearly 60 percent of
New Jersey households have an interest in the stock market, either
directly or through 401k plans or mutual funds. The state's
high-tech and pharmaceutical industries have expanded rapidly in
recent years, helping drive the unemployment rate down to just 4.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Department of Labor, the fastest growing
segment of the work force is now financial services, and the number
of commodities traders increased to 44,000 from 40,000 in the last
year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some recent polls suggest that the boom has not
completely erased New Jersey voters' suspicion of powerful
establishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are distrustful of big institutions, like big
business, even if people are doing well financially,'' said
Clifford Zukin, a Rutgers political science professor who heads the
university's polling institute. ``So in a Democratic primary, it
makes some sense to rail against big money.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the economic platform embraced by each candidate
has been shaped by strategic necessity. Corzine, a political
neophyte, has little choice but to maintain that his business
triumphs are a harbinger of success in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Florio left office in 1994, a year before most New Jerseyans
began to fully feel the end of the recession, so it would be
difficult for him to claim credit for the state's resurgence.
Florio's campaign resources are also dwarfed by Corzine's $300
million fortune (and his pledge to spend as much as necessary to
win). So the former governor has blasted Corzine's costly
advertising appeals in the hope that ``free media,'' newspapers and
television, will convey his message to voters.
</P>
<P>
   What has emerged is a series of increasingly heated
disagreements about economic disparity and the corrosive power of
wealth that at times seem more at home in the Dust Bowl era than
the Microsoft era. On the day Corzine released new television
commercials this month, campaign officials for Florio held a news
conference in which a prominent supporter ominously suggested that
Corzine's fortune might actually be worth more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 450 billionaires in the U.S.,'' warned the
supporter, Rep. Bill Pascrell Jr. ``And if they fan out across the
country, they can consume all of the congressional districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has tried to counter Florio's appeals to class
resentment by pointing out his working-class roots. He also
contends that the campaign is not about Wall Street, but about the
ability to understand and shape a rapidly changing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jim Florio is just out of touch with where the economy
of the U.S. is in this day and age,'' Corzine said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a recent advertising campaign, Corzine claimed some credit
for job growth in recent years, stating that during his stewardship
of Goldman, Sachs, the company's investments helped New Jersey
companies create or retain 700,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Florio ridiculed that assertion, saying it was absurd for an
investment banker to take credit for jobs created by his borrowers.
Many political analysts also characterized Corzine's ads as
exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine maintains that the ads are technically accurate and
that their message is that he learned to direct capital to areas
where it can spur economic development. He said he would use that
expertise in the Senate by pushing for an urban redevelopment bank
to encourage business growth in inner cities and by proposing
bountiful government subsidies for health care, preschool,
long-term care and college education.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Corzine also blames Florio for New Jersey's economic stagnation
during the early 1990s, saying that the governor's decision to push
a $2.8 billion tax increase through the Legislature in 1990 scared
off businesses, fueled unemployment and contributed to his being
voted out of office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't argue that it was going to be a generator of
business to New Jersey,'' Corzine said. ``It had a deleterious
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio, who pushed for the tax increase to pay for court-ordered
increases in school financing, dismisses those criticisms as the
naive quibbling of someone who has never had to make a tough
political decision.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Florio also contends that his long career in state politics has
made him singularly attuned to the worries of New Jersey families.
Florio cited several recent studies that show the gap between New
Jersey's rich and poor widening.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he makes campaign appearances at countless senior citizens
centers, union halls and kaffeeklatsches, Florio says he is often
surprised at the deep concern many New Jerseyans have about their
long-term financial security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks understand something is going on; the earth is moving,''
Florio said. ``The old defined benefit pension system is being
replaced, and it is the working families that will be squeezed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Florio is scheduled to release his own economic position paper
early next month. Drafts of the document call for targeted tax
cuts, funding for worker retraining and trade sanctions against
countries that do not uphold environmental and labor standards. But
thus far, most of the economic debate in the campaign has been a
critique of Corzine's ideas and his Wall Street resume.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Shure, whose liberal research organization, New Jersey
Policy Perspective, has released several studies about economic
disparity in the state, said it was heartening to hear a political
candidate call for economic justice, as Florio is doing. But Shure,
who was Florio's communications director as governor but is not
involved in his Senate campaign, warned that those left behind by
the boom also constitute the segment of the population least likely
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Florio says he is undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever accused me of taking the easy way,'' he said.
``But that's what leadership is about. Talking about important
things that many people aren't yet ready to address.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
