<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKC-NCAA-BOS &LR;      03-27 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOSTON UNIVERSITY-ST. LAWRENCE CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was when the overtimes began that the game picked up its
pace. No TV timeouts to disrupt the flow and the edge increasing as
one overtime dissolved into another _ a first, second, third, and,
incredibly, a fourth, before Robin Carruthers finally gave St.
Lawrence a 3-2 victory over Boston University on Sunday in the
longest NCAA hockey tournament game ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey was being played in its purest form, sudden death, no
artificial pauses, just players from both teams jumping over the
boards after shifts of a mere 20 and 25 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   St. Lawrence's Jason Windle blasted from the right point at
14:30 of the first overtime; save by Boston University goalie Rick
DiPietro. BU's John Sabo hauled down at the mouth of the crease
with 2:00 left in the first OT, Sabo seemingly set to score the
winning goal off a pass from Carl Corazzini, but Sabo never could
collect the pass as he was pushed into St. Lawrence goalie Derek
Gustafson. And BU could not take advantage of the penalty against
St. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the alley-ways of the Pepsi Arena in Albany, and
watching, were impatient players from two other teams, Maine and
Michigan, waiting to begin their game in the NCAA East Regional.
The Black Bears and Wolverines were in full pads for the first OT
of the BU and St. Lawrence game; by the second overtime, they were
were watching BU and St. Lawrence go up and down the ice in their
sweaters _ their team sweaters and not their hockey sweaters _ and
by the third OT, some were in shorts.
</P>
<P>
   But still watching.
</P>
<P>
   The game was now a classic. The Terriers and Saints somehow were
manufacturing scoring chances despite legs that were heavy and
cramped. And the scoring chances were rich and ripe _ incredibly
once again, 27 shots on net by the two teams in the third OT _ but
BU's DiPietro and St. Lawrence's Gustafson were stopping one and
all. NCAA tournament records were falling with every shot and save.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaways meant nothing to these two freshman goalies, and
neither did two-on-ones and three-on-ones, nor one-timers from the
point or screen shots from the top of the slot. The goalies just
would not let a puck behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give back all (77) saves if we had won the game,''
DiPietro said. ``To tell you the truth, I'd rather have had 10
shots and won than 77 saves and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston, the classic scratched in overtime from TV
because of a meaningless Celtics team playing a near-meaningless
game against Milwaukee, BU alumni were out in their cars, listening
to the game on the radio. But, in Albany, the game just went on . .
. and on . . . and on.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth overtime, only a penalty shot _ it seemed _ might
end this game that began at noon and still was being played as
twilight descended upon Albany. Each goalie seemed that confident,
that sure, that focused.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Venis, the BU trainer, was handing out dehydration pills
to players, and even to the referee. ``Guys were getting bad muscle
cramps, and they couldn't even stand up at times,'' said Venis.
``(BU player Dan) Cavanaugh was so cramped up that he got knocked
down once but he couldn't even pick himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Venis, a trainer for other BU teams, ``had never seen anything
like this in ice hockey.'' Football, yes, football on a scorching
day, but this was hockey in the North on a March day. Still, ``this
was a pretty hot building,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Venis was also concerned about DiPietro, ``because Ricky
cramps a lot. We pretty much gave him a lot of water all the time
and we actually started him off early in the day, hydrating him and
making sure he had extra water from breakfast on. Actually, because
it was such an early game, we started him (Saturday) night, making
sure he was hydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   For BU coach Jack Parker, ``it was a case of which guys were
going to survive this next shift. We had so many guys leaving
because of cramps and stuff. Cavanaugh left halfway through the
second overtime and he missed all of the third overtime and then
all of a sudden, he's putting his skates back on (for the fourth
overtime). The trainer had told me he wasn't going to be back at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   BU had played strongly in the third period and also came out
aggressively in the first OT, ``and I think, in retrospect, we had
that great third period and that great first overtime, and we had
our chances then,'' said Parker.
</P>
<P>
   St. Lawrence coach Joe Marsh said, ``I'm almost speechless'' _ a
rare occurrence _ after the classic ended after 123 minutes 53
seconds of hockey. As one intermission folded into the next, Marsh
said he had less and less to say to his players. ``Just let 'em
play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It ended after a combined 154 shots, after 149 saves by DiPietro
and Gustafson, Marsh saying the trite words so often said in sports
but so true this time, that neither team should have lost.
</P>
<P>
   And the Boston University hockey players boarded the bus for the
long ride along the New York Thruway and the Massachusetts Turnpike
back to Boston. ``A lot of the players still had cramps on the
bus,'' said Parker, ``but by the time we got back to Boston,'' the
players were in better physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The cramps diminsh, ``Once you stop sweating,'' said the coach.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotional cramp from the loss will take longer to
dissipate. Parker said his memories from the game are bittersweet,
sweet because the Terriers' effort against a rested and favored St.
Lawrence team exemplified the way ``the team has played all
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-sweet taste is obvious. This game that wouldn't end,
said Parker, ``is one game I'll always remember, that's for sure.''
But the memory ``would have been much sweeter if we had won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
