<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES SERIES OF CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to inoculate himself against attacks over
his own fund-raising record, Vice President Al Gore on Monday
acknowledged his mistakes and embraced a series of campaign finance
reforms intended to curb special-interest money coursing through
the political system.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of those changes, which the presumptive
Democratic presidential nominee unveiled in Wisconsin, would be the
creation of a $7.1 billion endowment fund that would be tapped to
pay for congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also proposed ending unregulated soft money, prodding
television stations to offer free time for candidates, forcing
outside groups who run political ads to disclose their funding
sources, and mandating that lobbyists file monthly reports
detailing their legislative activity.
</P>
<P>
   In an address at Marquette University in Milwaukee, Gore sought
to turn a political liability into an advantage by confessing his
past errors, linking himself to John McCain and other reformers,
and characterizing Republican opponent George W. Bush as a defender
of the flawed current system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I may be an imperfect messenger for this cause,'' Gore
said.``But the real wounds will be to our democracy itself unless
we address this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his proposals were intended to reverse the growing
amount of money pumped into campaigns to influence legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., standing by his side, Gore
said his first act as president would be to submit the campaign
reform legislation sponsored by Feingold and McCain. That
legislation includes the elimination of soft money, the unlimited
contributions given to political parties, which is intended for
party building but which has been increasingly used to help elect
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would veto the McCain-Feingold measure.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans dismissed the proposals as more big government and
repeated their contention that Gore has no credibility on the issue
as long as he refuses to explain his past and current fund-raising
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's pitch comes even as he crisscrosses the nation helping
the Democratic National Committee raise millions of dollars and as
Republicans ratchet up their criticism of his past actions,
including his 1996 attendance at a fund-raiser at a Buddhist
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Bush said that ``any promise to reform
our campaign finance system will ring hollow unless it is grounded
in credibility.'' He also characterized the Gore blueprint as ``a
taxpayer-financed government takeover of campaigns that replaces
individual spending decisions with decisions made by an unelected
government committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore are competing for independent voters who were
drawn to the campaign finance message of Republican McCain and
Democratic Bill Bradley in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lewis, who heads the Center for Public Integrity, called
Gore's proposals, ``one of the most elaborate and extensive plans
for cleaning up politics that we've seen in recent years by anyone,
including McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis said because of the vice president's past questionable
behavior he was unsure whether Gore was sincerely interested in
making changes or looking for short-term political cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is there are two Al Gores,'' said Lewis.`` There
is a good Al Gore and a bad Al Gore. There is the Boy Scout and
intense competitive pragmatic who would step over his grandmother.
Today we got the Boy Scout.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis and others said that Bush does not have the record to
credibly challenge Gore on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has never been enthusiastic about campaign finance
reform, Bush was pressured during the primaries to roll out a
modest series of changes, including the elimination of soft money
contributions from corporations and unions but not from
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also recommended more than tripling the
amount individuals can give to candidates in order to keep up with
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore slammed his rival's proposals, saying, ``Believe it or not
Governor Bush wants to open the floodgates even wider to special
interests donors and big money.'' .
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Gore has gone further than Bush in embracing
McCain's ideas, and praised the Arizona senator several times in
his Milwaukee speech.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, McCain said he welcomed ``any good-faith
proposal to reform our broken campaign finance system.'' But he
added, ``the vice president needs to back his action with
meaningful bipartisan action, as well as call for a complete and
open investigation of 1996 campaign finance irregularities.''
</P>
<P>
   The most innovative piece of Gore's plan is his proposal to
supplant the current system of private fund-raising with public-
private financing for congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   The general election for presidents is already financed by
taxpayers, with the revenue raised through the voluntary check-offs
on the income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for general elections for House and Senate seats, Gore
proposed the establishment over seven years of a $7 billion
endowment fund, financed by voluntary and tax deductible
contributions from corporations, unions, individuals and other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates would then be able to draw on the interest income
from the fund to wage their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The allocation would be based on a formula that takes into
account factors such as the cost of past races, population and
media markets in each district.
</P>
<P>
   A board, appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate,
would allocate the funds.
</P>
<P>
   One campaign finance analyst questioned whether it was realistic
to expect that most individuals and groups would contribute to a
fund that parcelled out money on a bipartisan basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the motivation or the incentive for these groups to
participate if they cannot designate where the money goes to?''
said Sheila Krumholtz, the research director for the Center for
Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
