<HEADER>
A9634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      03-27 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISCALCULATIONS BY BOTH SIDES SEEN IN FAILED CLINTON-ASSAD TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, was ``immovable''
during his meeting with President Clinton in Geneva, and appeared
to have come with the misconception that Clinton was in a position
to give him what he wanted from Israel, a senior administration
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration knew the meeting was a gamble, but believed
it had a better chance of success than proved to be the case, one
diplomat familiar with the lead-up to the meeting and its aftermath
said.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting, Assad gave what amounted to a lecture to
Clinton on the history of the border between Israel and Syria, the
main sticking point between the two sides, the senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had hoped that the encounter on Sunday between
the two leaders, the first in more than five years and a rare
foreign trip for the ailing Syrian, would produce enough common
ground for talks to renew between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Assad was obstinate in his long-held view that there
must be full Israeli withdrawal to the June 4, 1967, Israeli-Syrian
frontier that existed before the Six-Day War. In recent talks with
Israel, Syria insisted on the return of land before holding any
other negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Israelis have suggested a willingness to
return the Golan Heights, but stop short of having Syria back at
the water's edge at the lake of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's meeting, officials here and in the region assert
that the Syrian track of the Middle East process appears all but
dead, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the focus in Israel has switched to the unilateral
withdrawal of Israeli troops from the security zone in southern
Lebanon, and to getting the Palestinian talks into higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Israeli Prime Minister, Ehud Barak, moves toward
taking Israeli soldiers out of Lebanon without an agreement with
Syria, instability in Lebanon is likely to mount, draining any
momentum out of the peace process, diplomats in the region said.
</P>
<P>
   After the three hours of talks in Geneva, administration
officials insisted that the meeting had still been useful gamble,
because it was impossible to know whether the Israeli-Syrian track
could become unstuck without a face-to-face meeting of Clinton and
Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was able to move him in the past, to get this
whole process started,'' said the senior administration official,
referring to the talks that opened in January in West Virginia but
then broke off.
</P>
<P>
   But from the opening moments of Sunday's session, it appeared
clear to the Americans that Assad was not going to bend.
</P>
<P>
   Assad was described as the most implacable person in his
delegation, which also consisted of Abdul Raouf Al-Qasem, his
national security adviser; Riad Daoudi, his legal adviser; and
Farouk Al Shaara, the Syrian foreign minister, who led the talks in
Shepherdstown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   The administration knew it was playing a high-stakes poker game
with Assad: that with momentum for a peace agreement stalling, and
Clinton's lame-duck stature looming, the gains could be high, but
the losses could be enormous, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But there appeared to be a miscalculation in Washington, a
diplomat familiar with the process with the Syrians said. ``They
thought the chances of winning were greater,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House seems to have believed that Assad would show
some flexibility on the all important June 4, 1967, line: Assad is
demanding that Israel fully withdraw from the land it seized from
Syria in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a flawed notion that Assad would be flexible. ``He
would rather die than not get full withdrawal,'' an Arab official
said Monday of Assad. ``He hasn't changed his mind in 30 years, and
he is not going to change his mind in a couple of hours in
Geneva.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the meeting, the national security adviser,
Samuel R. Berger, said there was no certainty of a positive
outcome. But he portrayed a situation in which Clinton would
explain to Assad ``why he believes that negotiations can resume in
a serious fashion,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely result, Berger predicted, was that Assad would
return to Damascus, that Clinton would confer with Barak and on the
basis of those conversations a ``serious round'' of talks would
begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
