u k BC-EDIT-POWER-PLANTS-NYT     03-27 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POWER-PLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRESSURING THE POWER PLANTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 28:
</P>
<P>
   Each new day seems to bring further proof that something must be
done to limit the pollutants that originate in the coal-fired power
plants of the Midwest and are carried by air currents into the
Northeastern United States, where they contribute mightily to urban
smog and acid rain. The latest evidence is a survey conducted by
the General Accounting Office. It found a big reduction in one of
the pollutants, sulfur dioxide, but a dramatic rise in another
pollutant, nitrogen oxide, which is accelerating the decline of
many Northeastern lakes and streams, particularly in New York
state's Adirondacks region.
</P>
<P>
   The report is one more reason for state and federal officials to
keep pressing their legal and regulatory efforts to force the
Midwestern polluters to clean up their plants. It also sends an
important signal to Congress, which has two opportunities to
address the problem. One is a bill sponsored by three New Yorkers _
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat, and Reps. Sherwood
Boehlert and John Sweeney, Republicans _ that would require a 50
percent reduction in nitrogen oxide emissions below those required
by the 1990 Clean Air Act. The other is a broader effort by
Boehlert and like-minded Democrats to require stiff new controls on
dirty power plants as part of any bill deregulating the utility
industry. Such a bill would be aimed not only at reducing pollution
but at leveling the playing field in an industry where dirty power
tends to be cheaper than clean power.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' responsibility here arises from the fact that the 1990
act did not fully address the complex sources of acid rain, which
has been killing off fish in Adirondack waterways for many years.
At the time, sulfur dioxide was believed to be the overwhelming
cause of acid rain, so the act not only mandated sharp sulfur
dioxide reductions nationwide but set up an innovative emissions
trading scheme that great reduced industry's costs of compliance.
By contrast, the act gave industry a more leisurely timetable for
reducing nitrogen oxides, and also spared hundreds of the oldest,
dirtiest power plants from tough new controls in the false
expectation that they would soon be retired.
</P>
<P>
   Power industry officials contend that because the nitrogen oxide
requirements of the 1990 Clean Air Act did not kick in until 1996,
more time is needed to study their effects before imposing tighter
standards. But the 1990 requirements still need strengthening, if
only because they do not address the older, ``grandfathered''
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also asserts that reducing emissions from
coal-burning utilities will not solve the problem because one-third
of the nation's nitrogen oxide comes from cars and trucks. But even
if such vehicle emissions made a big difference in the Adirondacks,
for which there is little evidence, that is no reason not to
tighten controls on the utilities. It is past time for these
companies to start cleaning up. If they will not, Congress should
make them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
