<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORDOVA ENDS UP WITH THE BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ It was the shortest goodbye of the spring. Marty
Cordova packed his bags Sunday morning, wished the Red Sox luck,
and then said he was off to sign with either the Yankees or Blue
Jays. Twenty-four hours later, he was in uniform, greeting the team
he had just left.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox played the Blue Jays Monday at Dunedin Stadium. When
they got here, they saw Cordova in Jays garb, wearing No. 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised to see him,'' Sox manager Jimy Williams said.
``I didn't know he was coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova signed a one-year deal with the Jays. If he makes the
team, he will be a fourth or fifth outfielder. Toronto is committed
to a starting outfield of Junior Cruz, Shannon Stewart, and Raul
Mondesi. Cordova thought he would have a similar role with Boston,
but the team did not put the 30-year-old outfielder on its 40-man
roster. As a result, Cordova's two-year contract was not triggered
and, eventually, the Sox gave him his release and $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Cordova to distinguish himself during
Toronto's 8-6 win. In the first inning, Cordova _ who started in
left field _ made a diving catch of a Carl Everett liner. He also
had an error in the third. He was hitless in two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's off fast
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman had three hits Monday (single, double, home run),
boosting his spring average to .449. Offerman led off in a Sox
lineup that did not include Nomar Garciaparra, John Valentin, Trot
Nixon, Troy O'Leary, and Mike Stanley. The reconfigured lineup
featured Gary Gaetti batting cleanup and Donnie Sadler (who also
homered) playing short and batting ninth . . . The team didn't have
much to report on the status of Rod Beck. The reliever has a stiff
neck and may have to begin the season on the disabled list . . .
New Blue Jay Mondesi hit two home runs to left field. On both of
them, Sox left fielder Israel Alcantara never left his crouch as
the ball headed well over the fence toward a cluster of trees . . .
Garciaparra is one of the coverboys on the latest issue of GQ
Magazine. He is joined by shortstops Alex Rodriguez and Derek Jeter
. . . This was a homecoming for Williams. He has lived in this
small city since 1984 . . . There were eight home runs hit Monday.
Williams was asked if the number of long shots surprised him. ``Did
you see the hawk out there?'' he said. ``That hawk was pretty
good.'' Translation: There was a strong wind blowing out. Hawk or
no hawk, Carlos Delgado hit a tremendous homer to center that was
estimated at 450 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liquid diet kept 'em fit
</P>
<P>
   Protein shakes are the current fad among young and fit players.
Gaetti, who is 41, was asked about the fad when he was breaking
into the big leagues in the early 1980s. ``Hamms on tap,'' he said
with a laugh, describing himself and some of his beer-drinking
teammates . . . You could say that Everett had an interactive day
with the fans. Following batting practice, he was one of the few
Sox who stopped and signed autographs. A good cook, Everett used
the session to counsel some fans about food preparation. ``You've
got to know that mom isn't always going to cook for you,'' he said.
During the game, Everett lost control of his bat, and it went
flying over the first-base dugout and into the stands. The damage:
one spilled beer and one facial cut, which was treated with an ice
pack . . . Brian Daubach and Sadler hit their first home runs of
the spring. Jeff Frye made his second start in the outfield, went 2
for 5 and scored 2 runs . . . Williams stopped short of endorsing
lefty Sang Hoon Lee. ``The last two lefthanders he's faced with the
bases loaded, he's walked them both,'' the manager said. ``Just
being honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
