u s BC-GLF-SAWGRASS-BOS &LR;      03-27 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SAWGRASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON LETS HIS CLUBS DO THE TALKING IN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ He has visited ``hell on earth
before,'' so Hal Sutton wasn't about to back down from a few holes
of golf with anyone. Not even Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the greatest player in the game,'' said Sutton, ``but
you know what? I am not praying to him, so he is not God, for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton had used different sets of words to make that point
earlier in the week, and he was forced to do so again and again and
again as he stayed in the lead of The Players Championship at TPC
Sawgrass. Finally, after completing just the fourth wire-to-wire
victory in this prestigous championship by holding off Woods in the
rain-delayed final round Monday, Sutton had delivered his message
in a way that cannot possibly be misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got nervous as heck, knowing the big deal that had been made
(of going head-to-head with Woods),'' said Sutton, 41, after
finishing at 10-under 278 to beat Woods by a stroke and become the
oldest winner of this championship. ``But I am proud to have beaten
him. What else can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need to, because a bogey-free final round of 1-under
71 in which he hit 17 greens spoke volumes. The fact that it took
two days to complete and threw him into the trenches with arguably
the most dynamic sports personality in the world _ a player who has
been on a roll the likes of which golf has rarely seen _ made the
assignment that much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there Sutton was at 9 in the morning, holding a three-shot
lead over Woods and standing over a sand wedge from 82 yards to the
12th green. Sutton caught the shot heavy and settled for par, but
picked up a shot when Woods, whose day ended Sunday with his ball
on the green some 40 feet from the hole, three-putted.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had spent extra time making long putts before the round
resumed and approached his first shot of the day with confidence.
``I was sure of the speed and knew how important that putt was for
pace. It had the perfect pace.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the perfect line, for it rode too far left on a ridge,
missed the right break it needed to take, and fell hard left. He
pulled the 4-footer coming back and was now four back.
</P>
<P>
   That's a minor obstacle for a player who rallied from seven
shots down with seven holes to play (AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National
Pro-Am in February), a fact that Woods quickly reminded us of. He
stuck his shot within 5 feet on the par-3 13th to set up birdie and
cut the deficit to three. Then, after matching Sutton's pars at 14
and 15, Woods attacked the par-5 16th.
</P>
<P>
   He had not birdied any of the previous three par 5s in the final
round _ and wasn't thinking birdie here, either. Water runs down
the entire right side of the 507-yard hole and with the pin cut
back right, the safe play was the middle of the green and let the
slope funnel the ball toward the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Woods, however. He opted to ``slide a 5-iron in there''
from 195 yards and slide it did _ coming to rest 15 feet from the
pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was planning on him making that eagle putt,'' said Sutton,
to whom the 16th was a three-shot hole in soft conditions resulting
from Sunday night's heavy rain. ``I hope me planning on it didn't
force it in the hole for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful. That can be credited to a ``Tiger moment,'' which it
most certainly was. Knowing Sutton would make no better than par
(which he did), Woods understood the gravity of the situation, so
he opted to let the players on the nearby 17th tee hit. Then he
rolled the eagle dead-center to cut Sutton's lead to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made Hal work for it,'' said Woods, who shot 71 and has now
finished first or second in 10 of the last 11 PGA Tour events in
which he has played.
</P>
<P>
   At the island green 17th, Woods grabbed pitching wedge and took
aim 145 yards away at a flagstick cut front right over water that
had drenched many a player's dreams. ``The wind kept switching. I
felt a gust come up straight downwind so I shortened my golf swing
and played for the wind,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Only the gust, he said, died quickly and his shot landed on the
front of the green and spun back and sat down in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton was next to hit on a hole that is hated by many, though
no one denies its capacity for drama. ``There was no way I was
going to fire at that pin,'' he said, knowing he hade splashed one
in Round 3 to make triple-bogey and watch his four-shot lead shrink
to one. He negotiated his shot to the middle of the green, got down
in two to match Woods's par, and took his one-shot lead to the 18th
tee.
</P>
<P>
   It is the toughest closing hole these PGA Tour players
encounter, and for Sutton the task got tougher when Woods did the
unthinkable _ slam a 2-iron off the tee at a 447-yard hole. ``I was
really shocked when he pulled out his iron,'' said Sutton. ``I
thought to myself, `Maybe I ought to back off and hit 3-wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Sutton remembered who he is _ arguably the best
ball-striker around _ and from how far he had come _ a personal
life in turmoil and a professional game that had disintegrated so
badly he was embarrassed to be on the same range with his
colleagues. So he grabbed driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `I think I am one of the best drivers in the
game, so I am going to play to my strength,''' said Sutton, who
busted one down the right side and turned it beautifully in the
middle of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   It set up a 6-iron from 179 yards, which Sutton deposited some
12 feet below the pin, an easy two-putt to nail down the victory.
Woods had gone long with his approach and failed to chip in,
proving, as Sutton said, the kid was beatable.
</P>
<P>
   There was a $1,080,000 first-place prize, though the true source
of Sutton's happiness does not wear a price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of courage to play this golf course in
itself,'' said Sutton. ``Then, when you have got Tiger running
rampant out there, that makes it that much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But not so difficult that he was going to back down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
