<SLUG> BC-US-SURVEY-ADVISORY-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEW AMERICANS': A SPECIAL 9-PART `ECONOMIST' U.S. SURVEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   This nine-part package _ ``The New Americans'' _ on the changing
face of America is from the March 11 issue of The ECONOMIST
magazine. They are all coded to the ``k'' commentary category code.
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use _ free of charge _ by clients of The
Economist. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special
arrangement. For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OH, SAY, CAN YOU SEE?: IMMIGRATION IS RESHAPING AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-SURVEY-1-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1st of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950 census, America was 89 percent white and 10 percent
black. Other races hardly got a passing glance. Now Latinos account
for around 12 percent of the population; within the next five
years, they will overtake blacks to become the largest minority
group. This survey will seek to answer three fundamental questions:
Is the melting pot still working? Is it good for America? And how
will this latest wave of New Americans change their chosen
country?...By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Three trims, totaling 850 words; total uncut is 2,050) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIVE ME YOUR TIRED, YOUR CONFUSED: AMERICA'S IMMIGRATION
MUDDLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-SURVEY-2-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (2nd of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's immigration law is rather like a hedgehog: it has a
hard, prickly exterior, but its center is surprisingly soft. The
rules that govern immigrants' entry into America and their legal
status thereafter are, in turn, contradictory, disingenuous,
hypocritical, downright cruel and ridiculously overly generous.
Were they to be efficiently enforced, the result would be total
chaos...By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Four trims, totaling 1,050 words; total uncut is 2,075) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIVE STEPS TO HAVEN: GREEN CARDS IN AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-3-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (3rd of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other revolutions, America's ethnic make-over
officially dates back to 1965, when Congress dropped the hated
national quotas it had imposed in the 1920s. Instead, it brought in
quotas that favored family ties. In some ways the act was a
surrender to the status quo. Today, most immigrants fall into one
of five categories...By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO GAINS? NOT ONLY IMMIGRANTS, BUT AMERICA TOO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-4-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (4th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, most of the evidence suggests that the current wave of
immigration is good for America. But it is not good for everybody;
and the general benefits are often harder to identify than the
specific costs. Broadly speaking, though, most of the numbers
indicate that in the long term America gains from immigration _ but
that the immigrants gain even more...By John Micklethwait, The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 850 words; total uncut is 1,750) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MELTING POT: FROM HYPHEN AMERICANS TO AMPERSAND AMERICANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-5-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (5th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the hyphenated American (e.g., Mexican-American) giving way
to the ampersand one (Mexican &AMP; American)? A recent poll by the
Washington Post of 2,500 Latinos showed that nine out of ten who
have newly arrived in America think it is important to change to
fit in. But nine out of ten also think it is important to retain
part of their ethnic culture. With third-generation Latinos, this
proportion rises to 98 percent...By John Micklethwait, The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Four trims, totaling 1,050 words; total uncut is 2,100) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RAW DEAL: AMERICA'S SCHOOLS COULD SERVE IMMIGRANTS BETTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-6-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (6th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's learner is tomorrow's leader.'' The motto of Public
School 220 in Queens, N.Y., would do nicely for most New Americans.
Many of the notes pinned on the school's bulletin boards _ sample:
``Snowflakes are different, and so are we'' _ hint at the
challenges of trying to teach students who between them speak 26
foreign languages at home. Bilingual education is only part of the
problem, but it is indicative of the raw deal immigrants are
getting from America's education system...By John Micklethwait, The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS SLOWLY AWAKENS TO THE NEXT AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-7-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (7th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Latinos in America control around $300 billion of spending
power, and Asians another $100 billion. Yet immigrant groups
complain about being patronized or ignored by mainstream business.
This will change, if only because the newcomers, being young, will
play a growing part in setting the trends. As the editor of Latina,
a magazine for young girls, explained to Newsweek: ``Blacks said
`We will overcome.' Our motto is `We will overwhelm.'''...By John
Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING THE IMMIGRANT VOTE ISN'T EASY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-8-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (8th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Latino politicians in America are finding power elusive because
their supporters will not turn out at elections. Despite its large
Latino community, Los Angeles is still essentially run by Jews and
blacks. In national politics, Latinos make up only around 7 percent
of the likely voters, half the figure for blacks, but they may
punch above their weight in the presidential election later this
year...By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 275 words; total uncut is 1,200) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NORA, MARIA AND THE AMERICAN DREAM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-9-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Last of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to immigration, America has once again assembled a team
of people who have shown their willingness to compete and their
belief in the American Dream. Look around the United States _ not
only at the affluent Indian programmers in Silicon Valley and the
newly self-confident Latino middle class in Los Angeles, but at the
undernourished Uzbek children in Queens or the wretched Tejanos on
the Texas/Mexico border _ and you will find the drive is still
there. The rest of the country must not waste it...By John
Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
