<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AL-AMIN28-COX     03-27 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AL-AMIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin indictment possible today
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fulton County authorities are expected to seek a
murder indictment today against Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin and begin
the process of bringing him back to Atlanta to face trial for the
slaying of Deputy Ricky Kinchen.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes has indicated he won't begin extradition
proceedings until Al-Amin is indicted. The Fulton County grand jury
did not produce an indictment Friday but meets again today, its
other regular meeting day.
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, law enforcement officials say tests have shown
that the .223 caliber Ruger Mini-14 and the Browning Hi-Power 9 mm
pistol recovered when Al-Amin was arrested in Alabama are the
weapons that fired the shell casings found at the murder scene in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This gives prosecutors much stronger evidence to present to the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the tests, the only known evidence linkng Al-Amin to
the killing was an identification made by deputy Aldranon English,
who was severely wounded in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County, Ala., District Court Judge Lynn Bright set
April 12 for a probable cause hearing on the federal fugitive
charges on which Al-Amin is being held. In the meantime, she ruled,
Al-Amin will have to continue spending 23 hours a day in solitary
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he will have conditions more to his liking when he is
returned to Georgia is uncertain, because it has not been
determined where he will be held. Sgt. Clarence Huber, a spokesman
for the Fulton County sheriff's department, said it is unlikely he
will be kept in the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he is charged with killing a Fulton County deputy, this
would not be the best place to keep him,'' Huber said.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's lawyers have vowed to fight the extradition, and how
long it takes to return the suspect to Georgia depends largely on
how much time the Alabama court gives them to prepare their
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   After Barnes signs the order and sends it with accompanying
documents to the Alabama governor, he will pass it on to the
district attorney in Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney must then formally notify Al-Amin of the
charges against him in Georgia, and the fact that Georgia wants him
returned to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Assistant Attorney General Daryl A. Robinson
said, the suspect's attorney can begin his fight by filing a formal
challenge to the extradition papers.
</P>
<P>
   Only two issues can be challenged, according to the federal
Uniform Extradition Act: the validity of the extradition papers and
whether the man in jail in Montgomery is the one named in the
warrant or indictment.
</P>
<P>
   A judge will set a date that gives both parties time to prepare
their case, and that can be the single most time-consuming step in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Robinson said, the judge will rule at the conclusion
of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
