<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIST-ADVISORY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 25 March 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only for special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WATER: A SOLUBLE _ AND SOLVABLE _ PROBLEM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIVATIZE-WATER-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What could be more basic to life than a drink of water? Yet more
than a billion people have no access to safe water. Three times as
many lack adequate sanitation. World demand for fresh water is
expected to grow sharply, by 70 percent (for household use) by
2025. Shortages seem inevitable _ and even war. This dismal
reckoning lies behind the big world water summit held this week in
the Netherlands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAIWAN'S DARE, CHINA'S SCARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAIWAN-`ONE-CHINA'-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's election, which ended 50 years of Nationalist rule and
chose as the island's next president Chen Shui-bian, the candidate
of a hitherto pro-independence party, is a clear rebuff to China's
Communists, who claim Taiwan as their own. What will China do now?
The only solution remains for the two sides to decide together,
through negotiation, whether they are to be one China or two. But
as Taiwan changes and China grows ever more inflexible, that
becomes more difficult. Even if a crisis is averted this time, be
prepared for the next one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 225-word trim at 725; 1,075 words uncut) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREENSPAN'S DRIP-TORTURE STRATEGY IS DANGEROUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RISKY-FED-RATES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pour boiling water on a frog and it will jump away; heat it up
slowly in a pot of cold water, and it will die. America's Federal
Reserve, which raised short-term interest rates by another
quarter-point to 6 percent on March 21, may need reminding of this
tale. The Fed's strategy of slowing an overheating economy by
raising rates gradually might prove just as risky for America _ and
so for the world economy, as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EXTRAORDINARY MUTATION OF AMERICA'S SUBURBS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 'BURBS-AMERICANBEAUTY-ECONOMIST-550&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for Sunday's Oscars) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``American Beauty,'' the movie favored to sweep the Oscars
Sunday night, Lester and Carolyn Burnham (played by Kevin Spacey
and Annette Bening) live in a picture-perfect house in the suburbs,
with a manicured lawn and a white picket fence. Although ``American
Beauty'' is somewhat redeemed by fine acting, the film overall
recycles a tired cliche of suburbia _ that they are vortexes of
tedium and alienation _ which has been a staple of artistic
contempt at least since John Cheever. Actually, that view is
getting less accurate by the day, as the suburbs mutate in all
sorts of extraordinary ways. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 3 trims, totaling 225 words; 1,100 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIAMI VISE: FUMING TOBACCO INDUSTRY FACES JURY _ AND
BANKRUPTCY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO-EXTINGUISHED?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Miami and Tobacco-Industry States) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next month in Miami, the tobacco industry faces a jury decision
that could impose fines so vast that cigarette firms might end up
in bankruptcy. The upshot just might force debate about America's
``single most significant threat to public health'' into the forum
where it belongs, the Congress. But don't hold your breath. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MASSACHUSETTS IN HOT WATER OVER BOYCOTT. TEA, ANYONE? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MASS.-VS.-MYANMAR-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Mass. Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call it a case of states' rights vs. nations' wrongs. Little
Massachusetts is once again standing up for the democratic values
which it so boldly asserted before the American Revolution. Then it
boycotted English imports by tossing crates of tea into Boston
Harbor. Today the state is boycotting companies which do business
with Myanmar, home of one of the world's harshest military regimes.
Alas, two lower federal courts have ruled that Massachusetts's
well-intentioned foray into foreign affairs is unconstitutional. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STADIUM MUNIBOMBERS: FICKLE FANS, JOCKS FLOCK TO EVER-NEW
ARENAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOOMED-JOCK-PARKS-SE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade about half the stadiums in the nation
that house football, baseball, basketball or hockey games have been
replaced _ usually to lure new teams to a city, or in the case of
Seattle, to prevent the departure of existing teams. What's going
on? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LICENSE TO KILL: CHARGES KEEP ON TRUCKIN' AGAINST GOV. RYAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ILLINOIS-GOV-GUILT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Chicago Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like most good political thrillers, it seemed at first to be
just another tale of bureaucratic graft. In 1998, the Department of
Justice began in investigation of the Illinois secretary of state's
office that routinely sold drivers' licenses to unqualified truck
drivers. But three things have since made the story much more
explosive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TAXING DILEMMA OF E-COMMERCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAXMAN-INTERNET-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Internet currently displacing motherhood and apple pie
at the top of the list of American virtues, proposals to tax the
Net are not popular, indeed. But if e-commerce grows as quickly as
predicted, failing to tax it could do serious damage to the
finances of America's state and local governments, which depend on
sales taxes for much of their revenues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY: `AND THE WINNER IS...VLADIMIR PUTIN.' (ACT SURPRISED) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN-CORONATION-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sunday's election, Russia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even by old Soviet election standards, it has not been much of a
contest. Only the scale of Acting President Vladimir Putin's
victory Sunday is in doubt. Indeed, the most significant feature of
the election is not the railroaded result but the comprehensive way
in which the Kremlin has controlled the campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS BEREZOVSKY: KREMLIN PUPPETEER OR FUTURE PUTIN VICTIM? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BORIS-BEREZOVSKY-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sunday's election, Russia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Boris Berezovsky, Russia's oligarch-extraordinaire, see out
the year in jail, exile or the comfortable nook between business
and government that he currently occupies? The answer will give a
clear sign of where the country is headed under Vladimir Putin, who
is set to be elected president on March 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 650 words; 1,000 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `CHOLO' ALEJANDRO TOLEDO: PERU'S FAIRY-TALE CANDIDATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUJIMORI-RIVAL-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Timely for April 9 election, Peru) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political fairy tales are not unknown in Peru. In 1990, a
university rector named Alberto Fujimori rose from nowhere in the
final weeks of a presidential election campaign to trounce Mario
Vargas Llosa, a world-famous novelist. Now Fujimori is seeking a
third term in an election on April 9. He has seemed assured of easy
victory. Yet suddenly he has a serious challenger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERABEAM: THE NEXT TELECOMS GIANT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERABEAM-ME-UP-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to ground-breaking technology and ingenious new
Internet businesses, the `digerati' who show up for Esther Dyson's
annual PC Forum are blase to the point of weariness. That makes the
buzz caused last week by Seattle-based TeraBeam Networks all the
more remarkable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC APPEARS IN CONTROL OF OIL MARKETS. APPEARANCES DECEIVE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEC-SQUEEZED-ECONOMIST-800&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for March 27 OPEC meeting, Vienna) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oil has become a volatile substance. The world is producing
about 75 million barrels a day (b/d) of the stuff; it is consuming
about 77 million b/d. Nobody likes it that way. Producers and
consumers alike speak of their desire for stable oil prices. Yet
only in times of war or revolution has the price been wilder. Which
is one reason why, as OPEC gathers for its annual meeting in Vienna
on March 27, the hardest question is what will happen next? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,225 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
