<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-ACCESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR SECRETARY OUTLINES NEW PLAN FOR YOSEMITE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES with MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Long a victim of its own success, Yosemite
National Park would be returned to a wilder condition with major
reductions in parking spaces, roads and bridges and the elimination
of buildings and other structures in the park under a plan outlined
here on Monday by Bruce Babbitt, the secretary of the interior
</P>
<P>
   In the second attempt in two years to reduce the blight of
pollution and overcrowding that sometimes makes the roads in
Yosemite National Park feel like the Los Angeles Freeway, Babbitt
described a blueprint that would make major changes in the ways
visitors enjoy the park.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier plan led to major public opposition by proposing a
ban on most private cars in Yosemite Valley. The new plan is a
scaled-back version that calls for tearing out many parking lots
and roads in the eastern, most scenic parts of the valley, as well
as three bridges and the Cascades Dam, which interrupt the flow of
the Merced River.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would replace the parking lots with three new lots at
the edges of the park from which visitors would take shuttle buses
into the valley. Areas of the park that were destroyed by a New
Year's Day flood in 1997 would be part of the roughly 180 acres
restored to natural conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yosemite Valley is one of nature's most awesome creations,''
Babbitt said in a luncheon speech here at the Commonwealth Club.
``Over the years, roads and bridges and structures have been
constructed which, in some cases, have contributed to the sprawl
and crowding that visitors to Yosemite are trying to avoid. In
Yosemite, we're using the lessons and impetus from the New Year's
Day flood in 1997 to help adapt visitors to the needs and forces of
nature in the valley, rather than the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   With its 3,000-foot granite walls and world-famous falls and
views, Yosemite Valley drew nearly 4 million visitors last year.
</P>
<P>
   Love of nature and love of the automobile have collided head-on;
on peak days, rangers have lowered the gates of the park to prevent
more cars from entering. Air in the valley is on the edge of
violating Environmental Protection Agency standards, said Dave
Mihalic, the park superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, called the Yosemite Valley Plan, will undergo a series
of public hearings from Washington state to Chicago as well as
throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   In a preview of what seems an oxymoronic task for the National
Park Service to keep Yosemite fully accessible yet return it to its
pristine natural beauty, the plan drew mixed reviews from
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Watson, the western regional director of the Wilderness
Society, hailed what he called ``a significant reduction in cars,''
which he said would help restore the valley.
</P>
<P>
   But Friends of Yosemite Valley, which has sued the National Park
Service over the expansion of the Yosemite Lodge and the widening
of the major access road to the valley, said the plan did more to
retain Yosemite's profits than its nature. The group denounced the
plan's 1,600 new parking spaces, additional restaurant space, road
expansion and a diesel bus system.
</P>
<P>
   David Brower, a conservation movement leader who attended the
announcement, said, ``This plan has smoke, mirrors and hesitation
in it, and as we all know he who hesitates is lost, and is ready to
make a down payment on the liquidation of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Sierra Club, based in San Francisco, were not
happy either. They said the Interior Department should have
postponed the plan until after a separate study of the Merced River
was completed. Last year, a federal court judge in Fresno ordered
the study of the river, which runs through the heart of Yosemite
Valley, after the Sierra Club sued the Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no decision of record on the river,'' said Joyce Eden
of the Sierra Club, adding that the river plan should have driven
the valley plan.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen L. Hayes, a spokesman for the Mariposa County Visitors
Bureau, spoke favorably of the plan. ``I think some people can have
a really good experience by leaving the car behind and riding the
bus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the plan was based on the broad goals outlined for
the park 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those goals _ reducing traffic congestion, reclaiming natural
beauty, allowing natural processes to prevail, promoting visitor
understanding and enjoyment and reducing overcrowding _ could be
reached with considerable public help, Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will be available for public comment and review from
April 7 to July 5. The plan is available on the National Park
Service's Web site, www.nps.gov/yose/planning.htm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
