<HEADLINE>
JACKSON: GIVE HONOR ELSEWHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Disjointed and underachieving last year, on pace
for 68 wins this season, the Lakers are among the most improved
teams in the NBA. That's made an instant Coach of the Year
candidate out of Phil Jackson, even if he disagrees with the
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Jackson will probably get it because of the tremendous
job he's doing with the Lakers,'' said Orlando Magic coach Doc
Rivers, himself a strong candidate for the honor. ``(Jackson) has
gotten them to buy into the fact that you win with defense. That's
why the Lakers are a better team this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said several others are more deserving, pointing to
Rivers, Seattle's Paul Westphal, Philadelphia's Larry Brown and
Utah's Jerry Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are working with diminishing numbers and less
talent and probably driving their teams harder,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers and Jackson are most often mentioned as leading
candidates Jackson for obvious reasons and Rivers for taking a team
stripped of all its stars and putting it in position to make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give it to Doc Rivers,'' said Lakers forward Robert Horry,
``because we've got three high-profile athletes on our team, we
should win. They (the Magic) have a lot of no-name guys who are
stepping up, playing great for them. I think it's the way (Rivers)
has them playing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for making a dominant team out of Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe
Bryant, Glen Rice and Co., Jackson said it's ``the job you're
supposed to do'' and recalled the words of his former boss, Bulls
general manager Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Krause used to tell me a coach that gets a team that
should win 60 games and he wins 60 games, does his job. And that
was his way of telling me that I did the job that was expected of
me,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   MILESTONES: With a big surge in the final 11 games, O'Neal could
become the first player in 34 years to win both the scoring and
rebounding titles.
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain, then with Philadelphia, accomplished the feat
in the 1965-66 season, averaging 33.5 points and 24.6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is tied for first in scoring with Philadelphia's Allen
Iverson and trails only Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo in rebounding.
But Jackson wants to scale back O'Neal's minutes, which might deny
him the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be cutting more than anything else with
Shaquille, and even the rest of our players,'' he said. ``This is a
hard time (of the season). ... Everybody, I'm sure, was alerted
this week when Jason Kidd went down and (Arvydas) Sabonis had a
minor injury. ... Those are the kind of things that take a team
from playoff hopes to possible playoff eliminations.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
