<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE28-COX     03-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore's reform strategy faces test
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's proposal Monday for public
financing of elections drew ridicule from Republicans and
skepticism from some analysts. But the real test may be how it is
received by independent voters who are crucial to Gore's bid for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Milwaukee, Gore proposed tax breaks for
individual and corporate donors to a new ``Democracy Endowment.''
Funds from the trust would be used to finance Senate and House
candidates in general elections.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also proposed new regulations requiring
television stations to provide free air time to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged he was an ``imperfect messenger'' for campaign
finance reform, a reference to his own actions during the 1996
race. Gore telephoned contributors from his White House office _
becoming the subject of two Justice Department inquiries _ and
attended a controversial fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple in
California.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Monday that Gore's record, or lack of it, in
promoting campaign finance reform while he has been vice president
raised fundamental questions about his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Brookings Institution scholar Thomas Mann noted President
Clinton and Gore pledged to enact campaign finance reform when they
were first elected and had two years of a Democratic Congress to
accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a con,'' Mann said. ``They were never serious about
this. They moved reform forward in both houses while promising one
another that it would never become law. They don't have much of a
record on acting on this when they were in a position to do
something about it. There is a credibility issue here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has determined the most effective way to rebut the doubters
is to address the issue of campaign finance reform head-on,
pledging as he did Monday to make a ban on ``soft money,'' the
first piece of domestic legislation he would submit to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the doubts about whether I personally am serious
on campaign finance reform,'' Gore told students at Marquette
University. ``Although you will have to take my word for this next
point, I promise you that, if you entrust me with the presidency, I
will do more than try. I will lead. I will fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals would also facerough sledding among Republicans
in Congress, who have successfully rebuffed all major campaign
finance reform proposals during the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping a broken glass collection in the shower is a better
idea than Al Gore's ridiculous and contrived campaign finance
scheme,'' said Jonathan Baron, spokesman for Rep. Tom DeLay
(R-Texas), the majority whip. ``The idea that we are going to
create a new multibillion (dollar) bureaucracy, empowered by its
own investment fund, to underwrite, monitor and fund political
speech is simply ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has more immediate political motivations: namely,
inoculating himself against the allegations of fund-raising abuse
in 1996. He is also trying to woo the millions of independents who
voted in primaries for Republican and Arizona Sen. John McCain and
former Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, both of whom
promoted campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Gore's proposal serves to draw a sharper contrast
between himself and Gov. George Bush of Texas. While Bush also
favors banning unregulated soft money donations to political
parties, he opposes public financing for congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called Gore's proposal ``a taxpayer-financed government
takeover of campaigns that replaces individual spending decisions
with decisions made by an unelected government committee.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain issued a statement Monday that he welcomed ``any good
faith proposal to reform our broken campaign finance system.'' But
McCain also focused on Gore's credibility problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``To convince a skeptical public that his efforts are sincere
and not an election year conversion, the vice president needs to
back his words with meaningful, bipartisan action, as well as call
for a complete and open investigation of the 1996 campaign finance
irregularities,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, president of the campaign finance watchdog
group Democracy 21, said it remained to be seen whether Gore could
galvanize voters around campaign finance reform in the same way
McCain and, to a lesser extent, Bradley did. But Wertheimer said
the opening was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vice president is prepared to ... make the kind of
ongoing, clear commitment by which he would lock himself into
(reform) if elected, then I think he has the opportunity to regain
credibility,'' Wertheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   In crafting his proposal, Gore sought to create a public funding
mechanism that would overcome one of the central objections to
taxpayer-financed campaigns: that no taxpayer should be required to
contribute to a candidate whose views he or she does not agree
with. Gore's proposed ``Democracy Endowment'' would rely on
voluntary contributions from individuals and corporations, who
would then be able to claim a tax deduction for the donation. Gore
estimated the tax break could generate $7.1 billion in seven years,
enough to make the fund self-sustaining. After that, the tax break
would disappear. The fund would be administered by trustees
appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring lobbyists to submit monthly, detailed reports that
would include the names of officials being lobbied and the dates
and locations of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encouraging broadcasters to provide candidates five minutes of
air time each night in the 30 days before an election.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring broadcasters to provide equal air time to any
candidate who was mentioned in an issue ad aired on the station.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring organizations running issue advertisements 60 days
before an election to disclose their funding sources.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, who co-authored a book on campaign finance issues, said
the endowment was a creative idea but raised a fundamental
question: Why would anybody want to contribute to it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to sort of lay out a rationale for people to
contribute,'' Mann said. ``In general, people are inclined to
contribute to candidates or parties, not some endowment that
provides money to candidates they find utterly abhorrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokeswoman Kathleen Begala said the endowment would
attract donations from individuals and companies motivated by
public and self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
