<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY BILL AIMS TO IDENTIFY SEX OFFENDERS ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Frustrated that New Jersey courts have prevented
Megan's Law from reaching into cyberspace, Gov. Christie Whitman
introduced legislation Monday that would amend the state
constitution to allow officials to post convicted sex offenders'
names on an Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey began a national movement in 1995, when legislators
reacted to the outrage surrounding the murder of 7-year-old Megan
Kanka by enacting the nation's first law allowing the police to
notify residents when a paroled sex offender moves into their
community.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states now have similar statutes, and 16 states list the
names and addresses of paroled sexual predators on Web sites. But
New Jersey's Supreme Court, which has a history of judicial
activism, has demanded sharp limits on who can be notified, citing
concerns about vigilantism and parolees' privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey General Assembly passed a bill Monday to post
sexual predators' names and addresses on the Internet, but Whitman
said she believed that law would be struck down by the courts, so
she proposed the bold step of circumventing the courts by changing
the state constitution. ``We're always sensitive to the privacy
rights of individuals,'' Whitman said. ``But we are more sensitive
to the rights of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's constitution has been amended more than 150 times
since it was adopted in 1947, usually for bond initiatives and
other minor matters. The last time an amendment was used to
challenge a State Supreme Court ruling was in 1992, when voters and
legislators reaffirmed that the death penalty was constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional amendment would need the approval of two-thirds
of lawmakers in both houses of the legislature, and would then be
put on the ballot for voters in November. Even if the measure wins
approval, however, it could face a challenge in federal court,
because several recent rulings have raised concerns that Internet
sex-offender registries may go too far.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Jacobs, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union, said her organization was likely to challenge the
proposed amendment because it would subject convicted sex offenders
to punishment even after their prison terms ended. Under the
state's current policy, which notifies only those people who live
near a sex offender, there have been some incidents of housing
discrimination and physical threats, Jacobs said, including one
1998 case in which five gunshots were fired into a parolee's home.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said the new measure could also deter sexual assault
victims from reporting abuse by relatives, for fear that their
families might be subjected to public humiliation. ``One reason
attacks are not reported is the shame,'' she said. ``These laws
will do more to discourage people from reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman and many other New Jersey officials said they
believed that the benefits of publicizing sex offenders'
whereabouts far outweighed any drawbacks. The governor said the
state police had taken aggressive steps to prevent any vigilante
attacks and would intensify their efforts if the information was
made more widely available.
</P>
<P>
   The senate president, Donald T. DiFrancesco, said he supported
the governor's initiative because it would allow New Jersey voters
to decide whether widespread notification was appropriate. The
Assembly speaker, Jack Collins, whose support would be necessary
for any constitutional amendment to win approval, said he was open
to the proposal, but stopped short of endorsing it.
</P>
<P>
   Since states began posting sex offenders identities' on the
Internet, there have been some problems, but no reports of
vigilante attacks related to the Web sites, said Scott Matson, a
research associate at the Center for Sex Offender Management. The
most serious complaints in other states have involved incorrect
addresses being posted or juvenile offenders' names being included
with those of adults, Matson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been cases where people whose house was incorrectly
listed on the Web site end up getting harassed when they have no
criminal record at all,'' Matson said. ``It's mostly labeling and
verbal abuse, where they get called names.''
</P>
<P>
   In those states that have set up Internet registries, many
criminal justice experts have warned residents not to be lulled
into the false belief that they are fully apprised of the danger
around them. ``Up to 80 percent of sex offenders have never been
caught, so these Web sites have to be careful not to create a false
sense of security,'' Matson said. ``We try to remind people that
they still have to teach their children how to protect themselves
and watch for the warning signs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
