<HEADLINE>
FORMER FIRST LADY ROSALYNN CARTER URGES STRONGER EFFORTS IN
TREATING MENTAL ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS Knight Ridder Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mental-health treatment has come a long way,
but more needs to be done to ensure that people who suffer mental
illness _ and their loved ones _ get the help they need, former
first lady Rosalynn Carter said here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked in the mental-health field since 1971,'' Carter
said at a news conference before speaking at the Hyatt Regency
Crown Center hotel. ``At that time nobody would talk about mental
illness.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Carter said, knowledge of mental health and how
to treat mental illness has grown.
</P>
<P>
   But, Carter said, ``that stigma still exists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to when we didn't understand mental
illness,'' Carter said. ``To the time when we shut them away and
didn't want anyone to know about it. That kind of lingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, honorary chairwoman of the President's Commission on
Mental Health in her husband's administration, these days tries to
educate the public about mental illness through the Carter Center
in Atlanta. Her Kansas City visit was a fund-raiser for Truman
Medical Center's Behavioral Health Network.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is a proponent of national legislation to require health
insurance companies to cover mental illness on a par with physical
illness. Many insurance companies allow fewer doctor visits and
less time in the hospital, and require higher co-payments, for
people seeking treatment for mental illness, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no distinction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Increased access to treatment would mean fewer incidents of
violence among the mentally ill, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have those problems if we had the right kind of
services,'' Carter said. ``It all goes back to the lack of help.''
</P>
<P>
   That help should start early, Carter said. She suggested schools
should have mental-health professionals available for students.
</P>
<P>
   And that help should be available for the families of the
mentally ill, Cater said. Support groups, she added, are key in
helping people understand and help their mentally ill relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, chairman of the event, said it was
significant that someone as high-profile as a former first lady was
willing to speak out about mental health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give it attention that we would not otherwise get,''
Cleaver said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
