<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO HONG KONG VIA THE NORTH POLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lopping hours off flights between North America and Asia,
regular commercial jet service over the North Pole is to start July
1, the fruit of a growing partnership between Canadian and Russian
air traffic controllers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the ice curtain separating Russia and North
America started to thaw, regular transpolar flights are now on the
verge of becoming a reality as new long-range jets enter airline
fleets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have acted like a cheerleader on this,'' said Michael
Skrobica, a vice president of the Air Transportation Association of
Canada, an airline industry group in Ottawa. ``There is a huge cost
saving for airlines, much more convenience for passengers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is also the prospect of a bonanza in overflight fees for
Canada and Russia. If routed over the Arctic, a New York to Hong
Kong flight would save five hours and $33,000 in fuel and labor
costs over conventional routes, according to estimates by Nav
Canada, the nation's private, nonprofit air traffic control
authority. A Vancouver-New Delhi flight would save about four and a
half hours, and a Toronto-New Delhi flight would save almost two
hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Siberian shortcut would allow major savings in fuel and
passenger time for flights between the United States and Bangkok,
Beijing, the United Arab Emirates, Hong Kong and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as an experiment, Russia allowed Northwest to operate
a Detroit-Beijing polar flight and United Airlines to operate a
Chicago-Hong Kong polar flight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In February, we flew 24 days of 29 in the polar region,'' said
Gene Cameron, United's international dispatch manager. ``Between
United and Northwest, we are proving to the Russians that this is a
viable operation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polar routes have become possible because of a new generation of
Boeing and Airbus long-range jets that entered airline fleets in
the second half of the 1990s. In a new boost for polar routes, the
competing aircraft manufacturers have announced that in 2003 they
will come out with jets capable of flying fully loaded for 18 hours
_ the Boeing 777X and the Airbus A340-500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With these new, longer-range planes transpolar travel is going
to become common,'' said Michael J. Boyd, president of an aviation
consulting company in Colorado. ``The biggest growth market is
going to be in and out of China.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians, who see a gold mine in air-space charges, are
working closely with the Russians to upgrade Russian air traffic
control. Air space charges are based on weight at takeoff and
distance traveled over a country. For a New York to Hong Kong
flight by the regular east-west route through Canada, for example,
they are $1,825. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step is to staff enough of their facilities with
English-speaking controllers,'' said Sid Koslow, Nav Canada's vice
president for engineering. ``By the end of 2001, we hope they will
have the communications system in place to increase traffic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technical cooperation and aid in finding financing are part of
Canada's collaboration with Russia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Russian north, civilian traffic controllers are to be
concentrated at four sites that previously were largely dedicated
to military air defense. In Canada, air traffic control authorities
have started talking to Norad, the North American Aerospace Defense
Command, about adding commercial uses to existing air defense sites
in the Arctic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity to turn a sword into a plowshare,''
said Skrobica, of the Canadian airline industry group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With or without use of Norad sites, commercial jets will fly
over polar regions much the way they do over ocean stretches,
without radar coverage. In an international handoff system, planes
are tracked by reports of their timing, speed and direction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once North Pole routes are up and running, Canadian authorities
are confident that usage will steadily grow. Cathay Pacific has
already tested a transpolar New York-Hong Kong route. United would
like to try a Chicago-Shanghai transpolar route, and Air Canada,
Canada's largest airline, would like to test two transpolar routes
later this year, Toronto-Hong Kong and Toronto-Tokyo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
