<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-NAPSTER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Recording Industry Goes to Court to Battle Napster  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The recording industry went to court in San Francisco yesterday to
lay the legal groundwork to unplug Napster Inc., the controversial
San Mateo startup that makes software that finds and downloads free
music off the Internet.
<P>
   However, attorneys for the Recording Industry Association of
America, who called Napster a copyright ``infringement machine,''
conceded the earliest they could obtain a federal court injunction
to halt the firm's operations would be early June.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, Napster has gained millions of fans, particularly
college students with high-speed Internet access to download the
free program.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the RIAA filed suit against Napster on behalf of
A&AMP;M Records and several other top records labels that are members
of the Washington, D.C., trade organization, saying Napster
encourages rampant violation of copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   Napster denies the claim, saying the actual act of sharing songs
is done by customers. The firm insists its relationship with its
customers comes under the protection of the 1998 Digital Millennium
Copyright Act.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, in the first hearing since the filing of the suit,
the RIAA took steps to seek a preliminary injunction from U.S.
District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel to halt Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the RIAA asked Patel to speed up the normal
process to obtain internal documents and information from Napster
to support the injunction request.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Patel, who will rule on the case, said she
has downloaded a copy of Napster to see what the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   Patel, who did not issue a ruling and gave no clear indication
which way she was leaning, said she couldn't find the jazz and
classical songs she sought.
</P>
<P>
   She asked RIAA attorney Russell Frackman of Los Angeles if the
issues were similar to the motion picture industry's concerns about
video-tape machines in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this as much ado about not as much as you think it is?''
Patel asked.
</P>
<P>
   Patel grilled attorney Lawrence Pulgram for nearly an hour about
how Napster works. At one point, she questioned Pulgram's assertion
that Napster was trying to help new unknown artists get exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see much of anything that didn't seem recognizable,''
Patel said. ``These are not new artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Patel said she would hold a conference call with attorneys for
both sides sometime before the next court date on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. copyright laws, it is legal to copy compact
disc music for personal use, but not to give it to others. Napster,
however, denied that it was encouraging piracy, arguing instead
that the program only has created an online community of music
lovers who are free to share songs.
</P>
<P>
   The Napster program, written by a 19-year-old college student
who was frustrated looking for MP3 formatted songs on the Internet,
can search and download a specific song from the hard drives of any
of the thousands of computers that are also logged into the same
Napster server.
</P>
<P>
   The program has become so popular among college students that
about 100 universities around North America had to ban or restrict
use of Napster to keep their Internet access lines from becoming
clogged by music swappers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
