r f BC-BE-BE_SFCHRON &LR;      03-27 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BE-BE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Be Inc. Playing `Open Source' Card With Its Latest
Operating  System 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Be Inc. hasn't had much luck in winning over Windows users to its
alternative, multimedia-oriented PC operating system, but the
quixotic Menlo Park company isn't giving up just yet.
<P>
   Today, Be plans to release a new version of its system, BeOS 5,
in both a free, downloadable Personal Edition and a more advanced
Professional Edition, which will sell for $64.95. In addition, the
company will make the programming instructions that create its
system's look and feel available to other programmers on an ``open
source'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100,000 users have registered for the downloadable
version since it was unveiled in January, according to the company.
The system has gained a small but enthusiastic following, mainly
among ``content creators'' who value its ability to handle digital
audio and video far more smoothly and efficiently than Windows
does.
</P>
<P>
   Be, founded in 1990 by former Apple President Jean-Louis Gassee,
originally developed its operating system to run its own hardware,
which it first released in 1996. The company quickly abandoned the
hardware business, though, and ported its operating system first to
the Apple Macintosh, then _ with funding from Intel _ to standard
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous versions, BeOS 5 won't require PC users to
partition their hard drives between Windows and the Be environment
or to restart their machines to switch from Windows to BeOS. The
new version can be installed under Windows, in one large file that
looks like just another Windows application.
</P>
<P>
   When you want to use it, you'll simply have to double-click the
BeOS icon. At that point, Windows will be unloaded from memory and
Be will take over. It will still be necessary to restart to return
to Windows, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Professional Edition will include several new features
designed to attract fans of MP3 digital music, including programs
for encoding cuts from standard audio CDs into MP3 format and for
burning MP3 tunes onto writable CDs.
</P>
<P>
   While the Professional Edition will be available through retail
channels, it won't be distributed or marketed by Be itself. In the
United States, those chores will be handled by Gobe Software, a
Portland, Ore., company that developed the leading
productivity-software suite for BeOS. Hitachi will distribute the
system in Asia; several European distributors will be named soon,
according to Be.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Be has turned its attention to what it calls
BeIA, a version of its system designed for the stripped-down
Internet terminals known as ``information appliances.'' So far,
however, none of the many companies developing such devices has
publicly committed to using the Be software.
</P>
<P>
   Be hopes that the new release of its PC operating system, both
versions of which include programming tools, will attract
developers to BeIA.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, we look at the Personal Edition in
particular as a promotional tool for what we're doing in
appliances,'' said Frank Boosman, Be's vice president of marketing
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Catching developers' eyes is also the goal behind Be's plan to
release the source code for Tracker, its equivalent of the Windows
desktop or Mac Finder, and the Deskbar, its answer to the Windows
Taskbar. The license under which Be will offer the code will allow
developers not only to create enhancements, but also to incorporate
Be's code into their own commercial products. In contrast to the
licensing terms most commonly used in the Linux world, Be's terms
won't oblige developers to return their enhanced code to the
community or to Be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem they've got is that there isn't a lot of room for
a another alternative-to-Microsoft OS, now that Linux has taken off
and the Mac is doing better,'' said Rob Enderle, an analyst with
Giga Information Group. ``BeOS gets lost in the noise. They
desperately need a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Kusnetzky, vice president of system software research at
International Data Corp., said Be's reorientation toward
information appliances could open new opportunities for it, even
though it faces formidable competition from Linux, various Windows
offshoots (including ``the OS formerly known as Windows CE'') and a
variety of lesser-known alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the person in the street, or businesspeople, about
BeOS, they have no idea,'' Kusnetzky said. ``But the embedded OS
market offers at least some hope, because you can't yet point to a
clear winner there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at norrh(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
