<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ANDRONICOS-ANDRONICOS     03-27 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDRONICOS-ANDRONICOS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Andronico's the Latest to Target Those Too Busy to Cook  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Andronico's Market is throwing down the gauntlet in the highly
competitive world of gourmet-to-go.
<P>
   The supermarket operator, headquartered in Albany, has developed
a hybrid grocery/prepared-food outlet that opens next month in
Emeryville.
</P>
<P>
   Called Andronico's Central Market, the store is the retail
world's latest stab at the fast-growing category of ``home meal
replacement,'' which is distinct from fast food in that it
generally includes a warm entree and home-style side dishes rather
than a sandwich and french fries.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant take-out sales topped eat-in sales for the first time
in the mid-1990s, according to NPD Group, a research firm. So there
is a good deal of money to be made catering to folks who want a
nice meal at home, but don't want to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Meals-to-go are commonly sold by supermarkets or quick-serve
restaurants such as Boston Market, which specializes in rotisserie
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   But few food purveyors have found a formula that profitably
combines the quality of sit-down restaurant fare with convenience,
an appealing selection, and reasonable prices. In the Bay Area,
labor costs can push prices so close to restaurant levels that
customers won't pay them, said T.J. Callahan, a senior consultant
with Technomic Inc. in Chicago, a restaurant consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have had a tough time resolving the logistical
difficulties of home meal replacement,'' Callahan said. Meals-to-go
misses include:
</P>
<P>
   _Boston Market's parent, Boston Chicken, the pioneer of home
meal replacement. Boston Chicken was recently bought by McDonald's
after filing for bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   _An ill-fated attempt by Chevron Corp. to open Foodini's cafes
adjacent to gas stations failed quickly after four stores opened
last year.
</P>
<P>
   _Eatzi's, a closely watched gourmet-to-go chain owned by Brinker
International, recently closed two of its six locations and took a
$4.5 million charge to earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarkets, meanwhile, have had trouble offering the quality
and variety people want, said Callahan.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico's ``are food people, and they probably have as good of
a chance as anyone of putting together the magic formula,'' said
Callahan. ``If they can manage the logistics of food quality and
price and labor, then they have a winning combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Andronico, the 71-year-old company's chief executive, noted
that Andronico's has been profitably serving up prepared meals for
almost 20 years in its supermarkets. The company installed a
central kitchen in each of its grocery stores in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Central Market, at 9,000 square feet, is about one-quarter the
size of a conventional supermarket. The interior is chicly designed
with stainless steel countertops, wooden shelving and high ceilings
supported by timber beams.
</P>
<P>
   A patio out front, decked with a water fountain and displays of
fresh produce and flowers, will seat about 100 people in fair
weather.
</P>
<P>
   At food stations lining the store, staff will serve up &LR; 
 &LR; made-to-order meals such as lemon grilled chicken breast or udon
noodle soup with a choice of meats and broths.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers will also be able to find grab-and-go containers of
everything from sushi to potato salad to moussaka. Most of the
edibles will be prepared in a central kitchen and bakery located
just behind the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Heading to checkout, shoppers will pass refrigerated cases of
imported cheeses, fresh seasonal fish and semiprepared meats like
kebabs. Other major grocery categories will include wine, organic
produce and bulk foods, as well as necessities like toothpaste and
toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico expects one-third of sales to come from
nonperishables, one-quarter from prepared foods, 17 percent from
produce, 16 percent from meat and fish, and the remainder mostly
from bakery and floral.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico declined to provide financial details about his
family-owned company. But he said sales are well above high-end
rivals like Whole Foods Inc., which racked up annual sales per
square foot of $661 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Central Market is expected to generate 25 percent higher sales
per square foot than Andronico's supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to be a really good second format for
us,'' said Andronico. Central Market ``could fit into several dozen
areas (in the Bay Area), not that we would want to operate that
many stores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Emeryville Central Market is located on busy Hollis Street,
one block from Ashby Avenue, a major thoroughfare between
Interstate Highway  &LR; 80 and Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollis Street area is in the midst of a takeover by dot-com
companies and loft-dwelling professionals, who will be the primary
customers at Central Market, Andronico predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really an urban-type concept'' designed for densely
populated areas, Andronico said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two years, Andronico's will move its headquarters
into the 220,000-square-foot former manufacturing plant fronted by
the Central Market.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico's is also building a distribution center in the space,
along with the bakery and kitchen. Future Central Markets and some
supermarkets will be supplied by those facilities, Andronico said.
</P>
<P>
   On the supermarket front, Andronico's plans is planning  &LR; a new
location in Walnut Creek, one in Cupertino and one elsewhere on the
Peninsula, Andronico said. The company also continues to fill
orders for troubled e-grocer Peapod Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carol Emert at emertc(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
