<HEADER>
A9679 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-PARENT-MANAGER-LA     03-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PARENT-MANAGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENT: FROM CROUCHING TO COACHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Mark Parent had stubble on his chin and sweat
under his cap as he walked off a Seattle Mariners practice field,
having bagged the last batting-practice ball and dragged away the
last protective screen at the end of a morning with the club's
youngest prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a difference, somebody suggested to Parent, between last
spring, when he was a player in the San Diego Padres' major-league
camp on the other side of the lavish Peoria Sports Complex near
Phoenix, and this spring, when he's a manager in the Mariners'
minor-league camp. Then, big-league luxury. Now, bush-league grunt
work.
</P>
<P>
   Parent shrugged as he click-clacked up a concrete path toward
the minor-league clubhouse. ``You know,'' he said, giving no
indication he was trying to be funny, ``as a backup catcher, you
feel like you're doing grunt work anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   At 38, preparing for his rookie season as manager of the
Lancaster JetHawks of the Single-A California League, Parent looks
back on a big-league career that rarely resembled luxury.
</P>
<P>
   He spent parts of 13 major-league seasons with seven clubs, not
including repeat engagements with the Padres and the Baltimore
Orioles, and never got into a World Series. He never held down a
starting job for a full year. Twice he was traded in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   He failed to hit his weight seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Which tells you two things about Parent.
</P>
<P>
   First, he's a big guy, 225 pounds on a 6-foot-5 frame the last
time he was measured for a big-league uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Second, his talent, which produced a .214 career average with 53
home runs in 474 games, will never get him confused with old
teammates Tony Gwynn, Juan Gonzalez, Cal Ripken Jr. and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't bother Benny Looper, the Mariners' director of
player development, who hired Parent in November to manage the
JetHawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, guys make better instructors who weren't all that
great at it themselves,'' Looper said. ``The real good ones don't
have to study it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact Parent stretched his big-league career from 1986 to the
spring of 1999 after seven full seasons in the minors
</P>
<P>
   told Looper something.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other parts of his game must have been pretty good,'' the
executive said. ``He must have been good in the clubhouse and a
good defensive player. From my perspective, he's got an excellent
background to be a manager. He's been a catcher, which is a
position that requires you to be knowledgeable about hitters and
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that giving him this job was somewhat of a gamble,
because he's never coached or managed. But the more I talked to him
and the more I heard about him from other people, the more I
thought he's got a chance to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent replaced Darrin Garner, reassigned in the Mariners
organization after the JetHawks finished 55-85 in 1999, embarrassed
at one stage to find themselves with the worst won-lost record in
professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He had turned down managing possibilities on the East Coast, and
said no when the Dodgers called about a roving instructor's job so
he could be within day-off driving distance of his home in Las
Vegas. He and his wife, Wendy, have two sons, Nicholas and Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite his concern about what the strain of managing will
do to his family life, Parent said he plans to throw himself into
the job of improving the JetHawks. The grounds crew at the Hangar,
the team's wind-swept ballpark, already knows it will have to get
the field ready for some late practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a job like this saying, `Well, let's see if I like
it ...' you're cheating yourself and you're cheating the guys,''
said Parent, who will make his managerial debut April 6 when the
JetHawks play at Bakersfield. ``I feel I have a bigger
responsibility as a manager or coach even than I did as a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, because I have experience and I'm not that far
removed from playing, they'll listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent, who retired shortly before the 1999 season, said the
lessons he picked up from seven organizations during 20 years in
pro ball are his most valuable assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of respect for the coaches and instructors I had.
I tried to take little bits from most of those guys,'' said the
Ashland, Ore., native, who broke in as a pro by batting .190 for
Walla Walla of the Northwest League in 1979. ``It helped me to have
a pretty good career. But that's over. For me it's time to give
something back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you don't get rich doing this job. The reward is
seeing guys get better. What percentage of these guys are going to
get to the big leagues? A small number. So if you can help them
achieve to the best of their ability, then it's up to someone else
to say, `You know, you're just not going to make it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can help them through my experience, with how I went
through it. If I was a young player, I'd want me to be my coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent admits he has a temper, and hopes to control it as young
JetHawks, inevitably, make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, by the same token, it's good to have it,'' he said. ``If
I had a manager who never snapped, I didn't think he gave a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Parent admits, too, that when he hung up the phone accepting the
job, he thought, ``Ah, s---, what did I do?''
</P>
<P>
   But now he's prepared to take his managing career as far as it
goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Lou's job,'' he said of Lou Piniella, the
Mariners' major-league manager. ``I don't want the Double-A job. I
want to do my job. But any job you take, if you don't think about
the ultimate, if you don't have goals, then you settle for things
too easily, you don't push yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do this one year and go home and start playing golf
again, fine. But as long as I'm doing this I want to get to the
highest level. I want my (players) to do the same.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
