<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERUVIAN LEADER CALLS ELECTORAL PROCESS FAIR DESPITE WAVE OF
CRITICISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Amid fierce criticism from opposition politicians
and independent monitors that he is trying to rig the country's
upcoming election, President Alberto Fujimori insists that Peru's
electoral process has been free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the emergence of a strong challenger in the April 9
election is proof of a level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori remains the favorite to win a third consecutive
five-year term. But last week, new polls indicated that economist
Alejandro Toledo, a former shoeshine boy who has wide appeal among
the poor, surged into second place and could force Fujimori into a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is proof that we have an electoral process in which
everyone has equal opportunities,'' Fujimori said at the government
palace in Lima. ``What we want are clean, transparent and
legitimate elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori also described opposition candidates as woefully
unprepared, and dismissed Toledo as an irresponsible populist. He
also warned that hyperinflation and guerrilla terrorism _ twin
plagues that his government largely stamped out over the past
decade _ could return if he is forced to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure that there is no backsliding on the
progress that we have made,'' Fujimori said Saturday night as he
sipped tea to soothe his throat following a series of campaign
rallies around Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Fujimori appeared on his way to an easy
victory, but his momentum may have stalled. A poll by the private
firm Apoyo put Fujimori's support at 37 percent, compared to 27
percent for Toledo. Seven other opposition candidates are also on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   If no candidate receives more than 50 percent of the vote, a
runoff between the two top finishers will be held in June. The
Apoyo poll showed that in a runoff between the two men, Toledo
would attract 44 percent of the vote compared to 43 percent for
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   For months, election observers have suggested that the process
is heavily weighted in Fujimori's favor because an array of state
resources have been used to promote his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They also have accused the Fujimori government of harassing
opposition candidates and of denying them meaningful access to the
media by threatening TV stations with tax audits and with pulling
state advertising if they provide as much coverage of opposition
candidates as the president.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an investigation by the Lima daily El Comercio
indicated that Fujimori's campaign workers had forged more than 1
million signatures to get him on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has expressed concern about pre-election
conditions in Peru. And last week, a report by the Atlanta-based
Carter Center said that ``irreparable damage to the integrity of
the election process has already been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Rospigliosi, a columnist for the Lima magazine Caretas,
said ``the level of confidence in the electoral process is less
than zero.``
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori argued that ``errors and excesses'' are being
corrected. He added that allegations of forged signatures would be
investigated but said that the practice is common among political
parties in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about pro-government tabloids that have printed lurid
accounts about his challengers, Fujimori called it a sign of a
vigorous free press.
</P>
<P>
   As for TV stations refusing to broadcast commercials by his
rivals, Fujimori said that there was little interest in the
campaign until recently and that station owners preferred to run
higher-rated programming instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been in the past two weeks that the election has
started to heat up,'' Fujimori said. ``A soap opera gets much
better ratings. But little by little, the stations are opening up''
to political spots.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail Saturday, Fujimori wore faded jeans and an
orange shirt. His 19-year-old son Kenyi, who is spending his spring
break from Kansas State University in Manhattan, Kan., to help his
father campaign, was dressed in sneakers and sweat pants.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to allegations of the misuse of state resources,
Fujimori traveled in a rented Kia four-wheel-drive, and he was the
only one in an eight-vehicle entourage that paid fares at highway
tollbooths in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from Fujimori's first campaign in 1990. Back
then, he was a little-known university rector who raised campaign
funds at chicken barbecues and barnstormed on a brightly painted
tractor to gain attention.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed to poor and indigenous Peruvians who viewed him as
an outsider, and they helped him defeat Peruvian novelist Mario
Vargas Llosa in a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to lead a country terrorized by Shining Path
guerrillas and ravaged by inflation running at 7,500 percent
annually. But the capture of Shining Path leader Abimael Guzman in
1992 crippled the rebel organization, and a free-market economic
program cut inflation and brought billions of dollars in foreign
investment to Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Fujimori was re-elected by a landslide over former U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar. But his second term was
marred by an economic slowdown and charges that his government
trampled on democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Fujimori maneuvered to run for a third-straight
term despite a provision in the 1993 Constitution that permits
sitting presidents to stand for re-election just once.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned about his authoritarian style, Fujimori replied
that when Peru had a more conventional democracy, nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think that democracy is simply holding elections
and voting. Our concept is that there must be equality of
opportunities,'' he said. ``My government has been called
authoritarian, but in what sense? Past governments that called
themselves democratic couldn't get anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 61 and divorced, Fujimori spends most of his time at the
government palace or touring rural areas. He is often described as
a workaholic and as addicted to the power of the presidency. But
Fujimori said that running Peru is an enormous task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do anything else besides this,'' he said. ``I like to
go fishing, but this is a full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
