r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     03-27 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Not All Funds Stagnate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I've heard that a mutual fund's performance can lag when it
becomes too large. Does that apply to index funds like Vanguard's
S&AMP;P 500 fund?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: As mutual funds grow larger, they often are forced to increase
the number of securities in their portfolios. That's mainly because
there are limitations on the percentage of any one company's shares
that may be owned by a single fund.
</P>
<P>
   The more that funds diversify, the closer to average their
performances are likely to become because their holdings will
increasingly resemble the overall market. That's a good thing for
investors only if the fund's performance was previously below
average.
</P>
<P>
   However, index funds such as the Vanguard S&AMP;P 500 are an
exception to the rule. Their purpose is to track a particular
index, and they only buy securities that let them emulate the
performance of that index. They are not trying to beat the index,
nor will they invest in a way that causes them to significantly
underperform it.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, size will not noticeably affect their performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard S&AMP;P 500 is an excellent case in point. With a tad
less than $100 billion in assets at last report, it is a close
second in size to Fidelity Magellan, the largest mutual fund of
all. Yet it continues to mimic the performance of the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index almost exactly.
</P>
<P>
   And that, by the way, is better than the great majority of
mutual funds have performed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Welcome Changes for IRAs
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: It is my understanding that in a traditional individual
retirement account, where untaxed contributions are allowed to grow
untaxed until distributed, the distributions are taxed as ordinary
income even if much or most of the increase in value results from
capital gains, rather than dividends.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that this takes some of the luster off the IRA. Why
can't the dividends and capital gains be separated out so you can
take advantage of the tax break on long-term capital gains? It
seems to me that the present system tends to favor investors who
own high-dividend securities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You understand the law correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Your suggestion for changing it would be welcomed by most IRA
account holders, but because it would reduce government revenues,
it might meet resistance in Congress. You ought to at least pass it
along to your congressman.
</P>
<P>
   I don't follow your argument that the present system necessarily
favors investments in high-dividend securities.
</P>
<P>
   Because dividends and capital gains are on an equal tax footing
in a traditional IRA _ that is, they are taxed at the same rate _
one is as good as another. So, you have to analyze each investment
on the basis of its potential total return _ price gain and
dividends combined.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a stock pays no dividends but is likely to
increase in price by 15 percent a year, it would seem to be a
better choice than one that pays a dividend of 8 percent but with
prospects for only a 4 percent annual price increase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Good Value Line
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in finding an investment that matches the
performance of the Value Line index. Can you suggest any?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: There are various stocks and mutual funds that track the Dow
Jones industrial average, the S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq 100, among
other prominent indexes. But the folks at Value Line in New York
say they don't know of any that track the Value Line index. Value
Line itself sponsors numerous mutual funds, but none of them is a
Value Line index fund.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the only way you can invest in the Value Line
index _ apart from buying shares in the 1,650 companies that make
up the index _ is through the futures market.
</P>
<P>
   A futures contract on the Value Line index trades sporadically _
it is by no means a popular issue _ on the Kansas City Board of
Trade. Each contract is worth 100 times the index value, or
somewhat more than $100,000 at recent price levels.
</P>
<P>
   If you are hot to own the Value Line index, you can buy one
contract by depositing at least $7,490 on margin with a futures
broker. However, bear in mind that futures trading is extremely
risky. If the value of the index moves against you by 75 points, or
roughly 7 percent, that will wipe out your margin deposit.
</P>
<P>
   For those readers who are unfamiliar with it, the Value Line
index consists of a broad mix of blue-chip, mid-cap and
small-company stocks. Unlike the S&AMP;P 500 or the Nasdaq, it is not
weighted according to each company's total market value. Instead,
each company gets equal weighting.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Value Line index has performed somewhat better
than the Dow and S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(AT)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
