<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATINBANK-SUMMERS-1ST     03-27 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINBANK-SUMMERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES NEEDED TO BETTER COMBAT POVERTY IN LATIN AMERICA, U.S.
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recasts lede, adds more from Summers interview throughout,
protests at today's meeting, quote from Mexico's finance minister;
no pickup.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers called Monday
for sweeping changes in the way international aid agencies try to
combat poverty in Latin America, amid signs that robust economic
growth there has left more people behind than many economists
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, speaking to Latin American finance ministers and
development experts at the annual meeting of the Inter-American
Development Bank, said the United States wanted the bank to conduct
a full review of its lending programs, to raise the interest rates
it charges its wealthiest borrowers and to adopt more effective
ways of raising education levels and fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based bank, financed by leading industrial
nations, makes about $7 billion in development loans to Latin
America each year. Along with lending by the World Bank, it is the
main vehicle for the United States and other wealthy nations to
help alleviate poverty in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and other major Latin American
countries have all grown faster in the last year than most
economists had anticipated. They recovered swiftly from financial
crisis, and bank officials estimated Monday that the region would
grow at a pace of 3 percent to 4 percent in 2000, compared with an
estimated 0.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the recession erased some progress in fighting poverty from
the boom years of the early and mid-'90s, and inequality has
remained stubbornly high _ increasing by some measures. The
situation has frustrated international financial officials, who
expected that Latin America would follow the pattern of the Asian
recovery and that rapid economic growth would lift all boats and
ease social tensions more than it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America's economic success in recent years has not been
associated with a reduction in inequality,'' Summers said in an
interview. ``The pressing economic problem for Latin America is to
create an environment in which all people have a chance to benefit
from growth.''
</P>
<P>
   A study by the U.N. Economic Commission for Latin America found
that 15 percent of the region's people live in extreme poverty, a
level it said had barely budged in two decades. And the
Inter-American Development Bank released a report saying that 150
million people in the region live on $2 a day or less, and that the
gap between rich and poor widened in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This persistent income gap, some fear, may threaten the
consensus that has brought Latin American economies closer to world
levels in the last decade, especially at a time when globalization
is under attack by some labor unions and nongovernment
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the pressure against global integration comes
from interest groups in industrial nations, protesters in third
world countries argue that free trade and international financial
agencies benefit the rich at the expense of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Low-key demonstrations against the Inter-American Development
Bank occurred Monday. Three protesters slipped into the opening
ceremony for delegates, unfurling a banner that read ``Shut Down
the Bank,'' before they were evicted.
</P>
<P>
   Summers and many of the other finance ministers maintained that
high and sustained economic growth still constituted the best
antidote to poverty and had already improved living standards for
millions throughout the region. But they acknowledged that growth
alone had fallen short of achieving Latin American social goals,
and there appeared to be broad agreement that the development bank
should shift its priorities accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our countries are changing, our markets our changing and our
social needs are changing, so the IDB must also change,'' Jose
Angel Gurria, Mexico's finance minister, said in an interview. ``At
a time when most countries in the region have better access to
private capital, this should free up resources at the bank that can
be used for poverty programs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Summers noted that the Inter-American Development Bank had
already begun redirecting resources away from big projects, like
power plants, to support poverty reduction, he said that more could
be done. He declined to pass judgment on individual lending
projects, but suggested that some of the largest loans the bank was
considering, including one to finance a Brazilian dam, could
deplete capital that was better devoted to smaller, more specific
poverty-fighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is pushing the bank to establish performance
benchmarks that measure the effectiveness of its poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also urged the bank to conserve its resources in good
times to be better prepared to increase spending when times are
tough and the poor need help most.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are part of an overhaul Summers has proposed for all
the major lending institutions, including the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and regional development banks.
Summers has sought to blunt an attack on the IMF and the banks by
some members of Congress, who argue that they have outlived their
usefulness and may do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he said the World Bank should refocus its efforts
toward reducing poverty in the poorest nations and leave most
commercial projects to private business, particularly in countries
with good credit ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
