<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-JAPAN28-COX     03-27 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-JAPAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chasing the sun for historic opener
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Can you say ``Play ball!'' in Japanese?
</P>
<P>
   The major-league season won't open in Cincinnati or Baltimore,
as it has traditionally. Instead, the baseball regular season will
begin Wednesday in Tokyo, with the New York Mets and Chicago Cubs
opening a two-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans who want to see the first pitch on television will
have to get up early. The games begin at 5 a.m. EST and will be
carried by Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pureey boru!''
</P>
<P>
   Regular-season games have been played in Mexico, with the San
Diego Padres and Colorado Rockies opening last season in Monterrey.
But this is the first time regular-season games have been played
outside North America.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs and Mets players aren't all that happy about it, not even
after being promised $25,000 bonuses for making the long trip.
</P>
<P>
   Mets third baseman Robin Ventura tried to put as positive a spin
on the trip as he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense in sitting around and complaining about it,''
Ventura said. ``There's nothing you can do about it, so you might
as well enjoy it. They treat you great over here, but it's still a
long way to go to play a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets broke camp in Florida on Friday, took a flight to
Chicago and then boarded one for Toyko. The Cubs, who train in
Arizona, took a flight to Japan by way of San Francisco. The teams
traveled a total of 13,000 miles, with the flights lasting from 16
to 18 hours as the teams chased the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine managed one season in Japan. ``On
the flight, you look out and see the sun, then you sleep and wake
up and look out and see the sun,'' Valentine said. ``Then you eat
and look out and see the sun. It just follows you all the way
across. It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Valentine, the Mets were a logical choice to be
picked for the games. Sammy Sosa, who has hit 129 home runs the
past two seasons, and the Cubs make it a popular matchup. But the
Mets were supposed to be matched against the St. Louis Cardinals
and slugger Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire didn't want any part of the trip, however, and he and
his temmates voted unanimously not to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game is too international as it is,'' McGwire said last
week. ``It comes down to how much money they can make. Someone in
Japan paid Major League Baseball a lot of money. I know Major
League Baseball wants to do more internationally, but there's no
purpose in it. I don't agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig said, ``Mark McGwire and I have talked
about this. I look at this much differently. We hope this is only
the first of many such ventures. It is our hope and dream that the
World Series will be what the word connotes _ a true world
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yomiuri Giants beat the Cubs 6-0 in an exhibition game
Monday, while the Mets defeated the Seibu Lions 8-1. The teams
switch exhibition opponents today, then open the regular season
before a capacity crowd at the Toyko Dome on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, who was 22-4 last season for Houston, will throw
the first pitch for the Mets, designated as the home team for the
opener. Jon Leiber will pitch for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton brough his wife, mother, sister and brother along on the
trip. ``My dad's not too keen on that flying stuff,'' Hampton said.
``If he could drive, he said he'd come.''
</P>
<P>
   After the teams play again Thursday, it's back on a plane for
the long trip to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs play at St. Louis on Monday, while the Mets play their
home opener the same day against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment will be when you get back,'' said Cubs
first baseman Mark Grace, who played on an all-star tour of Japan.
``But it won't be so bad if we get a couple of wins. You're going
to see one (angry) human being if we come back on a 17-hour flight
with an 0-2 record.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
