<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-3COM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 3Com Plans Internet Device for the Home  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
3Com Corp., the Santa Clara company that launched the Palm, said it
plans to introduce an Internet appliance this summer that could be
``bigger than Palm.''
<P>
   Unlike the fast-selling handheld computer, which users can slip
into their coat pockets, the new 3Com device will likely be larger
and stationary. But 3Com said the device could give users access to
a wide range of information via the Internet and be simpler to use
than a PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the sort of appliance you might enjoy having on your
kitchen counter,'' Chief Executive Officer Eric Benhamou told
Reuters yesterday during a news conference in Cannes, France.
</P>
<P>
   A 3Com spokeswoman said the device is being developed at a
research facility in Rolling Meadows, Ill., near Chicago, and would
use the Palm's operating system. That means it should be possible
to swap information, such as an electronic Rolodex and calendar
information, between the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou told Reuters that the device should catch on ``much
more quickly than Palm because there is already a base of Palm
users _ 6 (million) or 7 million well-connected people who are
primed for the kind of product we are bringing onto the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Benhamou said it might be perfect for the kitchen, 3Com
spokeswoman Jan Rasmussen said it could really be used in any room
in the home. Rasmussen also said it wouldn't compete with the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   Like the new device, the Palm VII is also designed to access
news and other information on the Web. But unlike the Palm VII,
which uses a relatively slow wireless modem, the new device could
potentially tap into a superfast Internet connection, making it
easier to download graphics, video and other more elaborate
information.
</P>
<P>
   But 3Com was reluctant to share any more details about the
device, such as what it would look like, how much it would cost and
what products it would compete against.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough information to be able to make solid
enough analysis ... and revenue projections,'' said Merrill Lynch
analyst Michael Ching. ``It's just little snippets here and
there.''
</P>
<P>
   3Com also confirmed speculation that it could spin off a unit
that makes ``remote access devices'' to help Internet service
providers answer modem calls. Analysts estimated the unit has
annual revenue of between $800 million and $900 million. 3Com plans
to begin reporting the financial results separately starting with
this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a business that profiles very different from all the
other businesses that we are in,'' said 3Com spokesman Brian
Johnson. He added that spinning it off ``might be the right thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also made it clear that the move isn't imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta pick your moment,'' Johnson said. ``Is it ready to
go now? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Ching also said it wouldn't make sense to spin off the unit now.
Just last week, 3Com announced sweeping plans to refocus its
business, sell off some operations and jettison others. If 3Com
were ready to split off the Internet service business, Ching said
it would have made sense to unveil that move as well last week.
</P>
<P>
   3Com shares edged up 19 cents, to $67.19 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
