u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-27 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS: GORE NEEDS WOMEN VOTERS AT HOME; BUSH-LOG CABIN
FEUD CONTINUES; DEMOCRAT LEADS REPUBLICANS FOR KERREY'S SEAT;
`STUPID MISTAKE' IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Neb., Texas)  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE RACE IN TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore will need a substantial turnout of women
in his home state in November, according to a new poll, because the
gender gap so visible across the country is also a major factor in
Tennessee. The Mason-Dixon poll shows that while women in Tennessee
favor Gore by a margin of 20 points over Gov. George W. Bush, men
prefer Bush by an 8-point margin. Overall, Gore leads Bush, 47
percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent undecided. The poll,
conducted 10 days ago, has a margin of sampling error of 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ANGERS GAY GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Republican Party's most prominent gay rights
organization criticized Bush Monday for refusing to meet with them.
Leaders of the group, the Log Cabin Republicans, have been pressing
for a meeting with Bush since last spring, and at times Bush has
hinted that he might meet with them. But in recent weeks he has
demurred, saying that the group's leadership had supported his
former rival, Sen. John McCain. ``We think that's shortsighted,''
said Richard Tafel, executive director of the Log Cabin
Republicans. ``We are exactly the people he should be meeting with.
A lot of McCain people are watching the Bush campaign wondering if
they want us back, whether we will be welcome in the party.'' A
spokesman for the Bush campaign, Scott McClellen, said Bush would
probably not meet with leaders of the group because they had
continued to ``politicize'' the question of whether there would be
a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   NELSON LEADS IN NEBRASKA
</P>
<P>
   In the contest to fill the seat of Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska,
a Democrat who is retiring, former Gov. Ben Nelson, also a
Democrat, leads the six potential Republican nominees, according to
a poll by The Omaha (Neb.) World-Herald. Even though the state is
considered overwhelmingly Republican, Nelson would defeat each of
the Republicans by a margin of more than 2 to 1, the poll found.
The leading Republican in the poll, state Attorney General Don
Stenberg, has been an outspoken opponent of abortion,
characterizing certain procedures as something close to
infanticide. The poll found that Nelson had a favorable rating of
71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE'S VOTING `MISTAKE'
</P>
<P>
   James Epperson faced no opposition in the March 14 Republican
primary for his county commissioner seat in Edwards County, Texas,
so he crossed over to vote in the Democratic primary. But now,
because he voted in the Democratic race, Epperson cannot run for
his own seat as a Republican in November, according to Texas state
election laws. Republican Party officials can name a new candidate
for the general election, but so far they have declined to comment
on their plans. From his ranch 150 miles west of San Antonio,
Epperson told The San Antonio Express-News: ``I just made a stupid
mistake. That's all it boils down to.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Reston, Va., and Parsippany and Manville, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No public events.
</P>
</TEXT>
