<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-TPC28-COX     03-27 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sutton convinces himself, and beats Woods by 1
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ It has been a pain-or-pleasure journey
for Hal Sutton, the 41-year-old Louisianan once burdened with the
label of ``the next Jack Nicklaus.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when Sutton's swing vanished and he tumbled
down the PGA Tour money list, he was embarrassed to hit balls on
the practice range next to his fellow professionals. When he missed
a shot badly in competition, either side of the gallery might have
had to scramble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to hell on earth before,'' Sutton said. ``My game
went to the bleakest, blackest spot you can think of.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday in the The Players Championship at Sawgrass, Sutton
defeated Tiger Woods, golf's dominant player, for a
start-to-finish, one-stroke victory in the rain-delayed conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989-93, Sutton's swing was barely worth two cents and his
personal life, with a divorce, came apart proportionally.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton handled the pressure of ``the fifth major,'' a penalizing
target golf course and a head-to-head confrontation with the
world's best player. He closed with a 71 to finish at 10-under-par
278 and earn the richest first prize in golf, $1,080,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lead any golf tournament from start to finish is a dream
come true,'' said Sutton, who won the event in 1983, when Woods was
7 years old. ``But to lead The Players Championship from start to
finish and to be able to play in the final round with Tiger Woods
in the last group and to beat him head to head, I can't paint that
dream any prettier.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton had to hold off a classic charge by the 24-year-old
Woods, who was trying for an 11th victory in his past 17 PGA Tour
events. After Woods eagled the par-5, 16th hole to close within one
shot, the two players traded pars at the 17th. But Sutton clinched
the biggest victory of his career with a clutch 6-iron to the 18th
green, while Woods missed the green and then a birdie chip.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton conceded that he had to convince himself during the week
that Woods, whom he feels has been unrealistically deified by the
media, could be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods is not bigger than the game,'' Sutton said, ``and
you all (in the media) do a good job of making him bigger than the
game. ... The other night I thought, `Well, you know what? I'm not
praying to him, so he's not a god, for sure.' ... I mean, that
realization came over me like, `OK, he's just human just like I am,
so we can do this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything away from Tiger,'' Sutton said.
``He is the greatest player in the game, and he's done spectacular
things ... but if I bought into what you were saying (about Woods),
how could I convince myself that I could beat him?''
</P>
<P>
   Woods won $648,000 for second place, pushing his 2000 earnings
to $3,231,731, the third-best single season total in PGA Tour
history. Scott Dunlap earned the largest paycheck of his PGA Tour
career, $270,600, and finished in a tie for third at 4-under 284,
with Nick Price, Jeff Maggert, Colin Montgomerie and Robert Damron.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has finished first or second 10 times in his past 11
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed I didn't win, but at least I made
Hal work for it,'' he said. ``The key is always to keep putting
yourself in position. You put yourself in position enough times,
you're going to win your share.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton led by three shots when he and Woods resumed the final
round at the 12th hole. He expanded the lead to four when Woods
3-putted the hole for bogey. But at the 16th, Woods hit a 195-yard
5-iron to 12 feet and sank the putt for eagle; Sutton parred and
his lead was one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wasn't going to go without Tiger making his charge,''
Sutton said. ``He lives up to his No. 1 ranking all the time. I
can't say enough good things about Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
