<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-MICHSTATE28-COX     03-27 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHSTATE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cleaves tops among Spartans' pluses
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To know this Michigan State team is to love it _
mostly.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans do so many things well that it's easy to overlook
their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Izzo's team leads the nation in rebounding margin, 12.6 per
game over the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   It has two Wooden Award finalists, point guard Mateen Cleaves
and forward Morris Peterson, who has 1,500 points and 600 rebounds
for his career. The Spartans' off-guard, Charlie Bell, has
tendinitis in his knee but is a top player when he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Hutson, 6-feet-8 and 240 pounds, is tough inside, and
forward A.J. Granger averaged 18.5 points in victories against
Syracuse and Iowa State. The bench of 6-6 freshman Jason
Richardson, 6-8 Aloysius Anagonye and 6-9 Duke transfer Mike
Chappell helps.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Spartans play ugly at times and sometimes have trouble
scoring. They were embarrassed by Iowa State in rebounding 38-24.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the Spartans will be favored to win it all, starting
with Saturday's game against upstart Wisconsin, is Cleaves. The
senior is a difference-maker who has recorded more than 800 assists
during his time in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves and the rugged Spartans defense have won 30 games.
Michigan State allows 58.9 points per game, ninth in the nation,
and opponents shoot only 39.1 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   When the Spartans struggled against Utah in the NCAA second
round, trailing by six with 17 minutes to play, Cleaves led a 20-3
surge. He scored 11 of his game-high 21 points and passed out four
assists. In their victory against Syracuse in the Midwest Regional
semifinals, Cleaves finished with seven assists and 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cleaves' assist on a rafter-jarring Peterson dunk that
did in Iowa State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, Mateen took over,'' CBS announcer Bill
Raftery said. ``That alley-oop (dunk) after the timeout was
mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Now only two wins stand between the Spartans and what would be
their second national title. They won their first in 1979 when
Magic Johnson outdueled Indiana State's Larry Bird in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure has been there since the first magazine came out
and we were picked No. 1,'' Izzo said. ``These guys deserve what
they got. There is a relationship with this team. I think the
players really rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with Wisconsin will be their fourth of the season;
the Spartans won the first three. ``It's never easy to beat a team
twice,'' Izzo said. ``Three times is really tough. Four? Ouch.
They're on a roll and making shots now. (Coach Dick Bennett) has a
lot of players who are hungry to face the Spartans.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State won the three 61-44 on the road, 59-54 at home
and then 55-46 in the Big Ten Tournament. Beginning with a Feb. 5
victory at Minnesota, Wisconsin is 11-3, with the Spartans
responsible for the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State has put together a winning streak, too. The
Spartans have won nine in a row, 14 of their past 15. The loss was
an 81-79 overtime game to Indiana on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   After Michigan State defeated Illinois, 76-61 to win the
conference tournament, the Spartans showed little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy, but we're not satisfied,'' Cleaves said.
``Winning that tournament was a goal of ours, but we have bigger
and better goals. We want the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 seed seem to be headed there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
