<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PHONE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      03-27 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHONE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGEANT CHARGED IN BILLING OF CALLS TO WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Va.)  (lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An Army sergeant working for the White House has been
charged with fraud for telling several people in New York and New
Jersey how they could bill $50,000 worth of long-distance calls to
a White House telephone exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant, David Gilmer, 30, was arrested late Friday in
Virginia and appeared in court there Monday on the charges, which
were filed by the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal complaint, Gilmer worked for the White
House Communications Agency, which handles the phone system used by
President Clinton and other top federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint said Gilmer gave access codes to a toll-free
government number to several people in New York and New Jersey, who
placed a total of 9,400 calls through that line late last year and
early this year.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of calls, some from pay phones, aroused suspicion. A
telephone company was able to track many of them to homes and
businesses, including eight in New York City and one in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents do not specify how the people knew Gilmer or
whether he was paid for his help, and federal officials would not
provide more information.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by investigators, one of the people who had used an
access code agreed to secretly tape two conversations with Gilmer.
According to a federal affidavit, Gilmer acknowledged in the
conversations that he had passed on the codes.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Gilmer had not yet retained a lawyer and
did not enter a plea during his appearance Monday in federal court
in Alexandria, Va. Gilmer, who was released on bail, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
