<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 2)  
(jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Surfing Anniversary
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to surprise my husband, an avid surfer, with a
trip at the end of April for our 10th wedding anniversary. I prefer
upscale accommodations (no surf camps). We have been to Hawaii,
Costa Rica and other popular spots. Do you have any suggestions? _
C.K., Southampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The quick answer is, look south. Now that it's fall in the
Southern Hemisphere, storms and winds there are pushing toward the
Equator and even past it, according to Jeff Warner, a meteorologist
at Pennsylvania State University. So the best waves should be on
south-facing beaches the next few months, especially below the
Equator.
</P>
<P>
   Two specialty travel companies in California can help you take
advantage of waves kicked up by those ``roaring 40's'' winds (for
the latitudes they come from), and in comfortable surroundings. At
Wavehunters Surf Travel, the president, Henry Morales, suggested
resorts in Samoa, the Maldives, Brazil, Mexico and the Canary
Islands. A spokesman for Waterways Surf Adventures suggested Fiji
and Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   Among the places recommended by Wavehunters, 460 Ward Drive,
Santa Barbara, Calif. 93111, (888) 899-8823, fax (805) 681-8568,
and on the Web at www.wavehunters.com, is the Samoana Resort, on
the south shore of Upolu Island in Samoa. It takes only 12 guests
in its bungalows, and has a deck for dining and a lounge with bar,
television, video, pool table and a library. The cost of a week
with air fare from Los Angeles is $1,500 a person, double
occupancy, including three meals a day, and daily surf tours by
powerboat.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the Costa Azul resort, north of Puerto Vallarta,
Mexico, offers 28 air-conditioned suites and villas with Pacific
views. The surf there breaks predominantly to the left and ranges
from three to eight feet at this time of year, Morales said. The
resort has a pool, and arranges eco-tours in the jungle or to
turtle-nesting areas, horseback riding, kayaking and other water
sports. Packages include all meals and wine and beer, and are as
low as $98 a day a person after April.
</P>
<P>
   You can also book a stay at Costa Azul through Waterways, 15145
Califa Street, Van Nuys, Calif. 91411; (800) 928-3757, fax (818)
376-0353; www.waterwaystravel.com, but Waterways also suggested the
Lalati resort on Beqa (pronounced BENG-ah) Island, Fiji. It has
seven 900-square-foot fan-cooled bures, each with a bedroom and
living area, on 10 acres of beach and gardens overlooking Malumu
Bay. You can dive, paddle a kayak or play golf on the Robert Trent
Jones course at Pacific Harbor, 45 minutes away. The price for air
fare from Los Angeles, seven nights at Lalati and all meals is
about $2,600 each.
</P>
<P>
   For brand-name luxury accommodations, there are Four Seasons
resorts near surfing areas at Punta Mita, north of Puerto Vallarta,
where rates start at $495 a night, and in the Maldives, from $295 a
night. Information: (800) 332-3442.
</P>
<P>
   Theater in San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to spend Memorial Day weekend in San Francisco. How
can I find out what theater performances are planned then? _
R.S.G., Tenafly, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The simplest way to get a list of performances is to go to
the Web site of the San Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau,
www.sfcvb.org. Clicking on ``Calendar of Events'' and asking for
May events brought up 11 plays or theater groups, with schedules,
brief descriptions and telephone numbers for information.
</P>
<P>
   The list for Memorial Day weekend included Marlowe's ``Edward
II'' by the American Conservatory Theater at the Geary Theater, 415
Geary Street, (415) 749-2228 (tickets, $14 to $55); the revue
``Beach Blanket Babylon'' at Club Fugazi, 678 Green Street, (415)
421-4222 ($25 to $60); Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' in Stinson
Beach (in Marin County), (415) 868-1115 ($18), and the comedy
``Shear Madness,'' at the Mason Street Theater, 430 Mason Street,
(415) 982-5463 ($34).
</P>
<P>
   You can also request the list by mail from the visitors bureau
at Post Office Box 429097, San Francisco, Calif. 94142, or by
calling (415) 371-2000. The bureau takes e-mail information
requests at vic1(at)sfvcb.org.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Arts and Crafts
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are looking for an escorted 7- to 10-day tour of Mexican
towns known for their arts and crafts. Any suggestions? _ Phil
Pressel, San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Jean Grimm Art and Culture Tours, 1233 East Baker Dr. Tempe,
Ariz. 85282, (480) 730-1764, fax (480) 730-1771 periodically offers
such tours. Grimm, who is half-Mexican and has a master's degree in
art from New York University, will lead groups in and around Oaxaca
from Aug. 4 to 13 and Oct. 27 to Nov. 5. Activities will include
demonstrations by master wood carvers, rug weavers and ceramists,
meetings with painters, and visits to museums and ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The August trip costs $1,365 each, double occupancy, including
all meals and land transportation only. Accommodations are in the
Casa Panchita inn, and the group is limited to 11. The October
trip, using the larger Hostal La Noria, will cost $100 to $200 more
because it is a fund-raiser for the Scottsdale Museum of
Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Grimm plans tours to Veracruz, Puebla, Cuernavaca and
Mexico City in January, and to Morelia, Guanajuato and San Miguel
de Allende in March. If there is enough demand, she will add trips.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the New York nor the Los Angeles outlets of the Mexican
Government Tourism Office knew of any tours specifically devoted to
arts and crafts. But a number of agencies on the office's large
list of operators said that many of their tours visit cities and
towns with crafts centers.
</P>
<P>
   An example is Picturesque Mexico offered by Marco Polo Tours,
Saturno 90, Mexico City 06300, (52) 5583-5533, fax (52) 5782-3731.
This tour leaves weekly and lasts 14 days (segments available),
starting and ending in Mexico City. Among other places, it visits
San Juan del Rio, known for gemstones and alpaca; Guadalajara's San
Juan de Dios market, noted for ceramics and pottery, and Taxco, a
silver center. The price, $734 to $1,042, depending on hotels,
includes rooms, sightseeing by air-conditioned bus, van or car,
admission fees and English-speaking guide. Like many operators,
Marco Polo can design a custom trip.
</P>
<P>
   For names of agents and general information, contact the tourist
office at 2401 West Sixth St., Los Angeles, Calif. 90057; (800)
446-3942, fax (213) 351-20745.
</P>
</TEXT>
