<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS DISCUSS SALARY-CAP TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At an otherwise routine gathering of National
Football League owners Monday, two issues were percolating with
potential for creating a stir or leading to significant change. One
involved the Denver Broncos and an apparent violation of league
rules regarding deferred payments to John Elway, the former
quarterback, and Terrell Davis, the team's star running back.
</P>
<P>
   Also drawing interest was the Jets and the status of their star
wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, who remains on the trading block
despite the team's public stance. Several teams, including the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers, are interested in making a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL became concerned about the Broncos' situation when it
learned that Pat Bowlen, the Broncos' owner, had deferred almost
$30 million in salary payments to Elway and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Delaying payment allowed Bowlen to use the money for other
needs. The league frowns upon such arrangements, fearing a
franchise can get into deep, long-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was taken so seriously by Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
that he conducted a hearing on the issue earlier this month.
Tagliabue ordered Bowlen to pay most of the money immediately, and
Bowlen wrote a check for $22 million, which the league then gave to
Elway and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen acknowledged the arrangement with Elway and Davis, but
said, ``There was never a salary-cap violation.'' He said he
believed that other teams were attempting to spread such rumors.
Although the Broncos did not cheat the salary-cap rules, they
apparently did violate league guidelines regarding the way players
are paid.
</P>
<P>
   This episode demonstrates how complicated the simple task of
paying players can become. Teams are constantly trying to
manipulate the rules. The San Francisco 49ers have been accused of
major salary-cap violations, which the league is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Johnson situation has turned into a high-stakes
poker game. Jets Coach Al Groh reiterated a statement made last
week, asserting that the team was not going to trade the receiver
at this time. ``That's my story and I'm sticking to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do so at this time, given our salary-cap situation, would
harm our salary cap,'' Groh said while sitting in the lobby of the
Breakers Hotel, headquarters of the meetings. Groh added that the
receiver was ``one of our best players, and he has a contract with
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by the Jets' new owner, Robert Wood
Johnson IV, who said: ``I think when you make an agreement with
somebody who promises to do something, you should be able to take
that for what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a number of officials on NFL teams, however, the
Jets still want to trade the receiver, knowing that his salary
proposals will be too expensive for their payroll. Johnson may want
anywhere from $7 million to $10 million a season, and might propose
a signing bonus as high as $15 million. The Jets are trying to get
their payroll under control and simply don't think they can afford
to keep the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, however, Groh is maintaining a straight face, saying
the team will not trade Johnson, but leaving the door open with
such supplemental phrases as ``at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The stance the team is taking, league executives believe, is
meant to put pressure on the player and determine which teams are
truly serious about making a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers are interested in trading their two first-round
picks for the receiver, but the Jets want more, possibly a veteran
player in addition to the picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Jets are saying they are going to keep
Keyshawn,'' Tampa Bay Coach Tony Dungy said. ``That's how we have
to approach it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he truly believed that Johnson was not
available, Dungy smiled and said sarcastically: ``I always believe
coaches. Whatever they say.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh said he has spoken to the receiver several times by
telephone and the conversations were pleasant. Groh expects him to
report to the off-season workout program in April, but it is
unlikely that Johnson will, knowing the team is trying to trade
him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Johnson had told him he was going to hold out,
Groh said: ``Not specifically. But I don't have my head stuck in
the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners also approved the sale of 49 percent of the Baltimore
Ravens to the businessman Stephen Bisciotti for $275 million.
Bisciotti has the option to buy the remaining 51 percent from Art
Modell in 2004. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
