<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-FINALFOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRAST OF FINAL FOUR COACHES IN UNLIKELY PAIRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historians will determine if this year's Final Four is one of
the best in college basketball. The consensus will probably be
``Uh, no.'' But contemporary observers might agree that the
semifinalists heading to Indianapolis this week make up one of the
most interesting, unlikely and eclectic quartets in the modern
history of the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   When Michigan State, Wisconsin, North Carolina and Florida
gather at the RCA Dome, they could produce some more unexpected
plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA tournament is crazy enough that all you have to do is
put together three great weeks,'' said Tulsa Coach Bill Self, who
had that scenario in mind for his own until it lost on Sunday to
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels, like Wisconsin, entered the tournament with 13
defeats and were considered fortunate to make the 64-team field.
But both teams are 4-0 in these brackets. Referring to North
Carolina's last two weeks, Self said, ``There's no reason they
couldn't put together another one.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but the favorite among the four is Michigan State, which
will play the Badgers in Saturday's first semifinal. The Spartans
are the only surviving No. 1-seeded team from the four regions and
are the only team to return from last spring's Final Four. They
have the most victories (30-7) and they have played the toughest
competition, rallying for victories over Syracuse and Iowa State in
the last two games of the Midwest Regional. They have played
Wisconsin three times this season and won all three. And they will
be playing in Big Ten territory, within driving distance of their
large fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been there before,'' said Spartans guard Charlie Bell,
referring to the Final Four. ``We know the kind of media exposure
there's going to be, the hype surrounding it. We're not going to be
overwhelmed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (22-13) was the No. 8-seeded team in the West after
finishing sixth in the Big Ten. Unlike most elite teams, Wisconsin
lacks professional prospects. The Badgers last made the Final Four
in 1941, when they won the title. Their critics say Wisconsin's
slow, deliberate, defensive style is probably borrowed from the
playbook of that championship season, and even the Badgers make
jokes about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked guard Mike Kelley about watching Wisconsin
games on videotape, he replied, ``Do we have to?''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley will probably guard Mateen Cleaves, one of three Spartans
stars from Flint, Mich., who are nicknamed the Flintstones. Cleaves
tries to be a vocal leader in the manner of Magic Johnson, who led
Michigan State to its 1979 title.
</P>
<P>
   When the Spartans trailed Syracuse at halftime on Thursday
night, Cleaves spoke with anger to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if you miss a shot,'' Cleaves said later. ``But
if you're not playing hard, I'm going to get in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting how well Wisconsin and Michigan State know each other,
Cleaves said that in their last meeting he heard Badgers defenders
calling out Michigan State plays before the Spartans could.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin optimists might note that the Badgers _ who lost the
three games to Michigan State by an average of 10.3 points _ were
one of only two teams to outrebound the Spartans. (Iowa State was
the other). But Dick Bennett, the coach of Wisconsin, said he would
be careful not to put too much emphasis on the previous three
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this coaching business, you learn to live in the present,''
Bennett said. ``You don't dwell on what might be, but you do dream
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida-North Carolina game is, among other things, a
contrast of coaches. Bill Guthridge of North Carolina is 62 and in
his third season after 30 years as Dean Smith's assistant. Although
the Tar Heels were the No. 8-seeded team in the South Regional,
they have reached the Final Four 15 times and three times in the
last four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Forte, their star freshman guard, is averaging 16.7
points a game and is not intimidated by his surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take us to Indy,'' he said. Self calls Forte ``the
best freshman in the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Although their record is only 22-13, the Tar Heels' four-game
winning streak is their longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Guthridge's preparation time will be affected this week because
he went to Kansas for his mother's funeral. And it is not the only
distraction facing the team. Ed Cota and Terrence Newby of the Tar
Heels are due in court next Monday _ the night of the championship
game _ to face assault charges. The trial, delayed three times
already, stems from a street brawl on Halloween. Their lawyers are
requesting another rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
   But they might be free that night anyway if Florida continues
the run that raised its record to 28-7 after it was seeded No. 5 in
the East. The Gators are young, aggressive, cocky and edgy. Under
Billy Donovan, their 34-year-old coach from Rockville Center, N.Y.,
they use 10 players in regular rotation. They press on defense,
they push the ball up on offense, they throw elbows, they strut and
they preen. The coach loves them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys showed tremendous heart and character,'' Donovan
said after Sunday's 77-65 victory over Oklahoma State. ``We have a
class act. I'm proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan talks with volume and at a brisk pace, with as much
confidence as his team runs the floor. Despite his relative
inexperience among his peers, Donovan has sure opinions on all
things about basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, his players obey the coach, although Kenyan
Weaks, the only senior on the Gators, finished Sunday's game with a
gratuitous dunk, even after Donovan told the players not to shoot.
Now, Weaks has bigger things in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't wait to play North Carolina,'' he said. ``You
just don't know how much we want this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
