s t BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV02-     03-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Van Gogh Portraits Tour the United States &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh lovers, take note: museums in Detroit, Boston and
Philadelphia have found a new theme for exploring the artist's
perennially popular works _ ``Van Gogh: Face to Face,'' the first
exhibition to focus on his portraits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show, featuring more than 60 paintings and drawings, will be
on view at the Detroit Institute of Arts through June 4. In
slightly different forms, it then travels to the Museum of Fine
Arts in Boston, July 2 to Sept. 24, and ends at the Philadelphia
Museum of Art from Oct. 22 to Jan. 14, 2001. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh revered portraiture. He once wrote that he wanted to
``do portraits that will appear as revelations to people in 100
years' time.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With works drawn from collections in 10 countries, ``Face to
Face'' begins with the portraits van Gogh made of peasants and
pensioners in the Netherlands; follows him to Paris, where he
painted many intense self-portraits and celebratory examinations of
friends like the art dealer Alexander Reid; and ends in Provence,
where he made many penetrating portraits of the Roulin family and
others. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the best known in the show are ``Postman Joseph Roulin,''
``Madame Augustine Roulin Rocking a Cradle'' (aka ``La Berceuse'')
and ``The Zouave.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Institute of Arts, 5200 Woodward Avenue, is open
daily for this exhibition. Timed tickets, which include an audio
tour, are $16 on weekdays and $18 on weekends, with discounts for
students, and are available through Ticketmaster, (248) 433-8444,
or www.ticketmaster.com. Museum information is available on the van
Gogh hot line, (313) 833-8499 or www.dia.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel packages, which include immediate-access tickets to ``Face
to Face,'' are available at the Hyatt Regency Dearborn, the
Atheneum Suite Hotel and the Ritz-Carlton, Dearborn, and range from
$149 to $469. Information: (248) 584-4001. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Dallas to Dulles And Back for $306 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legend Airlines, which will offer all first-class seating at
coach prices, was scheduled to begin flying on Friday from Love
Field, near downtown Dallas, to Dulles Airport in Washington, Los
Angeles and Las Vegas. In response, American Airlines, which
dominates traffic at Dallas-Fort Worth airport and which went to
court to block the new carrier, said it plans to offer similar
service from Love Field as quickly as possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has higher air fares than Houston, in many cases twice as
high for advance-purchase tickets. Critics say this is a result of
American's efforts to stifle service from Love Field, which include
backing a federal law that limits long-haul flights from Love Field
to jets with fewer than 57 seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legend has found a way around the law. It leased four DC-9s and
put in 56 leather seats, spacious leg room, power ports for laptops
and live television via satellite and enough overhead, under seat
and closet storage that each passenger can carry on four bags.
</P>
<P>
   The company charges $306 round trip between Dallas and Dulles
with a 21-day advance purchase. Its walkup fare is $765 peak and
$716 off peak, the same as American's coach walkup fare from
Dallas-Fort Worth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American said that its new Love Field service will equip Fokker
100s, which are much narrower and smaller than DC-9s, with 56
first-class seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legend was started by T. Allan McArtor, onetime head of the
Federal Aviation Administration. The key to Legend's success will
be selling walkup fares to business travelers, he said. The company
plans to add flights from Dallas to Newark, Boston, Philadelphia,
Chicago and other business centers over the next five years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Big Red Boats Expand Their Range &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Premier Cruise Lines, known for Big Red Boat cruises to the
Bahamas from Port Canaveral, Fla., and for its emphasis on
children's programs, has announced plans to add a fourth ship and
sail from three more American ports starting in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company will base ships in Houston, New York, Los Angeles,
and in November, in Seattle or Vancouver. It will rename all its
vessels Big Red Boats and will continue to offer year-round three-
and four-night cruises to the Bahamas from Port Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   The company has acquired the Edinburgh Castle, a former gambling
ship, for seven-night spring, summer and fall cruises to New
England and Canada from New York. In winter it will operate out of
Tampa, Fla. Sailings begin from Houston in June, to Cozumel, Playa
del Carmen and Veracruz. In November three- and four-night cruises
begin from Los Angeles to Santa Catalina Island, San Diego, and
Ensenada, Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fares for three- and four-night cruises range from $399 to
$1,249 a person in double occupancy. Seven-night cruises range from
$799 to $1,749. As an introductory offer on the seven-night trips,
children cruise free; if you have no children, there is a $300
discount. Information: (800) 990-7770. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Landmark Status for Stonewall &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stonewall area in New York, a famous setting in the history
of gay and lesbian rights in the United States, was among 18 new
National Historic Landmarks created by the Interior Department last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Stonewall building, 51-53 Christopher Street in Greenwich
Village, the adjoining park and surrounding blocks entered the
register of 67,000 National Historic Places only a year ago; along
with only 3 percent of that list, it has now been designated a
landmark _ of historical importance to the nation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stonewall is the first federally listed site to recognize the
``national significance and contribution of lesbians and gay men,''
said M. John Berry, an assistant Interior Secretary. On June 28,
1969, after a police raid on the bar called the Stonewall Inn _ now
gone _ gay patrons fought back for the first time. On the following
nights they were joined in the streets by hundreds of protesters.
The movement toward gay and lesbian pride is generally dated from
these clashes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others landmarks on the list include the 1901 Henry M. Flagler
House in Palm Beach _ chosen because of the significance of its
architecture and its builder, the primary developer of Florida _
and Fort James Jackson, built by the United States in 1808-12 to
defend Savannah. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nathan and Polly Johnson Properties in New Bedford, Mass.,
was home to Frederick Douglass and his wife after they escaped from
slavery in 1838; the Johnsons assisted slaves on the Underground
Railroad, which sometimes included a sea voyage. Ferry Farm, George
Washington's boyhood home in Stafford County, Va., was chosen
because new information about the sorts of things the family owned
and used has been uncovered there. The area is also associated with
stories of Washington's youth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each place will get an Interior Department landmark plaque. The
Stonewall plaque is expected in time for anniversary celebrations
in June, said Kimberly Stahlman Kearns, executive director of the
Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Wade &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Correction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An article on March 12 about the value of thorough vacation
planning misidentified the seafood associated with Digby, Nova
Scotia, which the author learned about after her visit. The town is
known for scallops, not oysters. &QL;
</P>
