<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES COULD USE KINGS' MURRAY AS MOTIVATOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Was Kings coach Andy Murray excessive in
blistering his team Saturday afternoon for a lack of intensity
during a tie with Boston?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the team is on the verge of qualifying for just its
second postseason appearance in the last seven years. How about a
little slack?
</P>
<P>
   Ask the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   In January, they were spending their third month atop the
Pacific Division. Despite bowing out in the first round the past
four years, the Coyotes had developed into one of the league's
better teams.
</P>
<P>
   With two weeks left in the regular season, the Coyotes have
dropped seven straight. They are just two points ahead of the
Mighty Ducks for the final playoff spot in the West after losing
4-3 in overtime Sunday night in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Intensity?
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix had a 3-1 lead. But after battering Guy Hebert for 17
shots in the first period, they had seven the rest of the game,
including OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as low as we can be, no doubt about that,'' said
All-Star defenseman Teppo Numminen. ``It's been tough for
everybody. But you can't get too down and too emotional about it.
We have to keep our focus and concentrate on how we're playing and
the team will take care of itself. We have to fight back, but it's
tough right now. ... We're trying everything and we're getting
frustrated, but we just have to take a step back, relax, get our
confidence back and remember how we played when we were a good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said after Sunday's 4-1 victory in Atlanta that one of
the things he's most proud of this season is the way he never
wavered on his coaching philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   There were pats on the back when deserved, but Murray said
keeping the players accountable was a better way to shake a history
of losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is kind of an NHL cool that says the season is so long,
you're going to have those nights,'' he said. ``I never bought into
that. There were people this year who thought I should lighten up a
little. To me, that wasn't the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It has hurt Phoenix that captain Keith Tkachuk has missed 16
games with an injured ankle. He is back now, but the Coyotes' power
play (3 for 59) is not. The Kings went through a stretch like that
and then lost top winger Ziggy Palffy to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille went nine games without a goal. He has three in
his last three games.
</P>
<P>
   There also was talk that holdout All-Star goaltender Nikolai
Khabibulin, who is playing for the Long Beach Ice Dogs, might be
back for the end of the season because the team has lost confidence
in Sean Burke and Bob Essensa.
</P>
<P>
   But because he wasn't signed by the trade deadline, Khabibulin
will not be eligible for the rest of the season or playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   When last year's Kings coach Larry Robinson replaced Robbie
Ftorek in New Jersey even though the Devils have the best record in
the East, there were concerns in Phoenix whether first-year coach
Bob Francis was safe. The Coyotes are in a far greater free fall
than the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's certainly not my place to comment on
anything the New Jersey Devils do or how they run their team,''
Phoenix GM Bobby Smith said. ``From my perspective, I think Bob
Francis is a long-term coach for this team. He's a very good coach
and I expect him to coach our team for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith didn't want to give Francis a vote of confidence, which
usually means the coach will get fired. But there has been
grumbling in the Phoenix dressing room that Francis has worked the
team too hard, especially during the losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Respect always is a big issue, so anything could happen. Veteran
Rick Bowness is an assistant, but the Coyotes already have had four
coaches in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the reasons things have worked well here is the
message from the coach stays the same,'' Kings defenseman Mattias
Norstrom said. ``Players went down with injuries and we struggled,
but the expectation was always the same. This is a playoff team and
anything less is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   TIRADE DOESN'T HELP
</P>
<P>
   When Eric Lindros ripped the Philadelphia Flyers for withholding
the severity of his fourth concussion in two years, he guaranteed
the situation will not be resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers were wrong for not telling him his concussion was a
Grade II, which requires a minimum one month of doing nothing
before the situation could be reevaluated. They were seriously
wrong for letting him play four more games after the injury, which
occurred March 4 on a hit by Boston's Hal Gill.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is two points behind New Jersey for the top spot in
the East. The Flyers need Lindros, one of the game's top offensive
talents. But they also know his teammates think he's a tad wimpy.
</P>
<P>
   Like the much-discussed visor issue after Toronto's Bryan Berard
was blinded in one eye by a stick, the Flyers were trying to play
the macho card. Now it is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   How will the Flyers trade Lindros when there is no certainty he
will ever play again? In a cash-strapped league, who will want to
pick up his $8.5 million annual salary?
</P>
<P>
   Lindros is a great talent, but he never has played a full season
since joining the league in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' dislike for Flyers GM Bobby Clarke is no secret. But if
he really wanted out of Philadelphia, it should have been done
behind the scenes. Now, he is viewed as a wimpy, overpriced,
perhaps irreparably injured player.
</P>
<P>
   Happy trading. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers the Kings for the Daily
News. The NHL column runs every Tuesday through the regular
season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
