<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-ERICSSON28-COX     03-27 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ERICSSON28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Capriati comeback checks off Williams
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Before the match, Jennifer Capriati tried
to ignore the thoughts of what beating fifth seed Serena Williams
could mean to her comeback. She didn't want to make herself nervous
with pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But after she upset one of the hardest hitters on the women's
tour 7-6 (7-2), 1-6, 6-3, Capriati celebrated on stadium court at
the Ericsson Open like the teen-age tennis sweetheart she used to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' Capriati said about 45 minutes after
leaping for joy when she hit a 102-mph service winner on match
point. ``I'm just very happy because it shows I've really come a
long way. All the hard work has paid off. For a long time, this is
my biggest win.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Williams, this was a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   It means the trophy won't go home to Palm Beach Gardens with a
Williams sister for the first time since 1998, when Venus Williams
won the first of her two titles. Venus, who watched from the stands
with two dogs, couldn't play this year because of wrist tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   But this loss also reinforces the fact that Serena Williams
isn't the dominating force she has tried to become since winning
the U.S. Open in September.
</P>
<P>
   Her ranking is No. 6 after she finished 1999 at No. 4. She has
won one title this year but had two at this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   Against Capriati, the Williams sister with the more reliable
serve landed only 44 percent of first serves during the first set
and made 40 unforced errors. She finished with a first-serve
percentage of 50 percent and 77 unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati added 14 double faults and 65 unforced errors of her
own to the technically ugly match. Together, they hit 37 winners,
14 by Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I played OK,'' Williams said. ``She just played some
great shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Etienne Dumas, a coach who has worked with the Williams
sisters off-and-on for nearly a decade, thought Williams should
have won the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there were just too many unforced errors on her
part,'' he said. ``I think she played too much of a defensive game.
And I don't think she's moving well.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, father and coach of the girls, apparently
agreed. He left his courtside seat after the first set and
apparently left the tennis center after Williams lost her serve in
the second game of the third set.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati and Williams played a nearly equally bad match for the
first set, trading six service breaks to force the tiebreaker.
Capriati, a former South Florida resident who has won fans on her
comeback from drugs and disillusionment, got the enthusiastic crowd
behind her early and played aggressively in the tiebreaker to win
it.
</P>
<P>
   But she started the second set exhausted. Williams played
better, too, and won that set in 27 minutes after the 60-minute
first set.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Capriati started well, winning the first game on
her serve and then holding on to break Williams' serve in the
second game on her fourth break point and after five deuces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I started playing again like I did in the
first set,'' she said. ``I just got on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 3-0 lead, Capriati unintentionally solidified her fan
support for the rest of the match. Williams led 40-15 when Capriati
called a let mid-point because she saw something flying through the
air that turned out to be tennis ball fuzz.
</P>
<P>
   But only the chair umpire heard the let call, and she didn't see
the ball fuzz.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later, Williams returned a ball at least 6 inches
out. Capriati argued for the let, knowing she had little chance.
But fans thought Williams' ball had been called in. Instead,
Capriati lost the point because she ``stopped play for nothing,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   That incident seemed to disrupt Williams more than Capriati,
though, although Williams said the wind was the reason she fell to
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the next game, Capriati got within one point of victory,
leading 40-30. She made a mistake and, on the next point, hit her
first serve clear across the court and into the first row of fans
behind Williams. She put her hand over her mouth in embarrassment
and went on to lose the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won the next game before Capriati got a chance to serve
again. She double faulted twice and fought off three break points
before winning the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to get back to playing how I was playing to get
up to 5-1,'' Capriati said. ``I just kept going for it. Some of
those things you just can't explain. It's something supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams didn't think so. Those were points she should have
won. Any loss ``shocks'' her, she said, but she didn't seem
distraught afterward. That's because she's been trying to improve
how she handles losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to get devastated after losses anymore,'' Williams
said. ``I have to realize that this is just a game. I'm just out
there to please the crowd, just do the best I can. If I go too
extreme, I'll end up in the nut house with the other
perfectionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing that desire with one to reach No. 1 seems difficult.
For example, Williams balked upon hearing that Hingis said she
thinks Hingis and Lindsay Davenport are in a tier above the other
players on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play Martina again because she makes a lot of
comments,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   She paused briefly before continuing: ``But she's right. I've
been losing a lot. I lost in the Australian Open. I lost in Indian
Wells. I lost here. So yeah, it's her and Lindsay right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams seemed unsure what she will do to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I'm going to go home, talk things over with my
dad,'' she said. ``We'll evaluate things.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumas has much clearer ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Williams should have prepared better for this
tournament, and he hopes she will commit to working with him more
consistently so he can help her with things such as footwork,
conditioning and developing a full-time traveling team _ like those
of Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi _ to help keep her at the top and
keep her improving during tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   All of that would and should be done under her father's
guidance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel that she's so close and it's so easy to get
there,'' Dumas said. ``I really hope this will confirm that this is
what she needs to do and let's just get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
