<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-OSCAR-FASHION-NYT &LR;      03-27 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR STYLE: ALL POLISHED, PRETTY AND BANAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ On her way into the Vanity Fair Oscar
party early Monday morning, Queen Latifah did what any celebrity
might do when told she cannot bring her bodyguard into the hottest
party in town _ and it's 1 a.m., too late, practically speaking,
for a snit. She stripped off the several million dollars' worth of
borrowed Harry Winston jewels she had worn and handed them to the
bodyguard, right on the curb. Like they're loose change or
something.
</P>
<P>
   Then she sailed past the paparazzi gathered five deep behind the
rope line and into Morton's restaurant, where Brad Pitt, Jennifer
Aniston, Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman, Hilary Swank, Chloee Sevigny,
Matt Damon, Winona Ryder, Faye Dunaway, Jane Fonda _ well, everyone
who is anybody _ were already engaged in the frenetic business of
being a star on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   How can one describe the scene inside Morton's except to say
that it was strangely, marvelously surreal? Walter Cronkite was
talking to Steven Tisch, the entertainment executive. Bob
Colacello, a Vanity Fair writer who is working on a book about
Ronald Reagan, was saying something to Connie Wald, widow of the
producer Jerry Wald, who made ``Johnny Belinda'' and ``Key Largo.''
She looked fabulous in a black taffeta couture skirt with a black
Gap T-shirt she had thoughtfully adorned with a Mongolian lamb cowl
and jeweled earrings.
</P>
<P>
   They had all been there since 5 p.m. So had Tony Curtis, Billy
Wilder, Steve Martin, David Geffen, Fran Lebowitz, Penny Marshall,
Regis Philbin and Kelly Lynch, about 150 people in all invited by
Graydon Carter, the magazine's editor, to watch the Academy Awards
on big-screen televisions as they ate grilled ahi tuna with baby
bok choy and warm chocolate truffle cake.
</P>
<P>
   Unless one was an Oscar nominee or a presenter, or decided to
stay at home, as Rita Wilson and her husband, Tom Hanks, did
(``I'll be in my sweats,'' Wilson said happily on Saturday at the
lunch Barry Diller, the former Paramount chief, gave at his house
for several hundred people), the place to be on Oscar night was at
one of the half dozen or so parties that now seem to rival the
awards themselves for sheer star power. DreamWorks and Miramax had
their parties, so did the Elton John AIDS Foundation (with In Style
magazine). And there were the private affairs held in the days
leading up to the Oscars, like the dinner on Saturday night that
the agent Ed Limato had.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to seeing all those familiar faces, and
debating the merits of who wore what _ which has become a kind of
ruthless sport at Oscar time _ the Vanity Fair party was by far the
most elegant cattle call in town.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 150 people could be invited to the dinner, nearly
1,000 started pouring into Morton's when the awards show ended at
10:30 p.m. Within 30 minutes, when Cruise and Kidman arrived, the
area in front of the bar was so jammed that when someone suggested
everyone move into the tent, which had been set up in the back of
the restaurant, for dancing and just sitting around, Cruise became
a kind of ring leader. ``Hey, let's go back,'' he called out above
the roar. ``We're moving in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back, Kidman, who had on a gold silk Dior dress, let out
a sigh. ``I think we're just going to stay at this party,'' she
said, adding that she planned to leave at midnight for a flight to
Australia, where she is filming ``Moulin Rouge.'' Someone had
stepped on the train of her dress and put a tear in it. ``It's
madness,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Hefner was in a booth with four blondes, including a pair
of bosomy twins, and people came over just to gawk. Cher, who had
changed from her black Oscar gown into an ensemble of sequins with
a denim jacket, immediately spotted the dress designer Diane Von
Furstenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, how are you,'' Cher said to Von Furstenberg. ``I see your
stuff on QVC sometimes. One day I watched it for 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton's was throbbing with people. Carter was on the dance
floor with Minnie Driver. Lebowitz, meanwhile, spent most of the
night, until after 1 a.m., reclining on a sofa, with her high heels
dangling on the arm rest and a carton of Marlboro Lights next to
her. ``I have my drink and my cigarettes,'' she said. ``I'm just
waiting for the pizza to be delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then somebody brought over Heidi Fleiss, the former
Hollywood madam, to meet Lebowitz, and after Lebowitz introduced
another guest to Fleiss, who had on a velvet, fur-trimmed coat she
described as ``hooker-rock star,'' Lebowitz beamed. ``That's the
best introduction I've made since I introduced Liberace to Michael
Graves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As Pitt, who was a presenter, made his way into the tent, he was
asked what he thought of this year's Oscar fashion, which many
thought was a mixed bag. Pitt grinned. ``That's a woman thing,'' he
said. ``You don't ask a guy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Aniston, his girlfriend, gave him a look. ``Oh now, ask a guy,''
she said. ``He knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitt shrugged handsomely. ``Everybody was dressed, and I was
happy they were,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aniston, who was wearing a black halter-style dress by Lawrence
Steele, continued: ``You know the thing that burns me the most?
It's that people can't try something without going on trial or
getting ridiculed. It's that Joan Rivers and Melissa thing.'' She
was referring to the E! Entertainment channel's fashion critics.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, the fashion that comes down the red carpet has
become almost too banal to even comment upon. Actresses like
Charlize Theron, who had on a Vera Wang gown with Fred Leighton
diamond dress clips, and Ashley Judd, who wore lavender Valentino
with her hair in Southern ringlets, looked pretty. So did Sevigny
in a Madame X gown by Saint Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little surprise. No outrageous examples of bad
taste (unless you count Angelina Jolie's get-up, which was spooky).
Even the sexier clothes, like the Versace dresses worn by Cameron
Diaz and Lucy Liu, seemed somehow predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the beauty-pageant parade of Barbie doll dresses,''
said Randolph Duke, who scored something of a coup by designing
Swank's ball gown, made from 1950s French silk, which he called a
homage to Charles James. ``The risk-takers were fewer this year,''
he added. ``These girls get so many opinions: publicist, manager,
husband, mother. It's a committee decision, and you know what you
get with a committee decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an opinion, Lisa Eisner, the fashion muse and stylist,
said, ``I hate when young girls try to dress like older women.''
She mentioned the big gold hoop earrings that Uma Thurman wore with
her Alberta Ferretti dress, which she suggested were better than
aging diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   But who can say in Hollywood? There was Connie Wald, a doyenne,
in her Gap T-shirt. ``Nothing has changed in Hollywood,
basically,'' she said sweetly. ``It's all the same _ still
cutthroat, still competitive. Only the faces have changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
