<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-SUTTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SKILL AND MENTAL TOUGHNESS, SUTTON BEATS WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ His determined face said it all. His
rock-solid game was all he needed. Like a marathon runner who keeps
churning until the finish line, Hal Sutton captured the Players
Championship Monday because he refused to beaten.
</P>
<P>
   It took five days. It took withstanding a late charge by Tiger
Woods. It took one last encounter with two of the toughest
finishing holes in golf at the TPC at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever it took, Sutton was willing to do it. Seventeen
years after he first won this tournament, Sutton captured it again.
Only this time it was sweeter. He beat the world's No. 1 player,
Tiger Woods, by one stroke Monday in the completion of the final
round and continued a brilliant resurgence in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton led wire to wire and finished 10 under par for the
tournament (278), one stroke ahead of Woods (279), who saw another
rally on the back nine fall just short. Nick Price, Robert Damron,
Scott Dunlap, Jeff Maggert and Colin Montgomerie finished in a
five-way tie for third at four under par.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the tournament, Sutton vowed that he would stand up
to Woods, who has intimidated more than a few of his peers while
dominating the PGA Tour during the last year. Sutton made good on
that promise, refusing to wilt when Woods made an eagle at No. 16
and closed within one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Woods both made par at the nerve-racking island green
on No. 17, then Sutton closed the victory with a great tee shot and
a solid approach shot at No. 18, where both players made par.
</P>
<P>
   By winning Monday, the 41-year-old Sutton became the oldest
winner of the Players Championship, and he took home the biggest
paycheck in golf: $1.08 million. And by winning four times since
the fall of 1998, Sutton has overcome a midcareer slump in which he
did not win on Tour from 1987 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sutton was the star of the victorious United States
Ryder Cup team last year, earning 3{ points as one of the team's
inspirational leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's victory will hold a place of its own. Sutton
emphasized that he respected Woods greatly, and that made it
gratifying to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play in the final round with Tiger Woods in the last group
and beat him head to head, I can't paint that dream any prettier,''
said Sutton, who earned his 12th career victory on the Tour and
improved to No. 5 in the world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not going to beat myself. If you give him an open door,
he's going to rush through it. To win on this golf course, you have
to overcome nerves. You have to show courage. And for Tiger to be
the one that I was playing in the last group, that made it
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who was three strokes down when play resumed at the 12th
hole Monday, quickly fell to four strokes down when he made a
three-putt bogey at No. 12. But his birdie at No. 13, followed by
his eagle at the par-5 No. 15, pulled him within one stroke and put
the pressure on Sutton down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In his last 11 starts on the Tour, Woods has seven victories and
three second-place finishes. That sounds like someone who is ready
for next week's Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that I didn't win, but at least I made Hal
work for it,'' Woods said. ``I wasn't going to have a nice stroll
up No. 18 with no pressure on him. We had a good battle. Under the
most extreme conditions, I was able to hit the shots I wanted to.
That is what you want to see going into the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   The day got very interesting after Woods eagled the par-5,
507-yard No. 16, using his power to reach the green in two shots.
After a huge drive, Woods hit a beautiful 5-iron from 195 yards
that landed 12 feet right of the hole. Then he made the putt for
eagle. As the ball dropped into the hole, Woods was already doing
his fist-pump. Was there any doubt Woods would make a run? Sutton
did not think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was planning on him making that putt,'' Sutton said. ``He
lives up to his No. 1 ranking all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sutton never flinched. He still had a three-footer for par
after Woods' eagle putt, and Sutton calmly made it to stay one
ahead. Then came No. 17, where Sutton made a triple-bogey on
Saturday after hitting his tee shot into the water. But the hole
was not nearly as scary Monday because rain had softened the green
overnight and there was little wind.
</P>
<P>
   Woods relieved some of the pressure on Sutton by hitting a poor
tee shot at No. 17 that landed in the rough, enabling Sutton to hit
a safe shot into the middle of the green. Woods chipped and putted
for par, Sutton two-putted for par, and they moved to the toughest
finishing hole on tour statistically with Sutton still ahead by
one.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods drilled a 2-iron tee shot into the middle of the
fairway, Sutton took out his driver and poured a ball down the
middle of the fairway past Woods. Sutton missed only one fairway in
the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Woods knew he needed to hit his next shot close, but his 6-iron
from 193 yards was too long as it sailed over the green and into
the rough. Sutton closed in style by hitting a beautiful 6-iron
approach shot to 10 feet. Woods' last chance for birdie failed when
his chip from 20 feet was short. Sutton two-putted for par, shook
hands with Woods, then talked about their battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you the truth: I got nervous as heck,'' Sutton
said. ``It was nerve-racking to beat him. I feel really tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
