<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FREESPEECH-COMPLAINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-SPEECH SUITS FORCING U.S. COURTS INTO CITY HALL ROLES, JUDGES
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-SUIT) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In sharp new criticism of the Giuliani
administration's First Amendment policies, two federal appeals
court judges have complained that a ``relentless onslaught'' of
litigation over restrictions on political demonstrations and
artistic events has forced the federal courts to take on the role
of city licensing agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The judges leveled the criticism in a decision involving an
artist whose plans to photograph 75 to 100 nude models on a city
street were blocked by the police last July.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision, filed late Friday, the judges simply sent the
case to the New York Court of Appeals, the state's highest court,
for an interpretation of the state law at the center of the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But in writing the opinion, Judge Guido Calabresi of the 2nd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Manhattan, noted that the judges
``would be ostriches if we failed to take judicial notice of the
heavy stream of First Amendment litigation generated by New York
City in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited 17 cases over the last four years in which federal
courts had either barred city actions on free-speech issues or
ruled that policies limiting political demonstrations were
unconstitutional. He added, ``In the current and rather remarkable
state of affairs in New York City, there is an all-too-clear danger
that the courts, instead of merely interpreting and defending
federal rights, may cross the line and become, in effect, an agency
that performs crucial local government functions.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert D. Sack, who concurred in the decision, wrote a
separate opinion in which he also criticized the city. He said that
police officials' decision to stop the photographer, Spencer
Tunick, from taking the nude photographs in the absence of clear
rules against the practice represented a ``variation on the classic
theme of censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judges said it would be premature to rule on the
constitutionality of the city's actions until the state Court of
Appeals decided how to interpret part of a state law that bans most
public nudity.
</P>
<P>
   The third judge on the federal appeals panel, Ellsworth Van
Graafeiland, did not participate in the decision, saying he
believed that Tunick's case was now moot.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick has been arrested five times in recent years for
arranging photo shoots of naked people on city streets without a
permit, although the charges have been dropped. Last year, Tunick
applied for permits. He received one for a photo session involving
clothed models. But his request to photograph the nude models
between 5:30 and 6:30 on a Sunday morning on Madison Street,
between Catherine and Market Streets, was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick then sued, and a U.S. District Court judge ordered the
Police Department not to interfere with the photo shoot. But on
appeal from the city, the 2nd Circuit stayed that ruling, saying it
needed more time to take up the underlying legal issues.
</P>
<P>
   The case now centers on whether Tunick's photo sessions should
be covered under an exemption for artistic events in the state's
anti-nudity law. City officials have argued that the law allows
nudity in theater plays and other events indoors, where access can
be controlled, but not outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   But Calabresi wrote, ``One need not contemplate why, on the
city's reasoning, a totally naked production of `Hamlet' could be
staged in the middle of Grand Central Station during rush hour,
while Tunick's photo shoot had to be banned regardless of time,
place or manner in which it occurred, to say that the statute as
interpreted by the city would raise serious constitutional
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Koerner, the city's chief assistant corporation counsel,
said he thought that the judges' criticisms were gratuitous. He
said the city had asked them to send the case to the state appeals
court.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick's lawyer, Ronald L. Kuby, said, ``The bottom line is that
Tunick is moving closer to finally being able to take a picture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
