<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-EAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN IS FORCED TO BREAK A SWEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ A fight. How unfamiliar. The Connecticut women's
basketball team had not participated in such an event recently.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the nation's top-ranked team and the undisputed
favorite to advance to the Final Four, had walloped its first three
opponents in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament by an average of 43.6 points a game. But Monday night in
the East Regional final, Louisiana State made the Huskies sweat for
their ticket to the Final Four in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Svetlana Abrosimova buried a 3-pointer with 36
seconds left, giving the Huskies (34-1) an 84-69 lead, that
Connecticut had truly delivered its knockout punch. Abrosimova
scored 25 points to lead Connecticut to an 86-71 victory over LSU.
Abrosimova, a 6-foot-2 forward from St. Petersburg, Russia, was
named the East Regional's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is UConn's fourth trip to the Final Four in 10
years, it is the current Huskies first trip. In 1995, when
Connecticut won the national championship, it advanced from the
East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut did not care where it was playing, only that it
could advance to Philadelphia. The Huskies led by only 5 points at
halftime, after enduring an unconscious display of shooting from
LSU, 74 percent in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State, and its 18-year veteran coach Sue Gunter, have
never been to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Abrosimova scored 8 points in the first five minutes of the
second half, keeping the Huskies on top by no more than 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the deciding two possessions of the night, the
kind that heavyweights like Connecticut make.
</P>
<P>
   Asjha Jones scored on a fast break layup with 10 minutes 26
seconds remaining to give the Huskies a 63-52 lead. Connecticut did
not pause, setting up in its ferocious fullcourt defense on LSU's
inbounds play. The sophomore forward Tamika Williams stole the ball
for Connecticut and passed it to Shea Ralph, waiting under the
basket for an easy chip shot that gave the Huskies what was then
their largest lead of the night, 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph was not done. Her 3-pointer with six minutes remaining
gave UConn a 17-point lead. And even though LSU fought back to
close to 9 points with under three minutes to play, Abrosimova
score the crucial 5 points to send the Huskies to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   For the second half, the Tigers shot only 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State, the third-best team in the Southeastern
Conference, went into the game knowing it was a long shot.
``Stranger things have been known to happen,'' Gunter said before
the game. And there was nothing stranger than her players making
all but six of their 23 shots in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   April Brown, a Louisiana State junior forward who finished with
23 points, scored 18 points, 7 more than her average, in the first
18 minutes of the half. She was 4-for-4 from 3-point range and
missed just two shots all half. So did the junior point guard Marie
Ferdinand, the hero of the regional semifinal victory over
Oklahoma, who was 5 for 7 with 13 points. Brown and Ferdinand
allowed the Tigers to stay within single digits for most of the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting shots was the key, Gunter knew, after studying game
films of Tennessee's victory over the Huskies, their only loss of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   While Connecticut played eight players in the first nine minutes
of the game, LSU did not substitute until six minutes were left in
the first half. Not a bad strategy when the players on the floor
were shooting so well.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies had their stars as well. Abrosimova scored 10
points in the first 10 minutes, answering each LSU basket with a
timely 3-pointer or a runner. Abrosimova then scored 8 more points
in the first five minutes of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Bird, with 14 first-half points for UConn, complemented her,
going 4 for 6 from 3-point range. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
