<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIET-DRUG-LAWSUIT-685     03-27 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-DRUG-LAWSUIT-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MORE DIET-DRUG LAWSUITS ARE EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The advertisements began popping up on television and
radio two months ago: Weitz &AMP; Luxenberg, a Manhattan law firm, was
telling people who said they had been made ill by the diet pill
combination fen-phen that their chances of being fairly compensated
might be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   A $3.75 billion settlement in a class-action lawsuit could be
approved by a federal court soon, and the ads warned that most
people harmed by the once popular prescription would be barred from
bringing individual suits unless they ``opt out'' of the
class-action suit by Thursday. And of course the announcer urged
those affected to call Weitz &AMP; Luxenberg to ``investigate your
legal options.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm says it has received more than 200 responses to its ads
and has taken on 25 of the cases. Along with another law firm's Web
site, which is highly critical of the proposed class-action
settlement and has offered to provide forms for those wanting to
withdraw from the suit, the ads make clear that the tangle of
litigation over fen-phen will continue even if the class settlement
wins approval.
</P>
<P>
   The ads and the Web site, by the New York firm of Napoli, Kaiser
&AMP; Bern, highlight a paradox of the legal profession: Class-action
agreements can fuel the litigation fires they are intended to
douse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you about the culture of the legal profession and
about the money at stake,'' said Stephen Gillers, vice dean of New
York University School of Law. He said the ads did not breach legal
ethics. ``When we see plaintiff lawyers vs. defense lawyers, that's
only Act 1,'' he said of widespread personal injury litigation
involving a product or material. ``Act 2 becomes plaintiff lawyers
vs. plaintiff lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Brickman, a specialist in legal ethics at the Benjamin N.
Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva University, said plaintiff lawyers
skirmishing to either maximize or reduce the size of class-action
suits will say ``they're acting in the public interest.'' The
proposed fen-phen settlement includes up to $429 million in fees
for the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But Roy D. Simon, a law professor at Hofstra University, said,
``If it's accurate, I think this type of advertisement is actually
helpful to people.'' He said that usually in class litigation, ``If
people have large individual claims, they may be better off in an
individual action than a class action.'' An ad like this, he said,
affords ``another perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed settlement, intended to cover thousands of people
across the country who have suffered heart-valve damage after
taking two of the diet pills in the fen-phen combination, was
reached in October with American Home Products Corp., based in
Madison, N.J., and is subject to approval by the presiding judge,
Louis C. Bechtle, of U.S. District Court in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The company's pharmaceutical division, Wyeth-Ayerst
Laboratories, made Pondimin _ its brand name for fenfluramine, an
appetite depressant that is the ``fen'' in the case _ and
distributed a similar drug, Redux. Some 6 million people took one
or the other, often in combination with phentermine _ the ``phen''
in the formula _ which increases the rate at which calories are
burned.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gordon, a partner in Weitz &AMP; Luxenberg, which is not
involved in the class litigation, called the ads ``a public service
to alert people to deadlines they might not know about and to let
them know they may do better'' with an individual suit.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley M. Chesley, a plaintiffs' lawyer from Cincinnati who
helped negotiate the settlement, said, ``It's just another law firm
trying to get business at this late date.''
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products pulled Pondimin and Redux off the market
in late 1997 after studies linked them to heart-valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 individual suits have been filed by former users
claiming such damage. The class settlement would give those who
have ``serious'' damage _ and who did not opt out of the class
action _ payments ranging from $7,400 to nearly $1.5 million,
depending on factors like age and degree of damage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are provisions for withdrawing from the class lawsuit
after Thursday under certain circumstances. If too many withdraw to
pursue individual suits, American Home Products can scrap the
accord, and with it the legal fees. A spokesman for the company,
Doug Petkus, said it had not determined how many ``opt outs'' would
be too many.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said Weitz &AMP; Luxenberg had ``turned down far more than we
accepted'' of those who responded to its ads, which stopped running
two weeks ago, and had told many callers to stick with the class
settlement plan `'if they don't have a significant claim.'' He
added, ``I'm not saying the plan is bad, only that it's not right
for every case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
