<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- NY-LIVERY-CABS -- Judging
by statistics alone, New York is relatively safer these days for
its more than 41,000 livery-cab drivers - the drivers who make up
the only cab industry in most of the city, cruising the streets
where yellow cabs are rarely seen. But don't tell that to
Lakhwander Singh, right, a livery-cab driver who was wounded by
robbers Sunday. ``They took the money, and they shot me anyway,''
said Singh, 40, who lives with his cousin, Gurinder Singh, also a
livery driver. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) DUNELLEN, N.J. -- March 27, 2000 -- NJ-FLOOD-RECOVER --
Lawrence P. Kerwin at the Dunellen Hotel, whose restaurant and bar
he and his father have operated for decades, and Bettina
DeCaumette, who is taking over. But while the two toasted to
continuity, in fact nothing will be the same. Kerwin, 74, will be
leaving the only profession he has ever known, besides a brief
stint in the military. And for Mrs. DeCaumette, life has changed
profoundly in the six months since her business in Bound Brook was
wiped out in September by the floods of Tropical Storm Floyd. (Dith
Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
