<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-MOAS-EXTINCTION-2-B&AMP;W
-- Over the last 40,000 years, as anatomically modern but primitive
peoples equipped with stone-tipped weapons spread around the world,
species after species of big animal vanished from the earth in
their wake. ``Blitzkrieg'' has long been scientists' favorite image
for these spasms of biological destruction. Nowhere, perhaps, was
the extinction more striking than in New Zealand, where an entire
class of large flightless birds called moas once lived. An artist's
rendering of a moa at the American Museum of Natural History.
(American Museum of Natural History/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AUCKLAND, New Zealand -- March 27, 2000 --
SCI-MOAS-EXTINCTION-1-B&AMP;W -- Over the last 40,000 years, as
anatomically modern but primitive peoples equipped with
stone-tipped weapons spread around the world, species after species
of big animal vanished from the earth in their wake. ``Blitzkrieg''
has long been scientists' favorite image for these spasms of
biological destruction. Nowhere, perhaps, was the extinction more
striking than in New Zealand, where an entire class of large
flightless birds called moas once lived. A life-size model of a moa
at the Auckland Museum in 1997. (Lonnie Schlein/The New York Times)
