<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-NAMIBIA-2TAKES     03-27 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NAMIBIA-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW LONG CAN TIME STAND STILL?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly four hours, we absorbed the jolts along gutted roads,
churned through gushing rivers and twisted and turned in the rugged
mountains until finally, our battered sport utility vehicle
shuddered to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   We stepped onto a lush green plateau that was dotted with yellow
flowers, skittish goats and wooden huts. Then the people we had
been searching for came to greet us. The women stood tall and
bare-breasted, their dark brown skin stained red with ocher, their
long braids swinging below their shoulders. The men wore loincloths
and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   They smiled and gestured wordlessly at the flat rocks scattered
about the village, inviting us to sit. As the sun dropped, we
shivered by the small smoky fire and watched the children herd
goats and the women milk cows, as these nomadic shepherds have done
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dec. 29 and I was searching for a tribe with no
wristwatches, no wall calendars and no champagne to celebrate the
arrival of the year 2000. During a visit with the Himba people in
Ekambu, a village in this arid corner of northwest Namibia, my
husband, Henri, and I found a place where the electric light bulb
does not exist, the flush toilet is not yet imagined and the
priests still call to the gods and holy ancestors over the sacred
fire that burns in every village.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, a steady trickle of foreign travelers has come to
this remote region to admire the craggy terrain, the magnificent
Epupa waterfalls to the north and the desert elephants that lumber
through the Sesfontein region to the south. But nowadays, it is
often the people, not only the scenery, who draw the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Hiperue Koruhama, a villager with two wives and nine children,
had never heard of New York or the United States or the western
custom of numbering years and naming months. He told me his people
marked the new year with the coming of seasonal rains, and the
changing days and months with the sun and moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in the morning the sun is high up and the cows must go
to graze,'' Koruhama said simply, speaking in his Herero language,
while my guide interpreted. ``At sunset, the cows must come home.
That is how we live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Himba people walked into the Kaokoland region from what is
now Angola nearly 300 years ago and keep proudly to their
traditional ways. More and more Namibian lodges are advertising
guided tours to their villages, hoping to attract the planeloads of
German, Italian and Japanese tourists and the smaller number of
Americans who fly across the world to glimpse one of the last
self-sufficient tribes in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough people like this left in the world,''
said Lente Hamel, the manager of the Ohakane Lodge, one of the
hotels we stayed in during our weeklong journey. ``So people come
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But finding people truly untouched by the outside world is not
easy.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists estimate that only about 7,000 Himba live today
much as their ancestors did centuries ago, wearing animal skins,
raising cattle and moving as often as 10 times a year in search of
water and green grass for their goats and cows.
</P>
<P>
   It is often a harsh life, characterized by periods of drought
and hunger, and some Himba are giving it up, moving to towns,
finding jobs or sending their children to school. In the nearby
towns of Opuwo and Sesfontein, I found myself startled by the mix
of the modern and traditional. Young men wear baseball caps and
loincloths. And villagers sometimes cover their thatched roofs with
plastic tarpaulins to prevent leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Several lodges in those towns offer modest, welcoming rooms,
meals and daily tours of Himba villages. For many travelers, this
is the most comfortable option because the towns themselves offer
few amenities, like restaurants or movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   For tourists hoping to meet Himba people beyond the tourist
circuit, the traveling is rougher. We packed tents, sleeping bags,
mosquito netting, pots, canned food and bottled water. Ekambu is a
three-hour drive away from a working telephone. There are no
lodges, no hotels and no restaurants there.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists provide some struggling villages with desperately
needed assistance _ tour guides typically bring gifts of food on
each visit _ that helps the Himba get through lean times. But
increased contact with foreigners, who sometimes leave gifts of
alcohol and money, has also resulted in increased alcoholism and
prostitution, anthropologists and hotel owners say.
</P>
<P>
   And many tourists who arrive eager to snap photographs of the
Himba leave the villages thrilled by the people they have met, but
ambivalent about their visit. ``I was amazed by their way of
living, they're so beautiful,'' said Mariko Oura, who flew from
Japan with a large group of tourists. ``But frankly, I wonder if we
should come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They danced for us and posed for us and I took photos,'' said
Oura, an English tutor who lives outside Kobe in Japan. ``But I
wonder if everyone enjoys being photographed like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists say tourism in its worst forms carries negative
implications for the Himba. But at the same time, Margaret
Jacobsohn, who has written a book about these nomadic shepherds,
says the world should not treat the Himba like curios that must be
preserved in museums.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the arrival of growing numbers of tourists, she
says, the Himba had become increasingly exposed to the outside
world as they began to send their children to school and to mix
with foreign anthropologists and missionaries, as well as other
Namibians who wear western clothing and often work in offices and
drive cars.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many Himba dabble freely in both worlds. For instance,
Zepauandoui Koruhama, one of Koruhama's wives, told me she still
boiled the root of the sour plum tree to cure diarrhea but also
took aspirin for fever.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The Himba are changing,'' Jacobsohn said in a telephone
interview. ``It's not a static thing and it shouldn't be. People
are using both systems now. They live with a foot in each world.''
</P>
<P>
   Before taking busloads of tourists to the villages, the lodge
managers say they consult the local chief to see whether foreigners
and their cameras will be welcome there. Willy Kasupi, who works as
a guide for the Fort Sesfontein Lodge, says he tells tourists
specifically who wants to be photographed and who does not want to
have a picture taken, although he says tourists sometimes ignore
his instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people treat the villages like a zoo, which is what we
want to avoid,'' said Hamel, the manager of the Ohakane Lodge in
Opuwo. ``When we take tourists, we explain that they have to follow
the social rules of the village. You do not just walk into
someone's garden and start taking photos. It's basic. It's good
manners.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors typically start the journey in Windhoek, the capital of
Namibia, which is a two-hour flight from Johannesburg. From there,
you can rent a sport utility vehicle at the airport and take the 8-
to 10-hour drive to Sesfontein or Opuwo. Or you can charter a small
plane, which costs considerably more, and make the same journey in
about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   We flew to Sesfontein and stayed at the Fort Sesfontein Lodge,
which was built as a German fort back in 1896, when Namibia was a
German colony. The rustic lodge, while attractive, does not have
air-conditioning. But each room does have a ceiling fan, absolutely
essential if you're traveling during the hot months _ December,
January and February.
</P>
<P>
   The lodge offers day tours to Himba villages, but we wanted to
meet people unfamiliar with tourists. So we hired Kasupi, who
belongs to a tribe related to the Himba and speaks their language,
rented a sport utility from the lodge, packed our tents and
sleeping bags and drove two hours to Opuwo.
</P>
<P>
   In Opuwo, we shopped for pots, pasta, canned meatballs, fruit,
bread and bottled water. We booked rooms at the Ohakane Lodge for
our return to Opuwo and took off for Ekambu, where we pitched
tents, started a fire and cooked our pasta and meatballs and camped
for one night under the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Kasupi, who has been guiding tours for about three years now,
said that the Himba were often tickled by the idea that foreigners
wanted to visit them. ``They ask me, `Who are these people who say
they have never seen Himba?''' Kasupi said. ``They cannot imagine a
place where there are no Himba.''
</P>
<P>
   The villagers I met peppered me with questions about where I was
from. And I found myself pointing northwest, describing this huge
nation across the water called the United States, as they shook
their heads trying to imagine such a place.
</P>
<P>
   When the afternoon rains started falling, Koruhama invited me
into her thatched hut so we could talk without getting wet. I
ducked my head to enter the small doorway and sat on the blanket
she had spread out on the dirt floor. Kasupi joined us to
interpret.
</P>
<P>
   As her children ran in and out, marveling at me, an oddly
dressed stranger, Koruhama told me about her family, about the
hunger they endure during the dry season, about sending one son far
away to a western school and about her fears that the boy might
ultimately reject her people's traditional ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes are mainly touching younger people, the boys who
wear T-shirts and shorts,'' she said, sighing. ``But the older
people, they do not change. As you see, I'm still traditional. I
will always keep my lifestyle.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to visit the Himba &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 11, the State Department issued an announcement strongly
urging Americans to avoid the northern border area of Namibia,
including the entire Kavango and Caprivi regions, because fighting
in Angola has spilled over the border into Namibia on occasion. But
none of the places I visited to meet the Himba are in the region
covered by the State Department announcement. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations and Tours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Sesfontein Lodge in Sesfontein, telephone and fax
(264-61) 25-2508, is built on the striking ruins of a German fort
370 miles from Windhoek, Namibia's capital. The 12 rooms and 2
family units are modest but comfortable and the stone patio has a
lovely swimming pool. There are no phones, TV or air-conditioning,
but all rooms have ceiling fans. (The lodge's generator goes off at
11 every night.)
</P>
<P>
   During the summer season, which ends in April, rooms start at
about $122 for a double with breakfast and dinner, based on 6
Namibian dollars to the American dollar. During the fall and winter
season, which begins in May, rooms cost $155 with meals. Guided
tours accommodating up to four people cost about $208 a day in
summer and $267 in winter, with lunch. If you have a rental car and
just want to hire a guide, the day rate is about $50 through April,
$75 after.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohakane Lodge in Opuwo, (264-65) 27-3031, fax (264-65)
27-3025, is a modern, comfortable hotel about 500 miles from
Windhoek and 120 miles from Sesfontein. The lodge has small rooms
(the single rooms are very small) with air-conditioning and
telephones. Rooms start at about $83 for a double with breakfast.
Guided day tours to Himba villages that include lunch cost about
$30 a person. Five-day camping safaris cost $133 a person a day.
</P>
<P>
   Kaokohimba Safaris, telephone and fax (264-61) 22-2378, arranges
package tours for small groups to Himba villages. These include
charter flights from Windhoek, rustic lodging, tours and meals.
Rates run from $1,053 a person for three days to $2,063 a person
for 12 days. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting There &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air, (264-61) 22-8101, fax (264-61) 25-4345, offers
charter flights from Windhoek to Sesfontein and Opuwo and back. The
round-trip flight _ in single-prop planes that seat five people
with minimal luggage _ costs about $900. Bush Pilots, (264-61)
22-8316, fax (264-61) 24-5083, offers comparable fares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
