   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN --
Nathan Leventhal, president of Lincoln Center for the Performing
Arts, with Beverly Sills, chairman of the organization, during an
interview in May, 1999. In an announcement Monday, Leventhal said
he will leave his post at the end of the year but remain a member
of the board. Leventhal, 57, who is the longest tenured president
since the performing arts center was incorporated in 1956, will
step down Dec. 31. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- March 27, 2000 -- CIRCUS-PARADE --
Eight-month old twins Amina Otman, right, and Sophia Otman, look at
a parade of elephants from the Ringling Brothers, Barnum &AMP; Bailey
Circus as their brother Gabriel is temporarily distracted, Monday
in front of the Supreme Court. The circus continues its Washington
tour Tuesday night at the D.C. Armory. In the background, on the
steps of the court, are demonstrators protesting use of animals in
the circus. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-NANOTUBES -- ``Overview
of carbon microtrees of varying heights grown on a graphite
surface. A research team at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in
Troy, N.Y., has created tiny ``trees'' using flashes of extreme
heat to deposit carbon atoms in piles on a graphite surface. The
structures, which average about one one-hundredth of an inch in
height and can be as narrow as five-millionths of an inch in
diameter, are made using a process called chemical vapor
deposition, in which a graphite electrode is rapidly heated in a
pressurized atmosphere of methane and helium. (Courtesy of P.M.
Ajayan/The New York Time)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-BRODY-HEALTH -- Jessica
Turri in a scene from ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution,'' on HBO.
It is rare indeed for commercial television to produce a program of
such high quality and importance as this two-and-a-half-hour
documentary to be televised on Thursday. Turri, who at 10 received
a diagnosis of acute lymphoblastic leukemia, cannot help but bring
hope and moral support to every family facing childhood cancer. The
film follows her through the course of her treatment at St. Jude
Children's Research Hospital in Memphis and documents the
day-to-day trials of coping with cancer and its treatment. (HBO/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-CHILDREN-GRIEVE -- Dr.
Grace Hyslop Christ, author of ``Healing Children's Grief:
Surviving a Parent's Death From Cancer,'' in her office during a
recent interview. Christ's book, based on a large-scale study by
researchers at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center of families
coping with the illness and death of a parent, explores children's
ability to come to terms with their loss. (Barbara Alper/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-MOAS-EXTINCTION-2-B&AMP;W
-- Over the last 40,000 years, as anatomically modern but primitive
peoples equipped with stone-tipped weapons spread around the world,
species after species of big animal vanished from the earth in
their wake. ``Blitzkrieg'' has long been scientists' favorite image
for these spasms of biological destruction. Nowhere, perhaps, was
the extinction more striking than in New Zealand, where an entire
class of large flightless birds called moas once lived. An artist's
rendering of a moa at the American Museum of Natural History.
(American Museum of Natural History/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AUCKLAND, New Zealand -- March 27, 2000 --
SCI-MOAS-EXTINCTION-1-B&AMP;W -- Over the last 40,000 years, as
anatomically modern but primitive peoples equipped with
stone-tipped weapons spread around the world, species after species
of big animal vanished from the earth in their wake. ``Blitzkrieg''
has long been scientists' favorite image for these spasms of
biological destruction. Nowhere, perhaps, was the extinction more
striking than in New Zealand, where an entire class of large
flightless birds called moas once lived. A life-size model of a moa
at the Auckland Museum in 1997. (Lonnie Schlein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) OFF KEY LARGO, Fla. -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-CORAL-REEFS
-- Penny Bailey observes tiny eggs and sperm erupting from a
portion of the coral reefs along the Florida Keys in late
September, 1999. The federal government has issued a long-term plan
to save coral reefs along the coast of the United States and its
territories, setting aside many sites as ecological preserves over
the next 10 years. (Bob Kane, Monroe County Tourism Council/The New
York Times)
</P>
