<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- NY-FOSTER-CARE-3 --
Thousands of young adults in New York City's foster care system
have been pushed out of the system in recent years, forced as young
as 18 to fend for themselves. Sherrell F., with her daughter,
Tamara, is apartment-hunting, because in August, when she turns 18,
she will be discharged from the foster home in the Bronx where she
has been living. She expects another child in June. (James
Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- NY-FOSTER-CARE-2 --
Thousands of young adults in New York City's foster care system
have been pushed out of the system in recent years, forced as young
as 18 to fend for themselves. Jennifer Baum, a lawyer with the
Legal Aid Society, is trying to help young people make the
transition from foster homes to independence. (Suzanne DeChillo/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- NY-LIVERY-CABS -- Judging
by statistics alone, New York is relatively safer these days for
its more than 41,000 livery-cab drivers - the drivers who make up
the only cab industry in most of the city, cruising the streets
where yellow cabs are rarely seen. But don't tell that to
Lakhwander Singh, right, a livery-cab driver who was wounded by
robbers Sunday. ``They took the money, and they shot me anyway,''
said Singh, 40, who lives with his cousin, Gurinder Singh, also a
livery driver. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) DUNELLEN, N.J. -- March 27, 2000 -- NJ-FLOOD-RECOVER --
Lawrence P. Kerwin at the Dunellen Hotel, whose restaurant and bar
he and his father have operated for decades, and Bettina
DeCaumette, who is taking over. But while the two toasted to
continuity, in fact nothing will be the same. Kerwin, 74, will be
leaving the only profession he has ever known, besides a brief
stint in the military. And for Mrs. DeCaumette, life has changed
profoundly in the six months since her business in Bound Brook was
wiped out in September by the floods of Tropical Storm Floyd. (Dith
Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-SUIT --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani agreed Monday to abandon his campaign to
evict the Brooklyn Museum of Art and cut its city financing for
mounting an exhibition last year that he deemed offensive and
sacrilegious. Leaders of the museum in its case against the city
were Robert S. Rubin, left, board chairman, and Arnold L. Lehman,
the museum's director. With them was Floyd Abrams, the First
Amendment lawyer. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- NY-FOSTER-CARE --
Thousands of young adults in New York City's foster care system
have been pushed out of the system in recent years, forced as young
as 18 to fend for themselves. With her young daughter, Destiny, in
tow, Shanetta C., 18, last summer found herself at a city emergency
homeless shelter. With the help of the Emergency Assistance Unit,
Shanetta, who had run away from an abusive parent, lived on the
streets and shuttled among foster parents and group homes, finally
got a place of her own - a two-bedroom apartment in a Brooklyn
housing project. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- LEESON-AD-COLUMN --
Nicholas W. Leeson, the rogue stock trader who caused the collapse
of Britain's oldest merchant bank, Barings PLC, is appearing in a
campaign that promotes a Swedish dot-com stock trading company. It
may sound as bizarre as having the captain of the Exxon Valdez
endorse Bounty paper towels, but the commercial's creators said
bizarre was very much the point. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) SMITHVILLE, Mo. -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-DIABETES-DRUG-2
-- The removal of the diabetes drug Rezulin by the Food and Drug
Administration last week brought anger, confusion and a stream of
questions from doctors and patients alike. Shirley Griggs, shown
with her husband, Jerry, said it destroyed her liver and left her
in constant pain. Though she is now on a transplant list,
``thousands are ahead of me,'' she said. (Don Ipock/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) DARLINGTON, Md. -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-DIABETES-DRUG-1
-- The removal of the diabetes drug Rezulin by the Food and Drug
Administration last week brought anger, confusion and a stream of
questions from doctors and patients alike. Frank Hopkins, a
diabetic who raises racehorses, is upset about the removal of the
drug from the market because it greatly improved his health. ``I
think the number of people who have received a negative reaction is
so minimal, so why should the rest of us have to suffer?'' he
asked. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- TITO-OPERA-REVIEW --
Lorraine Hunt Lieberson and Kurt Streit in ``La Clemenza di Tito,''
written by Mozart shortly before his death. The opera was long
undervalued but now seems absolutely immediate. Not only is it
filled with great and glorious music - strongly presented in this
new City Opera production - but it speaks to concerns that are
ours. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) LES MAQUIGNONS, France -- March 27, 2000 --
U.S.-POET-FRANCE -- Almost 40 years ago, the poet Gustaf Sobin left
New England for Provence. He's still here. But with his third
novel, ``The Fly-Truffler,'' published in January, wider
recognition has suddenly come Sobin's way. ``Obviously I didn't
write novels for the attention, but it is certainly a pleasure to
receive,'' the 64-year-old writer said in his home - a once
abandoned stone building on the edge of town which has been
enlarged over the years to accommodate his wife, Susannah, a
painter, and their two now-grown children. (Alan Riding/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- WEST-THEATER-2 -- From
left, Philip Seymour Hoffman, John C. Reilly and Robert LuPone in
Sam Shepard's ``True West,'' which opened on Broadway to rave
reviews March 9. Portraying volatile brothers, Reilly, left, and
Hoffman switch roles every third performance. Audiences have
applauded the tactic; people leap to their feet at the end of each
performance, and the production has broken the record for weekly
gross sales at Circle in the Square Theater, with a total of
$243,063 for the week ending March 19. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- WEST-THEATER-1 --
Portraying volatile brothers, John C. Reilly, left, and Philip
Seymour Hoffman switch roles every third performance in Sam
Shepard's ``True West,'' which opened on Broadway to rave reviews
March 9. Critics seem to agree that neither casting configuration
is better than the other, and both are very good. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) HOLLYWOOD -- March 27, 2000 -- OSCARS-5 -- Warren
Beatty, the recipient of the Irving G. Thalberg Award for a
lifetime of achievement in the movie business, with presenter Jack
Nicholson at the Shrine Auditorium on Sunday night following the
Academy Awards. In accepting the award, Beatty paid tribute to his
fellow actors, to the friends who led him through his wilder single
years and to his wife, and made reference to his recent flirtation
with a campaign for president. ``If you had your choice and, say,
could have the Thalberg Award or, oh, the White House, I'd stick
with this,'' he said. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) HOLLYWOOD -- March 27, 2000 -- OSCARS-4 -- Academy Award
winner for best supporting actor, Michael Caine, after receiving
the award at the Shrine Auditorium on Sunday night. Caine won his
second award in the category for his role as an ether-sniffing
abortionist who runs an orphanage in ``The Cider House Rules.''
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ACKLEY, Iowa -- March 27, 2000 -- DISABLED-FARMERS-2 --
Darwin Hoffmeister with a modified hammer that lets him set the
nail and hammer it in using one hand. Hoffmeister, a 50-year-old
Iowa farmer, lost four fingers and the use of his left arm in a
combine accident five years ago, the kind of dreadful injury that
makes farming one of the nation's most dangerous professions.
(Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ACKLEY, Iowa -- March 27, 2000 -- DISABLED-FARMERS-1 --
Darwin Hoffmeister goes about his farming chores at his farm.
Hoffmeister, a 50-year-old Iowa farmer, lost four fingers and the
use of his left arm in a combine accident five years ago, the kind
of dreadful injury that makes farming one of the nation's most
dangerous professions. (Rodney White/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) HOLLYWOOD -- March 27, 2000 -- OSCARS-3 -- Academy Award
winner for best supporting actress, Angelina Jolie, after receiving
the award at the Shrine Auditorium on Sunday night. Jolie won the
Oscar for her turn as a hospitalized sociopath in ``Girl,
Interrupted.'' (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HOLLYWOOD -- March 27, 2000 -- OSCARS-2 -- Academy Award
winner for best actress, Hillary Swank, after receiving the award
at the Shrine Auditorium on Sunday night. The relatively
little-known Swank not only won the award for playing a young woman
who pretends to be a man in ``Boys Don't Cry,'' but she also did it
in a relatively small, independent film and in the process beat out
one of Hollywood's most popular actresses - Annette Bening. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HOLLYWOOD -- March 27, 2000 -- OSCARS-1 -- Six years
after DreamWorks SKG was founded by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen and only three years since it began
releasing movies, this mini-studio has at last risen to the top of
the pecking order with ``American Beauty,'' which was the big
winner at Sunday night's Academy Awards. Oscars were displayed by,
from left, ``American Beauty'' producer Bruce Cohen, screenwriter
Alan Ball, producer Dan Jinks, actor Kevin Spacey and director Sam
Mendes after receiving the awards at the Shrine Auditorium. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-3 -- A black
hole causes gas to swirl at high speed, and the collisions between
particles of jets release gamma rays. The rays, as seen while
looking directly down one of the jets, flare brightly. (NASA/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-2 -- A black
hole has swallowed a large amount of matter, sending a jet of
material straight up from its accretion disk. High-speed collisions
between particles of jets like this one produce gamma rays.
(NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-GAMMA-RAYS-1 -- A
computer animation shows how black holes could cause gamma rays,
which come from violent cosmic phenomena. A black hole causes gas
to swirl at high speed, and the colliding particles release rays.
(NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-2 --
Joseph F. Lovett, the host of ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution,''
to be aired at 8 p.m. Eastern time March 30 on HBO. It is rare for
commercial television to produce a program of such high quality and
importance as the two-and-a-half-hour documentary, which HBO is
making available to all cable subscribers, even those who do not
have access to the premium channel. Why? Because there is not a
family in America that has not been or will not be touched by
cancer. (Will Hart/HBO)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-BLACK-HOLES -- Dr.
Richard W. Pogge and Paul Martini used an infrared camera on the
Hubble Space Telescope to take pictures of the centers of 24 bright
nearby galaxies suspected of harboring black holes and combined
them with visible-light images in order to compensate for the
brightness of the stars and to bring out the faint dust clouds. The
resulting images of 20 of the galaxies show dust swirling around a
center where, presumably, a black hole is gobbling it up. (NASA/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) CANTON, Mass. -- March 27, 2000 -- DOCTOR-PLEA-BOS --
Dr. Sondra Crosby plays with her three adopted daughters, from top,
Madison, from China, Isatu, 8, and Nanah, 6, both from Sierra
Leone. Tending to her children's medical needs, Crosby found
herself on the other side of the waiting-room door. Her experience
resulted in an essay published by the Journal of the American
Medical Association titled ``A Mother's Prayer.'' The essay is part
mea culpa, part raw assessment of her experiences, and a plea to do
something about a medical industry directed more by profits than
patience. (Pat Greenhouse/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-NANOTUBES-2-B&AMP;W -- As
viewed through an electron microscope, ``craters'' that remained on
the graphite surface after the ``trees,'' created in a laboratory
in Troy, N.Y., were broken off. A research team at Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute has created tiny ``trees'' using flashes of
extreme heat to deposit carbon atoms in piles on a graphite
surface. The structures are made using a process called chemical
vapor deposition, in which a graphite electrode is rapidly heated
in a pressurized atmosphere of methane and helium. (Courtesy of
P.M. Ajayan/The New York Time)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HEMINGWAY, S.C. -- March 27, 2000 -- BAHAI-RADIO-2 --
Williamsburg County, a rural slice of the Bible Belt an hour's
drive from the Atlantic coast, is just the place one expects to
find religious radio. Yet it is this setting that makes WLGI, a
50,000-watt FM station outside this small town, such a surprise. To
listeners, WLGI is known as ``Radio Baha'i,'' a 15-year-old project
of one of the world's newer religions, a monotheistic faith that
emerged in 19th century Persia, now Iran. Ernest Hilton, assistant
manager of WLGI, pitches a ball during a kick ball game at the
Louis Gregory Institute owned by the Baha'i. (Wade Spees/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HEMINGWAY, S.C. -- March 27, 2000 -- BAHAI-RADIO-1 --
Williamsburg County, a rural slice of the Bible Belt an hour's
drive from the Atlantic coast, is just the place one expects to
find religious radio. Yet it is this setting that makes WLGI, a
50,000-watt FM station outside this small town, such a surprise. To
listeners, WLGI is known as ``Radio Baha'i,'' a 15-year-old project
of one of the world's newer religions, a monotheistic faith that
emerged in 19th century Persia, now Iran. Johnathan Graham, disc
jockey and music director for WLGI, selects music for his
broadcast. In the bacground, from left, is Nancy Nawi, Lanita
Barnes and Laurie Cohen. (Wade Spees/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- SCI-HEISENBERG-BOMB --
Physicists and historians gathered in Manhattan on Monday to
discuss the issues raised by Michael Frayn's play, ``Copenhagen,''
which deals with the relationship between quantum theorists Niels
Bohr and Werner Heisenberg and the German atomic bomb project. Hans
Bethe, left, and John Wheeler, contemporaries of Borh and
Hersenberg, on a Manhattan street, Monday. (Keith Meyers/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 27, 2000 -- LINCOLN-CENTER-RESIGN --
Nathan Leventhal, president of Lincoln Center for the Performing
Arts on Monday. Leventhal announced Monday that he will leave his
post at the end of the year but remain a member of the board.
Leventhal, 57, who is the longest tenured president since the
performing arts center was incorporated in 1956, will step down
Dec. 31. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
