<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DORISMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LESSONS FROM THE DORISMOND FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 28:
</P>
<P>
   The mourners who erupted in violence at Patrick Dorismond's
funeral on Saturday made the event immeasurably more painful for
the Dorismond family _ and were playing with the kind of fire that
easily burns out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The melee, which ended with two dozen police officers injured
and 27 civilians arrested, was less serious than it might have
been, thanks to police officers who behaved with restraint and
civilians who urged fellow mourners back from the brink of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the violence at the funeral was proof that New York
City has reached a critical juncture in its race relations. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, whose comments over the weekend continued to
raise tensions in the black community, needs to reach out and start
a dialogue with the black elected officials he has previously
shunned.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating tensions stem from events on March 16, when
Dorismond, a security guard, became the fourth unarmed black man to
be shot to death by the police in little more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, despite the absence of conclusive facts about how the
incident had unfolded, defended the police and described Dorismond
as a violent person whose actions may have provoked the shooting.
Giuliani tried to support that claim in part by releasing
information from sealed juvenile records dating to when Dorismond
was 13 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor came under heavy criticism for failing to express
sympathy for the grieving Dorismond family, but on Sunday he
finally began to make amends with an expression of sympathy for any
parent who loses a child.
</P>
<P>
   But even then the mayor promptly returned to maligning and
blaming the victim. He reiterated that Dorismond recently hit his
girlfriend in the face and suggested that the dead man's
temperament had led to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   For the good of the city, the mayor needs to put aside this
inflammatory line of discourse and wait for the Manhattan district
attorney to complete his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Giuliani needs to confer with black elected
officials, many of whom feel shut out at City Hall. A
well-publicized meeting with those officials would show New Yorkers
that Giuliani recognizes the seriousness of the rift that exists
between the police and the community _ and is seeking insights on
how to bridge the gap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
