<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE'S COACH CONFRONTS AND ADMIRES THE OPPOSITION  

</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Growing up in Raleigh, N.C., Jerry Dunn had limited
choices in television viewing. He recalls Saturdays filled with
Atlantic Coast Conference basketball and Sunday mornings devoted to
replays of Notre Dame and Penn State football.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn developed an appreciation for ACC basketball and for the
success of Penn State and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, things are going to look very familiar to Dunn,
Penn State's coach, when the National Invitation Tournament
semifinals get under way at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State (20-12) will face Wake Forest (20-14) in
the first game at 7 p.m. Eastern time, and Dunn's Nittany Lions
(18-15) will play Notre Dame (21-14) in the second semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   If Dunn can find a way to tame Notre Dame forward Troy Murphy,
who is averaging 22.9 points and 10.5 rebounds a game, then Penn
State will get a chance to appear in its second NIT championship
game in three years. In 1998, Penn State lost to Minnesota, 79-72.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a guy like Troy Murphy, you have to get him the
ball,'' Dunn said. ``But I don't think Notre Dame is a
one-dimensional team. They have other guys who can score also.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame Coach Matt Doherty has brought his team to New York
for the second time this month. The team was here earlier for the
Big East tournament. Notre Dame had thought that a good showing
would produce a bid to the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really disappointed we didn't get into the NCAA
tournament,'' Murphy said. ``But Coach Doherty told us that we had
to get over it and get excited about playing in the NIT. If we win
the NIT championship, then it will show that the NCAA. was wrong
about us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wake Forest and North Carolina State, this will be a rerun
of the head-banging matchups they experienced during the season.
The teams split games during the regular season, each winning on
its home court. But the teams did not meet in the ACC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden will present the perfect neutral site for this
all-ACC matchup.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State went through a seven-game losing streak
late in the season but reversed the trend just in time for the ACC
tournament and for postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   But Coach Herb Sendek said that, in a strange way, the streak
brought his Wolfpack team closer and made his players tougher for
the NIT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
