<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EXUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN EXUM, 88, MOUNTAIN CLIMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glenn Exum, a mountain climber who conquered the summits of the
Alps and the Rockies and shared his experience with hundreds of
others through his guide service, died on March 17 at his home in
Littleton, Colo. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   A tall, debonair man, Exum established one of the routes to the
peak of Grand Teton in 1931. He climbed what came to be known as
the Exum Ridge of that Wyoming mountain in a pair of
leather-cleated football shoes. His path had required jumping a
chasm, which later climbers learned to climb around.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Williamson, a former president of the American Alpine Club,
said that Exum studied European methods of guiding climbers in the
1930s and worked to change them. Those methods, Williamson said,
essentially involved tying a rope around the climbers and pulling
them up the mountain whenever they encountered difficulty. Then,
rather than rappelling down on their own, they would often be
lowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn's idea was that people ought to be responsible,''
Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Exum was born in Topaz, Idaho, on June 24, 1911. He had
taught music at a high school in Pocatello, Idaho. Building on his
passion for the outdoors, he climbed extensively in both the
Rockies and the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   He began working with Paul Petzoldt, the legendary mountaineer
and climbing instructor, in Petzoldt's guide service in Grand Teton
National Park, and took over the service in 1955. Now called the
Exum Mountain Guide Service, it has the concession from the
National Park Service for climbing instruction in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Al Read, the president of the guide service, said that Exum had
introduced courses to teach students technical skills. ``People can
now feel proud of what they're doing, instead of just being dragged
up something,'' Read said.
</P>
<P>
   Exum is survived by his wife, the former Beth Pauline Noben; his
son, Edward, of Denver; and his daughter, Glenda, of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, colon cancer was diagnosed in Exum, and he had several
operations, largely withdrawing from guiding and climbing.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1981 he climbed Grand Teton to observe the 50th
anniversary of scaling his ridge. He said that it was a privilege
to climb the peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Teton is endlessly different, with its changing
moods and attitudes, its eternal beauty,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2233EST &QL; 
