<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT &LR;      03-27 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING AGAIN FINDS HIMSELF AT THE CENTER OF CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ After three years of dizzying injuries, the
rumpled, old Patrick Ewing has emerged from the spin cycle as fresh
and bright as clean laundry.
</P>
<P>
   He feels great, looks rejuvenated and is waving for the ball as
if it were the spring of '97.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, he was at his lifesaving best in the last 33
seconds. He sank two free throws under hostile conditions in
Portland. Then, as an encore, he swatted a runner by Scottie Pippen
to douse the Trail Blazers' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   On other nights, he has not been so perfect in his effort to
recreate the past. When faced with Shaquille O'Neal on March 19,
Ewing felt so spry he tried to match the Lakers' powerful superstar
by taking 20 shots. He only made six of them in the Knicks' loss.
When the Knicks were in the midst of a mental meltdown against the
Indiana Pacers two days later, Ewing took 6 of his 18 shots in the
fourth quarter. He made only one.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks are living or dying by the grace or the
gaffe of Ewing. Even on the nights he has successfully turned back
the clock _ as in the aftermath of Sunday's game _ he still gets
questioned about his shot-happy tendencies. Lately, there has also
been an undercurrent of concern from a couple of Ewing's teammates.
Privately, they are thrilled with their proud star's ability to
contribute but a bit unsettled by the gradual return of a
Ewing-based offense.
</P>
<P>
   To Ewing, it is all just the same background noise he has been
ignoring for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to grumble,'' Ewing said. ``You have your
critics. I feel that I still have a lot of basketball in me. Like
I've said before, when they call my number, I've got to step up and
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   His career has been punctuated by great moments and blown
opportunities. Year after year, the burden was on Ewing. But with
the development of Allan Houston and the acquisition of Latrell
Sprewell, the pressure was supposed to be dispersed. When Ewing was
forced to step back as he played through pain last season, Houston
and Sprewell took on the nightly load. Then the two players pushed
onward the day Ewing sustained a partly torn Achilles' tendon
during the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Until Ewing returned in December, Houston and Sprewell were
still leading the team. While there is no doubt the Knicks are
better with Ewing, how much of him is too much of a good thing?
</P>
<P>
   In the months since Ewing came back, Houston's shot attempts
have dropped from 17 a game in December to 14.3 so far in March.
Sprewell's attempts took a dip from 16.7 a night in December to
13.8 in February, before going back up to 16 this month. In that
same period, Ewing's average attempts have risen from 10 in
December to 13.6 over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of the adjustments, the Knicks have struggled to
find a rhythm. Right now, they are humming along well enough. They
are tied with Miami for the lead in the Atlantic Division and are
coming off their most impressive road victory of the season _
courtesy of Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone seems to think the champion is going to come out of
the West,'' Ewing said. ``We want to make a statement that if we
get there, we have as good a chance to win a title as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks looked like top contenders Sunday night as they broke
out of their funk on the road against an elite team and began their
five-game West Coast swing with a victory. They will face the
Sacramento Kings on Tuesday night. With that in mind, Sprewell
said: ``It was just one game. If we finish this road trip the way
we started it, then we can say we made strides.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they can say they have found a groove. To this point,
everyone has been up and down. Ewing, in particular, has been prone
to rise and fall. At age 37, he can't bounce back the way he used
to. Even when he does, he is still asked about the appropriate size
of his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat has been here the longest,'' Larry Johnson said. ``'By
now, he knows how to take it all in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has been the core of the Knicks' world for the better part
of 15 years. After three seasons interrupted by injuries, Ewing is
focused on regaining his elite form _ or as close to it as age will
allow. An hour before the team bus departed their Portland hotel,
Ewing was already at the Rose Garden shooting jumpers. He just
keeps working, keeps shooting, no matter what anyone says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to defend,'' Ewing said. ``I think my
career speaks for itself. I'm not going to sit here and try to
defend myself or my career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
