<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIRELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRIMBLE'S NARROW VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 28:
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, who survived an unexpectedly strong challenge to
win re-election as head of the Ulster Unionist Party over the
weekend, is the most enlightened political leader Northern
Ireland's Protestant majority has yet produced.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his tactical maneuvers have been questionable. But
without his principled commitment to political power-sharing
between Protestants and Roman Catholics and respect for the civil
rights of all, there would have been no Good Friday peace agreement
two years ago and little hope for reviving Northern Ireland's
suspended home-rule government today.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial minority of Ulster Unionists has resisted
Trimble's peacemaking. Roughly 42 percent of party delegates
opposed his decision to join the home rule cabinet last November.
Some 43 percent voted Saturday to replace Trimble with the Rev.
Martin Smyth, an opponent of the Good Friday agreement. In both
votes Trimble was weakened by the Irish Republican Army's refusal
to commit itself to giving up its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Besides re-electing Trimble, the Ulster Unionists also voted not
to participate again in a home rule government unless Britain
abandoned its plan to change the name of the province's police
force, now known as the Royal Ulster Constabulary, to the Northern
Ireland Police Service.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's top official on Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, is
right in refusing to back down on the planned name change. The new
title is part of a wider police reform designed to create trust and
aid recruitment in the Catholic community. Currently the force is
more than 90 percent Protestant in a province that is almost 40
percent Catholic. With home rule suspended, it is especially
important that other reforms, like the police changes, go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble must take care to bring his party along with him. But he
should not modify his own progressive positions to accommodate
party opponents. In particular, he should not retreat from his
recently stated view that he would be willing to bring his party
back into a Northern Ireland government once the IRA made a firm
commitment to disarm, without waiting for the actual handover of
weapons to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA should respond by reviving and amplifying the proposal
it made and then withdrew in early February suggesting a
``context'' that would lead it to disarm. Trimble's strong
leadership will be needed as Northern Ireland pursues its quest for
a lasting peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
