<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYMOND KATZ, 83, A PRODUCER FOR TV, FILM AND THE THEATER 
KLAUS PIPER, GERMAN PUBLISHER, 88  
 ALBERT R. CONNELLY, ANTITRUST LAWYER, 91
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond Katz, a television and theatrical producer and a
personal manager, died on Thursday at a hospital in Los Angeles. He
was 83 and lived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1985 Katz, with his partner and cousin Sandy
Gallin, ran a management and production business that created
television shows starring some of the most popular entertainers of
the day. Among their hits were the series ``Donny and Marie'' and
the Emmy Award-winning ``Sold Out,'' starring Lily Tomlin and Kate
Smith, as well as specials featuring Cher, Mac Davis, Paul Lynde,
Dolly Parton and Olivia Newton John.
</P>
<P>
   They moved to television films in the early 1980s, producing
``The Miracle Worker'' with Melissa Gilbert and Patty Duke, ``Diary
of Anne Frank,'' ``Choices of the Heart,'' ``Family Secrets,''
``Splendor in the Grass'' and ``Without Her Consent.''
</P>
<P>
   They also produced the NBC mini-series ``Mussolini: The Untold
Story,'' starring George C. Scott, and ``Stagecoach,'' a CBS remake
of the John Ford Western, with Willie Nelson, Kris Kristofferson
and Johnny Cash.
</P>
<P>
   A native of New York, Katz began his career as the stage manager
of the Capitol Theater on Broadway. After directing the NBC ``Navy
Hour'' during World War II he accepted the position of program
director with MGM's New York radio station, WHN, where he created a
syndication division for original programming that presented weekly
series like ``Maisie,'' with Ann Sothern; ``Hardy Family,'' with
Mickey Rooney; and ``Woman of the Year,'' with Bette Davis. He
retired in 1960 to focus on personal management.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Katz produced the film ``I'm Gonna Git You Sucka,'' a
spoof of '70s blaxploitation movies, for United Artists. He also
produced several Broadway shows in the '80s, including ``Monday
After the Miracle.'' In 1991 he joined Herman Rush to establish
Katz-Rush Entertainment, which produced 13 episodes of ``The New
Original Amateur Hour'' for the Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KLAUS PIPER, GERMAN PUBLISHER, 88 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Piper, a German publisher who helped build his family's
business into one of Europe's most respected intellectual imprints,
died on Saturday at his home in Munich. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Piper (pronounced PEE-per) learned the trade after joining his
family's publishing house in 1932 as an apprentice. The
Munich-based firm R. Piper Verlag was founded in 1904 by his
father, Reinhard, who grounded it in philosophy, literature and the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   When his father died in 1953, Klaus Piper took the helm and
broadened the Piper catalog to encompass history, politics and the
natural and social sciences. His stable of internationally known
authors included the German philosopher and psychopathologist Karl
Jaspers, the German-American political theorist Hannah Arendt, the
violinist Yehudi Menuhin and the pianist Alfred Brendel.
</P>
<P>
   He personally brought Kurt Vonnegut Jr. into the fold with the
1977 publication of Vonnegut's novel ``Slapstick,'' translated into
German, no mean feat considering the author's inimitable style.
Complimented on his ``large vision,'' Vonnegut, on a visit to
Frankfurt, said it was obvious that Piper was ``the publisher for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Piper, who spoke English and French, agreed: ``I don't publish
books, I publish authors.''
</P>
<P>
   He sold his majority share in Piper Verlag to the Swedish
publishing group Bonnier in 1994, saying he wanted to assure the
company's future. Until two years ago he remained an adviser to the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   His survivors include his wife and five children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALBERT R. CONNELLY, ANTITRUST LAWYER, 91 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Albert R. Connelly, a retired partner at the New York
law firm of Cravath, Swaine &AMP; Moore, died at his home in Manhattan
last Wednesday. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly spent his entire professional career, from 1932 to
1978, at the law firm. He became a partner in 1941 and practiced in
many fields. He was particularly well known as a litigator and an
antitrust lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He argued nine cases before the Supreme Court, including United
States vs. Penn-Olin in 1964, a case in which he obtained an
affirmation of a lower-court ruling that allowed a joint venture
between two large companies that were potential competitors, the
Pennwalt Corp. and the Olin Mathieson Chemical Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Ray Connelly was born on Nov. 24, 1908, in Manhattan. He
graduated from Yale University and Yale Law School. From 1957 to
1958, he was chairman of the executive committee of the City Bar
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's wife, Eleanor, died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two daughters, Mary C. Graff of Urbanna, Va.,
and Jean C. Mooney of Healdsburg, Calif.; two granddaughters and
one great-grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
