<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS WAIVE HUDSON, SIGN BOHANNON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They didn't exactly super-size their situation,
but - for the Clippers - it was a relatively ``big'' move.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Troy Hudson is out.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward Etdrick Bohannon is in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to bring in another `big','' interim head coach Jim
Todd said Monday after the Clippers waived the 6-foot Hudson and
signed the 6-9 Bohannon to a 10-day contract. ``We felt we needed
extra energy inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy just got caught up in a numbers game ... we have a lot of
guys who can play the point guard position.''
</P>
<P>
   Clipper Tyrone Nesby, Hudson's best friend on the team, former
teammate at Sioux Falls of the CBA and an acquaintance since their
days on the high school circuit in southern Illinois, thinks there
were other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upset,'' Nesby said of Hudson, who averaged 8.8 points
and 3.9 assists in 62 games, ``because he knew he gave it
everything he had. He might think it's a personal thing between him
and the coach. I feel the same thing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing personal,'' Todd said of Hudson, who contributed
6.8 points per game last season after being rescued from the CBA
for the final 25 games. ``Somebody had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But things are far from gloomy in the Hudson camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy,'' said Hudson's agent, Bill Neff, who was hoping
the Clippers would pass on their option to pick up his client's
contract for next season. ``We saw it as a dead end there. We just
wish they had done it sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff also earned his percentage by throwing in a few
client-specific numbers. When Hudson played 30 or more minutes this
season for the 14-57 Clippers, they were 10-16.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are other factors involved in that record, but Neff
will stay the statistical course in his attempt to place Hudson
with another team next season. Any team hiring the former Southern
Illinois University star this season would not be able to suit him
up for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN IS GAINING: Bohannon, a springy 235-pounder from San
Bernardino, Calif. (not to mention a prep school and three
universities), averaged 12.5 points and 10.7 rebounds in 39 games
with the CBA's Fort Wayne Fury. Before joining the New York Knicks
on a recent 10-day contract, he had 21 rebounds in the CBA All-Star
game.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival was inspired by several nagging injuries currently
afflicting front-court Clippers. Maurice Taylor (ankle), Lamar Odom
(calf) and Keith Closs (asthma) will not play tonight against
Dallas at Staples Center. Nesby injured the middle finger of his
shooting hand against Detroit last Saturday; he didn't practice
Monday, but did have the finger X-rayed. Eric Piatkowski (back
spasms) also didn't practice, but expects to play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
