</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINKING RANGERS GIVE UP 14 GOALS IN CONSECUTIVE LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The boos grew louder each time Theo Fleury touched
the puck. By the time the Detroit Red Wings completed their 6-0
victory, all of the Rangers deserved to be booed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at the Garden, Fleury went another game without a
goal. He has just 15 this season _ one more than his career-low _
in 77 games.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury and Valery Kamensky, who was also a target of audience's
wrath, were acquired during the off season from Colorado to
jump-start the offense. But neither player has provided any
production on offense.
</P>
<P>
   With four games left in their season, the Rangers are on the
brink of playoff elimination. They have lost their last five games
by a combined score of 27-10. The Red Wings outscored the Rangers
by 14-2 the last two days. They have not given up 14 goals in
consecutive games since 1993. That season they lost seven of their
last 12 games and Coach Roger Neilson was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star Game break, the Rangers are 6-15-4 and have
dropped a season-high 9 games under .500, at 29-38-11. The Rangers
are 1-8-1 over their last ten games. They are mired in eleventh
place in the Eastern Conference. They are playing out the string.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sunday's 8-2 thumping in Detroit, the Rangers peppered
the Detroit goaltender Chris Osgood, who made 40 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been so bad as of late that ABC announced
Monday that it would not broadcast the originally scheduled
Rangers-Bruins game in Boston on Saturday. The game had been
scheduled for a national broadcast at 1 P.M., Eastern time. The
Rangers-Bruins game has been rescheduled for 4 P.M.
</P>
<P>
   Fans began the chants of ``Fire Muckler!'' midway through the
second period, directed at Coach John Muckler, after the Red Wings
_ who received two goals from their captain, Steve Yzerman _ had
opened a 3-0 lead on Mike Richter at 12 minutes 29 seconds on a
Brent Gilchrist goal. Todd Gill, Kirk Maltby and Tomas Holmstrom
scored the other goals for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The chants for Muckler's job grew louder in the third period.
The boos rang in Fleury's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Richter would probably welcome a fresh slate. After a brilliant
first half, Richter's season has also disintegrated since the
All-Star Game break. The Rangers' sole All-Star representative,
Richter has lost his last seven starts, allowing a total of 28
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are in danger of finishing out the season on a
nine-game losing streak. Monday night's loss guaranteed that the
team will have a losing record at the Garden for the third
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers cannot win either at home or on the road. Muckler is
certain to be fired after this season. The only real question
facing the Rangers is will team president and general manager Neil
Smith go, too.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's biggest signing, Fleury, has become the poster child for
the fading Rangers this season, but not in the way either he or the
Rangers envisioned when Fleury signed a 3-year, $21 million
contract last summer, one that is paying Fleury $8.5 million this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury will likely finish this season among the top 10 in the
National Hockey League in assists. But Fleury is being paid to
score goals. And that has not been lost on the Garden crowd, as it
watches the Rangers miss out on the playoffs for the third
consecutive year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
