a f BC-UAW-KAN &LR;      03-27 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAYCOMO WORKERS AUTHORIZE STRIKE IF NEGOTIATIONS FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER, KNIGHT-RIDDER NEWSPAPERS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Workers at Ford Motor Co.'s Claycomo plant
have authorized union leaders to call a strike if local
negotiations don't produce a new agreement with the automaker.
</P>
<P>
   About 99 percent of those who voted over the weekend approved
the move, said Jerry Kline, president of United Auto Workers Local
249.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Local 249 officials have negotiated for several months
without reaching a local agreement that supplements the national
contract settled in September.
</P>
<P>
   Kline said several health and safety issues remained unresolved.
In one dispute, the union is seeking a separate entrance for
commercial tractor-trailers doing business at the plant. The union
says truck traffic is a danger to employees as they arrive for and
leave their shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Kline said the two sides continued meeting through the weekend
in an attempt to reach a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The strike authorization vote is another step in the process of
negotiations in case union officials think a strike is necessary.
UAW officers from the international office in Detroit have also
begun participating in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it was optimistic that a local contract would be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to them with an eye toward resolving any
potential problems,'' said Ed Miller, a Ford spokesman at its
Dearborn, Mich., headquarters. ``These kind of votes are part of
the process, and we respect them for taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the last local strike at a Ford plant was in Atlanta
in 1986, lasting 26 days. The last time the UAW struck Ford
nationwide was 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history of getting these things settled,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant employs about 4,900 hourly employees. The
plant builds the Ford F-series pickup truck and is in the process
of launching a compact sport-utility vehicle called the Escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
