<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURTON-EMAILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN LAWMAKER SEEKS SPECIAL COUNSEL IN E-MAIL FEUD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee asked the Justice Department on Monday to appoint a
special counsel to investigate whether the White House obstructed
justice by failing to surrender e-mail messages that had been
subpoenaed by Congress and other investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who is a frequent critic
of Attorney General Janet Reno's, said that Reno and her deputies
faced a conflict of interest in pursuing the inquiry because of
what he described as their longstanding unwillingness to
investigate allegations of wrongdoing at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you and your staff are in charge, the proposed
investigation is fatally flawed,'' Burton said Monday in a letter
to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing consensus that you were, and are, unable to
supervise investigations involving the president, the vice
president and your political party,'' he said. ``For that reason, I
call on you to appoint a special counsel to investigate the
obstruction of justice charges against the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's chief spokesman, Myron Marlin, said in an
interview that Burton's letter was under review to see if ``yet
another outside investigator is truly necessary.'' He noted that
Robert Ray, the independent counsel in the investigation of the
Whitewater case and other issues, was also studying the handling of
the e-mail matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced last week that it had begun a
criminal investigation into whether White House officials illegally
suppressed e-mail messages that had been subpoenaed in
investigations of Clinton administration fund-raising and other
activities.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the department said it was also looking into
accusations that White House officials had threatened employees of
a private contractor, warning them not to discuss that the messages
were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry by the campaign finance unit at the Justice
Department started after Republicans accused the White House of
concealing private electronic communications that had been sought
by investigators in Congress, the Justice Department and Ray's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who succeeded Kenneth Starr, was appointed under terms of
an independent counsel law that expired last year. Aides to Burton
said that he wanted a so-called special counsel appointed under
regulations put in place last year that allow the attorney general
to seek an independent investigator when the department faces a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker's letter said that ``the individual chosen should
be completely independent, should have no current ties to the
Justice Department and should be seen by the American people to be
fair and impartial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
