u k BC-EDIT-GAYS-MILITARY-NY     03-27 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAYS-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HARASSMENT OF GAYS IN THE MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 28:
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Pentagon's inspector general should bring a dose
of reality to any military leaders who still refuse to believe that
anti-gay bias is a pervasive problem. Of the more than 71,000
officers and enlisted personnel surveyed, the overwhelming majority
said that anti-gay attitudes were common and to some extent even
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered the survey last December
after an Army private was convicted of murdering a gay soldier with
a baseball bat. The survey was conducted at 38 bases and on 11
ships and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   An alarming 37 percent of those responding reported that they
had witnessed or experienced harassment based on sexual orientation
in the past year. The harassment included such incidents as
vandalism, threats, unfair discipline, discrimination in career
opportunities and even physical assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a
legal aid group, also issued an annual report asserting that
incidents of verbal abuse and physical assaults against gay and
lesbian service members had more than doubled last year from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   These bleak results show that commanders are not doing enough to
root out abuse. Cohen is appointing a committee of senior military
and civilian leaders to review the survey results and draft a
corrective plan. Commanders need to make punishing harassers a
priority, and they must be held accountable for violations of the
Clinton administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that policy needs to change. Banning gays from
serving openly only creates a hostile atmosphere. For years,
military leaders have argued that the presence of openly gay
service members would threaten unit cohesion and morale. But as
Cohen noted, it is harassment that now seriously undermines good
order and discipline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
