<SLUG> BC-BANKONE-DIMON-600&AMP;ADD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK ONE CORP. NAMES DIMON CHAIRMAN AND CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change Bank to Banc in Banc of America Securities.)  
(mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank One Corp., rocked by a series of management blunders and
earnings shortfalls following one of the biggest mergers in banking
history, on Monday named James Dimon as its chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon, 44, one of the most well-regarded executives on Wall
Street, is himself a casualty of the recent merger boom in banking.
He was forced out of the presidency of financial-services giant
Citigroup in 1998 after an acrimonious and highly publicized
falling out with that company's co-chief executive, Sanford I.
Weill.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon faces an enormous challenge in turning around Bank One,
which is based in Chicago and has seen its profitability shredded
by, among other things, serious problems at its enormous credit
card operation, First USA. Bank One, which has $269.4 billion in
assets and is the fourth-largest bank in the country, has been the
subject of rampant takeover speculation ever since it began
announcing earnings shortfalls last August.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon said in a conference call Monday that the bank was not for
sale and that the company's board shared his desire to keep Bank
One independent. Dimon said the board had not given him a deadline
for restoring Bank One's profitability and reviving employee
morale.
</P>
<P>
   While Dimon, who goes by the nickname Jamie, is considered
extremely capable, his experience has largely been limited to the
corridors of Wall Street investment banks, not the hallways of Main
Street retail banks like Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie's young, he's inspiring, he's charismatic, and he's got
proven leadership abilities,'' said David Berry, a banking analyst
with Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods. ``On the other hand, he's never run a
bank before _ he's a brokerage guy and I would have thought he
would have stayed on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimon, however, took issue with that viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we had a big retail brokerage
operation,'' said Dimon, referring to his tenure overseeing
Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney investment banking unit. ``I think
that's fundamentally inaccurate because I understand retail
financial services.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Dimon's new job leaked out before the close of stock
market trading Monday, and Bank One's share price rose smartly on
an otherwise lackluster day for bank stocks. In trading on the New
York Stock Exchange, the shares rose $2.75, to $31.125, on
extremely heavy volume. Just last May, Bank One's shares were
trading at a 52-week high of $63.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon, who is moving his family to Chicago from New York, said
he plans to spend $2 million of his own money snapping up Bank One
shares. He declined to say how much Bank One was paying him to come
aboard, but his days on Wall Street and as Weill's right-hand man
had already left him a very wealthy man. His departure from
Citigroup alone netted him a severance package valued at about $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the musical-chairs-like quality of Monday's
announcement, Verne G. Istock, who has been Bank One's acting chief
executive since December, will leave that post but remain as
president. Istock replaced the bank's former chief executive, John
B. McCoy, who was forced to resign by the board because of the
managerial snafus and financial mishaps at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One was created by the 1998 merger of McCoy's bank, Bank
One of Columbus, Ohio, and Istock's bank, First Chicago NBD. At the
time of the merger, it was heralded as yet another example of the
advantages of size and consolidation in the banking industry. Yet
Bank One's problems have shown that size, untethered to realistic
business strategies or sound management, can quickly overwhelm
corporate managers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other banks, including First Union and Bank of America, have
been plagued with post-merger problems, while still others, like
Wells Fargo and Citigroup, have fared relatively well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is how do you run a big regional bank?'' said
Keefe Bruyette's Berry. ``Some have done it well in recent years
and some have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said, however, that Dimon had a good chance of
reversing Bank One's downward spiral. His biggest challenge will be
reviving the credit card operation _ the second-largest in the
country after Citigroup _ which in good times contributed as much
as a third of Bank One's total profits. Bank One also recently put
its online banking operation, Wingspan, up for sale in yet another
blow to the bank's credibility. Bankers with direct knowledge of
Wingspan's financial statements said that Bank One lost about $150
million in pretax dollars on the venture last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that I don't think the problems at Bank
One are intractable, despite how badly things have gone at First
USA,'' said Diane Glossman, an analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``I
don't think it's something that a dynamic, creative executive can't
address.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank One began searching for a new chief executive in
mid-January. It initially contacted 32 candidates for the job,
winnowing that list down to 10 executives who were interviewed. Of
that group, five executives were interviewed in depth. By late last
week, the survivors of the search were Dimon and Lewis W. Coleman,
the chairman of Bank of America's investment banking arm, Banc of
America Securities. Coleman was unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When Citicorp and Travelers Group merged in 1998 to form
Citigroup, Dimon was widely considered to be the person most likely
to run what is now the largest financial services concern in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon had spent years assisting Weill as he built Travelers from
the ground up into a major player in the insurance industry and on
Wall Street. The two men were very close, and many around them
considered them to be almost like a father and a son.
</P>
<P>
   But, following the departure of Weill's daughter from Travelers,
and in other twists worthy of Shakespeare, Weill eventually
maneuvered to have Dimon forced out of Citigroup just a few months
after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been periodic speculation about Dimon's
next move, speculation that ended Monday. Dimon joked freely Monday
about his ouster from Citigroup, saying he hoped it was the last
time in his career he would lose his job that way.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Citigroup has been pegged as one of the companies
that might attempt to buy Bank One some day _ a deal that, if it
were to occur, would return Dimon to his former employer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
