<HEADLINE>
GUIDEBOOKS FOR A WILD NATION 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some important guidebooks are shelved not in the travel section
but over in the nature section of the bookstore, keeping company
with ``Silent Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   These books enable us to say, ``Ah, bluebonnets!'' to the
wildflower that briefly rolls blue waves across Texas, and explain
to children why the mangrove is the way it is. Our family's packing
lists include books about the natural phenomena of an area, along
with walking maps and museum guides, because discussing things by
name is more satisfying and takes us deeper into a place. And not
incidentally, because ``What's that?'' is a classic stumper from
kids.
</P>
<P>
   The point was underlined last month by a Nature Conservancy
report that the biodiversity of the United States was greater than
expected: It was found to be home to 200,000 native species, double
the previous estimates, although 7 percent of the species were
found to be critically imperiled. The United States ranked first,
for example, in freshwater mussels, with 292 types, and sixth in
types of mammals, with 416. In some more ordinary categories, the
United States also has an important place, for instance in
needle-leafed evergreens, or gymnosperms _ pines included _ of
which there are 114 varieties, giving the country second place in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   For helping put names to what we see, there are several major
book series and one just making a debut.
</P>
<P>
   The Peterson Field Guides, which many of us grew up with, are
prospering with more than 50 titles. The National Audubon Society
Field Guides have been standards for 20 years and appear in both
regional and subject-oriented volumes. The National Geographic, in
addition to its titles like ``National Parks'' and ``State Parks,''
is just publishing the first volumes in a new series, ``Guide to
America's Outdoors.'' The Smithsonian Guides to Natural America, a
series that appeared five years ago, is, alas, being phased out.
</P>
<P>
   Although paperbacks, all of these share a drawback: They are
heavy. This is probably inevitable, considering color pictures are
printed on coated paper. Peterson First Guides ($5.95), for
beginners, are compact and lighter, but rudimentary.
</P>
<P>
   Mysteries to Solve
</P>
<P>
   Trees and wildflowers, birds and animals, the contours of the
soil, marshes, deserts, intertidal spaces, local weather systems
and the altered view of the night sky _ these are part of what I
want to find out about when traveling. After watching armadillos _
could that be? _ scuttling around Cumberland Island, Ga., my family
pulled out books. The Southeast volume of the Smithsonian Guides
says these ``recent interlopers arrived mysteriously.''
</P>
<P>
   I recalled decades before having to swear to the Porter family
upon renting a place on Great Spruce Head Island in Maine, which
they owned, that our son's pet hamster was not only not pregnant,
but was certified a male, before we were allowed to take the cage
ashore. I thought it preposterous, but looking at those sneaky
armadillos, I can see why islanders get anxious.
</P>
<P>
   After a stroll around a couple of stores in Manhattan
specializing in travel books, both filled with what seemed to be
virtually indistinguishable series concentrating primarily on
cities and the works of human hands in the world, I went to a
Barnes &AMP; Noble, on Fifth Avenue near Rockefeller Center. Nature
books were downstairs, 20 yard-long shelves of them, covering ants,
bears, palms and special topics like ``Mushrooms of North America''
and ``The Essential Cockatiel.'' I paused at an old friend,
``Beautiful Swimmers: Watermen, Crabs and the Chesapeake Bay'' by
William W. Warner (1977, Little, Brown), an essential for embarking
on the bay. It, and Henry Beston's 70-year-old ``Outermost House''
(Henry Holt), about Cape Cod, are gems of nature writing that are
ever young.
</P>
<P>
   The Audubon Regional Field Guides, a series of eight covering
the United States, with California and Florida each getting their
own, have been coming out since 1998. These pocket-sized volumes
published by Knopf have plastic-coated covers with wide flaps to
mark pages; they cost $19.95 each. They have the densely packed
material one needs: Three pages of photos of pines in the Florida
guide clearly show the differences. After an overview, the bulk of
the books deals with flora and fauna of an area _ about 1,000 items
in each book _ but parks and preserves are also mapped and
described.
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions deal with anomalies. The California fan palm is
described as the only palm native to the southwest United States.
Adjoining is a description and photo of a date palm, 20-foot leaves
akimbo. ``Habitat,'' says Audubon wryly: ``gardens, other
cultivated sites.'' This is a sanity-saver for visitors to Indio,
Calif., where the date palms wave and the proprietors advertise
their dates in grandiose terms.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By Its Cover
</P>
<P>
   The topical Audubon Field Guides, with imitation leather covers,
deal with specific subjects like the weather and the night sky, or
fishes. They originally came out 20 years ago and are constantly
being reissued. Susan D. Ralston of Knopf books, who oversees the
series, says that the Leatherette covers are not likely to be
abandoned because owners know, even when the printed half-jacket is
gone, that the red back is ``Eastern Birds.'' These books cost $19
each.
</P>
<P>
   After these did well, Ralston said, the company moved to guides
to like ``Wetlands of the United States'' before deciding that
people did not travel that way, but drove around a region at a
time. The regional guides were an outgrowth.
</P>
<P>
   The first two of National Geographic's new outdoor guides, the
Northern Rockies and Pacific Northwest, are due next month. The
cover describes the series as ``nature adventures in parks,
preserves, forests, wildlife refuges, wilderness areas.''
</P>
<P>
   An advance look showed glorious photographs of the sort long
associated with the magazine, but with the familiar yellow border
reduced to a yellow emblem at the top of each cover. Maps, hiking
directions, phone numbers and Web sites are all packed in, as well
as short articles on features like the ponderosa pine, or Lewis'
return route. These books, at 288 pages, are thick but narrow
enough (4\ by 8{ inches) for pockets. They are $24 each.
</P>
<P>
   The Peterson Guides, published by Houghton Mifflin, follow Roger
Tory Peterson's 1934 identification method: If you are holding a
yellow flower, you open to the pictures of yellow flowers and keep
looking until you find a match. ``Southeastern and Caribbean
Seashores'' says it seeks to be a ``beachwalker's companion,'' not
an exhaustive study. The author, Eugene H. Kaplan, is a happy
companion. On the subject of propagation of horseshoe crabs, he
writes: ``Wait for a day when the water reaches 70 degrees for the
first time in the spring to view the fantastic spectacle of this
mass-mating ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 50 of these titles in print, $20 to $24
each, starting with the original, ``Birds (Eastern).'' If the bird
is blue, you know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Such books can also do what cultural guides do: make you want to
go look. In the National Geographic ``Wildlife Watching,'' there is
an entry on Cheyenne Bottoms Preserve in central Kansas, which I
had never heard of. It has been designated a ``wetland of
international importance'' in a treaty signed by 92 countries,
including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly, the Bottoms does not comprise a majestic
landscape,'' writes Glen Martin, the author. ``Essentially it is a
mudflats hemmed in by agricultural fields.'' But it has been a
critical staging area for migratory shorebirds and waterfowl for
``at least 100,000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey found it to be the top shorebird springtime migration
area in the lower 48 states. And what is among the regular
visitors? A giant whooping crane or two, which was not so long ago
believed to be virtually extinct. The place, administered by the
state and the Nature Conservancy, is 128 miles northwest by road
from Wichita. Best time to go: March through May.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Guides to Natural America, published by Random
House, began to appear in 1996. There are 15, divided by region,
costing $19.95 each. These are bigger, better for the shelf than
the pocket. The sad news is that the Smithsonian says the division
that was responsible for these books has closed, and when the
current supply is exhausted, the series will not be reprinted.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures in these books are large and beautiful, some of them
paintings by artists like Winslow Homer and Audubon himself. The
narrative prose is not interrupted with descriptions of how to get
into the sanctuary, but asterisks lead to entries in the back with
phone numbers and types of facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Maps are important in all these series. The National
Geographic's new outdoors guides have contour maps, and when I
looked at one of Grinnell Glacier Trail in Montana, my legs
remembered a too-late cold return to Many Glacier Hotel one
September evening when a friend had overestimated her capacities.
But then I began reading.
</P>
<P>
   Of Grinnell Lake, it said: ``The water gets its turquoise color
from rock powder milled by upstream glaciers. The powder, sometimes
called glacial flour, remains in suspension and refracts blue light
into this lovely shade of bluish green.'' The exhaustion and worry
were worth it, and the book recaptured the sights for me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000327.0495 </DOCNO>
