<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9879 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-GLOBE-$     03-27 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-GLOBE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKESPEARE AS KARAOKE, WITH CRUMHORNS ON THE SOUNDTRACK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than 400 years, one of London's main lures has been the
theater. And one of the hottest attractions this season is
Shakespeare's Globe, the reconstructed playhouse on the South Bank
of the Thames where many of his greatest works were first
performed.
</P>
<P>
   A $12 adult ticket buys a group tour of the playhouse, a brief
history of the theater from a guide (who got only a couple of
things wrong) and entrance to the new Globe museum, which is where
the real fun begins.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe exhibitions mix computer technology and old-fashioned
display cases to provide something for everybody _ swordfighting
demonstrations (Elizabethans carried swords the way American
cowboys packed pistols); a costume exhibit (I never knew what
torture Elizabethan women endured just to get dressed in the
morning), and a music presentation (why doesn't anyone write
sonatas for cittern and shawm any more?)
</P>
<P>
   I hit the interactive exhibits like a kid in a video arcade.
There is a 10-question multiple-choice quiz on Shakespeare's First
Folio, the version actors use today. If you give a wrong answer,
you can try again. I aced eight answers on the first try, got
another one on the second and completely missed the tenth. (Well,
does anyone know how much a collection of plays cost in 1623?)
</P>
<P>
   I also tried the one where you can publish your own version of
Shakespeare, or at least the first 10 lines of Hamlet's ``To be or
not to be'' soliloquy. Choosing from half a dozen options, I opted
for the text from the 1603 quarto (a bootleg edition) with
Shakespeare's spelling and punctuation. It read:
</P>
<P>
   To be, or not to be, I there's the point,
</P>
<P>
   To Die, to sleepe, is that all? I all:
</P>
<P>
   No, to sleepe, to dreame, I mary there it goes.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem to me that one would play, let alone sell, so I
went back to the First Folio.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's plays also had music, of course, and that exhibit
features a case filled with Elizabethan instruments _ from
crumhorns (tenor and alto) to sackbuts _ and a terminal that allows
one to call up a brief history of each and then hear it played.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite exhibit consists of four booths where one can hear
great actors performing familiar Shake-spearean speeches: Ellen
Terry reading Portia's ``Quality of mercy'' soliloquy from ``The
Merchant of Venice'' (admittedly sounding a bit like chalk on a
blackboard); Edwin Booth reading from ``Othello'' and Henry Irving
declaiming ``Now is the winter of our discontent'' from ``Richard
III.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gielgud does ``Howl, howl, howl, howl!'' from ``King Lear''
and reads three sonnets, and in another booth different actors
interpret the same monologues from Hamlet. There are eight ``To be
or not to be's,'' ranging from Herbert Beerbohm to Richard Burton,
and four renditions of ``O, what a rogue,'' including Peter
O'Toole's. There is also the graveyard scene with Laurence Olivier
as Hamlet and Stanley Holloway playing the gravedigger.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the pros, I was ready for the main attraction, a
sort of Shakespeare karaoke in which you choose a scene from one of
eight plays to act in. The monitor scrolls through your lines, then
you are allowed a practice run-through. When you're ready for your
take, you punch a button and a voice gives you your cue. You
deliver your line, punch the button again, and your invisible
co-star responds. At the end you hear a playback of the scene.
</P>
<P>
   I went through most of the computer's repertory. I did the
gravedigger's scene from ``Hamlet'' (after my ``Alas, poor
Yorick,'' they'll forget Olivier); ``The King is dead'' from
``Macbeth,'' and the Soothsayer's ``Beware the Ides of March''
warning from ``Julius Caesar.'' Then I persuaded my wife, LuAnn, to
do the balcony scene with me from ``Romeo and Juliet.'' I was
pretty good; she needed work. I suggested that when we return she
should first brush up her Shakespeare. She suggested I volunteer
for the swordfighting demonstration. A hit, a palpable hit.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET THERE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's Globe is at 21 New Globe Walk, Bankside, (44-20)
7902 1500 for the exhibit, (44-20)7401 9919 for the theater,
www.shakespeares-globe.org. The theater is open for guided tours
from 9 a.m. to noon during the May to September performance season;
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily the rest of the year. The exhibit is open
daily 9 a.m. to noon and 1:30 to 4 p.m. during the season; 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m. the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $12 for adults for the tour and exhibit combined;
the price for the exhibit only (when the tour is not available) had
not been set in late March. Groups of 15 or more can prebook, but
it's first-come, first-serve for smaller parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-27-00 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
