<SLUG> BC-GUN-LOCKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY BACKS AWAY FROM GUN-LOCK GIVEAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ City leaders Monday backed out of a national
program that offers residents free gun locks through police
departments.
</P>
<P>
   Project HomeSafe, sponsored by the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, had offered to donate up to 1,500 cable-style gun locks
valued at $15,000 over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 31 cities, including Las Vegas, Pittsburg and Orlando,
Fla., have accepted a total of 50,000 gun locks from the
foundation's program. Another 106 cities, including Houston and
Miami, have scheduled giveaways this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The program is funded by gun dealers who are members of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But after visiting the foundation's Web site and consulting with
Interim City Manager Linda Barton and Mayor Chuck Mosher, Bellevue
Police Chief Jim Montgomery decided not to participate in the
program two days before it was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the idea of giving away gun locks, and we'd do it if
we had the money ourselves to fund it, absolutely, especially, when
it comes to children,'' said police spokeswoman Marcia Harnden.
``But at this time, the chief felt that until they were a little
better known to us, we couldn't be sure of their agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's political bent has spooked several other cities
approached to participate in Project HomeSafe. Seattle and King
County are among those who declined to accept the gun locks.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is a firearms trade organization that shares
members with the National Rifle Association. It also is a defendant
in civil lawsuits some cities have filed against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery planned to announce Bellevue's participation in the
giveaway program along with eight other Puget Sound cities at a
news conference Thursday. But a visit to the NSSF home page cooled
his interest.
</P>
<P>
   In news releases on the web site dated March 18, NSSF President
Robert Delfay blasts Smith &AMP; Wesson's recent decision to put safety
locks on its handguns, add smart-gun technology to new firearms to
prevent unauthorized use, and discontinue sales at gun shows where
background checks of buyers aren't done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ill-conceived action on the part of one of the most
revered names in the American firearms industry,'' Delfay states in
one of the releases.
</P>
<P>
   Said Harnden: ``We don't want the public to think we don't care
about gun safety but it's about this group's reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Police departments in eight other area cities _ Bothell, Des
Moines, Issaquah, Mercer Island, Kirkland, Tukwila, Sammamish and
Duvall _ plan to distribute the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Tukwila Police Chief Keith Haines had never heard of the NSSF
until last week when the Bean Agency, a Seattle public relations
firm, contacted one of his officers about Project HomeSafe.
</P>
<P>
   For Haines, the chance to save young lives overcame any
reservations he had about the Newtown, Conn.-based foundation, he
said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing it to encourage firearm safety in our community
and they are offering free cable gun locks that can work on
semiautomatic pistols, bolt-action rifles and revolvers. And
they're also offering safety tips,'' Haines said. ``If it keeps
even one child safe ... then it will all have been worthwhile, at
least in my view.''
</P>
<P>
   The King County Sheriff's Office hasn't signed on to distribute
the gun locks because the King County Council has to approve a
waiver before the sheriff's department can accept free merchandise,
said spokesman John Urquhart.
</P>
<P>
   Politics played no role in Seattle's decision, but Mayor Paul
Schell's spokesman, Dick Lilly, said credibility did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some inquiries about the public relations agency and
discovered that some of the cities that they said were involved
with Project Homesafe were not,'' Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city worried that the NSSF, best known as a
sponsor of shooting competitions and the Olympic target-shooting
team, was a defendant in civil lawsuits against gun manufacturers.
That fact convinced the mayor of St. Louis to reject the free
locks.
</P>
<P>
   And Seattle city attorneys were concerned that the gun locks,
which consist of a vinyl-covered loop of steel cable and an
inch-wide key padlock, wouldn't be compatible with some weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that they would not work for some types of guns and we
were in danger of liability if they didn't work,'' Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   When properly installed into the ejection port and magazine well
of an unloaded semiautomatic pistol or the barrel of a revolver,
the locks prevent closing the firearm's action.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Bean, whose public relations firm is coordinating the
project, admits the safety locks aren't a panacea for gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, wire cutters will snip it just like you can take a
hammer and knock a trigger lock off. But this is going to slow
someone down. ... It will deter a child,'' Bean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a critical safety program because it reaches out
to a new audience among gun owners _ people who have purchased
firearms but haven't gotten gun-safety education,'' said Doug
Painter, executive director of the NSSF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
