<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON RETRIAL CHOICE IS COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - George Cardona, one of two federal prosecutors who
won the 1997 bank fraud conviction of Fife Symington, is resigning,
complicating the federal government's decision on whether to retry
the former Arizona governor.
</P>
<P>
   Cardona, who is headed to a lecturer's post at UCLA's law
school, sought to minimize his importance to the Symington case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of good prosecutors,'' he said. ``The exhibits
are there, and there is a lot of witness testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cardona's pending departure, which follows last year's
resignation of his partner in the complicated case, comes at a
particularly problematic time for the office.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals last week rejected prosecutors'
request to reconsider a 1999 ruling that threw out Symington's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Cardona's loss is one of many concerns that the U.S. Attorney's
Office must now weigh as it ponders whether to retry the case, drop
it or seek review in the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Some concerns are subtle, involving the age of the case, public
perceptions of the justice system and the prosecutors' appetite for
another courthouse war against a man they already have forced from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Some are technical, involving the strength of the evidence
against Symington, who was charged with lying to lenders on his
real estate projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some concerns are simply pragmatic matters of cost and time.
</P>
<P>
   Symington, vowing Monday not to plea-bargain, said simple
fairness demands termination of a case that cost him the
governorship and cost his family millions in attorneys fees.
</P>
<P>
   Symington resigned immediately after a U.S. District Court jury
found him guilty of six counts of bank and wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that at some point an element of fairness needs
to enter the picture, and I feel it's time to end this,'' Symington
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Dowd, Symington's attorney in the case, said he will take
that message to Los Angeles when he meets with U.S Attorney
Alejandro Mayorkas sometime in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd was often combative and hostile in his exchanges with
Cardona and former prosecutor David Schindler. Now he is extending
an olive branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense Mr. Mayorkas is a very fair man,'' said Dowd, a former
top Justice Department prosecutor who is known for his talent at
high-level schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, a law professor at Loyola University in Los
Angeles, said three factors of the Symington case suggest to her
that prosecutors will yank him back to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high-profile case, it involves serious crimes, and
the conviction wasn't lost because of problems with the evidence,''
she said. ``It was lost on a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington's conviction was overturned last year when a
three-judge panel ruled that an elderly juror had been improperly
dismissed from the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Trial Judge Roger Strand had cut the juror loose after other
jurors complained that she was confused and unable to participate
in their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said the other jurors' statements showed that
there was a possibility that they wanted her off because she was
holding out for acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a professor of legal ethics at New York
University Law School, said prosecutors have to be concerned about
conclusions that the public may draw from the Symington case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want him to be able to claim that he has been
vindicated for what they believe were serious crimes,'' Gillers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardona took note Monday of the practical matters that will
enter into the decision on Symington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to trial would take substantial resources,'' he said.
``But the exhibits are there, there's a lot of testimony on the
record, and we know from the first time what the defense would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he leaves, Cardona will help guide decisions on the case.
One question is whether prosecutors at a new trial would present
only the six counts that produced guilty verdicts or try to
reinstate the 11 counts on which the jury deadlocked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
