<HEADLINE>
SLOAN REJOINS STARS' CHECKING LINE TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars' most-consistent line this season is
intact again. Rookie wing Blake Sloan returns tonight after missing
15 games since he suffered a hairline fracture of his left fibula
on Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   He rejoins Mike Keane and Guy Carbonneau, who wears a playing
cast on his fractured right wrist, on the line usually charged with
shutting down the opponent's top scoring line. Sloan adds speed and
peskiness to a line with two of the strongest positional players in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Keane, however, expects more than solid defense out of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out and not only play well in our end, but we
have to help the team and go out and score goals also,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trio has had a productive goal-scoring season, combining for
23 goals. Keane has 11, the most he has scored since 1993-94 when
he had 16 with the Montreal Canadiens, Carbonneau has eight, tying
his highest total in five seasons with the Stars, and Sloan has
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sloan has the legs and the tenacity to create pressure on a
deep forecheck, so he can get a lot pucks in areas where Keane and
Carbo can get them turned over, and then we can attack back to
them,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I think that's why that line is
so effective.'' &QL; 
Morrow pleased
</P>
<P>
   Rookie left wing Brenden Morrow expected to play this season for
the Stars' minor-league affiliate, the Michigan K-Wings. Instead,
injuries forced his promotion, and, as they say, the rest is
history.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow's 14 goals are the most by a Stars rookie since the team
moved to Texas before the 1993-94 season. With three game-winning
goals, he is tied for second among NHL rookies. He has played the
majority of the season alongside All-Star center Mike Modano on the
No. 1 line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing I expected for my first year,'' Morrow said. ``I
thought I would be playing three or four minutes a game and five
goals would be a good season. It's been unbelievable. Every day,
playing with great players, it's just a lot of fun.'' &QL; 
Lehtinen exam delayed
</P>
<P>
   Stars left wing Jere Lehtinen will have his ankle evaluated
tomorrow instead of today as previously scheduled. Lehtinen
underwent surgery after re-injuring the ankle Jan. 19, eight games
into his original comeback. If doctors deem his ankle fit, he could
be in the lineup Sunday in Colorado. \Nsubheds:Forward thinking
With Blake Sloan returning tonight, Scott Thornton coming back
tomorrow from his three-game suspension, and Jere Lehtinen a
possibility soon, a logjam of forwards deserve playing time.
Hitchcock said he won't hesitate to go with who's hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always found you need to have 15 forwards ready to
play,'' he said, ``but I think right now some of the younger
players have played better than some of the older players and I
think we wouldn't hesitate to start that way.'' &QL; 
Two's the goal
</P>
<P>
   Ed Belfour is expected to be in goal tonight. Coach Ken
Hitchcock had said he wanted Manny Fernandez to play in two of the
remaining seven regular-season games, but the coach has not said
when Fernandez will play.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
