<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ELSTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELSTER GOES FROM POOL TO PLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The lake, a five-minute drive from Kevin
Elster's house in suburban Las Vegas, is gorgeous. But he never
went; sitting by the pool was relaxing enough.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Elster spent last summer, that and making plans to
build a bar near the Las Vegas strip. The conceptual drawings were
complete and it probably would be opening soon.
</P>
<P>
   And then things changed slightly: Elster the entrepreneur has
reverted to Elster the ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   No more sleeping all morning, heading to the gym in the
afternoon and then coming home to do nothing. Elster is back in the
major leagues and working as hard as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Elster, 35, is a year removed from the game and 14 years removed
from a World Series title with the Mets. The cynics say his range
was only adequate and his offense lacking when he was 21, which
makes one wonder about the present.
</P>
<P>
   But the scouts are impressed. They say he fields flawlessly and
his bat speed is good, good enough that the Dodgers have named him
their starting shortstop to begin the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all this seems crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Elster was done with baseball last year. Now, he's an integral
part of a club whose payroll could bankroll a chain of high-end
bars.
</P>
<P>
   It all started about a month before spring training began, when
Elster decided he wanted to play baseball again and the Dodgers
decided they had nothing to lose if they invited him to spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have worked out better for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, I didn't come in here expecting this to
happen, but it has, so I'm really looking forward to it,'' Elster
said. ``On the weekends during (last) summer, I was by the pool all
day long. All day long. I'd cook out, have friends over. That's
what I did. That's my story. It was so nice by the pool I never
went to the lake, and the lake is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Elster's agent/brother, Patrick, began calling around when Kevin
decided he hadn't had his fill of baseball. Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone returned the phone call immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Elster was on the phone with Malone and liked what he
heard. Then his former manager and current Dodgers manager, Davey
Johnson, rang. After a 30-minute conversation, during which they
reminisced about their days together in New York in the late 1980s,
Elster was in effect a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was to provide a safety net in case young
shortstop Alex Cora struggled in the spring. Cora, 24, did just
that. Elster, having nothing to lose, was consistent from the first
grounder he caressed into his glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Kevin well, and I know that as long as he was in shape
he would be all right,'' Johnson said. ``I asked him what kind of
shape he was in and he said he was fine. I know what he's capable
of doing. When he was with me with the Mets, he went through that
streak (of 88 games without an error).''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an effortless transition.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Elster swung a bat or took a grounder was when he
was released by the Texas Rangers on July 31, 1998. He has some
rust to shed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I picked up a bat was when I got here,'' Elster
said. ``I did play catch three or four times. You can't come in
here and expect to start throwing 15 minutes a day from day one, so
I did throw the ball a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did come to spring training a week early to get as many
swings as he wanted in the batting cages and take grounders to get
back in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems a little weird, I know,'' Elster said. ``I've never
worked out in the winter. I like to forget all my bad habits and
start anew every year and see if I can find it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are convinced he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's way ahead of where I thought he'd be,'' Malone said.
``He's been much more consistent than I thought he would be after
missing well over a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Elster missed almost all of '92 when he had surgery on his right
shoulder, played 10 minor-league games in '93 and played sparingly
in '94 and '95. Then Texas invited him to spring training as a
nonroster invitee in '96.
</P>
<P>
   He stunned everyone by hitting 24 homers, driving in 99 runs and
batting .252 in 157 games. In his other 703 career games over 11
seasons, Elster has 50 homers, 245 RBI and hit .222.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, hitting ninth in the American League is a
joy,'' Elster said. ``That was the first year after being hurt. ...
I was a different person. I was bigger, stronger. I discovered
lifting weights with my upper body rather than my legs. That was
the first chance I got to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Elster parlayed that into a starting job with Pittsburgh in '97,
and he was producing again. He led the team with seven homers and
25 RBI in mid-May. The Pirates were so thrilled they offered Elster
a multiyear deal. The sides agreed, but the night before Elster was
to sign he was involved in a baserunning collision and shattered
his left wrist. Goodbye contract.
</P>
<P>
   He re-signed with the Rangers in '98, battled injuries and
fought for playing time before he was released.
</P>
<P>
   Elster had enough of baseball, so he went to the desert to start
the next phase of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I guess I just wanted one more shot at the
ring,'' Elster said. ``I think this team has a chance. That's why I
decided to come here. It's the championship ring. I have one, and I
want another.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
