<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SEEKING BALLAST FOR TOP-HEAVY LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Like Christopher Columbus, when the
Rangers embark on a new season Monday afternoon they can't be sure
whether they're going to discover the new world or simply drop off
the face of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   What they do know is exactly where the old world stops and the
new one, if it's there, kicks in _ at the No. 6 spot in the batting
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're going to prove,'' manager Johnny Oates predicted
boldly yesterday, echoing the Italian explorer of old, ``is that
the world is round.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' first five hitters represent the Rangers' world as we've
come to know it: Royce Clayton, Rusty Greer, Pudge Rodriguez,
Rafael Palmeiro and even new Ranger David Segui, who at least is a
known major-league quantity.
</P>
<P>
   But is there life after No. 5?
</P>
<P>
   More important, can the Rangers' veterans hold the fort long
enough for the babes who linger below the Segui Line to mature and
develop into bona fide major-league players?
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, this team could be history before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to fall off the face of the earth,'' Oates
declared. ``Supposedly, the strength of our ballclub is our
starting pitching. If we all carry the load and do our part, not
just our pitching, but Raffy and Pudge and Segui and Greer, we
should be OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veterans need to get us going and let the young kids catch
up. I don't think it's going to take long.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Opening Day, Oates was more than comfortable with the last
four hitters in his batting order, and why not? They included
American League MVP Rodriguez (.332, 35 home runs, 113 runs batted
in), first baseman/designated hitter Lee Stevens (.282, 24, 81),
third baseman Todd Zeile (.293, 24, 98) and Clayton (.288, 14, 52).
</P>
<P>
   This season, his last four hitters include two rookies, a
second-year player who hit .245 in his rookie season and an aging
veteran who struggled to break .200 last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a clear delineation: Through No. 5, it's All-Stars and
solid veterans; below No. 5, it's one big question mark.
</P>
<P>
   But don't write the Rangers off yet.
</P>
<P>
   The brightest story from this camp has been the hitting and
all-around play of center fielder Ruben Mateo, who will bat sixth,
and right fielder Gabe Kapler, who will be the seventh hitter in
Oates' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Evans, the minor-league journeyman who won the third-base
job by default when rookie Mike Lamb faltered this spring, and
veteran second baseman Luis Alicea complete the lineup, but there
may be relief there, too. Frank Catalanotto, another piece of the
Juan Gonzalez trade, has also impressed Oates with his bat this
spring and will get his share of playing time at second or third.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers' veterans can just buy the kids a little time ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We need for our veteran pitchers to pitch well in the first
month to give our young guys a chance to get their feet on the
ground,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``Without putting any
more pressure on them than is already there, you'd like to see them
give the younger guys a chance to get comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest thing for young players in the big leagues is to
feel you belong. These guys _ Mateo and Kapler _ act like they do
belong and that they're already big-league players.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to become impressed with the numbers Mateo and Kapler
have put up this spring, but those can easily be skewed. Lots of
players put up big numbers early in training camp as they feast on
pitchers throwing 85-mph fastballs. But numbers aren't all Oates
sees when he watches Mateo and Kapler play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skills and what they've already done at the minor-league
level, not in spring training, that's what I see,'' Oates said. ``I
watch how they've come together in the outfield, how they talk to
each other, how they're working on becoming a unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I get back to their skills again. They're not fringe
minor-leaguers who have been hanging around for 15 years and are
finally getting a shot. These are two players of the year. They are
five-tool players, both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   We haven't heard so much about five tools (hitting for average,
hitting for power, speed, defensive ability with the glove and arm
strength), in fact, since ``Five-Tool'' Tony Chance was in camp
with the replacement players.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not go back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both \RMateo and Kapler\S have shown good bat speed,'' Melvin
pointed out. ``You look for the skills and the adjustments they
make. They both went through a little stretch two or three weeks
ago where they weren't swinging it well, and they were out here,
putting in extra work after the games. Then they came on and got
hot again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe's been pretty consistent. Ruben's been on this hot
stretch now after struggling a little bit early. He kept his poise
and kept working at it. All of these guys have good work ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason the Rangers believe there can be life after
No. 5, if their young players don't get buried early. They won't if
the veterans can keep the team competitive while the youngsters are
learning the big-league ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be more reliance on guys who have been there,''
Greer said. ``By the same token, you can't go into a game thinking
that. You just have to let it happen. You don't want to put more
pressure on yourself, but you'd like to be able to take some
pressure off Gabe and Ruben.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, whether the Rangers can defend their AL West
championship will depend on what happens below the Segui Line.
</P>
<P>
   That's where they'll either discover a brave new world, or
completely drop off the face of the earth. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
