<HEADLINE>
NO-FEAR APPROACH NETS TITLE FOR SUTTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton added an exclamation point
yesterday to his weeklong message that Tiger Woods, the world's
top-ranked golfer, is not a final-round force to be feared at PGA
Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Respected, certainly. But Woods, in Sutton's estimation, is not
worthy of being placed on a pedestal and considered unbeatable, as
some peers have suggested during a streak that had seen the
24-year-old win 70 percent of his past 10 starts at tour events.
</P>
<P>
   That percentage dipped to 63.6 yesterday, when Sutton completed
a rain-delayed final round by holding off Woods in a head-to-head
duel at the TPC at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   The defining moments came at No. 18, where Sutton arrived with a
one-stroke lead after frittering away three strokes over the
previous five holes.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Woods split the 18th fairway with a 2-iron,
Sutton pulled a driver and pounded the ball 15 yards past his
pursuer. When Woods' 6-iron approach flew to the back fringe,
Sutton answered with a 6-iron that stopped 10 feet below the hole.
Sutton's two-putt par clinched the $1.08 million winner's check
after Woods' long birdie attempt from the fringe stayed wide of the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what golf is all about, coming down the stretch with
the best player in the world ... and winning,'' said Sutton, who
pumped his right fist after his momentum-turning approach at No.
18, then shared a lengthy high-five with caddie Freddie Burns after
tapping in for the clinching par. ``I stayed focused on what I was
doing, not Tiger. That's what I did best. I was not going to beat
myself. I'm proud of the way I played.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who shot Sutton a ``thumbs-up'' sign after Sutton's
6-iron at No. 18, told his conqueror ``Well done'' as the two
walked off the 18th green. For Woods, it was only the fourth time
in his past 11 starts at PGA Tour events that he has failed to win.
But he took little solace from his third runner-up finish in that
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   This, Woods said, was Sutton's day. In fact, it was Sutton's
week. Before the tournament, Sutton criticized peers _ in
particular, Colin Montgomerie _ for adopting a ``defeatist
attitude'' in matchups with Woods. During the final round, he
backed up his bow-before-no-Tiger stance with a closing 71,
matching Woods' final-round score, to finish at 10-under par and
protect the one-stroke advantage he enjoyed after 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton became the third wire-to-wire winner in the 27-year
history of the event, joining Steve Elkington (1997) and Greg
Norman (1994). At 41, Sutton is the oldest TPC champion. Sutton,
however, admitted to bouts of nervousness after his ``defeatist
attitude'' comments became the talk of tournament week and he
realized a matchup with Woods loomed on his horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been nervous for the last two or three days, knowing
the big deal that was made of it,'' Sutton said. ``The other night,
I was sitting in the bed saying, `You know, I'm not praying to him
\RWoods\S.' So he is not a god, for sure. When that realization
came over me, it was like, `OK, he's just human like I am. So I can
do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton did it in style, finishing the final round without a
bogey. He collected seven consecutive pars during yesterday's
conclusion to Sunday's suspended round, forcing Woods to take
chances to try to trim a three-stroke deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Woods began with a three-putt bogey at No. 12, falling four
strokes off the pace, before turning up the heat with a five-foot
birdie at No. 13 and a 12-foot eagle putt at the par-5 16th. That
sent Sutton to the tee box at No. 17, the TPC's island-green hole,
with a one-shot lead. During the third round, Sutton splashed his
tee shot there and took triple-bogey. This time, he stuck a 9-iron
on the middle of the green and two-putted, while Woods saved par
from the deep rough around the collar.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 18, Sutton applied the clincher, which drew praise from
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I didn't win, but at least I made Hal work
for it,'' Woods said. ``I wasn't going to give him a nice stroll up
18 without any pressure. I put a little heat on, and he responded.
It was a good battle. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sutton, it was validation of his weeklong stance that being
No. 1 in the world golf rankings does not always equate with being
No. 1 on the final-round leader board. &QL; 
Pleasant surprise
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton said he was ``really shocked'' when Tiger Woods hit a
2-iron off the tee box at the water-lined 18th hole. Briefly,
Sutton contemplated bagging the driver he was holding but stuck
with his instinct. He belted the ball 15 yards past Woods, straight
down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I needed the advantage on the last hole,'' said
Sutton, whose approach to the 18th green was 30 feet closer than
Woods'. ``I told myself, `I'm one of the best drivers in the game,
so I'm going to play to my strength.' '' &QL; 
Steady Sutton
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton said his bogey-free finish to the final round proved
pivotal in keeping Tiger Woods at bay. During yesterday's seven
holes, Sutton missed only one fairway and hit every green in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big factor,'' Sutton said. ``It never looked like I
was in trouble, from Tiger's perspective. That's what I was trying
to do. If you give him an open door, he just rushes through it. I
wanted to make sure I kept the door closed.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
