<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-VEGAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGAS PRESENTATION INTERESTS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Las Vegas made a serious pitch yesterday to
six major-league teams, trying to get them to move their
spring-training bases to the desert in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are definitely interested, said executive vice
president John McMichael, who represented the team at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team was sufficiently interested to proceed with the
discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers, pushed by their Fox television owners,
have shown the most interest in training in Las Vegas. The Toronto
Blue Jays, Houston Astros, Baltimore Orioles and Tampa Bay Devil
Rays were also represented at the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael said the financial and economic considerations were
not discussed. Instead, Las Vegas officials and architects showed
them a plan for a four-to-six-team training facility in the
southwest part of the city and a stadium downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a lot has to be in place to go from some nice
drawings on a board to an actual facility,'' McMichael said. ``But
based on what we saw, the teams have decided to proceed with the
financial and economic discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael said the teams involved will meet to discuss strategy,
then get back with the representatives from Las Vegas as early as
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest has been piqued,'' McMichael said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers want to make a decision on a future training site by
early summer. They have one more year on their lease in Port
Charlotte, Fla. A bill pending in the Florida legislature would
provide funds to upgrade spring-training facilities in the state.
The Rangers' baseball people, including general manager Doug Melvin
and manager Johnny Oates, have expressed a desire to remain in Port
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rangers owner Tom Hicks has concerns about Port
Charlotte's remote location and availability to fans traveling from
Texas. There are also concerns about attendance, although the
Rangers are drawing almost 1,000 more fans per game this year than
in 1999. The Rangers drew a sellout crowd of 4,519 yesterday when
the Cincinnati Reds brought Ken Griffey Jr. and Deion Sanders to
town.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas is obviously a more glamorous location that Port
Charlotte, but there are concerns about the weather, which is
colder and windier than Florida in February and March, and having
young baseball players training in a gambling and entertainment
mecca.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have also looked into Arizona and other Florida
locations.
nn
</P>
